<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-HUNDLEY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUNDLEY TAKES CRUSADE TO OUTFIELD 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT ST. LUCIE, Fla. _ By 1 o'clock on Sunday afternoon, the
energy was flowing out of Todd Hundley as freely as the
perspiration was dripping from his pores.
</P>
<P>
   During a two-hour workout under the Florida sun, Hundley took
live batting practice for the first time since undergoing
reconstructive elbow surgery last Sept. 26, shagged flies in right
field, practiced throwing from the outfield and ran backpedal
sprints.
</P>
<P>
   As determined as Hundley is to learn to play the outfield, he
seems even more determined not to allow his spirit to be broken by
the New York Mets organization he has been a part of for the last
dozen years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a quitter,'' he said. ``And I'm not going to quit on
this organization.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Hundley, who is still bothered by the way the Mets have
treated him since trading for Mike Piazza on May 22, admitted on
Sunday that he is engaged in a sort of crusade to find out who in
the Mets organization told the news media that he might have a
drinking problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``What have I done?'' Hundley said. ``Have I been arrested,
gotten a dui, been accused of rape? I haven't done anything.
Someone in the organization has it out for me. If I had done
something, I'd stand up to it. But I haven't done anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Hundley is not the only one who has been affected by the
controversy over the Piazza trade. Over the weekend, Piazza
admitted that he is a little uncomfortable, too, because of what
Hundley has gone through.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, at least, Hundley seemed to be enjoying learning a
new position. ``There are definitely ways to make this work,'' he
said. ``And I'm down here working on a solution to their problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Hundley added that he could be ready to return to the Mets in
about three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Outfield-wise, it's close,'' he said. ``Real close.
Catching-wise, that's a different story. Maybe five to six weeks.
But I could play the outfield and swing a bat in another couple of
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would love to be in the Yankee series,'' he said, referring
to the interleague series that begins on June 26. ``But that's not
my decision.''
</P>
<P>
   When Hundley is given the OK, Manager Bobby Valentine will have
to find a place to play him. Hundley all but ruled out sharing
first base with John Olerud, which is one reason he began to work
in the outfield this weekend. Under instructions given by General
Manager Steve Phillips, Hundley will continue to take fly balls in
left and right fields.
</P>
<P>
   Which makes sense. No regular in the Mets' outfield has more
than nine home runs. Hundley has hit 71 home runs in the last two
seasons. Bernard Gilkey is batting .251, Butch Huskey .249. Brian
McRae is batting .230. The last time Hundley hit below .259 was
1994.
</P>
<P>
   First, of course, Hundley has to show he can play the outfield.
After first saying he would play the position if the Mets gave him
a no-trade clause, he now says he said he will play the outfield
even if they don't.
</P>
<P>
   ``But even if they say no deal on the no-trade, I would still
hope they wouldn't trade me to a noncontending team, as much time
and effort as I have put into this organization,'' Hundley said.
</P>
<P>
   More time and more effort will be required. But Rich Miller, the
organization's minor league outfield coordinator, who has been
working with Hundley, sees some promise.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him there's a good chance of him becoming an adequate
outfielder,'' Miller said. ``He's a good athlete and this is a new
challenge. He just doesn't have his legs or his wind yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Hundley has slimmed down, however, and is near his playing
weight of between 195 and 200 pounds. He said he told Phillips:
``Give me some time in the outfield. I might take the catcher's
gear and burn it.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
