<SLUG> BC-SOC-WORLD </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WINNING IS GERMANS BUSINESS 
</HEADLINE>
 CUP-GERMANY-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; PARIS _ The wives and girlfriends are sunning themselves in
Juan-les-Pins, a beach or two out of reach. That was the plan. The
Germans may be quartered on the Riviera, but this is no vacation.
It's a boot camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I told you some of the things they are doing, you wouldn't
believe it,'' says US soccer captain Thomas Dooley, who grew up in
the Fatherland and knows its players by heart. ``They are even
controlling the phone calls from the rooms.''
</P>
<P>
   This ain't no party. This ain't no disco. This ain't no fooling
around. The Germans flew down last week from Frankfurt, checked
into their chateau at La Colle-sur-Loup, and three hours later were
working out inside their practice stadium in Nice. They don't come
to the World Cup to live out some adidas video. The Germans come to
win it. Always.
</P>
<P>
   They are supposed to beat the Americans Monday night in their
opener here in the Parc de Princes. They are supposed to win their
group, then go on to defeat the Belgians, Romanians, French, and
Brazilians and claim the Cup for the fourth time since 1954. The
Germans have done the math, as they always do.
</P>
<P>
   And if their calculus went cuckoo last time in America _ nobody
figured the Bulgarians would put them out in the quarterfinals _
it's all the more reason why they're leaving nothing to error this
time. Because this is their last roundup.
</P>
<P>
   The Germans, who average 30 years of age, are the oldest in the
32-team field. Three of them _ captain Jurgen Klinsmann, Lothar
Matthaeus, and Juergen Kohler _ have at least 100 international
caps. Four of them are playing in their third Cup. The 37-year-old
Matthaeus, who was captain when Germany (technically, West Germany)
won in 1990, is playing in his fifth.
</P>
<P>
   Almost nobody back home wanted Matthaeus on the team again. Not
coach Berti Vogts, who dumped him two years ago when Germany won
the European championship. And certainly not Klinsmann, who's been
barely on speaking terms with Matthaeus since their playing days at
Bayern Munich. ``I have no problems with Matthaeus the football
player,'' Klinsmann says, pointedly.
</P>
<P>
   Even Matthaeus didn't expect to be here. He'd booked a sunny
vacation months ago. Then Matthias Sammer had knee surgery and Olaf
Thon had ankle problems and Vogts came calling.
</P>
<P>
   He made it clear to Matthaeus that Klinsmann still would be
captain and that Matthaeus probably would be a reserve. ``I'm not
afraid of being on the bench,'' says Matthaeus with a shrug. ``I
was there in 1982. I know what it's like. I've had a long talk with
the coach about my role and we've come to an agreement. If I don't
play at the start, then I'll work to get into the team.''
</P>
<P>
   Most folks figure that Matthaeus will be on the field sooner
rather than later, especially if the Germans start off playing the
way they did during qualifying. After tying four matches _
including Northern Ireland at home _ Germany took it down to the
final day, defeating hapless Albania by only 4-3 at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were having so many problems in qualifying that I called
Lothar,'' says Dooley, who played a dozen years in Germany. ``I
told him, they need you in there to kick some butts. So when he
came back, I was happy for him but unhappy for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Another year, the Deutscher Fussball Bund would have bought
Matthaeus a rocking chair and told him to watch on TV with the old
folks back home. But this time the DFB is determined to dust off as
many creaking idols as it has to, because the Germans sense that
the Cup is theirs for the taking.
</P>
<P>
   The Brazilians seem out of rhythm. The Italians were lucky to
tie Chile. The English have nobody who's ever played a Cup match.
The Argentines never have won the Cup when it's been in Europe. The
French _ when have the Germans lost to the French when it mattered?
</P>
<P>
   And after what happened last time, when the Germans mailed in
the first round (beating Bolivia and South Korea each by a goal and
tying Spain) and squeaked past Belgium before the Bulgarian
debacle, they have much to prove to the doubters back home.
</P>
<P>
   When Vogts's old men take on the Yanks Monday night on the edge
of the Bois de Boulogne, everything will stop from Rostock to
Munich. ``No cars in the street,'' says US playmaker Claudio Reyna,
who plays for VfL Wolfsburg in the Bundesliga. ``Everyone sitting
in front of a TV set. You have 4-year-old kids and 85-year-old
grandmothers watching Germany playing Armenia in a qualifier.''
</P>
<P>
   It is unthinkable to them that Germany will lose to the
Americans. Not with a golden trophy at stake that comes around once
a quadrennium. ``Germany is always there to play,'' says Reyna.
``They'll always fight and they'll always run, even if the game
isn't going well.''
</P>
<P>
   They did not come for le bronzage on the topless beaches along
the Cote d'Azur. This ain't no fooling around. No sightseeing, no
shopping, and no phone calls from the room. ``I do not think,''
Dooley says, ``that the Germans have played golf here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
