<SLUG> BC-SOC-WORLD </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US MAKES WORLD CUP BOW 
</HEADLINE>
 CUP-US-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ They'd been sequestered (or imprisoned, depending on
whom you ask) in their ivy-covered chateau out in Beaujolais
country for more than a week. They'd met all the roosters and
ducks, they'd fed the fawns, they'd listened to the grapes grow.
They'd had la vie rustique up to their ears. ``And we'd broken
almost all our darts,'' reports striker Brian McBride.
</P>
<P>
   So the United States men's soccer team had no choice but to come
here and play the Germans Monday night in their World Cup opener at
the sold-out Parc des Princes, their biggest match since they met
Brazil four years ago in the Rose Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Their goal is to advance to the second round, as they did in
1994. But this time the task is decidedly tougher. Besides Germany,
the European champions and three-time Cup winners, the Americans
have politically-charged dates with Iran (June 21 in Lyon) and
Yugoslavia (June 25 in Nantes).
</P>
<P>
   Few outside their own camp give them much of a chance of
surviving their group or of beating the Germans, and the Yanks
understand that. ``In Europe, they have no respect for the US,''
says coach Steve Sampson, whose squad is a 150-1 shot to win the
Cup. ``And quite frankly, we have not earned it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Americans, after all, are only 10-29-5 against European
teams in Europe over the years and have been outscored, 123-42.
When Sampson's squad was being blanked in Belgium in February,
German coach Berti Vogts walked out with 20 minutes left.
</P>
<P>
   The Germans are 2-0 against the US (4-3 and 3-0 in the States in
1993) and fully expect to make it 3-0 Monday night. Their
chancellor, Helmut Kohl, openly predicted a 3-1 victory a few days
ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the back of their minds they think if they knock the ball
around, there is no chance for us to get it,'' says US captain
Thomas Dooley, who grew up in Germany and played a dozen pro
seasons there. ``Most people in Germany think that Americans are
not that good at soccer. But now we can show them.''
</P>
<P>
   Fact is, the Yanks are far from the innocents abroad that they
were in 1990, when they went three-and-out in Italy. ``It was kind
of a fluke that we went in at all,'' says midfielder Tab Ramos,
who's playing in his third Cup. ``We were just a bunch of college
guys. We were tourists out there. But now, we're a team people have
to watch out for.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the US played erratically in its Cup qualifiers, it shut
out Brazil in February and demolished Austria in Vienna in April.
``This is a team that always responds to great pressure,'' Sampson
says.
</P>
<P>
   If anything, the pressure Monday night will be on the Germans,
who have a habit of playing uninspired Cup openers (2-1-2 in their
last five). ``They need very badly to beat us, so they can go into
their match with Yugoslavia (a 1-0 victor over Iran Sunday) with
less pressure,'' says US midfielder Claudio Reyna, who plays for
VfL Wolfsburg in the Bundesliga.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans would be delighted with a tie, and they've been
saying that since last year's draw. ``Realistically, if we get a
point that'd be great,'' says Reyna.
</P>
<P>
   To do that, they'll have to play out the full 90 minutes against
a German side that traditionally leads the world in focus, stamina,
and technical savvy. ``Discipline and organization is their biggest
advantage,'' says Dooley. ``Everyone knows exactly which position
he is playing. If the coach says, you can't go up and down, you are
not going.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Americans have an advantage, it's that they know the
Germans inside and out. Seven of them (Reyna, Dooley, McBride, Eric
Wynalda, David Regis, Joe-Max Moore, Chad Deering) either play in
Germany now or have in the past. ``There will be no surprises,''
Sampson says.
</P>
<P>
   The US knows that the Germans build attacks from the back, using
gifted sweepers like Lothar Matthaeus, a five-time Cupper, and Olaf
Thon. ``Those guys can change the game and put everything
together,'' says Dooley. The Germans take control in the midfield,
then seek to service the most dangerous strikers in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Captain Jurgen Klinsmann, who has scored eight goals in the last
two Cups, may be 33 but he netted four in a match this season for
England's Tottenham Hotspur. Oliver Bierhoff, the hero of Germany's
European victory, led Italy's Serie A in scoring with Udinese. And
Ulf Kirsten was Bayer Leverkusen's ``tormeister''. ``They're all
deadly,'' says US defender Eddie Pope. ``You have to worry about
every one of them.''
</P>
<P>
   The Americans, who have shut out Kuwait, Macedonia, and Scotland
in their last three international matches, figure that their
midfield-heavy 3-6-1 formation could hold the Germans to a goal.
Question is whether they can crack the Germans' 3-5-2 with only one
striker.
</P>
<P>
   ``The striker has to make the ball stick,'' says Roy Wegerle,
who could start there for the US Monday night if Wynalda isn't
fully fit after spring microsurgery on a knee. ``If it doesn't, the
system goes out the window.''
</P>
<P>
   The Americans know that the German defenders will swarm their
striker and try to knock Reyna, whom they know by heart, off the
ball. But they also know that they don't have to score _ and
Deutschland does. ``If we can keep it tied up as long as
possible,'' muses midfielder Ernie Stewart, ``they'll start
panicking.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yanks had seven relentlessly isolated days to dream up any
number of scenarios. Now, their vie rustique is fini. Last week,
barnyard animals were their amusements. Monday night, it's guys
named Jurgen.
</P>
</TEXT>
