<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-DEVILRAYS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
O'LEARY, SOX GO EXTRA MILE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY WHITESIDE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ It wasn't pretty. But maybe the Red Sox have mastered
the knack of beating up on the have-nots of the American League
East like they're supposed to.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, their 3-2, 10-inning victory over the Tampa Bay Devil
Rays before 27,768 Sunday night at Fenway Park falls into that
category. Both teams had chances to win, but it was Boston that
prevailed on a one-out RBI single to right by Troy O'Leary. It
scored Nomar Garciaparra, who had singled and moved to second on a
bunt single by Mike Benjamin.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox (39-26) swept the two-game, rain-shortened series.
The loss for last-place Tampa Bay was its first in five
extra-inning games this year.
</P>
<P>
   Although the box score might not entirely back it up, this was a
game dominated by pitching. The teams combined for 23 hits, 13 by
Tampa Bay. But strong showings by Boston's Steve Avery and Tampa
Bay's Tony Saunders, both lefthanded starters, kept the score
close. After a while, it became a contest of which bullpen would
wilt first. Tampa Bay used seven pitchers, the last being Jim
Mecir, who gave up O'Leary's winning hit. Boston used five
pitchers, with the victory going to closer Tom Gordon, who worked
out of a jam in the top of the 10th.
</P>
<P>
   Boston took a 1-0 lead in the first and it was all Avery could
do to hold it for the next four innings. The run followed a leadoff
walk to Darren Lewis, a stolen base, and a wild pitch on ball four
to John Valentin. Lewis scored easily on a sacrifice fly by
Garciaparra.
</P>
<P>
   In the fifth, Tampa Bay tied it. Kevin Stocker beat out a bunt
single off Avery and moved to second on a ground out. Another
grounder sent him to third, and then Wade Boggs rose above a chorus
of boos by the Fenway Faithful, slamming a double off the Wall to
score Stocker.
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay took a 2-1 lead in the sixth on a solo home run by
Bobby Smith, his fifth of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Boston rebounded in the bottom of the inning to tie the game at
2. Valentin led off with a walk and moved to third on a single by
Garciaparra. Valentin just beat a throw by right fielder Dave
Martinez and a tag by Smith. Tampa Bay manager Larry Rothschild
came out to argue and was thrown out of the game by third base
umpire Rocky Roe.
</P>
<P>
   Valentin scored on a Mo Vaughn single.
</P>
<P>
   Avery left after six and was replaced by Derek Lowe. The Devil
Rays immediately mounted a threat, as Stocker singled and moved to
second on a bunt. After getting Quinton McCracken to ground to
second, moving Stocker to third, Lowe was replaced by lefthander
Ron Mahay. He did his job, getting Boggs to fly to left.
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay threatened again in the eighth, and Boston escaped
with some marvelous defensive play. Fred McGriff led off with a
single to right and moved to third on a hit by Smith. Martinez
followed with a grounder to second. Rather than give up the run,
Lou Merloni threw home in time to get McGriff.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Corsi replaced Mahay and was part of an even better play.
With runners on first and second, he got Mike DiFelice to hit into
a 3-6-1 double play. Vaughn made a brilliant stop, ranging far to
his right, to start the play, and Corsi hustled to the bag at first
and scooped up a low throw from Garciaparra.
</P>
<P>
   Boston squandered chances in the eighth and ninth innings.
</P>
<P>
   With one out in the 10th, Boggs doubled to left, his third hit
of the night, off Gordon. McGriff was walked intentionally. Smith
grounded into a force at second, Boggs moving to third. But the
threat died when Martinez flied to center after working Gordon
through 10 pitches.
</P>
</TEXT>
