<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-DEVILRAYS-BOS-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
O'LEARY, SOX GO EXTRA MILE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY WHITESIDE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ One thing the Red Sox are doing well this year is
beating up on the have-nots. If there is a shortcut to the American
League playoffs this year, that may be it.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, Sunday night's 3-2 victory over the Tampa Bay Devil
Rays before 27,768 at Fenway Park falls into that category. The
game took 10 innings and both teams had chances to win. But the Red
Sox prevailed on a clutch RBI single to right by Troy O'Leary. It
wasn't pretty, but these days it doesn't really matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We pitched good and we played good,'' said manager Jimy
Williams. ``When we do that, we've always got a chance to win.
Tampa Bay had a tough lefty in Tony Saunders. But we competed, and
that's what you ask for from your players.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams has been preaching this philosophy all year. A victory
like Sunday night's means his players not only are listening to the
game plan but are executing it. The Sox got six decent innings out
of Steve Avery, who left with the game tied at 2-2. Then they won
it as Derek Lowe, Ron Mahay, Jim Corsi, and Tom Gordon performed
their roles to perfection, holding Tampa Bay scoreless.
</P>
<P>
   Saunders also provided six good innings; the Devil Rays used six
pitchers in relief of him. O'Leary made the final one, righthander
Jim Mecir, pay.
</P>
<P>
   The Boston 10th started with a single by Nomar Garciaparra off
Albie Lopez. That was followed by a bunt hit by Mike Benjamin, who
had entered in the eighth as a pinch hitter. Tampa Bay then brought
in Matt Ruebel, who induced Reggie Jefferson to line to short.
</P>
<P>
   Then Tampa Bay manager Larry Rothschild turned to Mecir, who has
a reputation for pitching lefties tough and getting ground balls.
He got the grounder, as on a 2-2 count O'Leary hit a sharp shot
that first baseman Fred McGriff could not handle. It was McGriff
who had foiled an O'Leary bid for extra bases on a hard smash in
the eighth inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``He got me the first time,'' said O'Leary. ``I thought I had
hit the ball real good. But McGriff never moved off the bag and was
right there. The second time was different. Mecir is a righthander,
but he's tough on lefties. I think he wanted me to hit into a
double play. And if you look at my stats, I do. But it didn't
happen. He threw me a couple of fastballs inside. So I looked for
one and I got it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox (39-26) swept the two-game, rain-shortened series.
</P>
<P>
   The teams combined for 23 hits, 13 by Tampa Bay, but it was
pitching and defense that won the game.
</P>
<P>
   In the Tampa Bay eighth, McGriff and Bobby Smith led off with
singles, putting runners on first and third. McGriff then tried to
score on a ground ball to second and was nailed by a perfect throw
by Lou Merloni.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were cheating in a little bit,'' said Merloni. ``If it was
hit hard and we had a shot at McGriff, we said we'd go for it. The
ball wasn't hit too hard. But I kinda caught it high and he wasn't
going too hard to home plate. So I came up throwing. Probably if
I'd thought about it I would have gone for a double play. It was
just something that happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Then Williams brought in Jim Corsi, who got Mike DiFelice to hit
into a 3-6-1 double play. Mo Vaughn made a dynamite stop to start
it. Corsi finished it with a nice scoop of a wide throw by Nomar
Garciaparra.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't a Mickey Mouse pick,'' said Corsi. ``It was a good
one. I just busted my butt to get over to first. I got to the bag
and I was looking for the ball. Nomar got rid of it quick and threw
it a little bit to the right. I picked it. Afterwards, I got
excited.''
</P>
<P>
   He flipped the ball to the umpire backhanded and put on the
biggest smile at Fenway.
</P>
<P>
   ``What a game,'' said Williams. ``You had Merloni's (throw),
Vaughn and Corsi on the double play in the eighth, Nomar's plays at
short. Their lefthander was putting goose eggs on the board. But
Avery pitched a good game for us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
