<HEADLINE>
PIPPEN'S PAIN PUSHES JORDAN TO GREATEST FEAT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs for rewriting throughout) (sw) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALT LAKE CITY _ The limping Scottie Pippen worked his way
through the pack surrounding a fatigued but elated Michael Jordan
and embraced him with the most gingerly of hugs when it was over.
</P>
<P>
   It was a most powerful moment for a duo that may never be
together again if the Bulls dismantle. A second later, Pippen, who
played the game with severe back pain, was in tears because of his
emotions as the Bulls celebrated their sixth title in eight years,
eliminating the Jazz, 87-86, on Sunday night in Game 6 of the
National Basketball Association finals at the Delta Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was hurting pretty bad,'' Pippen said. ``At the start of the
game I was able to get a dunk and I came down, and the pain built
from that point. Every time I tried to run I was getting spasms. I
took the treatment, and told them I was going to try and gut it
out. I felt that my presence on the floor would mean more than just
sitting in the locker room.''
</P>
<P>
   Without Pippen, the victory may have been Jordan's greatest
feat. He put together a miracle performance that included 45
points, while Pippen played on with his face pinched in pain
because of a sore back that left him limited, at best, and absent
for much of Game 6.
</P>
<P>
   Pippen's restricted effectiveness touched every part of the
Bulls' strategy, from rebounding to defense, from offense to
Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   Without Pippen, Jordan was left to fight the fatigue of this
long series and long playoff run. Somehow, he made up the void.
Jordan stripped Karl Malone with 18 seconds left, then come down to
hit the game-winning shot with 5.2 seconds left to give the Bulls
the title.
</P>
<P>
   Pippen had a cortisone shot Saturday and felt some relief from
the pain that crept up on him after taking five charges in Game 3.
The discomfort may have had something to do with a 2-of-16
performance in Game 4, an effort that belied a series effort that
had many proclaiming him the most valuable player.
</P>
<P>
   Now the player who had been a defensive menace to the Jazz
walked off the floor and disappeared into the tunnel leading to the
locker room with 4 minutes 56 seconds left in the first quarter.
All of the electric stimulation he had before the game to loosen up
his back had not helped.
</P>
<P>
   Pippen underwent further treatment through the first half. He
returned to start the second half with a wince, only to leave
again. He came back with 9 minutes left in the game. Although he
was severely limited, Pippen's presence meant something. At least
he could function as a decoy.
</P>
<P>
   It was going to be up to Jordan to grab the Bulls by the collar
and keep them in the game. Jordan played all but two minutes in the
first half, ending it by hitting 9 of 19 shots for 23 points to
keep the Bulls within reach of the Jazz, down by just 49-45.
</P>
<P>
   Even when Pippen returned in the third quarter, he was more of a
decoy than a playmaker. The Jazz had to respect his presence, but
Pippen was clearly not himself. That was obvious midway through the
third quarter when he missed a layup that normally would have been
made via an explosive dunk.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan has always known how important Pippen has been to his
success and to his team's.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Scottie Pippen is a major reason why we're here,''
Jordan said before Game 5. ``I think he's a unique and creative
player. The harmony between us is incomparable. You can't compare
it to anything. It's just a rhythm you build with another player.
To play without him is like a slap in the face for me.''
</P>
<P>
   This was Jordan, wondering how he would play next year if Pippen
bolted Chicago in free agency. Pippen wouldn't commit to anything
on Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to have to let it all soak in and think about that
later,'' Pippen said. ``There are a lot of opportunities for me,
and I have to look down the road at my future. After all this soaks
in, you just never know what's going to happen.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
