</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-CAPITALS-KOLZIG-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOLZIG CAN'T STOP TIDE VS. WINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ For three rounds, he had been the story. He
outplayed his best friend, Bruins goalie Byron Dafoe, in the first
series. In the second, against Ottawa, he shined against the
offensive talents of Alexei Yashin and Daniel Alfredsson. Then, he
outdominated the Dominator _ Dominik Hasek _ in leading the
Washington Capitals to the club's first Stanley Cup finals.
</P>
<P>
   Like Godzilla, after whom he is nicknamed, Olaf Kolzig had been
bigger than life in the postseason _ until now. The Capitals'
stellar netminder and his teammates are one loss from being swept
in the finals by the defending champion Red Wings. If Detroit wins
Tuesday night in Game 4 at the MCI Center, it will mark the fourth
time in four years that the finals have been won in a sweep.
</P>
<P>
   After Game 3 Saturday night, which was won on a shot by Sergei
Fedorov with 4:51 left in regulation after Brian Bellows had
rallied Washington to a 1-1 tie only 4:34 earlier, Kolzig sat in
his locker-room stall fielding questions about what has gone wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could just as easily be up 3-0 and I think everybody in
this dressing room knows that,'' said Kolzig. ``I'm not going to go
out on a limb and say we outplayed the Red Wings by any means
because that's not true. But a bounce here, no call there, we could
easily be up 3-0 and we all realize that.''
</P>
<P>
   The biggest challenge for the Capitals is remaining positive
despite the enormous odds they face.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have a choice,'' said Kolzig. ``If we fold our tents
and decide just to mail in the game Tuesday, what does that say
about the Washington Capitals? Until they win that fourth game, the
series isn't over. It's obviously a monumental task to come back,
but funnier things have happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Only once. Since 1939, when the best-of-seven championship
format was implemented, teams winning Games 1, 2, and 3 have won
the Cup 23 of 24 times. The only time that didn't happen was in
1942, when Detroit won the first three games and Toronto won four
in a row to win the Cup. Kolzig said he and his teammates are
frustrated by the circumstances yet remain hopeful they can stage a
comeback because all three games have been decided by one goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to use the whole part of it because if you use the
frustrated part of it, you're not going to be anywhere in Game 4,
so we've got to realize we played just as good as these guys and
easily could be up 3-0,'' he said. ``If we get frustrated, we've
got no chance in Game 4.''
</P>
<P>
   After losing Game 1, Washington appeared in the driver's seat in
Game 2 with 3-1 and 4-2 leads. But the Red Wings rallied, winning
in overtime. Kolzig said that one really hurt.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had the game in control and it would've gotten us a split
out of there,'' he said. ``Coming into this building, we might have
had a whole lot more confidence. Not to say we didn't have any
confidence, but we would've known we beat the Detroit Red Wings. In
the back of our minds, we were saying, `We're right there with
them, we can beat these guys.' But until we actually do, I don't
know if we would've come out with quite as much hunger as if we
would have won the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Kolzig said perhaps depth has been the difference but he also
allowed that perhaps the real difference has been an intangible _
knowing how to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``Four years ago, they lost four straight to New Jersey, so they
knew what it was like to lose,'' he said. ``The year after, they
lost in the semifinals to Colorado. They knew how it felt to lose.
Last year, they put it all together. They took all the experiences
from the past and put it together and now they know how it feels to
win. I don't want to say, `Well, maybe that's what we need is to
lose' because that's definitely the experience we don't want, but
if we can get back here next year, then we would know how it feels
right now. I still think we're in this series.''
</P>
<P>
   While the Capitals' offense has been stymied in two of the three
games, Kolzig said the Red Wings deserve credit for preventing
Washington from implementing its game plan. At the same time, the
Wings have come at the Capitals from all angles.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're obviously a pretty deep team,'' Kolzig said. ``You
really can't concentrate on one guy like you did in the first two
series. We had to concentrate on (Bruins center) Jason Allison and
then Alexei Yashin in the second. If you take Steve Yzerman, that
leaves Fedorov. If you take Fedorov, that leaves Yzerman and Igor
Larionov. You can just go down the list with the amount of depth
these guys have. We have to play great against them as a team and
not concentrate on one individual.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're the defending champs, obviously, they know what it
takes to win. They feel they can win every game. We've got to find
a way to believe we're invincible, too.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
