<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-DELAHOYA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DE LA HOYA MUST EXTEND HIS REACH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; EL PASO _ Oscar De La Hoya said he wanted to fight the best
again Saturday night, but he continues to fight the rest.
</P>
<P>
   Immediately after devouring a French pastry named Patrick
Charpentier in less than three rounds at the Sun Bowl, De La Hoya
told a worldwide television audience that he ``wanted a chance to
make history.'' Minutes later he was talking about an already
scheduled September rematch with aged Julio Cesar Chavez, a fighter
who already is history.
</P>
<P>
   In November, promoter Bob Arum already has said, De La Hoya will
fight another Mexican national, 154-pound champion Yory Boy Campas,
whom rising welterweight challenger Jose Luis Lopez made history
when he beat him half to death, thus convincing Campas to add seven
pounds to get away from people like him.
</P>
<P>
   Those are not fights designed to make history. They are fights
designed to make money, an approach to prize fighting that is not
without precedent but is one whose time has run out for De La Hoya
if he truly hopes to reach the place he and his handlers seem to
think is his birthright.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's never been a perfect fighter, but Oscar has so much
potential he could end his career, in most people's eyes, as the
greatest fighter who ever lived,'' Gil Clancy, the veteran trainer
of Emile Griffith, said after his latest pupil had knocked
Charpentier flat three times before the fight was stopped at 1:56
of the third round, which was only two times less than Charpentier
hit him all night.
</P>
<P>
   For anyone who ever saw Sugar Ray Robinson when he was really
sweet or Muhammad Ali when he was really Ali or Sugar Ray Leonard
when he really could get away with stealing another man's nickname
or Mavelous Marvin Hagler when he really was, that seems a long
reach. But the '90s are the time of hyperbole and hype, so a
fighter who is 28-0 with world championships in four weight classes
inspires such comments regardless of their validity.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, they might prove accurate because De La Hoya is only
25 with at least five good years ahead of him and probably more.
But by that age, Leonard, for example, already had fought Roberto
Duran twice, Wilfred Benitez, and Thomas Hearns. De La Hoya has
fought only one man, Pernell Whitaker, who could be termed a
world-class fighter.
</P>
<P>
   To be fair, De La Hoya did fight a string of former or present
champions since he first won the junior lightweight title several
years ago, but these days boxing has more belts than Brooks
Brothers, so a champion's belt no longer automatically means you
can fight. It assures only that you're well-connected.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, De La Hoya is both. He is well-connected and he can
fight. But when will he fight the welterweights most likely to
fight back? When will he step in with World Boxing Association
champion Ike Quartey or International Boxing Federation titleholder
Felix Trinidad or even Lopez, who on his best days even De La Hoya
conceded last week was perhaps his most difficult opponent at his
present weight?
</P>
<P>
   Sounding like a revivalist preacher, Arum will say ``How long?
Not long!'' But then he schedules Chavez, a fight De La Hoya now
calls ``personal,'' and Campas, a fight that is about only one
thing _ sucking more money out of the wallets of De La Hoya's rabid
Hispanic fan base.
</P>
<P>
   Arum says he has offered Quartey $3.5 million, Trinidad $7
million, and Whitaker $4 million knowing those figures will not
make any of those fights because they are not negotiations, they
are dictates, and such men will not be dictated to.
</P>
<P>
   In Whitaker's case, $4 million at the time it was offered was
nearly a 50 percent pay cut for a rematch when he barely lost the
first fight on a night that did big pay-per-view business.
</P>
<P>
   In Trinidad's case, $7 million is more than he can make
elsewhere but is barely 30 percent of the likely revenues from
their all-Hispanic confrontation. A mere No. 1 contender like
Charpentier could end up with 25 percent if a bout of his simply
went to purse bids, so why would Trinidad or his father/manager
agree to such a number?
</P>
<P>
   In Quartey's case, he is in the midst of legal battles with
past, present, and probably future promoters and managers, so Arum
knows he is in no position to make a deal with De La Hoya or anyone
else of note until those crossed lines are straightened out.
</P>
<P>
   So how can such fights be made if that is Arum's approach? The
same way they were made when Leonard was fighting Duran twice and
Hearns and Benitez. They will be made the day De La Hoya tells Arum
rather than the world that he wants to fight the best.
</P>
<P>
   The day he walks into Arum's office in Las Vegas and tells him
to make the Trinidad fight or the Quartey fight or the Lopez fight
or he'll find someone who will, those fights will be made. Until
then, Arum will continue to make matches like the ones De La Hoya
has fought for the past two years.
</P>
<P>
   He will make high-paying, low-risk pay-per-view matches like the
ones with Hector Camacho, Chavez, or Campas and the
less-high-paying but even lower-risk ones on HBO for $4 million a
pop like Saturday night's batting practice exhibition against
Charpentier.
</P>
<P>
   That fight left nearly 45,000 fans in El Paso wildly cheering De
La Hoya but it left boxing experts cold. It was what it was
designed to be. It was an execution for De La Hoya's benefit,
restoring the belief for some that the knockout power he had at 130
and 135 pounds has come with him up to 147 even though he had
stopped only one man, an African version of Charpentier named David
Kamau, since moving up to the welterweight division to fight
Whitaker 14 months ago.
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya finally seems to have sensed that while his
popularity among Hispanics has skyrocketed, his pay-per-view and
HBO ratings slowly have begun to erode. He remains arguably the
second biggest draw in the sport next to the Godzilla of boxing,
Mike Tyson. Yet his numbers are going down at an age when they
should be going up, and in his heart he knows why.
</P>
<P>
   They have begun to slide because it is one thing to talk about
fighting the best and quite another to do it.
</P>
<P>
   So it is time for De La Hoya to stop talking about greatness and
start reaching for it, and that will require the one thing
promoters like Arum abhor. It will require he take a risk.
</P>
<P>
   Publicly, Arum says Trinidad and Quartey will go out as quickly
as Charpentier and perhaps he is right, although it is dubious. If
they do, De La Hoya's greatness will be established regardless of
what follows those fights. If he fights great battles and wins
despite grave difficulties, as Leonard did in his first
confrontation with Hearns, De La Hoya's greatness will be
established regardless of what follows as well. If he fights a
great battle and loses, as Leonard did in his first meeting with
Duran, De La Hoya's greatness still could be established if what
follows are stirring victories over similar opponents as Leonard's
were.
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya long has said he wanted to pattern his career after
Leonard's. Arum used to say the same thing. So the path to the
greatness they seek already is laid out for them.
</P>
<P>
   That path makes a man rich but not because he seeks only money.
That path leads a man to greatness not because he can attract young
Hispanic girls to throw their bras at him, as some did to De La
Hoya last week, but because he can stand up when men as young and
fast as he is throw punches at him.
</P>
<P>
   So if greatness is what Oscar De La Hoya truly seeks, all he has
to do is get on that path Hagler and Leonard and Ali and Robinson
walked.
</P>
<P>
   It is the path that leads to fearsome opponents like Trinidad
and Lopez and Quartey and others that may follow them.
</P>
<P>
   It is the path of pain.
</P>
<P>
   To boxing greatness, it is the only path that exists.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-15-98 0106EDT &QL; 
