<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-FIRE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVOLUTION BURNED BY FIRE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM GREENIDGE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ One could blame the fact that the New
England Revolution are without Joe-Max Moore and Mike Burns, who
are playing for the US national team at the World Cup. Or maybe
that Jair is out of the lineup until the end of the season because
of a left ankle fracture.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe that defender Manny Motajo was sitting out because of a
couple of yellow cards he received the week before against the Los
Angeles Galaxy, which means that the Revolution were playing
without a player because of that reason for the third time in the
last four weeks.
</P>
<P>
   But Sunday's 3-1 loss to the Chicago Fire before 6,823 at
Foxboro Stadium (17,054 paid), was for a different reason.
</P>
<P>
   Defender David Nakhid sprained his right ankle early in the
second half, with 41:13 left in the game, as he ran out of bounds
next to his team's bench. He went back in the game, but then was
substituted for by Dahir Mohammed.
</P>
<P>
   ``One player makes a difference in our chemistry,'' said the
Revolution's Thomas Rongen, who attended but did not coach Sunday
because of travel surrounding his assisting the US World Cup team.
``When David went out, we were not able to physically or mentally
stay with it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution were fine in the first half, the teams tied, 1-1,
at halftime. But the Fire scored the only two goals in the final 45
minutes. It was the sixth consecutive loss for the Revolution, who
are now 4-9. The expansion Fire are 9-5 and have won their last
seven contests.
</P>
<P>
   ``They kind of established their game in the second half,'' said
Revolution assistant coach Renato Capobianco, who ran the team from
the bench. ``Their game tatically changed with Nakhid's injury and
you can understand why Chicago is on that winning streak. Their
defense as a unit and the way they possessed the ball in the attack
with numbers, they didn't allow you very much time to get
organized.''
</P>
<P>
   The Fire, who at one time had a five-game losing string, scored
first, in the 25th minute when Jerzy Podbrozny converted a pass
from Jesse Marsch on the right side. Revolution midfielder Ted
Chronopoulos stretched to try to get to the pass, but he couldn't
reach it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't hear anyone tell me there was a runner behind me,''
Chronopoulos said. ``I should have known there was someone behind
me. I take the total responsibility for it.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Revolution evened it in the 39th minute, on a penalty
kick by Raul Diaz Arce. He kicked a blazer to the low left side,
past Fire goalkeeper Zach Thornton. It was his eighth goal of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   But the Revolution could have done better. ``We had four good
chances to score that first half and we didn't put in those
chances,'' Capobianco said. ``We need to put those chances away and
we didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Then came the second half, when the Fire did everything well.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't stick with the runners very well,'' Chronopoulos
said. ``Our defense didn't play that well.''
</P>
<P>
   Richie Kotschau scored in the 60th minute, on a header from 12
yards out. It was the third straight game in which Kotschau has had
a goal. And then came the insurance goal, at the 85th minute, when
Podbrozny, while facing Revolution defender Richard Goulooze,
flipped the ball high over his head, and over Ian Feuer's
6-foot-7-inch frame as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a good goal,'' Feuer said. ``You can tell he's a class
player, the way he stroked it and it dipped just under the
crossbar.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
