<HEADER>
A8900 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-JAZZ-MALONE-NYT &LR;      06-15 0748
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-JAZZ-MALONE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALONE HAS HIS TITLE SHOT RIPPED AWAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALT LAKE CITY _ Karl Malone turned around, and it was him
again.
</P>
<P>
   It was the man who has always managed to steal the moment Malone
has craved and swipe the title that he has struggled to grab for 13
years. It was Michael Jordan again. And at some point, long after
he arrives home from the Delta Center, Malone may look over his
shoulder and see Jordan's haunting figure once more, just as he did
on Sunday night with 18.9 seconds left in Game 6 of the National
Basketball Association finals.
</P>
<P>
   That was when Jordan, part of a double team, stripped the ball
away and snatched the series' life from Malone. A stunned Malone
could only watch Jordan tear off from the scene like a getaway car.
</P>
<P>
   ``Karl never saw me coming,'' Jordan said. ``I was able to knock
the ball away.''
</P>
<P>
   Seconds later, Malone witnessed Jordan transform his turnover
into a title-winning shot with 5.2 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   Failing to counter Jordan's jumper, the Jazz was left to exit
its own building with an 87-86 loss. As Malone departed, he had to
make his way across a floor flooded by the Bulls as they celebrated
their sixth title in eight years.
</P>
<P>
   Malone walked after with a couple of televised comments, saying,
``I'm not a quitter,'' when asked about his future. But there was
nothing more. He did not show up for interviews to face questions
about his lapse at the end or how Jordan had swooped down to
overshadow him again. Malone's 31 points were no match for Jordan's
45.
</P>
<P>
   So for the first time in anyone's memory, John Stockton walked
in before the cameras and microphones all alone after the game. No
Malone by his side. Just as the Bulls had done all season, on
Sunday night they had cut the tether between Stockton and Malone.
For two years, Stockton and Malone have been tied together in a
three-legged race to catch Jordan in the finals. They fell again.
</P>
<P>
   ``As you may expect, I'm not real open with my emotions,'' the
typically stoic Stockton said. ``But it's a painful experience, I
can tell you that.''
</P>
<P>
   Stockton could have erased Malone's mistake, but his rushed
3-pointer at the buzzer bounced off the front of the rim. Just like
the Jazz, the ball fell short of the mark. But Stockton was not
going to blame Malone for this, not his partner. ``I like my
chances with Karl every time,'' Stockton said. ``He scores, he
makes plays. So there.''
</P>
<P>
   So the Jazz players walk away with images in their heads that
will stay there for some time. Malone will have Jordan to think
about. And the Jazz will have a couple of calls to remember. The
24-second violation that wasn't, for one. In the first half, Howard
Eisley appeared to get off a 3-pointer just before the shot clock
expired. But it was waved off.
</P>
<P>
   ``What are you going to do?'' Coach Jerry Sloan asked. ``You're
still the loser.''
</P>
<P>
   The Jazz are not packing it in, though. Sloan does not buy the
belief that this was the last chance for Stockton, who is 36, and
Malone, who turns 35 next month.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think our future will be just fine,'' Sloan said.
``Obviously there are some young players out there and young teams
to compete with. But we've been hearing the same story for five
years, and how our window of opportunity has closed.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Malone's chance to steal a moment from Jordan is over.
Jordan may retire, Scottie Pippen may exit as a free agent and the
Bulls may never be the same. But typical Jazz, stubborn to the end,
few of them believe this was their last shot at the six-time
champions.
</P>
<P>
   ``This won't be Michael's last one,'' Stockton said. ``That's
been a nice story. But he's not quitting. He'll be back. Scottie
will be back and Phil Jackson will be back. I'm tired of hearing
it.''
</P>
<P>
   The sound might not have been so deafening if Malone had held on
with 18.9 seconds left. If he had, the Jazz might have pushed the
Bulls to a Game 7. But it has been in these critical moments _ like
the time he froze at the free-throw line of Game 2 in Chicago
during last year's finals _ when Malone has been left to see Jordan
emerge as the star.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a bitter pill to swallow,'' said Sloan, who was
talking in general but might as well have been referring to Malone.
``But that's why they are champions. You have to be strong mentally
and not allow things like turnovers to happen. Michael made big
plays, and he deserves credit for that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
