<SLUG> BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-OKAROH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OKAROH LENDS REVOLUTION HELPING HAND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM GREENIDGE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ There's no question that Francis Okaroh
misses his home, Woburn. He played for the Revolution for two
seasons and was named the team's best defensive player, even better
than headliner Alexi Lalas.
</P>
<P>
   It showed during his first five or six games this season with
expansion Chicago that he was hoping the Revolution and the Fire
would work a trade to get him back to Foxboro Stadium. It was never
worked out, though. The Revolution, who left him available for the
expansion draft, have no plans to bring him back.
</P>
<P>
   That's when Okaroh told himself he was going to start playing
rather than wondering if he would spend his entire season in
Chicago. And that's just about the time the Fire started their
winning string, which is now at seven after Sunday's 3-1 win over
the Revolution.
</P>
<P>
   ``Francis has been great with us,'' said Fire coach Bob Bradley.
``He's defending with experience and he can play with the ball out
of the backfield. He's always trying to help our younger players
and we picked him because we still feel he's one of the best
defenders in the league.
</P>
<P>
   ``This wasn't easy with him, this is his home. We try to show
him how much respect we have for his play. He's become a large part
of our team.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I told myself that the trade wasn't going to happen,'' said
Okaroh, the former Norwood High soccer coach and Boston
University's No. 3 all-time scorer. ``I want to stamp my name with
this organization. Those other two seasons with the Revolution are
in the past.''
</P>
<P>
   At 34, the Nigerian-born Okaroh is helping the younger players
on the team, passing on the experience he has gained while playing
with the Revolution, seven games for the Nigerian national team,
and 13 games in 1987-88 with the Cleveland Force indoors team.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was here I also did some coaching and it's something I
like doing,'' he said. ``When I see a younger player with
potential, I help coach any way I can. It's a young team and I have
to read the game and get involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think to some people we're still an expansion team. They
still think that we don't have a good defense, but we don't mind
that. We just keep working, and we're still not anywhere where we
want to be, but we hope to get there by the time the playoffs
come.''
</P>
<P>
   Early on, the Fire lost five in a row. They are winning now with
the same personnel, and they have the best goals-against in Major
League Soccer (1.16) and a nice 9-5 record.
</P>
<P>
   With Okaroh spearheading things back on defense.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
