<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-WORLDCUP-PREKI-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PREKI AN OLD HAND AT THIS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; PARIS _ The US national team spent Sunday attempting to avoid
attention while preparing for its opening game in the World Cup
finals.
</P>
<P>
   Team officials had invited the press to an 11:30 a.m. training
session at Parc des Princes, site of Monday night's match against
Germany, then went elsewhere for a 10 a.m. practice. The players
arrived at Parc des Princes, a 40,000-seat stadium in the 15th
arrondisement, at 12:40 p.m. and within 20 minutes had toured the
field, talked briefly with about 75 journalists, and rushed to
board a bus.
</P>
<P>
   A national team functionary disrupted interviews and urged
players to hurry through the ``mixed zone'' that had been set up
for that purpose. Alexi Lalas and Eric Wynalda, two of the more
popular choices for both the domestic and international press,
actually hurdled a fence to get away. They looked less like
professional athletes than starving artists pursued by gendarmes
after skipping on the check.
</P>
<P>
   It was a ludicrous scene. The US players, isolated in Chateau de
Pizay for two weeks, seemed appreciative that someone was
interested in them. And, as tout le monde knows, they need the
publicity.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the players did not stay long enough for anyone
to measure whether the pressure of the World Cup was affecting them
as much as their administrators.
</P>
<P>
   At least midfielder Preki Radosavljevic seemed unaffected by the
frenetic attitudes. He became a US citizen in 1996, but part of his
heart remains with his former countrymen and teammates in
Yugoslavia. Preki must have had other worries besides Monday
night's match.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be a tough game,'' Preki said. ``We'll see.
Hopefully, we will be ready to play. But you really can't know
until then.''
</P>
<P>
   Preki the pragmatist. He is a virtuoso player, the most
brilliant of the national team at solving one-on-one
confrontations. With interviewers, he charms with a clever line, a
quaint phrase, a blunt assessment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yugoslavia is where my family lives and I will always go back
there,'' Preki said. ``Not to stay, though. America is my home now.
What I would like is for Yugoslavia and the US to qualify for the
second round. That would mean we would have to knock Germany out.''
</P>
<P>
   That is a long shot, but Preki should be expected to support his
homeland and his home, especially since he played with many on
Yugoslavia's national team while developing in the Red Star
Belgrade system.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have not talked to any of them for a while,'' Preki said.
``I am staying away from that because they are the opposition. I
talk to a lot of friends and family from Yugoslavia, but not many
of them will be here because it is hard to get out of the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yugoslavia should have a good team because they have a lot of
talent. They just have to play together. I always thought they
would be better with the Croatian players and all the others,
because if you put them all together there is even more talent.''
</P>
<P>
   This is Preki's first and last World Cup. He has had an
adventurous life so far _ time in the post-Tito army, a
professional career in the US, England, Portugal. Now, Preki is
raising a family in Kansas City and he is eager for the spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   But he likely will not be in the starting lineup against
Germany, Iran (in Lyon June 21), or Yugoslavia (in Nantes June 25).
Preki is faced with a conundrum _ though he is the team's most
skillful player, until his teammates catch up he will not be a
full-time performer. In other words, the US will be in a
conservative, defensive mode in an attempt to avoid being
devastated.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will play the way I always play,'' Preki said. ``I will play
to help the team. How long can you defend? You can't defend for the
whole tournament. We will have to play offensively sometimes, score
a couple of goals if we want to make it to the second round.''
</P>
<P>
   Preki did just that in the last tournament, the CONCACAF Gold
Cup in California. He scored the winner against Costa Rica as the
US qualified for the semifinals, and the winner against Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't try to copy anybody else,'' Preki said. ``Why try to
copy when you are 35 years old? I do my own thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like the Germans. It doesn't matter if you are old. It
matters how you play.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
