<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-15 01:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8908 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-BULLS-JAZZ-BOS &LR;      06-15 0929
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-BULLS-JAZZ-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPEAT THREE-PEAT FOR BULLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALT LAKE CITY _ They may have grown tired of each other, of the
Medici Court intrigue in the organization, of the waffling comments
of the supernova, and the boorish antics of their
attention-seeeking non-conformist.
</P>
<P>
   But they never have grown tired of the feeling they felt Sunday
night, when the final horn sounded in a suddenly din-less Delta
Center, signaling yet another championship for the Chicago Bulls.
Once again, they set aside all the friction, tumult, and lunacy and
triumphed when it mattered most.
</P>
<P>
   Title No. 6 came courtesy of an 87-86 victory over the Jazz, a
likable, laudable lot who simply happen to be, like so many others
this decade, victims of bad timing. They had to confront the
messiah, Michael Jordan. The series MVP, in what could be the final
game of his brilliant career, had 45 points, including the
game-winner, as Chicago took the series, 4-2.
</P>
<P>
   With Scottie Pippen (bad back) all but a decoy, Jordan basically
turned the clock back to 1988 and did everything. His shot wasn't
always falling _ he was 15 for 35 _ but he got to the line (12 for
15) and hit two biggies down the stretch.
</P>
<P>
   In the final 40 seconds, Jordan blew past Bryon Russell for a
hoop off the glass, then stripped Karl Malone to force a huge
turnover _ ``He never saw me coming,'' Jordan said. And, of course,
hit the winner with 5.2 seconds left. That was a stop-and-pop from
the foul line, made easier when Russell slipped, giving Jordan an
open look. If that is his last shot, he went out in true style.
</P>
<P>
   ``The moment starts to become the moment for me,'' Jordan said
of that last possession. ``Things move slowly and I saw that
moment. I took advantage of that moment. I never doubted myself. I
never doubted during the whole game. Scottie was hurt. Dennis
(Rodman) was in foul trouble. But we kept hanging in there.''
</P>
<P>
   Said coach Phil Jackson, ``Michael is a guy who comes through.
He always comes through. He's a real-life hero.''
</P>
<P>
   The Jazz, too, were heroic to the end. Malone had a big game,
with 31 points, 11 rebounds, and 7 assists. His shot was falling.
But he also had five turnovers, including the big one with 18.9
seconds to play when Jordan took it away from him.
</P>
<P>
   ``We fought hard,'' Malone said. ``It's tough. It's a tough
loss. But give them credit. They won. What else can you say?''
</P>
<P>
   Utah, which also got 17 points from Jeff Hornacek, looked like
it might be home free when John Stockton (10 points, 5 assists)
knocked down a trey with 41.9 seconds to play. That snapped an
83-83 tie and put all the pressure on the Bulls. But putting
pressure on Jordan is almost asking for it. Even though he had
missed five straight shots, he kept firing and made the last two.
</P>
<P>
   Utah still had plenty of time. But Stockton missed a long trey
and the rebound was swatted away, ending a truly exciting game.
Coach Jerry Sloan said he wasn't happy with the way Utah ran the
final play, ``but we were just trying to get a shot. You just can't
afford to give them a second chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Once the ball bounced away and the game ended, the Bulls' bench
erupted. Jordan and Jackson hugged and Sloan, classy to the end,
stayed on the court to congratulate the gutsy Bulls. Malone hugged
Pippen, and Pippen broke down in tears. Rodman, who had 7 points
and 8 rebounds in 39 big minutes, celebrated, undoubtedly knowing
he now can hit Las Vegas with regularity. Jordan found his mother
and gave her a hug.
</P>
<P>
   Pippen played only 26 minutes, 19 in the second half. His sore
back was the topic of much pregame conversation and it was learned
that he had had a cortisone shot. He tried to be his usual force,
but clearly was in pain after opening the scoring with a dunk.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was so difficult,'' he said. ``I felt I was letting my
team down. I tried to gut it out and I felt my presence out there
was important. I didn't know how much I was going to be able to
help.''
</P>
<P>
   Both teams shot well _ Utah was at 50 percent, the Bulls at 51 _
and, over the final 39 minutes, the biggest lead by either team was
6. The Jazz led, 83-79, with 2:30 left on a Malone jumper, but
Jordan then hit four straight free throws. He scored the Bulls'
final 8 points.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, however, the triumph came as much because of
Chicago's perseverance as its ability to shield. This was a team so
overloaded by distraction _ a team that seemingly was rent asunder
in theory before it played a single game _ it's a wonder it even
got this far. Jordan may or may not come back. Pippen may or may
not come back. Jackson may not come back.
</P>
<P>
   ``We planned this as our last year,'' Jackson said. ``We're
celebrating this as our last year. Unless something unusual comes
out of left field, I don't expect to see us back together again.''
</P>
<P>
   Their chaotic season started with that uncharacteristic loss in
the FleetCenter to the running, trapping Celtics. The team absorbed
the loss of Pippen for 38 games and still shared the best record in
the league with the Jazz. It endured the ongoing soap opera of
Jackson's future, the occasional Al Haig injections of muscle by
management and, finally, its severest playoff test in years. It's
unlikely any team has had to go through what this team went through
_ and not only lived to tell about it, but learned to celebrate.
</P>
<P>
   This may indeed be the end. If it was, the Bulls showed, as
Madonna sings, ``there's no greater power than the power of
goodbye.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-15-98 0138EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980615.0015 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-15 01:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8909 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-BULLS-JAZZ-1STLD-     06-15 1127
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-BULLS-JAZZ-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BULLS SNATCH ANOTHER CHAMPIONSHIP WITH 87-86 VICTORY OVER THE JAZZ
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs for rewriting throughout)  (sw) 
 By MIKE WISE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALT LAKE CITY _ At some point, his skills will have to recede.
He will not hit the last-second shot or drive the lane with fire
and flair. He will be more than good, but less than great. He will
not be able to put all the magic together in one unreal sequence _
the way he did on Sunday night, seizing another world title in 37.1
scintillating seconds at the age of 35.
</P>
<P>
   In an encore that is not likely to be repeated _ but who can
tell anymore? _ Michael Jordan stole the Utah Jazz's soul while
adding the most incredible flourish yet to his legend.
</P>
<P>
   He made an 18-foot jump shot from the top of the key with 5.2
seconds left, sending the Chicago Bulls to their sixth National
Basketball Association title in eight seasons with a pulsating
87-86 victory in Game 6 of the finals. The shot came after he had
stolen the ball from Karl Malone along the baseline with 18.9
seconds remaining and Utah ahead by 1 point.
</P>
<P>
   He had already made a driving layup with his team trailing by 3
points with 37.1 seconds left. He scored the Bulls' last 8 points
as they won the NBA championship by four games to two.
</P>
<P>
   After Jordan's final basket, John Stockton's 3-pointer just
before the buzzer was off target, ending this wild game.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I got the ball, I looked up and saw 18.5 seconds left,''
Jordan said, describing the play that led to his last shot. ``And I
felt like we couldn't call a timeout; it gives the defense an
opportunity to set up. It was a do-or-die situation. I let the time
tick to where I had the court right where I wanted it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Great look. And it went in.''
</P>
<P>
   Stockton had made a 3-pointer to send the fanatical crowd into a
frenzy with 41.9 seconds remaining, seemingly all but sealing a
Game 7 here on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Never had Jordan's throne seemed so shaky, his dynasty so
vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   And then he went to work. He could have been starring in a video
game, or in a Hollywood fantasy _ or both _ when he drove the lane
and scored almost uncontested. He had missed five straight shots
from the perimeter before then, and had been lucky to get to the
free throw line on two out-of-control drives.
</P>
<P>
   He stole the game from Utah. He stole the season. He tamed the
rowdiest crowd in the league. And if he walked out of the
dead-quiet Delta Center on Sunday night and never came back to
basketball, he could retire for the second time knowing he went out
with unmatched brilliance. To go with his sixth championship
trophy, he also won his sixth award as most valuable player of the
finals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's the best performance ever by Michael Jordan at a
critical moment in a critical series,'' Bulls Coach Phil Jackson
said as he puffed on a cigar after the game. ``No one has ever done
it better.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan scored 45 points in 44 minutes, taking 35 shots because
he had to. His teammate Scottie Pippen was suffering from back
spasms.
</P>
<P>
   Toni Kukoc finished with 15 points, and Pippen played as well as
he could in 26 minutes. Malone finished with 31 points and 11
rebounds, working hard for every shot and trying his best to force
a decisive seventh game.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Hornacek added 17 points for Utah, and Stockton was all
over the floor, contributing 10 points and 5 assists.
</P>
<P>
   But the night, as usual at this time of year, belonged to
Jordan. With the Bulls trailing by 49-45 at halftime and by 66-61
after three quarters, he began to pace himself, almost as if he
knew how the ending would play out.
</P>
<P>
   The sequence that truly shifted the momentum involved Jordan's
sneaking along the baseline like a blitzing linebacker about to
blindside a quarterback. Malone had just received the ball in the
post with less than 20 seconds remaining and the Jazz ahead.
Suddenly, Jordan swooped in, and the ball was no longer Utah's.
</P>
<P>
   ``Karl never saw me coming, and I was able to knock the ball
away,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Pippen cried as he began embracing Jordan along with other Bulls
teammates at midcourt, after Stockton's shot had been tipped out to
the perimeter and the clock had sounded. It may have been the
thought of this Bulls team possibly not returning that got to him _
along with Jordan, Pippen and Dennis Rodman, the Bulls have four
other free agents _ or it may just have been watching the greatest
player ever performing another on-court miracle.
</P>
<P>
   But as they raised their sixth championship trophy high into the
air, the Bulls may have been celebrating their perseverance as much
as their dominance. Less than 48 hours after losing their homecourt
advantage with a Game 5 loss at the United Center, failing to give
their hometown fans a party, they came out and proved their merit
by winning a third straight championship for the second time in the
decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw the moment, and I took advantage of the moment,'' Jordan
said. ``I never doubted myself. I knew we had an opportunity to win
this game.''
</P>
<P>
   Eight years ago, a sky-walking shooting guard emerged from the
shadows of Larry Bird and Magic Johnson, grabbed the NBA's torch
and gracefully elevated toward the rim. A new order had come to
what was becoming America's game.
</P>
<P>
   Eight years later, he refuses to come down.
</P>
<P>
   The Bulls' two-year title gap in 1994 and 1995 covered Jordan's
year-and-a-half experiment with baseball. On Sunday night, he
looked as strong and agile as he did the night in 1991 when he
performed a wondrous act of in-air artistry and produced an
indelible NBA finals image, rising for a dunk with his right hand
before switching to his left for a layup at the last possible
moment. He hit the same kind of shot in Game 1 a year ago against
the Jazz in Chicago, putting the defender Bryon Russell on his
heels until he had enough room to release the ball _ just as he did
on Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``He made a couple of big plays right down the stretch,''
Stockton said. ``Mark another one in the books for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Jackson, ``I don't know if anybody could quite write a
dramatic scenario like that one.''
</P>
<P>
   After the Champagne had been sprayed and the cigars lit, Jordan
was asked more about his future than the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully I've put enough memories out there for everybody to
at least have some thoughts about what Michael Jordan did in his 13
or 14 years or whatever it takes, and put some comparisons up there
for kids to follow and compare themselves to,'' he said. ``I have
another life and I know I have to get to it at some place and
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Watching the televised replays of his astonishing finish, the
general feeling among observers after Sunday night was: what's the
rush?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
