<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SHAUGHNESSY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THEIR'S NO HEIR TO JORDAN'S THRONE 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALT LAKE CITY _ Ted Williams, perhaps the greatest hitter who
ever lived, homered in his final at-bat in the big leagues.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine that home run also winning the seventh game of the World
Series, and you begin to understand the Magnitude of Michael.
</P>
<P>
   Babe Ruth ... Joe Louis ... Jackie Robinson ... Muhammad Ali ...
These are the athletes who defined sports in America in this
century. And now there is Michael Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   Now and forever.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Bird was the first to see. Bird played one game against
rookie Jordan in 1984, then told the world that the high-flying kid
was the best he'd ever played against.
</P>
<P>
   Fourteen years, and six championships later, Jordan solidified
his stand as the best ever by single-handedly winning another title
for the Bulls. In what may have been his last NBA game, Jordan
Sunday night scored 45 points and snatched an 87-86 victory from
the Utah Jazz with two baskets and a steal in the final 37.1
seconds.
</P>
<P>
   On a night when back spasms rendered Scottie Pippen useless,
Jordan willed the Bulls to victory. He took 35 of 67 Chicago shots
and scored 52 percent of his team's points. He outscored poor Karl
Malone, 16-6, in the final quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Bulls coach Phil Jackson smoking a cigar a la Red Auerbach,
said, ``I don't know if anybody could write a scenario as amazing
as that. I think it's the best performance I've ever seen by
Michael Jordan in a critical game.''
</P>
<P>
   NBC's Dick Ebersol no doubt will get boffo ratings for Game 6.
The network milked Jordan dry this spring, making Sunday night
``Must-see-Michael'' TV. In May and June, Jordan got more air time
than Mike Wallace, Morley Safer, and Andy Rooney. The Peacock will
miss Michael.
</P>
<P>
   If Jerrys Reinsdorf and Krause wanted to see what the Bulls will
look like without Pippen, this was their opportunity. Pippen spent
most of the first half in the locker room and NBC reported he was
receiving electrical stimulation to loosen his back. There was
unconfirmed speculation that Ahmad Rashad provided the stimulation.
</P>
<P>
   Carrying 11 teammates and the Windy City on his back, Jordan
appeared exhausted in the final quarter. He'd missed five
consecutive shots when John Stockton drilled what looked like a
winning 3-pointer to give Utah an 86-83 lead with 41.9 seconds
left.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, no dope he, called Jordan's number. It took only 4.8
seconds for Jordan to cut the lead to 1 point with a driving layup.
</P>
<P>
   Utah came down and got the ball into the low post where Malone
(31 points) prepared to make a move on Dennis Rodman (the Worm's
latest hairdo makes it look as if he has a soccer ball on his
shoulders). Jordan abandoned Jeff Hornacek and came up behind
Malone on the baseline side. He stripped the ball, then roared down
the floor, and prepared to win another championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw that moment, and when I saw that moment, I took
advantage of it,'' said Jordan. ``I never doubted myself. We were
hanging too close. I knew we were going to have an opportunity to
win this game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw 18.5 seconds left. It was a do-or-die situation. I let
the time tick down till I felt I had the court the way I wanted to.
As soon as (Bryon) Russell reached, he gave me clear range. I made
my shot. Once it went in, I knew it was a game-winning basket.''
</P>
<P>
   Utah called time with 5.2 seconds left and got a long-range
buzzer-beating attempt from Stockton, but the ball hit the front of
the rim and came out long. That's when Chicago folks starting
lighting cigars.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan again said he'll wait until later this summer to decide
if he'll play next season. His decision may hinge on the
whereabouts of Jackson and Pippen, both of whom figure to be gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a gut feeling,'' said his Airness. ``When I walked away
the first time, it was a feeling. When I came back, it was a
feeling. If and when that time comes where I've got to walk away, I
hope that because I walked away no one will look at me any less.
Hopefully, I've put enough memories out there for everybody to at
least have some thoughts about what Michael Jordan did in his 13 or
14 years, and put some comparisons up there for kids to follow and
compare themselves and reach.''
</P>
<P>
   If there are no more games for Michael _ and why should there be
after this? _ Jordan can retire safe in the knowledge that he did
things no other man could do. He made the last two shots of his
career, and stole the ball in between those to deliver another
championship to Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   If this was the end for His Airness, a tape of Game 6 would
serve to explain what he has meant to basketball, what he has meant
to American pro sports.
</P>
<P>
   He hit a home run in his final at-bat in the big leagues. And
the homer won the seventh game of the World Series.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-15-98 0142EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
