<DOCNO> NYT19980615.0017 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-15 01:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8913 &Cx1f; tta-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-ARATON-COLUMN-1ST     06-15 0968
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ARATON-COLUMN-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: JORDAN STANDS ALONE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs for rewriting throughout) (sw) 
 By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALT LAKE CITY _ If this was the end, it looked suspiciously
like the beginning. Michael Jordan against the world, a celebrated
solo act. But even with his odds reduced by age, by Scottie
Pippen's injured back, this wasn't the place, or the time, for
Jordan to surrender pro basketball supremacy to a couple of
reticent stars who only come out to play. Why? The world's most
famously successful athlete willed it that way.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan stripped the ball from noble Karl Malone in the post,
then stole the championship dream of the Utah Jazz. His pull-up
jump shot from 18 feet as the Jazz's Bryon Russell backed away,
fearful of the drive, nailed down the Chicago Bulls' sixth title of
the 1990s on Sunday night at a stunned Delta Center. Stunned, not
surprised, for this was another season ended, another championship
won, as if it were scripted by the writers of Jordan's television
commercials.
</P>
<P>
   In one of them last year, Jordan spoke of repeatedly failing,
but citing his most unfruitful moments as the reasons why he
ultimately succeeds. Jordan made 35 shots on Sunday night. He
missed 20 of them. Then he scored the Bulls' last 8 points, the
crushing jump shot with 5.2 seconds remaining that won Game 6 by
87-86 and finished, finally, the long and winding pro basketball
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, in the fifth game here, I didn't think he could top
that,'' the Bulls' coach, Phil Jackson, said. ``I think he topped
that. I think this was his greatest game in a critical situation to
win the title.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, it was a flu-ridden Jordan rising from a sick bed to
carry the Bulls in the game they had to win here. This time, it was
Jordan, at 35 not the high flier he was, lifting himself and his
team with 45 points in 44 minutes, with the two end-game plays that
will be rewound, again and again, until Malone and the Jazz can
watch them no more.
</P>
<P>
   ``Go ahead, laugh all you want,'' Malone had told the snickering
news media after trustingly revealing how he soothed himself back
in Chicago before his breakout Game 4. He rode shotgun with an
Illinois state trooper, and went off to help weigh trucks.
</P>
<P>
   No more laughing at Malone, at his hobbies, but the truth is,
Malone and the Jazz had the Bulls right where they wanted them on
Sunday night, wounded, stressed, and could not, as Jordan said,
``burst out and leave us standing there.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A tough bunch,'' Jordan graciously called the Jazz. Just not
tough enough to knock the notion out of his head, that if it can
came down to him with the ball, him with a chance, he would make
the last shot, no matter how many he'd missed.
</P>
<P>
   He made the shot. He accepted his sixth most valuable player
trophy. He slipped into the ``Repeat Three-peat'' T-shirt that will
sell a few million by the end of the week. And David Stern can now
resume hoping that a more ratings-friendly team than the Jazz will
step up, or grow up, to carry the National Basketball Association
into the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
   In Chicago, the owner Jerry Reinsdorf will turn into Al Capone
if he doesn't come up with about $80 million to underwrite his
current roster for another go-round. No one will ask why CEO Jordan
can't take $10 million less so Pippen can get fair market value,
especially after Sunday night. And no one will contemplate the
impact on the sport's smaller markets as the larger ones push
salaries to unfathomable heights.
</P>
<P>
   That's what this summer's collective bargaining showdown will be
about, how viable an auto dealer entrepreneur such as the Utah
owner Larry Miller will be in the coming years. How many more John
Stocktons and Karl Malones are out there, relishing the thought of
getting away from the big-market glitz? Most of the kids coming
along now sat in front of their screens on Sunday night, blinded by
Jordan's brilliance. They never see themselves spending a decade in
places like Salt Lake.
</P>
<P>
   This is Stern's delicate balancing act of wanting his big-ticket
teams to produce the ratings the league can crow about this spring
without reaching the point where too many franchises become the
Montreal Expos. How to maintain interest over the course of a
playoff season that is the equivalent of four consecutive Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   The big numbers were being notched courtesy of this latest
Jordan epic _ the possibility of this being his last run _ which he
decided on Sunday night was ``the toughest route we've had.'' The
drama heightened in the first quarter, with Pippen in the locker
room, doubled over. When Jordan exploded for 15 second-quarter
points and a 23-point first half in a shootout with Malone that
kept the crippled Bulls close, you knew he had enough ego to
believe he still could win. You just wondered whether he had enough
legs.
</P>
<P>
   Late in the first half, Jordan twice ignored Toni Kukoc and
hoisted 3-pointers, leaving Kukoc shaking his head, hands on his
hips. Jordan obviously would leave this game to no one, taking
himself back to the mid-1980s, trying to win it by himself.
</P>
<P>
   People for years now have pointed out that Jordan never won a
playoff game back when he was a one-man team, before Pippen came
along to become ``little brother.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan won it that way on Sunday night, with a little help from
his friends, a brave, struggling Pippen included. Jordan was so
good that he moved Pippen, of all people, to post-game tears. Six
titles in eight years. A team in awe of its leading man, like
everyone else who watched.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe they all come back next year _ Jordan, Pippen, Jackson,
even Dennis Rodman. Maybe not.
</P>
<P>
   If this is the end, and the circle of greatness is closed,
Michael Jordan stands alone. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
