<SLUG> BC-BKL-SPARKS-LESLIE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOUL-PLAGUED LESLIE HELPLESS IN LOSS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PAUL CORO  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - With a dry uniform beneath her gold pullover, Los
Angeles Sparks center Lisa Leslie watched the most critical stretch
of Sunday's 70-60 Mercury victory with the scrubs.
</P>
<P>
   Leslie down with two fouls less than five minutes after she gave
the Sparks a quick 10-4 lead with three straight baskets. For the
next 8{ minutes, she watched helplessly as the Mercury dismantled
that work with a 17-7 run that put Phoenix ahead permanently.
</P>
<P>
   Frustrated star turned into frustrated team captain after the
game. Minutes after hearing the echoes of Cheryl Miller's post-game
celebration on the public-address system, Leslie said, ``We did a
good job of fighting back, but we lost our team chemistry and our
game plan and started going more one-on-one. If we could jump it up
and start over, we'd do it. We're not intimidated by them by any
means.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sparks (1-1) will tell you that they are still getting to
know one another, and that is why their offense looked out of whack
Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   But the Mercury, which had even more roster introductions held
up by the World Championships, put a defensive hurt on Los Angeles
that demanded credit for the Sparks' 19 turnovers, shot-clock
violations and awful perimeter shooting.
</P>
<P>
   Leslie and guard Tamecka Dixon scored 42 points in Los Angeles'
opener, but they had to sit together for much of the Mercury game
because of foul trouble. When they sat, the Sparks' offense turned
dormant against a mobile, swarming Mercury defense.
</P>
<P>
   When Los Angeles finally got the lineup it wanted on the floor
in the second half, its offense clicked, but its defense allowed
the Mercury several easy baskets.
</P>
<P>
   The Sparks-Mercury rivalry was founded on the Leslie-Jennifer
Gillom post wars. It carried on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Leslie got her second double-double (18 points, 10 rebounds) in
as many games, while Gillom put up a game-high 20 points to go with
six rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``The match-up will probably last forever,'' Leslie said. ``I
can't stop her and she can't stop me.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
