<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARINERS BLOW 3-0 LEAD, WASTE CLOUDE'S EFFORT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM STREET  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ Mariner right-hander Ken Cloude has pitched
games worth putting in a video collection and saving forever.
</P>
<P>
   Other starts warrant instant trash-can treatment.
</P>
<P>
   File Sunday's game against the Oakland Athletics on the keeper
shelf but don't ask Cloude if the effort was worth it. His best
outing of the season became virtually worthless as the Mariners
blew a three-run lead in the seventh inning and slipped deeper into
the American League West cellar with 4-3 loss in 10 innings before
21,503 fans at the Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   Every run-producing Seattle hit went over the fence.
</P>
<P>
   Oakland, meanwhile, used dribblers to catch up in the seventh
inning and won it in the 10th on a leadoff walk, a ground-ball
single, a long fly ball and an error by Mariners third baseman Russ
Davis on a ball hit by former Mariner Mike Blowers.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I hit it, I told myself to run really hard because I
didn't want to hit into a double play right there,'' Blowers said.
</P>
<P>
   He could have coasted.
</P>
<P>
   The ball took one hop and bounced into and out of Davis' glove.
Before he could regain possession and at least attempt to throw out
Scott Spiezio at the plate, the runner was sliding across the
plate, sticking Davis with his league-leading 17th error in 65
games.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners played the outfield shallow and decided to try for
an inning-ending double play on a sharply hit grounder.
</P>
<P>
   Davis had the option of going for the out at home or attempting
the double play.
</P>
<P>
   ``The choice was there,'' manager Lou Piniella said, ``but you
have to catch it before you do either.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis sat in front of his locker, commenting to no one.
</P>
<P>
   Spiezio led off the 10th with a walk, moved to second on Ben
Grieve's opposite-field single and to third when Matt Stairs flied
out to Jay Buhner in right.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners figured the percentages were better facing the
slow-footed Blowers than walking him intentionally and having
left-handed hitting Jason Giambi facing Heathcliff Slocumb with the
bases loaded.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Slocumb took a loss in a game Cloude should have
won.
</P>
<P>
   After failing to get beyond the third inning in three of his
past six starts, Cloude mastered the A's over six innings, allowing
one hit _ Stairs' infield single in the second inning _ and walking
one. Neither of the runners reached second base.
</P>
<P>
   Solo homers by Glenallen Hill in the second, Alex Rodriguez in
the third and David Segui in the sixth sent Cloude and the Mariners
into the seventh inning with a three-run lead.
</P>
<P>
   But for the ninth time this season Seattle squandered a lead of
three runs or more in the fifth inning or later.
</P>
<P>
   Grieve led off with a double and Stairs walked. After Cloude
struck out Blowers, Piniella summoned left-hander Paul Spoljaric to
face left-handed hitting Giambi.
</P>
<P>
   Spoljaric walked Giambi to load the bases and turn up the heat
on the next pitcher, Mike Timlin.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I do my job, maybe it's a different scenario,'' Spoljaric
said. ``Instead of just letting things happen, I tried to force the
issue and didn't do the job.''
</P>
<P>
   Timlin did his job, but that didn't work, either.
</P>
<P>
   Pinch-hitting Kevin Mitchell bounced a grounder up the middle
that Rodriguez missed by about an inch. Second baseman Joey Cora
flagged it down, but had no play.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Macfarlane then drove a grounder up the middle, again
barely out of the diving Rodriguez's reach, scoring two runs to tie
the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``A foot one way or the other on either one of those and we're
out of the inning,'' said Timlin, who absorbed his fourth blown
save in five opportunities. ``When you make the pitches you want,
get them to hit the ball on the ground, and still don't get an out,
it's very frustrating. Weird.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Kenny pitched his butt off and should have won,'' Timlin
added.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything was working for me and it shows I can do the job
when I'm relaxed and focused,'' Cloude said. ``Hopefully, I can
pitch the same way in my other 20 starts this year. If I can do
that, I will be successful.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners lost three of four in the series and five of seven
in the Bay Area.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Bay Area is just a small microcosm of what we've gone
through this year,'' Piniella said. ``I don't think anything has
worked out the way we expected this year.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
