<HEADER>
A8938 &Cx1f; tth-z
r S &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI &LR;      06-15 0811
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JORDAN REDEFINES BOUNDARY OF GREATNESS IN TWO MINUTES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALT LAKE CITY _ Small as it is, the I Don't Like Mike Club
thought it had a moment.
</P>
<P>
   The ego of Michael Jordan, immense as the Wasatch Mountains, was
finally dragging down the Chicago Bulls.
</P>
<P>
   As Game 6 of the NBA Finals dwindled to an excruciating climax,
the Utah Jazz had the home court, the momentum, the lead and the
prospect of Game 7 Wednesday without having to face Scottie Pippen
because of an ailing back.
</P>
<P>
   In desperation, Jordan was thrashing and hacking, forcing his
game beyond its already distant limits.
</P>
<P>
   Then the chance for change at the NBA's pinnacle suddenly
vanished. Gone.
</P>
<P>
   In the final two minutes, lightning flashed, the Jazz lay
prostrate on the salt flats, the Bulls had an 87-86 victory and
their sixth NBA championship, and the rest of us are in positions
of supplication: We are not worthy.
</P>
<P>
   Shazam. Or whatever is said when logic takes it in the pants.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if you could write a more dramatic scenario,''
said a beaming Phil Jackson, waving a stogie as well as a goodbye
to the Bulls' dynasty.
</P>
<P>
   This was supposed to be the end of the Bulls' run _ but only if
you still are into the Easter bunny and Santa.
</P>
<P>
   As Utah's John Stockton, whose final shot missed by an inch in
forcing Game 7, put it in his usual no-nonsense fashion:
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it will be his last one. It's been a nice story
for everybody here, but he's not quitting. Phil will be back, and
Scottie will be back and Michael will be back. I am tired of
hearing all of that.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it works for them, so give them credit.''
</P>
<P>
   Much as NBC and the NBA have enjoyed wrapping Jordan's season in
poetry and suspense, there is no way the guy goes out now.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody who can do what Jordan did in the last two minutes in
Game 6 is through.
</P>
<P>
   With Utah up 83-79, Jordan made four free throws, a driving
lay-in, stole the ball from Karl Malone, and with six seconds left,
made the game-winning jumper. That made for a 45-point evening and
an even more stupendous finish than the fifth game of last year's
finals between the Bulls and Jazz.
</P>
<P>
   You may recall that Jordan, despite a bout of food poisoning,
scored 38 points to win here and all but clinch the 1997 title.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think you could top the performance he had in that
game, but he topped it tonight,'' said Jackson. ``I think it's the
best performance I've seen in a critical situation and a critical
game in a series.''
</P>
<P>
   What that says is Jordan has not lost a thing when it comes to
dominating the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   Remember, this was a Bulls team weaker than its predecessors.
They gave up on two helpful frontliners in Brian Williams and Jason
Caffey. They had a season-long circus with Dennis Rodman, and
Jackson and Pippen pouted all year about their futures.
</P>
<P>
   The Bulls faced a Jazz team that had swept them in the regular
season, had the home-court advantage, a deeper bench, an easier
postseason and an unsurpassed passion for revenge from last season.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the Bulls did it again.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was the toughest route, the toughest challenge, in the
six championships we've won,'' said Jordan. ``In some people's
eyes, no one expected us to fulfill this, and that was part of the
challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``As soon as (Game 5) ended in Chicago there were some dim
feelings and some negative thoughts. Then I think everybody
realized if we want that sixth title, we have to go through Utah to
get it. Those negative thoughts erased very quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   It's become plain that Jordan, Pippen and Jackson have given
Bulls' owner Jerry Reinsdorf no justification for altering the key
ingredients. In recent days, Reinsdorf as well as the coach and
players have backed away from their positions of opposition.
</P>
<P>
   If you believe the fanciful stories of Jordan's $10 billion
economic impact, then Reinsdorf faces a financial imperative to
keep the machine intact.
</P>
<P>
   As much mayhem as may have taken place in the streets of Chicago
Sunday night, it would look like recess compared to the riot that
would ensue if Reinsdorf did not return the royal court.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have another life,'' said Jordan. ``I know I have to get to
it at some point and hopefully the fans and the people
understand.''
</P>
<P>
   But that other life probably has another 50 years to go. His
current doings show little sign of decay. As Pippen put it Sunday
night, ``Michael has probably four or five years left.''
</P>
<P>
   If the looks of dismay on the faces of Malone, Stockton and
thousands of Jazz fans were not despairing enough, just lay that
thought on them to see genuine hurt.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the size of the I Don't Like Mike Club, there is a good
chance it will have multiple seasons to recruit new members.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
