<HEADLINE>
2 BLOWN CALLS FATAL FOR JAZZ 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB YOUNG  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALT LAKE CITY _ When the Utah Jazz looks back at their loss in
Game 6 of the NBA Finals, two plays will be a lot more painful than
 &UR; Michael Jordan's game-winning shot or &UR; John Stockton's final-second
miss.
</P>
<P>
   Two blown calls by the officiating crew of  &UR; Dick Bavetta, &UR; Hue
 &UR; Hollins and &UR; Danny Crawford cost Utah five points and might have
made the difference between another Chicago championship or a Game
7 showdown.
</P>
<P>
   The first came early in the second quarter when Utah guard
 &UR; Howard Eisley put up a 25-foot shot that appeared to be good for
three points that would have given Utah a seven-point lead. But
Bavetta waived the shot off, saying Eisley launched it after the
24-second shot clock had expired.
</P>
<P>
   Television replays showed Bavetta was wrong. The ball was about
10 feet out of Eisley's hand before the clock expired.
</P>
<P>
   The second blown call came at a more critical time. This time,
Chicago's  &UR; Ron Harper put up a short leaner as the shot-clock
buzzer sounded that tied the score at 79 with 3:44 to play in the
game. The replay showed that Harper did not beat the clock.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no control over that,'' Utah Coach  &UR; Jerry Sloan said.
``What are you going to do?'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Preview &QL; 
 &QL; 
Pro wrestling fans might have gotten a sample of what they can
expect next month when &UR; Dennis Rodman of the Bulls and  &UR; Karl Malone
of the Jazz square off in a pay-per-view tag-team match.
</P>
<P>
   Malone and Rodman went at it most of the game, exchanging elbows
and flops. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-15-98 0213EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
