<HEADLINE>
DENVER COACH FACING REPRI MAND? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Denver Broncos assistant  &UR; John Teerlinck's next visit to the
principal's office might not be so friendly.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Teerlinck, then a Detroit Lions assistant, was
summoned to see NFL Commissioner  &UR; Paul Tagliabue to discuss whether
he was teaching his Detroit Lions defensive linemen to play dirty.
The meeting was set up after the Lions roughed up quarterbacks
 &UR; Warren
 &UR; Moon,  &UR; Trent Dilfer, &UR; Erik Kramer and  &UR; Bobby Hebert in four of the
first six games.
</P>
<P>
   Teerlinck, former assistant for the Arizona Wranglers and
Outlaws of the now-defunct U.S. Football League, might be visiting
Tagliabue again as the result of a lawsuit filed against him last
Wednesday by a Scottsdale woman who alleges she was raped by
Teerlinck before last January's Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   The woman, &UR; Shelley McClain, said in the suit that she went to
San Diego on Jan. 18 to meet with Teerlinck about Super Bowl
tickets he had promised her. She claims in the suit that Teerlinck,
after drinking 10 to 15 beers, ``physically assaulted and raped''
her, forcing her to have sexual intercourse and oral sex by
grabbing her by the throat.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit, filed against Teerlinck and the Broncos, is being
taken seriously by the NFL, which has a new violent crime policy.
But Teerlinck is not subjected to being punished under that policy
because the case is a civil matter.
</P>
<P>
   San Diego police said it investigated the complaint and that
``there is not strong evidence at this point to support a criminal
charge.'' But the police have turned the matter over to the San
Diego district attorney to decide whether to prosecute.
</P>
<P>
   The Broncos and the NFL, meanwhile, are embarrassed by the
incident, and the league's showcase event has been sullied.
</P>
<P>
   Teerlinck remains employed by the Broncos, who weren't bothered
by his controversial reputation when they hired him.
</P>
<P>
   He has been accused of teaching dirty tactics at each of his NFL
stops and was fired by the Outlaws in 1985 when he got into a fight
with a player on the team plane. &QL; 
Proof positive &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Former Cardinals running back &UR; LeShon Johnson will begin
chemotherapy treatments today in New Jersey. New York Giants
doctors recently discovered he has cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's in great spirits,'' Johnson's agent,  &UR; Gary Wichard, said.
``He's expecting a full recovery. Everyone is pleased with his
progress. The Giants have been great to him. It's fortunate it was
caught so quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, who signed a free-agent deal with the Giants in the
off-season, had a routine physical before May's minicamp. A chest
X-ray showed that he had tumor in his chest. &QL; 
Another doubter &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals'  &UR; Jake Plummer isn't the only young quarterback
being targeted by the new football league who has little interest
in joining.
</P>
<P>
   Carolina's  &UR; Kerry Collins scoffed at a published report that the
new league, being bankrolled by NBC and Turner Broadcasting, wants
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd rather stick a fork in my eye than do something like
that,'' Collins said. ``To me, that would be taking a step down in
a big way.'' &QL; 
Plummer said last week he wouldn't consider jumping leagues.
</P>
<P>
   Hold everything &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Neal Pilson, former president of CBS Sports, said he explored
the viability of forming a new pro football league when the network
lost NFL TV rights four years ago but decided against it.
</P>
<P>
   He's not optimistic that the proposed league will be successful.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm convinced General Electric and Time Warner (the parent
companies) have the financial resources and the media power to
launch a new league,'' Pilson said. ``I'm also convinced it won't
work. . . . We didn't find a public or advertising community dying
to have what would have to be minor league football. I think
there's an abundant supply of players but a short supply of the the
kind of players the public expects from pro football.'' &QL; 
Short shots &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Chicago Bears were so worried about defensive lineman &UR; Alonzo
 &UR; Spellman's mental state, they increased security at their team
facility when they released him last Friday. Spellman's release
will cost the Bears $1 million against their salary cap each of the
next two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona State running backs coach  &UR; Cornell Jackson will work at
the St. Louis Rams' training camp for three weeks this summer as
part of the NFL's minority coaching development program.
</P>
<P>
   There's no question that the Green Bay Packers are the NFL's
richest team. They informed stock holders last week that they have
cash reserves of $51.9 million. Their waiting list for season
tickets is up to 44,000, more than many teams' sales, including the
Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Schoenfeld can be reached at 602-444-8334 or at
steve.schoenfeld(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
