<SLUG> BC-BBN-DBACKS-CARDINALS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
D-BACKS' BATS GO SILENT  
 CARDINALS PITCHERS THROW 4-HIT SHUTOUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DON KETCHUM  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - The Diamondbacks' dugout must have felt like a cavern
to pitcher Willie Blair on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   There were plenty of echoes.
</P>
<P>
   `` Hello, hello, hello''.``''
</P>
<P>
   `` Is anybody in here, here, here''?``''
</P>
<P>
   `` Can somebody help me, me, me''?``''
</P>
<P>
   Blair gave up two runs and scattered eight hits through seven
innings and struck out slugger Mark McGwire three times. But the
right-hander got no support from his offense, which had averaged
7.2 runs in its previous seven games.
</P>
<P>
   All the Diamondbacks could muster were four hits and two walks
against St. Louis right-handers Mark Petkovsek and Kent
Bottenfield, and the Cardinals escaped with a 2-0 victory in front
of the third straight sellout crowd at Bank One Ballpark. It was
the fifth time Arizona has been shut out this season.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks, who fell to 22-47, grounded into three double
plays.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time you hold a team to two runs, you feel like you have
the chance to win,'' said Diamondbacks Manager Buck Showalter,
whose team begins an eight-game trip in Cincinnati on Tuesday.
``But we couldn't string anything together. We knew pretty much
what Petkovsek would do _ we didn't make the necessary adjustments.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was proud of the way Willie went about things out there. I
know it's frustrating.''
</P>
<P>
   Blair (2-9) admitted he was disappointed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that I threw the ball well,'' he said. ``I don't think
I can throw much better. I did what I could.''
</P>
<P>
   McGwire struck out swinging three times against Blair _ in the
first, fourth and seventh innings and walked in the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key was getting ahead of him early in the count,'' Blair
said. ``I tried to give him sliders down and away.''
</P>
<P>
   Blair and Petkovsek were locked in a scoreless duel for the
first four innings.
</P>
<P>
   Petkovsek (4-3) walked Andy Fox in the first inning, but Fox was
quickly erased on a double-play grounder to third baseman Gary
Gaetti by Jay Bell.
</P>
<P>
   Petkovsek struck out two men in the second and third, and got
another double-play grounder to Gaetti in the fourth, this one by
Matt Williams, after a single by Travis Lee.
</P>
<P>
   Blair, meanwhile, kept the Cardinals off the board in the first
inning despite a one-out triple by Delino DeShields, who increased
his hitting streak to 14 games. A strikeout of McGwire for the
second out was the key.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals (32-35) touched Blair for their first run in the
fifth inning.
</P>
<P>
   Shortstop Royce Clayton singled with one out, stole second,
moved to third on a fly to center by catcher Tom Pagnozzi and
scored on a single up the middle by Petkovsek, who left the game
after the fifth because of a cramp in his left leg.
</P>
<P>
   Blair escaped a potential disaster in the sixth when he walked
McGwire with one out, gave up a two-out double to Gaetti and got
Ron Gant on a grounder.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals scored their second run in the seventh inning as
they collected three infield hits.
</P>
<P>
   Clayton, the leadoff man, reached first on a slow-rolling base
hit in front of Williams. Pagnozzi sacrificed him to second and
John Mabry got him to third with a fly to left.
</P>
<P>
   Clayton scored as Willie McGee hit a comebacker off Blair's
glove that second baseman Fox retrieved but couldn't make the throw
in time. DeShields hit another off Blair's glove, and shortstop Jay
Bell couldn't make the play in time. Blair struck out McGwire to
end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I probably should have had both of those hit back to me,''
Blair said.
</P>
<P>
   Bottenfield gave up a leadoff single to Lee in the seventh, but
Lee was erased again as Williams grounded to Gaetti for another
5-4-3 double play.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona's last ray of hope came in the eighth when Karim Garcia
singled with two out, but pinch-hitter Mike Robertson flied out to
right to end the inning. Bottenfield went on to retire the side in
order in the ninth to earn his fourth save. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
