<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-FINALS-BICKLEY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS TIME IT WAS ALL JORDAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN BICKLEY  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALT LAKE CITY - His sidekick cried on his shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   His coach smiled in amazement.
</P>
<P>
   His mother hugged him and wouldn't let go.
</P>
<P>
   And finally, with a cigar in hand and a pair of trophies on the
way, he wiped the sweat of miracles from his face.
</P>
<P>
   Basketball Jesus rose up once again and saved a dynasty. He put
his greatness on display, a team on his back and a defining
signature on his sport. There is Michael Jordan, there is everyone
else, and that's just the way it is.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe he should walk away now. After all, it can't get any
better than this. This was Ted Williams hitting a home run in his
final swing. This was Secretariat roaring down the stretch, right
off to the stud farm.
</P>
<P>
   This was the essence of Michael, and his cologne has never
smelled sweeter.
</P>
<P>
   No role players this time. In a blurring sequence of brilliance,
Michael simply stole the moment, stole the championship, furthering
a legend that never ceases to grow and never, ever disappoints.
</P>
<P>
   The layup. The theft of Karl Malone. The game-winning jump shot
for, oh, the 7,000th time. He didn't just break the heart of an
opponent. He ripped it out and stepped on it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you have to say that Michael is the kind of guy that
comes through,'' Bulls' Coach Phil Jackson said, puffing on a
cigar. ``He always comes through. He's a real-life hero.'`
</P>
<P>
   Credit Karl Malone for finding a soul. Credit the Jazz for
making this a series. Credit Pippen for playing through the pain,
lending his presence to the floor. But in the end, none of it could
match the vintage of Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the greatest player that has ever played the game,'` Jazz
Coach Jerry Sloan said. ``We just have so many things that are
sideshows to this game that he hasn't allowed to happen, and I
think that's the most important thing. He has allowed the game to
be the most important thing, and the other things came afterwards.
And I think sometimes we have a tendency to get those things in
reverse.'`
</P>
<P>
   In all likelihood, the dynasty will be deep-sixed. Jackson
already has cleaned out his office. As much as Bulls' owner Jerry
Reinsdorf applies his spin to the situation, he will be reluctant
to give Pippen what he deserves: a long-term deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless something absolutely unusual comes out of left field, I
don't expect to see us back again,'` Jackson said. ``And what a
great run it has been.'`
</P>
<P>
   With six titles in eight years, they are second on the totem
pole of dynasties, ranking only behind Bill Russell's Celtics. In
the process, their victims have been plenty. They dethroned the
Pistons, stifled an uprising in New York, smothered a movement in
Orlando. They beat five different teams in their six title runs,
disposing of Magic, Barkley, Drexler, Payton and Kemp, Stockton and
Malone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can never see another team in the future being as dominant
as this one,'' Pippen said.
</P>
<P>
   While Pippen claims Jordan could play another five years without
missing a beat, Jordan says it will depend on a ``gut feeling.'`
Sometime over the summer, while a nasty lock-out swallows the
league, he will look back on this game and smile. With Pippen
hampered by a back injury, the stage couldn't have been better.
With 45 points _ the number he chose when he returned to basketball
only to trash it in defiance _ the symmetry is perfect.
</P>
<P>
   A satisfying ending, no?
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' Jordan said. ``If that's the case, yes.'`
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if anyone could write a scenario as dramatic as
that one,'` Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
   No, there has never been a finer moment, even if the memories
fill a scrapbook: Jordan cradling the first trophy, weeping like a
baby. His string of six three-pointers and the shrug against
Portland. The bad pizza in Utah that gave Jordan food poisoning and
a forum to score 38 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``And then there was my rookie year in Phoenix,'` Steve Kerr
said. ``Michael got the ball, looked at me on the bench, and said,
'Watch this.' He dunked on Dan Majerle, and went up court
laughing.'`
</P>
<P>
   Kerr smiles. ``Sorry, Dan,`' he said.
</P>
<P>
   No apologies necessary. Not for a team that transcended the NBA,
a global entity that became so large that even its groupies spawned
groupies. No ending has ever been more fitting for a superstar, and
when it was over, Randy Brown hugged the real-life hero.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank you, man,'` Brown said. ``Thank you.`'
</P>
<P>
   Our sentiments exactly. &QL; 
Dan Bickley can be reached at 602-444-8253 or at
dan.bickley(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-15-98 0216EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
