<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-15 02:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8945 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-NBA-FINALS-GAME6-     06-15 0798
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA-FINALS-GAME6-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JORDAN WILLS BULLS TO SIXTH TITLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB YOUNG  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALT LAKE CITY _ If it was Michael Jordan's final moment in the
NBA, it might be remembered as his greatest.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan carried the Chicago Bulls to their sixth NBA championship
of the 1990s on Sunday, scoring 45 points and producing three
critical plays in the final 38 seconds as Chicago beat the Utah
Jazz, 87-86, at the Delta Center to win the best-of-seven series,
4-2.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan's game-winning shot with 5.2 seconds to play will be
remembered most, but he arguably is the greatest player in the
history of the league because he can dominate a game defensively as
well as offensively.
</P>
<P>
   It was a Jordan defensive gem that led to the decisive shot. He
stripped the ball from Utah's Karl Malone with 18 seconds
remaining, setting up the final shot. Jordan feinted toward the
basket, and Utah's Bryon Russell lost his footing.
</P>
<P>
   That was all Jordan needed. He set his feet and fired the game
winner from 18 feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never doubted the whole game,'' Jordan said. ``We hung too
close. I knew we were going to have an opportunity to win this
game, and I just wanted an opportunity to do that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once it went in, I knew that we had been hanging around so
long, it was the game-winning basket.''
</P>
<P>
   The Jazz had a final attempt, but John Stockton's three-point
attempt just before the final buzzer hit the front of the rim.
</P>
<P>
   The Chicago victory had appeared unlikely, as it has so many
times for Jordan and the Bulls. Stockton's three-point shot with 42
seconds remaining gave Utah a three-point lead, and it looked like
the Bulls were headed toward a seventh game in the NBA Finals for
the first time.
</P>
<P>
   But Jordan quickly trimmed it back to a point by driving past
Russell for a layup. That set the stage for his heroics in the
final seconds, and they clinched a championship in Game 6 for the
fifth time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if anybody could write a scenario as dramatic as
that one,'' Chicago Coach Phil Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
   It punctuated what turned out to be the best game of the series.
</P>
<P>
   The Bulls jumped out early, 17-8, but forward Scottie Pippen
aggravated a lower-back strain in the opening seconds on a dunk.
Pippen had needed anti-inflammatory shots Saturday to relieve
spasms that started after he took several charging fouls in Game 5.
</P>
<P>
   Pippen went to the locker room with 4:56 remaining in the first
quarter, and the Jazz took advantage with an 11-1 run and went on
to lead, 25-22, after the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Pippen returned in the second half after treatments, but it was
clear that if the Bulls were going to win the championship, it
would be Jordan who would deliver it.
</P>
<P>
   He scored 15 points in the second quarter to keep the Bulls
within four points of the Jazz, and then he began driving hard to
the basket in the second half. He finished the job with 16
fourth-quarter points.
</P>
<P>
   Now the questions to be answered are whether Jordan has wagged
his tongue for the last time and if the Bulls will return intact
next season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It won't be his last (game),'' Stockton said of Jordan. ``It's
been a nice story for everyone here, but he's not quitting. He'll
be back. Scottie will be back and Phil Jackson will be back. I'm
tired of hearing all of that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Jazz may be back, too, after reaching the Finals two
straight times and losing to Chicago. The Jazz took the lead into
the final minutes in five of the six games in the series, the only
exception being the 42-point blowout loss in Game 3. But it was
Chicago that found a way to make clutch plays in three of the five
games that went to the wire.
</P>
<P>
   Utah Coach Jerry Sloan said the final play broke down because
Chicago's defense forced the play too far out on the floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we did a very poor job of executing the play that we
drew,'' he said. ``John had to take a hurried shot.''
</P>
<P>
   Stockton said he thought he had made it, just as he had made the
three-pointer to put Utah ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a good look at (the last shot of the game),'' Stockton
said. ``I know you never hear anybody shoot the last shot that
doesn't say they thought it felt like it was going in, but I did.''
</P>
<P>
   But Sloan said the game was lost because of Utah's carelessness
with the ball. He didn't specifically cite Jordan's strip of
Malone, but that was the most costly.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't afford to give them second chances,'' he said.
``With Michael Jordan out there, he was going to make the plays. He
was able to do that, and you live with that. It's a very bitter
pill to swallow, but that's why they're champions. They've been
there. They know how to make the play after the mistake you make
and capitalize on it.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
