<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKL-MERCURY-SPARKS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MERCURY DIVES DEEP INTO BENCH FOR WIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF METCALFE  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - For the endless summer for which Phoenix is famous,
the Mercury offers an antidote: the endless bench.
</P>
<P>
   Even without 6-foot-8 Maria Stepanova taking a step onto the
court and veterans Marlies Askamp and Mikiko Hagiwara in street
clothes, the reserves outscored Los Angeles, 27-9, on Sunday in a
surprisingly easy 70-60 victory at America West Arena.
</P>
<P>
   The defending Western Conference champion Mercury, now 2-0,
flexed a depth unseen last season in creating 13-2 and 16-2 scoring
runs to take a 39-23 halftime lead over its archrival. The Sparks
(1-1) got as close as six in the closing two minutes but never
really threatened the lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm obviously pleased with the W, but it doesn't mean anything
unless we complete it,'' said Coach Cheryl Miller of a game at 7
tonight against the expansion Washington Mystics (0-2). ``It's a
decent win, but we don't want to lose our focus.''
</P>
<P>
   That won't happen, point guard Michele Timms promises. ``We're
too professional to get big heads at this stage.''
</P>
<P>
   Plus, Phoenix failed to sweep any of six back-to-back chances
last season and, because of a six-game midseason losing streak, had
to scrape past the Sparks just to make the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   A crowd of 13,057, less than 900 below the team's 1997
WNBA-leading average on the first of nine doubleheader days with
the Diamondbacks, got its first look at Michelle Griffiths and fell
in love.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-1 Australian power forward played 31 minutes, many of
those against Sparks 6-5 center Lisa Leslie, because of a right
ankle sprain that limited starter Toni Foster.
</P>
<P>
   Leslie, who sat out more than an eight-minute stretch of the
first half after committing two fouls in 14 seconds, had her
expected production (18 points, 10 rebounds), but Griffiths was not
far back (16 points, four rebounds).
</P>
<P>
   ``Offensively, I'm comfortable against her,'' said the
25-year-old Griffiths, who has played a half-dozen or more
international games against Leslie. ``Defensively, it's harder. We
haven't built a great defensive (team) relationship yet, where I
know they'll be help behind me.''
</P>
<P>
   That construction will come after tonight, when the Mercury uses
five days off to fully integrate Griffiths, Australians Timms and
Kristi Harrower, and Stepanova into systems introduced while they
were at the World Championships.
</P>
<P>
   If Phoenix goes 3-0 into that break, it will be at least a game
ahead of what was considered likely because of the six late
arrivals, including Askamp and Hagiwara. But the Sparks, who were
intact during training camp except for Leslie and 6-foot-8 center
Hiaxia Zheng, could not take advantage of the Mercury's lack of
cohesiveness.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not closing the way we need to,'' Miller said, ``but
we're starting to see the chemistry.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Griffiths, Andrea Kuklova and Harrower combined
for nine points off the bench, which excelled even with rookie
Brandy Reed having her least impressive game to date.
</P>
<P>
   Other teams, like the New York Liberty (0-2), would do well to
watch the waiver wire in the next week or so if the Mercury is
forced to make a difficult cut or two when the injured players
recover.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a nice team this year,'' guard Bridget Pettis said.
``It's not just five veteran players. It's five veterans with a
bench and chemistry.''
</P>
<P>
   Mercury center Jennifer Gillom had her second consecutive
20-point game, and Pettis contributed 12. Other double-figure
scorers for the Sparks were Tamecka Dixon, who had 12 of her 14 in
the second half, and forward Pam McGee with 10.
</P>
<P>
   Rebounding was tied at halftime, but the Sparks had a 21-9
second-half edge as they hung within 10-12 points. A pair of free
throws, three-point play and 8-footer, all by Dixon, cut the
Phoenix lead to 64-58 with 1:13 left, but Gillom responded with a
14-foot jumper to close the door.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if I delivered as well as Karl (Malone) did the
other night,'' Gillom said, ``but I love the pressure. I try to be
the leader. We have such depth, that's going to be a big factor.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
