</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKL-MERCURY-CASSTEVENS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO PLACE IN WNBA FOR DENISE RODMAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID CASSTEVENS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Last night I dreamed the Phoenix Mercury introduced a
new player at Sunday's home opener.
</P>
<P>
   Her name is Denise.
</P>
<P>
   Denise Rodman. Dennis's sister.
</P>
<P>
   Denise is different from other WNBA players. In my dream, she
showed up for the Mercury's nationally televised debut wearing a
lime green pageboy, color by Krylon, and a matching feather boa.
During warm-ups, she puffed a footlong cigar.
</P>
<P>
   Denise can't shoot. Her free throws are iffy. Unpredictable, she
skipped the team's last practice, showing up instead in the company
of two roller-derby queens at a Hollywood body-piercing and tattoo
emporium.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's Denise,'' Coach Cheryl Miller said. Her sigh said it
all.
</P>
<P>
   Denise is egocentric, to say the least. But she can rebound and
play defense. In my dream, Denise shut down LA Sparks star Lisa
Leslie, holding the 6-foot-5 center to two points.
</P>
<P>
   In my dream, Denise is everywhere. TV. Radio. Magazine covers.
The media is preoccupied with her. She doesn't represent the image
the WNBA wants to promote, but she generates more publicity for the
league than money can buy.
</P>
<P>
   Does the WNBA need a Rodman? The WNBA president appeared more
amused by the question than intrigued by it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure how to answer that,'' Val Ackerman said.
``There's not another person like Dennis in any other league.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Denise'' Rodman? Ackerman shook her head and smiled.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we have enough personalities to sell our game. I did
talk with (NBA Commissioner) David Stern. He said Dennis wouldn't
be allowed to play in ``both'' leagues.''
</P>
<P>
   The WNBA has a core of stars. Last year's ``We Got Next''
marketing campaign targeted three of them: Leslie, Rebecca Lobo,
and Sheryl Swoopes, who missed most of the WNBA's inaugural season
while pregnant.
</P>
<P>
   But name another star player. Most of us can't _ not yet. The
league is still young. If there is a Michael Jordan of the WNBA, it
is Cynthia Cooper of the Houston Comets, last year's Most Valuable
Player.
</P>
<P>
   The league doesn't have a female Dennis Rodman, and maybe it
doesn't need one.
</P>
<P>
   After the Mercury's 70-60 victory on Sunday, before 13,057,
point guard Michele Timms said, ``We can get by all right with the
characters we have.''
</P>
<P>
   Some never will accept women's pro hoops as a legitimate sport.
The league is an easy target on male-oriented radio sports talk
shows. Fact is, Phoenix is the WNBA's most successful franchise.
The Mercury led the league in attendance last season, averaging
13,700.
</P>
<P>
   The team isn't short on personalities. Timms, the
bleached-haired point guard with a Crocodile Dundee accent. Bridget
Pettis, who started every game last season and led the league in
free-throw percentage (.898). Jennifer Gillom scored 20 points
Sunday, and no one enjoyed the game more. The 34-year-old center
has a face made for smiling.
</P>
<P>
   The largest personality belongs to the coach/general
manager/head cheerleader. Wearing a long-coated, black pinstripe
suit, satin shirt and silver necktie _ Abe Lincoln as Capone _
Cheryl Miller celebrated the victory as no NBA coach would dare to.
</P>
<P>
   On the court, Miller danced with the team's hip-hop squad,
shimmying and gyrating to the music's pounding beat. Then, with the
practiced ease of a nightclub entertainer, the coach took the
microphone and spoke to the cult following, telling Mercury fans
what they wanted to hear.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tell you what, Phoenix!'' Miller said. ``The Diamondbacks are
(playing) next door . . .''
</P>
<P>
   Strangely, fans began to boo.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, no,'' Miller said, quieting them. Colangelo partnerships
own both teams. ``It's all good,'' Miller reminded. Miller turned
in place, her eyes scanning the arena where fans, Ackerman among
them, were on their feet, taking it all in. ``This just shows how
much you love the Mercury to come here! ''
</P>
<P>
   The address was heart-warming, or hokey, depending upon one's
point of view. But those in attendance loved it. They felt
connected, in a personal way, to the coach and to the team. They
don't need Denise Rodman to bring them back. &QL; 
David Casstevens can be reached at 602-444-8635 or at
david.casstevens(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-15-98 0219EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
