<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-BULLS-PIPPEN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PIPPEN HOLDS OFF TALK OF HIS FUTURE WITH BULLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB YOUNG  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALT LAKE CITY _ There's nothing quite like nice, warm weather
to soothe an aching back.
</P>
<P>
   At least, that's what the Suns are hoping Chicago free agent
Scottie Pippen will think about during the coming weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Pippen was evasive about his future with the Bulls or other
teams in the wake of Chicago's series-clinching Game 6 victory
Sunday at the Delta Center. But Pippen has said before that Phoenix
is one of the places he would strongly consider playing next
season.
</P>
<P>
   He has wavered on whether he is willing to re-sign with Chicago
for next season, and was noncommittal Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not thinking about that right now,'' Pippen said. ``Give
me a couple of days, and I'll give you and answer. But right now, I
just want to enjoy this moment and get myself feeling good again
physically. I just have to sit back and enjoy this moment, and I'll
just see what's going to happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything's possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Pippen played only 26 minutes and scored eight points in what
may have been his last game in a Chicago uniform. He was suffering
from back spasms that required anti-inflammatory injections
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   He aggravated the back while dunking in the opening minute of
the game and twice had to leave the court to get treatment in the
Bulls' locker room.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just tried to gut it out and was able to get six, seven
minutes in the first half. I told (Coach) Phil (Jackson) to take me
out of the game. It was just very difficult for me.''
</P>
<P>
   But Pippen played the final 10 minutes and put to rest a lot of
questions about his toughness and desire. Those questions started
in 1990 when Pippen had migraine headaches during the Eastern
Conference finals and Detroit eliminated the Bulls.
</P>
<P>
   He took heat later for refusing to go into a game when Jackson
wanted him to be the decoy in the final 1.8 seconds so that Toni
Kukoc could take the final shot.
</P>
<P>
   But Pippen said none of that mattered.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not exactly,'' he said. ``I just wanted to get the series over
with. I wanted the team to stay close and allow me the opportunity
to come out and give my best 24 minutes, which didn't look that
great.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was important for me to try to be on the court and make my
presence known. But I don't want to reflect on those (past) things.
I just try to go out and play for my teammates, and give the best
performance I can and try to come away with a win.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-15-98 0219EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
