A8949 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-BOXING-NOTEBOOK-A     06-15 0669
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-BOXING-NOTEBOOK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DE LA HOYA CONTINUES `LOVE AFFAIR' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By NORM FRAUENHEIM  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   O &UR; scar De La Hoya's love affair with the public is moving in a
couple of directions at a rapid rate. Make that an alarming rate.
</P>
<P>
   His third-round victory by technical knockout Saturday night
over
 &UR; Patrick Charpentier at El Paso was a sure sign that he has yet to
reach his peak in popularity.
</P>
<P>
   For all it mattered, De La Hoya could have been punching a beach
ball. Come to think of it, an average, off-the-shelf inflatable
might have offered more resistence than Charpentier, who landed on
the canvas nearly as often as he landed punches. In three rounds,
the Frenchman suffered three knockdowns and connected only five
times.
</P>
<P>
   But the Sun Bowl crowd of more than 45,000 didn't care. De La
Hoya could do no wrong. In part, his burgeoning popularity is
rooted in the growing economic clout of Mexican-Americans, the
dominant demographic in today's boxing audience.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, as De La Hoya's popularity soars, he also is moving
headlong toward a credibility gap. One threatens to undercut the
other. At some point, he has to fight legitimate contenders,
instead of unknown Frenchmen and other assorted phonies.
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya hears skeptical talk about his record and claim on
being the world's best, regardless of weight. So has his promoter,
 &UR; Bob  &UR; Arum, who often appears to be in the business of selling
Oscar the personality instead of De La Hoya the puncher. Make no
mistake, it's hard to blame Arum. Oscar the personality is making
Arum rich all over again.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, there are signs of impatience with welterweight bouts that
have been scheduled for De La Hoya the puncher. There's a rematch
on Sept. 18 with aging  &UR; Julio Cesar Chavez, who first has to win a
tuneup on June 25 at Mashantucket, Conn. Then, there's a
possibility of Mexican Yory Boy Campas in November.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, there's just talk about  &UR; Felix Trinidad, &UR; Ike Quartey
and
 &UR; Jose  &UR; Luis Lopez. Arum says he has made offers to Trinidad and
Ouartey.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've put huge money on the table,'' said Arum, who has yet to
express interest in Lopez. ``I've offered Trinidad $7 million, and
that's a firm offer. I've offered Quartey's people $3.5 million
anytime they want it.''
</P>
<P>
   There are explanations as to why no deals have been struck.
Trinidad is still under contract to Arum rival  &UR; Don King. Quartey
has management problems. Blah-blah, yadda-yadda. Fact is, De La
Hoya is the most powerful figure in the sport. If he really wants
those bouts, he can make them happen. The stakes are his
credibility, which is a lot more durable than either popularity or
punching power. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Briefly . . .
</P>
<P>
   It sounds as if De La Hoya pushed for a Chavez rematch. He says
he has score to settle with Chavez, who said a cut in training led
to his fourth-round loss in the first bout. ``Chavez is personal,''
De La Hoya said. ``He never gave me the respect I deserved, so now
I want to be the first to knock him out. I'm disappointed by the
way he acts, makes excuses. It's terrible to find out my childhood
idol is the way he is. I want to punish him.''
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya paid a price for wearing that gold sombrero and
matching suit to the ring before opening bell. His fashion
statement cost $15,000.
</P>
<P>
   World Boxing Association featherweight champion &UR; 
 &UR; Freddy  &UR; Norwood _ impressive Saturday in an ABC-telecast victory
from Atlantic City _ has a Phoenix-based manager,  &UR; Barrett Silver.
The hope is for Norwood to fight for big money against  &UR; Prince
Naseem Hamed, although Hamed might back away from a date with the
skillful Norwood.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Danny Romero's chances of avenging last summer's loss to
Albuquerque rival  &UR; Johnny Tapia appear to have improved because of
the cancellation 10 days ago of a  &UR; Evander Holyfield-featured card
after  &UR; Henry Akinwande was found to have Hepatitis B. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Norm Frauenheim can be reached at 602-444-8259 or
norm.frauenheim(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-15-98 0220EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980615.0042 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-15 02:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8950 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-DBACKS-BLAIR-AZR &LR;      06-15 0546
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DBACKS-BLAIR-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLAIR BAFFLES, IMPRESSES CARDS  
 `I'D TAKE HIM,' MCGWIRE SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB COHN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   If this was an audition, Willie Blair passed it.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks right-hander has been the subject of trade
rumors lately. One of the reported suitors is the St. Louis
Cardinals, whose starting pitchers have been racking up
frequent-guest points in the trainer's room. On Sunday at Bank One
Ballpark, Blair did nothing to diminish his appeal, even though the
Cardinals won, 2-0.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I threw the ball today as well as I possibly could
have,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Offering no resistance to the thought was Cardinals slugger Mark
McGwire, who struck out three times against Blair.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd take him on my team any day,'' said McGwire, who pleaded
ignorance to any trade talk and volunteered the comment.
</P>
<P>
   When told of the rumors, he reiterated his point.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to see him in this locker room,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   It isn't that big of a secret that the Cardinals have been
scouting Blair, who fell to 2-9, despite giving up only two runs
and seven hits in seven innings while striking out five and walking
two. The Cards' intended rotation of Todd Stottlemyre, Alan Benes,
Matt Morris, Kent Mercker and Donovan Osborne has been scuttled by
injuries. Only Stottlemyre and Mercker have recorded 10 or more
starts, and help is being sought.
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis got some Sunday when Mark Petkovsek and Kent
Bottenfield combined on a four-hitter, but another starter probably
would be useful.
</P>
<P>
   Blair, perhaps? Probably not. The Diamondbacks almost certainly
would demand a couple of prospects. The Cards likely would offer
Ron Gant, their $5 million part-time left fielder who would not be
a good fit. The Diamondbacks like their own left fielder, rookie
David Dellucci, better than Gant.
</P>
<P>
   Cardinals Manager Tony La Russa liked what he saw from Blair,
whose ERA has has made a steady descent from the stratosphere to
4.84 after he lost his first seven decisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen him with different clubs, and he's always impressed
me,'' La Russa said. ``He does a couple of things with his
fastball, a couple of things with his breaking ball. He changes
speeds. He's very competitive.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're looking all over the place for pitchers. If any team has
mentioned that one of their pitchers is available, we've talked
about him.''
</P>
<P>
   La Russa said he wasn't specifically describing ``Mr. Blair,''
because that, after all, would be tampering. Blair, for his part,
said he tries not to think about speculation and just pitches. And
how do the Diamondbacks feel about it?
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not trying to trade him,'' Manager Buck Showalter said.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire, who came up empty on a fishing expedition for several
of Blair's pitches out of the strike zone, likes how Blair mixes
things up.
</P>
<P>
   ``He changes speeds very well,'' Mac said. ``He doesn't seem to
have a set pattern. In, out, up, down. He knows how to pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   McGwire, who also walked, once again seemed exasperated to see a
horde of reporters gathered outside his locker. He believes he
doesn't need to comment if his performance wasn't relevant to the
outcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not an individual sport,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-15-98 0220EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
