A9146 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS     06-15 0949
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS-$ADV21-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW &AMP; NOTEWORTHY PAPERBACKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release on Sunday, June 21.)  
 (HLW)  
 By SCOTT VEALE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; THE PERFECT STORM: A TRUE STORY OF MEN AGAINST THE SEA &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Sebastian Junger. Harper Paperbacks, $6.99.
</P>
<P>
   In 1991, a 72-foot swordfishing boat and its crew of six were
hit in the Atlantic by a violent nor'easter with 120-mile-per-hour
winds and waves up to 100 feet high. The ensuing tragedy is
reconstructed in harrowing fashion, largely through the accounts of
survivors in other boats. ``The result is thrilling _ a boat ride
into and (for us) out of a watery hell,'' Anthony Bailey said here
last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PUBLISH AND PERISH: THREE TALES OF TENURE AND TERROR &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By James Hynes. Picador USA, $14.
</P>
<P>
   These novellas, driven by the monsters of pretension and
ambition that lurk in the groves of academe, meld post-modern farce
with old-fashioned cliffhanging narrative. ``Hynes is fearlessly
playful, a riveting storyteller and a graceful observer of human
folly,'' Cathleen Schine wrote last year in the Book Review.
Another satirical romp set in academia,  &UR; STRAIGHT MAN &LR; , by Richard
Russo (Vintage Contemporaries, $13), follows the misadventures of a
wisenheimer English professor at a third-rate college in
Pennsylvania. In 1997 our reviewer, Tom De Haven, called this ``the
funniest serious novel I have read since _ well, maybe since
'Portnoy's Complaint.' ''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SOUTHERN CROSS: THE BEGINNINGS OF THE BIBLE BELT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Christine Leigh Heyrman.
</P>
<P>
   University of North Carolina, $16.95.
</P>
<P>
   The itinerant evangelical preachers who swept through the South
as the Baptist and Methodist churches were taking shape in the late
18th century adapted their tone and theology in surprising ways to
win white male converts and broaden their appeal beyond women,
children, and slaves. This is a ``wonderfully told and beautifully
written story,'' Charles B. Dew wrote here in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE SHARP TEETH OF LOVE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Doris Betts. Scribner, $12.
</P>
<P>
   A former anorexic and current medical illustrator named Luna
Stone ditches her handsome fiance as they head to Nevada to get
married, and flees to the mountains near Donner Lake, where she
takes up with a snaggletoothed boy and a dropout from a Lutheran
seminary. Last year in the Book Review, Maxine Chernoff said this
novel ``relates with considerable tenderness'' the story of how the
three wanderers ``emerge from their emotional wilderness.'' The
same publisher has reissued a collection of Betts's short fiction,
 &UR; BEASTS OF THE SOUTHERN WILD: AND OTHER STORIES &LR;  ($11). Whether
exploring the inner life of a girl in labor, a schoolteacher or a
disfigured bus passenger, the writing ``remains very much an index
of one woman's intriguing mind,'' Michael Mewshaw wrote here in
1973.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TREASURE HUNT: A NEW YORK TIMES REPORTER TRACKS THE QUEDLINBURG
HOARD &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By William H. Honan. Delta, $12.95.
</P>
<P>
   At the close of the Second World War, 12 priceless medieval
objects were stolen from a cave near an ancient German town by a
kleptomaniac American soldier. The author, a correspondent for The
New York Times, tells in colorful detail how he and a European art
sleuth turned up the loot in small-town Texas nearly 50 years
later. ``This exciting and often rather touching book'' is ''a very
good read, full of suspense,'' Lynn Nicholas wrote here last year.
 &UR; THE LOST MUSEUM: THE NAZI CONSPIRACY TO STEAL THE WORLD'S GREATEST
WORKS OF ART &LR; , by Hector Feliciano (Basic Books, $15), traces the
fate of thousands of plundered artworks from Jewish collections in
occupied France as they passed from top Nazi officials to
collectors and dealers in France, Switzerland, and elsewhere. This
disturbing account of opportunistic greed and the banality of evil
is an ``important and instructive book,'' Richard Bernstein said in
The Times in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE SPEED QUEEN &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Stewart O'Nan. Ballantine, $12.
</P>
<P>
   In a creepy death-row novel straight out of Oliver Stone
country, a young woman explains how she slipped off track and wound
up as a partner in a drug-fueled killing spree that left 12 people
dead. Last year our reviewer, George Stade, said this lurid
confessional displays ``an unfailing intelligence, a grim and
bracing humor, an unblinking eye for the telling detail.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MONSTER: LIVING OFF THE BIG SCREEN &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By John Gregory Dunne. Vintage, $12.
</P>
<P>
   The author recounts one of the many screenwriting campaigns that
turned him and his partner and wife, Joan Didion, into hardened
veterans. In showing how the creature of the title (money) and its
best friend (the star) control the ``creative'' process, this book
``offers a crash course in getting a script through the hazards of
the present-day studio system,'' Larry Gelbart wrote here last
year. The same publisher has reissued an earlier account of Dunne's
Hollywood adventures,  &UR; THE STUDIO &LR;  ($13), which details the inner
workings of 20th Century Fox and the moviemaking ethos in 1967,
when films like ``Planet of the Apes'' were taking shape. In 1969,
one critic admired how the author captured the ''Gothic mix of
greed, hypocrisy, shrewd calculation, mad hoopla and boundless
optimism that shapes American films.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMFORT WOMAN &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Nora Okja Keller. Penguin, $12.95.
</P>
<P>
   A young Korean-American woman discovers that her tormented
mother was sold by her family during World War II and forced into a
``recreation center'' run by the Japanese army. Switching between
the daughter's voice and the mother's, this ``accomplished first
novel ... beautifully evokes both their anguish and their love,''
Lise Funderburg said here in 1997.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-15-98 0912EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980615.0048 </DOCNO>
