<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THISWEEK-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
13.) 
 GM WORKERS WALK OUT IN WIDENING STRIKE 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing. Originally filed on Saturday, June (The Week in Review)  
 (bl)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   General Motors and the United Automobile Workers union stumbled
into another showdown, as a spreading strike by auto parts workers
in Flint, Mich., forced the temporary closing of dozens of GM
assembly plants and parts factories.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of workers struck over GM's efforts to move production
to other factories inside and outside the country where costs are
lower.
</P>
<P>
   The auto maker had infuriated the union by removing parts-making
equipment from a Flint factory over the Memorial Day weekend, but
negotiators began making progress after GM agreed on Thursday to
return the equipment. Remaining are a series of financial issues,
on which it will be easier to split the difference in the coming
days or weeks.
</P>
<P>
   _ By KEITH BRADSHER &QR;
</P>
<P>
   NATO Warns Serbs
</P>
<P>
   No one wants full-scale war over Kosovo. ``It is not our desire
to use force,'' Secretary of State Madeleine Albright stressed. At
the same &QL; 
time, she said she felt the need to send a ``strong message'' to
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic in response to persistent
attacks on the province by his forces.
</P>
<P>
   The NATO alliance agreed, authorizing a big military exercise
just across the border from Kosovo. And Russia joined the United
States and its major allies in demanding that the Serbs desist by
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   _ By HUBERT B. HERRING
</P>
<P>
   Cigarette Maker Held Liable
</P>
<P>
   The tobacco industry's tight door against lawsuits was jolted
open when a Florida jury ordered Brown &AMP; Williamson Tobacco Co. to
pay $1 million to the family of a man whose death from cancer was
blamed on cigarettes. The award included $450,000 in punitive
damages, marking the first time a jury in a tobacco case as ordered
such a penalty.
</P>
<P>
   And it may not be the last. The winning lawyer, Norwood Wilner
of Jacksonville, Fla., has 100 claims pending against cigarette
makers.
</P>
<P>
   _ By BARRY MEIER
</P>
<P>
   Moscow Aims at Tax Evasion
</P>
<P>
   Getting a handle on Russia's economic activity is notoriously
difficult because businesses routinely under-report their
production to minimize taxes. The government of Boris Yeltsin took
a first step toward improving official economic estimates by
arresting the country's top statisticians and accusing them of
manipulating data to help Russian companies avoid taxes.
</P>
<P>
   The International Monetary Fund, which told the government it
needed to slash its budget deficit and overhaul its tax system to
qualify for billions of dollars in extra loans, says Russia's
economic production is roughly 20 percent greater than official
estimates.
</P>
<P>
   Honda and Ford Fined Millions
</P>
<P>
   The air has gotten cleaner even as the number of cars has
skyrocketed, partly because new autos have sophisticated computers
that monitor engine functions. But Honda and Ford's vehicles were a
little TOO sophisticated, the government said.
</P>
<P>
   The automakers agreed to pay millions of dollars in civil fines
for selling cars that were designed to pass emissions tests but run
dirtier on the road, according to federal prosecutors. Both
companies denied wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   _ By MATTHEW L. WALD
</P>
<P>
   Tuberculosis DNA Is Decoded  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For a really scary disease, forget Ebola and other plagues.
Tuberculosis, contained at present by antibiotics, may not be kept
at bay for long. The bacterium, which is easily inhaled, already
infects much of the world's population and kills three million
people a year in the less developed world.
</P>
<P>
   But scientists at the Sanger Center in England, in a tour de
force that took two years, have deciphered the 4.4 million letters
of the bacterium's genetic code, revealing every genetic weapon in
the organism's armory. Designers of drugs and vaccines can now
choose among the microbe's 4,000 genes for suitable targets.
</P>
<P>
   _ By NICHOLAS WADE &QR;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Heart Drug Is Withdrawn  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When Food and Drug Administration officials approved the heart
drug Posicor last June, they knew it could be lethal when mixed
with certain other drugs. But the danger was worse than they
imagined.
</P>
<P>
   By last week, the FDA had tallied 26 medications that are toxic
in combination with Posicor, forcing Roche Laboratories of Nutley,
N.J., to recall the drug from pharmacy shelves in 38 countries.
</P>
<P>
   It was only the third time in the past decade, FDA officials
said, that they have taken an approved drug off the market.
</P>
<P>
   _ By SHERYL GAY STOLBERG
</P>
<P>
   Kim Goes to Washington  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Washington paid homage to the President of South Korea, Kim
Dae-jung, who is in the United States seeking investment for his
beleaguered economy and lobbying for an easing of international
sanctions on North Korea. President Clinton welcomed Kim with a
private Oval Office meeting and a sumptuous state dinner.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton likened the frail, 74-year-old Kim, a longtime dissident
imprisoned, exiled and sentenced to die by the former South Korean
authorities, to Lech Walesa and Nelson Mandela. But Clinton did not
accede to Kim's request to lift U.S. economic sanctions on
communist North Korea.
</P>
<P>
   _ By JOHN M. BRODER
</P>
<P>
   Intel Cited in Antitrust Suit  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In an unusual antitrust case, the Federal Trade Commission filed
suit against Intel Corp., accusing the company of withholding
information about its chips that three computer makers considered
crucial to developing their own products based on Intel
microprocessors.
</P>
<P>
   Antitrust laws are designed to prevent monopolists from using
predatory tactics to destroy rivals; in this case, however, Intel
is accused of victimizing putative competitors that are also among
its major customers.
</P>
<P>
   Vouchers for Church Schools  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In a decision many believe is headed for the U.S. Supreme Court,
the Wisconsin Supreme Court ruled that the city of Milwaukee may
use school vouchers to send poor children to parochial schools,
saying the plan did not violate the First Amendment's separation of
church and state.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling gave a boost to the growing school-choice movement,
which seeks to send children in failing public schools to private
ones, most of which have religious affiliations. The aim is to
inject competition into education as a means of forcing
improvement.
</P>
<P>
   _ By ETHAN BRONNER
</P>
<P>
   Ruling on Online Privacy
</P>
<P>
   It was not the retirement that Master Chief Petty Officer
Timothy R. McVeigh had wanted. But after America Online violated
its in-house rules and disclosed to a military investigator that
the sailor had posted an electronic message describing himself as
gay, McVeigh said he was left with little choice but to go.
</P>
<P>
   The Navy had originally planned to discharge McVeigh without
retirement benefits. But after a federal judge's ruling that the
Defense Department had violated its ``don't ask, don't tell'' rule
in investigating McVeigh's sexual orientation, the Navy agreed to
provide him with full benefits and pay his legal fees.
</P>
<P>
   America Online reached a separate settlement and agreed to pay
damages to McVeigh for violating his privacy; the sum was not
disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   _ By PHILIP SHENON
</P>
<P>
   Health Plans for Elderly
</P>
<P>
   Medicare recipients will soon have a wide range of health
insurance options like those available to workers in private
industry. Consumer advocates predict that the new choices will be
confusing to the elderly, most of whom have little experience with
managed health care.
</P>
<P>
   The new options offer the promise of extra benefits, like
prescription drugs, but could also increase costs for some patients
or limit their freedom to choose doctors and hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   _ By ROBERT PEAR
</P>
<P>
   Abraham Lincoln, Deadbeat
</P>
<P>
   House Republicans last week excoriated their fellow Americans as
a bunch of deadbeats casually running up debts and then
disingenuously pleading bankruptcy to wipe their slates clean.
</P>
<P>
   A record 1.4 million people declared bankruptcy last year _
evidence, lawmakers said, that a tighter law and more personal
responsibility were in order.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans did not mention that one of their party's most
prominent members was a self-declared ``insolvent debtor'' who
would surely have filed for bankruptcy had the current laws been
available to him.
</P>
<P>
   In 1832 a young man named Abraham Lincoln bought a small general
store in New Salem, Ill., with a partner. On credit, they acquired
the inventory of other nearby stores.
</P>
<P>
   The economy was booming, but the two prairie entrepreneurs could
not make a go of it and began sliding into debt.
</P>
<P>
   Lincoln sold his share, but when his partner died he became
liable for $1,000 in debts, according to Gerald Prokopowicz, a
scholar at the Lincoln Museum in Fort Wayne, Ind.
</P>
<P>
   Creditors hauled Lincoln into court, and the sheriff seized his
only assets _ his survey equipment and his horse. The store, in
Lincoln's phrase, ``winked out.''
</P>
<P>
   As a budding state legislator in 1835, Lincoln introduced a bill
to provide relief for insolvent debtors. But it didn't pass, and
Honest Abe was still repaying his debts ``well into the 1840s,''
said Kim Bauer, curator at the Illinois State Historical Library.
</P>
<P>
   It was so onerous that Lincoln called it ``my national debt.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE
</P>
<P>
   A Hairdresser Strikes Oil
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes the march of progress goes past some incongruous
places, like the Alabama ditch where space agency engineers
gathered to pump dirty water through a barrel partly filled with
human hair.
</P>
<P>
   And while inventions may come in a flash from above, sometimes
they grow out of odd observations about everyday stuff. Such was
the case with Phil McCrory, the hairdresser whose salon floor
provided the hair in the NASA barrel, which was being tested as a
potentially quicker and cheaper way to clean up oil spills.
</P>
<P>
   It was television footage of the Exxon Valdez spill in 1989 that
started McCrory thinking about oil, particularly a shot of an otter
rolling in a slick. ``That's when the light went off,'' McCrory
said. The otter's fur was soaking up lots of oil _ would human hair
do the same?
</P>
<P>
   To find out, he stuffed a pair of his wife's pantyhose with as
much hair as it would hold _ three or four pounds _ poured a gallon
of used motor oil into the water in his son's wading pool and
dropped his ``test otter'' in. ``In two minutes the water was
crystal clear,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the hair on the floor of McCrory's Huntsville salon came
from workers at NASA's Marshall Space Flight Center, who put him in
touch with Maurice Hale, a technology transfer expert.
</P>
<P>
   It turns out the tiny cuticles that cover a shaft of human hair
give the surface tension of oil, which is repelled by water,
something to cling to.
</P>
<P>
   McCrory's dream is to stuff hair collected from salons all over
the country into small reusable mesh pillows that can be quickly
deployed to soak up oil spills. Sounds like a cutting-edge
solution.
</P>
<P>
   _ By JOHN O'NEIL
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
