 NEWS &AMP; FEATURES SUMMARY No 2455 - JUNE 15, 1998  
<TEXT>
<P>
   1. JOHN GLENN FOR THE SPACE AGE John Glenn will be 77 when he
makes his sec[~nd spaceflight. To some, it's a political payoff.
John Glenn himself says he's returning to space to promote research
on aging. His trip is undoubtedly a publicity stunt - but trading
on nostalgia is only one aspect of the NASA project. For 10
weightless days, Glenn will subject himself to a marathon of
geriatic experimentation. By Thomas Mallon. From The New York Times
Magazine. 2,000 words.
_______________________________________________________________2.
'THE X-FILES' ... IT JUST LOOKS PARANOID An 'X-Files' movie, based
on television's weirdest prime-time drama, is opening, no doubt, to
lots of Deep Think about how spooky and conspiratorial America has
become. But maybe what is oddest about the hit series is how
reassuring it can be. By Charles McGrath. From The New York Times
Magazine. 3,000 words.
_______________________________________________________________ 3.
WHAT'S DOING IN .... Tips on events, sightseeing, hotels and
restaurants in European cities. From The New York Times Way To Go!
A. PARIS By Corinne LaBalme. 1,500 words + photos+ map. B.
BARCELONA By Steven Greenhouse. 1,400 words + photos. C. LISBON By
Marvine Howe. 1,700 words + photos.
_______________________________________________________________4.
COSMIC CLUTTER This time of year, one can see a slew of manmade
objects slowly crisscrossing the heavens. They weren't visible two
months ago, and they won't be around after August. But they are
here now during satellite season, when Earth's northern axis tilts
just 5 degrees from its maximum sunward extreme. By Bob Berman.
From Discover magazine. 600 words + photos.
_______________________________________________________________ 5.
AMERICANIZING ASIA? It is presumptuous to think the Asian financial
crisis foretells Asian acceptance of American ways. The Asian
economies holding up the best may be those with the most political
freedom, but the real key may be competent government. East Asia is
changing, but not Americanizing. By Donald K. Emmerson. From
Foreign Affairs magazine. 1,300 words.
_______________________________________________________________6.
FUSION'S FUTURE Will tomorrow's power plants run on a few ounces of
hydrogen and boron instead of several hundred tons of coal?
Physicist Hendrik Monkhorst is betting on it, writes Jeffrey
Winters. From Discover magazine. 800 words + photo
_______________________________________________________________ 7.
GOOD GOVERNMENT The late Mancur Olson, who died in February, was
one of the most distinguished economists of our time. Olson's
analysis of how political lobbies weaken democracies subverts both
left and right. By Iain McLean. Prospect magazine. (N/A U.K.) 3,000
words.
_______________________________________________________________8.
AN ALTERNATIVE BIG BANG THEORY Exposure to loud noises can cause
permanent damage to hearing. Unlike normal age-related hearing
loss, damage caused by exposure to high noise levels cannot be
corrected with a hearing aid. But exactly how does the damage
occur? Swedish researchers provide the first dynamic description of
the changes that go on in the ear after exposure to loud noises. By
Helen Phillips. Nature News Service. (N/A France, Spain.) 600
words.
_______________________________________________________________ 9.
ARE YOUR CHILDREN SAFE IN YOUR CAR? Patrick Boyle offers a series
of safety, maintenance and driving strategies for the concerned
parent, from what you need in your glove compartment and your
breakdown emergency kit to what you should look for in your tyres
and brakes. From Child magazine. 1,100 words.
_______________________________________________________________10.
WOULD PATIENTS DO BETTER IF THEY LOWERED THEIR BLOOD
</P>
<P>
   PRESSURE EVEN FURTHER? In a large study published in this week's
Lancet, researchers found that lowering a patient's blood pressure
slightly lower, to 140/85, provided more protection against the
complications of hypertension than did lowering it to 140/90, but
that lowering it further, below 140/85, provided no additional
benefit. In addition, the researchers found that with the newer
medications used in this study, this level of blood pressure
reduction could be easily achieved in most of the patients. By
Michael McCarthy. The Lancet News Service. 1,000 words.
_______________________________________________________________ 11.
FROM NEW SCIENTIST (Not available in Australia, New Zealand,
Brazil) A. ALL FOR ONE ... ONE FOR ALL : Ants behave with a
collective intelligence that can't be explained by their genes
alone, says Brian Goodwin. And he's built a virtual colony to show
the team in action. 2,000 words. B. ROBOJEEP : The U.S. Marine
Corps has ambitious plans to redesign that old military workhorse,
the Jeep. Adam Marcus finds out how the prototypes are shaping up.
1,200 words.
</P>
