<HEADER>
A9306 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN16-COX     06-15 0586
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Baptists turn back clock on American family life
 &HT;    (ATTN: Editorial, opinion page editors)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By TOM TEEPEN
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   My parents taught me it is best not to fuss at other folks'
religions and that's still good advice, but, Lord, it's difficult
to stick to when the Southern Baptist Convention gets together.
</P>
<P>
   The Southern Baptists, the nation's largest Protestant
denomination, have been marching deeper into theological
conservatism throughout the 1980s and '90s _and typically deeper
into political conservatism as well _ and this year, going
head-to-head with the hardly liberal Mormons of Salt Lake City,
they seem to have broken through conservatism into outright
reaction.
</P>
<P>
   As part of its Baptist Faith and Message, the denomination's
basic grid of religious beliefs, the convention adopted a
declaration on family life that few of us outside the religion can
read as anything much better than a demand for domestic feudalism.
You can guess who get to be the serfs.
</P>
<P>
   The statement declares that while husbands and wives are equal
before God, wives must ``submit graciously'' to the leadership of
their husbands _ ``even as the church willingly submits to the
headship of Christ.''
</P>
<P>
   Husbands, then, are in effect the homebody analogues of the
godhead, a status few of us have dared openly to assert, however
much privately we may have thought it so.
</P>
<P>
   Baptists are an independent lot, almost instinctively
anti-dogma, and are capable of a good bit of doctrinal unruliness,
but where it can _ in its publications and seminaries, for instance
_ the convention's leadership has been firmly enforcing its
deepening pre-modernism. The line is thus being pounded home on
ever more pulpits.
</P>
<P>
   That has both personal and public consequences. The new family
policy amounts to an attempt to enforce theologically what can no
longer be enforced legally _ a version of the old Head and Master
laws, which lasted into the 1980s in some states and gave husbands,
as legal heads of their households, control of all family assets.
</P>
<P>
   It is hard to imagine Baptist marriages that are happy on
whatever basis giving this new injunction a second thought, so no
harm done there. But it is not difficult to imagine the imperative
being taken up by precisely the sort of husbands who should not be
trusted with it. Expect damage.
</P>
<P>
   And because religious attitudes flow into the social hubbub from
which we extract public policy, the Baptist declaration is bound to
turn up in politics, adding, for example, to the push already under
way to repeal no-fault divorce and enact so-called covenant
marriages, together an attempt to return to days when marriages
were based as much on coercion as on mutual consent.
</P>
<P>
   The convention was responding to what it sees as a crisis in
American family life. That crisis is less clear to others. Yes, a
bit more than four in 10 marriages will end in divorce. That's too
many. But the rate has declined about 15 percent from its high in
1980, and many divorces _ at last count, nearly half _ involve no
minor children and thus amount to private matters, often personally
painful but relatively free of social consequences.
</P>
<P>
   Argue that one whichever way you like. Either way, it is hard to
see how American family life would be uplifted by basing it on
power instead of partnership.
</P>
<P>
   E-Mail:teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
