<HEADER>
A9395 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ARTHUR-MURRAY16-COX     06-15 1488
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARTHUR-MURRAY16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Takin' a swing at ballroom dancing
 &HT;    By Loretta Grantham
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   If Arthur Murray were here today, he'd probably use the Gap
khaki commercial as a teaching tool.
</P>
<P>
   (Who needs a footprint diagram when you have wiggling models
doing the Lindy hop to Louis Prima?)
</P>
<P>
   As Murray studios celebrate 85 years of eliminating two left
feet, ballroom dancing is becoming hip again - thanks largely to TV
and film.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd say my business has gone up 25 percent just from the Gap
commercial and others like it that show the swing,'' says Angelo
Caruso, owner of Caruso Dance Sport in West Palm Beach.
</P>
<P>
   (Dance 101: The swing is also called the Lindy hop, jive, shag,
jitterbug and boogie-woogie.)
</P>
<P>
   ``People come in here wanting to do the `Gap dance,' `` he says.
``Especially young couples.''
</P>
<P>
   Like rising college sophomore Annie Evans, 18, of North Palm
Beach and her boyfriend, Travis Grainger, 24, who plan to take
lessons this summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want something new and different to do,'' she says.
``Besides, swing dancing is the newest thing at clubs, and we have
no idea how to dance together.''
</P>
<P>
   Dewey Whitley, marketing vice president at Arthur Murray
International - based in Coral Gables - is amused by the
``newness.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This has all been around for so long,'' he says. ``And now
it's a retro craze. Many people moved away from ballrooms after
World War II, so it's really more accurate to call this `social
dancing' or `touch dancing' - where partners are in contact and the
man leads.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Al Pacino in Scent of a Woman and Arnold Schwarzenegger in
True Lies, who both whipped the tango right back into pop culture,
red rose included.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of movies, The Last Days of Disco, which opened last
week, is one of several recent '70s flicks resurrecting the hustle.
Simply Ballroom and Shall We Dance? are also boosting dance-school
business. And Vanessa Williams' Dance with Me, which debuts July
31, will add fuel to the fire.
</P>
<P>
   It's the same effect Rocky films had on boxing gyms.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of a sudden there has just been this major rush,'' says
Gayle Morley, who owns Dancin' Dance Centre in Palm Beach Gardens
with her husband, Joseph.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of requests for swing and disco lessons, and
the people who've been coming in are right around 20 to 30 years
old.
</P>
<P>
   ``Young people are searching for something else to do besides
the same old bar scene,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   ``And they're tired of standing across from each other, bouncing
up and down and calling it dancing,'' Joseph adds.
</P>
<P>
   (The U.S. Amateur Ballroom Dancers Association, by the way, has
more than doubled to 15,000 members since 1993, mostly because of
the 30-and-under set.)
</P>
<P>
   Another reason for the ballroom-dance revival is that Baby
Boomers are getting older. And with age comes ... decorum.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you get into your late 30s and up, you don't want to get
out there and do the jerk on the dance floor when you're executive
vice president of a company,'' Whitley says. ``And you can't
exactly do Michael Jackson moves at a charity gala.''
</P>
<P>
   (Or a ball chairman might tell you to beat it. Ahem.)
</P>
<P>
   Long before Gap ads and dance flicks, however, there was Arthur
Murray - an immigrant baker's son who became the world's best-known
teacher of ballroom dancing. He died in 1991 at age 95.
</P>
<P>
   A native New Yorker, Arthur Murray Teichman - who shortened his
name in 1914 at the suggestion of his dance partner - taught his
first lesson 85 years ago. Now there are about 200 franchised
studios, including one in Fort Lauderdale and another in Sunrise.
</P>
<P>
   In the beginning, the ``Murray method'' involved diagrams with
numbered footsteps; handsome instructors who were told to keep
smiling; studios that Murray kept clean and decorous; and
fashionable dance steps, some of which he helped popularize by
paying young folks to do them in nightclubs.
</P>
<P>
   His clients included Eleanor Roosevelt, the Duke and Duchess of
Windsor, John D. Rockefeller Jr., Cornelius Vanderbilt Whitney,
Barbara Hutton and Elizabeth Arden. And that's just the short list.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the '20s, Arthur Murray branched out into mail order, which
was very unusual at the time,'' says Tony Cardinali, franchise vice
president for Arthur Murray International. ``You could order the
diagrams, which were printed on large sheets like butcher paper,
and spread them out on the floor.''
</P>
<P>
   Think Twister board. The diagrams - which can be tough to
decipher - are no longer used (except for decoration).
</P>
<P>
   It's just as confusing to try to learn from a book, although
there are plenty of ballroom-dance manuals that give instructions
like ``hand hold push'' and ``Step R foot complete cuddle.''
</P>
<P>
   Huh? Take a class.
</P>
<P>
   When Murray started out, a dance lesson cost $5. Nowadays, a
session averages about $40 for 45 minutes to an hour but can run
less if purchased in a package. Prices also vary depending on
whether it's individual or couple instruction.
</P>
<P>
   Another strategy is to take a group lesson like the ones taught
at area dance halls.
</P>
<P>
   ``It costs $7 a person to get in on ballroom nights - Thursdays
and Saturdays from 8 to 11 p.m. - and we have a class beforehand to
review steps and introduce new ones,'' says Rob McGregor, an owner
of Dazzle Me Twice, a ballroom in West Palm Beach.
</P>
<P>
   ``People used to think of ballroom dancing as this dusty old
thing, but it's had quite a face lift, and we're seeing it here. It
certainly seems to have a more gymnastic, athletic quality about
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed. In September, the International Olympic Committee gave
full recognition to the International Dancesport Federation, a
vital step in making competitive ballroom dancing - or dancesport,
as some folks call it - an Olympic event. And cable TV channels are
increasing coverage, so it's not just on PBS anymore.
</P>
<P>
   Dancesport will be an exhibition gig in the 2000 Olympics in
Sydney, then officials will decide in 2001 if it'll be a medal
event in future Games.
</P>
<P>
   Fear not, however, if you're no world-class athlete.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's extremely rare to teach someone who just doesn't get
it,'' Whitley says. ``In 20 years of being in this business, I've
never had a total failure.
</P>
<P>
   ``But that's the best thing about ballroom dancing. If you know
how to walk, you've mastered the hard part.''
</P>
<P>
   See a video of Gap's swing commercial and learn more about the
dance craze at Palm Beach Interactive: www.GoPBI.com/aroundtown THE
SWING 1930s and 1998
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to the ``khakis swing' Gap ad campaign and the resurging
popularity of lounges (what's a disco?), the swing - popular in the
'30s - is reborn. The Depression, which made record sales drop from
100 million in 1927 to 6 million in 1931, had the music industry
scrambling for a new sound. Enter ``King of Swing'' Benny Goodman,
who gave jazz rhythms an uplifted tempo that was perfect for
dancing. First known as the Lindy hop after Charles Lindberg's
``hop'' across the Atlantic to Paris, the swing has variations
called the jitterbug, shag, jive and boogie-woogie. Because the
dance involved acrobatic movements, it was barred from many dance
halls as being too dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   (GT) THE TANGO 1912
</P>
<P>
   The tango is a mixture of the tangano a dance that African
slaves take to Haiti and Cuba in the 18th century and the habanera
(''Havana dance'') of 19th-century Cuba. The combo arrives in
Argentina via migrants and becomes a hit among cowboys and in the
Buenos Aires slums. While rich folks think it too unrefined, the
dance nevertheless moves to Europe first Paris, then London in 1912
where it is performed on stage in The Sunshine Girl. That same
year, Murray Teichman who changes his name to Arthur Murray in 1914
teaches his first dance lesson at the Grand Central Plaza in New
York. THE MAMBO 1943
</P>
<P>
   Cuban bandleader Perez Prado is credited with creating the mambo
craze in 1943 by modifying the dances performed by sugar-cane
cutters and introducing them in Havana nightclubs. (The word
``mambo'' supposedly comes from the Nanigo dialect spoken in Cuba.
Another version says it's the borrowed name of an African
priestess.) A blend of Latin American and jazz rhythms, the mambo's
trademark is a beat in each bar on which the dancer takes no step.
By 1953, there are weekly mambo contests at the Savoy Ballroom in
Harlem. THE HUSTLE 1975
</P>
<P>
   After a decade of solo dancing, couples in the '70s return to
partner formations, and the hustle actually requires folks to touch
(forget the bump). The step-tap-step-tap American-born jig has
variations in discos across the country (i.e., the New Yor
</P>
<P>
   (Bet you can still hum the tune.) Four years later, Gloria
Gaynor's I Will Survive is the No. 1 hit, but the hustle doesn't
survive. By the mid-'80s, solo dancing (to tunes like Michael
Jackson's Beat It) is back.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
