<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-15 12:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9396 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOMELESS-LAWSUIT16-CO     06-15 1701
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOMELESS-LAWSUIT16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By Jenny Staletovich
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI, Fla. _ Milton Finney is a small man with small needs.
Five feet is a struggle but making ends meet has never been a
problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to be a millionaire,'' said Finney, who is
homeless and eats most meals at Camillus House, a downtown Miami
shelter.
</P>
<P>
   Like thousands of other homeless in the city, Finney might
qualify for a landmark settlement hammered out of a 1988 class
action suit against the city for harassing homeless people. Unlike
many at Camillus House one day this week, Finney, 58, has actually
heard about it, especially the part where he gets $1,250. He is, in
fact, already banking on it for his move to easy street.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I could just get a little bit of money and put it in the
bank,'' he whispers conspiratorially, ``I could live off the
interest.''
</P>
<P>
   And there, in a nutshell, is the problem.
</P>
<P>
   The case, considered remarkable by many civil libertarians, is
the first to lay down rules protecting the homeless as a group.
</P>
<P>
   But while it untangles constitutional issues, in practical terms
the settlement poses more complicated problems.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, contrary to Finney's calculations, interest on
$1,250 will definitely not line his pockets and finance his
retirement. Finney would be better served, some suggest, by giving
the money to an agency that could help him off the street.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're talking about giving a dysfunctional person $1,250 to
continue to be dysfunctional,'' says Brother Paul Johnson, director
of Camillus House for the last two decades. ``It doesn't bring
about large change and my point is people who are homeless don't
have the same ability to operate like you and me. They're too busy
running from the police or whatever.''
</P>
<P>
   The legal theorists who wage the war for the homeless realize
this. But as they see it, the homeless should be free to do as they
please. Isn't that what they spent 10 years proving?
</P>
<P>
   ``I doubt anybody in the class will take the $1,250 and invest
it wisely and make themselves into substantial economic citizens,''
said Bruce Rogow, a constitutional law expert and American Civil
Liberties Union lawyer arguing another case connected to the
homeless in Fort Lauderdale, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   ``But as a matter of law they are entitled to some compensation
for their travails and if they misspend it, so be it.''
</P>
<P>
   Money aside, how in the world do you track down all the homeless
people who might qualify?
</P>
<P>
   Next month, the ACLU hopes to start signing up homeless to
collect the money paid out by the city. The ACLU, which sued the
city in 1988 to stop police from running ``bum details'' and
generally harassing people forced to live on the streets, plans to
run newspaper ads. The ads will appear each week for the first
three weeks in July. They're also hoping homeless groups will get
the word out. They have 90 days to sign people up and, so far, are
keeping their fingers crossed.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's some people who feel we'll be lucky if we get 20
people to come forward,'' said Benjamin Waxman, an ACLU attorney
who argued the case.
</P>
<P>
   The case has its beginnings on the day before New Year's Eve in
1987, when a cold front crept over Miami and dropped temperatures
to 51 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   As beds and floor space filled up at Camillus House, Brother
Paul _ one of three priests from the Brother of the Good Shepherd
living at the downtown mission _ started handing out blankets to
those locked out of the gated compound and sleeping on the street.
</P>
<P>
   ``I woke up at 1 a.m. and heard someone on speakers so I went to
the chapel and looked out the door and Miami police had cordoned
off the street and had buses,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That night, 40 homeless people were arrested, clearing the way
for the next day's King Orange Jamboree Parade through the heart of
the downtown.
</P>
<P>
   Brother Paul, an attorney for the mission and other homeless
advocates met that day with the chief of police and complained
bitterly.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were going to do an internal investigation, but they
never got back to me,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next year, police raided parks before events, including
Pope John Paul II's visit in the spring of 1987. Twice in early
1990, they rousted groups in parks, gathered up their belongings
and set them on fire. Altogether, the ACLU estimates 3,500 homeless
were arrested in sweeps between 1987 and 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Johnny ``Charles'' Major was 19, earning $3.35 an hour working
day labor and living in Lummus Park in Miami when police handcuffed
him, burned his belongings and took him to jail.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was trying my best in life. My best,'' said Major, who moved
out of his parents house and lived in the park for two months
before finding another relative to live with. ``When you go through
things like that and don't know why you're accosted, that can
contaminate your mind.''
</P>
<P>
   So in late 1988, ACLU lawyers met at Camillus House to plot a
strategy and came up with the lawsuit, Waxman said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The theory of the lawsuit was the city had this secret agenda
to drive homeless people out of the city, so it used an array of
misdemeanor ordinances that homeless people would be in violation
of to target them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We saw this as just trampling the rights of the most
powerless, impoverished citizens of the city. The city denied it up
one side and down the other. It's one thing to say we made a
mistake or haven't looked at it that way. But to just deny
something so clearly obvious and so severely injurious to the
lowest of the low got people's passions up.''
</P>
<P>
   Three men at the shelter agreed to be plaintiffs in the case and
at the end of December, the agency sued the city.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, U.S. District Judge C. Clyde Atkins refused to issue
an injunction against the city to stop sweeps. But after ACLU
attorneys convinced him to make it a class action and presented
evidence of the 1990 raids, Atkins ordered the city to stop.
</P>
<P>
   Two years later Atkins issued a stunning ruling finding the city
violated rights of the homeless and ordered the city to establish
two ``safe zones'' where homeless could live without fear of
arrest. City officials met with ACLU lawyers, but refused to set up
the safe zones and instead appealed Atkins' decision.
</P>
<P>
   The appellate court sent the case back to Atkins and asked him
to reconsider, saying conditions might have changed after four
years.
</P>
<P>
   A second trial in 1995 ended with the same ruling. The city
again appealed. But this time the appellate court ordered the ACLU
and the city to settle.
</P>
<P>
   ``It struck us as being unusual,'' Waxman said. ``I don't think
there was anyone who thought it could be resolved through that
process, not only because of the breadth and magnitude of the
issues, but because of the real kind of hostility that there was.''
</P>
<P>
   In February, the two sides finally submitted their settlement to
Atkins, a 32-page deal that includes sensitivity training for
police, new definitions for when a homeless person can be arrested,
the kind of documentation needed to claim part of the settlement
and what kind of money should be awarded.
</P>
<P>
   The money came down to $600,000 for the estimated 3,500 eligible
homeless and $900,000 for attorneys.
</P>
<P>
   The money would be divided up into $1,500 vouchers _ or a debit
card worth $1,500 that could be used in area stores _ to those
still homeless and $1,250 cash to those now living in homes.
</P>
<P>
   Atkins, however, suggested a few tougher standards when he
reviewed the settlement before approving a notice to the class.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, he didn't think attorneys should be paid more
than the homeless and suggested reducing attorney's fees to
$749,000 and increasing the cap on awards to $751,000.
</P>
<P>
   Atkins also thought requiring homeless to document their arrest
or loss of belongings was a bit absurd.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not as if they will have receipts proving that they
bought their cardboard boxes, etc.; or a government report of the
destruction of their belongings unless they were arrested,'' he
wrote in May.
</P>
<P>
   Sworn affidavits, he suggested, would suffice.
</P>
<P>
   He also pointed out that the agreement failed to provide for one
of the most basic needs of the homeless.
</P>
<P>
   ``The court suggests that public restrooms be designated as
accessible to homeless persons in the downtown areas at all times
of day or night. One way to do this would be to install, at least
temporarily, banks of `port-a-johns' with sinks and/or showers at
locations downtown where homeless people congregate,'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   The order was just another reason why homeless advocates have
cheered Atkins throughout the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``The homeless are really fortunate Clyde Atkins was assigned
this case because he's been a maverick,'' Brother Paul said. ``He's
going to go down in history as a real champion of the poor.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Atkins suggestions are just that. Suggestions. And so far
the city has done nothing to implement them, Waxman said. Since two
previous safe zones _one under the overpass to Miami Beach and
another at Bicentennial Park _ have been closed, no others have
been established.
</P>
<P>
   Warren Bittner, an assistant city attorney, declined to comment
on the details of the case and said the two sides still need to
discuss Atkins' suggestions.
</P>
<P>
   Atkins will hold a hearing on the settlement Sept. 29. In the
meantime, the Miami-Dade County Providers Forum, a collection of
groups that help the homeless, will meet next week to figure out
how to begin carrying out the settlement, said Morris Drew, interim
director of the Rainbow Beginning Ministries, Inc.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be monumental,'' said Drew, who wandered through
downtown one day this week in search of homeless to tell about the
deal. ``It's not just finding those now. That won't be so hard.
It's the old ones. We had a list of 30, but that was two years ago.
Since then, they've all scattered this way and that. There's some
skepticism that we'll get enough people to meet the $600,000. But
we're going to push for the max.''
</P>
<P>
   Jenny Staletovich writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm
Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
