<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HUMMINGBIRDS-STUDY16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hummingbirds give lessons in flight at UT
 &HT;    By Dick Stanley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ University of Texas zoologist Peng Chai really
started something in 1996 when he captured eight ruby-throated
hummingbirds in his West Austin back yard to study their flight
performance.
</P>
<P>
   Within a year, senior UT aerospace engineering students were
also studying the popular birds, using high-speed video cameras and
computers to analyze their wing movements in hopes of learning how
to build a robot hummingbird for military reconnaissance.
</P>
<P>
   Despite equipment failures and other setbacks, the students in
aerospace engineer Ron Stearman's design classes had soon found
something new.
</P>
<P>
   Research in the 1930s had shown that, at their normal rate of 55
beats a second, the birds' wings twist like a propeller blade,
tracing horizontal figure-eights in the air to hold their bodies in
a hover. The UT students found that the wingtips apparently can
also trace the shape of an airfoil, the curved profile of an
airplane's wing.
</P>
<P>
   A robot hummingbird would be a candidate for what the Defense
Advanced Research Projects Agency calls micro air vehicles:
miniature reconnaissance aircraft that soldiers could carry in
their packs to safely find out what's over the next hill and select
targets for artillery or airstrikes.
</P>
<P>
   Tentative specifications call for a 6-inch micro aircraft
weighing less than 2 ounces and capable of carrying a
camera-on-a-microchip for 60-minute surveillance flights at a range
of six miles.
</P>
<P>
   Engineers at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology have
developed a conventional jet engine that is less than one-half inch
long. It is one of several candidates to be the propulsion system .
</P>
<P>
   The 3-inch-long ruby throats, one of more than 300 species of
hummingbirds that are found only in the Western Hemisphere, are an
appealing model for a micro airplane because they can take off and
land quickly, flit from side to side while hovering and even fly
upside down.
</P>
<P>
   All that motion comes at a high price in energy. Previous
research has found that a 170-pound person would have to consume
130 pounds of bread to match a hummingbird's energy output.
</P>
<P>
   Chai has found his captive ruby throats amazingly easy to train
to fly in a wind tunnel and to hover at a sugar-water feeder in a
clear plastic study box. He has measured their average maximum
flight speed at 35 mph and found that, during migration, when they
put on extra weight for the trip, the females are better at
hovering than the males.
</P>
<P>
   The birds have not taken as well to the engineering studies.
Stearman's classes have found it easier, for instance, to
photograph hovering males than females.
</P>
<P>
   ``During filming, the hummingbird Felice would not cooperate,''
the spring study group, led by senior Erol Cagatay , wrote in its
final report. ``Felice did not react to the filming environment as
well as last semester's hummingbird, Bob, did (until) live, red
flowers (were put) at the end of the feeder to simulate a real
environment.''
</P>
<P>
   The students found that Felice was hard to film because she
didn't fly perpendicular to the horizon but rolled to one side and
skewed to the left or right, which they assumed was related to the
location of the feeder.
</P>
<P>
   Chai, however, theorized that Felice merely was attuned to the
students in the lab and was flying that way to keep an eye on what
they were doing.
</P>
<P>
   Stearman's spring semester students also arranged with the UT
geology department for a , CAT scan of a dead hummingbird's
skeleton to learn more about how a living hummingbird's wings work.
</P>
<P>
   A bird's wings are comparable to a person's arms, folding and
bending at the elbow and wrist with each wing beat. But older
research has shown that hummingbird wings do not move at the elbow
and wrist. Instead, their shoulders are jointed in such a way that
the wings are free to move in all directions.
</P>
<P>
   Hummingbird bones are fragile, however, and the CAT scan was
successful only in imaging the bird's head and beak.
</P>
<P>
   Another scan is planned this summer as a guide for building a
three-dimensional model of a hummingbird's full skeleton.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope to have that constructed in about a month,'' Stearman
said.
</P>
<P>
   Dick Stanley writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
