<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KABAT-COLUMN16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Commentary: The company of women
 &HT;    By Vicki Marsh Kabat
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ There is something about the company of women.
</P>
<P>
   It can be exhilarating or frustrating, hilarious or solemn,
silly or serious. Or all of those things simultaneously.
</P>
<P>
   I have not always had the company of women. As a young girl, I
had a ``best friend.'' We were blood sisters in the truest Tom
Sawyer sense of the term. We sat side by side on creekbanks, caught
frogs together, went skinny-dipping in the pond and pointed out to
each other rainbowed moons on hazy nights.
</P>
<P>
   We fantasized about what it would be like to kiss a boy. We
whispered about secret loves over our geography books and read
parts of Laura Ingalls Wilder's books aloud to one another. We
experimented with lipstick and mascara and shared the trauma of our
first pairs of pantyhose and pumps.
</P>
<P>
   The truly fortunate retain that first ``best'' friendship all
their lives. But I didn't. Nor do I remember why we drifted apart.
I suppose it doesn't matter at this late date. I still have these
memories. And other ``best friends'' came along _ each one moving
on before I was ready, but heeding some cosmic call neither one of
us understood.
</P>
<P>
   As a woman, my best friends became mentors. Wise women, usually
older than me, who lovingly and patiently guided me. They helped me
with my parenting and career, with my spiritual journey and
personal frustration. Their very presence, older and calmer,
modeled hope and possibility for me at a time in my life when both
were in short supply.
</P>
<P>
   There was one bleak period when I looked around and suddenly
realized I had no circle of friends. The most recent ones had
either moved away or emotionally distanced themselves. I had one or
two good friends, but time and responsibilities kept us from
investing what was needed for that most special of bonds, and
aching for the company of women.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly I had many acquaintances, either from church or PTA or
work. But no one to ask over to watch ``Out of Africa'' with. No
one with whom to run to Dairy Queen at 9 p.m. for a Buster Bar. You
know ... friends.
</P>
<P>
   I came to realize those times of aloneness are a natural part of
the seasons of one's life. They happen, and during them we must
learn to be patient and mindful. What am I learning about myself
during this time of solitude that will make me a better friend when
the next one comes along? Because they always do. Usually when we
least expect them.
</P>
<P>
   That's what happened to bring me into the circle of women
friends I now have and treasure. A phone call, actually, from a
woman I know who said she and another friend were forming a small
group to meet regularly to share our spiritual journeys. Would I
like to join them?
</P>
<P>
   Now, such groups can be stimulating or a total waste of time.
Much work must be done on group dynamics, bonding and building
community along the way. It doesn't just happen. It's a process,
and every step is fraught with both discovery and danger. Walking
the path, however, can be well worth it.
</P>
<P>
   So more than a year ago, we began to meet. We talk about what
God is doing in our lives, or not doing. We share good books, both
enlightening and lusty. We share recipes and baby pictures. We
laugh together and cry together. Sometimes we just sit and listen
to ``Ode to Joy'' played on a dulcimer. Other times, we sit in the
scented glow of a candle and pray.
</P>
<P>
   We bring together many gifts and talents. We are an amazing
circle of women _ strong, yet fragile; whole, yet hurting;
confident, yet shaky. All these things we pour out and into one
another until we each are built up by this, our very own ``cloud of
witnesses.''
</P>
<P>
   I like to imagine us 40 years from now, still meeting, probably
widowed. Still laughing and crying, still sharing books _ both
enlightening and lusty, still encouraging one another along the
journey.
</P>
<P>
   I see our gray heads bowed in a circle, our wrinkled,
age-spotted hands clasped as the warmth and strength of one flows
into the other and the other and the other ... in this company of
women.
</P>
<P>
   Vicki Marsh Kabat writes for the Waco (Texas) Tribune-Herald.
She can be reached online at VMKabat(at)aol.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The WACO TRIBUNE-HERALD
</P>
<P>
   AP-NY-06-12-98 1004E
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
