A9399 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LANE-COLUMN16-COX     06-15 0723
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LANE-COLUMN16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Commentary: Mouseketeers in the hands of an angry God
 &HT;    By Mark Lane
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's not easy living just down the interstate from Disney World.
</P>
<P>
   There's the traffic congestion. There are those out-of-state
guests who always want you to take them there. And then there are
the hurricanes and giant meteoroids of death crashing in from outer
space.
</P>
<P>
   Televangelist and former Republican presidential candidate Pat
Robertson recently warned about those last two problems. Robertson
said that by allowing gay groups to come to Disney World, Disney
and the city of Orlando are risking divine retribution.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would warn Orlando that you're right in the way of some
serious hurricanes, and I don't think I'd be waving those flags in
God's face if I were you,'' Robertson said on ``The 700 Club''
television show. The flags he mentioned were rainbow-motif banners
brought out for the Gay Days gathering in Orlando.
</P>
<P>
   Robertson warned that toleration of homosexuality ``will bring
about terrorist bombs. It will bring earthquakes, tornadoes and
possibly a meteor.''
</P>
<P>
   We've been warned.
</P>
<P>
   The Greater Disney World area is, geologically speaking, fairly
safe from earthquakes. Hurricanes, though, remain a problem but
more for coastal areas than for Orlando and Disney. Great. God gets
angry at Disney and smites Daytona Beach or Merritt Island. Is this
fair?
</P>
<P>
   And why would God punish Disney World for hosting gay people and
leave Key West alone? Central Florida coastal homeowners want this
theology expounded in greater detail so they can send rebuttals to
their insurance companies.
</P>
<P>
   As a coastal dweller and a person whose livelihood depends on
the brisk sale of newspapers, my vote is with the meteor.
</P>
<P>
   The destruction of Disney World by a giant, burning rock hurled
from the far reaches of the Solar System is not without a certain
mean-spirited appeal -- particularly after Disney hiked ticket
prices the way it's been doing.
</P>
<P>
   This lamentable celestial event would be a great story during a
slow news cycle and would give us a chance to build Interstate 4
over again. This time doing it right.
</P>
<P>
   Another plus is that meteorites are valuable.
</P>
<P>
   In Monahans, Texas, a meteorite that recently fell near a public
basketball court was supposed to be worth several thousand dollars.
This set off a controversy between the city and the kids who found
it. The city commission decided the kids would get the rock.
</P>
<P>
   So there you go. If the Disney neighborhood were hit by a
good-sized meteorite, you get both divine retribution and
compensation for property owners.
</P>
<P>
   That would be a big improvement over the cruder destruction done
by hurricanes, but maybe I'm just biased.
</P>
<P>
   Robertson, however, does not share this view. He has a certain
fondness for hurricanes.
</P>
<P>
   He says that not only once but twice he made hurricanes change
course to avoid Virginia Beach and his broadcasting equipment. The
last time, in 1986, the hurricane spared the broadcasting antennae
but instead killed 16 people where it finally did touch down.
Divine deliverance doesn't have the same effect for everyone
involved.
</P>
<P>
   This time though, Robertson is changing his shtick by bringing a
hurricane to an area.
</P>
<P>
   Like a lot of people, Robertson likes his divine displeasure
sudden, dramatic and big. Hurricanes, bombs and rocks hurtling from
outer space. This seems to presume that God wants the maximum
publicity for His efforts.
</P>
<P>
   I believe the Lord hurts those who hurt themselves. This tends
not to be flashy as your usual clouds of locusts, hurricanes and
exploding buildings. Sin punishment is a slow and grinding business
and it never seems to stop.
</P>
<P>
   We get punished for greed by seeing forests turn into strip
malls. We get punished for intolerance by people killing each
other. We get punished for neglecting kids by seeing them turn into
nasty adults.
</P>
<P>
   And we are already being punished for Disney World by having
traffic back up on Interstate 4 for the width of the state.
</P>
<P>
   A quick hurricane can be child's play by comparison.
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Lane is an associate editor for The Daytona Beach (Fla.)
News-Journal. He may be reached at marklane(at)n-jcenter.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
