<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROSENFELD-SHORTTAKES16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Short Takes: Death and taxes _ and confidentiality
 &HT;    By Arnold Rosenfeld
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Independent prosecutor Ken Starr's theory that no trust survives
a dead client and his lawyer as long as the inquisitor's heart is
pure would have thrilled Inspector Javert. The extremity of Starr's
argument may be his way of negotiating the Supreme Court into a
milder, but still beneficial, decision that opens the gate to the
unfortunate Vince Foster's terminal agony. Read that as Hillary
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The difference in scenarios is only in degree of mischief. How
does this sound? You're buying an antique foot-warmer from your
aunt. You happen to mention to your lawyer you think your uncle is
a mountebank and poltroon. Your lawyer makes a note, ``uncle fred .
. . mountebank, poltroon.'' You die. Uncle Fred thinks he's got a
case against your estate. He sues, gets the notes.
</P>
<P>
   Or, rumor persists that O.J. Simpson, now dead, told Johnny
Cochran, his lawyer, what really happened. Prosecutor Marcia Clark
subpoenas Cochran's notes. Or, by then the principle is so degraded
Cochran wants to release his notes and write a book. All in the
interest of justice, both claim.
</P>
<P>
   Starr's team put it straight to the Supreme Court. This means
everyone. Confidentiality dies with you. That inspiration turns the
legal profession into a gaggle of potential snitches. The Supreme
Court shouldn't fall for it _ or a blander alternative. Zealotry in
pin-stripes and a smile is still zealotry.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold Rosenfeld is editor-in-chief of the Cox Newspapers.
E-mail: arnold.rosenfeld(at)cox.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-15-98 1216EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
