<DOCNO> NYT19980615.0086 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-15 12:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9401 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YOUNG-GRADUATE16-COX     06-15 1001
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-GRADUATE16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Early learning pushed young graduate to academic heights
 &HT;    By Dan Moffett
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Shortly after turning 9 years old, Julius Su declared his
intentions to the world.
</P>
<P>
   He said he would attend prestigious Cal Tech, a university that
claims 24 Nobel Prize winners. He said he would pursue a career in
science _ chemistry, perhaps. And he assured all around him he was
dead serious.
</P>
<P>
   Since Julius Su was solving college-level calculus problems at 8
years old, everybody naturally believed whatever he said at 9.
</P>
<P>
   Friday he graduated from Cal Tech, as promised and with honors,
having just turned 19, and with a commitment from Harvard to do
graduate work there as soon as he is available.
</P>
<P>
   He says he is intrigued by something called ``femto chemistry,''
an exquisitely technical pursuit that seeks to understand molecules
at their birth. For the sake of the layman, this is like trying to
figure what's up with the egg at the precise, absolute,
meticulously calculated instant it hits the frying pan _ at the
femtosecond, roughly a million-billionth of a heartbeat, or
thereabouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``A pretty amazing field,'' says Su, a pretty amazing teen who
is the first-born in a pretty amazing family.
</P>
<P>
   Julius is the son of Dr. Joe Su, an ocean engineering professor
at Florida Atlantic University, and Dr. Angie Su, a special
programs administrator with the Palm Beach County School Board who
is best known for her innovations in math teaching.
</P>
<P>
   Behind Julius is 18-year-old Jonathan, who is finishing his
sophomore year at Stanford University where he is a pre-med major.
</P>
<P>
   Then comes Judith, 16, who just graduated from Pine Crest High
School in Fort Lauderdale and soon will be off to study engineering
at MIT.
</P>
<P>
   The baby of the Boca Raton family is 7-year-old Jessica, whose
intellectual skills are already apparent: She was counting at 12
months, reading at 17 months and today uses her personal computer
to go on line and solve algebra problems at university Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was reading before I was even aware of it,'' Dr. Angie
said. ``I took her to sign up for pre-school. We walked into the
office, and she saw some bottles of cleaning liquids on the shelf.
She started reading off the names _ Windex . . . Mr. Clean . . .
Lysol . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``The teacher there couldn't believe it and took her into a room
and gave her a book. She started reading that, too. She was not 18
months old. I don't know for sure how long she had been able to
read like that.''
</P>
<P>
   It would be easy to conclude that the Su family's remarkable
academic achievements are the results of two expert educators
working with a fine gene pool. That is correct.
</P>
<P>
   But wait just a femtosecond here.
</P>
<P>
   Angie Su wants parents to understand that they are all capable
of making all their children smarter. Environment, she maintains,
is still a powerful factor in development, and it isn't being
exploited nearly enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe in constant stimulation for the child,'' she said.
``Teach children as early as possible _ the day they come home from
the hospital. There should be no down time. They should not be left
alone by themselves, but the environment should be structured
either to be self-stimulating or stimulated by the care-giver.''
</P>
<P>
   Simply put, this means babies need constant action and
inter-action. They need to have their five senses touched, the more
the better. They need to do and not watch.
</P>
<P>
   The Sus raised their kids by continually bombarding them with
incentives to use their brains: Oversized books were left propped
open in the crib; classical music was played during naps and at
bedtime; reading aloud became epidemic.
</P>
<P>
   And mathematics was introduced on Day One. Dr. Angie invented
the nationally heralded Math Is Not Difficult (MIND) program for
use in the schools, and numbers were invaluable to accelerating the
development of her children in the home.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you develop math abilities, somehow the brain structure
changes, and other learning becomes easier,'' she said. ``Studies
have shown the brain gets wired differently when children become
mathematically literate at an early age. Math opens other doors and
is a big reason why our children have performed so well
academically.''
</P>
<P>
   Su pasted multiplication tables throughout her house. Her
children grew up playing math games instead of board games. When
Julius turned 9, he had progressed enough to edit his mother's
doctoral thesis on math education.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes he was frightening,'' she said. ``We just couldn't
believe a boy could learn that much.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. and Dr. Su came to Florida 13 years ago, having met and
married in their Queens, N.Y., Taiwanese-American community. Though
she has been a much heralded innovator in the public schools, all
of her children have gone to private schools, except for brief
terms in summer gifted programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I disagree with my husband on this,'' she says. ``He believes
private schools do a better job of catering to your needs. He won.
But I believe in the public schools. I have a lot of friends who
went through the public schools and did just as well. I'm a product
of the public schools.''
</P>
<P>
   The Su family set aside research projects long enough to gather
in Pasadena, Calif., this weekend to celebrate Julius' graduation.
Angie and Joe reflected upon the many wonderful surprises their
bright children have given them.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, that tuition bill that came from Cal Tech several
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``It said, `amount owed: zero.' We thought it was a mistake,''
Angie Su said. ``We called Julius. It turned out he had won a full
scholarship. He's so modest he didn't tell us.''
</P>
<P>
   To this math-loving family, it was a zero that was counted as a
great return on lifelong investments.
</P>
<P>
   --ENDIT--
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The PALM BEACH POST, WEST PALM BEACH, FLORIDA
</P>
<P>
   AP-NY-06-14-98 1906E
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
