<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980615.0087 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-15 12:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9402 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSH-CHRISTIANS16-COX     06-15 1332
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-CHRISTIANS16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Christian Coalition gives governor many nods, few hallelujahs
 &HT;    By Ken Herman
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ In a political year when the GOP treats him
as a political deity, about the only Republicans who don't profess
undying belief in Gov. George W. Bush are members of the Christian
Coalition.
</P>
<P>
   They say _ always with a smile, always with respect _ Bush is
not everything they want him to be. For some, he is a hair off on
the issues. For others, he is not loud enough.
</P>
<P>
   They are backing him for re-election, but some are not ready to
sign on for a possible Bush presidential race. With Democrat Garry
Mauro as the only other major choice in November, Bush runs no risk
of losing Christian Coalition support at the ballot box this year.
</P>
<P>
   But that could change in 2000 if he enters the presidential
derby that could feature several candidates _ including Pat
Buchanan, Dan Quayle, John Ashcroft, Gary Bauer and Steve Forbes _
whose paths to the White House run through the farther-to-the-right
wing of the GOP.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that with time he will become more forceful,'' Texas
Christian Coalition member Kathryn Green of Pampa said of Bush .
</P>
<P>
   Sam Gaines of San Antonio, Texas, is another Christian Coalition
supporter who finds himself concerned about the ``degree'' of
Bush's commitment to the ideals the organization pushes.
</P>
<P>
   ``He may be articulating it, but I'm not hearing it,'' Gaines
said. ``I don't think it's an issue of a conscious decision. It is
probably more trying to keep a coalition built or together.''
</P>
<P>
   As Bush moves toward the November election he hopes will be a
Democratic disaster of biblical proportion, the coalition is the
goal. Doing the things that would make folks like Gaines and Green
happy could make other voters unhappy.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Democrats, who will hold their convention later this month
in San Antonio, are ever eager to make the case that the state GOP
is held captive by the religious right. Last month, when Bush took
a hard line against Indian casinos, Democratic gubernatorial
candidate Mauro said Bush _ with an eye on a presidential race _
was pandering to the religious right.
</P>
<P>
   For Bush, the lack of unquestioning loyalty from Christian
Coalition backers is a conundrum for a governor who works religious
faith into all of his major speeches.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'll be getting a governor who believes in the power of
faith to transform lives, and who believes government should
welcome and encourage the help of churches and synagogues and
people of faith to bring hope and help to those who need it,'' he
said in his convention speech.
</P>
<P>
   But if he wants to move toward the White House after November,
Bush might have to court the Christian Coalition more vigorously.
In Iowa, home of the nation's first presidential caucus, the
religious right represents about 45 percent of the caucus vote and
is a major force in the state party. Faith and freedom
</P>
<P>
   Bush lit up the joint wherever he showed up at the convention.
Friday morning, Texas Federation of Republican Women members
happily lined up to pay $10 for a photo with the governor. At a
breakfast afterward, he drew an enthusiastic response, topped only
by the thunderous applause that greeted him Friday when he spoke to
the convention.
</P>
<P>
   But the biggest convention event that Bush did not attend, and
about the only one where his name went unmentioned from the dais,
was the Texas Christian Coalition's ``Faith and Freedom Banquet''
that drew 1,500 people and raised about $120,000.
</P>
<P>
   The event also served as a reminder that the Christian Coalition
and its supporters _ through nothing more nefarious that
willingness being willing to get involved in the process _ have
worked their way into the party leadership. State GOP Chairwoman
Susan Weddington, a vocal Bush backer , was recognized at the
banquet as a past winner of the group's ``Friend of the Family
Award.'' State GOP Vice Chairman David Barton emceed the banquet.
</P>
<P>
   As they waited in the buffet line, Christian Coalition members
and supporters talked about Bush as a politician with potential.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some things I differ with him on,'' said Barbara
Kelly of Dallas. ``He is not as strong on the abortion issue for
one thing. He never verbalizes it enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush believes abortion should be legal only in cases involving
rape, incest or a threat to the health of the mother. While the
Christian Coalition seeks to ban abortions, Bush pushes a pragmatic
message. ``We must reduce the number of abortions in Texas and
America by encouraging adoption, by promoting abstinence and by
making sure Texas parents are involved in the major decision of a
minor child,'' he told the convention.
</P>
<P>
   He also pitched his education plan based on making sure all kids
can read at grade level and barring promotion for students who fail
the state's standardized test, a concept that, in effect, overrules
a school district's ability to decide who gets promoted.
</P>
<P>
   The governor drew criticism at the Christian Coalition banquet
for his stands on education, a keystone of his re-election
campaign. Though a firm believer in local control, Bush is seen by
some Christian Coalition backers as a big-government guy.
</P>
<P>
   When asked what she does not like about Bush's education stand,
Sadie Liska of Dallas replied, ``Goals 2000'' _ a federal program
that gives grants to states that develop more rigorous academic
standards.
</P>
<P>
   ``His dad started it, really pushed it, and we're just not in
agreement with it,'' she said. ``I just think it should be back to
the traditional way of teaching and disciplining. Goals 2000 is a
whole new ball game.''
</P>
<P>
   Goals 2000 is blasted in the Texas GOP platform approved
Saturday as an example of ``federal projects of social
restructuring . . . which involve real interference with parental
and local control.''
</P>
<P>
   Larry Stevens of Fort Worth, a Christian Coalition backer,
criticized Bush for supporting the ``school-to-work'' education
program that critics see as pigeon-holing students too early by
forcing them to make choices on their futures.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a violation of the American dream,'' said Stevens. ``When
you have kids in grade nine having to predetermine what the future
will be after that point and then elect whether to go to college or
not or to train for various skills, that is not beneficial for the
state.''
</P>
<P>
   The state GOP platform criticizes school-to-work as a plan to
train a ``docile workforce.''
</P>
<P>
   The platform also took a shot at Bush, calling on him ``to honor
his 1994 pledge to abolish the regulatory authority of the Texas
Education Agency and to transfer their responsibilities to the
elected State Board of Education.'' Minor disagreements
</P>
<P>
   Texas Christian Coalition Chairman Dick Weinhold, an
enthusiastic backer of Bush, said the qualified support from some
Christian Coalition members is to be expected.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are minor areas where he and I might disagree,''
Weinhold said. ``But they are insignificant.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't even think of one off the top of my head. I'd like him
to be more aggressive (on education issues). More local control.
More parent involvement. Those kinds of things. But he is making
good strides.''
</P>
<P>
   Randy Tate, national executive director for the Christian
Coalition, said he is impressed with Bush's efforts at putting
``faith-based solutions to many of the social problems.''
</P>
<P>
   But he said Bush, like many politicians, needs occasional
prodding. ``Even some of those that are with us on many, many
issues need that reinforcement, and I'm sure the governor on down
to some of the members of Congress need that constant,'' he said.
``That's the only way we are going to really change this country.''
</P>
<P>
   This article includes material from Knight Ridder Newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Herman writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
