<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-15 12:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9404 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CASTLE-FUGITIVE16-COX     06-15 1336
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CASTLE-FUGITIVE16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fugitive finally caught after 21 years on run
 &HT;    By Joe Capozzi
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAKE FOREST PARK, Wash. _ ``Big Bird'' got his nickname because
he was always in the trees.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot-7-inch senior citizen often was spotted with his
pruning tools in the upper reaches of the evergeens and cedars
around his home here, a white-brick fourplex 10 miles north of
Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``You see a guy, 6-foot-7, up a step ladder in a tree, you know
what I mean?'' said Bob Henderson, who slapped the moniker on his
next-door neighbor, a 63-year-old retiree who called himself Mark
Bradfield and sometimes went by the nickname Sam.
</P>
<P>
   The retiree and his wife, Linda, had lived in the fourplex about
five years, Henderson said. She worked part-time as a nanny; he was
an excellent handyman who once rebuilt an old dentist's chair he
used as a recliner.
</P>
<P>
   The couple went for walks, out to dinner, barbecued steaks on
the back patio. But the man known as Mark made an impression on
Henderson not so much because of his size, but his generosity.
</P>
<P>
   ``He would do anything for anyone'' _ from pruning trees to
looking after his landlord's wheelchair-bound son, Henderson said.
Henderson was picked up a year ago and charged with driving while
intoxicated, and ``he bailed me out of jail.''
</P>
<P>
   But recently, Henderson learned something else about Big Bird.
At 5:45 a.m., he noticed five men in blue jeans approaching the
fourplex. Henderson greeted them under the building's arched
entryway.
</P>
<P>
   The men _ part of a multi-agency police task force including the
King County (Wash.) Sheriff's Office, the Seattle Police Department
and the Seattle branch of the FBI _ flashed their badges and asked,
``Where does Mark Bradfield live?''
</P>
<P>
   Henderson nodded down the hall. ``They told me to go back
inside.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he heard loud knocking, followed by muffled voices. He
cracked open his door, and he saw the men rolling Big Bird onto his
stomach in the hallway and handcuffing his thick wrists behind his
back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mark wasn't saying anything,'' Henderson said. And as the
posse escorted its catch past the ``Spring Is For The Birds'' sign
decorating the fourplex's front doors, Henderson shouted after
them: ``You could have rang the doorbell. You didn't need to wake
everybody up!''
</P>
<P>
   Excuse the authorities for not realizing the early hour. After
21 years and a few near-misses, their search was over: They say
they had finally nabbed the elusive Darion Northrup ``Sam'' Castle.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities say the man Henderson has seen reading medical
journals and listening to classical music is Sam Castle, a wealthy
Palm Beach County, Fla. fugitive who was convicted in 1972 for
setting a boat on fire. Both he and his girlfriend were badly
burned in the ensuing blaze. She eventually died.
</P>
<P>
   Castle has been on the run since Feb. 2, 1977, authorities say.
That's the day he was supposed to turn himself in to begin serving
a 10-year sentence for arson and conspiracy.
</P>
<P>
   But the man now being held without bail in a federal detention
center outside Seattle hasn't identified himself since the
early-morning raid. His next court appearance is scheduled for
Thursday when federal prosecutors will hold a hearing to determine
his identity with photographs, fingerprints or testimony from
people who know him. An extradition hearing will be scheduled
sometime later.
</P>
<P>
   Castle did tell arresting officers last week that he didn't know
he was a wanted man, said Marlin Bachler of the King County
Sheriff's Office.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I asked him how he could avoid being arrested on this
warrant for 21 years, he said he has been a very law-abiding
citizen,'' Bachler said in court documents.
</P>
<P>
   It's unclear how long Castle has been living in the Seattle
area. For the past five years here, he kept no regular job, had no
driver license and went by the name Mark Bradfield, the name of the
Palm Beach County prosecutor who handled the original arson case,
said Dick Thurston, spokesman for the FBI's Seattle office.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities believe Castle was able to elude them for so long
because of his family's wealth. He's a descendant of Samuel
Northrup Castle, one of the earliest settlers in Hawaii and
co-founder in 1851 of Castle &AMP; Cooke, a mercantile company that
eventually became part of the Dole produce company. One of the
reasons he's being held on no bail is authorities' fear he could
post a multimillion-dollar cash bond.
</P>
<P>
   Henderson said the man he knew never talked about money or
pineapples. He did mention that he'd traveled all over the world.
But he certainly never mentioned anything about a boat fire in
Florida.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1960s, Castle and his first wife, Frances, lived in a
West Palm Beach marina aboard a 28-foot ketch that Castle built
himself and named the ``Keuwa,'' Hawaiian for ``vagabond.'' When
daughter Lisa Ann was born in 1967, they flew a diaper from the
mast, according to published reports.
</P>
<P>
   In 1970, the couple separated and fell into a nasty divorce. The
boat was registered to Frances Castle but in June 1970, Sam Castle
claimed he'd bought it for $10. A short time later he insured it
for $15,000.
</P>
<P>
   On Labor Day 1970, the Kuewa burned after an explosion in a boat
yard. Castle and another woman, go-go dancer Mary Patricia Kirby,
were thrown into the water and badly injured.
</P>
<P>
   A week later, both were charged with arson and conspiracy.
Prosecutors contended the explosion was the result of a botched
arson attempt. On Sept. 29, Kirby died. Castle was not charged in
her death.
</P>
<P>
   In 1972, a jury convicted him of arson, conspiracy to commit a
felony and distribution of a flammable substance with intent to
burn. He remained free on $10,000 bond during his appeal. When the
U.S. Supreme Court rejected his final appeal five years later,
Castle took off.
</P>
<P>
   Seven years after that, a Sam Coleman _ a giant of a man like
Castle _ was arrested in British Columbia on an immigration
violation. But the man wasn't talking so Canadian authorities asked
for fingerprint identification. When a snowstorm in Washington,
D.C., prevented an FBI agent from getting Castle's prints to
Vancouver in time, the man was released from a British Columbia
jail.
</P>
<P>
   Canadian authorities say Castle and his girflriend at the time,
Linda Sue King from Tallahassee, Fla., drove off in a van headed
for the Canadian mountains. The couple eventually abandoned the
van, then walked into the woods, never to be seen, published
reports say.
</P>
<P>
   Reports and sightings over the years have placed Castle in the
Philippines and in Alaska working as a lumberjack.
</P>
<P>
   Last Monday, the Seattle Area Fugitive Apprehension Team got a
tip _ authorities refuse to elaborate on the source _ that Castle's
wife, Linda, would be flying to Seattle-Tacoma International
Airport from Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
   At the airport, authorities say, she changed clothes and drove a
rental car in circles to lose anyone who might be tailing her.
Eventually she led authorities to Castle's home on 61st Avenue, a
winding, hilly road that ends on a bluff overlooking a seaplane
marina along Lake Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Castle's wife wouldn't comment for this story.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Henderson said, he tried to visit his neighbor in
jail but wasn't able to see him.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy's been a model citizen,'' Henderson said. ``Why don't
they back off?''
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Hamilton, an assistant U.S. attorney in Seattle, said
Castle's case isn't so cut and dried. If Castle hadn't taken off 21
years ago, he added, he probably would have served his time and
been back on the streets by now.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not like The Fugitive, where an innocent man is on the
run. We're not looking for a One-Armed Man,'' Hamilton said,
referring to the popular television series and movie. ``He was
sentenced to 10 years in prison, and he ran. What else can you say?
</P>
<P>
   Joe Capozzi writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
