<HEADER>
A9405 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CELIBACY-DEBATE16-COX     06-15 0998
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CELIBACY-DEBATE16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The two sides of celibacy: Is it liberating, or limiting?
 &HT;    By Steve Gushee
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ The Rev. Louis Guerin has 64 first
cousins. His mother was one of 20 children. The idea of family for
Guerin is a crowd of relatives big enough to fill the Orange Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   But as parents and grandparents at such a gathering might recite
the names of their brood, Guerin would have to be satisfied to be
an observer. He had to promise not to have a family of his own when
he became a Roman Catholic priest almost 20 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The Roman Catholic Church insists that its priests be celibate.
They can never marry and must abstain from all sexual
relationships.
</P>
<P>
   That decision was a struggle for Guerin, 46, who is the pastor
of St. Lucy Church in Highland Park. He wanted a family. He worried
about being lonely as a single man. But he found celibacy to be a
gift that freed him to embrace his congregation, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came to realize that family is far more than just your own
offspring,'' Guerin said. ``Celibacy is a different form of loving.
It's really loving in a dimension that supersedes human touch.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, required celibacy remains a controversial subject.
</P>
<P>
   Whenever a sex scandal breaks in the Roman Catholic Church, some
critics inevitably blame celibacy. The recent resignation of Bishop
Keith Symons has them talking.
</P>
<P>
   Symons left the top job in the Diocese of Palm Beach last week,
confessing to inappropriate sexual activity with young boys more
than 25 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   But celibacy doesn't cause pedophilia. And marriage won't
prevent it. Bishop Robert Lynch, who is the apostolic administrator
of the diocese, called Symons' behavior a disease. Others call it a
disorder. Celibacy is a lifestyle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Celibacy does not lead to pedophilia,'' said Debra Haffner,
president of SIECUS, an international clearinghouse on human
sexuality in New York that promotes sexuality education. ``Nor does
celibacy lead to homosexuality. Nor does it lead to other
aggressive social acts or mental illness.''
</P>
<P>
   Celibacy is a perfectly legitimate choice to abstain from sex
with other people, Haffner said.
</P>
<P>
   But the Roman Catholic Church requires it, and many clergy think
they should have the option of choosing married or celibate life.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Hugh Duffy, pastor of Sacred Heart Church in
Okeechobee, is happy as a celibate priest but thinks it should not
be required of all clergy.
</P>
<P>
   He struggled with the need to give up marriage and children as a
seminarian, he said, but discovered that celibate life was an
honest choice as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a gift,'' Duffy said. ``It takes a special kind of
personality to be single and emotionally and spiritually fulfilled.
That's why it shouldn't be obligatory in the priesthood.''
</P>
<P>
   The church can change its policy. A celibate priesthood is not
biblically based nor seen as a divinely ordered way of life, Duffy
said.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Roman Harmas is a married deacon who assists at Duffy's
church. Harmas comes from the Ukrainian Catholic Church that has
been in union with the church in Rome for 450 years but allows
married clergy, Duffy said.
</P>
<P>
   The choice to be married was available in the early church.
Universal celibacy was required only in the 11th century, and that
was done more to protect the church's property than the priest's
virtue.
</P>
<P>
   The practice grew slowly. In the fourth century, there were
fewer ways to demonstrate the depth of your faith. The church was
legal and had become the religion of the state. No one had to give
their life for Jesus. Christians were no longer sent to the lions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once there were no more martyrs, a great sign of commitment
was a religious life with perpetual chastity,'' said the Rev.
Charles Curran, a Roman Catholic priest and professor of human
values at Southern Methodist University in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Celibacy became a way of bearing witness to your faith. It also
became a way of ducking that nasty reality called sex.
</P>
<P>
   Many scholars of the early church taught that the body and its
functions were less than good and sex was fraught with the danger
of sin.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be really pleasing to God, you gave up sex,'' said Eugene
Bianchi, professor of religion at Emory University in Atlanta.
Bianchi is a former Jesuit priest who left the ministry and got
married. ``There was something about sex that was disorderly and
led you to sin. You used it only to have children.''
</P>
<P>
   Celibacy became a popular choice. Soon bishops began to require
it. Local councils called for it, Curran said.
</P>
<P>
   But it was not until the early 11th century that Pope Benedict
VIII made celibacy the norm throughout the church, he said. And the
pope did that to prevent clergy from passing ownership of the
church's property to their children.
</P>
<P>
   ``Benedict VIII enacted legislation (about celibacy) to protect
the lands of the church,'' Curran said. ``He did it because of the
money aspect.''
</P>
<P>
   And, later, the church used celibacy as a way of highlighting
the differences between Catholic and Protestant, Bianchi said.
</P>
<P>
   The church reinforced its demands for a celibate clergy after
the Reformation in the 16th century when Protestant ministers were
allowed to marry, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, celibacy is a gift for many clergy that offers
opportunity for service and a way to be available to a larger
family without the demands of a biological family.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at celibacy as a discipline, it becomes a
hardship,'' Guerin said. ``If you see it as a liberty, it becomes
extremely liberating. It allows you to be part of every family.''
</P>
<P>
   Many clergy have left the ministry to marry, and others may
clamor for the right to do so and remain a priest, but Guerin is
happy in the celibate life.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the Holy Father allowed priests to marry tomorrow, I don't
think I'd start dating,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
