<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Marilyn Geewax's Business Commentary: Traditional manufacturing
jobs now just a 'blip' in U.S. economy
 &HT;    By Marilyn Geewax
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When Henry Ford announced in 1914 that he would pay $5
for eight hours of factory work, other business owners attacked his
radicalism. They feared that by paying twice the going rate for
unskilled labor, Ford would spoil workers and bankrupt employers.
</P>
<P>
   But the early industrialist realized that to sell his cars in
large numbers, he would have to help create a middle class of
well-paid workers. Unions embraced Ford's idea, using it to argue
for higher wages at all auto plants.
</P>
<P>
   For decades, that argument made good sense. As the ranks of
autoworkers expanded and their paychecks increased, the economy
blossomed. By 1952, roughly 700,000 U.S. factory workers were
building cars and using their healthy wages to buy autos, homes and
appliances. That samep create a middle class of well-paid workers.
Unions embraced Ford's idea, using it to argue for higher wages at
all auto plants.
</P>
<P>
   For decades, that argument made good sense. As the ranks of
autoworkers expanded and their paychecks increased, the economy
blossomed. By 1952, roughly 700,000 U.S. factory workers were
building cars and using their healthy wages to buy autos, homes and
appliances. That same year, General Motors President Charles Wilson
declared: ``What was good for our country was also good for General
Motors, and vice versa.''
</P>
<P>
   Autoworkers still insist that their above-average wages are
vital to a robust economy. But they are wrong.
</P>
<P>
   While hundreds of thousands of Americans continue to work in the
auto industry, their role has diminished dramatically. The rest of
the U.S. economy has grown so mightily that what's good for GM and
its workers no longer matters very much.
</P>
<P>
   This point was driven home last week when the United Auto
Workers' strike at a key GM metal stamping plant in Flint, Mich.,
began spreading and crippling other GM operations. At GM's
Doraville plant, the strike forced the company to cancel planned
overtime and brace for a possible shutdown.
</P>
<P>
   Not long ago, a big auto strike would have generated front-page
headlines nationwide. When the UAW and GM battled in 1970, the
entire economy took a beating. But today, experts are describing
the overall impact of the GM strike as ``a blip'' that will
scarcely slow the economy.
</P>
<P>
   But how could a company as big as GM be so puny in its economic
impact? Don't we still need autoworkers' wages to help keep the
middle class strong?
</P>
<P>
   Answers to those questions could be found last week in downtown
Atlanta, at the Supercomm '98 trade show. The gathering, which
featured all sorts of communications devices, drew about 45,000
people and underscored how fast new jobs are being created outside
the traditional industrial base.
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago, a ``telephone'' trade show would have been a
yawner. Today, a ``telecommunications'' convention is dazzling. The
booths offered jaw-dropping displays of equipment involving the
Internet, satellite communications, computer telephony, fiber
optics and much more.
</P>
<P>
   One of the companies participating in Supercomm was General
Motors.
</P>
<P>
   A car company at a telecom show?
</P>
<P>
   Yes. GM had representatives explaining OnStar, an advanced
communications device that can dial a cellular phone on voice
command, use the satellite-based Global Positioning System to
locate your vehicle, automatically dial 911 when air bags deploy,
unlock the car doors by remote control and just about kiss you good
night.
</P>
<P>
   While GM factory workers were striking in Flint, GM employees at
Supercomm were describing how they could turn your car into a
rolling communications center.
</P>
<P>
   And to keep all these new telecom devices working, thousands and
thousands of good-paying jobs are being created all over the
country.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, many communities are still very dependent upon auto
plant wages to support their local economies. In Flint, the GM
strike is far more than a ``blip.'' But for most of the country,
manufacturing jobs no longer serve as the middle class' mainstay.
So many new types of jobs are being created that the melting away
of traditional factory jobs hardly matters to the economy anymore.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
