<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN: Small fish are bigger in a small pond
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio. A few years ago when I was editing a
small-town newspaper, we ran a letter from a reader wanting to
share her
</P>
<P>
   grandmother's cure for arthritis - raisins soaked in gin. ``Eat
six a day. Use a cheap gin,'' she advised, ``but don't drink it.''
</P>
<P>
   We ran the letter on our Village Views page and in short order
the testimonials began pouring in. ``It works,'' one reader
enthused. ``Joint swelling is down and my ankles have begun to move
again. Only problem is my mother-in-law helped herself to some of
my `medicine' and now I suspect she's drinking the gin. What should
I do?''
</P>
<P>
   We heard from readers as far away as Florida and Arizona (where
many of our subscribers spent the winter), praising the cure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hallelujah!'' wrote one retiree. ``I've tried it and the
swelling in my index finger has gone down, my knees are working
again, and I'm going dancing once a week. I feel like a teenager.''
</P>
<P>
   Another time we ran a letter from a lady explaining to the
readers why her name appeared so often in the Blotter (police calls
section). ``I'm not doing anything wrong, I just need the officer
to stop by ever (sic) so often to get God out of my kitchen. He's
in there waiting to jump out and scare me so that nice policeman,
the skinny one whose momma was a Sanderson before she married,
comes and gets God out of there so I can have my bedtime coffee.''
</P>
<P>
   Folks in small towns like to open up the paper and see a picture
of somebody they know - even if it's a shadowy figure standing
outside a burning barn at 3 a.m. And everyone enjoys reading about
the latest escapades of Squirt, the Lutheran minister's Great Dane,
who wanders through town looking for a car ride back home. Squirt
isn't picky. He'll ride with anybody, anywhere. Folks have to be
quick loading groceries at the corner market or old Squirt will
gallop up and, in one leap followed by a slow turnaround, settle
himself in the passenger's seat of any car with an open door,
grinning and panting in anticipation.
</P>
<P>
   Small town folks have a tough time with big town news. That's
why we live here and not there, because we really don't want to
hear about things like a New York City public school teacher being
attacked by four sixth-grade students because she wouldn't allow
them to watch the Jerry Springer Show on a classroom television.
It's tough for us to imagine four little girls (11 and 12) who've
barely outgrown their Barbies, slapping, kicking, punching, and
spitting on their 44-year-old teacher because she nixed Springer's
``Bisexual Relationships Hurt Married Couples'' show in favor of an
educational presentation.
</P>
<P>
   Occasionally, something grabs us like the story of a Georgia
lawmaker who proposed arming teachers in order to prevent school
</P>
<P>
   shootings. Those of us in the teaching business had a good
giggle picturing ourselves taking morning attendance with a
six-iron strapped
</P>
<P>
   on our hips or drawing down on young Sammy when he came to class
without his homework.
</P>
<P>
   Can't recall anybody in particular being upset because French
wine is coming out in pop-top cans; California vintage is about as
exotic as we get around here. And few of us have heard of Elizabeth
Hurley and even fewer care that she went to a wedding in England
wearing a red Versace dress slit up to her...well...leopard-print
skivvies.
</P>
<P>
   We're not particularly happy that Pakistan and India have THE
bomb. Truth of the matter is, we're not too happy that
(ITAL)anybody(END ITAL) has THE bomb. One of my neighbors offered
his solution to the arms race. ``Let's equipt everyone with
laughing gas and he who laughs longest and loudest wins the war.''
</P>
<P>
   We don't care that Carol Channing only had sex twice in 41
years. In fact, one of my farmer buddies commented: ``Gawd! It took
her long enough to catch on.'' He also commented on the NASCAR
driver who had a sex change and is now driving as a girl. ``Who the
hell cares as long as he doesn't change his name? Can't picture
myself cheering for some driver named Crystal.''
</P>
<P>
   And finally, even though we're more interested in crop yields
than C-Span, we've not recently fallen off of the south end of a
northbound turnip truck. There is no way we're believing the R.J.
Reynolds spokesman who insists, ``In truth, we made sure Joe Camel
did not appeal to kids.''
</P>
<P>
   The real news of the world is on tree-lined, shady streets just
like ours. It's proud grandparents pushing strollers, and kids with
ball
</P>
<P>
   gloves headed for the park. And occasionally, it's a cure for
arthritis, a car-crazy Great Dane, and a friendly policeman who's
willing to take God for a ride.
</P>
<P>
   Small towns like small news.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
