<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Monday, June 15, 1998      The Hearst News Service will file the following stories for
Tuesday. If you have questions, call Tim Spence at 202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
    NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
<TEXT>
<P>
   SCHOOL-SHOOTINGS (Albany, N.Y.) _ Students returning to
Rensselaer Junior-Senior High School next year may have a new
safety drill. Administrators are considering having students
practice how they would respond if a gunman were to show up on
school grounds. By RICK KARLIN.
</P>
<P>
   BAKERY-SUIT (San Francisco) _ Fifteen African American Wonder
Bread workers have joined together to file an unusual racial
discrimination lawsuit against Wonder, the nation's largest bakery.
By LANCE WILLIAMS.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL NEWS (``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   KASHMIR-DISPUTE (Spinagar, India) _ Many in the disputed
territory of Kashmir believe they would be on the front line in the
event of a nuclear exchange between India and Pakistan. A look at
the low-grade guerrilla war between Indian troops and Muslim
separatists and its atmosphere of fear. ``India and Pakistan are
greedy. They want land, not people,'' is a refrain heard in
Kashmir. By MARION LLOYD.
</P>
<P>
   KASHMIR-SIDER (Spinagar, India) _ A look at the politics and
history of the disputed area. By MARION LLOYD.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   GAY-CATALOG (San Antonio) _ What may be the world's largest
lesbian and gay mail-order store isn't in New York City or San
Francisco. It is located in San Antonio on a tree-shaded block. The
company generates more than $1 million in revenue each year and
plans to double the number of catalogs it mails _ to more than 1
million. By JOHN GUTIERREZ-MIER.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   GEISHA-AUDITIONS (San Francisco) _ An open casting call for the
lead role in ``Memoirs of a Geisha,'' a film to be directed by
Steven Spielberg based on the best-selling novel by Arthur Golden,
brought a bevy of candidates responding to the ads calling for
``extraordinarily beautiful'' Asian females, ages 16 to 27. By
JULIE CHAO.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   HOME-POOLS (Albany, N.Y.) _ If you're looking to reduce stress,
or to exercise for physical therapy, health and weight control, or
just have plain ol' recreational fun, a swimming pool might be your
answer. There are approximately 3.5 million in-ground pools and 2.5
million above-ground pools in America. By FRANCES INGRAHAM.
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-COLUMN (Undated) _ A beginning gardener who is trying to
learn some of the basics of keeping a is having problems with
clumps that have tall stalks that grow quickly and look unsightly.
The readers wants to know how to solve this. By KATHY HUBER.
</P>
<P>
   VIAGRA-BROTHELS (Nuevo Laredo, Mexico) _ The pricey blue pill
known as Viagra is popping up in this border city's infamous
red-light district as revitalized older men become brother
customers. By DANE SCHILLER.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL (``t'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-COLUMN (Undated) _ Based on my experiences during a
just-completed hiatus across the right pond, every European seems
addicted to two material possessions: a bicycle and cellular phone.
Random tips and thoughts that may help in planning your trip or
avoiding potential pitfalls. By HARRY SHATTUCK.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   GLF-OPEN-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ The Olympic Club is the most
beautiful golf course in the history of the world. Trees that kiss
the sky, greens like God's gardener did the work, fairways like the
best mattress you ever slept on, sand straight from the lobby ash
trays at the Ritz-Carlton. Makes Augusta National look like a
goat's diner, right? By RAY RATTO.
</P>
<P>
   GLF-OPEN-NICKLAUS (San Francisco) _ The old Golden Bear was just
about ready for hibernation. But then U.S. Golf Association vice
president Trey Holland called Jack Nicklaus and offered him a
special invitation to play in the next three U.S. Opens, including
this week's tournament at the Olympic Club, saying things just
wouldn't be the same without him in the field. By DWIGHT CHAPIN.
</P>
<P>
   GLF-SCIENCE (San Francisco) _ To the legions of duffers looking
to gain inspiration from the pros at this week's U.S. Open in San
Francisco, there's a lesson here: Golf's not just a sport, it's a
science. That's not to say you'll lower your handicap by cracking a
few books. But mastering some of the science might help explain why
your drives fall short and your putts run long. By KEAY DAVIDSON.
</P>
<P>
   OUTDOORS-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ The easiest way I know to
transform a weekend into a life of leisure is to head into the
Santa Cruz Mountains and spend two nights in a tent cabin at Big
Basin Redwoods State Park. Covering a vast swathe of redwoods and
wildlands, Big Basin is one of the best parks anywhere. By TOM
STIENSTRA.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   LYNCH-COLUMN (Albany, N.Y.) _ If parole is tightened up in New
York state, some people will stay in the slammer for almost their
entire terms. And New York will be a safer place. But people who
are first-time offenders, who may merit early release, will stay in
longer, too. So there's no perfect solution here. You simply opt
for the one with the smaller warts. By DAN LYNCH.
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-REFORM (San Jose, Calif.) _ When the House of
Representatives takes up campaign finance reform in the coming
weeks, we will have our best chance in decades to enact real
reform. The way to do it is to limit contributions to the
candidate's home turf. By TOM CAMPBELL.
</P>
<P>
   ROBISON-COLUMN (Austin, Texas) _ Gov. George W. Bush's war
against two Texas Indian tribes over casino gambling on their
reservations is the latest chapter in officialdom's inconsistent _
and uneasy _ relationship with games of chance. By CLAY ROBISON.
</P>
<P>
   ENGLISH-ONLY (San Francisco) _ The people have spoken. They say:
No bilingual education in California, por favor. But the supporters
of Proposition 227 did not go far enough. We need not merely more
English; we need better English. We need Proposition 227, Part II:
The Test. By PHILIP WITTE.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
