<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-15 12:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9418 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NETWATCH16-COX     06-15 0635
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETWATCH16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NetW(at)atch: Pitch to Slate subscribers
 &HT;    comes straight from top
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Beware of e-mail letters from celebrities. Unless they
are personal friends of yours, chances are they want something.
</P>
<P>
   That was the case with the letter sent by Slate Editor Michael
Kinsley to the Internet magazine's 20,000 subscribers. At first
they must have thought it was kind of cool to receive a personal
note from Kinsley -- or just plain old ``Mike'' to the few, proud
Slate subscribers who paid $19.95 a year to read the online
magazine backed by Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   Mike's message to the flock is a chatty little note talking
about some of the improvements he'd like to make to Slate
(http://www.slate.com), such as adding more content to the
informational e-mail packages already being sent to subscribers
upon request. He's also adding new columns, including a more
frequent advice column (edited by Ann Landers' daughter, no less)
and a Wall Street insider column called ``Moneybox.'' Mike is even
planning to let readers listen in on the daily conferences between
the magazine's editors and writers, which ought to be fun. This
frenzy of content development is good news for Slate subscribers,
who will get more as part of their subscription.
</P>
<P>
   But eventually Kinsley gets to the real reason for his e-mail.
He notes with some pride the 20,000 subscribers. But as a slew of
analysts and pundits and even Slate itself readily admits, that's
not enough to keep a high-quality Web magazine afloat.
</P>
<P>
   Desperate times call for desperate measures. Kinsley, once the
famous ``voice from the left'' on CNN's ``Crossfire,'' quotes such
famous conservatives as Fox News' Brit Hume and William F. Buckley
Jr. as saying how much they love Slate. Dark days, indeed.
</P>
<P>
   But then he moves in for the kill. It's not enough you have
subscribed to Slate. Kinsley asks you to persuade all your friends
to subscribe. Once you persuade a few people, send Slate the names
of friends who promised they'd subscribe, along with their e-mail
addresses. If you can persuade your pals to subscribe for at least
eight weeks, you'll get six months added to your own Slate
subscription. And if you don't want to hassle your friends into
subscribing, Kinsley has another idea -- give them a gift
subscription!
</P>
<P>
   Is it an outrage to send this kind of e-mail asking subscribers
to hook their friends? Not at all, says Thom Weidlich, senior
writer for Direct, a direct-marketing trade magazine. He says its
not spam because the direct-marketing pitch was sent to Slate
subscribers who have a relationship with the publication and are
used to receiving e-mail from Slate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have a problem with the letter,'' he says. ``I have a
problem with the approach of the letter.'' He questioned how Slate
would be able to track which new subscribers were referred by which
current subscribers.
</P>
<P>
   So, in the final analysis, Kinsley's letter may be annoying,
misleading, complicated and a bit silly. But it is a bona fide way
to solicit new subscribers. It may not work, but that's one of the
things that makes Slate a charming enterprise despite its corporate
ties to Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   Slate's continual experimentation and willingness to admit and
learn from its mistakes is a breath of fresh air amid a sea of
content developers endlessly pretending they have all the answers.
Slate's willingness to throw almost anything up against the wall to
see if it sticks makes it one of the most interesting Web ventures
on the Web -- and nothing at all like parent company Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The Atlanta Journal-Constitution
</P>
<P>
   AP-NY-06-12-98 2242E
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
