</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FEATURES-BJT16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE TUESDAY FEATURES BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These stories for release Tuesday, June 16, 1998, are moving
today to clients of the New York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   Separate budgets move daily with spot news, sports, business and
commentary.
</P>
<P>
   Stories are moving in the category they're listed under. Stories
moving to duplicate categories are marked. All stories have moved
except those with an ETA.
</P>
<P>
   If you have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the
Cox News Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS (e category)
</P>
<P>
   TVSURFER-COLUMN _ PBS's ``POV'' airs the excellent ``The Band,''
a Decatur filmmaker's poignant documentary about teen life through
the eyes of members of Decatur High School's band _ it looks deeply
at coping with death, eating disorders, drug use, race relations.
Grade: A- (show airs this night on WGTV and on Wednesday on WAPB);
plus it's start of MTV's ``The Real World'' in Seattle. (Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   MOVIE-REVIEWS _ Capsule reviews of recently released movies.
``Almost Heroes'' _ ``Woo.'' (Hamilton, Murray, Ringel, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED 6/12.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE (l category)
</P>
<P>
   CELIBACY-DEBATE _ The Roman Catholic Church insists that its
priests be celibate. They can never marry and must abstain from all
sexual relationships. That decision was a struggle for the Rev.
Louis Guerin , 46, who is the pastor of St. Lucy Church in Highland
Park, Florida. But he found celibacy to be a gift that freed him to
embrace his congregation, he said. (Gushee, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   CASTLE-FUGITIVE _ After 21 years and a few near-misses, their
search was over: The police say they had finally nabbed the elusive
Darion Northrup ``Sam'' Castle. (Capozzi, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   FATHER-KIDNAPPER _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Amy Habie has seen
her twins, Danny and Alexandra, only once since April 13, 1992. A
few cards, an occasional phone conversation, that's it. They were
just 2 when their father, Joey Habie, took them from their Boca
Raton, Fla. home, loaded them onto his private Lear jet in Fort
Lauderdale, Fla. and flew them to his home in Guatemala. And kept
them. (Reid, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-CHRISTIAN _ FORT WORTH, Texas _ In a political year when
the GOP treats him as a political deity, about the only Republicans
who don't profess undying belief in Gov. George W. Bush are members
of the Christian Coalition. They are backing him for re-election,
but some are not ready to sign on for a possible Bush presidential
race. (Herman, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   YOUNG-GRADUATE _ Shortly after turning 9 years old, Julius Su
declared his intentions to the world. He said he would attend
prestigious Cal Tech, a university that claims 24 Nobel Prize
winners. He said he would pursue a career in science _ chemistry,
perhaps. And he assured all around him he was dead serious. Since
Julius Su was solving college-level calculus problems at 8 years
old, everybody naturally believed whatever he said at 9. (Moffett,
Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   HOMELESS-LAWSUIT _ MIAMI, Fla. _ Milton Finney might qualify for
a landmark settlement hammered out of a 1988 class action suit
against the city for harassing homeless people. Unlike many at
Camillus House one day this week, Finney, 58, has actually heard
about it, especially the part where he gets $1,250. He is, in fact,
already banking on it for his move to easy street. (Staletovich,
Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   ARTHUR-MURRAY _ If Arthur Murray were here today, he'd probably
use the Gap khaki commercial as a teaching tool. (Who needs a
footprint diagram when you have wiggling models doing the Lindy hop
to Louis Prima?) As Murray studios celebrate 85 years of
eliminating two left feet, ballroom dancing is becoming hip again -
thanks largely to TV and film. (Grantham, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   NETWATCH _ATLANTA _ Beware of e-mail letters from celebrities.
Unless they are personal friends of yours, chances are they want
something. (Katz, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   CYBERSCENE _ ATLANTA _ There's something a little silly about
turning to your PC for advice about exercise. After all, if you
didn't spend so danged much time sitting at the keyboard, cruising
the Web and sending e-mail, you'd get outside more. But since the
PC and the Internet are facts of life now, you might as well use
some of the resources of the World Wide Web to find ways to get in
shape.(Husted, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED. (l, f)
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE/MEDICINE (a and/or l category)
</P>
<P>
   HUMMINGBIRDS-STUDY _ A robot hummingbird would be a candidate
for what the Defense Advanced Research Projects Agency calls micro
air vehicles: miniature reconnaissance aircraft that soldiers could
carry in their packs to safely find out what's over the next hill
and select targets for artillery or airstrikes. (Stanley, Austin
American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
