<HEADLINE>
GAY CATALOG COMPANY FINDS IT'S RIGHT AT HOME ... IN TEXAS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN GUTIERREZ-MIER  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ What may be the world's largest lesbian and gay
mail-order department store isn't in New York City or San
Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   It is located in San Antonio on a tree-shaded block of East
Euclid Avenue. The company generates more than $1 million in
revenue each year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our forerunner, Shocking Gray, was the world's first and only
lesbian and gay mail-order business when they opened in 1991,''
said Glenn Chase, president of ZEBRA'z. ``Shocking Gray opened a
lot of doors for us, and now we have suppliers contacting us
instead of the other way around.''
</P>
<P>
   Shocking Gray filed for bankruptcy in 1995. Chase and several
other investors have since taken over and operate the business and
showroom.
</P>
<P>
   The store draws visitors from across the country and a few
international customers. The 800-square-foot showroom is filled
with rainbow candles, flags, clothing, books, videos, greeting
cards and jewelry.
</P>
<P>
   The company offers about 5,000 items through its catalog and Web
site. Chase hopes to double the number of catalogs its mails,
currently about 600,000 per year.
</P>
<P>
   Sex toys, Chase said, are not sold by the company, but it does
carry items such as cake-toppers.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of our best sellers is the same-sex marriage
cake-topper,'' Chase said. He explained that the individual bride
and grooms come in a variety of ethnic backgrounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have Anglo, Hispanic, African-American and Asian toppers,''
Chase said.
</P>
<P>
   Although gay marriages are not recognized in the United States,
gay and lesbian couples have commitment ceremonies. In San
Francisco, a gay and lesbian partnership ceremony is sponsored by
city officials.
</P>
<P>
   This month is especially busy for Chase and his employees. Gay
Pride is celebrated throughout June in many major cities.
</P>
<P>
   ZEBRA'z reach is international, Chase said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a growing business,'' he said. ``Last week we shipped to
Norway and Spain. Here in the United States, a large portion of our
business are rural orders.''
</P>
<P>
   John Struggs, owner of Earthly Pride in Hammond, Ind., said
ZEBRA'z is an asset to smaller communities.
</P>
<P>
   ``We order anything related to pride from them, including pins,
jewelry and flags,'' said Struggs, whose store is located 50 miles
east of Chicago. ``Our prices are a little lower than Chicago. And
people don't have to drive all the way into the city to get gifts
and personal items.''
</P>
<P>
   Many ZEBRA'z customers are surprised to discover the company is
based in San Antonio, Chase said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people think of San Francisco or New York City when it
comes to gay and lesbian civil rights,'' Chase said. ``San Antonio
is a good city to do business in, especially mail order business.
The overhead is low and it's a nice place to live.''
</P>
</TEXT>
