<HEADLINE>
IN CHURCH VS. STATE, PAT ROBERTSON IS NO LAUGHING MATTER 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEPHANIE SALTER  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Ha, ha, ha. That wacky Pat Robertson is at it
again. This time, the failed presidential candidate and right-wing
Christian TV preacher is predicting ``earthquakes, tornadoes and
possibly a meteor'' as God's answer to homosexuality.
</P>
<P>
   Railing on a segment of his weekday TV show, ``The 700 Club,''
Robertson opined at length about the annual Gay Days weekend at
Disney World and the rainbow-colored gay flag.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would warn Orlando that you're right in the way of some
serious hurricanes, and I don't think I'd be waving those flags in
God's face if I were you,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ha, ha, ha.
</P>
<P>
   Last time it was the Equal Rights Amendment. When Iowa voters
considered a 1992 ballot measure that would have added it to the
state constitution, Roberts warned that the ERA was part of ``the
radical feminist agenda.'' And that agenda promotes ``a socialist,
anti-family, political movement that encourages women to leave
their husbands, kill their children, practice witchcraft, destroy
capitalism and become lesbians.''
</P>
<P>
   Ha, ha, ha.
</P>
<P>
   Except, the truth is, Pat Robertson is about as funny as a
truckload of nuclear waste being driven by a drunk on a foggy
mountain road.
</P>
<P>
   Some not-so-amusing facts:
</P>
<P>
   The Christian Coalition, which Robertson founded in 1989 after
he lost a presidential bid, claims 1.8 million members, 1,900
chapters and a flow of more than $20 million in donations in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Its annual budget is $27 million.
</P>
<P>
   Still passing itself off as an ``educational and nonpartisan''
nonprofit organization that ``promotes public welfare,'' the
Coalition is one of the most powerful players in the Republican
Party. Yet, it pays no taxes. It is not subject to campaign
spending laws that apply to political action committees.
</P>
<P>
   Last September in Atlanta, Robertson was recorded in a closed
meeting of Coalition members, ruminating on his group's clout.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of Congress, he said: ``Look, we put you in power in
1994, and we want you to deliver.''
</P>
<P>
   Dreaming of the ideal presidential candidate, he said: ``We need
to come together on somebody who reflects our values and has the
stature to be president ... We need to be like a united front. I
know that all these laws say that we've got to be careful, but
there's nothing that says we can't have a few informal discussions
among ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Last June, Rupert Murdoch's News Corp. paid $1.7 billion for
Robertson's Family Entertainment Network. Robertson remained as
co-chairman of the company, his son as president and chief
executive. The network includes the Family Channel, the nation's
9th largest, which reaches 67 million homes.
</P>
<P>
   Robertson's Christian Broadcasting Network, which airs ``The 700
Club'' and reaches a million homes, owned 3.8 million shares of the
family entertainment stock. Robertson said the $136.1 million
realized by CBN's sale of stock would go toward a global TV
evangelism project. A stock-based trust established by Robertson
will net CBN an additional $109.3 million.
</P>
<P>
   Regent University in Virginia, which Robertson also founded, got
$147 million for its 4.2 million shares.
</P>
<P>
   In September 1996, at a San Diego coalition rally where
Robertson stumped heavily for Republican presidential candidate Bob
Dole, the nonpartisan TV preacher was in classic form.
</P>
<P>
   He blasted the ``unremitting assault by the ACLU, the National
Organization for Women and other radical groups'' on family values,
and said that ``this left-wing, radical-extremist coalition has
battered down the laws to preserve family unity.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither he nor the Christian Coalition would rest, he said,
until ``the rotting carcass of the Lyndon Johnson Great Society
programs'' is ``buried once and for all.''
</P>
<P>
   Funny stuff, eh?
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stephanie Salter is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
