<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LYNCH-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN CRIMINAL JUSTICE, A SEARCH FOR THE SMALLER WARTS 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN LYNCH  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ No names here.
</P>
<P>
   These two guys have troubles enough without me identifying them.
That probably would make their lives even tougher. But their
stories have relevance as the New York Legislature grapples with
the question of whether to limit parole in the Empire State. After
the death of a young woman in downtown Albany and the separate
killings of two New York City police officers _ all, authorities
say, at the hands of parolees _ this is a bipartisan effort to keep
violent people off the street longer, as many other states do.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, a first-time violent felon is currently eligible
for parole after serving a third of his sentence. He must be
granted parole after serving two-thirds. One legislative proposal _
and it's probably close to what will become law _ would require
inmates to serve 6/7th of their sentences.
</P>
<P>
   But Paul _ that's what we'll call him _ thinks this is overly
harsh. He's a solid, middle-class guy who lives in the Albany area.
He has a kid who did something immensely stupid.
</P>
<P>
   Some guys were smashing up his son's car. Rather than call the
cops, Paul's son squeezed off a couple of shots, just to scare
them. He wound up charged with attempted murder.
</P>
<P>
   The kid pleaded guilty to reckless endangerment. He got 2 1/3 to
7 years. He just came up for parole and was turned down. He'll do
two more years, at least.
</P>
<P>
   This kid never did anything wrong before, Paul says. While
waiting to go away, he went to college. In the slammer, he has been
taking college courses and keeping his nose clean. If he were
released on parole, he probably would be fine.
</P>
<P>
   Under the proposed legislation, however, he would be in the can
for a long time. Paul sees no sense in that.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's Dave. He's 41 and from the Bronx. He has been in
and out of prison since age 19. He has three robbery convictions.
Only the first one is legit, he told me. The other two were cases
of mistaken identity.
</P>
<P>
   During his last stint in prison, Dave met a woman from the
Albany metro area and married her. When he was paroled, he moved in
with her. It didn't work out, so now he's on his own in a strange
area. His white parole officer picks on him, Dave says. The guy
insists that Dave is involved in some criminal activity, which Dave
denies. But, he says, the parole officer abuses him with racial
insults, imposes silly rules on him and constantly threatens to
send him back to prison.
</P>
<P>
   The guy bursts into his apartment and tosses it regularly. He
also has the local cops hassle Dave. People are afraid to become
his friends, Dave says. He feels isolated and put upon. He has some
emotional problems and is seeing a shrink. If this keeps up, Dave
says, he'll get so upset that he'll lose hope and commit some
horrible crime, just to get even with society.
</P>
<P>
   I mention these stories so you might have some idea of what kind
of people you find in prison in New York. Sometimes they're kids
like Paul's son, who got hot and did something incredibly
boneheaded without considering the consequences. Or they're guys
like Dave, who've spent a lifetime screwing up and who're unable to
recognize any authority higher than their own desires.
</P>
<P>
   If parole is tightened up, people like Dave will stay in the
slammer for almost their entire terms. And New York will be a safer
place. But people like Paul's son will stay in longer, too.
</P>
<P>
   So there's no perfect solution here.
</P>
<P>
   You simply opt for the one with the smaller warts.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Lynch is a columnist for the Albany Times Union, P.O. Box
15000, Albany, NY 12212.)
</P>
</TEXT>
