<DOCNO> NYT19980615.0115 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-15 13:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9470 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAMPAIGN-REFORM-HNS &LR;      06-15 0625
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-REFORM-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW TO OVERHAUL THE CAMPAIGN FINANCE SYSTEM 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TOM CAMPBELL  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JOSE, Calif. _ When the House of Representatives takes up
campaign finance reform in the coming weeks, we will have our best
chance in decades to enact real reform.
</P>
<P>
   Through the bipartisan efforts of many individual members of
Congress, especially my 11 Republican colleagues whom I joined in
signing the discharge petition requiring consideration of several
campaign finance bills, the Republican leadership last month
promised that reforms will be fully and openly debated.
</P>
<P>
   This was a major victory for all supporters, both Democrat and
Republican, of serious campaign reform.
</P>
<P>
   The bill we'll start with will be the bipartisan initiative
commonly referred to as the ``Freshman Bill,'' authored by two
first-term congressmen, Reps. Asa Hutchinson, R-Ark., and Thomas H.
Allen, D-Maine.
</P>
<P>
   Their proposed legislation is a good bill from which to build.
It would ban soft money, the unlimited amounts of money that now
can be given to political parties but spent by them to support
candidates. It's in this area that the greatest abuses have been
reported.
</P>
<P>
   Transfers of soft money between the states also would be
prohibited.
</P>
<P>
   Contribution limits to federal parties and candidates would be
indexed for inflation.
</P>
<P>
   And there would be greater disclosure of contributions from
outside groups.
</P>
<P>
   This bill, however, is only a start to comprehensive reform. I
will be offering an amendment that is similar to a bill I
introduced while I served in the California state senate.
</P>
<P>
   It is simple in concept. It would offer the truest type of
reform: If a person can't vote, that person can't contribute. But
if a potential donor is eligible to vote in the state where a
candidate is running for the U.S. Senate, or in a district where a
candidate is running for the House, that individual could give the
candidate up to $1,000. All other donors would be limited to gifts
of $100 or less.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, all political action committees would be banned
from giving money to federal candidates. No PACs, no companies, no
labor unions. Just people to whom that elected official is
responsible at the ballot box. Only they could give money.
</P>
<P>
   Also included would be a ban on unions spending portions of dues
for political purposes without prior written consent from members,
a federal version of the Proposition 226 that California voters
rejected on June 2. But the same kind of limits would extend to
corporations, restricting political gifts in proportion to the
percent of shareholders who don't object.
</P>
<P>
   This would dramatically change the landscape of our political
campaigns by returning the real power for choosing our
representatives to the people who actually elect them. Imagine a
candidate having to raise most of the campaign money from
constituents.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine not having any special interest groups unduly
influencing our congressional elections.
</P>
<P>
   In this Congress and the last, I've worked many hours on a
bipartisan basis with my colleagues for the consideration and
support of campaign finance reform in a full and open manner. This
resulted from the persistent efforts of individuals willing to go
on the line and take the criticism for it. And also because of the
responsiveness of the House leadership, which has been willing to
listen and accommodate the concerns of the membership.
</P>
<P>
   I hope Congress will seize this historic opportunity to reform a
campaign process whose abuses are daily becoming more and more
apparent.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Tom Campbell is a Republican U.S. representative from
California.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
