<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-15 13:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9474 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OUTDOORS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      06-15 0769
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUTDOORS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GETTING IN TOUCH WITH NATURE AMID GIANT REDWOODS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TOM STIENSTRA  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The easiest way I know to transform your weekend
into a life of leisure, freedom and play is to head into the Santa
Cruz Mountains and spend Friday and Saturday nights in a tent cabin
at Big Basin Redwoods State Park.
</P>
<P>
   Covering a vast swathe of redwoods and wildlands, about 10,000
acres in all, Big Basin is one of the best parks anywhere. I keep
returning for the hikes and natural beauty. It has a network of 80
miles of trails, waterfalls, an ocean view from a little-known
lookout and an easy loop walk amid giant redwoods 1,500 to 2,000
years old. There is also some challenging but fantastic mountain
biking available on some back-country fire roads.
</P>
<P>
   About 20 miles from Santa Cruz, the park is close enough to
reach easily in a morning drive from anywhere in the San Francisco
Bay area but remote enough to feel as if you have left the masses
far away. I've visited dozens of times and will keep coming back
for more.
</P>
<P>
   The tent cabins are well removed from the park's developed
campgrounds. Big Basin has 138 drive-in sites, 38 walk-in sites and
35 tent cabins, but the cabins are located off Huckleberry Camp
Loop Road, about two miles from headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   As you drive up, you will immediately see the appeal. Tent
cabins allow you to go camping without having to deal with any of
the sometimes troublesome stuff like setting up a tent and trying
to sleep comfortably or staying clean, dry and warm.
</P>
<P>
   Made of wood and canvas, these tent cabins measure 12 by 14 feet
and come with two full-size beds, a table and a wood stove. You
should take sleeping bags, a lantern, cooking gear, food, cooler
and firewood although lanterns are available for rent and small
bundles of firewood available for sale.
</P>
<P>
   The cost is $40 a night. Reservations are required. As of July
1, summer rates will go into effect for July and August: $42 per
night Sunday through Thursday, two-night minimum; and $44 per night
Friday and Saturday. Holiday weekends will require a three-night
minimum at $49 per night.
</P>
<P>
   When I made my reservation, I was assigned Tent Cabin No. 30.
What a perfect choice: It just so happened that a surprise rain
shower ripped through the area that night, pounding so hard that it
sounded as if someone were standing on the roof with a machine gun.
If I had hiked to a trail camp, everything would have been soaked.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, I woke up the next morning a bit bleary-eyed but dry,
warm and ready for adventure.
</P>
<P>
   Right out from camp, there is an easy loop trail to Sempervirens
Falls, a chute-like, narrow stream of flowing silver. The hiking
and biking here are stellar.
</P>
<P>
   Big Basin's most famous trail is the Skyline-to-Sea Trail
leading to 70-foot Berry Creek Falls, one of the prettiest natural
settings in Northern California. From the trailhead at park
headquarters, it's a 4.7-mile, one-way hike. You can add another
mile by heading up the canyon to see Silver Falls, a beautiful free
fall, and Golden Falls, which looks like a giant golden water
slide.
</P>
<P>
   Although it is not as famous, a favorite of mine is the Meteor
Trail, a 5.2-mile round trip to a lookout over the Waddell Creek
canyon and beyond to the Pacific Coast. The route starts by running
upstream along pretty Opal Creek on the Skyline-to-Sea Trail for
two miles, then cuts off on the Meteor Trail and climbs 400 feet to
the Middle Ridge Fire Road. From here, you walk about 200 yards to
the lookout, set at an elevation of 1,600 feet.
</P>
<P>
   The park's back country provides access to a network of fire
roads that are perfect for ambitious mountain bikers who are in
great physical condition. The best is China Grade, which ranges for
miles into the back country in a half loop from Highway 236. It has
some potholes from the heavy rains, but it's passable. Be certain
to have plenty of drinking water.
</P>
<P>
   The park suffered vast trail damage from storm washouts, but
most of it has been repaired. There are still a few bridge washouts
along streams, but most visitors are not deterred. They have been
wading across, finding a downed tree to use as a natural bridge or
just hopping across shallow spots.
</P>
<P>
   After all, what trouble is a little stream-hopping when you know
you have a warm, dry tent cabin waiting for you?
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (For tent cabin reservations, phone 1-800-874-8368. To contact
Big Basin Redwoods State Park, phone 408-429-2851. The area code
will change to 831 on July 11.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
