<HEADLINE>
HOW DOES YOUR FOOT `FALL ASLEEP'? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By USHA LEE MCFARLING  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. When your foot ``falls asleep'' because you sat on it too
long, what exactly is happening inside, and what causes that
tingling feeling?
</P>
<P>
   S.B., Boston
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. The most common reason for a foot falling asleep is that
blood flow to the nerves has been cut, says Dr. Ira Black,
professor and chair of the Department of Neuroscience and Cell
Biology at Robert Wood Johnson Medical School in Piscataway, N.J.
This can happen if you cross your legs for too long or hold your
legs in any position that puts pressure on the arteries that bring
blood from the heart, blocking the flow. The same thing can occur
in your hands if blood flow through your arms is impeded.
</P>
<P>
   All parts of the body, including the nerves, require blood to
function, says Black. Sensory nerves normally send information
about pressure, pain, and temperature from the body to the brain by
sending out electrical impulses in response to particular stimuli.
When the blood supply is limited, though, the nerve begins to act
abnormally.
</P>
<P>
   The tingling sensation you feel actually occurs when the nerve
``wakes up.'' As blood begins to flow back into the region, the
nerve goes back to work. But for a short time, it sends out its
electrical impulses in a disorganized manner, not in response to
the proper stimuli. This is why you might feel pressure, tingling,
or even a burning sensation.
</P>
<P>
   Even though nothing is actually happening to your legs, the
brain is getting signals from the nerves. The different sensations,
such as burning or tingling, come from different nerves that
normally carry different types of sensory information, says Black,
a former president of the Society for Neuroscience.
</P>
<P>
   ``People report a lot of very strange types of information,'' he
says. The same phenomenon can occur around the mouth and jaw after
a trip to the dentist when the Novocain wears off.
</P>
<P>
   Tingling feet are normal _ if they occur after a foot has fallen
asleep. But tingling and other strange sensations that regularly
occur in the limbs for no apparent reason may be a sign of nerve
disease and should be checked by a physician, says Black.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. We all know that there are good and bad bacteria that live in
the body. Are there good viruses, too, or are all viruses bad?
</P>
<P>
   J.W.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. From the fungi that cause bread to rise and beer to ferment
to the antibiotic-producing bacteria that fight illness, a host of
natural organisms have turned out to be beneficial to humans. Can
viruses do good as well?
</P>
<P>
   ``One suspects so,'' says virologist Michael B.A. Oldstone, a
professor at The Scripps Research Institute in California and
author of the recent book, ``Viruses, Plagues and History.'' There
may be many viruses that are somehow beneficial to humans out there
_ among the myriad viruses that are still unknown or unstudied.
</P>
<P>
   It's not unlikely that a virus might be beneficial. Most viruses
are parasites _ they require a host cell in order to reproduce and
infect other cells. ``They've evolved to favor their own
persistence,'' says Oldstone. In other words, they don't want to
bite the hand that feeds them, so they aren't always noxious to the
hosts they depend on.
</P>
<P>
   One known case of a virus doing good, at least for Dutch tulip
sellers, comes from the tulip mosaic virus. This virus caused
streaks to appear in tulips, and the colorful result meant the
flowers could be sold at premium prices, says Oldstone.
</P>
<P>
   Many biotechnology firms are also hard at work trying to coax
viruses into creating products that would be medically beneficial,
says Oldstone. The smallpox virus, for instance, promotes the
growth of skin cells, which produces the unsightly pox. While
infection with smallpox can be fatal, scientists are trying to use
non-lethal portions of the virus to encourage skin growth as a
therapy for people with burns.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Other scientists are trying to exploit some of the clever
tricks used by viruses. For example, when a cell is infected by a
virus, that cell then begins to look ``foreign'' to immune cells
that seek out and kill any foreign substance that might harm the
body. Some viruses can mask this signal after they infect a cell so
that the cell they reside in is not attacked. If scientists could
harness this masking technique, or use viruses to perform the same
masking service, they might be better at preventing immune system
rejection of skin grafts or organ transplants.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Readers are invited to send science questions to How&AMP;Why. Write
to How&AMP;Why, Health/Science, Box 2378, The Boston Globe, Boston, MA
02107; or send via Internet to: howwhy(at)globe.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
