<SLUG> BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOUNG COUPLE SHOULD PLAN FOR TAX HIT WHEN THEY CASH IN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. My wife and I are both 34 years old and collectively earn
$380,000 a year. Our children are aged four and six, and a third is
on the way. Our house is appraised at $1.1 million, and there is a
$380,000 mortgage balance which I am determined to prepay within
three years.
</P>
<P>
   We have $465,000 in mutual fund accounts, of which $22,000 is
earmarked for our children's education, $80,000 in a high-yield
bond fund, and the rest in stock-dominated funds. I own a business
worth approximately $400,000 and have no debts.
</P>
<P>
   We make monthly contributions of $600 to the children's college
fund and $10,000 to investments or prepayments on the mortgage.
</P>
<P>
   We hope to retire as soon as possible, although we may not make
that move for many years because we do enjoy working. We just want
the freedom to be able to retire. We anticipate we would need
$8,000 a month to support ourselves in retirement, provided the
mortgage has been retired.
</P>
<P>
   What are we doing right, and wrong? At what age can we retire?
Will the children's accounts be adequate for their college?
</P>
<P>
   I.N., San Diego
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Well, the big thing you are doing right is earning a lot of
money at a relatively young age, and saving a lot of it. The only
wrong things I can see, unless you are omitting details, is that
you have adopted none of the various tax-deferral plans (such as
annuities, 0401(k)s, IRAs, SEP-IRAs, nor made investments designed
to reduce current taxes (such as municipal bonds or municipal bond
funds). Finally, you have perhaps underestimated your children's
likely college costs, and accordingly may be underfunding that
account.
</P>
<P>
   To begin with, if you plan to retire at a very early age -- and
anywhere in your forties is mighty early -- you will need a great
deal more money than do people who retire later in life. This is
because your retirement funds need not only be sufficient to
provide you with an income stream, but there must also be
significant amounts put aside in long-term growth instruments which
will protect you against the inexorable ravages of future
inflation. Thus while you might calculate that a $1.4 million
savings pool could generate the desired $96,000 annual income
stream, you should probably have a minimum of an additional
$600,000 in the growth account, and given the vagaries of markets
and inflation rates, more would be a lot more comfortable. So let's
set a target of $2 million flat from the investment accounts,
calculating that the sale of your business could represent the
'more' if you chose retirement when the cash accounts reached that
level.
</P>
<P>
   Next, if you are resolved to pay off your mortgage within three
years, almost all of your current savings will be required there --
which seems fine to me, since I distrust the current market. So
let's presume that there are no additional to the investments
during the next three years, and that average annual growth during
that period is 8 percent (which is perhaps an ambitious
projection). That would take the accounts from $443,000 (since I
have put the college funds on another sheet) to $558,052. If you
then resumed contributing to the accounts at a $10,000 monthly
rate, and if we presume that for this longer haul you can achieve
average annual total returns of 10 percent, it would require 73
months -- a little more than six additional year -- for the account
to build to $2 million.
</P>
<P>
   Thus by this reasoning you might retire in a total of nine
years.
</P>
<P>
   But of course that presumes there is no problem with the
children's education accounts.
</P>
<P>
   I did a fairly elaborate tally of likely total costs, which
space forbids inclusion in full, but the bottom line comes to a
total of $582,757 for the private college education of your three
children, beginning when each is 17, or of $225,493 if all were to
go to public schools.
</P>
<P>
   (These figures are based on the average costs supplied by the
Student Advantage Guide to Paying for College, published annually
by Random House, which presumes an ongoing 6 percent inflation in
college costs.) At your current savings rate, you will have
accumulated $203,295 in the college account by the time the first
child enters college in 11 years -- more than enough if all choose
public schools, but not enough if they go to private colleges, or
if they go to private schools with above-average costs.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, I suggest two things: if possible, bump that $600
monthly contribution to the college fund to $1,000. Second, unless
you simply omitted details of tax-advantaged investments, I suggest
you have a good tax accountant go over your portfolio and make
whatever changes would serve to reduce both current and future tax
liabilities.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am a 65-year-old woman, single and retired. After health
insurance payments, I have $1,400 monthly income. I also have
approximately $100,000 in savings and $60,000 in stock. Would it be
financially reckless for me to buy a condominium -- and also the
maximum price I might pay?
</P>
<P>
   M.N., Quincy, Mass. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. My first instinct was to simply say 'yes, it would be pretty
risky.' But I'll let you decide for yourself. Let's suppose you
were able to find a modest condo that could be purchased at a total
cost to you of $60,000. By total cost, I'm including not only the
purchase price, but also attorney's fees, other closing costs, and
the cost of moving.
</P>
<P>
   You might suppose that you could simply swap your stock holdings
for the condo -- but remember, if you have held the stock for some
time, you are likely to have capital gains in the positions, and
could thus face a nasty tax bill if you sold.
</P>
<P>
   But let's suppose that the tax liability is nonexistent or
minimal.
</P>
<P>
   Then let's look at your current housing costs versus the total
cost of the condo. We'll begin by looking first at the income
generated by your stock holdings -- the actual dividends -- and
also at the income stream that might be generated by that $60,000
if it were invested to produce an optimum income stream with
reasonable safety. For example, supposing you wouldn't face tax
liabilities if you sold, you might move that $60,000 into a good
government-guaranteed bond fund which could yield you $3,900 a
year. That is the amount of income you might be foregoing if you
bought the condo. But to that cost, you must add the real estate
taxes on the condo, the fee charged by the company managing the
condo association, the cost of insurance on the condo, and a
projected cost of maintaining the property. (In this latter
category, the costs can be discretionary on your part, such as
repainting or replacing cabinets, or it can be non-discretionary,
such as a new roof for the entire condo group which is dictated by
the ownership agreement or the vote of a majority of owners.) Let's
suppose the total figure for these costs comes to $200 a month.
Thus you can calculate that the total cost of the condo would be
$525 a month -- the $200 in ongoing expenses plus the $325 a month
that represents the maximum prudent income from your $60,000.
</P>
<P>
   How does that $525 a month (or whatever figure you have
calculated applying this approach to your own situation) compare to
your current rental cost, or to any alternative rental cost you may
contemplate? If the cost of the condo is significantly higher, you
probably should abandon the idea here.
</P>
<P>
   If you're still tempted, let's consider another set of
questions.
</P>
<P>
   How comfortably are you able to live within your $1,400 monthly
income. If you're usually right at the edge, or even are dipping
into your savings to get by from time to time, the condo is likely
in time to prove an increasing burden, and one from which it may be
difficult and/or expensive to extricate yourself.
</P>
<P>
   But if you are able to live fairly comfortable within your
income -- and perhaps even to make regular albeit modest additions
to your savings -- and if all of the numbers we went through above
work out in your favor, why not?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. In a previous column you mention the Fidelity Insight and
FundsNet Insight newsletters.
</P>
<P>
   How can I get in touch with them?
</P>
<P>
   S.H., Valley Center, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. The address for Fidelity Insight is P.O. Box 9315, Wellesley
Hills, MA 02481-9135, and for FundsNet Insight it is P.O.. Box
91431, Wellesley Hills, MA 02481-9131. You can also reach either
toll-free by calling 800-444-MFIA.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Send letters, including your name, address and telephone
number, to: Kenneth Hooker, The Boston Globe, Boston, Mass.
02107-2378.)
</P>
</TEXT>
