<HEADLINE>
AN FBI OUT OF BALANCE 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW BRELIS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ With its wood veneer, lofty arched ceiling, and
ambience of power, Courtroom 5 in US District Court seems, in many
ways, an unusual venue for the deconstruction of the Boston office
of the Federal Bureau of Investigation.
</P>
<P>
   But the witnesses parading through the courtroom have told
sordid tales of how members of the nation's elite law enforcement
agency for years cozied up to two of Boston's most notorious
underworld figures and may have allowed them to commit crimes
without repercussions, all to keep the information flowing. To
protect those relationships, the agents and their supervisors hid
them from prosecutors and judges alike.
</P>
<P>
   Coming in the wake of a series of FBI controversies around the
country in recent years, from the assault at Ruby Ridge in 1992 to
the disclosures that the vaunted agency crime lab was a den of
incompetence and a potential nursery of flawed testimony, the
Boston developments have helped to undermine the tie-straight
professional FBI image of Efrem Zimbalist Jr.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Apparently, high-ranking Washington officials in the FBI and
Justice Department were frequently out of the loop concerning
crimes the Boston informants committed, indicating a flawed chain
of command. In response to problems of the last few years, Director
Louis J. Freeh says he has imposed reforms designed to better
manage local offices and operations, and to restore trust.
</P>
<P>
   Whether those reforms succeed is significant. For the plain
fact, is, how can the public have faith in its criminal justice
system if the nation's top law enforcement organization keeps
stumbling or, worse, can't be trusted?
</P>
<P>
   The ability of the FBI and its more than 11,000 special agents
to pursue crime across state lines and national boundaries (there
are 36 agents in 34 other countries), coupled with its budget of $3
billion, make it unique in US law enforcement. For decades, the
agency was showered with almost reflexive trust from the American
people.
</P>
<P>
   But the recent tarnish on its reputation is causing many people
to view the agency in a harsher light and is even prompting some
analysts to wonder whether highly professional investigations may
just as likely be found in reformed big city police departments,
where oversight of operations is much clearer and focused _ and
where local accountability is plain.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, big city departments such as in Boston and New York are
enjoying a resurgence of respect in recent years, and have been
showered with praise as their violent crime rates have dropped
dramatically. But the FBI, which has assisted city departments in
bringing down crime, has been mired in its crises, garnering little
favorable publicity for its role in cutting crime.
</P>
<P>
   And unlike local police departments, oversight of the FBI is
much more diffuse. Former Massachusetts Governor William Weld
testified in Courtroom 5 that he suspected that James J. ``Whitey''
Bulger, the reputed South Boston crime lord who allegedly
controlled the Irish mob, was an FBI informant. Even though Weld
was US Attorney from 1981 to 1986 _ and as such, the top federal
law enforcement official in the state and responsible for the
veracity of applications to federal judges for electronic
surveillance _ he never asked the FBI if his suspicions were
accurate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Had I asked, I would have expected them to tell me to pound
sand,'' Weld said. While the names of informants are scrupulously
guarded, and agents may have felt wary revealing their identity to
an attorney who was likely to end up in private practice (as indeed
Weld has), his testimony spoke volumes about the lack of oversight
of the system.
</P>
<P>
   ``Suffolk District Attorney Ralph Martin would never put up with
`go pound sand,' and he would not hesitate to ask the question,''
says defense attorney Harvey Silverglate, who does not often spout
libertarian ideals. ``I think this is something true of federal law
enforcement that is much less true of state and local enforcement,
that the bigger the governmental unit, the less responsive it is.
``If this happened in the Boston Police Department, Martin would
raise holy hell. He is elected and can insist on answers. With the
FBI, the situation is so remote there is no one to demand
answers.''
</P>
<P>
   FBI agents and federal prosecutors also know that US attorneys
will come and go, but the bureau is there forever. ``They know they
can outlast us,'' says one former federal prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
   Oversight and examination are easy following a major controversy
such as at Ruby Ridge, where a 1992 standoff in Montana resulted in
the deaths of a US marshal from Quincy as well as the wife and son
of white separatist Randy Weaver, or at Waco, Texas, where 80
people died during a 1993 federal raid on the Branch Davidian
compound. Such monitoring comes not only from upper management but
also from Congress. Several oversight committees in the Senate and
House review FBI budgets, programs, and occassionally invididual
investigations. Still, in the two years after Waco, the FBI's
budget rose by $130 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be disastrous to have Congress micromanage
professionals at the FBI and federal prosecutors,'' says US
Representative Martin Meehan of Massachusetts, a member of the
House Judiciary Committee and a former prosecutor. ``Congress has
focused on investigatory tactics ... but it is always reactive. The
interest in Congress stems from what we hear about regarding cases,
and it is possible the Bulger case will result in scrutiny of the
FBI's use of informants.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
