<HEADLINE>
POOLS OFFER A BACKYARD PARADISE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By FRANCES INGRAHAM  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ If you're looking to reduce stress, or to
exercise for physical therapy, health and weight control, or just
have plain old recreational fun, a swimming pool might be your
answer.
</P>
<P>
   According to Jack Cergol, marketing director of the National
Spas and Pool Institute in Alexandria, Va., there are approximately
3.5 million in-ground pools and 2.5 million above-ground pools in
America. New York has a particular affinity for backyard pools.
There were 477,000 above-ground pools in the Empire State in 1993,
according to statistics from the institute, a national trade
association.
</P>
<P>
   New York, the nation's third-most-populous state, ranked first
in above-ground pools.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our most recent figures are still being compiled,'' said
Suzanne Stearns, communications manager for the institute. ``But I
would guestimate that there are another 40,000 to 50,000
above-ground pools that have been built since then. As you fly over
the state, all you see are little blue dots, to the rear of
houses.''
</P>
<P>
   That number may be growing, as more and more people are spending
more leisure time at home entertaining family and friends. Swimming
is a family activity, one that can be enjoyed by all ages.
</P>
<P>
   There are two pool options you can choose from: The in-ground
pool, which requires space digging, construction, deep pockets, and
in some cases, zoning approval; or an above-ground pool, which is
less expensive, impermanent and doesn't affect your property taxes.
</P>
<P>
   The latter is a relatively easy way to cool off for summer.
</P>
<P>
   In-ground pools cost between $12,000 and $30,000. Above-ground
pools cost between $2,000 and $4,000, including installation.
</P>
<P>
   Also, used above-ground pools, sometimes taken as a trade in a
pool upgrade, may be reconditioned and spruced up with a new liner
and sold for between $500 and $1,000 depending on the size.
</P>
<P>
   The above-ground pool is often used as a steppingstone to an
in-ground pool, especially once the children have grown and honed
their swimming skills and water etiquette, said Mike Nogavero,
manager of Phoenix Pools of Upstate New York in Burnt Hills.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cost of an in-ground pool can rise if you have abnormal
ground conditions, such as ledge rock or large boulders to dig
out,'' Nogavero said. ``An above-ground pool just needs a level
piece of land that's stable.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I got a 21-foot round above-ground pool for my house as a
reason to build a deck,'' Nogavero said. ``It's great. Gather up
the family or a few friends, settle in the pool and call it a
day.''
</P>
<P>
   Above-ground pools are usually easy for the do-it-yourselfer and
they fit just about anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   As a safety precaution, an above-ground pool should never be
installed next to an overhanging area, such as a garage or house
roof, to prevent the roof from being used as a jumping-off point.
Diving boards and pool slides are also a no-no for above-ground
pools, because of the relatively shallow water level.
</P>
<P>
   Most above-ground pools are only 48 inches high to 52 inches
high, a swimming depth of about 4 feet.
</P>
<P>
   They come in a variety of sizes, starting with the smallest with
a 12-foot diameter to 41 feet long by 21 feet wide and almost 7
feet deep.
</P>
<P>
   Above-ground pools are easily filled with a garden hose. You
would need approximately 5,285 gallons of water to fill a
15-foot-diameter pool that is 4 feet deep, and 13,525 gallons for a
24-foot-diameter pool.
</P>
<P>
   If you have well water, you may want to have a water company
truck the water in for you.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the rust factor, most above-ground pools today are
made from resins and resin-coated steel to prevent corrosion.
</P>
<P>
   ``They may fade in 20 years,'' said Michael Giovanone, president
of Concord Pools in Latham, N.Y. ``But they will still look the
same, even the resin ladders. All of the auxiliary equipment,
including filters, pumps, skimmers and vacuums, are also all
noncorrosive. You'll get 20 to 30 years wear out of these compared
to five or more years with uncoated steel.''
</P>
<P>
   Above-ground pools should also have a main drain at the bottom
of the pool in the center, to maintain proper chemical balance,
circulation, water clarity and warmth. From the drain, the water is
recirculated through the filter, cleaned and sent back to the pool
through the return. Also, a heater can be added to an above-ground
pool. And a solar cover, which can be used to keep heat in at night
and on cloudy days, comes with most above-ground packages.
</P>
<P>
   Vinyl liners, which are now made as tough as the lining material
for the roof of a house, can create an inviting color or patterned
environment. Liners come in earth and sky tones, in florals,
mosaics, geometrics and abstract designs. But when choosing a
liner, look for a beaded one that fits in a track around the rim,
instead of folding over the top of the wall to the pool, where it
can get crimped and buckled rather than staying flush to the
contour of the pool, pool experts say.
</P>
<P>
   You would close an above-ground pool in winter as you would an
in-ground pool, by draining it to just a few inches to the bottom
of the skimmer and place a cover over the pool to keep debris out,
Giovanone said.
</P>
<P>
   Warranties vary from store to store. Many cover materials for as
long as the customer owns the pool and labor for one year. A
manufacturer's warranty differs from a dealer's warranty, where you
can get direct service. In a manufacturer's warranty, you may have
to pack the whole pool up and send it back to the manufacturer if
there should be a problem, Giovanone said.
</P>
<P>
   ``During the summer, our above-ground pool is the center of
activity, where even our dogs join in,'' Nogavero said. ``We bring
them in to swim with us. The only problem is that they can't get
out on their own. We need to help. But they love it and they don't
care what it costs.''
</P>
<P>
   And if you move, you can consider packing up the pool and taking
it with you.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
