<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-15 13:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9505 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBI-IMAGE-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAKE-B     06-15 1012
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBI-IMAGE-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 BOSTON: ... of informants.''  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Oversight is much trickier in day-to-day crime fighting, present
and former federal officials acknowledge. When supervision is left
to upper echelons, those in charge, in large part, need to rely on
lower management to tell them what is going on. The FBI and
Department of Justice both have offices of professional
responsibility to conduct investigations, but that usually means
upper management must be aware of a potential problem.
</P>
<P>
   And if the US Attorney cannot ask a probing question, then it is
left up to the courts to review the actions of the FBI, such as
approving the use of a wiretap, or authorizing a search warrant.
</P>
<P>
   Since becoming director of the FBI in 1993, Freeh, a former
federal prosecutor and federal judge, has instituted numerous
changes in the agency's operations to ensure the integrity of the
court as a checkpoint. Classroom time on ethics at the FBI Academy
was increased from two hours to 18. And Freeh stopped agents from
using subterfuge to interrogate suspect Richard Jewell in
connection with the Olympic bombing. (Jewell eventually was
cleared.) Of particular concern for Freeh is that agents would be
less than truthful on the witness stand or would lie in submitting
applications to judges. He made it clear in a dispatch to all
offices that such conduct would no longer be tolerated _ even if
that meant letting a defendant walk.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today's FBI is more open and accountable than ever in its
history,'' says Barry W. Mawn, special agent in charge of the
Boston office. ``We, like all organizations, are made up of
individuals who at times make mistakes ... When mistakes are made,
to include criminal misconduct, the FBI participates in identifying
and disclosing this activity and subsequently takes appropriate
action to hopefully prevent their recurrence.''
</P>
<P>
   But for all their efforts, the agency, and to some extent Freeh,
still have difficulty avoiding controversy. In 1996, the FBI was
criticized for turning over sensitive background investigation
files of Republicans to the White House, which Freeh called
``egregious violations of privacy.''
</P>
<P>
   Those FBI-conducted background investigations make some
politically ambitious officials, from prosecutors to judges, uneasy
in making waves against the agency, says Silverglate, adding,
``They have files on so many people.''
</P>
<P>
   Just as the FBI is unique, so too is American law enforcement in
its reliance on paid police informants.
</P>
<P>
   ``We play a very rough game of balancing, of letting people off
for crimes in exchange for testimony. It is very American and it is
very effective. We get a great deal for it,'' says Harvard Law
School professor Philip Heymann, the former deputy attorney general
in charge of the Criminal Division. In 1980, he authored guidelines
dealing with informants.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it is like a very powerful form of chemotherapy. It is
playing with dynamite, and clearly, we are not good enough at
regulating it,'' says Heymann, who declined to discuss the current
case. ``It is a terrible problem, and it is not getting any better.
If there is a scandal, it is that by now, it ought to be better.''
</P>
<P>
   That relationship between police and informants is the source of
the stench coming from Courtroom 5.
</P>
<P>
   The extraordinary revelations in the unfolding testimony point
to a litany of problems created by using Bulger and his alleged
cohort in crime and snitching, Steven ``The Rifleman'' Flemmi, as
informants:
</P>
<P>
   _ Retired Special Agent John Morris, a former organized crime
supervisor, acknowledged he took $7,000 and two cases of wine from
the reputed mobsters.
</P>
<P>
   _ FBI supervisors and John Connolly, the now retired agent who
``handled'' Bulger, allegedly protected Bulger and Flemmi from
other investigations, as varied as whether a city public works crew
was doing work on a liquor store with ties to Bulger, to something
more routine: Bulger and Flemmi shaking down drug dealers in South
Boston.
</P>
<P>
   _ Morris also said he told Connolly that an alleged fringe
player, Edward ``Brian'' Halloran, had implicated Bulger and Flemmi
in the 1981 murder of Roger Wheeler, a World Jai Alai executive in
Oklahoma. Halloran was murdered shortly thereafter, and Morris
suspected Bulger and Flemmi were involved. While the FBI
photographed and fingerprinted them and questioned them in 1983 in
connection with Wheeler's slaying, the information was not passed
on to Oklahoma authorities. Bulger and Flemmi continued to work as
FBI informants.
</P>
<P>
   _ Agents and supervisors dining with the informants was
commonplace. Sometimes they'd eat at the home of an agent,
sometimes at the home of a gangster. Gifts were exchanged at
Christmas. And when Connolly told Morris that the two informants
demanded a ``head start'' in return for the information, Morris did
not object. Flemmi contends Bulger fled before he could be
arrested, tipped off by the FBI.
</P>
<P>
   _ In the 1970s, agents planted a phony bomb in the car of a man
they were trying to terrify into becoming an informant. The ploy
did not work.
</P>
<P>
   _ James Ring, another retired organized crime supervisory agent,
said that Angelo ``Sonny'' Mercurio was kept as an informant after
he engaged in the attempted murder of Salemme in 1989, even though
there had been discussions about dropping him before the shooting
occurred.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Morris, Connolly has not been offered immunity and has
not testified. In prior interviews, he denied wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI's apparent disregard for Heymann's earlier guidelines is
now a constant theme in the questioning of agents by defense
attorney Martin Weinberg in Courtroom 5.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hearings have been extremely damaging to the FBI,'' says
Meehan. ``The result, ultimately, will be substantive changes in
how cooperation results in criminal cases. But when controversies
like this are damaging, they serve a very useful purpose.
Corrections need to be made, and will be made, and the FBI will
continue to be one of the most effective law enforcement agencies
in the world.''
</P>
</TEXT>
