u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SKATEBOARD-GIRL-BOS &LR;      06-15 1230
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKATEBOARD-GIRL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIA `GIRL' PROSPERS IN MALE-LED SPORT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and s coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNDA GOROV  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORANGE, Calif. -- It's a girl, silly.
</P>
<P>
   Every time Cara-Beth Burnside repeats the line, she laughs out
loud. As the ``girl'' in question, she knows how unexpected her
performance is, or used to be. Now more and more young women are
showing the same guts on their skate-boards as the guys. And
Burnside is among the best of them.
</P>
<P>
   The line that gets her laughing again and again is in a new TV
commercial for a shoe by Vans Inc., the one with her signature
inside and a copy of her sunburst tattoo on the heel, the one she
helped design and that brings in the royalty checks.
</P>
<P>
   Art imitating life, Burnside is at first mistaken for a guy in
the ad. After all, she's got the attitude and the elevation, not to
mention the baggy clothes. Then a squad of cheerleaders realizes
he's a she and goes wild, until Burnside knocks them over with her
board in another of Vans' good-natured digs at team sports.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a crack-up,'' Burnside said after the shoot, which was
delayed briefly until a helmet could be found, since she's trying
to avoid a sixth concussion. ``I love hearing them yell, `Go, girl,
go.' That's not something girl skaters get to hear a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Burnside, the first and only female skateboarder with a shoe of
her own, is out to change all that. At skating clinics, shopping
malls, anywhere the Southern California-based Vans sends her, she
talks up girls and young women who want to ride like her, want to
be like her. Even in celebrity-jaded LA, a crowd of boys and girls
gathers to watch her stretch out midair until her body was almost
parallel to the ground.
</P>
<P>
   She is, of course, selling shoes _ more than 150,000 pairs since
they hit stores late last year. As an athlete in one of the
perilous board-riding sports _ skateboarding, snowboarding,
wakeboarding, street luge _ Burnside is suddenly big business.
She's upfront about wanting to cash in as a skateboarder and
Olympic medalist in snowboarding while her knees and elbows and
other joints last. But she's also selling acceptance in a sport
where female role models remain almost as rare as when she was a
girl.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's never been suggested that girls skateboard before,'' said
Burnside, who picked up her first board at age 11. ``But if they
promote it as too gnarly, girls won't be into it. I want to show
they can have fun and look good, too. Too many girls worry about
makeup and being popular and stuff like that instead of being
productive at something they could be good at.''
</P>
<P>
   Burnside, approaching 30 but reluctant to be more specific about
her age, knows firsthand how hard it can be for girl skaters. Until
the Vans deal came along, no matter how good she got, as a
teen-ager and then as a college student at the University of
California Davis campus, she couldn't make even a meager living
skateboarding. There were no endorsement deals, no big-stakes
competitions. So she did what any all-round athelete would do: She
switched one so-called extreme sport for another.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, the avid surfer chose another board sport.
This time it was snowboarding and she had women to compete against
all the way to the Olympics. In the inaugural snowboarding
competition, Burnside rode her signature orange board to third
place in the women's half-pipe. The board, like all of her gear,
save the sunglasses supplied by yet another sponsor, was courtesy
of Burton Snowboards in Burlington, Vt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cara-Beth's a very aggressive individual,'' Barry Dugin,
Burton's team promotions manager said of the 5-foot 3-inch
Burnside, who weighs maybe 120 pounds in her snowsuit. ``She packs
an unbelievable amount of energy into a small frame.''
</P>
<P>
   In snowboarding, Burnside has found a world of women she hopes
to replicate in skateboarding. For her it's personal, as well as
professional. While she stars in Vans competitions as well as the
Santa Fe Springs company's print and TV ads, she also chats up girl
skaters at city parks. More than a few of them know her on sight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cara-Beth rules,'' said Melissa Longfellow, co-publisher of
Fresh &AMP; Tasty, a Cambridge-based snowboarding magazine for young
women with a circulation of 75,000. ``She's one of those people
who's been snowboarding for a long time and, as everyone knows,
skateboarding is a million times harder so you have to give her a
lot of credit. ... In our world, she's an icon now.''
</P>
<P>
   Being a name brand, however, can be exhausting. Burnside may
make riding the ramp look like fun, but to her it's business. She
knows her competing years are limited. These days, in fact, she's
so busy with deals and endorsements that she doesn't get to skate
or snowboard nearly as much as she'd like. She hasn't surfed once
this year, sacrilege in the Orange County town where she grew up
and still keeps her equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Stretched out in her parents' Jacuzzi the other day, a portable
phone in one hand, a pen in the other, Burnside did business the
California way: in a red bikini with matching Arnett sunglasses.
She had airline reservations to make for a competition, photo
sessions to arrange, a weekend with her niece and nephews to plan.
Sure she was in the sun. But she made clear she wasn't relaxing.
</P>
<P>
   ``People think you just wake up and skate, but with all these
sponsors and endorsements, it's not like that,'' said Burnside, who
does try to get in three hours a day on her skateboard, sometimes
late in the evening. ``But it's a total business thing. I want to
make a living out of this.''
</P>
<P>
   The schedule includes as many as nine snowboard competitions a
year, plus her work for Vans and her other sponsors. She shows up
at some skateboarding events, shuns others when she feels women
aren't wanted. She describes a recent event in Canada as ``not
really a thing for girls. They're all for guys.'' She pauses, then
adds, ``That's changing.''
</P>
<P>
   The guys don't scare Burnside, though _ never did. She used to
play full contact football for fun and score off the boys. She
studied karate. The back of a trading card with her likeness on it
boasts that she's been known to shame the guys red with her
skateboarding tricks. She's also careful to note that she's always
in control, even when she's flying through the air.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not that dangerous,'' insisted Burnside, who has broken
her arm and a couple fingers and spent the night in the hospital
when she whacked her head. ``I'm not into jumping out of a plane.
Anyone can do that, doesn't take much of a brain. I'm not into the
adrenaline rush. I like tricks, skills. It's not a daredevil thing
for me. It's not like I drive ridiculously fast.''
</P>
<P>
   Burnside is too cool for that. With a toss of her ponytail, she
says she was stoked but not stunned to find herself at the
Olympics. Even so, she is not, she says, ``an Olympic-type
athlete.'' She likes training on her own time at her own pace,
which makes the individualism of extreme sports perfectly suited
for her. The skateboard goes most everywhere with her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't need a coat; I don't need anyone,'' said Burnside. ``I
can go anywhere I want. I'll always skate. But I don't know how
long I can do this competitively. That's why I'm out there making
things happen while I can.''
</P>
</TEXT>
