<HEADER>
A9516 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-NEWSCOPES-BOS &LR;      06-15 1360
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-NEW </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW TELESCOPES PAY OFF IN THE DETAILS 
</HEADLINE>
 SCOPES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID L. CHANDLER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Astronomers in the 1990s are seeing the dawn of an
unprecedented golden age: New telescopes of a size and power
undreamed of just a few years ago are busting out all over,
promising to open the floodgates for a cascade of discoveries.
</P>
<P>
   Just last week, astronomers unveiled the ``first light'' images
of a new telescope that will survey the night skies to produce the
definitive roadmap of the heavens for decades to come. Two weeks
earlier, a new instrument prosaically called the Very Large
Telescope, whose makers say it is now the most powerful in the
world, produced its own dazzling ``first light'' pictures _ the
astronomers' term for the first usable astronomical images from a
new scope.
</P>
<P>
   Much more is on the way: While the venerable 200-inch Hale
telescope on Palomar Mountain reigned supreme for nearly four
decades, four new telescopes that surpass it have been completed
this decade, and at least a half-dozen more will join the ranks
over the next three years.
</P>
<P>
   Several factors have combined to make this remarkable telescopic
rennaissance possible: The dramatic and ever-growing power of
computers to control huge scopes with pinpoint precision using
smaller, simpler mountings, breakthrough concepts for making the
giant slabs of glass for telescope mirrors, and innovative
barn-like replacements for the unwieldy observatory domes of yore.
</P>
<P>
   The Very Large Telescope, built by a consortium of eight nations
known as the European Southern Observatory and installed on a
mountaintop called Cerro Paranal in the Chilean Andes, will
eventually consist of four identical linked telescopes. When
completed in two years, the four telescopes will be arrayed so that
their light can be combined, simulating one telescopic behemoth far
bigger than any telescope in existence or planned. (The Hubble
telescope, by contrast, gains its power to see fine detail by
escaping the atmosphere's turbulence; the scope itself is modest in
size, exceeded by no fewer than 30 telescopes around the world.)
</P>
<P>
   Even now, with just one of its telescopes completed, the Chilean
observatory reports that its first images demonstrate an ability to
detect fine details _ called ``resolving power'' _ that ``even at
this early stage, is unequalled by any large ground-based
telescope.''
</P>
<P>
   The telescope's main mirror is 8.2 meters, or about 27 feet, in
diameter _ making it the largest one-piece telescope mirror now in
service. It is unlike any of the other large telescope mirrors now
in use or being built: It is made of a thin sheet of glass glued
onto a honeycomb supporting structure. This unusual design makes it
flexible enough so that tiny computer-controlled devices can
constantly monitor and adjust its surface shape.
</P>
<P>
   Other large mirrors have either been assembled from an array of
hexagonal pieces fitted together like a tile floor, or cast in one
large solid piece to give them enough strength to hold their shape,
but with hollowed-out spaces in the back to lower their weight. The
VLT's innovative flexible mirrors may set a new standard for the
future.
</P>
<P>
   But size isn't everything. The Sloan Digital Sky survey uses a
new telescope whose mirror is neither exceptionally large (albeit
slightly bigger than Hubble's) nor unusual in design. But this new
telescope, based at Apache Point, N.M., is innovative in other
ways: A unique robotically-controlled system can move 640 optical
fibers so that each one aligns with a specific galaxy in the
scope's unusually wide field of view. That enables it to take
spectrograms _ spreading out the colors of the object's light to
reveal its chemical composition, distance and motion _ of hundreds
of galaxies at once.
</P>
<P>
   By the time it is completed, the telescope's survey will have
determined the distance and velocity of a million galaxies and
100,000 quasars _ far more than all the world's telescopes combined
have produced in the history of astronomy.
</P>
<P>
   The unusually sensitive and comprehensive coverage of this new
survey is expected to provide the photographic ``maps'' of the
heavens that astronomers will use to plan and guide their
observations for the next 50 years. To demonstrate its power,
astronomers last week rolled out a 35-foot-long panoramic image of
one tiny patch of sky, compiled from the telescope's ``first
light'' observations, at a meeting of the American Astronomical
Society.
</P>
<P>
   But these two new telescopes are just a few of the innovative,
powerful new instruments now nearing completion around the world.
Among the others:
</P>
<P>
   _The Large Binocular Telescope. Being built on Arizona's Mount
Graham after years of court battles with environmental groups
worried about the observatory's impact on the mountain's rare red
squirrels, this scope will carry a pair of 8.4 meter mirrors on a
single, large mounting. By combining the light from the two
mirrors, it should achieve a resolving power equal to a telescope
with a single mirror with a diameter of 23 meters, or 75 feet. The
first of its twin mirrors was cast last year in the unique spinning
furnace of the University of Arizona's mirror lab.
</P>
<P>
   _The Subaru telescope. Nearing completion in Hawaii by a
Japanese group, this telescope is equal in size to one of the VLT's
four telescopes, and it will provide a northern complement to that
southern-hemisphere observatory.
</P>
<P>
   _The Multiple Mirror Telescope conversion on Arizona's Mount
Hopkins. After years of successful operation with a telescope that
used an array of six mirrors on a single mount, the scope _
operated by the Cambridge-based Harvard-Smithsonian Center for
Astrophysics _ was shut down this spring for a yearlong conversion
process to a single 6.5 meter (or 21 foot) mirror. Its new mirror
was another product of the University of Arizona's spinning
furnace. The conversion is expected to be completed and the
telescope returned to active research by the middle of next year. A
twin telescope, called Magellan, is being built in Chile.
</P>
<P>
   _The Gemini telescopes. Another pair of twins, one in Hawaii and
one in Chile, will each have 8 meter (26 foot) telescopes. Being
built by a seven-nation collaboration, the first of the twin
scopes, on Hawaii's Mauna Kea, is expected to see first light this
December.
</P>
<P>
   With this dazzling array of powerful new instruments,
astronomers are expecting a wealth of data and discoveries unlike
anything the field has seen before. ``This is not just a new
telescope, this is a science factory'' said James Crocker, an
astronomer at Johns Hopkins University, last week in describing the
new Sloan Digital Sky Survey.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Margon, an astronomer at the University of Washington and
science director for the Sloan survey, added that by the time that
survey finishes its five-year mapping of the heavens, it will have
produced 10 terabytes of data (that's 10,000,000,000,000 bytes),
equal to the total amount of information currently stored in the
Library of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   And some of the first images from the Very Large Telescope have
already achieved a resolution of about one-quarter of an arcsecond
_ far better than astronomers just a few years ago believed could
ever be achieved by an Earth-based telescope. That's a power
equivalent to being able to see the separate headlight beams of a
car 750 miles away.
</P>
<P>
   The total power of the new instruments should make it possible
to gain new insights into the arrangements of stars and galaxies in
space, revealing how the universe has evolved since the Big Bang,
and to discover entirely new kinds of objects in the vast reaches
of the cosmos.
</P>
<P>
   It's the culmination of a revolution that may be unequalled
since Rene Descartes summed up the impact of Galileo's first use of
a telescope to study the heavens just a quarter-century earlier.
</P>
<P>
   ``By taking our sense of sight far beyond the realm of our
forebears' imagination,'' he wrote in 1637, ``these wonderful
instruments, the telescopes, open the way to a deeper and more
perfect understanding of nature.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
