<HEADLINE>
GLOBE CRITICS RATE FILMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
 ! poor, !! fair, !!! good, !!!! excellent  
 
 !!! ``Beyond Silence''  A beautiful and ultimately heartwarming
German film about the tensions in a family whose daughter must
serve as the ears for her deaf parents and become their go-between
with the hearing world. The emotions are honest and mostly loving,
avoiding sentimentality and special pleading, even when the stress
level rises after she decides to leave home and study music.
(PG-13)
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; !! &LR;   &UR; ``The Break'' &LR;  An intriguing premise never fulfills its
promise in this film about an IRA terrorist who escapes prison and
is befriended by Guatemalan refugees in New York. Stephen Rea
(``The Crying Game'') makes an intense impression as the gunman on
the run, but the attempt to combine the political Troubles of
Northern Ireland with violence in Latin America is hampered by weak
characters, clipped dialogue, and a thin plot. (Unrated) (Patti
Hartigan)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; !! 1/2 ``Can't Hardly Wait''  &LR; This breezy summer flick should
connect strongly with seasonally school-free teenagers. An earnest
suitor (Ethan Embry) works up his courage to deliver a love letter
to the prom queen (Jennifer Love Hewitt) who ignored him for four
years. (PG-13) (Michael Saunders)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; !!! 1/2 ``Kurt and Courtney'' &LR;  Nick Broomfield's arresting
documentary about the apparent suicide of Nirvana's Kurt Cobain in
1994 doesn't prove Courtney Love had anything to do with her
husband's death. But it is a hypnotically watchable horror show,
and a luridly fascinating trip along the underbelly of fame.
(Unrated) (ReneeGraham)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; !! 1/2 ``Mr. Jealousy''  &LR; Light-handed, sophisticated, and
disarmingly rueful romantic comedy about a handful of self-centered
New Yorkers trying to sort out their love lives. Eric Stoltz is an
obsessional type doing his inadvertent best to sabotage his romance
with Annabella Sciorra's art historian by assuming a false identity
to become part of her ex-lover's therapy group. Only the
characters' ultimate inability to avoid being off-putting in their
self-indulgence keeps it from taking wing. (R)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; !! 1/2 ``Six Days, Seven Nights''  &LR; Think of it as Harrison Ford
lite. He's a brush pilot who finds himself in a desert-island
romance with Anne Heche's workaholic careerist after they crash,
then fall for each other. Totally predictable, but passably
enjoyable as film's equivalent of a beach-blanket escapist novel _
Ford and Heche find ways to bounce the comedy off one another and
keep us hooked, too. (PG-13)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; (FL)!!!! ``Under the Skin''  &LR; As a young woman in Liverpool flailing
her way through a series of self-lacerating sexual encounters by
way of grieving for her dead mother, Samantha Morton delivers the
year's most extraordinary performance, overwhelming in its
outpouring of raw pain _ and an almost unbearable intimacy with her
sister and sibling rival, played by Claire Rushbrooke of ``Secrets
and Lies.'' Morton convinces us there's nothing histrionic and
everything primal in her convulsive, loose-cannon heedlessness and
choked rage. (Unrated)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Globe movie critic Jay Carr's entire archive of reviews may be
retrieved from Boston.com, the Globe's on-line service on the
Internet's World Wide Web; key words ``movie reviews.'')
</P>
</TEXT>
