<HEADER>
A9518 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-MERMAIDS-BOS &LR;      06-15 0757
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-MERMAIDS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A NOVEL OF STRONG WOMEN WITH FRESH, DISTINCT VOICES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CLEA SIMON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
THE MERMAIDS SINGING 
By Lisa Carey 
Bard, 257 pp., $22 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mingling myth and motherhood, and jumping generations and
continents, former Bostonian Lisa Carey has created a magical first
novel. And in this lovely book, which intertwines three complicated
and realistic life stories, the magic is as often in what we don't
see on the page as it is in what we do. Despite the temptations to
turn treacly as mothers and daughters lose and then find one
another again oceans away, Carey's story of three generations of
strong women manages to avoid the sticky stain of sentimentality,
instead presenting with nuance and balance believable characters
who grow and change.
</P>
<P>
   This is not an easy task, because the Irish-American Carey (a
Boston College graduate and former Brookline Booksmith employee)
not only chooses relationships that have become the stuff of
cliche, but also jumps from such heavily written-about populations
as the Boston Brahmins to the rural Irish and back again,
rediscovering roots galore as she mixes in touches of Irish magic
and legend, particularly the mermaids of the title. Traveling back
to the ``auld sod,'' in this case a barren rocky island called Inis
Muruch, with grandmother Cliona, mother Grace, and the teenage
Grainne, Carey sticks to true emotion, and that elevates her
predictable mother-daughter conflicts. In ``The Mermaids Singing''
we see tears and lost opportunities, but also witness a bereaved
mother's fierce anger upon hearing that her daughter died without
her, and a daughter's denial that her mother is dying _ a denial
both foolish and heartbreaking, because it is rooted in the younger
woman's hope against all reason that wishing will make it so.
</P>
<P>
   The action of this novel is not all unexpected: On their paths
from Ireland to Boston and back again, all of these women go
through heartbreak and sexual thrill-seeking, searching all the
while for the community and love they could find in each other, if
they only recognized it. But though such interactions are simple,
even predictable, they are related here with such clarity and
honesty that their unfolding _ and the book that holds them all _
rise above the mundane, and certainly above the expected
intergenerational mush that makes up so much ``women's fiction.''
</P>
<P>
   Credit goes to the 28-year-old author. Carey crafts her three
protagonists with a keen ear for language. Avoiding the easy outs
of overdone dialect and accent, she nonetheless situates her people
in place and time with very few words: ``It's still my belief that
if I'd gotten Grace home earlier, when she was still the wee child,
she'd be living in Ireland today,'' says Cliona, beginning one of
her sections. Just a few words _ the choice of an article and an
adjective _ place her as as both Irish and of an older generation.
Such distinct voices add to the stories' individuality, gently
coloring the three first-person narratives to fill out the scenes
they only occasionally describe.
</P>
<P>
   Subtle changes in tone also clarify the jumps Carey makes in
time and place, switching from one woman's funeral to that same
woman's youth. In addition, the separate voices allow readers to
move between narratives without confusing characters, despite the
lack of conventional transitions (beyond chapter titles). This
distinction is necessary, because for all the similarity of their
basic experiences, these women live in very different worlds and
cope with different mores, all of which is conveyed in nuance of
language, in the way they talk about sex and sin, their men, and
their families of origin. And from their diverse worldviews _ that
of a young single mother hoping to save her daughter from a similar
fate, and later another mother, wanting to free her daughter to
view men as she only learned to do with difficulty _ come their
conflicts.
</P>
<P>
   Laid out so plainly, their tragedies are obvious, and Carey's
time-jumping serves to juxtapose their individual crises, allowing
us the tease of knowing at that moment what others do not learn
till later. That the young author can tie her tales together at the
end with some kind of resolution should not be a surprise; in that
way, this first novel is true to its genre. But that Carey does so
without losing any of the novel's emotional resonance is a tribute
to her ear and eye for detail and her courage to be honest.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
