<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHITE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAGAZINES CASH IN AS GUYS GO GLOSSY
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   What do men want? Women tend to think the answer is pretty
obvious. Sure, they want that, but they want a lot of other things,
too. Tight triceps. Pizza for breakfast. A cream linen suit.
Glowing skin. A boss who's not insane. The perfect chicken
marinade.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, men want a lot of the same things women do, if some of the
current new-look men's magazines are anything to go by. Still,
after spending an afternoon with several of these publications _
digesting stories about the ups and downs of rock climbing, how to
beat bad breath, choosing the perfect pair of loafers to wear with
that cream linen suit (socks are optional) _ I am left with the
lingering impression that the thing men want most of all is summed
up in the headline of a story in the June issue of Men's Health:
``Live to 90 (and die having sex).'' Not that there's anything
wrong with that.
</P>
<P>
   This story is illustrated with a photograph of ``Banana George''
Blair _ who still does snowboarding and barefoot water-skiing at
age 83 _ surrounded by a half dozen bikini-clad babes. The writer,
George Kita, has rounded up some tips for aging well, among them a
warning that the biggest health threat of all is stupidity. If
true, this means readers of both men's and women's magazines may be
in more danger than they realize.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it's unfair to judge either sex by the content of the
popular magazines they read. (I'd like to think that, anyway,
because on my desk is the June issue of Redbook, which features a
cover story titled ``23 Ways to Make Him Insane With Desire.'')
When Men's Health was launched, many people assumed it would expire
quickly because men simply wouldn't buy a magazine that ran the
kind of stories that women's magazines have been spinning into gold
for years, stories like ``Strip Away Fat! See Results in 9 Days''
and ``The 10 Most Common Summer Clothing Mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   But here it is, almost 10 years later, and Men's Health is
making money hand over fist with stories like the two above, both
in the June issue. The success of Men's Health has spawned half a
dozen new men's magazines and forced older monthlies like Esquire
and GQ to expand their coverage of fashion and grooming, to run
more advice columns and service stories.
</P>
<P>
   Men are only human, after all, and as baby-boom boys are dragged
reluctantly toward middle-aged manhood, they're as hungry as their
female counterparts for information about how to tighten their abs,
rid their faces of wrinkles, and punch up their sex lives, to say
nothing of how to locate the ideal barbecue grill.
</P>
<P>
   The new (and the revamped) men's magazines range over some of
the same territory, but in different ways. Understanding and
communicating with the opposite sex is a never-ending source of
material, just as it is for women's magazines.
</P>
<P>
   The June Men's Health features a story titled ``Sex: What Women
Want.'' The July issue of Men's Fitness has one titled ``Sex:
Insider Secrets to Keep 'em Coming Back.'' Both stories are written
by women. While they appear to be about the same subject, they're
quite different. The Men's Health piece is an exhaustively
anatomical description of the sex act from a woman's point of view.
By contrast, the Men's Fitness piece is a lighthearted guide about
what not to do when courting a woman: ``When she says, `I'm getting
fat,' respond with `Why don't you join my gym?''
</P>
<P>
   If it were human, Maxim would be the kind of guy you're drawn to
against your better judgment because he's so ... different. One of
the newer men's magazines, Maxim promises everything, to wit:
``Sex, Sports, Beer, Gadgets, Clothes, Fitness.'' It's what you
might get if you crossed Playboy with the Fortean Times. A
first-person piece by a guy who was almost eaten by an alligator.
Suggestions from a woman columnist on how to arrange a menage a
trois. Step-by-step instructions on how to deliver a baby. Food.
Fashion. Drinks. Sexy photos of more-or-less fully clothed women.
The June issue asks 31 women to review men's pickup lines. Do men
really have to be told, ``Don't ramble on like a bore''? Or ``It
makes me uncomfortable if a guy comments on my body in any way''?
Sadly, yes. Some men, anyway, have to be told.
</P>
<P>
   Men's Journal and Esquire are the most manly of these men's
magazines, i.e. the least like women's magazines. Still, they have
their moments. Kurt Vonnegut explains summer lust in the June/July
issue of Men's Journal. It's a very short piece. Men's Journal
readers seem to have a limited amount of time to read about sex
since they're so busy surfing, mountain climbing, biking, kayaking,
diving, etc., and worrying about what to wear when doing, or not
doing, all of the above (``There's just something about navy that
seems natural around water ...'').
</P>
<P>
   This issue of Men's Journal is so stuffed with ads and articles
about gear, gadgets, and clothes that you might think you were
reading Vogue, except that in Men's Journal fashion runs to wet
suits and tackle bags.
</P>
<P>
   There's a lot about fashion, but remarkably little about sex, in
Esquire's June issue, unless you count this quote from the wine
column: ``I was reeling from a bad love affair with pinot noir and
fell into the arms of Rhone wines.'' Esquire has been
``re-energized,'' or so I read somewhere, and it shows in the
``brothers'' issue, the one with the remaining sons of Robert F.
Kennedy on the cover. It has some good stories on that close male
bond, including a fascinating piece by Tom Junod, ``One Too Many,''
about a man who murders his twin brother.
</P>
<P>
   It's tempting to compare the June Esquire with the June GQ,
which drools, photographically if not editorially, over 17-year-old
cover girl Martina Hingis. GQ is fatter and glossier than any of
the other men's magazines, a tribute to its winning combination of
fashion, food, drink, travel, and titillating journalism. In this
issue there's a chilling piece on the murder of a mail-order bride,
another on cheerleading (``Rah! Booty-Shaking at Louisville U.'').
</P>
<P>
   What does the GQ man want? I turn to the magazine's advice
column, GQ&AMP;A. ``What's the lowdown on wearing sandals?'' asks B.D.
of Gary, Ind. Where have I seen this question before? Vogue?
Glamour?
</P>
<P>
   I pick up the June issue of Details. ``I never know how long to
wear my necktie,'' a reader agonizes to Glenn O'Brien, the
magazine's ``Style Guy'' advice columnist. Another wants to know:
``I just purchased my first suit. Should I leave those little tags
on the sleeve or are they meant to be taken off?''
</P>
<P>
   Oh dear. Details is supposed to be so young, so cutting edge. It
has a lot of attitude, certainly. But these questions make one
wonder what's on some of its readers' minds. ``I've read that
circumcised men are 33 percent more likely to receive oral sex,''
another reader writes. ``Would it be risky for me to consider going
under the knife?''
</P>
<P>
   Where did he read that, I wonder? In some other men's magazine?
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Diane White is a columnist with The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
