<HEADLINE>
MOSQUITO REPELLENTS BUZZ INTO SUMMER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATRICIA WEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ever think your overhead smash in tennis would kill a mosquito?
It could if you used the ``Racquet Zapper,'' a $13 battery-powered
racquet made by Chicago Model International in Lake Bluff, Ill.,
that promises to electrocute mosquitos on contact with its charged
strings.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps a mosquito-repellent bracelet is your weapon of choice.
New to the market is the $4 ``insect-repelling wristband,'' made by
Repello Products in Mineola, N.Y., with its ``timed vapor release''
feature.
</P>
<P>
   As Americans head into summer, there's a multitude of new
products on store shelves designed to kill or repel those pesky
creatures that suck our blood and make us itch.
</P>
<P>
   But before you throw money at these new devices, you may want to
know that mosquito specialists say the best protection comes from
applying a chemical-based repellent directly to your skin or
clothes.
</P>
<P>
   Brad Mitchell, chief of Massachusetts' pesticide bureau, said
it's safe and most effective to use a cream or spray containing the
active ingredient, N-N-diethyl-meta-toluamide, also known as DEET.
He recommends, however, that consumers use cream on their exposed
skin and spray clothing before wearing DEET to avoid breathing the
substance.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell said federal rules now prohibit manufacturers from
claiming their DEET products are child-safe. He said there's no way
to determine how much will be applied or absorbed by someone's skin
at any given time, so firms can no longer advertise their products
as particularly safe for children.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Mitchell said he isn't enthusiastic about these new brands
that mix sunscreen with mosquito repellent. Though DEET is proven
to be safe and there have been only 20 reported cases worldwide of
a major allergic reaction to the chemical, Mitchell said people,
especially children, shouldn't have these chemicals on their skin
unless there's a need.
</P>
<P>
   To help figure out how best to combat mosquitos, here are some
basic facts to help you know your enemy.
</P>
<P>
   _The role of human smell: It's a mystery, but mosquitos are
attracted to a combination of carbon dioxide, which we breathe out,
and some unknown smells from humans and other mammals. For reasons
that elude scientists, some people are more attractive to mosquitos
than others.
</P>
<P>
   Most repellents mask the human smell, which is what the
DEET-containing lotions and sprays do well. Products like mosquito
coils and citronella candles, often used outdoors, aren't generally
that effective because the repellent odors become too diffuse, said
John Smith of the Norfolk (Mass.) County Mosquito Control Project.
</P>
<P>
   _City mosquitos prey around midnight: While there are dozens of
species of mosquitos, in urban areas, the overwhelming majority of
mosquitos are the Culex pipiens breed that feeds at night,
generally between midnight and 2 a.m. If you live in the suburbs,
you have more species to worry about.
</P>
<P>
   If you have an annoying wake-up call from a mosquito, you must
kill it or it will find you. Mosquitos can bite through sheets and
clothing. It will probably feed just once, so you could let it bite
you (or your bed mate) and go back to sleep.
</P>
<P>
   _Mosquitos tend to fly below 8 feet or so: Most mosquitos that
annoy humans can't fly much higher than six or eight feet. So, if
you live on a higher floor, you are less likely to be exposed to
mosquitos, unless you bring them in from outside.
</P>
<P>
   _Keep the area around your home dry: Female mosquitos lay their
eggs slightly above water level. Any stagnant water in your
backyard, even in a glass jar, can serve as a home to mosquito
eggs. Once there's a rainfall, the water level rises and the water
helps the eggs hatch.
</P>
<P>
   For some interesting but less practical trivia, we learned that
only female mosquitos suck human blood and males are only good for
procreation. Females usually bite humans only once in their adult
lifetime, which lasts about one week. With the blood, they proceed
to lay eggs, anywhere from 60 to 400.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A couple of months ago, we wrote about local residents with
Asian and Hispanic surnames who were irked that they were pitched
directly in a foreign language, even when they spoke English and
didn't speak a word of their ancestor's tongue.
</P>
<P>
   These assumptions are now extending to other groups. A Globe
reporter who is second-generation Polish American, Gregg Krupa,
last month received a mailing from Sprint that promoted low rates
to Poland. The letter started, ``We know how important it is to
keep in touch with the people you care about back home.''
</P>
<P>
   Krupa said he keeps in touch with no relatives in Poland. He
doesn't speak Polish, but he did figure out how to say one thing in
Polish to Sprint officials: ``Dziekuje Nie'' (No, thanks.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (If you have a consumer tip, e-mail mohl(at)globe.com or
wen(at)globe.com, or write Box 2378, Boston, MA 02107-2378.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-15-98 1338EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980615.0140 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-15 13:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9530 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STAGE-PLAYWRIGHTS-BOS     06-15 1280
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAGE-PLAYWRIGHTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVISITING THE TWIN TOWERS OF MODERNISM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ED SIEGEL  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; LONDON _ Although Eugene O'Neill often hailed Henrik Ibsen as
one of his primary influences, they are not often seen as kindred
spirits. A pair of justifiably acclaimed productions here of two of
their less frequently produced classics _ the Almeida Theatre's
brilliant staging of ``The Iceman
</P>
<P>
   Cometh'' and the Royal National Theatre's radical retake on
Ibsen's ``An Enemy of the People'' _ certainly offer their share of
contrasts.
</P>
<P>
   There is O'Neill's depressive isolation vs. Ibsen's more
activist, political sensibility. In these productions there are
even opposite acting styles that nevertheless result in two
superlative performances: by Kevin Spacey in ``The Iceman'' and by
Ian McKellen as ``The Enemy.''
</P>
<P>
   But to see them back to back offers more cogent lessons in their
similarities than in their differences. These two loving,
provocative productions make it obvious that the playwrights are
twin towers of modernism. Ibsen and O'Neill come to different
conclusions at the end of their long day's journeys into night
(``Iceman'' is 4 1/2 hours, ``Enemy'' a mere three), but they fight
a similar battle along the way. Namely, how is it possible to live
a life with meaning and values when an honest examination of the
world leads us to despair that meaning and values are illusion? The
unexamined life may not be worth living, but in contemporary times
the examined life might result in jumping off the fire escape.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Iceman Cometh'' opens in a seedy bar where the denizens,
in various stages of physical and psychological disarray, are
slumbering from the previous evening's collective drunk. All except
Larry Slade, the ``recovered'' alcoholic who now casts a sober,
cynical eye over his barmates' besottedness. The elongated stage
but intimate Almeida setting practically invites us to come upstage
and throw our lot in with the guys. (Some dolls will be along
later.)
</P>
<P>
   We also share their restlessness as we wonder what all the
yammering in this pit of inertia is about. We share their
excitement when, an hour into the play, the eagerly awaited
Hickey/Spacey bursts into the bar. We want to share their cheer at
the jolt of electricity that goes through the building, not from
the People-magazine thrill of having a celebrity onstage, but from
the sense we're about to be delivered from drabness.
</P>
<P>
   That's immediately what Hickey promises us _ deliverance. He has
given up drink because he has found peace without it and he is
going to share his secret with his pals. As Spacey speeds his way
through the lines, he's an existentialist evangelist, promising to
get everyone off his bar stool and back into the world. He's no
temperance convert, he tells us, with religious-right snake oil,
but he's here to tell us to forget about tomorrow being another
day. That's the lie. The cure is to act now.
</P>
<P>
   But that's merely what he seems to be saying. We know from that
famous look in Spacey's eye that shoots charismatic daggers that
he's promising nothing so free of danger as ``get up, stand up.''
What Hickey is really selling, to his friends' horror, is the idea
that everything is illusion, or ``pipe dreams,'' as Hickey calls
it, particularly the myth that things will be better tomorrow. Our
careers aren't going to take off. Love (not that there is such a
thing) isn't going to knock on our door tomorrow. Godot isn't going
to come. (``Iceman'' was staged nine years before ``Godot.'')
</P>
<P>
   After he's shattered their illusions, he asks, ``Don't you know
you're free now to be yourselves, without having to feel remorse or
guilt, or lie to yourselves about reforming tomorrow? Can't you see
there is no tomorrow now? You're rid of it forever! You've killed
it! You don't have to care a damn about anything anymore! You've
finally got the game of life licked, don't you see that?''
</P>
<P>
   They don't see it and neither do we, even though Spacey is
hammering these lines home with an intensity that makes his words
hard to deny. Still, the barmates wonder why Hickey had to ruin the
party. As we join them in rejecting the horrible freedom in the
death of illusion that Hickey, if not O'Neill, is offering, our
denial echoes those of the characters left whimpering about
tomorrow in the bar.
</P>
<P>
   Hickey can't be right. Can he?
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Stockmann in ``An Enemy of the People'' has to confront
different illusions, and in Christopher Hampton's translation at
the Royal National Theatre they take on a distinctly contemporary
edge. While paying tribute to Arthur Miller's earlier translation,
Hampton notes that Stockmann was more, and less, than an
anti-McCarthyite hero. He was a flawed hero with a self-righteous
streak that made his words tougher to swallow. Because of Hampton's
translation and McKellen's impeccably classical acting, Stockmann
emerges as a more human and complex character.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, it's hard not to see in Hampton's translation
something of the British left's frustration with the mushy politics
of Tony Blair and, by extension, Bill Clinton. Stockmann is
fighting not only against the environmental destruction wrought by
compromise with conservative big-business interests, but with
liberal pieties concerning democracy itself.
</P>
<P>
   In trying to shake the public out of its illusions about lower
taxes being the path to a better life, glibly caring politicians,
an independent press, and the politics of compromise in general,
Stockmann becomes, like Hickey, the Cassandra who tells us what we
don't want to hear. Like Hickey, he sees that the problem is
spiritual as well as political.
</P>
<P>
   Although no one will confuse the 1,121-seat Olivier Theatre at
the National with the 300-seat Almeida, director Trevor Nunn and
Hampton plant hecklers in the audience to bring the audience more
directly into the catalytic scene where Stockmann addresses the
townspeople:
</P>
<P>
   ``All our spiritual springs are poisoned and the whole of our
society rests on the plague-infected soil of lies ... The most
dangerous enemy of truth and freedom in our midst is the solid
majority. ... The majority never has right on its side. I said
never! That's one of those social lies, which a free, intelligent
man has to rebel against. Who is it who makes up the majority of
inhabitants of any given country? The clever or the stupid? I think
that we can agree all over the world, the stupid are in a quite
frighteningly overwhelming majority. But surely to God it can't be
right that through all eternity the stupid should have dominion
over the clever!''
</P>
<P>
   Ibsen's townspeople are even more furious with Stockmann than
O'Neill's bar rats are with Hickey, and he'll pay a heavy price for
trying to lift the veil of democratic illusion and political
correctness (Hampton practically uses the term) from their eyes.
</P>
<P>
   It is wrong, though, to equate Hickey's and Stockmann's attempts
to rid their companions' lives of illusions with O'Neill and
Ibsen's attempts to do the same with their audiences, although
that's certainly part of their intention. There is the sense in
both plays that Hickey and Stockmann go too far, that their
individual tragedies are not realizing that life is impossible
without illusion and compromise. It's not clear whether Stockmann
has learned that lesson at the end of the play, when he decides
that he's going to stay and fight, even if it means standing alone.
</P>
<P>
   Standing alone is very much the pose of the modern artist as
well, and these two superb productions show us why O'Neill and
Ibsen were such masters of modernism.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-15-98 1340EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
