A9532 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-TRUMAN-BOS &LR;      06-15 1069
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-TRUMAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REAL TARGET OF SATIRE IN `THE TRUMAN SHOW' IS US 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW GILBERT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Promotion for ``The Truman Show'' has popped up everywhere in
the past few weeks. Like most multimillion-dollar entertainment
packages, the cleverest of the big summer movies has saturated the
media and left Jim Carrey's toothy mug on billboards and television
screens and magazines across America. Hypocritical, isn't it, that
a cracked fairy tale satirizing the media age should so
triumphantly take advantage of its prey, utilizing the subtle
commercial aesthetic it so thoroughly upends?
</P>
<P>
   No, not really. While it is indeed about the ever-growing power
of television, ``The Truman Show'' is an anti-TV statement only on
the surface. The real target of this sunny movie's very dark view
of life is us, the audience, the global population of Peeping Toms
who, like one of the TV watchers in the movie, lie wrinkling unto
death in a tepid bath, clicker firmly in hand. We are the object of
the ire of ``The Truman Show,'' ire that is so cloaked in
theme-park pastels and Rockwellian banality that you could almost
overlook it, just as Truman could almost overlook his wife's
nefariously crossed fingers. It is our passivity as TV viewers, and
not the medium of TV itself, that gives ``The Truman Show'' its
biggest pause, and cause.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, TV viewers _ and not Truman _ are ultimately the
puppets in ``The Truman Show.'' The premise is that Truman is being
filmed 24 hours a day, seven days a week, on 5,000 cameras hidden
throughout his ``Leave It to Beaver'' hometown of Seahaven. He
doesn't know it, but Seahaven is a giant, biosphere-like television
studio, and his life is a show broadcast to a world of eager,
voyeuristic viewers. His best friend, his wife, his mother, they're
all actors given direction by a hidden ``televisionary'' named
Christof, a God-like puppeteer who shouts commands like ``Cue the
sun!'' Truman is so famous that the world fawns over his every
sneeze, not because he can sing or dance but simply because he's so
purely himself, lovable, fatherless Truman.
</P>
<P>
   Christof's show is a huge success, naturally, or else it would
be canceled. It airs in bars, where we see groups of drinkers
responding passionately to the tiny shifts in Truman's fate; it
airs in front of two older women clutching a Truman pillow like
teeny-boppers; it airs in Times Square. It is pacifying and
comforting, the real-time soap opera of a happy man in an idyllic,
candy-coated setting, with isolated dramatic moments like the
``death'' by drowning of his father, then the return of his father
after years of amnesia. It's the sort of reality exercise that Andy
Warhol used with more avant-garde motives in the 1960s, creating
underground films on the exceedingly mundane including ``Eat,''
``Haircut,'' and ``Sleep,'' which featured eight hours of a man
unconscious.
</P>
<P>
   Repeatedly, director Peter Weir and screenwriter Andrew Niccol
bring their story back to the people mesmerized by the show within
``The Truman Show.'' (At moments, these viewers resemble the
gatherings in the tavern in Elton, England, when Louise Woodward
was on trial, emotionally bound round the clock to someone else's
story.) While poor Truman gradually discovers that his entire life
is fraudulent, that even the most incidental people around him are
two-faced, that all of his paranoid fears are justified, the TV
audiences sit watching the story as if it's no different from ``The
Young and the Restless.'' They're so laid-back you can't quite
accuse them of maliciousness, the kind of misguided media
engagement that Fred Schepisi abhorred in ``A Cry in the Dark,''
the story of the Lindy Chamberlain trial in Australia that became a
witch hunt. And yet their moral distance from the life that's at
stake is insidious.
</P>
<P>
   After the story of Truman ends in near catastrophe, a policeman
watching lazily says to his buddy with a haunting casualness, ``See
what else is on.''
</P>
<P>
   The hero of the movie is Truman Burbank himself, the man who
refuses to have television forced upon him. In all his schoolboy
dorkiness and dawning paranoia, Jim Carrey's Truman is a rebel for
the millennium, making his wily exit out of his massive media
victimization by pretending to be asleep. He refuses to be a
puppet, delivering the most explicit line in a script that's
ingeniously nonconfrontational, snarling at Christof, ``You never
had a camera in my head.'' At the end of the movie, when even the
monster Christof has been foiled by the natural humanity of the man
he kept in a zoo for 30 years, Truman becomes Ulysses, setting sail
from Calypso's island, turning his back on immortality, bravely
heading into he-knows-not-what.
</P>
<P>
   And who just says no to fame these days? Our cultural
temperament is marked by a dependence on the electronic validation
offered by camcorders and Web sites and tabloid talk shows. Privacy
is passe, as people like Monica Lewinsky and the purchases of their
books are pulled into the spotlight, high-tech surveillance
mechanisms more efficiently follow our movements, and entertainers
make love to the cameras. Markers of cultural exhibitionism reach
back to PBS's ``An American Family'' in the 1970s, and they extend
to MTV's ``The Real World,'' ``America's Funniest Home Videos,''
and just about anything having to do with Madonna. (Remember Warren
Beatty's caustic remarks about his then girlfriend in ``Truth or
Dare'': ``She doesn't want to be seen off-camera, much less
talk.'') The Internet makes visibility eerily accessible, enabling
people like Jennifer Ringley to transmit every moment of her daily
life over the information highway, via her JenniCAM site.
</P>
<P>
   Since it opened, ``The Truman Show'' has been compared with
``Forrest Gump,'' as both are about history and culture acting upon
innocent men. But while ``Gump'' celebrates its hero's fickleness,
making it into his source of strength, ``Truman'' tracks its hero's
journey from unknowingness into wisdom and pain. Until he discovers
that he's a media dupe, and that his existence is ridden with
product placement, Truman is not free. He is a prisoner not just of
Christof's controlling nature, but of our passivity, as we dully
aim our remote controls at him. In ``The Truman Show,'' the hero's
revolution will not be televised.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
