u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-UBU-BOS &LR;      06-15 0881
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-UBU-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PERE UBU: THINKING PERSON'S NONTHINKING BAND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM SULLIVAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   David Thomas, leader of the veteran self-described
``avant-garage'' band Pere Ubu, is tossed a softball. The group's
11th and latest album, ``Pennsylvania,'' is a stunner, blending a
dead-on pop sensibility and careening musical twists and turns,
irony and passion. It could be the apotheosis of modern art-rock.
Might Peru Ubu find that ever-elusive stratum, success?
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' says Thomas, from his home in Hove, outside Brighton,
England.
</P>
<P>
   Which is the answer he has given to this sort of question for
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yep,'' says Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   So, how does Pere Ubu _ a Cleveland-based band that anticipated
the creative burst of mid-1970s punk and new wave _ fit into
today's alt-rock world?
</P>
<P>
   ``We fit in like we always do,'' the 44-year-old singer says.
``If you mean commercially, we don't fit in: We are unsuccessful.
If you mean artistically, I suppose you'd have to say the same:
We're probably unsuccessful. I would say that only a fool would buy
our records. ... We're no good. I don't know why you bothered to
interview me. I wouldn't waste the time or the print. Nobody's
going to thank you for writing about us. If you say anything good,
nobody will believe you or they'll just ignore you. You're wasting
your time; I'm wasting my time, but, well, that's your decision.
That's OK. I'll try to help you waste your time more efficiently.''
</P>
<P>
   If he's being darkly ironic or absurdist, he doesn't let on.
Thomas is known for being quirky, cantankerous, sardonic, ornery.
Maybe he's just telling the plain truth as he sees it. Maybe every
other pop artist is a self-aggrandizing fraud.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, Thomas stays on the telephone and discusses
``Pennsylvania,'' an oddly accessible, albeit offbeat
semi-conceptual album about journeys down many a weird road. It
sounds chaotic at times _ especially at the beginning and the end _
but it's not done scattershot style.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything we do is plotted out,'' explains Thomas. ``I don't
know exactly the places, and how or why it was plotted out.
`Pennsylvania' really is about the space between where you are and
where you're going to. And that space in between has a lot of
really lousy roads on it and a very low speed limit.'' Modern pop
culture takes a hit, too, in ``Woolie Bullie'': ``Culture is a
weapon that's used against us/Nah, culture is a swamp of
superstition, ignorance and abuse.''
</P>
<P>
   In concert, Thomas can seem like a demented evengelical preacher
or, as critic Greil Marcus recently wrote, admiringly, ``a man
muttering in a crowd.''
</P>
<P>
   His bandmates _ guitarists Tom Hermon and Jim Jones, synthist
Robert Wheeler, bassist Michele Temple, and drummer Steve Mehlman _
all live around Cleveland. Thomas fled to London in the mid-'80s.
``I don't know why,'' he says. ``This is just where I am at the
moment, for no particular reason.'' (He adds that England is Pere
Ubu's worst market.)
</P>
<P>
   Thomas, who can seem like the answer man onstage, professes
perplexity off. ``I don't understand the idea of being
accessible,'' he says, noting that writers he's talked to have
called Pere Ubu's recent work both melodic and unmelodic. ``I have
no idea what you guys are listening to. Could you try and talk
among yourselves and figure it out?'' (Thomas's resume includes a
stint as a rock critic.)
</P>
<P>
   As to accessibility, Thomas maintains, ``Nobody asks anybody
else to be accessible. If you read a book that was `accessible,'
you probably wouldn't finish it because it wouldn't be anything
(you'd want) to finish.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas has long pursued a variety of outside-Ubu projects. He's
worked with English master-of-all-trades Richard Thompson and
former Boston art-rocker Daved Hild; he's still involved with the
English duo Two Pale Boys (``Just as pale as ever,'' he says) and
will bring them over later this year to participate in a New York
performance of ``Disastrodome,'' a lectural/musical/theatrical
extravaganza Thomas recently staged in London. During this show, he
discusses the ``geography of sound.''
</P>
<P>
   It is here that Thomas gets on a roll. ``There's an internal
landscape that informs the geography that we live in,'' he says,
``and the geography that surrounds us and forms that internal
landscape, which consists of a series of sensations that are most
easily translated as sound. I call them `hieroglyphics.' They're
not verbal, they're not ideas; they are the component of human
consciousness. When you think, for instance, of your home, there's
not a series of pictures, there's not a series of ideas, there's
not a map that comes to mind. There's a sensation that you feel, a
complex sensation that you need to communicate, but you don't use
words.''
</P>
<P>
   And, the kicker: ``I don't think that I have come to the
conclusion that there is such a thing as thinking. I, for instance,
have never had a thought in my life, and nothing is very cognitive
about anything. So, where does consciousness come from? It must
come from these hieroglyphics, these complex sensations,
remembrances of intellectual ideas and visionary moments. From
these things, we pull the words when we need them. Otherwise, there
are no words.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
