<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEARST-NEWS-BUDGET-HNS </SLUG>
  
 Monday, June 15, 1998     
 Editors      The Hearst News Service will file the following
stories for Tuesday. If you have questions, please call Susie McBee
or Tim Spence at 202-298-6920.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;  (The ``HNS'' tag appears in all sluglines.)  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   DISABLED-PRISONERS (Washington) _ The Supreme Court rules that
state prison inmates are protected under the American Disabilities
Act, which bans discrimination against the disabled. In a Texas
case, the court also deals a heavy blow to a multistate program
that provides some $100 million a year for legal help for the poor.
By MARK HELM.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ Charlton Heston's strange idea of
how to soften the National Rifle Association's rabid pro-gun image
is to oppose extending the law that requires a waiting period for
gun purchases. He also wants to gut the instant background checks
that are supposed to supplant the law. He's got Senate Majority
Leader Trent Lott in his corner, but not folks who want to end
firearm violence. By MARIANNE MEANS.
</P>
<P>
   TOO-MUCH-NEWS (Paris) _ The World Cup soccer championship in
France is monopolizing news space in the papers and on TV. Other
events of second- and third-rate importance have gone unreported.
Apparently, they are unmissed. Could it be that ordinarily much of
the news that is solemnly reported could safely be ignored? By
BERNARD D. KAPLAN.
</P>
</TEXT>
