<HEADER>
A9556 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRAVECOMBO-MUSIC-1500     06-15 0806
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAVECOMBO-MUSIC-1500(2TAKES)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MESSAGE AFTER 19 YEARS IS SAME: WORLD MUSIC IS GOOD FOR YOU
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE FERMAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENTON, Texas _ Those wishing to summarize Brave Combo in its
19th year could have asked for no better time than a week this past
April.
</P>
<P>
   One day the country's favorite ``nuclear polka'' band, six guys
with a song book of more than 600 tunes, were in Los Angeles
playing a celebrity-packed party celebrating the 200th episode of
``The Simpsons'' at the behest of series creator Matt Groening.
</P>
<P>
   That weekend they were back home in North Texas_ or, rather,
playing at Coppell's Pig Fest '98, a celebration of all things
pork-related, which also included a pot-bellied pig parade and
fashion show and an ... ahem, ``pig-nic.''
</P>
<P>
   What other band would do both? What other band would be ASKED to
do both? Therein lies Brave Combo's considerable charm.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to the mix of their world-music-in-a-blender sound and
just-regular-guys group personality, they're welcome everywhere
from major music festivals to New York's Lincoln Center (where
they're hosting a cha-cha night in July), to a bar near you.
</P>
<P>
   Comboworld is the home of founder (and only remaining original
member) Carl Finch, multi-instrumentalist Jeffrey Barnes,
percussionist Joe Cripps, drummer Alan Emert, bassist Cenobio
Xavier ``Bubba'' Hernandez and trumpeter Danny O'Brien. It is the
only place where ``The Hokey Pokey'' will ever be done as a rock
tune and the Rolling Stones' ``Satisfaction'' as a cha-cha, where
the late Tiny Tim was a musical collaborator and where Sandra
Bullock was recently seen dancing down front at an Austin show,
where gigs at major European rock festivals are on the same
itinerary as the Concerts in the Garden series at the Fort Worth
Botanic Garden.
</P>
<P>
   ``We definitely have our own orbit,'' Cripps said one afternoon.
``We don't have any pressure to do anything _ the only thing people
expect of us is the unexpected. We're successful in what we view
success as _ we get to make a living doing this.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah,'' said Barnes, looking up from a National Geographic
world atlas. ``I play music I don't hate and sometimes love _ and I
get paid for it, too.''
</P>
<P>
   By now, after more than a dozen releases, a Grammy nomination
(in 1996, for the ``Polkas for a Gloomy World'' CD) and more than
400 weddings, BC has the world pretty much on its side. The band
can play anything it wants, from traditional polkas to tangos to
rock to Greek folk songs. The group has as many gigs as band
members could ask for, between 150 and 175 per year, and they tour
Europe and Japan.
</P>
<P>
   They have no desire to leave Denton, they say, mainly because
it's home, it's inexpensive, and it's centrally located. Moreover,
they still get such high-profile jobs as providing music for David
Byrne's 1986 film ``True Stories'' and the 1994 Olympic performance
of ice dancers Elizabeth Punsalan and Jerod Swallow.
</P>
<P>
   Finch, 46, the guy who founded BC, is professionally friendly,
interrupting an interview only to talk with a Swedish booking agent
about their upcoming European tour, which includes the band's first
gig above the Arctic Circle. But this fellow who has been known to
lead a conga line of fans through a club can also settle into
serious discussions about the history of the polka and various
strains of ethnic music.
</P>
<P>
   After all, lurking under the mix 'n' match musical shenanigans
and the goofily retooled cover versions, there's always been a
point to BC's existence. And that point, says Finch, is to stop
people's preconceived notions about what is ``good music.''
</P>
<P>
   Back in the mid-'70s, Finch found himself thinking long and hard
about ``value judgments and music _ how people say, `I hate opera'
or whatever. I couldn't figure out how people made that leap _ it
parallels other prejudices.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Finch was discovering polka _ from traditional
European polkas to the regional styles of South Texas and the
Midwest. In polka, he realized, he had found the perfect way to
challenge people's notions about what is or is not good music, what
they'd spend an evening listening to or run screaming away from.
</P>
<P>
   At first, the danceably kitsch value of their music wasn't
appreciated. Their first receptive audiences, in fact, were found
during their first Texas tour _ of mental hospitals. At the same
time, punk music was exploding,
</P>
<P>
   ``Punk clubs would book us and a lot of our first fans were
punks,'' Finch said. ``And once people heard us, they liked it.''
</P>
<P>
   Thus the BC ethic was established: They would have fun, as would
those who listened to them, but they would also be serious about
it. They released a long string of CDs on Rounder, and low-paying
bar gigs gave way, increasingly, to weddings.
</P>
<P>
   MORE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Weddings allow us to do other things we want to do _ they're
lucrative,'' said Cripps. ``And they're great for bringing in new
fans. In the last couple years people will call and ask if they can
go to a wedding we're playing, just to hear us. We have to say no _
we're just the hired help. And people also ask if we need roadies
when we go to Europe.''
</P>
<P>
   The answer is no _ BC doesn't have roadies, not even one guy to
do the heavy lifting. Or a manager. Or a booking agent.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of booking agents are used to dealing with clubs,'' said
Cripps. ``But if they had to deal with the bride's mother, they
couldn't handle it.''
</P>
<P>
   The pragmatic approach goes for the music, too. BC has always
gone its own merry musical way, the only rule being that there are
no rules.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't plan stuff _ it happens,'' Finch said. ``You just
never know. Someone will bring in a song, and we'll attempt it. Or
a fan will suggest something _ a guy came up and said, `Hey,
Ringo's (Starr) ``No No Song'' would be a good cha-cha.' So we did
it. And we added `Satisfaction' onto the top of it _ I liked the
idea of putting them together.''
</P>
<P>
   During the years, there have been 12 Combo members, including
five drummers. The current lineup has been in place since August,
when Emert rejoined after a year's absence.
</P>
<P>
   The major musical shift came in 1993, with the ``No, No, No Cha
Cha Cha'' CD. Previously, Combo CDs were a mix of sounds and
genres; afterward, the CDs would focus on one type of music or
theme. For instance, last year's ``Group Dance Epidemic'' was a
collection of songs designed for mass limb-shaking, such as ``The
Mexican Hat Dance'' and Van McCoy's ``The Hustle.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the truth is: Brave Combo wants a hit single.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're doing OK, but if we had a master plan, it would be to
have a hit and live off it forever,'' Barnes said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But you have to wonder how much soul you'd have to sell for
that hit,'' said Cripps. ``I don't want it to become an issue.''
</P>
<P>
   And chances are, really, that it won't be an issue any time
soon. More than likely, BC will be mixing styles and encouraging
clubs full of noisy patrons to do the bunny hop and the cha-cha
well into the next century.
</P>
<P>
   Where they stop, nobody knows.
</P>
<P>
   (Dave Ferman is music critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
E-mail him at dfer(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
