<SLUG> BC-VIAGRA-BROTHELS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BORDER CITY'S RED-LIGHT DISTRICT YIELDS TO VIAGRA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DANE SCHILLER  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NUEVO LAREDO, Mexico _ Geriatric zone doesn't have the same zing
as Boys Town, but the pricey blue pill known as Viagra is popping
up in this border city's infamous red-light district.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't mind getting the message out: Viagra works,'' a
61-year-old Texan said as he made his way out of Martha's, one of
dozens of bars lining the storied, unpaved streets of the walled
compound.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is effective for a very secret, private problem,'' said the
man, who would not give his name. ``It affects millions and
millions of men.''
</P>
<P>
   A red-headed Paola Montiel, who identified herself as a
prostitute, said she believed the impotence tablet already is
boosting business.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some men that are so old they can hardly walk, but
they can do it,'' said Montiel, 21, who works at Tamyko's, a
towering brothel with a Japanese-style garden and pond.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're like 82 years old, you know something happened,''
another woman chimed in.
</P>
<P>
   Pharmacists across town last weekend began stocking shelves with
the first shipment of Viagra to arrive in Nuevo Laredo, which
across the Rio Grande from Laredo, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   If Viagra's debut at Benavides Pharmacy was any indication, it
could be a while before the drug draws a flood of foreign tourists
hunting for inexpensive and hassle-free prescriptions.
</P>
<P>
   For one, the price is slightly more than $12 per pill, said
Enrique Moreno, a pharmacist. That compares with $7 to $10 per pill
in the United States of, depending on the dosage.
</P>
<P>
   And to purchase Viagra, customers need a prescription from a
urologist, Moreno said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The price could still go down. The thing is that it's a new
drug,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. analysts say as many as 40,000 prescriptions a day are
being issued for Viagra, which is manufactured by the New
York-based Pfizer Inc.
</P>
<P>
   At least 16 men have died after taking the wildly popular drug _
including seven who reportedly died during or after sex. But the
U.S. Food and Drug Administration could not establish a link
between the drug and the deaths.
</P>
<P>
   The FDA, however, warns that heart patients who take
nitroglycerin shouldn't mix their medication with the
anti-impotence drug.
</P>
<P>
   Late last week, Florida man, 89, was charged with attempted
murder after a woman accused him of clubbing her with a crowbar
when she refused his Viagra-induced advances.
</P>
<P>
   Due to similar concerns shared by the Mexican government, the
Viagra at Benavides is kept under lock and key in an area separate
from other medications.
</P>
<P>
   ``Americans come and come asking for the pill, but they don't
have prescriptions, so they're not going to get it,'' a Benavides
clerk said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At Boys Town, the Texan leaving Martha's said he had been
battling impotence for five years, and he welcomed the options
afforded by mixing Viagra with Boys Town.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been married three times and divorced three times; this
place suits me. I don't want to get married again,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A block away at a shop that bore no name on its front window, a
woman arranged displays of condoms, lingerie and assorted
paraphernalia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to be able to sell Viagra,'' she said. ``What a great
way to make money.''
</P>
</TEXT>
