<HEADER>
A9560 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHICK-FLICKS-TEX     06-15 0850
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHICK-FLICKS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE GRRRLS OF SUMMER: A GUIDE TO THIS YEAR'S CHICK FLICKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
.MDNM/By LIZ STEVENS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's not all big lizards and asteroids at the movies. It's also
the summer of ``chick flicks.''
</P>
<P>
   Time to dust off our favorite sexist term and apply it to all
those romantic summer movies with a (sexy) female lead and a
(hunky) male love interest. In other words: flicks that demand
hankies and a very tolerant date.
</P>
<P>
   Below, we've surveyed five such films that appeal to the sappy
side in all of us and flagged their consummately chick qualities.
</P>
<P>
   And remember, just because a movie doesn't have a theme song by
Bryan Adams, doesn't mean it won't make you cry.
</P>
<P>
   _ DESIGN: CHART CATEGORIES Chick and her love interest Hanky
factor (scale of 1 to 5) The chick's shtick Why chicks dig it Best
chick-flick moment Intrusive guy element Chick accessory (something
only a chick would notice) Chick-flick overkill
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``The Horse Whisperer''
</P>
<P>
   Chick and her love interest: Kristin Scott Thomas and Robert
Redford
</P>
<P>
   Hanky factor (scale of 1 to 5): 2 hankies
</P>
<P>
   The chick's shtick: Urbane magazine editor consumed by her work
is out of touch with her feelings until a hunky Montana horse
trainer twice her age changes everything.
</P>
<P>
   Why chicks dig it: Bob in chaps!
</P>
<P>
   Best chick-flick moment: While KST's husband chats with the guys
during a slow song, she and Redford sway on the dance floor,
radiating enough steam heat to curl hair.
</P>
<P>
   Intrusive guy element: Horrific horse-and-rider/truck wreck.
</P>
<P>
   Chick accessory (something only a chick would notice): KST's
petite drop earrings. Subtle and sophisticated.
</P>
<P>
   Chick-flick overkill: Gratuitous shots of Redford and the
Montana landscape bathed in a celestial golden glow.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``Six Days, Seven Nights''
</P>
<P>
   Chick and her love interest: Anne Heche and Harrison Ford
</P>
<P>
   Hanky factor (scale of 1 to 5): 0 hankies
</P>
<P>
   The chick's shtick: Urbane assistant magazine editor consumed by
her work is out of touch with her feelings until a hunky tropical
airplane pilot twice her age changes everything.
</P>
<P>
   Why chicks dig it: Indiana Jones in shorts!
</P>
<P>
   Best chick-flick moment: As they wade through a river in the
midst of their deserted island, the childless Ford tells Heche, ``I
always wanted kids. Bunches of 'em.''
</P>
<P>
   Intrusive guy element: Fist fight with sweaty pirates carrying
machine guns; one big boat explosion.
</P>
<P>
   Chick accessory (something only a chick would notice): Heche's
high-heeled hiking boots. No way she made it up that mountain in
those ankle busters.
</P>
<P>
   Chick-flick overkill: Heche to Ford: ``Was what we had on that
island anything?'' Oh, boo-hoo.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``Deja Vu''
</P>
<P>
   Chick and her love interest: Victoria Foyt and Stephen Dillane
</P>
<P>
   Hanky factor (scale of 1 to 5): 1 hanky, 2 barf bags
</P>
<P>
   The chick's shtick: Fate leads a Prozac-deprived manic
depressive to Israel, France, England and, finally, to her true
soul mate. Two problems: she's engaged; he's married.
</P>
<P>
   Why chicks dig it: Most probably won't.
</P>
<P>
   Best chick-flick moment: Dancing to the Sinatra-sung ``These
Foolish Things (Remind Me of You)'' in his Dover, England,
loft/studio.
</P>
<P>
   Intrusive guy element: Some chatter about a Victorian
gentlemen's games parlor.
</P>
<P>
   Chick accessory (something only a chick would notice): Her
wrinkle-free slim black slacks. They travel exceptionally well.
</P>
<P>
   Chick flick overkill: Foyt as Dana: ``I just wanted to feel
connected to a part of me that's more timeless.'' Still got that
barf bag?
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``Hope Floats''
</P>
<P>
   Chick and her love interest: Sandra Bullock and Harry Connick
</P>
<P>
   Hanky factor (scale of 1 to 5): 4 hankies
</P>
<P>
   The chick's shtick: Small-town beauty queen returns home to
Texas from Chicago after her husband runs off with her best friend.
</P>
<P>
   Why chicks dig it: Harry in tight T-shirts!
</P>
<P>
   Best chick-flick moment: Connick's heavy breathing all over
Bullock's neck during a scene in which they never even kiss. Get
out!
</P>
<P>
   Intrusive guy element: None!
</P>
<P>
   Chick accessory (something only a chick would notice): Bullock's
galvanized steel lunch box-as-purse. Very grrrrl chic.
</P>
<P>
   Chick-flick overkill: Bullock's pathetic solo walk in the rain.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``Mulan''
</P>
<P>
   Chick and her love interest: Mulan and Shang
</P>
<P>
   Hanky factor (scale of 1 to 5): 1 hanky
</P>
<P>
   The chick's shtick: Budding Chinese feminist cuts her hair and
joins the army to save her father's life and the family's honor.
</P>
<P>
   Why chicks dig it: Spunky, smart Mulan saves her country and its
emperor while teaching those seriously sexist bad guys a thing or
two about ``grrrl power.''
</P>
<P>
   Best chick-flick moment: Mulan's grandma upon seeing Shang for
the first time: ``Woo! Sign me up for the next war!''
</P>
<P>
   Intrusive guy element: Menacing Hun warriors, battle scenes and
brief nose picking.
</P>
<P>
   Chick accessory (something only a chick would notice): Gee, that
Mulan has great hair.
</P>
<P>
   Chick-flick overkill: None!
</P>
