<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HUTCHESON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCENIC ROADS IN TEXAS? NOT OFFICIALLY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RON HUTCHESON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The federal government picked 33 new scenic
roadways last week, and Texas got aced again. That's right. Not a
single Texas highway made the list of roads that are considered
worth a detour because of great views, historic sites or other
attractions.
</P>
<P>
   Texas also missed out on the last round of designations in 1996,
when 20 roads received the Transportation Department's seal of
approval.
</P>
<P>
   Don't blame the feds. Texas didn't make the list because Texans
didn't want any part of the federal program or the federal money
that goes with it. Fierce opposition from roadside property owners
persuaded state highway officials to drop the scenic roads project
two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the loudest complaints came from the Big Bend region in
far West Texas, a prime candidate for the scenic designation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The citizens didn't want it. They didn't want to be told what
to do, in a nutshell,'' said Michelle Conkle of the Texas
Department of Transportation. ``They were very, very, very opposed.
They spoke and we listened, and we did what they said.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of the opposition seems to have stemmed from a deep
distrust of government. Opponents feared that the scenic
designation would open the door to repressive government
restrictions on land use along the route. It hasn't worked out that
way in other states.
</P>
<P>
   The scenic byways program was established by Congress in 1991 to
promote and protect roads that have special significance.
Nominations from each state are screened by a citizen panel that
includes representatives from the tourism industry.
</P>
<P>
   The winning nominations are divided into two categories:
All-American Roads, which are considered ``the best of the best,''
and National Scenic Byways, which offer visitors beautiful scenery
or other notable features.
</P>
<P>
   Examples of All-American Roads include the Pacific Coast Highway
in California, the Blue Ridge Parkway in North Carolina and the San
Juan Skyway, a 233-mile route through the mountains of southwestern
Colorado. Only 14 roads have received the All-American designation.
</P>
<P>
   More than three dozen roads have qualified as National Scenic
Byways, including a handful within an easy drive from Texas. In
Louisiana, the 180-mile Creole Nature Trail travels along the Gulf
of Mexico in southern Calcasieu and Cameron parishes. New Mexico
routes include the Billy The Kid Scenic Byway, a loop linking
Ruidoso, Hondo, Lincoln and Capitan, and the Santa Fe Trail at
Raton.
</P>
<P>
   Roads that receive the special designations qualify for federal
grants that can be used for scenic overlooks, tourist signs,
hike-and-bike paths, or basic maintenance. The six-year highway
bill that President Clinton signed last week earmarked $148 million
for scenic byways.
</P>
<P>
   In return for the federal designation, state and local officials
agree to protect the road's special qualities. How they do that is
up to local officials, not the federal government, but the feds do
want a ban on new billboards along the route.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to access to federal cash, the scenic designation
usually means increased tourism and economic development. If a
community decides that maintaining the scenic corridor is too much
trouble, it can opt out of the program.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't had complaints from any communities that are
participating in the program,'' said Sharon Hurt Davidson, a
federal transportation official. ``It's a totally voluntary
program. We would love to work with Texas if they were
interested.''
</P>
<P>
   Thanks for the offer. We'll get back to you on that.
</P>
<P>
   (Ron Hutcheson is chief of the Fort Worth Star-Telegram's
Washington bureau. You can e-mail him at
rhutcheson(at)krwashington.com or call him at (202) 383-6000. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
