r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WRIGHT-COLUMN-TEX     06-15 1048
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WRIGHT-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SPANISH-AMERICAN WAR: AMERICA'S COMING OF AGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM WRIGHT 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   One hundred years ago this week, Theodore Roosevelt's Rough
Riders, along with other volunteer military contingents, embarked
enthusiastically from Tampa Bay and were en route to Cuba and a
series of successful skirmishes known as the Spanish-American War.
Their impressive efforts and Spain's quick surrender catapulted the
United States into its 20th-century role as a world power.
</P>
<P>
   That war, officially declared by Congress on April 25, lasted
only a few weeks and was described by then-Secretary of State John
Hay as a ``splendid little war.''
</P>
<P>
   Like the Persian Gulf conflict of 1991, it produced a quick,
easy victory, dramatically showcasing America's military
superiority.
</P>
<P>
   For our country, there was only brief fighting, and very little
dying, but a newfound glory that brought a sort of unifying closure
to the bloody divisiveness of the Civil War just as, almost a
century later, our one-sided routing of Iraq seemed to cure
America's national hangover from Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   But the ``splendid little war'' in the Caribbean and South China
seas did much, much more. It thrust America, almost against its
national will, into the big, complex world of global
responsibilities that we have increasingly shouldered throughout
the 20th century.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone reacted joyously. So fixed were House Speaker
Thomas Brackett Reed's convictions against expanding American
hegemony or assimilating Filipinos and Puerto Ricans into an
American amalgam that he resigned the speakership rather than
participate in the new roles that the Spanish-American War thrust
upon his country.
</P>
<P>
   By 1898, America was already a political inspiration, and
arguably the world's foremost industrial power. Ours was the model
for popular people's movements on every continent. And reports of
our emerging egalitarian prosperity and open opportunity were
drawing waves of immigrants, magnet-like, from stale and hopeless
cells of stratified poverty throughout the world.
</P>
<P>
   But aside from the Monroe Doctrine and our pre-Civil War
flirtation with the ``Manifest Destiny'' credo, America's interests
had been largely domestic. We'd been content to mind our own
business and plow our own acres. Didn't George Washington admonish
us to beware of entangling alliances?
</P>
<P>
   Now, suddenly, with Spain's faded empire so decisively
vanquished, we emerged like a young giant upon the world stage. It
was a sort of national coming of age, with elements both awkward
and heroic.
</P>
<P>
   Changes in the style and quality of American life swept across
the scene with that war. One of those, championed by William
Randolph Hearst, was an entirely new style of journalism,
infinitely more colorful and entertaining, and certainly more
influential if lamentably less reliable.
</P>
<P>
   It was Hearst's crusading newspapers whose screaming headlines
and extravagant claims stampeded public opinion, ultimately driving
Congress into declaring war.
</P>
<P>
   Ben Procter, in his authoritative and revealing new book on
Hearst (''William Randolph Hearst, The Early Years, 1863-1910'')
shows how the flamboyant publisher used his New York Journal to
seize quick advantage of a tragic explosion to kindle nationwide
outrage and fan it into a war cry.
</P>
<P>
   The arrogant Spanish overlords of Cuba had sunk the battleship
Maine in Havana Harbor, killing 266 U.S. servicemen, asserted
Hearst immediately. By 6 a.m. the next morning, a Journal extra was
on the streets, huge headlines announcing the ship's destruction
``BY AN ENEMY'S SECRET INFERNAL MACHINE.''
</P>
<P>
   On Feb. 20, after four days of sensationalized finger-pointing,
the Journal's bold headline claimed ``PROOF OF A SUBMARINE MINE.''
Ensuing issues featured purported quotes from underwater divers
supplying ``positive proof'' that the Spanish, in spite of their
denials, had masterminded the gory disaster. (Years later, official
examinations of the hull would speculate that the Maine had blown
up internally, probably from combustion or accidental fire in the
coal supply, setting off explosions of the adjacent ammunition
stores.)
</P>
<P>
   Hearst had been crusading to free Cuba from Spanish rule, the
goal of repeated uprisings since at least 1878. The Journal had
championed Cuban rebels, once fictionalizing a daring ``rescue'' of
a saintly young nun from a corrupt Spanish prison. Public support
was rising for the Cuba Libre cause. The sinking of the Maine was
an irresistible instrument with which to whip sentiment to a level
of frenzy.
</P>
<P>
   With a sense of high idealism, Congress adopted by joint
resolution a firm commitment to Cuban independence as its
justification for war. ``The people of the island of Cuba are and
of right ought to be free and independent,'' proclaimed Congress,
demanding that Spain relinquish power and directing President
McKinley to use armed force if necessary to achieve that end.
</P>
<P>
   Congress declared further that the United States ``hereby
disclaims any disposition of intention to exercise sovereignty,
jurisdiction, or control over said island except for pacification
thereof, and asserts its determination, when that is accomplished,
to leave the government and control of the island to its people.''
</P>
<P>
   It didn't work out that way. Cuban Gen. Calixto Garcia and other
revolutionaries who'd fought beside our troops to liberate the
island were cut out of the negotiations and out of governance, to
the bitter disillusionment of Cuban patriots.
</P>
<P>
   McKinley appointed an overseer, Governor General Leonard Wood,
who said that any Cuban without at least $250 represented ``a
social element unworthy'' of the ballot. ``Let him not vote.'' We
didn't yet know how a democracy could exercise world power.
</P>
<P>
   A century later, Hawaii is a state; Puerto Rico soon may be; the
Philippines are free and mostly friendly; ours is the undisputed
mantle of world preeminence. We still haven't made peace with Cuba.
Perhaps it's time.
</P>
<P>
   (Jim Wright of Fort Worth, a Democrat, is a former speaker of
the U.S. House of Representatives. You can write him at P.O. Box
1413, Fort Worth, TX 76101. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
