</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOO-MUCH-NEWS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IS THERE TOO MUCH `NEWS'? 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BERNARD D. KAPLAN  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ The World Cup soccer championship in France is
monopolizing news space in the European papers and on TV.
</P>
<P>
   Other events of second- and third-rate importance that would
normally occupy columns of newsprint and several minutes of air
time on the nightly news have gone unreported. Apparently, they are
unmissed.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, a huge amount of space is being devoted not only to the
matches themselves but to the minutiae surrounding them: how the
fans are behaving, the latest snarl over the distribution of
tickets and which team's supporters have done themselves up in the
wackiest costumes. In all, as much attention goes to the peripheral
happenings as to the actual contests.
</P>
<P>
   This has led some of us to ponder the following: If the news
pages can be swallowed up day after day in this fashion, could it
be that ordinarily much of the news that is solemnly reported could
safely be ignored? In other words, do we receive too much
information from the media for our own good?
</P>
<P>
   It is, of course, heresy for a journalist to ask such questions.
Information, as we're constantly told, is vital to democracy, to
the right of every citizen to know about matters that are of
concern to a well-functioning society.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, it's valid to ask whether these days we get so much news
that we are becoming intellectually punch drunk. Every minor
uprising in every minor country is now reported in exhausting
detail _ except when the World Cup is on _ only to disappear
entirely from the newspapers and airwaves a day or two later.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, how much do most people elsewhere need to know
about the fighting in a border dispute between Eritrea and Ethiopia
that has recently been in the news? I suspect the stark truth is
that when such events are reported on newscasts, the audience
switches off mentally, if not physically.
</P>
<P>
   There is evidence that readers and listeners are getting jaded
by this cascade of force-fed facts, much of which they feel they
have no need to absorb. Around-the-clock TV news channels have
become a worldwide phenomenon. The British Broadcasting Corporation
began a 24-hour service a few months ago. Out of a potential
audience of 30 million, fewer than 400,000 regularly tune in.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most things don't matter at all,'' remarked Arthur Balfour, a
British prime minister early in this century, ``and nothing matters
very much.''
</P>
<P>
   Balfour has been dismissed as a cynical aristocrat _ which he
was _ for saying that. It runs against all our conventional wisdom.
But maybe, with some exceptions, he was right. At any rate, his
words are worth recalling the next time you switch on the nightly
news.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-15-98 1415EDT &QL; 
