A9587 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-REALWORLD-SPI &LR;      06-15 1012
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-REALWORLD-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`REAL WORLD' PUTS ITS OWN INSULAR SPIN ON LIFE IN SEATTLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Let's get it over with, shall we? ``The Real World'' is as
believable as whatever planet Dennis Rodman calls home. Those with
views to the contrary are seriously deluded, or they just happen to
live in 4,500-square-foot waterfront homes where hot and cold
running commentary on the others who live there is a regular slice
of life.
</P>
<P>
   But admit it. If someone invited you to live rent free in lavish
Seattle surroundings with six other people for four-plus months,
with a side trip to, say, Nepal, would you say no?
</P>
<P>
   You might if you knew who your housemates were going to be. But
the producers of ``The Real World'' would never divulge that sort
of thing in advance. They don't even like to divulge the last names
of the cast members because, in the real world, last names are just
so much excess baggage, dude.
</P>
<P>
   Mystery, in fact, is at the heart of ``The Real World,'' and
over seven seasons its producers, Mary-Ellis Bunim and Jonathan
Murray, have become so adept at stringing along the viewer that
it's easy to dismiss the show as a load of manipulative melodrama.
</P>
<P>
   As ``reality,'' it is eminently dismissible, since every minute
that makes it on the air is distilled from about six hours of
taping. What we don't get to see on the screen, of course, is what
we really want to know. Is David really that slimy? Will Nathan get
a mind of his own? Did Irene have special training to acquire that
annoying voice? Will Janet and Lindsay ever stop talking? Is
Stephen the sensitive type or just a whiner? Is Rebecca too good to
be true?
</P>
<P>
   Tune in every Tuesday night at 10 to find out just what
Bunim/Murray want you to find out. Here are the early indications
from the sumptuous digs on Seattle's Pier 70: David Burns, Nathan
Blackburn, Janet Choi and Lindsay Brien are the ``Ins,'' Rebecca
Lord, Stephen Williams and Irene McGee are the ``Outs.'' (Irene is
so out that she left the show before taping was finished.)
</P>
<P>
   If past seasons offer any clue, these impressions may change as
MTV's little exercise in group dynamics unfolds. One thing is
certain: Observing human behavior is always a kick, orchestrated or
not. It's kind of surprising that one of the big broadcast networks
hasn't stolen the ``Real World'' idea, because as entertainment it
sure beats another boatload of funniest home videos.
</P>
<P>
   The Seattle apartment that was the castmates' home from January
to May is a hedonist's holiday. Built on an actual commercial pier
jutting into Elliott Bay, it features the requisite fireplace, pool
table, spa and exercise equipment, plus a climbing wall for
climbing the walls, and a hole in the floor for, one presumes, a
little late-night squid jigging.
</P>
<P>
   With 12 surveillance cameras and microphones throughout the pad
providing an endless stream of images and sound to 15 monitors in
the control room next door, the cast members were essentially seven
little Keikos. Add to that the rail-crossing bells that go off
about every 20 minutes along Alaskan Way and the stage is set for
some real killer wails over the next few months.
</P>
<P>
   Still, about 15,000 people apply to be on ``The Real World'' and
its spinoff, ``Road Rules'' (for which the cast members live in a
29-foot Winnebago instead of a stationary cush-pad).
</P>
<P>
   The reason is simple: a moment of fame and a semester away from
college. But, as David says when he and Nathan see the apartment
for the first time: ``Even the soap's cool. We can't lose.''
</P>
<P>
   Adds Nathan: ``It's like looking into a candy store when you're
a little kid. I couldn't believe it. It was just Christmas all over
again, a hundred times more.''
</P>
<P>
   It is especially meaningful to them because, if you saw last
week's casting special _ don't worry, MTV repeats everything _ you
know they both come from humble beginnings and they don't see a lot
of frills at the Virginia Military Institute.
</P>
<P>
   But their having known each other for three years is a different
sort of ``Real World'' wrinkle. It immediately puts Stephen, the
only other male cast member, into a fifth-wheel funk. The immediate
bonding of Janet and Lindsay creates the same sort of alienation
for Rebecca and Irene.
</P>
<P>
   And then, when Nathan and Janet ``discover'' a discarded journal
entry that carps about a lack of diversity in the group, the seeds
of discord start sprouting. Janet and Nathan assume it was written
by Stephen, but it turns out that Nathan's own buddy, David, is the
author.
</P>
<P>
   The coincidence of this discovery is so tortured that it strains
credulity, but it's also beside the point. The manufacturing of
conflict is a hallmark of ``The Real World,'' and it hardly matters
if it's staged or not. (Nathan's girlfriend back in Virginia, who
hadn't even applied to the show, was ``considered'' for the cast at
the last minute, then rejected. The inevitable result: Tomorrow's
episode alone has enough spite-filled phone calls to last seven
seasons.)
</P>
<P>
   So, whoever comes out of this looking good is partly up to the
individual and partly up to the tape editor. Rebecca, at 19 the
youngest and seemingly most naive of the group, looks the best
after the first show because she manages to avoid conflict. What
happens as the gang goes to work at KNDD-FM and makes its
REI-sponsored trek to the Himalayas and wanders around Seattle is
the next question.
</P>
<P>
   For MTV, the answer doesn't matter. With slick production values
and physically attractive cast members, ``The Real World,''
contrived or not, appeals to the voyeur in all of us.
</P>
<P>
   The Real World. Hourlong premiere of the seventh season of the
``reality-based'' show that chronicles the lives of seven young
adults living together in front of the camera for four months.
Tuesday MTV. Check local listings. Parental guideline rating:
TV-PG.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   To reach John Levesque, call 206-448-8330, or send an e-mail
message to: tvguy(at)seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
