<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-15 14:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9622 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      06-15 0922
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE TIMES ARE RIGHT FOR A REJUVENATED PEACE CORPS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (k and w coding.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS OLIPHANT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON -- Wherever American foreign policy is headed, I have
a sneaking suspicion that Dennis Robinson is going to get there
first. If we let him.
</P>
<P>
   Like 6,100 other Americans, Dennis Robinson is in the Peace
Corps. He's just back from Panama, on the front lines of one of
today's most important battles _ against the primal forces behind
slash-and-burn agriculture and the dire threat it poses to public
health, the environment and the world's ability to feed a
still-exploding population.
</P>
<P>
   His work in the countryside has involved showing farmers how to
keep a chunk of land in production, the key to stabilizing rural
life as well as the rural environment.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, the Peace Corps lit Dennis Robinson's candle. He
is anything but quixotic as he discusses the pressures on the
people he has served. But he is clearly in awe at how the Peace
Corps took a kid out of a small community in Kentucky, fresh out of
college, and connected him to the world. Like 151,000 other
Americans over the past generation-plus, he is utterly transformed.
</P>
<P>
   You couldn't imagine a better choice for an important new facet
of the program _ the Crisis Corps, which is shipping experienced
volunteers into places that have suffered natural disasters or
where peace has only recently replaced chaos and violence.
</P>
<P>
   It's not a question of will but of money. More outrageously,
it's a question of a small amount of money _ maybe $45 million,
which is chicken feed next to the tens of billions in pure pork
that fattened the highway bill President Clinton signed last week.
</P>
<P>
   In many respects, this is very much your father's or your
mother's Peace Corps, its well-tried concept of service chugging
along in 84 countries. But in many others, it's different, more
vital _ the fruit of director Mark Gearan's work since the
president shipped his longtime pal over there in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   It is, for example, very much a part of post-Cold War
reconstruction. From an opening wedge in Eastern Europe, it has
moved into the battered former republics of the former Soviet Union
itself _ in Ukraine, Armenia, Kyrgyzstan. Georgia is next.
</P>
<P>
   The first English teachers went to China five years ago. The
first volunteers went back to Haiti while peacekeepers were still
patrolling there in 1996. And perhaps the luckiest volunteers are
now working with schoolteachers in reborn South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Anything but a dumb pol, Gearan yanked me down the street to eat
sandwiches with a dozen just-returned volunteers, who, like Peace
Corps workers for 37 years, can make the program's case in ways
that Director No. 14 (just like No. 1, R. Sargent Shriver) can't.
</P>
<P>
   The case is easily the biggest no-brainer in Washington. After
roughly 20 flat years the time has come to take the Peace Corps to
a new level. Clinton decided in January to take it from 6,100
volunteers and $220-plus million this year to 10,000 volunteers and
$270 million in the year 2000, still well under the
15,000-volunteer peak in 1966.
</P>
<P>
   At the time there was no dissent, no argument. But within
Congress there has also been no action since. Part of it is the
general congressional dysfunction and part is the specific
dysfunction over the budget. With account juggling there could be
room within the emerging Senate appropriation, but Newt Gingrich's
House right now couldn't decide to fund the tissue in its
restrooms.
</P>
<P>
   Going a bit deeper, though, modern conservatism is growing
isolationist appendages; it's much less Reagan and Bush and more
and more Pat Buchanan. It shows in a growing hostility to trade, to
international engagement, to the United Nations, and to the
International Monetary Fund.
</P>
<P>
   The president confronts this effectively on occasion, as he did
on China last week, but he needs to do it more and more loudly.
</P>
<P>
   He has experience fighting for his domestic counterpart,
AmeriCorps. This stunning start-up _ with major business and
bipartisan support_ survives Gingrich-inspired troublemakers
because each year the president simply refuses to accept the larger
appropriation bill that includes AmeriCorps until the program is
sufficiently funded.
</P>
<P>
   A little of that spirit would help him and, more important, help
the Peace Corps.
</P>
<P>
   The times are right. Since 1994 the number of inquiries by
potential volunteers has soared by nearly 50 percent, to more than
150,000. The spirit is there in a generation that deserves more
than Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   The times are also right in the world. Freedom, independence,
and market economies _ the raw material for a better, stable world
_ are in the ascendancy, and Peace Corp volunteers are democracy's
retailers.
</P>
<P>
   And the times are also right for their modern mission. Education
remains the core, as it should, but what is new is a fresh emphasis
on environmental projects and small-business and community
development.
</P>
<P>
   T.J. Jones is a sharp kid out of Rocky Mount, N.C., an
African-American in the middle of Ukraine. Among its many evils,
communism blocked the normal institutions of community life. T.J.
Jones is up to his ears helping nonprofit, service organizations
put concrete in democracy's foundation.
</P>
<P>
   For his sake, for theirs and for ours, the idea that we are not
literally throwing money at T.J. Jones is absurd.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Thomas Oliphant is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
