<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-15 15:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9732 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BULLS-JORDAN-MONEY-MA     06-15 0988
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BULLS-JORDAN-MONEY-MANIA-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SO JUST WHAT IS MICHAEL JORDAN WORTH? 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (This has already moved to clients of Richard Roeper's popular
weekly columns, now being offered as a regular New York Times
Syndicate feature. For a bio &AMP; photo _ as well as special contract
rates _ please contact your sales representative:
 &HT;    _ If you're in the Eastern time zone or Canada, call BOB FARNELL
at 1-800-535-4425. Or send a fax to him at (717) 646-4850.
 &HT;    _ If you're in the Central time zone, call CONNIE WHITE at
1-800-444-0267. Or fax her at (816) 822-1444.
 &HT;    _ If you're in the Pacific or Mountain time zones or in Latin
America, call OLIVIA VASQUEZ at (310) 996-0075. Or fax her at (310)
996-0089.
 &HT;    
 By RICHARD ROEPER  
 c.1998 The Chicago Sun-Times  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   Ten billion. It's a number that will forever be associated with
Michael Jordan, as much as his NBA championships and his scoring
titles and his MVP awards.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan has had a $10 billion impact on the U.S. economy since
joining the NBA in 1984, according to an article in Fortune
magazine that was cited by virtually every media outlet in the
country.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Jordan. Ten billion dollars. Married forever.
</P>
<P>
   Kind of reminds me of the famous stat about the TV audience for
the Oscars. Every year, we're told ``one billion viewers worldwide
tuned in for the Academy Awards.''
</P>
<P>
   Nobody ever questions that figure _ or at least nobody did until
earlier this year, when Buzz magazine did some digging and found
that even if the entire populations of every country that receives
the telecast were glued to the set, the number of viewers would
fall far short of the magic one billion figure _ which was
conceived by an exuberant publicist years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Ah, so what. The myth is too strong to kill.
</P>
<P>
   We love round numbers. If the economists commissioned by Fortune
to help them estimate ``The Jordan Effect''' had come up with a
figure of, say, $9.654 billion - well, that's just not as enticing
as 10 billion, is it? Why not round it off and attract even more
free publicity for your magazine?
</P>
<P>
   I envy their savvy.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, to theorize about something like the total economic
impact of Air Jordan is to engage in a kind of nebular hypothesis;
it's impossible to determine an exact figure. But sifting through
the lengthy article and the charts and figures, I came across a
number of eyebrow-raising elements.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Fortune adds up the profits of 70 Jordan-related
books, his sports videos, the cologne and underwear he endorses and
the worldwide box office and video totals for his movie ``Space
Jam,'' and they come up with a figure of $701 million.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously if you were to subtract the production and marketing
cost of the movie; the salaries of hundreds of employees who make
the underwear, print the books, etc.; and the costs of publishing a
book, among other expenses, the figure would be considerably lower.
</P>
<P>
   You could do the same thing with each category _ from NBA
attendance to the value of the Bulls' franchise to TV revenues to
advertising dough, and you'd end up with a much lesser figure. But
it wouldn't be as much fun if Fortune had said Jordan's net
economic effect was something like $3 billion or even less.
</P>
<P>
   One also has to consider that some player _ or, more likely, a
number of players _ would have generated some of the money
attributed to Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   If we lived in a Michael-less world (perish the thought!), Nike
would have made someone else their prime star, and Warner Brothers
would have found some other athlete to star in a movie with its
cartoon characters, the league would have sold jerseys bearing some
other player's name and number, and sportswriters would have
written books about other athletes.
</P>
<P>
   (Heck, maybe there'd be a Zippy Pippy cologne inspired by
Scottie Pippen, who knows.)
</P>
<P>
   The point is, not every one of these dollars can be attributed
solely to the Jordan factor.
</P>
<P>
   And what about the negative financial impact Jordan has wrought?
Why, earlier this month a study was released saying that workplace
chatter about the Bulls could cost the Chicago-area economy alone
more than $90 million!
</P>
<P>
   Extrapolate those figures over the years and factor in the
nationwide work stoppages that occur because of conversation about
Michael, and he's probably cost the American workplace a few
billion, easily.
</P>
<P>
   Not to mention all the players who have been driven to
unemployment ... after being embarrassed on the court by MJ. And
the local eateries that don't do as well because of the presence of
Michael Jordan's Restaurant. And the sneaker companies that have
had to lay off employees after being stomped on by the Air Jordan
line.
</P>
<P>
   Oh but wait a minute. We haven't factored in the increase in
sales at bars, restaurants, liquor stores, catering businesses,
etc., that occurs every time the Bulls play.
</P>
<P>
   Nor have we included the salaries of the people on Jordan's own
payroll, the profits of his own restaurants and golf centers, the
positive effect he's had on the sport of golf, the rise in sales of
shaving cream and razor blades now that millions are emulating his
chrome dome look...
</P>
<P>
   Ouch. Brain cramp! Upon further review, I've decided the $10
billion figure provided by Fortune is exactly right.
</P>
<P>
   To the penny.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Richard Roeper (rroeper &LR; suntimes.com) can be heard on the
``Media Creatures'' show, which airs daily in Chicago from 10 a.m.
to 2 p.m. on WMVP-AM (1000) and appears Tuesday and Thursday at
7:55 a.m. on WFLD-TV's ``Fox Thing in the Morning.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (A daily columnist for the Chicago Sun-Times, Roeper has also
written for TV Guide, Spy, Playboy, Chicago magazine and many other
publications, and has appeared as a guest on ``Nightline'' and
``Oprah.'') &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ---------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
