<DOCNO> NYT19980615.0186 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-15 15:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9738 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-BLINEBURYCOLUMN-H     06-15 0802
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-BLINEBURYCOLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Air lift complete; questions remain
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By FRAN BLINEBURY &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
SALT LAKE CITY _ A lone tear ran down his cheek. Or was it a single
bead of sweat?
</P>
<P>
   For Michael Jordan, both were appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   If this was, indeed, the end of the line, the conclusion to the
wild, incredible, amazing, often controversial magical mystery tour
of the Chicago Bulls and the greatest player of our time, it was a
moment for a tinge of sadness.
</P>
<P>
   If this was just another game, one of many more in which Jordan
will run and shoot and drive himself and outperform everybody else
on the court in seasons and years to come, then it was a message of
what it means for every man, even the very best, to go to work.
</P>
<P>
   Like Sinatra, he did it his way. Taking all the big shots,
making all the big plays, embracing the biggest stage as his own
personal platform.
</P>
<P>
   It was more than the Bulls winning their sixth NBA title and
Jordan scoring 45 points. It was one final, dominating minute in
which he again lifted his team and carried it to a stunning 87-86
victory over the Jazz that in 60 gripping seconds defined and
underlined his career.
</P>
<P>
   All of the talk for the past days and weeks and months had been
about where the Bulls would go from here.
</P>
<P>
   Would Jordan finally and this time permanently hang up his
designer hightops? Would Scottie Pippen, feeling unappreciated,
sign with another team as a free agent? Would coach Phil Jackson
follow up on his pledge to walk out the door? Would Weird Dennis
Rodman take his bizarre act to another locale?
</P>
<P>
   One of a kind
</P>
<P>
   So many questions. So many emotions for the players in the
locker room and the Bulls fans around the world, wondering if it
was a time to celebrate an achievement or mourn the end of an era.
</P>
<P>
   The Beatles broke up, John Lennon died and the sun continued to
shine. But the music has never been the same.
</P>
<P>
   If Jordan leaves, there will be a similar emptiness, a dark
void.
</P>
<P>
   But for a night, he simply did what he does. He was the light.
</P>
<P>
   ``Michael is a guy who comes through,'' Jackson said. ``He is a
real life hero.''
</P>
<P>
   He is more than an athlete for the ages. He's an artist who
fills up the entire canvas, a dramatist who knows how to write the
last act. He owned the fourth quarter, scoring 16 points, and that
hardly tells the tale.
</P>
<P>
   Two Jordan free throws with 59.2 seconds remaining, tied the
score at 83-all and set up the final curtain.
</P>
<P>
   When John Stockton nailed a 3-pointer with 41.9 seconds to go,
it was a game the Jazz could hold.
</P>
<P>
   Until Jordan ripped it from their grasp.
</P>
<P>
   It was already a night when the Lone Ranger rode without Tonto
as Pippen labored with a painfully aching back.
</P>
<P>
   Then he did more. A driving basket over the arms of Utah
defenders and the Bulls were down by just one.
</P>
<P>
   What next?
</P>
<P>
   With just 20 seconds left, Karl Malone, who scored 31 points,
tried to set up in the low blocks. Rodman was behind him. But
Jordan crept up like a cat burglar from the side. He flicked the
ball away and now the game was where he wanted it. In his hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt confident when I got that ball,'' Jordan said. ``At
that point, the crowd gets quiet and the moment becomes the moment.
Things start to move slowly. You can see it unfolding. You can read
the defense and see what it's going to do. I saw it. When (Bryon)
Russell reached, I knew what I was going to do.''
</P>
<P>
   He stabbed one foot and delivered a 17-foot dagger into the
teeth of the howling Delta Center crowd with 5.2 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   The Jazz could go away regretting that a desperate 3-point try
by Stockton clanked off the front rim. Utah could complain about a
horrible call by referee Dick Bavetta in the second quarter that
wiped out a trey by Howard Eisley on a 24-second violation or a
non-call on a shot by Ron Harper that tied the game with 3:44 left.
Bavetta is to officiating what Barney Fife is to law enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   But to cry is to diminish the valiant fight. To rant in protest
is to surrender dignity, to deny that Jordan wouldn't have done
more, found another way. He always does. He always has.
</P>
<P>
   Now the questions remain. Will he or won't he?
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, that's a gut feeling that I have,'' Jordan said.
``When I walked away the first time, it was a feeling. It wasn't
something someone told me. When I came back, it was a feeling. If
and when that time comes where I've got to walk away, I hope that
no one will look at me any less. Hopefully, I've put enough
memories out there for everybody to at least have some thoughts
about what Michael Jordan did.''
</P>
<P>
   One more night, one more memory. Of blood, of sweat, maybe of
even a tear of goodbye.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Jordan earned it all again.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-15-98 1528EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980615.0187 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-15 15:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9740 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ROBISON-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      06-15 0811
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROBISON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEEL STILL SPINNING ON RESERVATION CASINOS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLAY ROBISON 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Nothing brings out the schizophrenia in our
government quite like gambling does.
</P>
<P>
   What that says about the people our government purports to
represent, I'm not sure. But Gov. George W. Bush's war against two
Texas Indian tribes over casino gambling on their reservations is
the latest chapter in officialdom's inconsistent _ and uneasy _
relationship with games of chance.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is seeking legal action against casinos operated by the
Tiguas in El Paso and the Kickapoos in Eagle Pass for allegedly
violating Texas' anti-gambling laws.
</P>
<P>
   He recently renewed a request to Attorney General Dan Morales
after a lawyer for the Texas Lottery Commission told him the Tiguas
were using Las Vegas-style slot machines at their casino in El
Paso.
</P>
<P>
   Two sets of laws _ federal and state _ are potentially in
conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Federal law allows Indian tribes to conduct on their
reservations the same types of games that are legal in the state in
which the reservation is located.
</P>
<P>
   Casino gambling isn't legal in Texas, a point that Bush has
repeatedly made. But the lottery is legal in this state, and
federal law, the Indians' supporters say, lumps lotteries and
casino gambling into the same classification.
</P>
<P>
   Morales was reluctant to take on the Indians. But the Tiguas
filed their own suit in federal court, arguing that the state lacks
jurisdiction over how a federally recognized Indian tribe conducts
gambling on its reservation.
</P>
<P>
   And Democratic challenger Garry Mauro stepped in to criticize
Bush. Mauro insisted the casinos were legal and an economic boon to
the tribes. He also said the state, if it cooperated with the
Indians, could be sharing revenue from the casinos.
</P>
<P>
   How this dispute will play out _ legally and politically _
remains to be seen, but this isn't the first time Bush has staked
out an anti-gambling position. He also has been leading an attack
on eight-liners, simulated slot machines operated in some bars and
truck stops.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has been so outspoken against gambling that some people who
like to read presidential politics into everything the governor
does have even speculated that he views this as an issue to ride
into the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Bush isn't the only official in Austin to oppose casinos.
Opposition in the Legislature also has been strong against them,
despite lawmakers' approval of parimutuel betting on horse and dog
races, the lottery and charitable bingo.
</P>
<P>
   There is a law on the books allowing cruise ships that offer
casino gambling to dock in Texas ports, as long as the gambling
actually takes place outside Texas waters. But those enterprises
have had some rough sailing.
</P>
<P>
   Casino gambling is viewed as undesirable, even unsavory, by many
Texans and their leaders, even by those who regularly risk their
money on lottery tickets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Casino gambling, for whatever reason, is looked at through a
different lens,'' said Sue Cox, director of the Texas Council on
Problem and Compulsive Gambling.
</P>
<P>
   Ann Richards was governor when the lottery was created in 1991,
and she had to twist a lot of arms to win the necessary two-thirds
vote for legislative approval. Once it cleared the Legislature, the
proposal didn't have any trouble winning final approval from Texas
voters.
</P>
<P>
   Richards sold the lottery as an important new revenue raiser for
the state, especially for education, at a time when the state was
still recovering from a recession and facing a budget crunch.
</P>
<P>
   Proponents of parimutuel wagering, who had been shut out by the
Legislature for years, used a similar argument during the darkest
days of the recession to finally break through. In a special
session in 1986, they convinced lawmakers _ who were facing deep
budget cuts and a large tax bill in an election year _ that race
track betting also could be an important source of state revenue
and a significant boost to the Texas economy.
</P>
<P>
   So far, parimutuel hasn't lived up to its promise. Many tracks
have struggled, and some have failed. But the lottery was an
immediate hit and is still contributing more than $1 billion a year
to the state treasury.
</P>
<P>
   Had Bush been governor during those tight budget periods, would
he have lobbied lawmakers to create the lottery or supported
parimutuel betting? Who knows?
</P>
<P>
   Then-Gov. Mark White demonstrated the difficulty many elected
officials have with the gambling issue. He didn't sign the
parimutuel bill but, yielding to the arguments that it was a needed
revenue raiser, he let it become law without his signature.
</P>
<P>
   And he issued a written statement, preaching against the evils
of gambling.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Robison is chief of the Chronicle's Austin Bureau. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
