<HEADER>
A9741 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      06-15 1312
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A HEALTHY LAWN DISCOURAGES WEEDS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By KATHY HUBER 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: I am a beginning gardener and am trying to learn some of the
basics of keeping my lawn. The lawn is only 5 or 6 months old, and
we are having problems with clumps that have tall stalks that grow
quickly and look unsightly. In trying to build up our lawn, we've
been using lawn fertilizer. What do the three numbers on the
package mean?
</P>
<P>
   A: Those quick-growing, tall clumps may be a type of weed. Do
they look different from your turf grass? Dallisgrass is a
perennial weed that forms a large clump of dark green foliage and
within days of mowing sends stalks with black seeds. Crabgrass is a
warm-season annual that forms loose clumps and sends out runners.
The foliage is a lighter green and dull. You can dig such weeds
out, and the turf will fill in.
</P>
<P>
   Generally, I think it's best to strive for a healthy lawn, as
this will discourage weeds. The key steps to a healthy lawn are
aeration, proper mowing, watering and fertilization.
</P>
<P>
   I like to aerate a lawn once or twice a year by walking around
on the lawn with spiky shoes. This creates holes that help oxygen
and rain travel down into the soil. You may have seen aerator shoes
at garden centers or in catalogs. St. Augustine is best kept at a
height between 2 and 3 inches. A mulching mower will cut the grass
blades into small pieces that quickly break down, returning
nitrogen to the soil. St. Augustine needs about 2 inches of water a
week during the hot, dry summer. If it doesn't rain, water your
lawn to make up the deficit.
</P>
<P>
   Fertilize after the grass has greened in the spring and is
beginning to grow. Apply a slow-release or organic product. A 3-1-2
ratio is good. This means that the fertilizer contains 3 percent by
weight of nitrogen, 1 percent phosphorus and 2 percent potassium.
Nitrogen promotes good leaf and stem growth. Phosphorus stimulates
root development, helps plants mature and encourages the production
of flowers. Potassium aids cell metabolism and encourages heat- and
cold-hardiness. Fertilize again in the fall, not to promote top
growth, but to promote good root growth during the winter.
</P>
<P>
   There are herbicides for lawn weeds. These are categorized as
pre-emergents _ applied before the weeds come up, or
post-emergents, applied after the weeds appear. St. Augustine and
Bermuda are turf grasses grown here. However, you must be careful
to select a herbicide, or weed killer, that will not kill the turf
grass. There is a limited number of herbicides that can be used on
St. Augustine. Always study the label carefully before using a
product.
</P>
<P>
   If you must, you can use a spot weed killer that contains
glyphosate to kill weeds in St. Augustine. This herbicide will
damage the turf grass around the weed, so aim carefully or you'll
have temporary brown spots.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q:  &LR; I have a bush/tree in my front yard that was given to me by
a former neighbor who could only tell me the plant is a native of
his homeland, Korea. I hope you can help me identify this plant and
give me some information on care and propagation.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A:  &LR; The photos you sent are of an althea (Hibiscus syriacus), a
great, old-fashioned large shrub/small tree. This member of the
hibiscus genus and mallow family is native to eastern Asia but was
popular in Southern gardens. Also known as rose of Sharon, the
althea is deciduous, shedding its leaves during winter, leafing out
in spring, then flowering late spring to fall. Blooms may be single
or double; colors include white with maroon eye, blue and pink. The
blooms, like those of other members of this family, last but a day,
but most produce abundant flowers.
</P>
<P>
   The low-care althea endures heat, humidity, even drought once
established. It does prefer good drainage and may suffer cotton
root rot if the soil is too alkaline. Mature height is 12 feet.
This plant accepts light shade but blooms best with some sun.
Altheas flower on new wood, so prune in late winter. Root cuttings
in late spring or early summer.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q:  &LR; We are buying a new house in a new subdivision. The lawn
and some landscaping for the front are included, but the big fenced
back yard will be bare dirt. I like the idea of using natives, so I
was considering a wildflower meadow. Could you give a few pros and
cons on that idea? How about buffalo grass? I also would like to
plant a spreading, deciduous shade tree that would grow quickly but
still have a good long life.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A:  &LR; A wildflower meadow would be beautiful, but this type of
project takes planning and time. And you need to keep in mind it
will be ``beautiful'' only part of the year. You would need to let
it go to seed for future returns. I am not trying to discourage
you, only trying to point out that your back yard would be
``natural'' while your front is more ``cultivated.''
</P>
<P>
   I think it would be wise to read about sowing such a meadow.
Wildseed Farms provides excellent information on growing
wildflowers. Call 800-848-0078 for a catalog with valuable
information on sowing wildflowers and cultural tips on those
flowers available. Laura Martin's The Wildflower Meadow Book (Globe
Pequot Press) and Jim Wilson's Landscaping With Wildflowers
(Houghton Mifflin, $21.95 paperback) would also be of help.
</P>
<P>
   You might start by sowing smaller areas with annual and
perennial types this fall to determine favorites and traits of
each.
</P>
<P>
   Trees that grow quickly can have weak wood and be susceptible to
wind damage. The Drummond red maple is one of the quicker growers
among the good shade trees for our area. Ours shot from 8 feet to
above a second-floor window in less than 10 years time, and spreads
30-something feet. This tree provides fairly dense shade, and only
shade-tolerant ground covers will thrive beneath the established
canopy. The red maple is a beautiful tree, however, and fall color
is often good. Life span is approximately 50 years.
</P>
<P>
   The bur oak is a deciduous, long-lived tree and a fairly fast
grower, for an oak. It does well here and produces acorns up to 2
inches long. You said your back yard is large, and this is a large
tree, maturing to approximately 80 feet in height and 50 feet in
width, but, of course, it will take some years before this size is
reached.
</P>
<P>
   The swamp chestnut oak tolerates sand or gumbo and has red fall
color. It is a slow-grower, however, and has a canopy of about 45
feet at maturity.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, you might study various landscapes with natives to
learn which shade and ornamental trees, shrubs, perennials and
bulbs as well as perennial and annual wildflowers would work and
which you would like in your garden. Make lists of your favorites.
Draw a large box representative of your back yard, then sketch
curving beds around the perimeter, leaving an area near the back
door for a deck or patio and a small- to medium-size lawn, if
wanted. Decide the best place for your shade tree, then mark spots
for smaller trees and shrubs. Then, as your budget allows, you can
actually build those beds.
</P>
<P>
   Sally and Andy Wasowski's books, Native Texas Plants:
Landscaping Region by Region (Gulf Publishing, $27.95) and Native
Texas Gardens: Maximum Beauty, Minimum Upkeep (Gulf Publishing,
$39.95), will give you ideas.
</P>
<P>
   Buffalo grass adapts best in areas with low rainfall, high
sunlight and less foot traffic. Therefore, it is not commonly used
as turf grass here. I would visit a site where it exists, study its
appearance and walk on it. If you know of none, contact a grass
company and inquire. Zoysia is another type of turf grass that you
might explore.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Mail garden questions to Kathy Huber, Garden Editor, Houston
Chronicle, P.O. Box 4260, Houston, Texas 77210. The bulk of mail
prevents individual replies to all unpublished letters.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
