<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-15 15:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9746 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KASHMIR-DISPUTE-HNS &LR;      06-15 1642
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KASHMIR-DISPUTE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLD INDIA-PAKISTAN FEUD TAKES A NEW TWIST FOR KASHMIRIS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MARION LLOYD 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SRINAGAR, India _ The gunmen waited until the Muslim villagers
were safely at the mosque before swooping down from their mountain
hide-out and massacring 23 Hindus in their homes. Only an
11-year-old boy survived after pretending to be dead while the
assailants torched the Hindu temple next door and fled.
</P>
<P>
   The Jan. 25 massacre in Wandhama village was one of several mass
attacks this year against Hindus in the northern Indian state of
Jammu and Kashmir, where pro-Islamic militants are fighting for
independence from mainly Hindu India. But the attacks have failed
in their main objective _ to paint the struggle along religious
lines.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, both Muslims and Hindus say it is not religion, but
rather politicians in Pakistan and India, who are to blame. And now
that both countries are declared nuclear powers, Kashmiris fear
they are caught in an increasingly perilous cross fire between the
hostile neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   ``India and Pakistan are greedy. They want land, not people, and
they would think nothing of dropping bombs here,'' said Gulam Ahmed
Bhat, a retired Muslim sign painter in Srinagar, the state's summer
capital. He said he was disillusioned with both countries and that
independence was the only option, a growing belief among the
residents of India's only Muslim-majority state.
</P>
<P>
   The attack in Wyndhama, just 13 miles north of Srinagar, was a
sign of the Indian government's failure to contain the violence,
which has claimed between 15,000 and 70,000 lives since Kashmiri
youths took up arms in 1989. The New Delhi government does not keep
records on civilian casualties but does on the 9,000 soldiers
killed in the conflict.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute over Kashmir, a third of which is controlled by
Pakistan, has been the primary source of tension between the
hostile neighbors since the subcontinent gained independence from
Britain in 1947.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the countries have fought three wars, two of them
over Kashmir, which Pakistan claims was illegally grafted onto
India at independence. But it took the demonstration of India and
Pakistan's nuclear capability to call world attention to the
troubled state.
</P>
<P>
   Last month's successful nuclear tests have intensified the
51-year dispute. The subsequent war of words between the two
fledgling nuclear powers prompted members of the United Nations
Security Council to call an emergency meeting June 4, in which they
urged a peaceful resolution of the conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Both countries have expressed willingness to use nuclear weapons
to defend their territory. Kashmiris fear that pledge may extend to
their disputed homeland, making them the first victims of a
potential nuclear war.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are slaves to the whims of India and Pakistan,'' said
17-year-old Adil Khan. ``But what about our lives. Does that not
mean anything?''
</P>
<P>
   The Indian government has refused to consider independence,
saying Kashmir voluntarily chose to join India and that most
residents support the status quo. Last week, India's government
rejected a proposal by the U.N. Security Council to serve as
mediators.
</P>
<P>
   But while the government has portrayed the conflict as an
attempt by Muslim extremists to impose their will on the majority,
the fighting has taken an equally harsh toll on Muslims, who have
borne the brunt of the Indian army's counterinsurgency tactics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our fathers are being tortured by the army, and we have no
food to eat, no money to pay our school fees,'' said 12-year-old
Mushtaq Ahmed Rather, from Nagbl village outside Srinagar. He said
his father was tortured by the army, which accused him of being a
militant, and was detained for three years without trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``The soldiers are always drunk, and they abuse our mothers and
our sisters,'' he charged.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, army officers barged into his brother's house at 5:30
a.m. and demanded to know where the militants were hiding. ``We
told them we don't know any militants, but they ransacked our house
and abused us,'' said Rather's sister-in-law, Ashai Kader.
</P>
<P>
   Other Muslims tell horror stories of whole families being shot
in their homes by soldiers and women being gang-raped as revenge
against militant attacks on army outposts. Many say militants are
guilty of similar atrocities, usually in revenge against Muslims
they believed have informed against them.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly every family has lost a relative in the fighting, which
has caused 70,000 Hindus to flee to the southern Hindu-dominated
area of Jammu and to New Delhi, the Indian capital, since 1989.
Those who remain live in fear, and the New Delhi government has
been forced to deploy thousands of soldiers to guard the scattered
Hindu enclaves.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rich men have fled, and only the poor people have stayed
behind,'' said Jawaharlal Mathoo, a Hindu whose sister was killed
in the massacre at Wandhama. Fifteen Indian soldiers are stationed
round the clock outside his modest brick house in nearby Tulmula
village, where he earns $75 a month as a plantation supervisor for
the Indian government.
</P>
<P>
   He said he didn't blame Muslims for the attack, because
``they're suffering too.''
</P>
<P>
   The fighting has devastated the economy of the Kashmir Valley, a
spectacular expanse of emerald rice fields and quaint villages
surrounded by snowcapped mountains.
</P>
<P>
   Tourism, once the third-largest industry, has practically
stopped since the rebel movement emerged in 1989. In 1988, 722,000
tourists visited the area, famous for its scenic Himalayan treks
and woolen handicrafts. The valley was also a favorite among Bombay
filmmakers, who shot the standard pastoral dance scenes found in
Hindi films in the valley's lush fields.
</P>
<P>
   In 1991 at the height of the violence, fewer than 7,000 tourists
arrived, most of them foreign. Filmmakers abandoned the valley,
choosing to pay higher prices for shooting in Switzerland. Nearly
all the hotels have been expropriated by the army for barracks and
offices, while most of the houseboat inns along Srinagar's Dal Lake
are vacant.
</P>
<P>
   The situation has improved slightly since the army began a
massive counteroffensive in 1994, chasing militants into the
mountains and rural areas. But the 10,000 tourists who visited
Kashmir last year were only a fraction of earlier arrivals.
</P>
<P>
   The government can't launch a major campaign to lure tourists
back until the danger subsides, said one tourism official who asked
to remain anonymous. But he said the government is offering
incentives for workers to renovate hotels and other facilities to
prepare for the tourists' eventual return.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a drop in violence in the mid-1990s around Srinagar, the
kidnapping of six foreign hikers in 1995 dashed hopes that the
valley was safe for tourists. The hikers, from the United States,
Britain, Norway and Germany, were abducted in three separate
incidents by what was believed to be a little known militant group.
After the Indian government refused to accede to the kidnappers'
demands to release 21 militants, the decapitated body of one of the
hostages, Norwegian Hans Christian Ostro, was found by the side of
a mountain road. The other five hostages were never released and
are believed to have been killed.
</P>
<P>
   The incident was condemned by pro-independence and pro-Pakistani
leaders, who claimed it was orchestrated by the Indian government
to discredit their movements internationally. The government denies
these claims.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the pervasive violence, however, many Kashmiris remain
sympathetic to the militants, whom they claim are the lesser of two
evils.
</P>
<P>
   When an Indian soldier used a metal club to break up a crowd of
Muslim youths talking to a reporter in downtown Srinagar, one
teen-ager remarked, ``See, that's the army's attitude, and they
claim the militants are violent.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``martyrs' graveyard'' in downtown Srinagar is filled with
women weeping for their lost sons and young men, paying homage to
their heroes.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were fighting for independence and they were right. It is
a noble cause,'' said Bilal Ahmed, a carpet salesmen whose two
militant cousins are buried in the graveyard.
</P>
<P>
   Ahmed condemned the militants who had surrendered and gone over
to the government's side. He claimed the renegades had ``made a
business'' of kidnapping Muslim civilians believed to be
sympathetic to the militants.
</P>
<P>
   Jan Bebe, a Muslim woman whose militant son was killed by the
army two years ago, said she hoped ``the mission my son led will be
accomplished.'' She came to pay respects to other fallen militants,
since ``the army would not give me my son's body.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, most Kashmiris blame both sides for the violence, and
believe their best hope for peace is to become an independent
country, despite critics' claims that a small, landlocked Kashmir
could never survive between behemoths China and India, and Pakistan
to the south.
</P>
<P>
   On June 4, pro-independence groups called a strike in Srinagar
to demand that the government allow them to decide their future
status through a referendum. Protesters carried signs reading ``We
want freedom'' and hurled rocks at Indian soldiers to signal their
discontent with Indian rule.
</P>
<P>
   They want the Indian government to comply with a 1948 U.N.
resolution calling for a referendum to let the state decide whether
to align with India or Pakistan. The residents also demand a third
option of independence on the referendum.
</P>
<P>
   But few expect that their demands will be met.
</P>
<P>
   ``For 50 years they've been promising us the right to determine
our fate,'' complained sign painter Bhat. ``What's to say anything
will change now?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Marion Lloyd is a free-lance journalist who wrote this for the
Houston Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
