<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-15 15:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9749 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KASHMIRE-SIDER-HNS &LR;      06-15 1233
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KASHMIRE-SIDER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    INTERNATIONAL PRESSURE UNLIKELY TO FORGE A RESOLUTION ON KASHMIR
RESOLUTION
 &HT;    
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MARION LLOYD 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SRINAGAR, India _ By declaring themselves nuclear powers, India
and Pakistan have raised the stakes in their decades-old rivalry
and sent alarmed world leaders scrambling to find a solution to the
countries' prime area of conflict, the disputed Himalayan territory
of Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
   But it will take more than international pressure to persuade
Pakistan and India to settle their differences and bury fears of a
potential nuclear war. Although Pakistan and India swapped
proposals last week, they seemed to have difficulties finding any
common ground, and they did not agree to talk.
</P>
<P>
   India gained control of two-thirds of the formerly princely
state of Jammu and Kashmir, and left Pakistan with the remaining
third after the subcontinent split at independence in 1947. India
called the region it controlled Jammu and Kashmir, while Pakistan
named its area Kashmir. Since then, Pakistan, which claims it was
robbed of its rightful control over Muslim-majority territory, has
demanded that India comply with a 1948 United Nations resolution
calling for a referendum to decide the territory's status.
</P>
<P>
   India has refused, and on June 7 the Indian government dismissed
as interference a U.N. Security Council offer to mediate in what it
argues is a bilateral issue.
</P>
<P>
   The Indian government also refused to submit to U.N. pressure
that it sign the Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty in the wake of last
month's nuclear tests by India and Pakistan. It accused the world
body of bias, pointing to the fact that the U.N. session was
chaired by China, Pakistan's longtime ally and the suspected source
of its nuclear technology. China, which, since 1959, has controlled
a swath of mostly unpopulated territory in Kashmir's northeast
sector following an agreement with Pakistan, has a vested interest
in the dispute.
</P>
<P>
   The conflict over the region has sparked two wars between India
and Pakistan since 1947 and claimed at least 15,000 lives since
1989, when pro-Islamic militants took up arms against the Indian
government.
</P>
<P>
   India blames Pakistan for the insurgency, saying the Pakistani
government provides arms and training for militants _ charges that
Pakistan denies. New Delhi also claims there is little mass support
for the militants' demands and that most Kashmiris want to remain
part of India.
</P>
<P>
   So why the fear of a referendum, ask pro-Pakistani and
pro-independence groups. They claim the Indian government brought
about the insurgency by refusing to grant Kashmiris the right to
self-determination, and, that if given the choice, the people would
overwhelmingly opt to secede from India. By using force to squash
resistance movements in the early 1980s, the Indian government
created the atmosphere for armed conflict, they argue. India then
exacerbated the violence by ordering the army to crush the
insurgency at any cost, critics said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government of India used violence to crush our nonviolent
resistance, so the Kashmiri youths took up guns,'' said Yasin
Malik, the former leader of the Jammu and Kashmir Liberation Front,
the first of about a dozen militant groups to emerge in the region.
``Now they commit atrocities with the message `behave or you will
have to face this.'''
</P>
<P>
   Malik, who spent seven years in jail on conspiracy charges
before his release in 1994, has since founded a political wing of
the liberation front to push for a peaceful resolution. He claims
as many as 70,000 people have been killed in the fighting _ five
times the official figure of 15,000 _ since 1989 and argues that
independence from India and Pakistan is the only way to achieve a
lasting peace while protecting the interests of the state's diverse
religious groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people of Kashmir are by nature anti-Indian,'' said Malik.
``They will never reconcile with the side of the Indians.'' He said
he opposed joining with Pakistan, because he said they
discriminated against religious minorities. ``They believe in the
Islamic philosophy but they must learn to respect individual
values.''
</P>
<P>
   Among anti-India leaders, the pro-independence stand articulated
by Malik is dominant. But a few members of the All Parties Huriyet
Conference, the alliance of opposition parties to which he belongs,
support joining Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   Sayed Shah Ali Gilani, the current chairman of the congress,
favors sticking with the original U.N. proposal for a referendum,
which did not include independence as an option.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as the Kashmir problem is concerned, it took place by
the partition of united India, the basis for which is a two-nation
theory,'' he said. But he said that if other secessionist leaders
insisted on putting independence on the ballot, he would accept it.
</P>
<P>
   Indian loyalists claim such a vote would jeopardize the
territorial integrity of India by encouraging separatist movements
in other parts of the country, particularly in the far eastern
states, which are virtually cut off from the rest of the country.
They further argue India's accession of Kashmir was legal and that
residents have no claim toward independence.
</P>
<P>
   India would win a referendum because most Kashmiris blame
Pakistan for fueling the violence, said Javaid Shah, a former
militant leader who was granted amnesty after he renounced the
fight in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the time, they told us to take up arms to protect Islam and
that it was a jihad (holy war),'' said Shah, who was elected to the
state's legislative assembly last year on a platform of peace and
economic development. ``But ultimately I realized that Islam was
not in decline and that we were creating needless violence.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that he had firsthand knowledge that Pakistan was
funding the insurgents. ``Only if Pakistan stops providing guns and
money will the fighting stop,'' he said, adding ``the international
community has the power to make that happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Moderates say both sides will have to compromise if the violence
is to be stopped. Kashmir's home minister, Ali Mohammed Sager,
argues for a return to the partial autonomy granted Jammu and
Kashmir in the early years after the territory's Hindu ruler agreed
to merge with newly independent India. The state's ``special
status'' was later revoked in 1954 with the approval of Kashmir's
pro-Indian chief minister, Bakshi Ghulam Muhammed.
</P>
<P>
   Such an arrangement would please both independence groups and
the state's Hindu minority, most of whom support remaining part of
India, Sager said. However, he acknowledged that Pakistan would
probably resist such a move, since it would mean an end to
Islamabad's hopes of seeing a united Muslim state.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pakistan is not reconciling the situation, thinking wherever
there are Muslims they are a part of Pakistan,'' he said. ``They
are under the illusion that they are the rulers of the whole
Islamic world.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, fears of nuclear confrontation with India might prompt
Pakistani leaders to rethink their demands, he argued.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Kashmiris are not fundamentalists by nature, nor are they
violent,'' he said. ``Now what they really want is development, and
they want peace.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Marion Lloyd is a free-lance journalist who wrote this for the
Houston Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
