<HEADLINE>
MAKING EUROPEAN TRIP STUMBLE-FREE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By HARRY SHATTUCK 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Based on my experiences during a just-completed hiatus across
the right pond, every European seems addicted to two material
possessions: a bicycle and a cellular phone.
</P>
<P>
   It's best to stay well out of harm's way when they are used
conjunctively.
</P>
<P>
   Even more precarious is the increasingly popular
cell-phone/in-line skate combo. The latter is so much the rage that
my favorite lasting image is of a 2-year-old wearing skates and
peering from a baby carriage beside Lake Lucerne in Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
   In time, I'll share some adventures _ and misadventures _ from a
two-week romp around Germany, Austria and Switzerland. For now,
here are random tips that may help in planning your trip or
avoiding potential pitfalls.
</P>
<P>
   Currency exchange is a frequent topic of debate for
international travelers. An increasing number swear by ATMs; others
warn about problems interpreting instructions written in unfamiliar
languages and cite instances of machines ``swallowing'' their cards
when they tarried too long in the translation. Credit card
purchases can provide a dependable exchange rate. And you can
almost always count on a full-service bank offering a more
favorable rate than conveniently located counters in airports and
train stations.
</P>
<P>
   Call me old-fashioned, but I still carry travelers' checks. They
can be secured in several currencies _ including French and Swiss
francs, British pounds and Deutsche marks _ prior to leaving home.
Once abroad, in contrast to the time-consuming paperwork and fees
associated with converting travelers' checks issued in U.S. dollar
denominations, they can be cashed or used for direct payments in
many hotels, restaurants and shops.
</P>
<P>
   An especially good deal: The American Automobile Association
offers foreign-denomination travelers' checks to its members at no
charge. You pay only the set exchange rate _ and AAA's rates are
competitive _ and, in theory, no commission or fee when cashing the
checks.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, no system is foolproof. Near the end of this trip, a desk
clerk at one Lake Constance-area hotel in Germany assured me with a
smile that he would happily cash my 100-mark check. I gave my
signature, and he handed me a 50-mark bill and two 20s. ``We keep
10 marks,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The lesson: Inquire in advance about charges before initiating
any transaction. Acquaintances cite similar inconsistencies in
other countries.
</P>
<P>
   I recommend exchanging a limited amount of cash, too, before
leaving home for international travel. But be aware that several
European countries have printed new currency in recent years, and
the bills look nothing like their predecessors. Yet at least one
major Houston bank is still issuing old Deutsche mark bills, as I
learned in dismay when they were rejected at a Munich restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   ``What can I do?'' I asked the English-speaking concierge at my
hotel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Throw them away,'' he replied. ``They are worthless.''
</P>
<P>
   Good thing I didn't listen. Instead, I visited a Munich bank,
and the teller explained, ``Because these bills are now out of
circulation, many businesses won't take them. But any bank will
exchange them evenly for the newer bills.''
</P>
<P>
   The same proved true in Switzerland. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Multiday, multicountry rail passes purchased in the United
States remain an economical and convenient way to move around
Europe. But know exactly which specific pass you are buying and how
you intend to use it, or risk an additional expense as incurred by
dozens of travelers with whom I shared a train from Munich to
Lucerne.
</P>
<P>
   These individuals had purchased a basic Europass _ among the
most popular alternatives _ valid for unlimited first-class rail
travel in five countries, including Germany and Switzerland. But
this particular train made one quick stop in Bregenz, Austria. And
travel in Austria with a Europass requires a supplementary payment.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that none of these Europass holders intended to
depart the train in Bregenz. A strictly-by-the-book conductor
offered two options: Exit the train before leaving Germany or fork
over more cash.
</P>
<P>
   More tips:
</P>
<P>
   _ Packing light is always advisable. But if you must take along
several bags _ and I'm now admonishing the face in the mirror _
resist a taxi driver's invitation to stuff them all in the trunk of
his vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   Policies vary even within nations, but many European taxi fare
structures _ if such a thing exists _ include up to a $2 charge for
each item stowed in the trunk. And you are placed at a distinct
competitive disadvantage during the inevitable end-of-trip dispute
with the driver who holds your luggage hostage as he invents and
explains other unexpected charges.
</P>
<P>
   _ One of the pleasures associated with staying in small central
European hotels has always been the scarcity of room televisions,
facilitating a more complete escape from the outer world. No more.
Everybody has discovered cable. And CNN International. For about
$15 an hour, you can even access the Internet and send or receive
e-mail on some larger lodgings' in-room TVs.
</P>
<P>
   I figure next time I visit, the Swiss and Germans, having
abandoned cell phones, will be sending e-mail on computers attached
to their bicycles. Or baby carriages.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
