u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ASTROS-HNS &LR;      06-15 0867
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Astros end Red scare, strike late to beat Shaw
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JOSEPH DUARTE &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
CINCINNATI _ As far as the Astros are concerned, the first eight
innings of a game are merely a formality. Things don't count until
the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   For the third time in the past week, the Astros waited until
last call to pull out a victory. Facing one of the National
League's toughest closers, they rallied for five runs off
Cincinnati's Jeff Shaw over the final two innings for a 6-3 victory
in 10 innings Sunday afternoon at Cinergy Field.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Spiers went 4-for-5, including a leadoff double that
sparked a two-run rally by the Astros in the ninth and a two-run
homer off Shaw in the 10th that enabled the Astros to notch their
first win in three tries during this four-game series.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros, who rallied in the ninth for two consecutive
victories against Detroit last week, won for only the second time
in six extra-inning games this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really haven't swung the bat well at all on the road trip
except for the eighth and ninth innings of every game,'' said
Astros first baseman Jeff Bagwell, who had two hits. ``That's not
usually how you want to have it done. We've been fortunate to come
back three times.''
</P>
<P>
   It didn't appear the Astros would get the chance for another
comeback Sunday after Cincinnati rallied for two runs in the eighth
for a 3-1 lead and sent Shaw to the mound in the ninth. He entered
with a 0.97 ERA _ best among NL closers _ and had not allowed an
earned run in his previous 25 innings.
</P>
<P>
   That streak ended in a hurry.
</P>
<P>
   Spiers opened the floodgates with a leadoff double, and Bagwell
followed with a one-out RBI single that sliced the Reds' lead to
3-2. Bagwell advanced to third on a single by Moises Alou, his
third hit of the game, and scored when Reds shortstop Barry Larkin
hurried the flip to second while trying to turn a double play on a
soft grounder by Carl Everett.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of going for the save, Shaw was fighting for the win. He
got neither.
</P>
<P>
   Ricky Gutierrez walked to begin the Astros' 10th, stole second
and scored on Craig Biggio's single to center field for the
go-ahead run.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a huge comeback,'' Biggio said. ``When you lose the
first two games of the series, their guys are pitching well, and
suddenly they have a closer with an ERA of nothing on the mound, it
makes it tough. We battled and finally got some runs.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros weren't finished as Spiers sent a 2-1 pitch into the
right-field stands for his second home run of the season. Spiers,
who at one point this season was batting .180, matched a career
high with four hits and came within a triple of hitting for the
cycle. He is batting .360 in his last 23 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look for that kind of game every day,'' Spiers said of his
first four-hit game since last September against San Francisco.
``It was a big win for us, getting down like we did and coming
back. I wouldn't say it was a must win, but it felt like a
pick-me-up. We needed that. Those are the kinds of games you need
to have during the course of the season if you are going to do
anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Billy Wagner (1-2) escaped a jam in the ninth, and after
allowing a leadoff single to Pat Watkins in the 10th, struck out
the final three batters.
</P>
<P>
   Astros righthander Sean Bergman kept the Reds scoreless for five
innings before Eddie Taubensee homered to lead off the sixth.
Bergman allowed two runs and eight hits in 7 innings and struck out
a season-high seven. He worked out of threats in the second and
fourth innings, when the Reds put two runners on base.
</P>
<P>
   Bergman's counterpart, Cincinnati righthander Scott Winchester,
was just as impressive. Winchester, who hadn't struck out more than
three batters in his previous nine major-league starts, had a
three-hitter and a career-high seven strikeouts before being
replaced to begin the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't until Winchester was removed that the Astros managed
to get on the scoreboard. Facing reliever Scott Sullivan, Alou hit
his 15th home run of the season and third in six games to forge a
1-1 in the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   ``Outside of Alou's home run, I'm not sure we hit any balls hard
for seven or eight innings. It looked feeble,'' Astros manager
Larry Dierker said. ``I hope this helps shake a few guys out (of
their slumps). Honestly, I don't think we are playing our best
baseball right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Cincinnati regained the lead in the eighth on Eduardo Perez's
two-run, bases-loaded single off Mike Magnante. The Reds started
the uprising when Dmitri Young doubled to left-center field with
one out off Bergman and Bret Boone singled to the mound, the ball
deflecting off Magnante's glove. Magnante walked Melvin Nieves on
four pitches to load the bases and set up Perez's pinch-hit single.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly afterward, the Astros did what they do best. Wait until
the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it speaks a lot about the character of this club,''
said Dierker, whose team is 5-20 when trailing after the eighth
inning. ``But I also think it also says we haven't been quite as
good for the first eight innings like we were earlier this year.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
