<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN--BULLS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Jordan reinforces legend as Bulls lengthen title run
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By EDDIE SEFKO &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
SALT LAKE CITY _ If this was farewell, Michael Jordan did more than
just fare well. He went out like the true master he is.
</P>
<P>
   And if this is the end of the line for the Chicago Bulls as the
sports world has come to know them, they made sure nobody can
question their status as one of the greatest dynasties in NBA
history.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan hit his last two shots, including an 18-footer with 5.2
seconds left after he had stripped Utah's Karl Malone, and the
Bulls earned a hard-fought 87-86 victory to win the NBA
championship Sunday night at the Delta Center.
</P>
<P>
   And now, the Bulls know the meaning of sixcess. Their 4-2 win in
the Finals gave them their sixth title _ and second three-peat _ in
the past eight years. For Jordan, championships have come in the
past six consecutive seasons he started with the Bulls.
</P>
<P>
   With sidekick Scottie Pippen hindered by a painful back injury,
Jordan took the Bulls on his shoulders and escorted them to
greatness. He had 45 points, including the Bulls' last eight when
they overcame an 83-79 deficit in the final 2:10. And when John
Stockton's 3-pointer at the buzzer missed, the Bulls were dancing _
maybe last-dancing _ around the Delta Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``Michael's a guy who always comes through in the clutch,''
Bulls coach Phil Jackson said. ``He's a real-life hero. Last year
in the fifth game (of the Finals), I didn't think he could top
that. But I think this is the greatest moment he's ever had.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan's effort earned him a unanimous Most Valuable Player vote
for the Finals. And it came under difficult circumstances. The Jazz
had the lead virtually throughout the final three quarters. But it
never got more than six points ahead. And when the door cracked for
a Michael Moment, he delivered.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the toughest route, the toughest challenge we've had in
the six championships we've won,'' Jordan said. ``That was part of
the challenge. After Game 5, there were some negative thoughts. But
I think we all realized that if we wanted to win the sixth title,
we were going to have to play our best game and we were going to
have to do it in Utah.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan in particular responded.
</P>
<P>
   Stockton's 3-pointer with 41.9 seconds left put the Jazz ahead
86-83. Those were the only points the Jazz scored in the final 2:30
as the Chicago defense dug in. But Jordan countered with a driving
bucket with 36 seconds to play. Before that shot, he had been
2-for-8 from the field in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Then, Jordan again showed he's no one-trick pony. The Jazz tried
to get the ball to Malone in the low post. Malone was having a
monster game with 31 points, 11 rebounds and seven assists. But as
Malone received the ball from Stockton, Jordan stopped tracking
Jeff Hornacek and snuck behind Malone on his right side and made a
clean steal.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than call timeout, Jordan attacked. He got the ball in
one of his favorite spots, near the 3-point line just to the left
of the top of the circle. He started to drive on Bryon Russell,
then saw Russell slip slightly just after he had reached in to try
to disrupt Jordan's drive.
</P>
<P>
   That was all it took. Jordan was wide-open and swished the
18-footer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd been trying to double-team him,'' he said of the steal
against Malone. ``Hornacek never really cleared, and I was able to
come up from behind. Once I got the ball, I saw 18 seconds left,
and I knew I couldn't call timeout and give them a chance to set up
their defense. It was a do-or-die situation. I let the clock tick
until I had the court set up the way I wanted it. As soon as
Russell reached, I pulled up.''
</P>
<P>
   And Utah, which had forced Game 6 with a gritty 83-81 win Friday
in Chicago, had to settle for second-best for the second year in a
row.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have a terrific team, and he (Jordan) is a terrific
player,'' said Utah coach Jerry Sloan. ``I think the thing that
hurt us was that we had some turnovers down the stretch, and you
can't afford to give this team second chances, because you know
Michael is going to make the plays.''
</P>
<P>
   And if this is Jordan's last game?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everybody knows how he should be remembered,'' Sloan
said. ``He's the best player that's ever played the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Nothing he did Sunday would change Sloan's opinion.
</P>
<P>
   After Jordan's shot, the Jazz had slightly more than five
seconds to try to pull out the win. But Stockton's 3-pointer after
he used a high screen hit the front of the rim. It was short all
the way, and he didn't get a home-court bounce off the rim.
</P>
<P>
   Then the celebration began. And so did the questions about the
Bulls' future.
</P>
<P>
   ``How sweet it is,'' Jackson said. ``It was a wonderful win for
us. They put up a heck of a fight.''
</P>
<P>
   And about the future?
</P>
<P>
   ``The reality is we planned this as our last year,'' Jackson
said. ``Right now, we're celebrating that way. All we can do is
celebrate. Unless something comes out of left field, I don't expect
to see us back here again. It's been a great run.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan gave no clues about his intentions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a gut feeling,'' Jordan said. ``When I walked away the
first time (for a short-lived baseball career), it was a feeling.
When the time comes and I walk away, I hope nobody will think less
of me.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Stockton: ``He's going to be back. Scottie's going to be
back. And Dennis (Rodman). And Phil. I'm tired of hearing all that.
But it worked for them.''
</P>
<P>
   There were some crazy moments early in the game. First, the
Bulls found out what life without Pippen would be like. He left the
game with 4:56 to go in the first quarter and did not return in the
first half.
</P>
<P>
   Pippen looked mobile and active as the game began. He dunked
Chicago's first points after a lob pass from Ron Harper. But it
wasn't long before Pippen was favoring his back. Without him, Bulls
such as Jud Buechler and Bill Wennington were leaned on to produce.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-15-98 1531EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
