r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHOOL-SHOOTINGS-HNS &LR;      06-15 0563
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-SHOOTINGS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHOOLS TAKE STEPS TO CURB THREAT OF GUN VIOLENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RICK KARLIN  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Students returning to Rensselaer Junior-Senior
High School next year may have a new safety drill. Administrators
are considering having students practice how they would respond if
a gunman were to show up at school.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of recent deadly shootings at schools in Arkansas,
Kentucky, Mississippi and Oregon, students are facing a climate of
heightened security. Even idle talk of violence can result in
suspensions or formal charges as educators grapple with how to
respond to the threats without causing undue alarm.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fear is, you'll become the next poster boy for everything
that is wrong,'' said Blaise Salerno, superintendent of the
Guilderland school system in upstate New York. ``Everybody in the
administrations are just getting blitzed if you don't take
everything seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   But can schools go too far, creating a climate of fear? There is
concern a crackdown will lead to a spate of lawsuits for throwing
out students who don't plan to act on their statements.
</P>
<P>
   That happened with the zero-tolerance policies schools have
instituted regarding drugs. In some cases, children were suspended
for taking Advil or Midol to school. Those suspensions led to
several lawsuits, said Renee Williams, spokeswoman for the National
School Boards Association in Alexandria, Va.
</P>
<P>
   Students themselves are sometimes confused by the latest
crackdown.
</P>
<P>
   A Rensselaer student was recently suspended for drawing a
cartoon showing a student shooting a teacher. Soon after, school
officials held an assembly to explain their new policy against even
the most casual threats of violence. After the meeting, a couple of
students tested the policy and joked about going home and getting
guns. They too, were suspended.
</P>
<P>
   In years past, violent cartoons or threats made in jest would
have meant, ``a detention or two,'' said Adam Mancini, a
seventh-grader at Rensselaer.
</P>
<P>
   Said Rensselaer Principal Mike Dawkins: ``We don't have the
luxury to make the judgments as to whether you meant what you
said.''
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, while increasing school violence has been a concern
for much of the 1990s, statistics do not point to any sudden,
short-term tidal wave of violence, despite the isolated but highly
publicized shootings.
</P>
<P>
   Still, these incidents prompt some experts to call for action.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a wake-up call,'' said Kevin Dwyer, spokesman for the
National Association of School Psychologists.
</P>
<P>
   Dwyer's organization has long maintained that schools don't have
enough psychologists and others who can weave a social safety net
for troubled children. And he worries that punitive, zero-tolerance
policies won't address underlying problems facing students who
fight or make threats.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to talk more about solutions, more about long-term
kinds of planning,'' Dwyer said.
</P>
<P>
   But, he added, the shootings of the past few months have, if
nothing else, focused attention on school violence and behavior
problems in general.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have gotten calls from the National Association of
Elementary School Principals and American Association of School
Administrators, asking `What should we be doing?' This is really a
very positive change.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-15-98 1533EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980615.0196 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-15 15:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9795 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOLDWATER-AZR &LR;      06-15 1762
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOLDWATER-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOLDWATER'S LAST DAYS: FEARLESS, FUNNY UNTIL END, WIFE RECALLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MAUREEN WEST  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; ``EDITOR'S NOTE: In her first major interview since her
89-year-old husband's death May 29,'' ``Susan Goldwater talks in
detail about his final days and months''.
</P>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ ``You're my wife, right?''
</P>
<P>
   Barry Goldwater was recovering from a major stroke that had
caused swelling in the frontal lobe of his brain.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what they tell me,'' answered Susan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, if you weren't, I'd ask you to marry me anyway,'' he
replied.
</P>
<P>
   That was 1996. As his mental and physical condition deteriorated
over the following two years, he never lost his ability to come up
with a humorous twist or a gentlemanly compliment to cover the
confusions and disorientations of his stroke-induced disorder,
which goes by the name of multi-infarct dementia.
</P>
<P>
   There would be moments when he couldn't quite place Susan
immediately. But he would remember in detail conversations of 25 or
50 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   He spent most of those days looking out over the Phoenix skyline
from the native rock home atop a hill near 44th Street and McDonald
Drive. There, he had lived most of his adult life _ seven years of
it with Susan, his second wife.
</P>
<P>
   She was a nurse who showed up at his door one day to take his
blood pressure.
</P>
<P>
   Once they got to know each other, she assumed the task of
finding him a suitable woman friend his age. Playing matchmaker for
one of Arizona's crustiest characters proved too much for her
social Rolodex.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, what about you?'' he asked her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm too young,'' she replied, not wanting to say that he was
too old.
</P>
<P>
   He looked her up and down.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, you're not that young,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   So that was that, and they were married 2{ years later. That was
almost seven years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Very, you know, Barry-like,'' is the best way she can describe
the man she married.
</P>
<P>
   Through most of last year, standing or sitting at the great
picture windows of his ranchlike home, he watched the construction
of Bank One Ballpark in the distance, and worried that its massive
bulk might mar the cityscape. But he loved baseball, so he let it
go.
</P>
<P>
   He built dozens of model airplanes and ships, painting them in
meticulous detail _ a skill that grew less perfect in his last
year. He knew the specifications of the planes and had flown the
real versions of most of them.
</P>
<P>
   His old photo lab had been turned into a miniature factory for
the mass production of these symbols of his highest-flying days. He
had, after all, almost single-handedly remodeled the American
military as the powerful chairman of the Senate Armed Services
Committee.
</P>
<P>
   He kept a busy schedule of seeing visitors and answering letters
from his command post in the living room. He went for almost daily
car rides with certified nursing assistant Joel Carey, his personal
caregiver and designated driver. They went cruising for milkshakes
and to see the sights.
</P>
<P>
   ``You got any money?'' he would ask Carey as they left.
</P>
<P>
   ``That goddamned Susan never leaves me any,'' he would quip.
</P>
<P>
   ``He never, ever got too ill to kid,'' Carey said. For much of
the past two years Goldwater used a walker. He didn't use a
wheelchair until the final few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   About six months ago, a change came over the senator and former
presidential candidate. He didn't challenge Susan and his
caregivers at every turn or want to go out for a drive as often.
One morning he didn't even want to get out of bed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you giving up?'' Susan asked him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Giving up on what?'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``On just pushing through, being up and about and living. Some
people give up and want to die,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hell, no! I love life,'' he said. Susan Goldwater said that he
meant it with deep sincerity. But she believes he was making a
transition to a new place. He was doing the hard spiritual work of
preparing himself.
</P>
<P>
   He became very selective in seeing visitors, preferring to spend
time with his brother and sister and a few old friends and
political associates. His world was narrowing. He stopped going for
rides altogether, and as the months went by lost interest in
answering his mail and even in making airplanes and ships.
</P>
<P>
   The aperture of his world view _ and it had been a wide one _
closed ever more as he curled inward to a world of comfort and
loving care.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a naturally occurring part of life,'' Susan said. ``At
the beginning of life a baby wants comfort and love and nurturing.
That's what we want at the end, too. And that is what we gave to
Barry.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the caregivers really understood what Barry was doing,
there was an effort to get him up and active. They even considered
some kind of group therapy _ for about 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was painful to think that he might become bedridden, so we
tried not to let that happen,'' Susan said.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Gillian Hamilton, who works at Hospice of the Valley,
finally suggested that they simply let the senator do as he had
always done _ whatever he wanted to do. That worked best.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Goldwater, executive director of Hospice of the Valley,
was getting a lesson in end-of-life care from another perspective.
She was developing a new awe for the energy and time it takes to
care well for someone, even someone with great resources. For
others, she realized, more needs to be done somehow.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I didn't have this round-the-clock support, I don't know
what I would have done,'' said the energetic 58-year-old.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``I'm not the average spouse of an 85-to-89-year-old _ the
average spouse would be 75 to 85 and would not be a hospice worker
with all these resources and knowledge,'' she said. ``I can
understand why depression would enter in _ why there would be
desperation and disorganization.'' The wheels were spinning in the
professional part of her mind but she hasn't a plan or solution
yet.
</P>
<P>
   During the last two months, the senator spent more time in bed.
His caregivers propped up his bedding so he could look out toward
downtown.
</P>
<P>
   ``His Valley,'' the family called it.
</P>
<P>
   He watched political hearings on C-SPAN and some sporting
events. In the final weeks his attention turned to shows about
nature. Often, he just observed the native landscape surrounding
his home.
</P>
<P>
   ``He adapted to every new part of his life, even in these last
days,'' Susan observed. He accepted the mission ahead.
</P>
<P>
   A month or so before his death he became more articulate than he
had been in days before. She asked: ``Are you frightened about
anything coming to this point in your life?''
</P>
<P>
   He looked at her with calm surprise: ``Frightened? I don't think
I've been frightened of anything in my whole life.''
</P>
<P>
   It was genuine, Susan said. ``There was no question in my mind
that he meant that. I think he was dealing with what was coming,
and I believe he knew.
</P>
<P>
   ``But he was not frightened. I don't think he was delighted
either. He was not one of those people who is going to fold his
hands across his chest and say he's happy to go meet his Lord. That
was not who Barry was. I think he would much rather have lived.''
</P>
<P>
   But he was a realist, she continued.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you were, say, climbing Everest, Barry would be the type to
see the storm coming and know when to tell the guys to go back down
the slope. He would want to keep climbing, but know it's time to
head down. I think he faced that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Barry was working through a lot of undefinable issues
in his own soul during the last week of his life. We watched him
when he was in bed _ he was more peaceful than he'd been in the
previous month. I think he was working things out.''
</P>
<P>
   She walked into the living room one day to see him sitting in a
well-worn leather chair silently holding the hand of his 4-year-old
step-granddaughter, Rebecca, who enjoyed helping the nurse by using
a play stethoscope to take the senator's vital signs.
</P>
<P>
   Those vital signs started on a long glide path downward in the
last week of his life, and the family gathered around. But the
89-year-old Arizonan was, to the eyes of Susan Goldwater, totally
happy and peaceful. She watched and listened closely. He was, she
believes, mentally flying over his favorite lands in northern
Arizona, or traveling those parts again with his beloved mother,
Josephine _ Arizona's pioneer nurse.
</P>
<P>
   The thought of flying over Arizona was a comfort to Susan, too.
Her favorite memories of Barry are of long plane flights with him
over the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``He would know every rock down there, and have stories about
it. To me, he was a part of the landscape,'' she said. And always a
stubborn part of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``He, of course, would have wanted to choose his last moment,
and I believe he did. I think he made a decision the morning he
died. I saw it,'' she said. ``He had been quietly winding down in
terms of his vital signs. Then his eyes opened a little and that
blue was really showing. Then he closed his eyes very tight _ the
way he made a face sometimes when he was making a decision. I
believe I saw Barry deciding to let go. I could feel his spirit
just soaring away.''
</P>
<P>
   He died shortly after sunrise May 29, on a day of unusual winds
and cool temperatures. Good tail winds, one might say, for an easy
flight north over the canyons.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks have passed.
</P>
<P>
   There are now hundreds of letters and notes in piles on the
tables of the Goldwater home. Susan and other family members have
them sorted into piles: answered, read but not answered, not read,
and letters so dear that they must be read again. Some are just
addressed to ``The Goldwater Family, Phoenix, Arizona.'' She reads
them as a comfort.
</P>
<P>
   Joel Carey is still helping the household cope with the change.
After two years, he has become an unofficial member of the family.
On Friday he was helping Susan and her 35-year-old daughter, Samara
Hutman, sort through the letters from princes and regular guys.
Barry was both, they agreed by the stories they remember as they
sorted.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; She will start returning to her duties at Hospice of the Valley
this week, having learned again things she has learned several
times before: that death is a personal experience, not a medical
event, and that death can be and should be peaceful and
comfortable.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is nothing that can't be managed at home,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Susan will stay in that home for now. She doesn't know what she
will do with the leftover time _ the hole. But she has books to
read, she says. And letters to write. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
