<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRACTICAL-TRAVELER-2TAKES-$ADV21-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOARDING PASSES TAKE A NOSEDIVE  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 21) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.J.)   (af)  
 By BETSY WADE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Advance boarding passes are becoming relics. Tim Smith, a
spokesman for American Airlines, which stopped issuing them June 1,
said they actually became useless almost two years ago, after the
July 1996 explosion aboard a Trans World Airlines plane off Long
Island.
</P>
<P>
   The government quickly tightened security regulations then, and
all passengers are now required to go to an airport counter to
present photo identification before boarding any flight.
</P>
<P>
   As a traveler, I did not grasp that the game was up until early
this year, when I flew from New York to Miami on the briefly
rejuvenated Pan Am. A friend and I arrived at the airport in good
time, but found a snaking line. If we had boarding passes, we were
told, we could go straight to the gate.
</P>
<P>
   We did have advance boarding passes, and seat assignments,
courtesy of our travel agent. But at the gate, we were told the
passes, despite their labels, were not boarding passes: only the
agent at the airport could issue boarding passes that were valid.
</P>
<P>
   These days travel agents cannot issue advance boarding passes,
and most airlines have stopped issuing them entirely. Security is
not the only reason: advance boarding passes were formerly issued
to overseas travelers, even though they were subject to passport
control long before the TWA explosion.
</P>
<P>
   The other blow to the boarding pass is the airlines' rising use
of so-called electronic tickets, whereby the ``ticket'' is only a
record in the airline's computer system, and a boarding pass is
issued when the passenger appears at the airport and presents
identification, usually including the credit card that was used to
buy the ``ticket.''
</P>
<P>
   As the airlines have pressed their ticketless tickets _ American
says they now constitute 50 percent of sales where there is a
choice _ the boarding pass has lost another round.
</P>
<P>
   This is a situation in transition. Northwest stopped issuing
advance boarding passes last November; Continental followed.
American and TWA, which both stopped June 1, and United, which
stopped June 8, are the most recent. US Airways announced on June
12 that it would stop providing advance boarding passes on July 7.
Delta was still providing them domestically as of June 15, but a
change seemed imminent.
</P>
<P>
   The black hole at the center of this shift is the question
whether a particular seat is being held for the traveler, or if the
traveler is merely one of 250 people planning to board a
150-passenger plane. The advance boarding pass usually gave the
seat number, and families traveling together clutched those passes
like security blankets, as one airline employee said.
</P>
<P>
   The passes with seat numbers were a bulwark against being
separated from the children or, worst of all, being left behind.
</P>
<P>
   The airlines report that boarding is no more harried than
before, but the change is still new.
</P>
<P>
   For vacationers, as opposed to executives hurrying to a
conference, the issue then becomes how early can a seat assignment
be given, and what documentation of this assignment is available in
the likely event of overbooking?
</P>
<P>
   The time period during which seat assignments are made in
advance varies. The period starts when a line's computer system
creates a diagram of the cabin for a particular flight. The
computer model will have certain choice seats marked out that will
never be assigned until just before the flight because they are
held for travelers who book late and therefore pay the highest
price, even in the coach section.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Here are the advance time periods reported by the seven major
United States airlines:
</P>
<P>
   Continental will provide a seat assignment 335 days in advance
of a flight.
</P>
<P>
   United, 11 months.
</P>
<P>
   American, 331 days.
</P>
<P>
   US Airways, 130 days. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Northwest, 90 days.
</P>
<P>
   TWA, 90 days.
</P>
<P>
   Delta, 30 days.
</P>
<P>
   Any early purchaser of a ticket who is concerned about seat
location, whether the ticket is bought from a travel agent or from
an airline, should ask for a seat assignment at the time the deal
is made.
</P>
<P>
   If the airline says it is too early, the passenger should then
ask if a seat preference can be recorded, for example, two aisle
seats across from each other. Not all airlines will accept
preferences.
</P>
<P>
   The next question is: If I cannot enter a preference, or I
forget to, will the computer take care of this and pop my
reservation into a specific seat when the window period opens?
Generally not, although some airline officials wobbled in their
answers.
</P>
<P>
   For a ticket bought before seat assignments are accepted _ a
situation more likely at Delta, Northwest and TWA than at the four
others _ the traveler should call promptly when seat assignments
are possible. Because the going and return dates are different, it
may take two telephone calls to get a specific seat in each
direction.
</P>
<P>
   A number of scenarios were put before the airline people. For
example, suppose a traveler forgets to call at the right time to
get a seat assignment and then the flight is overbooked? Is this
traveler at a disadvantage compared with the traveler who has an
assignment and a fax or a memo with the number on it? Generally the
answer was yes.
</P>
<P>
   The airline spokesmen emphasized that so long as passengers
check in ahead of deadline _ 30 minutes or so before flight time,
when all remaining seat assignments are released _ they should get
on the flight. But they agreed that lines get long and people with
no seat assignments are sometimes last.
</P>
<P>
   The seat assignment period is the moment when the travel agent
is the passenger's best friend: the agent has messages that pop up
in the computer that should ward off the memory failure that flesh
is heir to. Better yet, the agent can then send the traveler a
modified itinerary that will list the seat numbers for all legs.
That at least is something to hold in the hand when push comes to
shove.
</P>
<P>
   The seat-assignment issue is tightly knitted into the paperless
ticket. These bookings, which can be made from a cell phone on the
way to the airport and require no physical delivery, are far more
popular with business travelers than with others.
</P>
<P>
   Bernice Rosmarin, director of special projects at Stratton
Travel in Franklin Lakes, N.J., said a few months ago that she had
not found ``one leisure client so far'' willing to accept a
paperless ticket. Now she says she has found one or two among the
30 percent of her clients who are leisure travelers.
</P>
<P>
   The paperless system has smoothed out, she said. ``But I feel as
if we have taken 20 steps backward,'' she added. ``There are a lot
of people who have never flown before who take a flight and they
want something to hold in their hands.'' They may indeed get a
ticket to hold, but they are unlikely ever to see an advance
boarding pass.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
