<SLUG> BC-HEALTH-WATCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOPE AND HEART 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Wis.)  (lh) 
 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Disease is depressing; depression complicates recovery from
disease. That vicious circle has proved especially intractable for
older people who have severe coronary problems, compounded by the
fact that the main class of antidepressant drugs used in the last
20 years often made heart conditions worse.
</P>
<P>
   Now, it appears that newer antidepressants, including Prozac,
may be safer for people with heart disease, a study published last
month in the American Journal of Psychiatry says.
</P>
<P>
   The study, led by Dr. Stephen Roose of Columbia University,
followed 87 patients who had severe heart disease and severe
depression. Three-quarters of the group were men, and the average
age was 73.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-seven of the patients were treated with fluoxetine, the
drug generally known as Prozac, the most widely used of the new
antidepressants, known as selective seratonin reuptake inhibitors.
In a comparison group, 60 other patients were treated with
nortriptyline, one of the older class of antidepressant drugs,
known as tricyclics.
</P>
<P>
   Over the seven weeks of the study, heart functions worsened for
12 of the 60 patients receiving a trycyclic; by contrast, only one
of the 27 patients receiving Prozac grew worse, and a number of
patients in that group showed improvement.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Roose cautioned against drawing too broad a conclusion from
such a short, small study, but he added, ``The data we do have are
encouraging.''
</P>
<P>
   SMOKING MAY HARM HEARING
</P>
<P>
   Add hearing loss to the list of maladies cigarette smoking may
cause in middle-aged and elderly Americans. Researchers at the
University of Wisconsin Medical School found that smokers were
nearly 1.7 times as likely to suffer hearing loss than nonsmokers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This suggests that age-related hearing loss isn't inevitable
but might be preventable,'' said Dr. Karen J. Cruickshanks, the
associate professor of ophthalmology and visual sciences who led
the research team. The study, which was published in the June 3
issue of the Journal of the American Medical Association, was
financed by the National Institute on Aging.
</P>
<P>
   For five years, Dr. Cruickshanks and her colleagues evaluated
3,753 people between ages 48 and 92. They all lived in Beaver Dam,
Wis., a town of 20,000, about 40 miles northeast of Madison, that
had been used before for studies about the connection between
smoking and vision. Of the hearing study group, 46 percent were
nonsmokers, 30.3 percent used to smoke and 14.7 still smoked.
</P>
<P>
   The chances of hearing loss increased the more a person smoked.
For example, those who smoked a pack a day for 40 years were 1.3
times more likely to have hearing loss than someone who smoked a
pack a day for a decade.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Cruickshanks said the next step in her research would be a
five-year follow-up study that would try to explain how smoking
causes the hearing damage.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
