<SLUG> BC-CYBER-TRAVEL-$ADV21-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SURFING THE NET  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 21) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By L.R. SHANNON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LEAVING NOTHING TO CHANCE: Plus a Permanent Record &QL;
</P>
<P>
   www.recipeswinetravel.com &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Some people cross the last ``t'' and dot the last ``i'' when
planning a trip. Others of us are more casual. Still others may
carelessly dot a ``t'' or two. Multimedia Travel Workshop is for
the first group, although the merely moderately obsessive may find
it good for discipline. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With the Workshop, which comes on a CD-ROM for Windows 95 or
Windows NT, you write your own travel guide before you take the
trip. Back home, you can share the highlights of the journey on
your computer with friends in a fin de siecle equivalent of setting
up a projector and screen and dimming the lights. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Information about hotels, restaurants, sights and landmarks can
be typed into the detailed forms provided on the screen from books,
magazine and newspaper articles, and personal recommendations, or
downloaded from the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The entries are automatically indexed and can be viewed
subsequently as detailed lists (how detailed depends on your
perseverance); as simpler lists that face pages with other
information, including a photograph of the establishment if you
have taken one with a digital camera or scanned or downloaded one,
and various other formats. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Workshop, a product of Craftsbury Software, of Chevy Chase,
Md., contains a guide to Washington by way of inspiration. There
are also routines to build itineraries, maintain calendars, keep
track of frequent-flier miles and calculate currency exchanges.
</P>
<P>
   A packing checklist is divided into things to store in the
suitcase (such essentials as shoes, socks and a corkscrew) and
things to carry on (tickets, passport and a blindfold for sleeping
on the plane). It's a program with many features, but easy enough
to run if you are acquainted with other Windows software. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   You can sample the Multimedia Travel Workshop at
www.recipeswinetravel.com. Here there are numerous examples of
guide pages, itineraries, calendars and diaries, as well as a
frequently updated list of other relevant Internet sites.
</P>
<P>
   The program, which is $34.95, can be ordered from the Web site,
or by calling (301) 656-1029. As the name of the site suggests,
Craftsbury Software also produces recipe and wine programs, which
can be sampled at the site. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PLANNING FOR EUROPE: Preview Vacations &QL;
</P>
<P>
   New and updated CD-ROMs &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Planetware, of Richmond Hill, Ontario, has issued two CD-ROMs
that amount to travel encyclopedias with, according to the company,
40,000 sites and events in 21 European countries, 900 photographs,
700 maps, 3.6 million words and the texts of 27 Baedeker travel
books. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The two CDs are the Mediterranean Travel Planner, which is new,
and the Northern Europe Travel Planner, which is an updated version
of a disk first released in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   If you are going to Britain or France for the first time, you
will find the sights you have to see; if you are a veteran, you
will find the sights you didn't see on earlier trips. Since the
disks are almost endlessly searchable, you can look for sites of
personal interest _ coin collections, wax museums, caves. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Don't look for hotels or restaurants, though, or try to reserve
tickets. Planetware wisely does not include such time-sensitive
information on the disks, which work with Windows 3.1 or Windows 95
and are widely available at retail outlets for $44.95 each or
less. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MOOD ENHANCERS: Brochures Galore &QL;
</P>
<P>
   www.wwb.com &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Planning a trip wouldn't be complete without a collection of
brochures from tourist organizations, cruise lines and hotels. They
are handier to refer to than Web sites, and of course you can get
them from the Web. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Worldwide Brochures says it offers more than 10,000 free maps,
guides and brochures. There are several options for searching. I
tried the ``dictionary,'' a page bearing an alphabet where you
click on the first letter of the destination, event or topic you
are interested in. I clicked on ``m'' and got a lengthy list,
beginning with Maalaea and ending with Mzima Springs.
</P>
<P>
   I stopped at My Old Kentucky Home and, a couple of clicks later,
was invited to add a brochure about the state park in central
Kentucky to my electronic cart. Ten minutes here and you could fill
your mailbox for months. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
