<P>
   EDITORS:
</P>
<P>
   New York Times editors are CONSIDERING these stories for
Tuesday's Page 1:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL (Coded i) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BOSNIA-NATO (S &LR; kopje &UR; , Macedonia) &LR;  _ With conflict in
separatist Kosovo Province intensifying, and diplomats fear, likely
to spread to other Balkan countries, the West has threatened the
Yugoslav president, Slobodan Milosevic, with air strikes unless he
stops the stop using military force against civilians and enters
serious negotiations. To make that message clear more than 80 NATO
warplanes lifted off from 15 European bases Monday morning,
coursing across the skies over the Adriatic Sea and Albania and
Macedonia. &UR;  &LR; By Mike O'Connor.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CHINA-BULLS FEVER  &LR; (Beijing) _ It was class time at Beijing
University, but at 10 this morning seven guys in shorts and
T-shirts crowded around a large-screen color TV in dorm room 511, a
spare cement cubicle decorated with three metal bunkbeds and
yesterday's laundry. Nine student ``shareholders'' had bought the
TV last month in anticipation of just such an occasion and now
hoots and jeers filled the air as they watched the Chicago Bulls
clinched their sixth National Basketball Association championship
half a world away. &UR;  &LR; By Elizabeth Rosenthal.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON (Coded w) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCOTUS-CLIENT  &LR; (Washington) _ The Supreme Court, by the
narrowest of margins, endangered multistate programs that for two
decades have provided the nation's poor with up to $100 million
worth of free legal help each year. Voting 5-4 in a Texas case, the
justices ruled Monday that the interest earned from short-term
trust accounts lawyers hold for their clients are the private
property of those clients.
 &UR;  &QL; 
 &LR;   &UR; TEEN-GAMBLING  &LR; (Atlantic City, N.J.) _ Gambling and its
ubiquitous presence throughout the country has created a new rite
of passage for young people on their way to adulthood. By Brett
Pulley.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LOTT-RELIGION &LR;  (Washington) &UR;  &LR; _ In an unusual television
interview exploring his personal and religious beliefs, Sen. Trent
Lott agreed with a conservative talk show host that homosexuality
is a sin and he compared it to such personal problems as
alcoholism, kleptomania and ``sex addiction.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL (Coded f)  &LR;   &UR; SUNBEAM-DUNLAP  &LR; (Undated) _ America's
leading corporate downsizer has just been downsized. Albert Dunlap,
the publicity-seeking chief executive who took almost perverse
pride in throwing thousands of people out of work in the name of
raising his company's stock price was thrown out of his own job as
chief executive of the Sunbeam Corp. over the weekend. The
self-proclaimed turnaround artist, who had been running the company
for almost two years, was dismissed by a board in a revolt led by
some of his hand-picked directors.
</P>
