<HEADER>
A9899 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-OPEN-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      06-15 0927
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-OPEN-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEAUTY AND THE BEASTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RAY RATTO  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The Olympic Club is the most beautiful golf
course in the history of the world. Trees that kiss the sky, greens
like God's gardener did the work, fairways like the best mattress
you ever slept on, sand straight from the lobby ash trays at the
Ritz-Carlton. Makes Augusta National look like a goat's diner,
right?
</P>
<P>
   Hey, that's what the brochure says, and it would be unkind to
quibble now that everyone is here and ready to party.
</P>
<P>
   For the next week, though, the Olympic Club won't be heaven on
Earth but a U.S. Open course, which means it will be a mean,
vicious, hateful old orchard, knocking millionaires who own their
own jets and the pilots who fly them off their Foot-Joys and onto
their backs like starving turtles.
</P>
<P>
   That is, if the USGA has properly done its job, and we are sure
they have. At least as far as it goes.
</P>
<P>
   You see, this isn't just the U.S. Open. This is San Francisco's
U.S. Open, and although that might not mean much to David Eger,
Phil Mickelson or Jumbo Ozaki, it means plenty to us, the most
self-absorbed people in the history of the world. And yes, that's
in the brochure, too.
</P>
<P>
   The Olympic Club could have been tarted up not only to reflect
the USGA's more sadistic side but San Francisco's tourist needs as
well. Our guests would still be fighting to break par while they
would also be getting the full flavor of our hospitality. And we
are talking hospitality well beyond our usual summer weather _
traditionally night and morning raining crud, with afternoon wind
gusts of between 10 and 340 mph. Especially if the local
meteorological genii tell us it's going to be 74 and glorious.
</P>
<P>
   There is, for example, no reason why the USGA, while making sure
the fairways were 4 feet wide and the roughs filled with sinkholes
and puff adders, could not have put at the first tee a tape loop of
Mayor Willie Brown arguing with state Sen. Quentin Kopp about the
true value of the borsalino in politics. There isn't a golfer in
the PGA (or, for that matter, a human being with ears) whose nerves
wouldn't be so jangled that his drive would hit the pro shop on the
bounce.
</P>
<P>
   The USGA could have agreed to put a hot table from any of our
finer restaurants at the tee on No. 5, and made a brief nosh one of
the rules. If you think for 15 seconds that Fred Couples could put
down a single calamari or pickled pig's knuckle from Caesar's
without losing the entire equilibrium of his swing, you order your
dinner through an intercom. ``Well, I know I shot an 83,'' Couples
would say, ``but I've never eaten better in my life.''
</P>
<P>
   The Masters has Amen Corner. We could have Hell's Big Bend _ a
combination Gay Freedom Day parade, the line outside Pat O'Shea's
on St. Patty's Eve and any Tenderloin corner on a Saturday night,
thrashing the day away behind the 12th hole and 13th tee. You think
some stately creek eating golf balls every 15 minutes has anything
on that? Don't even start.
</P>
<P>
   And what's a rough without a little local flavor? Poison oak?
Too generic. Bear traps? Hey, this isn't Montana. No, what we need
is the alligator that terrorized all those TV camera crews in
Mountain Lake Park a couple of years ago. Sure, he was only 3 or 4
feet long, but he could still snap off an ankle here and there and
spit out the spikes without losing his smile. If you think Casey
Martin needed an exemption for his serious leg problems, what about
the first poor dupe who has to hop around the course for the last
three days?
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of Mr. Martin, good luck to him, but this being the
Open and all, you ever hear of the ol' Denver Boot? The meter
fiends who tour North Beach with citations galore and wear the
smile of a hundred papered windshields and a job well done all day
long? How about some of those backward-facing iron spikes that blow
holes in tires, or better yet, having to pay to park his cart at
the daily rate in the Embarcadero garage? His concentration would
probably be jarred a hair or two, which is precisely what our USGA
comrades are looking for, yes?
</P>
<P>
   None of this is actually sporting, mind you, and since the
USGA's creativity extends only so far (there was talk in the
preliminary stages about having no holes at all on Nos. 7, 12 and
16), we are saddened to report that none of these local additives
will be included this week. The Olympic Club, all 6,800 yards of
her, will have to stand on its own, dealing out every bit of
frontier justice her groundskeepers can manage.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco is a proud little burg, though. No golfer worthy
of the name will sit in his room for a whole week thinking about
the break on No. 8, and slapping a new grip on his wedge, or even
coordinating his wardrobe differently. Claustrophobia does not make
for good golf any more than lining up a putt while someone has put
a pot over your head and pounds it with a metal ladle.
</P>
<P>
   At some point, every golfer in the field has to come out and
eat, and hobnob with the locals, and schmooze over an adult
beverage in an adult restaurant with adults who have lived here
most of their adult lives.
</P>
<P>
   And that's when we've got them. We can't trick up the golf
course to reflect the city, but we can haul out the city and make
it reflect itself on the golf course.
</P>
<P>
   The clubs and shoes they choose are their own, but for the next
week, their stomachs and livers are ours. Welcome, gents, and watch
yourselves. We are everywhere.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-15-98 1638EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
