<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-15 16:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9905 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-B52S-BOS &LR;      06-15 1027
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-B52S-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
'80S SURVIVORS, THE B52S, RETURN WITH A HAPPY SUMMER SOUND 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating for all needing; originally moved May 29)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM SULLIVAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Is it time yet?
</P>
<P>
   Cindy Wilson, one of the B-52's three singers-front folks, waves
a figurative finger in the wind. ``I think,'' she says, ``it might
be the right mood this summer.''
</P>
<P>
   For dancin'? Romancin'? Embracin' the essence of the silly
season? Could be. Surveys show we're a shiny happy country -- the
economy's good; there's no war; the crime rate's down. The new wave
music of the early '80s has bubbled up again (in ``The Wedding
Singer'' soundtrack among other places), and the reconstituted,
rejuvenated B-52's are primed to ride yet another wave.
</P>
<P>
   But must you go away for so long in order for the public to miss
you?
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely. I mean, I had to get away,'' says a chipper
Wilson, on the phone. ``I could imagine even the fans had to.''
</P>
<P>
   Absent for six years, the B-52's are back.
</P>
<P>
   The B-52's defined hip-kitsch summer culture of the late
1970s-early 1980s -- as much a part of that era as the Beach Boys
were of the mid-1960s. ``Baked potatoes, bakin' in the sun!''
exclaimed ecstatic singer Fred Schneider in the B's
double-entendre-laden, sexy-silly first hit, ``Rock Lobster.'' On
their debut album, they took a zany place in outer space (``Planet
Claire''); later they invited us to the ``Party Out of Bounds,''
then they took us to the ``Love Shack.''
</P>
<P>
   The B-52's are calling their current swing through America's
outdoor amphitheaters the ``Time Capsule Tour.'' Their album is
``Time Capsule: Songs for a Future Generation,'' an 18-track
best-of collection with hits like ``Rock Lobster,'' ``Roam,'' and
``Love Shack,'' plus two new tunes, ``Debbie'' and ``Hallucinating
Pluto.''
</P>
<P>
   The B-52's -- Athens, Ga.'s favorite dance-crazed, sex-role
blurring sons and daughters in the pre-R.E.M. era -- had one
improbable comeback in 1989 with ``Cosmic Thing.'' Could they,
perhaps, rise from dormancy once again? Can boomer parents and
their teenage kids both do the Camel Walk to the B-52's of '98?
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still dancing, thank God,'' says Wilson, who shares and
swaps vocals with fellow co-founders Kate Pierson and Schneider.
``Thank God'' is not idle chat; her brother, guitarist-songwriter
Ricky Wilson, died from AIDS in 1985. ``When you come to the show,
you're going to have to get up,'' says Wilson. ``We've got these
go-go cages . . . `` Select fans will get the chance to shimmer and
shine in those cages.
</P>
<P>
   OK, but are the B-52's still relevant?
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, that's a good question,'' Wilson says. ``I don't know,
exactly, but if dancing and having a good time is irrelevant, then
I think that's terrible.
</P>
<P>
   But, yes, people want to hear our songs, and I think it's been
long enough where it will be fun and fresh again.'' Keep in mind,
too, that the B-52's lace their retro-futurist pop with
pro-environmental, humanistic concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think, basically, it doesn't take much for us to want to get
back together,'' Wilson adds. ``But you have to have a reason and,
to be honest, money was the first reason. And perfectly cool. But I
think it went beyond that to actually be -- for me and I suspect
everybody else -- a lot of fun.''
</P>
<P>
   For a moment, let Wilson take you back to the early days, 1978,
when the campy, wide-eyed B-52's crashed the dingy, but hip, New
York punk scene and found the jaded punks too fashionably
disaffected to dance. The B's were miffed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Hurrah's show,'' says Wilson, mentioning a famed,
long-defunct club, ``that's when I knew something was going on,
right after (the single) `52 Girls.' That's what spread the news,
for us becoming a . . . thing. It was going to be a regular show
and we looked out the window and there was a line around the block.
We flipped out. Bells rang. Things were happening. This was the
moment for me. It's funny 'cause I remember Ricky just freaking out
and getting so nervous. He lost it that night. . . . I cherish the
old days, when it was fun and small.''
</P>
<P>
   But the B-52's of today -- with former drummer Keith Strickland
taking over Ricky's guitarist slot -- are a bigger, if more
nebulous, entity. Session players and pals -- bassist Tracy
Wormworth, drummer Charlie Drayden, keyboardist Pat Irwin -- flesh
out the band.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are plateaus,'' says Wilson, looking back on the B's.
``For any musician, any rocker. It's just what you go through.
There were pitfalls and changes -- some exciting changes. `Cosmic
Thing' was a blessing. We went from the small band to the big band.
And not having Ricky behind me was really scary . . . I didn't
think I could live without Ricky.''
</P>
<P>
   Cindy dropped out of the B's after the ``Cosmic Thing'' tour.
She wanted to go out on a high note; she wanted to have a baby,
move from New York back to Georgia. She admits, ``I was kind of
burnt out. And there were a few squabbles in the band. I wasn't
having as much fun. In rock 'n' roll, it's crucial, for me anyway,
to have fun.'' Wilson gave the band a year's notice and was
replaced by Julee Cruise, who toured with the B's in 1992-93.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson came back to the fold, she says, in a casual manner. She
began to jam with the band. The time seemed right. They did some
corporate gigs -- that is, accepting big bucks to play conventions
for private companies and their employees -- and ``it was kind of
like us getting used to doing it. It unified us, to where we had a
goal. Now all the other stuff is falling in.''
</P>
<P>
   The B-52's are implicitly asking you to decide: What is
timeless, classic?
</P>
<P>
   What is faded, dated? Is a kitsch sensibility and a fascination
with creatures from outer space pop-worthy?
</P>
<P>
   ``We never lost that,'' says Wilson, of their fixations. Of
their serio-comic weave -- causes and a rock beat, she adds,
``One's just the style of the band and, I guess, one's just your
conscience, what you believe. I never had a problem with mixing,
never thought it was a problem. Human beings are multilayered and
nobody's a cartoon. It's a moment of time, basically.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-15-98 1641EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
