A9912 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-REAL-WORLD-BOS &LR;      06-15 0758
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-REAL-WORLD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SHAMELESSLY SUPERFICIAL `REAL WORLD' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW GILBERT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
THE REAL WORLD 
On: MTV 
Time: Tuesday night at 10 
Rated: TVPG 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Even with its he-said-she-said gender wars and its racial
tensions, MTV's ``The Real World'' has always been about as real as
summer camp. And as it begins its seventh season, which is set in
the alternative-rock mecca of Seattle, the infamous documentary
series now appears to be aiming for new heights of unreality, not
least of all thanks to the spiffy rock-climbing wall in the
apartment's living room.
</P>
<P>
   What's different about the show this year is that it no longer
seems interested in cultivating even a veneer of serious
documentary, pretending to be some sort of anthropological profile
of the nose-ring generation and its pressing issues. The game is up
in Seattle, with the cast members even talking openly about the
fact that ``The Real World'' is the best star-making machinery this
side of a Miramax movie. After a few minutes of set-up time, a
shamelessly light, playful atmosphere takes hold of the show and
finds our seven roomies quickly digging into the Seattle nightclub
scene and some randy pillow fighting.
</P>
<P>
   In past years, the ``Real World'' apartments have been quite hip
and showy. But this year's space, on Pier 70 on Elliott Bay, is in
a league of its own in terms of fantasy living. The palatial
interior is wide open and laid out like a TV set, with donated art
works and funky gimmicks all around, including hand-carved beds, a
barking metal-bulldog doorbell, an aquarium, a library of books
(including, of course, ``Sex for Dummies,'' which is quickly given
a public reading), a hot tub, a pool table, and an exercise room.
In a surreal touch, the cast members drink coffee (of course) out
of oversized cups, making them appear as though they only just fell
through a looking glass.
</P>
<P>
   Also, forget about last year's attempt, with the Boston cast, to
add a conscience to ``The Real World'' by making the gang work for
a children's after-school program. This year they are employed at a
commercial, alternative-rock radio station, where they will be able
to contemplate their hazy millennial futures in the company of some
pretty cool music-world celebrities.
</P>
<P>
   Based on the hourlong season premiere, which airs tonight at 10,
this year's cast is as TV-friendly as their apartment and their
jobs. Each person is instantly vivid in a way that has been missing
from the series since the third and best season, in San Francisco.
By the end of the first episode, you can easily remember each of
their names. And while this is Seattle, none of the cast members
seems to be caught up in any arch grunge or neo-Beat or
hipper-than-thou attitudes _ if anything, they're a surprisingly
wholesome bunch. (Don't they watch MTV?!)
</P>
<P>
   Two of the men, Nathan and David, are already best buds, as
fellow students at the Virginia Miliary Institute in Virginia.
David is a native of our own Charlestown, where he narrowly escaped
street violence and drug abuse, and with his Boston accent, his
class consciousness, and his loyalty to Nathan, he brings a welcome
dash of ``Good Will Hunting'' to the show. Not surprisingly, David
and Nathan's bond makes the third man, Stephen, feel excluded and
betrayed. Stephen, who appears to be moody and prickly, is
something of a diversity windfall for the makers of the show, as he
is both African-American and Jewish.
</P>
<P>
   The women immediately pair off, with Janet and Lindsay
distinguishing themselves as the resident extroverts, sometimes
even hugging their new roommates upon first meeting. Lindsay is on
the fast track to winning the most annoying award, bringing every
conversation around to sex and divisively trying to turn Janet
against the other two women. With Janet, who keeps yelling ``Shut
(itals)up(unitals)'' when she gets unbelievably excited, Lindsay
raids the boys' bedroom and jumps on top of David, who
automatically pulls off his T-shirt for some fun. She's either very
hot-to-trot or bristling with misplaced anger. The other two women
are less attention-getting, but potentially interesting. Rebecca is
graceful and intellectual, and Irene is a witty joker who
reportedly will not finish the season on the show.
</P>
<P>
   After last season's drabness and hostility in Boston, Seattle
promises to be fun city. And when all is said and done, why act as
though ``The Real World'' is anything other than a respite from its
title?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-15-98 1644EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
