<SLUG> BC-SCI-PHYSICS-ESSAY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LANGUAGE OF PHYSICS TIES PHYSICISTS' TONGUES
</HEADLINE>
   (ja) 
 By MALCOLM W. BROWNE    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAKAYAMA, Japan _ The language of physics, as spoken at
international conferences like the one last week where the
discovery of neutrino mass was announced, is becoming difficult
even for physicists to understand.
</P>
<P>
   Physicists take for granted the need for fluency in an enormous
vocabulary of difficult words and phrases unknown to most
nonphysicists. Some samples: eigenstates, fermions, bosons, spin,
coupling constants, hamiltonians, gauge invariance, Monte Carlo
simulation, the eightfold way, asympotic freedom and hundreds of
other verbal expressions of profound ideas.
</P>
<P>
   But remembering the acronyms used to denote specific experiments
poses another layer of difficulty.
</P>
<P>
   A physicist last week remarked that ``when Karmen sings, we'll
get to the bottom of this problem.'' To understand that he was not
referring to an opera by Bizet, a listener had to know that Karmen
stands for ``Karlsruhe-Rutherford Medium Energy Neutrino
Experiment.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the acronyms of experiments discussed last week by the 300
physicists who gathered for a meeting called ``Neutrino '98'' were
these:
</P>
<P>
   SUDAN, MACRO, CHOOZ, KAMLAND, GALLEX, CHORUS, NOMAD, DONUT,
MUNU, NEMO, DAMA, AMANDA, CRESST, EROS, GENIUS, EDELWEISS and OGLE.
</P>
<P>
   Some acronyms are compact and highly description, if a physicist
happens to know what they mean. For example the acronym for a major
Japanese-American experiment that is being built is called K2K
(pronounced ``Kay-to-Kay''). The name refers to a big Japanese
particle accelerator called KEK and to the underground neutrino
detector called Super-Kamiokande at the Kamioka Observatory near
here. When the K2K experiment is ready in two years, the KEK
accelerator will send a beam of neutrinos 140 miles through the
Earth's crust to the Kamioka detector; hence the name ``KEK to
Kamioka,'' or K2K for short.
</P>
<P>
   Political changes sometimes influence the names of experiments
or research organizations while leaving original acronyms intact.
For example, an underground neutrino detection experiment using a
huge tank of liquid gallium metal was named ``SAGE,'' which stood
for Soviet-American Gallium Experiment. The Soviet Union is no
more, and the experiment is now the ``Russian-American Gallium
Experiment,'' but since the acronym for this would be RAGE, the
experiment is still called SAGE.
</P>
<P>
   Changes in public sentiment also prompt changes in names.
</P>
<P>
   In the late 1940s a collaboration of seven European nations
created the great particle physics laboratory called CERN
(pronounced ``SURN''), near Geneva, CERN being the French acronym
for European Center for Nuclear Research. But by the 1980s the word
``nuclear'' had acquired such unpleasant associations for opponents
of nuclear weapons and power plants that nuclear was dropped from
the laboratory name, which became ``European Laboratory for
Particle Physics.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless the laboratory is still universally called CERN,
even though the acronym, is now meaningless.
</P>
<P>
   Virtually all major international meetings of physicists are
conducted in English, which is very convenient for scientists whose
native tongue that is. But at last week's meeting, participants
included physicists from Japan, Germany, Russia, France, Italy,
Spain, Portugal, Hungary, Korea and India. Some spoke excellent
English but others were barely comprehensible and their conference
presentations were hardly understood.
</P>
<P>
   Language problems at meetings like this are often exacerbated by
poorly prepared exhibits. Physicists commonly illustrate their
technical talks with diagrams, graphs and tables scrawled on
transparencies that are projected on a screen. But the equations
and words crammed into these transparencies, usually prepared in
haste, are often so small and messy that only audience members with
binoculars can read them.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can always tell which speakers are professors and which
are graduate students,'' said Maurice Goldhaber, former director of
the Brookhaven National Laboratory in Long Island. ``The professors
know that it isn't enough to understand your own experiment. You
must be able to make it intelligible to an audience.''
</P>
<P>
   Making particle physics generally accessible even to particle
physicists poses a growing challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``The field of neutrino physics is growing so fast that the work
of one physicist is no longer necessarily understood by a scientist
working in some other branch of the same field,'' said David
Caldwell of the University of California at Santa Barbara.
</P>
<P>
   Commented another physicist, ``It's time to bring some coherence
to the language of a field that might become a kind of Tower of
Babel.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
