<SLUG> BC-SOC-WORLDCUP-ENGLAND-650(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRENCH RIOT POLICE TRY TO CONTROL BRITISH HOOLIGANS  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER CLAREY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MARSEILLE, France _ For the second consecutive day, tear gas
drifted through the streets of this port city. The World Cup that
Marseille hoped to celebrate with parades, concerts and bicycle
races on the beach has not gone according to plan.
</P>
<P>
   French riot police had to intervene again on Monday to stop
fighting between fans of England's and Tunisia's soccer teams. As
of 9 p.m., 16 more people had been arrested and 22 treated at local
hospitals, according to a spokesperson for the regional prefecture.
On Sunday night, 35 people were hospitalized, including one
Englishman with a serious knife wound, and 50 arrested _ 30
English, 14 French and six Tunisian _ during rioting in the old
port of Marseille.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until last night, this was a party, but it's not a party
anymore,'' said Jean-Noel Ruiz, a 17-year-old from Marseille.
</P>
<P>
   Regional prefect Jean-Paul Proust responded by prohibiting the
sale of alcohol in Marseille after 4:30 p.m. to people who wished
to take it away. He also ordered bars in the city center to close
by 11 p.m., although many establishments elected not to open at all
on Monday night after the violence continued during the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``If these people want to continue creating violence here, they
will be expelled from French territory and will not be allowed to
come back for other matches,'' Proust said.
</P>
<P>
   The first incident on Monday occurred outside the gates of the
Stade-Velodrome approximately two hours before the start of the
England and Tunisia game in Group G. As fans emerged from the metro
and made their way toward the stadium, groups of Tunisian and
English supporters began hurling bottles and cans at each other and
exchanging blows. According to police, 10 English fans were
arrested.
</P>
<P>
   Three hours later, there would be more altercations, injuries
and arrests at the Prado beach approximately one mile from the
stadium where thousands of fans were watching the match on a
giant-screen television. According to witnesses, the trouble began
shortly after striker Alan Shearer gave England a 1-0 lead in the
43rd minute of the match that England would end up winning, 2-0.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until then, it was calm,'' said Maxime Dray, 30, of Marseille
who was sitting in the temporary stands. ``Before the match, there
were English and Tunisian fans playing soccer together on the
grass. When the game started, the Tunisian fans went into the
stands, and the English stayed on the grass. But after Shearer
scored, some of the English fans turned around and started taunting
the Tunisian supporters.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Dray and Hilde Smet, a Belgian, someone threw a
bottle in the direction of the English fans, who quickly
retaliated. The opposing fans began throwing bottles, cans, rocks
and plastic seats at each other. Dray said thousands of bystanders,
including elderly people and parents with young children, were
forced to flee.
</P>
<P>
   ``A group of English fans charged toward the stands, and there
was general panic,'' Dray said.
</P>
<P>
   Riot police arrived several minutes later, and fired tear-gas
cannisters into the crowd, and as the match at Stade-Velodrome
continued, the acrid smell of the tear gas soon drifted into the
upper reaches of the stadium. The prefecture's spokesperson said 18
people were treated at local hospitals because of injuries suffered
at Prado beach. A child was reportedly injured by a thrown bottle,
but the prefecture said none of the injured were in critical
condition.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's war,'' said one French teen-ager of North African
descent, as he limped away from the beach.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the hooligans against us,'' said Ramzi Hizi, a
18-year-old French youth whose parents are Tunisian immigrants as
he pointed to a large bruise on his wrist he said was caused by a
rock. ``I don't know why people are surprised. When the English
fans come to town, it is always like this.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   English clubs were banned from competing in European Cup
competition in May 1985 after 39 people died and more than 400 were
injured when a wall collapsed at Heysel Stadium in Brussels,
Belgium, because rioting by English fans caused panic. The ban was
lifted before the 1990-91 season. The incidents in Marseille are
the most serious involving English fans since 1993 when they
clashed with Dutch supporters before a World Cup qualifying match
in Rotterdam, Netherlands. England ultimately would not qualify for
the 1994 World Cup finals in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, British Prime Minister Tony Blair responded to the
incidents in the old port by terming the behavior of the English
fans ``a total disgrace.''
</P>
<P>
   Gareth Davies, a 30-year-old from Surrey who attended the match
in Marseille wearing an English jersey said, ``I'm ashamed to wear
the shirt.''
</P>
<P>
   Marseille residents were quick to turn their anger with the
English into support for the Tunisians. ``I've never seen so many
French people rooting for Tunisia,'' said Mehdi Benismail, a
25-year-old from Paris with dual Tunisian and French citizenship.
``There's a lot of racism against North Africans in France, but
people were honking at me and shouting encouragement to me when
they saw me wearing my Tunisian flag to the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul Thompson, also from Surrey, said of the violence: ``It all
takes the edge off our team's victory a bit. But we arrived this
morning and went through the city, and there were so many bars, and
all the English fans were drinking themselves into oblivion. The
authorities should have thought before the match about all of this.
It's up to them. They can either make money selling alcohol or they
can pay the bill to clean up the mess afterwards.''
</P>
<P>
   Proust said eight fans were scheduled to appear in a Marseille
courtroom on Monday and that 16 shops and restaurants in the old
port were damaged during the incidents on Sunday night. He said
English police had been working closely with French police to help
identify potential hooligans but said ``you can't check every
person who comes into Marseille.''
</P>
<P>
   Police were stationed at toll gates leading into the city before
Monday's game, and authorities said that reinforcements had been
called in to supplement the 1,900 law-enforcement officers already
scheduled to be deployed. Marseille police chief Michel Sappin said
an error had been made by scheduling England's opening game on a
Monday because it allowed fans the possibility of arriving on the
weekend and making mayhem.
</P>
<P>
   Keith Cooper, a spokesman for soccer's international governing
body FIFA, said the schedule had been made two years earlier _ long
before England qualified for the World Cup _ and could not have
been modified. He also said there were no plans to ban England from
this World Cup finals. ``The English Football Association and the
English football team cannot be held responsible for people
throwing chairs through restaurant windows or setting fire to their
opponents' flag,'' Cooper said.
</P>
<P>
   Interior Minister Jean-Pierre Chevenement said extra security
measures would be taken for England's next two games in Group G:
Monday, June 22 in Toulouse against Romania and Saturday June 26 in
Lens against Colombia.
</P>
<P>
   Some Toulouse residents already are preparing for the worst.
</P>
<P>
   ``I won't be working that night,'' said Jean-Paul Garcia, a taxi
driver in Toulouse on Monday. ``I don't want my car to be
damaged.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
