<HEADLINE>
TRAVEL QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 21) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By RAY CORMIER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; TAKING A CAR TO EUROPE &LR;  &QL; 
Q. (italics)I am planning to live in Europe for a few years,
starting in Britain, and I want to take my car. Can I ship it as
freight and go along as a passenger? _ Robert B. Carlin, New York,
N.Y.(end italics)
</P>
<P>
   A. A very comfortable way to accompany your car to Britain is on
the Queen Elizabeth 2. And since you are relocating, it may not be
as costly as you might think.
</P>
<P>
   JoNell Modys, a Cunard Lines spokeswoman, said Cunard offered
passengers who were moving overseas free shipping of a car on the
Queen Elizabeth with a booking in a midgrade (C5) or above on a
trans-Atlantic crossing _ $3,630 a person and up, double occupancy.
Return air fare is included in the cost of the cruise; since you
won't be returning the line absorbs the cost of the car shipping
instead, she explained.
</P>
<P>
   For those not relocating, the cost of shipping a car on the
liner is $2,550 one way and $3,950 round trip, plus $85 in port and
handling charges. Motorcycles cost $1,195 each way and bicycles,
stored in the ship's hold, $45 each.
</P>
<P>
   The QE2 usually makes eight eastbound trans-Atlantic crossing a
year, April through December, from New York. Call Cunard at (800)
528-6273.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to make your passage on a freighter, or pay less,
you may have to make a detour through Rotterdam. Travl Tips, a
Queens, N.Y., cruise company that deals with freighters, can book
you and your car on one of two Mineral Shipping freighters. The
Patty and the Christiane are seven-passenger freighters that sail
between Savannah, Ga., and Rotterdam about once a month, according
to George Koch of Travl Tips. Both ships offer outside cabins with
private bath.
</P>
<P>
   The cost is $650 a car one way, plus, on the Patty, $1,250 for a
one-way passenger or on the Christiane $1,400. Travl Tips can be
reached at (800) 872-8584 or (718) 939-2400.
</P>
<P>
   Among companies that will ship cars but won't take passengers,
Auto Overseas, (800) 283-3990, offers service to either Liverpool
or Southampton. Cars are priced by size: $700 for a small car, $800
for a midsize.
</P>
<P>
   Before moving, don't forget to check with United States Customs
and British Information Services in New York, (212) 752-5747, for
information on regulations and taxes you may face.
</P>
<P>
   Generally, relief from customs duty and value added tax is
available if you plan to live in Britain at least a year.
</P>
<P>
   Also, you might want to read ``Moto Europa,'' a guide to driving
in Europe, by Eric Bredesen. It includes a chapter on shipping and
importing vehicles. It is $15.95 from Seren Publishing, (800)
387-6728. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; ON HANS BRINKER'S HEELS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. (italics)My family is interested in a skating holiday in the
Netherlands. Can you suggest a route and how to find
accommodations? _ Elaine Fallon, Baltimore (end italics)
</P>
<P>
   A. While ice skating and the Netherlands seem synonymous, there
is no guarantee that the canals of Holland will freeze at any given
time in winter. Freezing can start in late December, but late
January and February are more likely to bring very cold weather.
</P>
<P>
   Your best bet is probably to head for the northern province of
Friesland, home of the Eleven Towns Race, the Elfstedentocht, or to
North Holland, in and around Amsterdam, according to Annemijn
Delavieter, a spokeswoman for the Netherlands Board of Tourism.
</P>
<P>
   The Elfstedentocht, a one-day, 124-mile test of endurance that
begins and ends in Leeuwarden and follows the canals connecting 11
towns, takes place only when the canals freeze. It was held last on
Jan. 4, 1997, but that was the first one since 1986.
</P>
<P>
   When it is held _ and there is usually only a few days' notice _
it attracts serious, even world-class speed skaters, and thousands
of spectators. But it also attracts thousands of others who tag
along at a more leisurely pace, or take part in shorter races on
the canals.
</P>
<P>
   So, with luck, you might follow the route _ through Kokkum,
Franeker, Harlingen, Bolsward, Workum, Hindeloopen, Stavoren,
Sloten, Ijlst and Sneek. If it is cold but the canals aren't safely
frozen, there is still a good chance for skating in the squares and
ponds in these towns, Ms. Delavieter said. There is also a skating
museum, Het Eerste Friese Schaatmuseum, in Hindelopen.
</P>
<P>
   For information, call the Netherlands Board of Tourism at (888)
464-6552. The board's Web site _ www.nbt.nl _ is also a good place
to start looking for accommodations. It includes a form to order
the book ``Bed &AMP; Breakfast in Holland,'' which costs about $17. It
can also be ordered by sending credit card information by fax to
(31-50) 313-3177. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; CIVIL WAR TOURS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. (italics)I am interested in tours that visit major Civil War
sites with knowledgeable guides. Do such tours exist? _ J. Michael
Parker, Narragansett, R.I.(end italics)
</P>
<P>
   A. There are indeed companies specializing in Civil War tours,
including at least three in Virginia, near many of the most famous
battle sites. These companies say they use historians _ authors,
teachers or National Park Service employees _ as guides. Most of
their tours last one to three days, and do not include
transportation to the base or starting place for the tours.
</P>
<P>
   The Civil War Society, Post Office Box 770, Berryville, Va.
22611, has been in business more than 16 years, Kevin Dunbar, the
marketing director, said. The organization has eight remaining
tours this year through November _ from a one-day look at
Sheridan's 1964 Cavalry Drive on Richmond, on Aug. 1 in
Fredericksburg, Va., ($60) to one- and two-week versions of The
Civil War in the West through Georgia, Kentucky, Mississippi and
Tennessee, Oct. 18 to 29 ($1,195 to $2,195 for tours, hotels and
daily breakfast and two dinners). Call (800) 247-6253 for the full
schedule, or see www.civilwarsociety.com.
</P>
<P>
   The Civil War Education Association, 21 North Loudon Street,
Winchester, Va. 22601, has nine tours left this year, most focusing
on Gettysburg or Fredericksburg. Fees range from $95, including
lunch, for one-day walking tours of Gettysburg on Sept. 26 and Oct.
3, to $275 for Fallen Knights: The Brothers Ashby in Winchester,
Va., on Oct. 22 to 25, which includes two lunches and a dinner but
not lodging. Information: (800) 298-1861, fax (800) 550-1347.
</P>
<P>
   A newcomer to the field is Hardtack Tours, 30 Blue Ridge Avenue,
Front Royal, Va. 22630. Among its offerings is a Newport News, Va.,
tour, Aug. 20 to 22, that includes a harbor cruise to the site of
the Monitor vs. Merrimack battle and a Civil War mystery play and
dinner ($185). Phone and fax: (540) 635-5078.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
