<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-15 17:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9975 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-SCIENCE-HNS &LR;      06-15 1023
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-SCIENCE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SECRET OF A GOOD GOLF GAME IS FOUND IN SCIENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By KEAY DAVIDSON  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ When 93-year-old Theodore P. Jorgensen isn't
trying to extract secrets of quantum mechanics from Albert
Einstein's special theory of relativity, he's thinking about golf.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went to a driving range here in town,'' said the
semi-retired University of Nebraska physicist. ``There was this guy
down there, swinging, hooking and slicing. I thought, `This is
terrible.' So I asked him if I could coach him a bit.''
</P>
<P>
   Jorgensen _ who, late in World War II, built monitors to measure
shock waves from an atomic blast _ explained a few principles of
physics.
</P>
<P>
   After the man took several swings, Jorgensen said, ``he turned
to me and asked, `Is that all there is to it?'''
</P>
<P>
   To the legions of duffers looking to gain inspiration from the
pros at this week's U.S. Open in San Francisco, there's a lesson
here: Golf is not just a sport, it's a science.
</P>
<P>
   That is not to say you will lower your handicap by cracking a
few books. But mastering some of the science might help explain why
your drives fall short and your putts run long.
</P>
<P>
   And you'll know a lot more about what happens when the club head
meets the ball.
</P>
<P>
   For example: A typical golf ball moves about 160 mph when struck
by the average pro on the PGA tour.
</P>
<P>
   On a drive, the ball spins backward at as many as 8,000
revolutions per minute, according to the book ``Newton at the
Bat,'' edited by Eric W. Schrier and William D. Allman.
</P>
<P>
   The dimples on a golf ball aren't just for looks; they make a
big difference in performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``A drive hit without backspin will come down after four seconds
from a height of 65 feet. The same drive hit with a dimpled golf
ball will stay up for six seconds, resulting in a drive up to 80
feet longer,'' writes Ira Flatow in the book ``Rainbows, Curve
Balls and Other Wonders of the Natural World Explained.''
</P>
<P>
   It's the same phenomenon that enables an 800,000-pound Boeing
747 to lift off the ground: If the ball spins backward, toward the
golfer, the air under the ball will flow more slowly than the air
above.
</P>
<P>
   Because of a principle that scientist Daniel Bernouilli
explained in 1738, the air below the ball is slightly denser than
above. That forces the ball slightly upward, prolonging its
distance and time aloft.
</P>
<P>
   The dimples on golf balls scoop up air and force it around the
ball, increasing the pressure difference.
</P>
<P>
   It works the same way on a plane, the wings are shaped to move
the air faster above and slower below. The result is lift.
</P>
<P>
   The makers of golf balls use countless designs to persuade
hackers that they can gain a competitive edge. Even though the
United States Golf Association sets strict guidelines for design,
about 1,900 different types of golf balls are qualified for use.
</P>
<P>
   Jorgensen, who didn't first hit the greens until age 50, about
the time President Dwight Eisenhower was putting on the White House
Lawn, is skeptical that the aerodynamic properties are markedly
different.
</P>
<P>
   ``I doubt it very much,'' he said. Still, ``some of these balls
are put together with different materials, so their rotational
parameters are different ... and the dimples come in different
shapes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't realize how intricate the aerodynamics of (golf
ball) surfaces really is,'' said Jorgensen, who wrote the book
``The Physics of Golf.'' ``It's one of the most complicated aspects
(in physics). I'm in my 93rd year, but I keep working on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Jorgensen's book isn't a simple how-to guide to playing a better
game. The book requires careful study to grasp its advice, which is
based on principles of classical physics that go back to the days
of the great 17th-century physicist Isaac Newton.
</P>
<P>
   Among other things, the book explains that Many golfers fail to
exploit a principle known to physicists as ``centrifugal torque.''
An everyday example is how water stays in a bucket being swung in a
circle. Using physics calculations and geometrical examples,
Jorgensen explains how a golfer can best exploit centrifugal torque
at the club head by relaxing, not stiffening, his wrist on the
downward swing.
</P>
<P>
   Golfers often don't understand that by swinging their clubs in
certain ways, they alter the angle of other body parts and weaken
the club's impact on the ball. Using a simple analogy that involves
a yardstick and a string, Jorgensen shows in his book why a
right-handed golfer should use his left shoulder to pull on his
left arm during the swing.
</P>
<P>
   That causes the club to swing more precisely, he said, because
the legs, thighs and back muscles will be aligned ideally to inject
maximum energy into the swing.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The quest for perfection doesn't stop with the ball or the
golfer.
</P>
<P>
   The golf equipment company Orlimar is ballyhooing its new
``TriMetal'' wood, claiming it ``uses a unique combination of
metals and weighting for superior strength and accuracy.''
</P>
<P>
   In the last decade, said Orlimar President Jesse Ortiz, golf
club design has relied heavily on materials from the aerospace
industry, such as metal-mix composites and ceramics.
</P>
<P>
   The introduction of graphite shafts has ``tremendously helped''
women, Ortiz said. The shafts are stronger, so more of the club's
weight can be shifted to the head, where it can do the most good.
</P>
<P>
   Hot new designs, not coincidentally, also have tremendously
helped equipment makers. Orlimar anticipates close to $30 million
in sales this year, compared with $1.5 million the year before.
</P>
<P>
   Science could bring out professional skills in even ordinary
players if the USGA didn't clamp restrictions on technical
innovations.
</P>
<P>
   By tinkering with the arrangement and shape of dimples, ``they
could make golf balls that anybody could hit 300 to 350 yards if
the ball manufacturers didn't have any restrictions,'' Ortiz said.
</P>
<P>
   The trouble is, ``if that happened, then it would destroy the
game, because anybody could be a Tiger Woods.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
