<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-15 17:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0051 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-OPEN-NICKLAUS-HNS     06-15 0806
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-OPEN-NICKLAUS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOLDEN BEAR MOVES BACK INTO THE LIMELIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DWIGHT CHAPIN  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The old Golden Bear was just about ready for
hibernation.
</P>
<P>
   Playing in the four major golf tournaments every year since 1962
_ 145 in a row _ seemingly was enough for Jack Nicklaus.
</P>
<P>
   He said that he and his wife, Barbara, who shares in all his big
decisions, had pretty much made up their minds that his historic
consecutive-tournament streak would end with the 1998 Masters in
April.
</P>
<P>
   But then United States Golf Association vice president Trey
Holland called Nicklaus and offered him a special invitation to
play in the next three U.S. Opens, including this week's tournament
at the Olympic Club in San Francisco, saying things just wouldn't
be the same without him in the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very flattered by the invitation,'' Nicklaus, 58, said,
``but I don't want to play if I can't be competitive.''
</P>
<P>
   That didn't seem to be a problem, seeing as how Nicklaus _ who
has won a record-tying four Opens and finished second four other
times _ shot a 283 at the Masters and finished just four shots
behind winner Mark O'Meara.
</P>
<P>
   ``Barbara said, `If you think you can add to the tournament and
be competitive and you want to work to do it, then you should,'''
Nicklaus said. ```But you took a big load off your back a few days
ago when you made the decision (to end the streak). Do you want to
put it back on?'
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `Barbara, the USGA has never made a decision like this
before. They're setting a precedent. If they feel that strongly
that I could help their golf tournament, then I have to accept.''
</P>
<P>
   Nicklaus will not be merely the oldest player in the field on
the Lake Course this week. He'll also be the only one who has
played 42 consecutive Opens (11 more than Gene Sarazen and Arnold
Palmer), made 34 cuts (21 straight between 1964 and 1984), had the
most subpar rounds (35) and the most rounds in the 60s (29).
</P>
<P>
   As if the USGA had to think twice about his helping the
tournament.
</P>
<P>
   The Olympic Club, however, has not been one of his most
memorable venues.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never done anything special there,'' said Nicklaus, who
finished third at the U.S. Open at Olympic in 1966 and was just one
shot out of the lead after 36 holes in the 1987 Open, but finished
far down the list after closing rounds of 76 and 77. ``I've always
liked the Olympic Club and played reasonably well there, but I've
never won.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, that's not literally true.
</P>
<P>
   Just 11 months ago, Nicklaus hammered Johnny Miller for an
11-stroke victory there in the two-man, made-for-television
``Shell's Wonderful World of Golf.'' Nicklaus shot a 1-under-par
70, making only two bad swings all day: an errant iron off the tee
at the seventh hole and a poor drive at the 12th that led to
bogeys.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jack put on a clinic out there,'' Miller said the day of his
defeat. ``He didn't make a mental mistake all day. If there was a
U.S. Open this week, he'd have a shot.''
</P>
<P>
   Nicklaus isn't making bold predictions about his 1998 finish,
but during a USGA telephone interview, he did say:
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope the type of game I'm playing right now will be very
suitable for the Olympic Club. I'm hitting the ball solidly,
driving pretty straight, and my putting has been pretty good.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been able to hit the ball left to right or right to left.
Those are things you need to do at an Open. You need to be able to
play all your shots. I go into a lot of tournaments where I only
have half my game or two-thirds of my game in shape and kind of
struggle with the rest.''
</P>
<P>
   Nicklaus' struggles aren't much like the struggles of ordinary
golfers, of course.
</P>
<P>
   And his Open history speaks for itself.
</P>
<P>
   In 1962, at Oakmont Country Club, he beat Palmer by four strokes
for his first Open victory. Five years later, at Baltusrol, he
topped Palmer again, by four strokes. In 1972, at Pebble Beach, he
bested Bruce Crampton by three strokes, then defeated Isao Aoki by
two at Baltusrol in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first time I played in the Open was at Inverness (in
Toledo, Ohio) in 1957, when I was 17 years old,'' Nicklaus said.
``The tournament has always been special. I played with Ben Hogan
the last two rounds in 1960, finishing second as an amateur, then
beat Arnold in a playoff in '62 for my first professional win. In
'67, I broke Hogan's record (with a 275), then won at Pebble Beach,
probably my favorite place to play, and came back at Baltusrol to
break my own scoring record.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, it's the first of at least three more hurrahs for the Bear,
who is no longer contemplating hibernation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've played a lot of golf at the Olympic Club, and it's a
great golf course,'' he said. ``I'm looking forward to it very
much.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
