A0078 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BASEBALL-SUPERSTITION     06-15 0669
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BASEBALL-SUPERSTITIONS13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The secret to success? It's superstitions
 &HT;    By Dan Graziano
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Not all baseball superstitions are as obvious as the Florida
Marlins' high black socks. Most of them, you don't even notice.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, did you ever notice how Edgar Renteria, when he
runs out to his position to start the game, stops to bend down and
touch the chalk on the first-base line?
</P>
<P>
   Or did you know that Jay Powell wears the same cap all season _
actually had them sew the World Series patch onto his sweat-stained
black Marlins cap last October?
</P>
<P>
   And how about Marlins third-base coach Rich Donnelly? He chews
two kinds of gum. Before the game, he chews only Wrigley's
Doublemint gum (the kind with the green wrapper). And during games,
he chews only Wrigley's spearmint (white wrapper).
</P>
<P>
   Donnelly has been doing it since last July, and he's so stuck on
it that, when the Marlins played their first-round playoff series
in San Francisco last season, he remembered the lack of Wrigley's
gum in the visitor's clubhouse at 3Com Park (apparently, they serve
only bubble gum) and brought a pack of each with him from the
hotel.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not a lot of success in this game, so the times you do
have success, you want to hang onto it,'' Donnelly said. ``To me,
it's not superstitious, but more that you feel good about what
you're doing. If you go out and get a steak and get five hits, I
guarantee you a lot of guys are going to go back to that steak
place. It doesn't have a thing to do with your hitting, but it
makes you feel better.''
</P>
<P>
   So after coaching third base in a pennant race, the playoffs and
the World Series last season, Donnelly figures he'd better stick
with the chewing gum. Just like this year's Marlins, after taking
2-of-3 against the Blue Jays this week while wearing those high
socks, figure they'll keep wearing them as long as they keep
playing well.
</P>
<P>
   ``After you've lost 10 or 11 in a row, you'll try anything,''
Powell said. ``Obviously the socks didn't win the games for us, but
over 162 games, you've got to do something different every once in
a while.''
</P>
<P>
   The socks stand out as an example because a whole team is doing
it. But baseball is loaded with individual superstitions, from Wade
Boggs eating chicken before every game to Toronto reliever Randy
Myers circling the mound after every pitch to some players' complex
adjustment routines before they step into the batter's box.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look at what a guy like (Boston's Nomar) Garciaparra does
when he gets up to bat,'' Powell said of the shortstop's batting
glove routine. ``I don't know how he remembers to do all that
stuff. Most guys, if you ask them about it, they probably won't
talk to you about it, because either they don't know they do it or
they don't want to know they do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Renteria is a good example. Approached about his pre-game
touching of the base line, he shrugged.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always done that,'' he said. ``Always.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a touchy subject, perhaps as much as any in baseball. Asked
if baseball players are more superstitious than people in other
professions, Donnelly didn't hesitate to say yes.
</P>
<P>
   He did not, however, single out baseball players among athletes.
Donnelly said he used to read about the subject, and he discovered
once that the Lakers' Jerry West used to chew a half a stick of gum
and be the second-to-last one out of the locker room before every
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``What do you have to be superstitious about in some jobs?''
Donnelly asked. ``This job is based on success every day. You have
to do something every day to keep your job. So, from the time
you're in the big leagues, you watch to make sure you don't step on
cracks, you see guys who don't change their underwear when they're
going good. You keep it going because it makes you feel like you're
doing something to help yourself, and that makes you feel good.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
