<HEADER>
A0079 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STODA-COLUMN13-COX     06-15 0663
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STODA-COLUMN13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rodman more of a pain to Jazz than Bulls
 &HT;    By Greg Stoda
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was two years ago, with the Chicago Bulls on their way to a
72-10 regular-season record and their fourth NBA championship of
this decade, when Michael Jordan plopped himself down in the
visitors' locker room at Miami Arena and said this about Dennis
Rodman:
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not sitting back waiting for Dennis to screw up. If we
look at it that way, it'll consume us. We have given him our
trust.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodman has since folded, spindled and mutilated that trust. He
has twisted it, ripped it and mangled it. He has mocked the Bulls
from front office to head coach to teammates.
</P>
<P>
   He is a narcissist and a clown. He is dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   But he has not consumed the Bulls.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Rodman has elevated them _ in support of Jordan and
Scottie Pippen, to be sure _ to the cusp of a repeat three-peat.
The Bulls, without Rodman, almost certainly would not hold a 3-1
edge on the Utah Jazz with an opportunity to close out the
best-of-seven series tonight in Chicago and claim their sixth title
in the '90s.
</P>
<P>
   Because on a basketball court, assigned to the specific tasks of
defense and rebounding, Rodman is simply an extraordinary talent.
</P>
<P>
   Forget the free throws Rodman made Wednesday night to help seal
Chicago's third victory against the Jazz, because those were flukes
as much as anything else.
</P>
<P>
   What is worth remembering is Rodman grabbed 14 rebounds, which
pretty much represents an average evening's work, and muzzled Utah
strongman Karl Malone. What matters is Rodman, when the mood
strikes him, is the only player in the NBA who can dramatically
influence a game by scoring very little or not at all.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, the mood has struck Rodman again.
</P>
<P>
   Last season at this time, if you'll remember, the Bulls were
playing Utah for the same prize, and the concern in Chicago's camp
was Rodman was being too sedate. That's hardly a worry these days.
</P>
<P>
   Rodman skipped Monday's team practice, turned up in suburban
Detroit for a pro wrestling show that night and laughed all the way
to the bank on his way back to the NBA Finals. Rodman received a
reported $250,000 for his appearance as a cigar-smoking bad guy in
the brotherhood of Hulk Hogan, which more than compensated for any
fines accumulated as a basketball truant.
</P>
<P>
   But if Rodman's behavior has consumed anybody, it has consumed
the Jazz.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't have him,'' Utah coach Jerry Sloan said. ``I'd just
as soon lose.''
</P>
<P>
   Umm, Jerry, Rodman is busy helping you out with that even as you
speak. And the idea that Malone and John Stockton and Jeff Hornacek
wouldn't trade their famous Jazz-happy camaraderie for one
championship ring is ludicrous.
</P>
<P>
   Make no mistake.
</P>
<P>
   The Bulls don't like Rodman; they endure him. Chicago center Luc
Longley nailed it when he said, ``We're sleeping in a nest that we
helped to build. Our acceptance of him and our tolerance of him
perpetuated the myth.''
</P>
<P>
   And all Rodman is doing is feathering his own nest. He's playing
for his next contract, which will probably come from somewhere else
(see: Los Angeles _ Lakers, Clippers or Hollywood), and punctuating
it with outlandish behavior that will help sell tickets.
</P>
<P>
   The whispers now are Jordan won't quit, after all. He may even
talk Pippen into re-signing, which, in turn, may influence Bulls
coach Phil Jackson to stay.
</P>
<P>
   Rodman, though, is gone.
</P>
<P>
   This is Jordan on Rodman, two years later:
</P>
<P>
   ``I can never figure this guy out, and I won't even start. We
have come to live with it and not really try to dissect this
individual. I don't know if he is an individual.
</P>
<P>
   ``But, somehow, he's always ready to play ... but there's no
understanding Dennis.''
</P>
<P>
   Against long odds, a fragile trust remains.
</P>
<P>
   It has been a wickedly unholy alliance, but a mesmerizingly
successful one.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
