<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Tuesday, June 16, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(lh) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Light rain fell at Anchorage, Alaska, on Sunday, marking a
record 17th consecutive day with measurable rainfall. On Tuesday,
the low-pressure system responsible for prolonging Anchorage's
rainy streak will forge into Montana, setting the stage for showers
and thunderstorms in the northern Rockies. Steadier rains will fall
in western Montana, where moist winds wrapping southwest around the
surface low are forced to rise up mountain slopes.
</P>
<P>
   Farther east, heavy rain is possible in the Black Hills of South
Dakota as increasingly damp air from the southeast is drawn into
the Montana system's wind circulation and then forced to ascend the
sloping terrain. Late Tuesday, clusters of showers and
thunderstorms will flare up over the high plains of eastern
Colorado and western Nebraska as the advancing system interacts
with a stream of humid Gulf of Mexico air accelerating north at an
altitude of 2,000 feet.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, isolated thunderstorms will erupt over the eastern
Gulf Coast and Southeast states as very warm and humid air rises
ahead of a slow-moving cool front. With a plume of high-level
moisture streaming east from the remnants of eastern Pacific
Tropical Storm Agatha, a few storms may produce very heavy rain.
</P>
<P>
   More rain will dampen northern New England as a slow-moving low
works in tandem with persistent onshore winds. West of the low, a
pool of cold air at 18,000 feet will promote showers and
thunderstroms from the Great Lakes and Ohio Valley to the central
Appalachians.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Excessive Rainfall
</P>
<P>
   Over 13 inches of rain fell at Atlantic, Iowa, on Sunday, as two
seasonal catalysts for excessive rain joined forces. Warmth and
humidity built in the lowest layer of the atmosphere, creating a
powder-keg of energy consistent with the heavy rains of summer.
Aloft, a formidable jet stream disturbance reminiscent of early
spring provided strong dynamic lifting of air near 18,000 feet.
With mechanisms for heavy rains in spring and summer coming
together, the stage was set for a cloudburst. The sluggishness of
the weather pattern over the Midwest also was a factor.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
