A0081 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GEORGE-COLUMN16-COX     06-15 0728
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEORGE-COLUMN16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    No news is good news for Marlins
 &HT;    By Dave George
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   I've changed my mind.
</P>
<P>
   That's basically what Wayne Huizenga said last June when he
announced that the Florida Marlins were for sale and that's what
I'm saying today.
</P>
<P>
   The startling revelation that major league baseball is in no
real danger of petering out in South Florida actually came to me
while team owners gathered last week in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   You see, no action was taken on the Marlins' proposed sale to a
group of investors led by team President Don Smiley. Nothing
happened and that was OK. If nothing happens between now and
Christmas but a series of further postponements, that's OK, too.
</P>
<P>
   There's just no killing baseball, whether nothing happens or
something happens or everything happens.
</P>
<P>
   It would be easy to call this a peculiarly American quirk but it
works in Canada, too. There is no logical reason for the Montreal
Expos to be in business after years of playing before pitiful
crowds in a money pit of an old stadium. Yet the team goes on,
existing in a bizarre state of suspended competition.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, there is no need for the Marlins, World Series waifs,
to question the inevitability of their own survival. The proof is
in the pudding that passes for our brains. Not even the
cancellation of a World Series was enough to bury baseball.
</P>
<P>
   That disaster of disasters occurred in 1994, the year Jacobs
Field opened in Cleveland with the enthusiastic support of a
generation of tortured fans. Just as the Indians were driving
toward their first playoff spot in 26 years, the game shut itself
down for the rest of the season. And what happened the following
year?
</P>
<P>
   Average attendance went up at Jacobs Field and the Indians went
to the World Series. Baseball choked but it didn't croak.
</P>
<P>
   Neither will the game budge, no matter how violent the pull of
economic factors. The last time a major league franchise
transferred from one city to the next was 1972, when the Washington
Senators became the Texas Rangers. Livan Hernandez, the Marlins'
World Series MVP, had yet to arrive on the planet in 1972.
</P>
<P>
   Simply put, an NFL team might back up the trucks and leave town
in the middle of the night but baseball refuses to acknowledge,
much less accept, failure.
</P>
<P>
   Why, the San Francisco Giants had been sold to St. Petersburg,
Fla. in 1992 when former National League President Bill White
stepped in and said no. The team stayed put, its money and stadium
problems still unsolved, but even so the Giants will open the 2000
season in a new ballpark in downtown San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   And so the Marlins will eventually succeed. They will coddle the
feelings of wounded fans and be forgiven, just as a special $1 kids
ticket promotion helped bring an astounding 35,652 to Pro Player
Stadium on Friday night. They will wave the World Series pennant as
physical evidence of a supernatural visitation. They will get final
approval for the purchase of the team by Smiley's investment group,
following up on the preliminary approval given by major league
owners in March when the picture was even fuzzier. And they will
get their new stadium, no matter how fantastic it now seems, even
as Huizenga's Florida Panthers prepare to open a new hockey arena
supported by Broward County tourist taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, the contradictions are everywhere, beginning with
Huizenga's statement that the team will never get a ballpark built
with public money as long as he's the owner of the team.
</P>
<P>
   Of the nine investors reportedly aligning to buy the Marlins,
three are currently on Wayne's payroll. There's Smiley, who started
out as marketing director for Huizenga Holdings in 1985. There's
Whit Hudson, Wayne's brother-in-law and vice chairman of Huizenga's
Republic Industries. And there's Huizenga himself, whose strategy
would be to withdraw as other investors come on board.
</P>
<P>
   These potential stumbling blocks still concern me but no longer
do they cloud my vision. I have changed my mind about the Marlins
eventually getting everything they want, for the simple reason that
there is no dying in baseball.
</P>
<P>
   A change of heart, now that will be slower in coming.
</P>
<P>
   Dave George writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
