<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Memories of Detroit days good ones for Caps' Oates
 &HT;    By Brian Biggane
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ The first games of the Stanley Cup finals at Joe Louis
Arena marked a homecoming of sorts for Washington's Adam Oates.
</P>
<P>
   Oates, 35, was drafted as a free agent by Detroit out of
Rensselaer Polytechnic Institute (R.P.I.) in Troy, N.Y., in June
1985 and played four seasons with the Red Wings before being traded
to St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have some great memories,'' Oates said. ``Our team went to
the conference finals two years in a row (losing to Edmonton in
1987 and '88) and I really enjoyed it here. I think any player has
fond memories of his first team.''
</P>
<P>
   Oates recalled that his best friends on the Red Wings were Steve
Yzerman and Joey Kocur; Yzerman is still with the team 10 years
later while Kocur has returned after stints with the Rangers and
Vancouver.
</P>
<P>
   ``I loved this team, and I've got great memories of that time,''
Oates said.
</P>
<P>
   Yzerman recalled the point in Wings' history better than he did
Oates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a vague recollection of it,'' he said. ``What I do
remember is that was when we first started selling out the building
(Joe Louis Arena) because we were started to play better hockey.''
Detroit qualified for the playoffs only four times in the period
from 1966-86.
</P>
<P>
   Oates said his clearest memory of Detroit was when he was traded
in June 1989 for Tony McKegney and Bernie Federko.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your first trade is always tough,'' he said. ``When I was
traded it was a shock.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Shanahan hurting: Detroit coach Scotty Bowman dismissed the
problems Brendan Shanahan has been having _ Shanahan hasn't scored
in nine games _ by saying Shanahan ``might have some discomfort.''
</P>
<P>
   The word is that Shanahan, an 11-year veteran, is suffering from
a problem with a disk in his lower back and is unable to put any
torque into his shot.
</P>
<P>
   _ Bowman on summer hockey: Bowman offered some frank opinions
when asked if the season has been too long to sustain interest in
this series.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know there's interest in the two cities involved, but I'm
not sure there's much in other places,'' he said. ``I don't even
know if there's much in Montreal or Toronto. It might pick up if
the NBA finishes (tonight).
</P>
<P>
   ``But now is better than October. Then you've got the World
Series, college football is in full swing and the NFL has started
up. Now baseball is the only real competition.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Lightning acquire Janney: Tampa Bay sent left wing Louie
DeBrusk and a fifth-round pick in this month's NHL Draft to the
Phoenix Coyotes in exchange for center Craig Janney.
</P>
<P>
   Janney, who's appeared in 704 games during an 11-year career,
had 10 goals and 43 assists in 68 games for the Coyotes last
season. His most productive year was 1992-93 when he had 24 goals
and 82 assists for St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   _ Noteworthy: Since the best-of-seven format was introduced in
1939, teams that went up 2-0 had gone on to win 36-of-39 series.
... No one can accuse Leslie Wills of Mount Clemens, Mich., of not
being a diehard Wings fan. Despite having contractions five minutes
apart, Wills remained in her seat until the end of Game 1, then
gave birth four hours later.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
