<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAYNARD-TRUDEAU16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    One-shot wonder takes long way to easy street
 &HT;    By Dave George
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOYNTON BEACH _ Maynard Trudeau scored a basketful of money at
the NBA Finals. A quarter of a million dollars, that's what they
said. So what exactly has changed in the life of Palm Beach
County's most sudden sports celebrity?
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing,'' says Maynard, who stepped quietly out of the limo
that brought him home from Palm Beach International Airport last
Saturday night and went directly to bed. ``I'm still laying carpet,
two or three days a week. I won't stop doing that until I'm 80.''
</P>
<P>
   That's six more years as a working man. The fast life of
hobnobbing with NBA Commissioner David Stern and entertaining a
packed house at Salt Lake City's Delta Center was fun for a night
but not as a habit.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, the payoff on Trudeau's successful swish shot from
three-point range in the AT&AMP;T Million-Dollar Shootout wasn't
exactly as enormous as advertised. Instead of $250,000, the amount
written on the huge cardboard check in all the photographs, Maynard
chose an option that will net him less than half.
</P>
<P>
   ``They gave me a contract explaining all the rules before I ever
left home but I never got time to read it,'' Trudeau said. ``Then
after I made the shot that night, a fellow showed me how it works.
I could either take the whole amount and have it stretched out over
25 years at $10,000 a year, or I could take a lump sum of $140,000
up front.''
</P>
<P>
   Trudeau took his lump and counted himself lucky. Once the
government gets its cut, he figures there will $110,000 with which
to invest. And even if it's less, the $10,000 that's left on their
27-year-old home is no longer a concern.
</P>
<P>
   ``What difference would it have made if I had read the contract
before we left Florida?'' Trudeau asks. ``I wouldn't have stayed
home.''
</P>
<P>
   In Utah Trudeau met Stern and watched Michael Jordan play
basketball from the luxury box of Jazz owner Larry Miller. There
were dozens of TV and radio interviews to do, enough exposure to
have people recognizing Trudeau back home these days at the grocery
store and the bank and the family-priced restaurant where he ate
lunch Thursday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Best of all, when the time came to demonstrate the underhand
shooting skill taught him by Santaluces High School basketball
coach Willie Gibson, Maynard immediately killed the suspense by
hitting the first of the five shots he was allowed under contest
rules.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said I would make one,'' said Maynard, who hit nothing but
net. ``After that, I really wasn't thinking anything at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Since then, however, there has been plenty of time since to
contemplate the future. The big plans devised thus far by Maynard
and Virginia, his wife of 52 years, are as follows.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to have a yard sale here pretty soon,'' he said.
``But I won't be putting the ball out there.''
</P>
<P>
   He's talking about a basketball signed by Jordan and Scottie
Pippen, too. That's supposed to be coming in the mail soon, along
with the money. Already half a dozen financial advisers have called
to suggest ways to spend it. The first phoned in on the night the
Trudeaus arrived home from Utah and he was in their living room the
next morning. Fast cash always brings fast action but the sharks
may go hungry here.
</P>
<P>
   Trudeau says he won't buy a big-screen TV. If he takes a trip
anytime soon, it will be back to Ohio to visit family. And you can
forget seeing a new Lexus or Range Rover next to the carpet van in
the driveway of Maynard's home west of Boynton Beach.
</P>
<P>
   ``That Lincoln of mine out there is a 1980 but it's only got
60,000 miles on it,'' he said. ``Why would I want to spend $20,000
on a new car? There's a dent or two on the one I've got but it runs
fine.''
</P>
<P>
   If there's any dissatisfaction here, it's that Dennis Rodman
didn't slow down to sign a T-shirt that the Trudeau's granddaughter
Jennifer held out at the locker room door. That steamed Virginia,
and so did Maynard's playful suggestion that he might just dye his
snow-white crew cut a Wormy shade of green.
</P>
<P>
   ``You do and I'll put a bag over your head,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The other night Trudeau watched on television as another lucky
contest winner got a shot at a million dollars during an
intermission in the NHL Finals at Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy said he'd been practicing,'' said Trudeau, ``but he
missed the hole where he was supposed to hit the puck by 6 feet.''
</P>
<P>
   That's Maynard for you. Been there. Won that.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
