<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PANTHERS-COACH16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Panthers need leadership...now
 &HT;    By Brian Biggane
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ The Florida Panthers were supposed to
have a coach by early June. Now it's mid-June, the expansion and
amateur drafts are less than two weeks away, and still no coach. So
what's the holdup?
</P>
<P>
   This much is clear: General Manager Bryan Murray has narrowed
his field to Dave King and his brother, Terry Murray. Both meet all
his criteria. In all likelihood, Murray has made his decision. Yet
he waits.
</P>
<P>
   Murray knows the beat writers who have covered the situation are
out of town until the Stanley Cup finals are over. When they
return, he'll make his announcement.
</P>
<P>
   And it looks very much like he'll be picking Terry Murray.
</P>
<P>
   Bryan Murray knows there will be a backlash. What you have to
admire about him is he's willing to go ahead anyway, even as he was
willing to trade Tom Fitzgerald last March for an unknown named
Mark Parrish, a deal many around the NHL are now calling a stroke
of genius.
</P>
<P>
   Terry Murray also knows he will be in the middle of a firestorm
if he's selected. Discussing the situation Saturday morning, he
emits a touch of anger and a touch of sadness that the issue
figures to be so prominent.
</P>
<P>
   ``My view is it should not be brought into play very much,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact is, I have a resume that qualifies me to get back
into this kind of a coaching situation, and that's what needs to be
taken into account.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a fact of life that people want to work with people they
know. Bryan Murray knows Dave King; the two worked together briefly
years ago and word is they got along. But that pales in comparison
to his relationship with his brother.
</P>
<P>
   Terry and Bryan say the two _ who are eight years apart _ aren't
that close. On the other hand, Bryan once taught Terry in school,
he coached him at the end of his career, and the two were coach and
assistant on the same staff in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we have a very respectful relationship, a professional
relationship,'' Terry said. ``That's the way it was for many years
in Washington, and it needs to be if it happens again.''
</P>
<P>
   As a scout for Philadelphia last season, Murray saw a lot of the
Panthers. He considers the disappointment of last season something
of an aberration and sees the pieces in place for a return to the
playoffs next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Rob) Niedermayer had an unfortunate year, and injuries like
that are a big part of why a team has a tough year,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But they can rebound. There's an opportunity to make a big
move. Look at Washington _ they missed the playoffs last year and
now they're in the finals. That's one things about the Eastern
Conference; the teams are so close there can be swings of four or
five positions in the standings in one year.''
</P>
<P>
   Terry has heard nothing from Bryan about his decision-making
process. Far from being disappointed, he said that's how it should
be.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm one of the candidates, and that's how I should be
treated,'' he said. ``I don't look to get privileged information
... and I don't want to be handed the position if the people down
there don't think I deserve it.''
</P>
<P>
   Bryan Murray is not in an enviable position. If he picks his
brother, he'll be ripped for nepotism; if he doesn't, he may be
passing over the most qualified candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Knowing Bryan, he'll do whatever he's decided is best for the
organization. It's only a guess, but the guess here is he'll pick
Terry.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Biggane writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
