<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEYTALK16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Money Talk: Help your kids manage money
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By Hank Ezell
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Here's a familiar worry, one that blooms anew with
each generation: Nobody teaches the kids about money these days.
</P>
<P>
   Here's an all-purpose answer, renewable for each generation of
new parents: We have to do it ourselves.
</P>
<P>
   The schools may develop financial education classes. Banks and
mutual fund families can be counted on to market their products to
the consumers of tomorrow. Still, they are our kids, and it's up to
us.
</P>
<P>
   That comes to mind right now because it's summer, and many
youngsters are heading off to their first full-time jobs. If you
want to help them become responsible money managers, there's no
time like the present.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a really good time to have a dress rehearsal, when the
effects won't be devastating,'' advises Neale S. Godfrey, author of
several books on teaching kids about money. ``None of us (adults)
came up with budgeting by ourselves. Why should we expect our
children to do it?''
</P>
<P>
   Here are some specifics that parents and teenagers can deal
with:
</P>
<P>
   -- Take-home pay. Everybody has to learn sometime about the
impact of taxes. The idea is to find out how much you'll take home
each week -- and what the total for the summer is. Then develop a
realistic budget.
</P>
<P>
   -- Savings objectives. ``Most teenagers don't think about
managing money,'' said Steven Sanders, a financial consultant
allied with Citibank. ``They think about spending it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to teach them,'' added Godfrey. ``You have to talk
about the fact that in real life we can't spend all our money. We
have to save and invest some.''
</P>
<P>
   -- Spending plans. The worksheet lays out the steps involved.
Note the priorities it establishes: savings first, then necessary
spending, then the fun stuff.
</P>
<P>
   Godfrey would add another category: giving to charity. ``Most
young people are incredibly willing to do that,'' she said. ``They
just never thought about it.''
</P>
<P>
   -- Parental leadership. ``You can say, 'Here's what I'd like you
to do, and I'll help you with it,''' Godfrey said. ``You can go
with them to open a bank account. You can help them study stocks
that they know about, to invest in.''
</P>
<P>
   -- Credit cards. Children of all ages have them these days.
Adults need to point out how much trouble they can lead to when not
used thoughtfully. ``Pay off what you charge each month, without
dipping into your savings,'' advises Suzanne Boas of the Consumer
Credit Counseling Service.
</P>
<P>
   -- A reality check. Midway through the summer, teenagers need to
stop and review their budget. Ask these questions: Am I saving
enough? Are expenses running higher than I budgeted? Do I need to
change my spending? It might be time, for instance, to find a
cheaper way to get to work. Or you might try renting videos, rather
than going to the movies.
</P>
<P>
   For a sensible and comprehensible elaboration of these points,
call Citibank at 1-800-669-2635 and ask for a free copy of the
leaflet ``Beach Blanket Budget.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The Atlanta Journal-Constitution
</P>
<P>
   AP-NY-06-12-98 2319E
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
