<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Four plans designed to help pay off college loans
 &HT;    By Gene Tharpe
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ This year's college graduates, thanks to a strong
economy, are enjoying increased job offers with good salaries --
but many graduates will soon encounter something they won't like:
repaying college loans.
</P>
<P>
   About one-half of the graduates financed part or all of their
education with student loans that average about $12,000. Repayment
for those who don't seek higher degrees is scheduled to begin in
six months.
</P>
<P>
   Because of high default rates in past years, the U.S. Department
of Education's Direct Loan Program now offers four repayment plans
for its borrowers intended to ease the ``stress'' of repayment:
</P>
<P>
   -- The Standard Repayment Plan requires the payment of a fixed
amount -- at least $50 -- each month for a period not to exceed 10
years. The length of the actual repayment period depends on the
loan total and the amount paid monthly.
</P>
<P>
   -- The Extended Repayment Plan permits fixed monthly payments
for 12 to 30 years, depending on the amount owed. Monthly payments
are lower than the standard plan -- except for a minimum payment of
$50 -- but the total paid will be more because of interest charges
for the longer period.
</P>
<P>
   -- The Graduated Repayment Plan allows lower payments at first
that gradually increase every two years over a period generally
ranging from 12 to 30 years. This is aimed at graduates who expect
their income to rise steadily as they grow older.
</P>
<P>
   -- The Income Contingent Repayment Plan bases monthly payments
on borrower's yearly income and loan amount. As income rises or
falls, so do payments. After 25 years, any remaining balance is
``forgiven,'' although taxes will be due on the amount forgiven.
</P>
<P>
   For more information on the Direct Loan Program payment options,
call 1-800-848-0979.
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, other types of student loans -- including some
Federal Family Education Loan Program loans -- may be consolidated
with the Direct Loan Program to arrange for a single payment and,
perhaps, a longer payment period and lower interest. Call
1-800-557-7392 for information.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Family Education Loan Program also offers some
repayment options for its borrowers, as well as consolidation
loans. For details on Federal Family Education Loan options and
loans, call the Georgia Student Finance Authority at 770-414-3000
in metro Atlanta, or 1-800-776-6878.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government has become increasingly aggressive in the
last few years with students who have failed to pay back loans, and
the default rate has fallen from about 22 percent in 1990 to 10
percent in 1995. Collection tactics include seizure of income tax
refunds and the hiring of professional debt collectors.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
