<HEADER>
A0091 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GUINESS-FLEADH-575&AMP;AD     06-15 0979
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUINESS-FLEADH-575&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MAGIC OF A VOICE, THE UNITY OF PEOPLES 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By ANN POWERS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In the midst of summer festivals focused on political
issues (the Tibet Festival, held simultaneously in Washington)
alternative culture (the late, lost Lollapalooza), a specific
gender (Lilith Fair) and varying genres (Ozzfest, Smokin' Grooves),
the Guinness Fleadh (pronounced flah) is a festival focused on
music. Yet this stout-sponsored event, which this past weekend
visited Randalls Island for the second time, still realized an
agenda of its own. Its 60-plus acts coalesced around two romantic
notions of popular music's power: its ability to elevate solitary
voices and its magical way of bonding communities, both onstage and
in the audience.
</P>
<P>
   These themes connected the festival to its roots in Irish
culture, as it moved further from that country's folkways. The
traditional crafts and arts offered at the fair's sideshow and
smallest performance tent, the Irish Village, did allow for a
predominantly Celtic experience. But artists on the show's main
stage and in its two other tents emphasized a different shared
identity: the musician as cultural diplomat, communicating common
wisdom and banishing conflicts from the dance floor. Irish music,
split between a singing tradition that functions as oral history
and an instrumental style based in fleet, rhythmic virtuosity,
provided the context within which different performers explored
this role.
</P>
<P>
   Folk-flavored storytellers presented a number of solo sets, with
most on Saturday. An affable Richard Thompson played acoustic
guitar and pulled selections from his excellent song book, offering
witty remarks to the audience between songs. Chris Smither treated
a rapt audience to a dazzling show of Delta blues-style playing,
keeping time with his microphone-amplified foot. Loudon Wainwright
III proved as entertaining as ever, poking fun at the ubiquitous
Irish penny whistle and singing a song about taking LSD that made
use of the colorful light show available in his tent.
</P>
<P>
   Other Saturday performers played with bands, extending
individual expression outward into the audience. Tommy Makem led a
sing-along that ended with a rousing version of the Irish anthem
``Four Green Fields,'' which had some fans weeping. The English
anarchist collective Chumbawamba got the main stage crowd jumping
with ``Tubthumping,'' its smash song celebrating the resilience of
the human spirit. Jeb Loy Nichols, whose excellent band built a
sexy groove that sent many couples dancing, showed how one approach
to singing and songwriting can span several genres, from smooth
soul to lovers' rock-style reggae to country.
</P>
<P>
   Sinead O'Connor once again showed why her resolute individualism
has made her the most notable Irish pop performer, aside from
superstars U2, of her generation. Her set featured songs from
throughout her career, including a moody new ballad featuring piper
Davey Spillane. Opening her mouth wide, Ms. O'Connor let loose the
raw, haunting tones that unite rock vocalizing with age-old Irish
techniques.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, musicianly interplay took precedence over singing. Yo
La Tengo demonstrated its emotive brand of punk musicianship, while
Shane McGowan, the increasingly dissipated Irish punk pioneer,
relied on his band, as tight as he was loose, to carry his set.
Patti Smith and Joe Ely both turned to their bands to fuel their
lively dramatics. Los Lobos worked the miracle of taking subtlety
to a stadium performance with its highly inventive blend of Latin
and rock styles.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Creating a similar, but Irish-based, fusion, the Eileen Ivers
band electrified a familiar repertory. Ms. Ivers, a fiddler with
the show ``Riverdance,'' threw off reels at hardcore-punk speeds
and made her instrument sound like Jimi Hendrix's guitar. Her band
merged the Celtic and African diasporas, inspiringly expanding
Irish folk expression.
</P>
<P>
   Many Fleadh performers stretched their chosen genres, but for
sheer impact no one could beat the concentrated punk of X. The band
has returned to its original lineup, with the enigmatic Billy Zoom
on guitar, for a handful of dates. Zoom took the stage before his
band mates and was greeted with ecstatic cheers. The group's set
showed why: His solid minimalism maintained the purity of a sound
that hit upon rock's raw essentials: a fast, lurching beat secured
by drummer D.J. Bonebrake; the sexual tension between the former
spouses and co-vocalists Exene Cervenkova and John Doe, who also
plays bass; confrontational lyrics about the risky allure of modern
urban life. Summoning the drive that incited them 20 years ago, X
proved that a great band is often exactly the sum of its parts.
</P>
<P>
   The other partnership that shone at the Fleadh did not just
resurrect the past; it also crossed mortal boundaries to link two
sets of contemporary musicians with a forefather. Not long ago,
Billy Bragg, the stalwart English folk rocker, and Wilco, the
Midwestern country-rock band, were asked by Nora Guthrie, the
daughter of Woody Guthrie, to write music for some of her father's
lyrics never before set to music. The resulting songs extend
Guthrie's legacy into the millennium. In separate sets on Sunday,
Wilco and Bragg featured songs from this project.
</P>
<P>
   Bragg particularly emphasized this material, explaining each
lyric's political significance before he and his band offered their
sparkling renderings. The emotional high point came when Ms.
Guthrie joined Bragg and members of Wilco to sing one of these
miraculous collaborations. At that moment, the Guinness Fleadh
stood for more than just good sounds: It captured music's power to
preserve one compelling voice, cleaving it to the hearts of others
across time and space.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
