<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-15 17:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0092 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JASPER-COMMENTARY-COX     06-15 1455
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JASPER-COMMENTARY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Texas town will seek justice in racial killing
 &HT;    By John Reetz
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   There was a time _ just a few days ago _ that when asked of my
hometown, the talk took a long, explanatory path: a tiny town in
the pine woods, a place of dogwoods and azaleas, of hard-working,
simple, tough and honest people, of a boyhood spent playing ball in
pastures and sandlots, of friendships that endure even when contact
is absent, of relatives that go back to the town's beginning.
</P>
<P>
   It was a place where the slogan on the local weekly paper's mast
said it all: ``We Bend Our Knee to None But God.'' It's a town
named after a patriot who died in the Siege of Savannah in 1776,
and is memorialized in one of that city's downtown squares.
</P>
<P>
   It was a place my mother's family moved to in 1849, leaving
Georgia, but bringing with them the name ``Peachtree'' for the
little community they settled in just outside the town. Townspeople
knew my great-grandfather simply as ``Uncle Bob,'' remembered in
his obit as ``a kindly God fearing man ... a tireless worker'' who
cultivated a crop for 60 consecutive years.
</P>
<P>
   My dad came to town with World War II, training across the river
at Camp Polk, La. He met my mother and when he survived infantry
time in Germany and the Korean War, he returned, built a house and
raised a family.
</P>
<P>
   No longer, however, is such a long detailed description needed
of my hometown.
</P>
<P>
   For my hometown is Jasper, Texas, and most have formed their own
mental image of that little town buried deep in the dark, brooding
woods of East Texas.
</P>
<P>
   On June 7, James Byrd Jr., a 49-year-old black man, was killed 5
miles east of Jasper in a horrible manner: beaten into
unconsciousness, chained to the back of a pickup truck and dragged
to his death along a 3-mile stretch of rural road. Three
ex-convicts have been charged with the horrific murder, a killing
described by the Rev. Jesse Jackson as the most brutal race murder
he's seen since Mississippi, 1955.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday they buried James Byrd Jr., but the rage that crime of
hate spawns cannot _ and should not _ be buried.
</P>
<P>
   What happened in Jasper, Texas, evokes revulsion, disgust, shame
_ all the emotions that come with such crimes that not only violate
and brutalize an individual and their family, but strike against
humanity itself.
</P>
<P>
   Where does it end? None of us can even hazard a guess, for there
is rage all around, at different levels, but in too many of us.
</P>
<P>
   What drove the thinking of the person who shackled James Byrd to
the back of that pickup early on that Sunday morning?
</P>
<P>
   And think of what else has consumed us in recent days.
</P>
<P>
   What was in the mind of the carjackers who killed a Dunwoody,
Ga., youth just to steal his auto?
</P>
<P>
   And who can sort through the minds of the young gunmen who
plague our schools?
</P>
<P>
   Out of the office last week, my first clue to what happened in
Jasper came from a newspaper while waiting for an overnight flight
from San Francisco to Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   As we departed, a woman in front of me pored over the article,
reading and re-reading. The headline: ``This is the most gruesome
thing I've ever heard of.''
</P>
<P>
   First, came shame that it could happen in ``my'' town. Second, a
sick feeling and a desire to put it out of my mind, and stay away
from it. But somewhere in midflight in the early morning hours, the
oddest of lyrics came to my troubled and weary mind, a song drilled
into our little brains at Sunday School at the First Baptist Church
of Jasper: ``Jesus loves the little children; All the children of
the world; Red and yellow, black and white; They are precious in
his sight; Jesus loves the little children of the world.''
</P>
<P>
   As children, we learned by rote, but it made sense when we were
old enough to understand the words.
</P>
<P>
   By week's end, the national press was in Jasper, and we saw the
suspects walk out of the Jasper County courthouse, headed for jail.
It was on that courthouse lawn that George Custer camped with his
troops during Reconstruction. It was on that lawn that I'd go with
my dad to watch as they wrote election results on a gigantic
chalkboard. It was on that lawn that my high school band played
Christmas concerts, and around that square each May would come the
annual Rodeo Parade, a huge assemblage of bands, horses, clowns,
wagons and floats announcing the start of the annual rodeo.
</P>
<P>
   My grandmother lived just a block down the street; down the
street the other way I went to church. And over the other direction
a block was The Jasper News-Boy, the little weekly where I got my
start, working for free before I got a raise to $3 a week.
</P>
<P>
   Across the street from that courthouse lawn was the Texas
Theater, where I saw ``The Ten Commandments'' with my mother, and
on the same block were Hancock Drug Store and Henderson Drug Store,
where we gathered for cherry Cokes.
</P>
<P>
   Halfway down the block from the courthouse was the Jasper Bake
Shop, and the man who baked the lightest donuts I've ever had
worked there when I was in high school. His name was Zeke Spikes,
and he had a son my age, named Warren.
</P>
<P>
   When the federal government instituted its ``Freedom of Choice''
option before full integration, Warren came to Jasper High School
along with two other black students. Those three became the first
to graduate from the previously segregated Jasper High School. It
made so much sense then, back in 1968, so why do we still struggle
with race issues?
</P>
<P>
   Before coming to the white school, blacks attended Rowe High
School, a school in the old Texas Negro Interscholastic League.
Rowe's football team was generally 10-0 and playoff-bound and the
white school's record was generally 0-10 or 1-9. When I worked at
the News-Boy, it was more fun to cover Rowe.
</P>
<P>
   Get the picture now about Jasper?
</P>
<P>
   If you grew up in any rural area in the '60s, you can relate to
practically everything you know now of Jasper. You probably skipped
school, too, raced tractors through pastures, had a few illegal
beers from the bootlegger on occasion and the Louisiana state line
on other occasions, struggled with the transition from a flattop to
a mild pony tail in the late `60s and early `70s, went off to
college and vowed never to return. Then missed it the rest of your
life.
</P>
<P>
   But despite the commonalities with any other rural town of that
time, the horrific crime against James Byrd Jr., his family, his
town, this country makes Jasper stand out, and will put it to a
test.
</P>
<P>
   One of the more visible figures as the case unfolds will be
District Attorney Guy James Gray. My memories are of Guy James as
second baseman on the school baseball team. In the first days after
the crime, he and Sheriff Billy Rowles were most visible, as Rowles
asked that Jasper not be judged for this act alone.
</P>
<P>
   Can Jasper, as it seeks justice for Byrd, be the place that the
line is drawn in the sand on racism and hatred, as it was at the
Alamo a century and a half ago on behalf of Texas liberty?
</P>
<P>
   Can it be where we all say enough is enough?
</P>
<P>
   Rev. Jackson, in town for Byrd's funeral, preached
reconciliation, not retribution, and said he saw a relationship
between whites and blacks that he usually doesn't see in such
cases. Jasper's reaction, Jackson said, ``set a standard for the
nation...In this town blacks and whites have come together like
nothing I've ever seen.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison talked of the stoic reaction of
Byrd's family and the example they set for others.
</P>
<P>
   Stoicism is nothing new to Deep East Texas.
</P>
<P>
   These are people who work hard, don't earn a lot of money, are
independent-minded, loving but cautious, and quiet, not boastful.
Their ancestors had a hard life, coming to these dark woods from
Georgia, Mississippi, Alabama and elsewhere, living always on the
edge of the frontier. As a result, they know how to put up with a
lot, and wait for the bad to pass.
</P>
<P>
   That stoicism, that tenacity will help Byrd's family carry on,
and it will help Guy James Gray and the rest of the town seek
justice in his name.
</P>
<P>
   West of Jasper there is a grown-over family cemetery, where my
great-grandmother's grave is topped with a tombstone that says it
all about a frontier woman: ``She Hath Done What She Could.''
</P>
<P>
   May we all commit to the same as Jasper, and this country, does
what it can to seek out the good in the aftermath of this tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   John Reetz is an assistant managing editor of The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, and director of CoxNet, which includes Cox
Newspapers's Wide Area Network and Cox News Service.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
