<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-15 17:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0095 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOLSENDOLPH-COLUMN16-     06-15 0816
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLSENDOLPH-COLUMN16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ernest Holsendolph's Business Commentary: BellSouth's plan for
wireless TV intrigues viewers
 &HT;    By Ernest Holsendolph
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When BellSouth announced that it is offering something
fresh, television over the air to the tune of some 160 channels,
the news created an instant buzz. BellSouth was positively
overwhelmed. But for cable TV operators, the outpouring of interest
in BellSouth's news had to carry a sobering message.
</P>
<P>
   Lots of folks out there were saying, I don't know what this
wireless television is, but whatever it is, I want to give it a
chance. Anybody but cable!
</P>
<P>
   There is even the view that, true to BellSouth's commercials and
marketing, people are beginning to view the phone company as the
epitome of reliability and service.
</P>
<P>
   Wasn't it only yesterday that Lily Tomlin had us rolling with
her sharp needles at Ma Bell: ``I'm from the phone company and I
don't care.''
</P>
<P>
   Images change.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the phone company Miss Tomlin was lampooning does not
really exist anymore. It was the Ma Bell that let us choose some
colors and touch tones, but offered far too few alternative
services. Now, BellSouth and cable officials agree, the excitement
is over the idea of competition.
</P>
<P>
   For all we know, the outpouring of calls that flooded the
BellSouth staff may have been principally curiosity -- a desire to
know more about this new service, and to know if it would be
available in particular neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   John Hartman, vice president of BellSouth Entertainment, said
there were actually three primary areas of inquiry by callers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people said they simply wanted a service provided by
BellSouth, showing some attraction to the brand,'' said Hartman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Others were looking for what we call 'tonnage,' some means to
get a huge package of entertainment that they could sift through to
find what pleases them,'' Hartman said. ``Still others, maybe the
most technically knowledgeable, were looking for digital quality,
regardless of cost, so they could get a clearer picture than they
normally get.''
</P>
<P>
   He made it clear that the seekers of ``tonnage'' were not
necessarily couch potatoes, who plop down and watch hours of TV
each evening. Rather, they were most likely to be busy people, who
want to go directly to subject matters that tie into their
lifestyles or interests.
</P>
<P>
   Among those people are many newcomers to Atlanta, who came from
communities with broader selections of channels and are highly
disappointed that the limited choices here do not include certain
information channels, a well-displayed weather radar, or a nimble
navigational system that lets the viewer know instantly what's on
each channel.
</P>
<P>
   ``You would be amazed at how passionate people get over TV
programming,'' Hartman said.
</P>
<P>
   ``And beyond TV, many people want the 30-channel package of
digital stereo music of all kinds, ranging from classical to
popular and jazz.'' Actually MediaOne and others offer the music
package, but in some cases separately, with a special box apart
from the channel tuner.
</P>
<P>
   Because many of the newcomers did not find their favorite
channels on existing cable, they immediately turned their backs on
local companies and tried satellite TV, only to be disappointed by
certain limitations such as lack of local channels.
</P>
<P>
   And so did all this have ears burning over at local operators
like MediaOne?
</P>
<P>
   ``We definitely have had plenty of meetings about this,'' said
Reg Griffin, MediaOne spokesman. ``We know that we have not been
able to upgrade the system fast enough to meet the expectations of
many customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``And we also know there are people out there just waiting for
all this promised competition that they heard would come with the
new communications legislation.''
</P>
<P>
   MediaOne still has, in a sense, two steps to take before it can
match what BellSouth is offering many Atlantans now. It must first
complete its upgrade of the cable systems it operates in vast
reaches of Atlanta, and then it can turn to offering ``a digital
tier'' of services that would roughly compare to the 160-channel
service being rolled out by BellSouth.
</P>
<P>
   Neither company will be able to accommodate everybody this year.
MediaOne must complete its upgrade, and BellSouth must figure out
ways to reach more homes of Atlantans who live on hills and in
valleys in this tree-shrouded city.
</P>
<P>
   MediaOne has one sure advantage. Eventually it will be able to
reach, with improvements, virtually 100 percent of the customers
the service passes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are confident our digital picture will match theirs,'' said
Griffin. ``And we will also have the advantage of two-way
communication, including phone service and Internet connections. We
are confident we will be all right.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
