<HEADER>
A0096 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REALWORLD-TV-NYT &LR;      06-15 0860
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REALWORLD-TV-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE REAL WORLD': ANOTHER SEASON SHOWING TV'S GRIP ON SOCIETY
</HEADLINE>
   (ja) 
 By CARYN JAMES    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For children of the media age, who have grown up with
MTV and ``Entertainment Tonight,'' the idea of living your life in
front of a camera may not be astonishing. That's one reason MTV
cutting-edge series ``The Real World,'' which begins its seventh
season Tuesday at 10 (check local listing), is central to the
suddenly hot topic of how television and reality shape each other.
</P>
<P>
   More than ``The Truman Show,'' a wafer-thin hit movie pretending
to be profound, and more than all the orchestrated ``Jerry
Springer'' brawls put together, ``The Real World'' blurs the line
between television and private life. More telling, it accepts that
fuzzy line as a given.
</P>
<P>
   In the show, which MTV calls a ``reality-based soap opera,'' men
and women in their early 20s live in a house together for six
months and are trailed by cameras everywhere. Each season offers a
different cast of seven roommates in a different city. This season
happens to be set in Seattle, but that's a detail; so are the
people. The revolving door of characters works because the series'
appeal is the irresistible pull of watching lives, any lives,
unfold without a script.
</P>
<P>
   This is the genuine ``Truman Show,'' but it makes more sense
because the people on camera know they're being filmed and welcome
the attention. ``The Real World'' offers a touchstone of our
culture's connection to the screen: everyone wants to be on
television. And though the series obviously comes from a long
cinema verite tradition, its media-bred young people see no
difference between acting out their lives before a camera and
simply living them.
</P>
<P>
   Their youth has a lot to do with that inbred attitude, and with
the series' energy. College age or just beyond, the roommates
grapple with the spill-it-out issues that obsess people beginning
to find their way. Each cast is selected, it seems, to insure
maximum tension: there are love interests, racial strife,
adolescent navel-gazing, job hunting and, one season, even
abortion.
</P>
<P>
   In Tuesday night's episode the roommates move into a huge
pier-side house furnished to resemble an adult playground. There is
a rock-climbing wall, exercise equipment, an aquarium, a kitchen
counter with stools that looks like a retro diner. The roommates
include two cadets from Virginia Military Institute: Nathan has
left behind a girlfriend who was not chosen for the show and whines
to him endlessly on the phone; David is from a tough neighborhood
outside Boston. Stephen is the only black roommate. Janet is close
to her ambitious Asian-American family. Lindsay is loud and bouncy;
Rebecca a quiet blonde; Irene witty but guarded. They all have been
given jobs at a Seattle radio station.
</P>
<P>
   A shrewd, suspense-enhancing, voyeuristic touch is that anyone
who watched last week's ``Real World Casting Special'' on MTV,
which followed how the roommates were chosen, knows more about them
than they do about one another right now. Of the 14,000 people who
applied to appear on the show, 120 were interviewed as
semi-finalists. In their one-on-one interviews with the casting
directors, Rebecca revealed that she longs to have a family, but is
still a virgin terrified of sex. We also know that Stephen was
raised as a Muslim but converted to Judaism. The yarmulke he wore
in one scene of the casting special has not yet appeared in the
Seattle house.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes the characters talk directly to the camera behind
their roommates' backs, which further blurs the line between living
for the screen and for themselves. The camera becomes one more
friend to complain to or confide in.
</P>
<P>
   Even in the first episode, friendships and tensions are forming.
Stephen and Rebecca feel hurt when the rest of the cast goes to a
bar they can't get into because they are under 21. Someone leaves a
page of a diary lying around, which includes a complaint about the
homogeneous white middle-class makeup of the cast. Stephen, whom
Nathan calls ``the black guy,'' is the obvious suspect, but the
writer turns out to be David, and the issue a matter of class not
race.
</P>
<P>
   The cast's youth, and the show's relatively advanced age, are
factors that have likely caused ``The Real World'' to be ignored in
all the ``Truman''-provoked discussions about television's grip on
society. And people beyond the age of the cast members may not find
their problems intriguing for more than five minutes at a time. But
dipping in and out of other people's lives is precisely what the
current television culture is about.
</P>
<P>
   It is a culture in which being wary of the camera seems bizarre.
At the end of the ``Real World Casting Special,'' cameras watch as
some finalists get phone calls telling them whether they have been
selected. Irene says she threatened the camera crew: If she hadn't
been chosen, they were not leaving with their film. She also says
she became more nervous after having been selected for the show,
more aware that anything she says can turn up on screen. She may be
too thoughtful for the role.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
