<SLUG> BC-CULTURE-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CULTURE NOTES: STATION INSPIRATION; GIVING SCREENWRITERS THEIR DUE;
AWAITING KNIGHTHOOD; GARLANDS OF TALENT  
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., N.Y., Great Britain)  (mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the days after the Franco-Prussian War and the Paris Commune
in 1870-71, Manet, Monet and other Impressionists were attracted to
the Quartier de l'Europe around the Saint-Lazare station in Paris,
where they practiced their art. Some of the results are on view
through Sept. 20 in ``Manet, Monet and the Gare Saint-Lazare'' at
the National Gallery in Washington. Nearly 40 paintings, drawings
and prints include all 11 Monet paintings of the station, exhibited
together for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   Penmanship
</P>
<P>
   Film is generally regarded as a director's medium, but at the
Nantucket Film Festival, which begins Tuesday, screenwriters, who
often get short shrift, are going to get their due. The event, on
Nantucket Island, was created to celebrate original voices in film
and to explore the art of screenwriting, and the third annual
festival, through Sunday, includes for the first time a Writer's
Tribute, sponsored by NBC, on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The honoree is Ring Lardner Jr., who won Oscars for ``Woman of
the Year'' (1942) and MASH (1970) and was one of the Hollywood 10,
who defied the House Committee on Un-American Activities in the
1940s. He was imprisoned and blacklisted during its hunt for
communist influence in Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   By Candlelight
</P>
<P>
   When the Queen of England celebrates her birthday, others can
celebrate, too. This year's birthday honors list includes
knighthoods for the playwright David Hare, author of a current
Broadway attraction, ``The Judas Kiss''; John Mortimer, the
barrister, playwright and novelist who created ``Rumpole of the
Bailey,'' and Ian Holm, the stage and screen actor whose films
include ``Chariots of Fire,'' ``Greystoke, the Legend of Tarzan,
Lord of the Apes'' and ``Henry V.''
</P>
<P>
   Night to Remember
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Lorna Luft will serve as co-host with Robert Stack
and sing ``San Francisco'' and ``The Man That Got Away.'' Bebe
Neuwirth will sing ``Zing! Went the Strings of My Heart.'' And
there will be contributions by everyone from Lionel Bart, Betty
Comden, Adolph Green and Lea DeLaria to Nancy Dussault, Gogi Grant,
Robert Goulet, Skitch Henderson, Jack Jones, Alan King, Robert
Morse and Elaine Stritch. And that's not all who are scheduled to
turn out at 7:30 Tuesday night and Wednesday night at Carnegie
Hall.
</P>
<P>
   The real question is: Who could call forth such an army of
talent? The answer is: Judy Garland. The occasion is ``Carnegie
Hall Celebrates the Music of Judy Garland,'' two different programs
that recall Garland's sold-out concerts at Carnegie in the spring
of 1961. The performances, with original orchestrations,
reminiscences and film clips, are the hall's fourth annual
``American Popular Song Celebration,'' surveying the work of a
particular artist, song style or composer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
