<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCIENCE-WATCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCIENCE'S DEFINING MOMENT  
 HARD TIMES FOR GORILLAS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Md.)   (af)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Science, it seems, defies description. At least that's what the
American Physical Society discovered when it set out to try to
define the term.
</P>
<P>
   ``It turned out to be not that easy,'' Robert L. Park, a physics
professor at the University of Maryland, said of the effort by a
small group of members. What they came up with ``was not a bad
definition,'' he said. ``But it was really a definition written for
other scientists.''
</P>
<P>
   That was not what they had in mind. The purpose, Park said, was
to provide a simple definition to help the public sort science from
nonsense.
</P>
<P>
   Every scientific society, he said, is concerned with ``the
frightening growth of antiscience and pseudoscience and all sorts
of wacky substitutes for science.''
</P>
<P>
   Particularly worrisome to the American Physical Society are some
of the claims of alternative medicine, which, Park said, ``violate
the principles of physics.'' A solid definition of what science is
would make it easier for the society to refute such claims.
</P>
<P>
   But the group's statement proved to be far from straightforward.
``We used words like `falsifiable,' which the public is confused
by,'' Park said. ``They're words that philosophers of science love
to use.'' He said that the group would try again, this time
enlisting other scientific societies to write a consensus
definition.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps science is like pornography, as described by Justice
Potter Stewart in a 1963 Supreme Court case. Stewart wrote that he
wouldn't bother to define hard-core smut, but that ``I know it when
I see it.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe so. But the fact that some legitimate scientists have
endorsed spurious pseudoscientific claims, Park said, makes it
important to try to define the term.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, there are even some scientists who don't know it
when they see it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Henry Fountain &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The lowland eastern gorillas live in turbulent times. A civil
war in their home nation, Congo, has left many guns in the hands of
poachers, and people are encroaching on the gorillas' forests. A
recent survey of the gorilla territory, which spans about 35,000
square miles, found that most of the animals are holding their own
for now, but their survival is becoming more precarious.
</P>
<P>
   The lowland eastern, or Grauer's, gorillas have generally not
received the attention paid to western and mountain gorillas
because they live in such inaccessible areas. The logistics of the
Grauer's gorilla survey, published in the April issue of the
journal Oryx and conducted from 1994 to 1996, required the planning
of a military excursion.
</P>
<P>
   To keep from disturbing the gorillas, researchers counted nests,
then tracked at least three gorillas to verify that the nests were
fresh. ``You could often see a little smooth place in a nest that
was a small bed for an infant,'' said Ilambu Omari, a biologist at
Kahuzi-Biega National Park, where many of the animals live.
</P>
<P>
   The Wildlife Conservation Society, based at the Bronx Zoo, paid
for most of the research, working with Congo's park service.
</P>
<P>
   While gorillas seem to be doing relatively well in parks, groups
in other areas, like Kasese, have been thinned by hunting.
Kahuzi-Biega staff members need only look at one of their
favorites, a gorilla named Lamb Chop who is missing a hand, to be
reminded of how wire snares set by hunters are maiming gorillas.
</P>
<P>
   In the mountainous eastern end of Kahuzi-Biega, more people are
moving into the gorillas' forests to flee areas largely stripped of
trees during the sojourn of Rwandan refugees.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are worried,'' Omari said. ``Everyone speaks of human
rights, and that is good. But the gorillas have a right to survive,
too. They are suffering.''
</P>
<P>
   Karen Freeman &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
