A0108 &Cx1f; paxxx
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STATES-RIDGE-PA     06-15 0367
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-RIDGE-PA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     
 &HT;    
 &HT;      RIDGE CALLS ON FATHERS TO STAY HOME
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;     By Paul Kane  
 &HT;    c. 1998 States News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, June 15 -- Gov. Tom Ridge railed against the plague
of absentee fathers Monday and called on federal and state
governments to push for more grants to private, community-based
groups that could teach today's youths the importance of parenting.
</P>
<P>
   ``You see, any male can father a child. But it takes a real man
to be a father to a child,'' the Republican governor told the
Second National Summit on Fatherhood, a meeting of some of the
leading public and private male figures in Washington assembled to
come up with ideas make young fathers more responsible.
</P>
<P>
   Ridge appeared with a cross section of figures, including Vice
President Al Gore, representatives from the Promise Keepers and
Robert Goodwin, executive director of the National Points of Light
Foundation, which was founded by President Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Noting that nearly four out of 10 children ``will go to sleep at
night in a home without a father,'' Ridge said fatherless children
are five times more likely to live in poverty and they make up 70
percent of violent, long-term violent criminals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until we address the crisis of family, specifically father
absent families, the promise of a better, brighter tomorrow will
not be part of the personal dream of hundreds of thousands of our
children,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   His recipe for the problem relied on community efforts backed up
with state grants, similar to Pennsylvania's mentoring grants
designed to teach teens how to be a father. He cited the Fathers
Workshop in Erie and the Young Fathers Workshop in Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   But Ridge's proposals came laced with some ideological rhetoric
as he pushed conservative approaches, saying there should not be
any new government programs to run these outreach efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Government can't love. Government can't nurture. Government
can't teach your child to ride a bike, help with homework, or wipe
away the tears after a scraped knee,'' he said. ``There has never
been, nor will ever be, a well intentioned government program that
can be a surrogate or a substitute for a father who loves a
child.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
