<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAKERY-SUIT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WONDER BREAD SUED FOR DISCRIMINATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LANCE WILLIAMS  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Fifteen black employees of Wonder Bread have
filed a racial discrimination lawsuit against the nation's largest
bakery, saying Wonder's small African-American workforce here is
subject to a steady barrage of racial jokes and insults.
</P>
<P>
   In their complaint, the 15 men _ who say they represent nearly
half of all the blacks the company employs in the San Francisco
area _ say Wonder's local operation is so inhospitable to black
workers that it's known as ``the White House.'' The workers are
seeking $260 million in damages.
</P>
<P>
   According to the lawsuit, the company refuses to hire new black
employees in San Francisco and won't promote the ones it has. The
suit contends that black workers are given worse jobs and cut far
less slack than other employees.
</P>
<P>
   There is even a rule that bans blacks _ but not members of other
racial groups _ from talking to one another or ``congregating,''
the lawsuit says.
</P>
<P>
   Wonder's parent, Kansas City, Mo.-based Interstate Brands Corp.,
says it strives to maintain a workplace that is free from racial
discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Dirkes, Interstate Brands' senior vice president, said the
company was aware of the lawsuit but could not comment on
specifics.
</P>
<P>
   But, he said, ``We're clearly an equal opportunity employer, and
we don't tolerate discrimination.''
</P>
<P>
   Interstate Brands is a $3 billion-per-year food giant with 63
regional bakeries, making it the nation's largest baker. In
addition to Wonder Bread, it makes Home Pride bread and Hostess
cupcakes.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit was filed in San Francisco Superior Court by former
San Francisco Supervisor Angela Alioto, the lawyer representing the
men.
</P>
<P>
   According to the suit, Wonder employs 683 workers in the San
Francisco area. Of them, 31 are black.
</P>
<P>
   The company's management in the San Francisco area includes no
blacks, the lawsuit says, and except for one bakery foreman, every
African-American employee of Wonder Bread is still in an
entry-level job, it claims. One man, plaintiff Winston Foote, has
been in an entry-level job in the bakery's sanitation department
for 28 years.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, the company has hired only a handful of black
workers, the complaint says. Foote alleged in the lawsuit that when
he asked why blacks weren't being hired, a supervisor responded,
``They are too lazy.''
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit is peppered with allegations of discriminatory
treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Theodis Carroll, 32, contended in the suit that soon after he
went to work in the bread-wrapping room in 1995, it became evident
that blacks were being singled out for bad treatment.
</P>
<P>
   White and Latino workers were permitted longer breaks than
blacks, and received better on the-job training, he said. Black
workers also tended to be assigned to work at bread-wrapping
machines that were older and more prone to breakdown, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll alleged that at one point, management ordered black
workers not to ``congregate'' in the bakery, citing a fear of
gangs. No such rule was enforced against other races, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't like for the blacks to get together and talk, but
the white guys are sitting down there on the floor (of the bakery)
and that's OK,'' he said. ``Me, I like to talk to everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the company did nothing to stop supervisors from using
racially tinged or abusive language.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
