<P>
   COURT-TRUST-ACCOUNTS _ WASHINGTON _ The Supreme Court, ruling
5-4 in a Texas case, said Monday that interest earned from pooled
short-term trust accounts that lawyers hold for their clients
belongs to the clients and cannot be used for charitable purposes.
(Harlan, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   LOW-INCOME-HOUSING _ WASHINGTON _ The Center on Budget and
Policy Priorities releases a report showing that the shortage of
low-cost rental housing on the United States reached a record high
in 1995. (Carr, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGNS _ Funded by the Pew Charitable Trust, a Washington
non-profit is launching a campaign to improve the local media
coverage of political contests in 10 states around the country. The
Alliance for Better Campaigns believes voters will get more
information about candidates and issues if local television
stations give more coverage to the races. The Alliance formally
launches the effort June 15 with a television ad created by a
Democratic and Republican ad maker, both of whom are known for
aggressive, negative campaign tactics. (Foskett, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   FORD-JEWELS _A metro Atlanta jeweler who helped recover stolen
jewels from the Ford family in Palm Beach, Fla., claims the Ford's
are stiffing him on the promised $1 million reward. The jeweler
spotted the stolen emerald when a customer brought it in to be
reset. A friend of the jeweler spotted a picture of the jewel on
the internet, posted by Palm Beach P.D. That led to the arrest of
the thief. But the Ford family has yet to turn over the $1 million
and the jeweler has hired his own attorney. (Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) WITH PHOTOS
</P>
<P>
   SOUTH-FUTURE _ LOUISVILLE, Ky._The Commission on the Future of
the South issues its annual report Monday. We report on what the
commission said and other matters involving the Southern Growth
Policies Board, which oversees the project. (Burritt, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-CHRISTIAN _ FORT WORTH, Texas _ In a political year when
the GOP treats him as a political deity, about the only Republicans
who don't profess undying belief in Gov. George W. Bush are members
of the Christian Coalition. They are backing him for re-election,
but some are not ready to sign on for a possible Bush presidential
race. (Herman, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   JASPER-COMMENTARY _ There was a time _ just a few days ago _
that when asked of my hometown, the talk took a long, explanatory
path. No longer, however, is such a long detailed description
needed of my hometown. For my hometown is Jasper, Texas, and most
have formed their own mental image of that little town buried deep
in the dark, brooding woods of East Texas. (Reetz, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   NO-BOMB _ WACO, Texas _ Postal workers sorting through packages
at 5:30 this morning found a package making a ``beeping or
humming'' noise. Notified manager, who took the package out to the
far corner of the Highway 6 post office's employee parking lot and
called police. Fort Hood bomb squad called in along with local
authorities to check out the suspicious package. Took about four
hours to identify contents as clothes and a portable cassette
player with headphones and batteries included, which caused the
player to turn on and make the noise. Customers were not prevented
access to the post office during the investigation. (Waco
Tribune-Herald)
</P>
<P>
   TRIGBOY _ WACO, Texas _ Midway junior Joseph Short, winner of
the state TrigStar trigonometry competition, took the national test
today along with one other Texas student and up to two students
from the other 49 states. He completed the state test in 8 minutes,
50 seconds, but the national test stumped him with its one problem
dealing with determining the length of guy wires on a radio tower.
(Waco Tribune-Herald)
</P>
<P>
   HOT- WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Is Florida withering under the
hottest temperatures ever for a June? We check in with growers,
Disney, FPL, enviro officials on the health alert, forestry for
brush fires around the state, etc. And we answer the big question:
Why is it so damn hot. We're caught in a vicious weather circle:
High pressure pushing down on us does not let rain clouds form.
Crop loss in North Florida could be as much $100 million. (King,
Palm Beach)
</P>
