<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEVENDOSKY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(JT) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 YOUTH TO REJUVENATE OUR AILING NATIONAL PARKS  (EDITOR'S NOTE:
Charles Levendosky, editorial page editor of the Casper (Wyo.)
Star-Tribune, has a national reputation for First Amendment
commentary. His e-mail address is levendos(AT-sign)trib.com.)  By CHARLES LEVENDOSKY    
 c. 1998 Casper (Wyo.) Star-Tribune    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   National Park Service Director Robert Stanton promised to
involve more young people in the park system when he accepted the
top parks job last year. This month, he took a giant step toward
keeping that promise.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview last August, Stanton said, `I believe it's
critically important that we work with youth-serving organizations
... to give our youth the opportunity to experience their own
national parks ... It helps them to become better citizens in terms
of greater appreciation of their own natural and cultural
heritage.`
</P>
<P>
   On June 8, the NPS kicked off a Public Land Corps Youth Program
with restoration work on the Chesapeake and Ohio Canal National
Historic Park in Maryland. Fifty young people from the Student
Conservation Association and the Montgomery County Conservation
Corps began clearing out the woody vegetation from culverts and
locks of the canal. And this is only the beginning.
</P>
<P>
   In this first year, more than $3 million has been committed for
much needed maintenance projects in our national parks. This year
nearly 100 national parks will be involved in the program that will
rebuild trails, restore campgrounds and cabins, and remove
non-native vegetation and trash from campsites.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview Friday, Stanton commented on the new program:
`This is a tremendous opportunity to expand the involvement of
young people in conservation, resource preservation, and
maintenance work in our parks.`
</P>
<P>
   Some of the money for the program comes from the recreational
fee demonstration program that allows the National Park Service to
retain revenues generated _ to be used for repairs and maintenance
projects. The recreational fee program, according to Stanton, will
generate an estimated $135 million this year.
</P>
<P>
   `We wanted to actively engage other youth-serving organizations
in a partnership, in which they could bring their expertise, their
leadership skills, as well as some of their resources to the park
programs,` Stanton said. `For each park there is a partnership
organization involved. For example, in Yellowstone National Park
(Wyo.) we will have young people working on projects and they will
be recruited by and supervised by the Montana Conservation Corps.
</P>
<P>
   `We envision this as long term _ to continue to involve the
young people in the Public Land Corps ... work that is commensurate
with the capabilities of the young people _ doing trail
rehabilitation, sign rehabilitation, and other maintenance work
that is critically important, but lends itself to a day-to-day
staff as opposed to a major contract. The program gives us an
opportunity to match up the need with the capability of the young
people.`
</P>
<P>
   In Yellowstone, one Public Land Corps project will restore and
reroute DeLacy Creek Trail, one of the most heavily used hiking
trails in the park. The condition of the trail has seriously
deteriorated over the years. Hikers using the trail in the spring
when parts of it are under creek water end up tramping and
destroying sensitive wetlands areas.
</P>
<P>
   Before the end of June, an eight person crew from the Montana
Conservation Corps will be working alongside and supervised by a
NPS trail crew to relocate the trail away from DeLacy Creek and
important riparian areas. The project is scheduled to take no more
than six weeks to complete.
</P>
<P>
   There are a number of other PLC projects scheduled for
Yellowstone _ restoration and stabilization of campgrounds and
other trails and repairing or removing fences _ in partnership with
the Student Conservation Association and the Youth Conservation
Corps.
</P>
<P>
   PLC projects in 40 states and the District of Columbia will
begin this month _ including restoration and repair projects in
Redwood National Park (Calif.), Grand Canyon National Park (Ariz.),
Dinosaur National Monument (Colo.), Craters of the Moon National
Monument (Idaho), Glacier National Park (Mont.), Bryce Canyon
National Park (Utah), Blue Ridge Parkway (Va.), and Mount Rainier
National Park (Wash.).
</P>
<P>
   Youth from the Sitka Tribe will repair eroded trails in the
Sitka National Historic Park in Alaska.
</P>
<P>
   Eight students from the Rocky Mountain Youth Corps will work to
reconstruct eroded trails in the Rocky Mountain National Park in
Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   A community service group called the Juvenile Diversion Program,
aimed at preventing youth crime and violence in small Colorado
towns, will help fight the spread of non-native vegetation in the
Great Sand Dunes National Monument by pulling the exotic plants out
by hand.
</P>
<P>
   Volunteers from the Youth Conservation Corps will assist in
restoring an historic cabin in Yosemite National Park's back
country in California.
</P>
<P>
   Youth corps query national parks nearby to find out what backlog
maintenance or restoration needs to be done. Corps officials write
grant requests for PLC funding for a particular work project in the
national park. If the request is authorized, the youth corps then
accepts volunteers and supervises them under the direction of park
rangers.
</P>
<P>
   Each youth group in the PLC partnership pays its student workers
differently _ some only pay living expenses, then after the work is
completed, an educational stipend of nearly $5,000 for a year
commitment or half that for a six-month commitment. But there are
youth programs that pay minimum wage for participating in
conservation projects that last only four to eight weeks.
</P>
<P>
   More than a thousand young people from the ages of 16 to 20 will
participate in helping restore our national parks this year. While
that number is relatively small, it is only the beginning of a new
kind of investment in our youth and in our national parks.
</P>
<P>
   It's a bold move that highlights the best spirit of our youth
and entrusts the future of one of the great heritages of this
nation to their willing and able hands.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
