A0131 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MSKUBE-COLUMN16-COX     06-15 0824
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MSKUBE-COLUMN16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN:30 years after Dr. King's death: Have things changed that
much?
 &HT;    By Michael Skube
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA--On Saturday afternoon, while most people were out
enjoying the weekend, she holed up in her room at a Atlanta hotel,
a New Yorker writing a freelance article for a newspaper in
Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   Mentally if not physically, Tamar Jacoby has been bounding back
and forth, from New York to Detroit to Atlanta, for several years
now. In her mind the three cities form a triangle of American
tragedy. Each in its own way is representative not only of
Americans' disenchantment with integration but, even more, an
acceptance of a new racial separatism.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't supposed to work this way. The legal barriers of the
past are museum pieces, as strange to our eyes as a ``Whites only''
sign, and yet we're as divided as ever. In some ways, more so. How
often do you hear people talking hopefully, optimistically of
integration? Thirty years after the Rev. Martin Luther King Jr.'s
assassination, that dream's been given up.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Tamar Jacoby visited the Martin Luther King Visitors
Center on Auburn Avenue. She spent time in the hallowed Ebenezer
Baptist Church, cradle of the civil rights movement. She had been
there before, researching her recently published book ``Someone
Else's House: America's Unfinished Struggle for Integration'' (Free
Press).
</P>
<P>
   At the church, a nine-minute videotape highlighted its history
before King's emergence and after. The church's pastor, the Rev.
Joseph L. Roberts, spoke earnestly of King's gospel of nonviolence.
Across the street, at the Visitors Center, photos, films and other
exhibits memorialized the same gospel and recorded the angry
resistence it met in Selma and Birmingham, in rural Mississippi, in
a Chicago suburb.
</P>
<P>
   Here, in this quiet church, at this museum, you had a sense of
history in a city that otherwise hasn't much time for history. Yet
in neither church nor museum was there unambiguous emphasis on what
King's gospel was really about: Laying down once and for all the
burden of race and living together as one people.
</P>
<P>
   ``In our heart of hearts,'' Jacoby said, King said that
underneath, we're basically the same; Malcolm said we're basically
different.''
</P>
<P>
   Jacoby was in town on a book tour, her local stops including a
signing Monday night at Chapter 11 bookstore in the Ansley Mall.
She is a slender, sharp-featured woman in her early 40s, a New
Yorker by upbringing and a former deputy editor of The New York
Times op-ed page. Like many in her generation, she came of age in
the civil rights movement and regarded King as a figure who
transcended his time.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the late 1950s, when King came along,'' Jacoby says,
``things were starting to change. People knew segregation was
wrong. But King took it a huge leap forward. He crystallized the
vision of people, the ideal of one communty, which is a lot more
than just getting rid of the legal barriers. It was almost as if we
had overcome.''
</P>
<P>
   Almost ... But somewhere we lost our way. We became persuaded
that the ideal was not, in King's words, ``a beloved community,''
rooted in mutuality, but instead something called ``diversity,''
each group wary of the other, each properly respectful of
unbridgeable ``differences.''
</P>
<P>
   Jacoby's reservoirs of optimism are deep, but not bottomless.
She tells of a course she taught last year at a college in New
York. Many of her students were black, not the familiar products of
the inner city but young people reared in middle class families.
Their future held promise. But even they, she said, saw the
classroom as another expression of a ``white culture.''
</P>
<P>
   ``One of them told me, `When we come in here we have to leave
our culture behind,''' Jacoby says, mystified. ``I asked, `How can
that be? Why do learning and studying have to be cultural
things?'''
</P>
<P>
   In her book, Jacoby makes New York, Detroit and Atlanta test
cases in the evolution of race relations, Atlanta because it was
here more than anywhere that King's dream should have been
realized. It had always been a biracial city, one that had largely
avoided ugly confrontation.
</P>
<P>
   But even here, in the city where it was born, King's dream has
meant a kind of peaceful coexistence. ``Deep down,'' one black
professional told her, ``the black middle class in Atlanta is still
integrationist.'' A middle-class white man told her: ``That
spiritual, theological strain in the civil right movement in our
way, we hold on to that.''
</P>
<P>
   What was unsaid was that both white and black are at impasse,
like spouses who have had a falling out, neither wanting to give up
the marriage, both hoping the other will come forward in
reconciliation. Two people can live in the same house without
making a home together.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: mskube(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
