<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Magazine picks best places to live
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you're a twentysomething looking for a place to settle, check
out this month's issue of Swing ($2.95). The Gen-X mag lists the
country's 10 hottest urban centers and the three best areas in each
city to live. In Atlanta, Swing selected East Atlanta as the best
bet, followed by Decatur and Cabbagetown. East Atlanta Village,
near Grant Park, is described as a multicultural neighborhood of
gay, straight, Latino, African-American and Caucasian where starter
houses cost $65,000 to $90,000.
</P>
<P>
   SURF'S UP: This week's Entertainment Weekly ($2.50) has a full
page touting its new EW Internet supplement, but not all of the
magazines have the insert. None of the newsstand issues have it and
only 400,000 of EW's subscribers. ``We've targeted the subscriber
list according to our research as to who is online,'' says EW
publicist Sandy Drayton. ``But anyone who wants to get a free copy
of EW Internet issue can register on our website
(http://www.ew.com) or by calling 800-828-6882.''
</P>
<P>
   Drayton says EW Internet _ a miniature version of the magazine _
will be devoted to online and multimedia articles. Included in the
first issue are a critique of the games unveiled at the recent
Eleectronic Entertainment Expo in Atlanta and a guide to the best
entertainment web sites. The next insert will appear in September,
with six supplements scheduled for 1999.
</P>
<P>
   BEHIND PALACE WALLS: Interest in monarchies waned a bit after
the death of Princess Diana, but the fascination with kings and
queens and sheikhs and princesses is still strong. While giving
special attention to Prince William, Life ($3.95) devotes this
week's issue to 28 monarchies around the world. Included is a
genealogical chart that traces the 10 heirs of Europe back to one
17th-century German prince.
</P>
<P>
   IS THE TRUTH OUT THERE? When it comes to keeping secrets, the
federal government could take some lessons from Chris Carter.
According to Newsweek's ($2.95) cover story, the creator of ``The
X-Files'' was so obsessed with maintaining secrecy around the movie
that scripts were printed on non-copyable red paper. Phony pages
were leaked and disinformation spread over the Internet. One rumor
that is not true, Carter tells Newsweek, is that Duchovny fans will
get a naked rear view of him in the movie.
</P>
<P>
   In a separate issue this week, Newsweek celebrates a century of
movies with a list of the American Film Institute's 100 greatest
American movies of all time. The magazine, which hits newsstands
Wednesday, contains essays by directors Steven Spielberg, Martin
Scorsese, film critic Pauline Kael and author Gore Vidal.
</P>
<P>
   THE GREATEST? Time's ($2.95) timing is as perfect as that of the
magazine's cover subject: Michael Jordan. Thanks to Jordan's
heroics, the Chicago Bulls won their sixth NBA title as Time was en
route to subscribers. Editor Daniel Okrent concedes that Jordan is
the greatest athlete in the United States, but picks Brazilian
soccer star Pele as the greatest in the world.
</P>
<P>
   BRIDAL PATH: In a special ``Love &AMP; Marriage'' issue, People
($3.95) reports on the most memorable celebrity weddings of the
year, from superheroes (Lucy Lawless and Rob Tapert, Kevin Sorbo
and Sam Jenkins) to superstars (Will Smith and Jada Pinkett, Sharon
Stone and Phil Bronstein). Among the trends People noted: pets,
medieval costumes and bubbles (instead of rice) were part of
wedding ceremonies; more wedding pictures are being shot in black
and white; and red meat is back. Both Lawless and Kelsey Grammer
opted for rack of lamb.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
