<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-15 17:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0142 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PATTERNS-FASHION-NYT &LR;      06-15 0710
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PATTERNS-FASHION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FASHION NOTES AND NEWS  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By CONSTANCE C.R. WHITE    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Johnnie Walker Man
</P>
<P>
   The fact that fashion has become a tenet of pop culture has not
been lost on marketers. Increasingly, style has become an engine of
marketing for companies like Johnnie Walker, the liquor label. This
fall, Johnnie Walker will introduce a men's sportswear and
accessories collection, to be sold exclusively in Bloomingdale's
stores and its Christmas catalog.
</P>
<P>
   More than the usual promotional baseball cap and logo-emblazoned
jacket that liquor and tobacco companies favor, the line is being
designed by Jeffrey Banks. For four years ending in 1997, Banks was
the designer for the Bloomingdale's men's-wear label. The Johnnie
Walker collection signifies a re-emergence for Banks, who has kept
a low profile since blowing onto the fashion scene with his own
collection in the early 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   This fall he will introduce his own signature men's sportswear
line, as well.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who knows Banks' oeuvre _ understated, preppy _ will
already sense that the Johnnie Walker line won't boast boxer shorts
printed with liquor bottles. But the brand's recognizable logo, a
jaunty silhouette of a man in a top hat, will be evident on some
shirt hems and breast pockets. ``It's not on everything,'' Banks
said. ``I've tried to keep it dignified and discreet.''
</P>
<P>
   The company has made the prime target for its clothes the same
as for its Scotch, the upwardly mobile young man. ``This is the guy
two years ago who wore his baseball cap backwards, drank beer out
of a can and wore baggy jeans,'' Banks said. ``He now wears a
$1,000 suit and is working on Wall Street, he's smoking cigars,
drinking Cosmopolitans, and he wants to look as good on the
weekends as he does during the week.''
</P>
<P>
   It was Marvin Traub, the president of the marketing consultancy
Marvin Traub Associates and a senior adviser to Financo, an
investment company, who recommended that Johnnie Walker go into the
fashion business. The company had approached Traub, a former
chairman of Bloomingdale's, looking for a way to leverage its
brand.
</P>
<P>
   ``As I look at many of the global brands that are becoming
broader and broader in their range, they started with fashion,''
Traub said. ``You look at Ralph Lauren, who is the epitome, who's
now in paint.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnnie Walker clothing is to be introduced during the spring
1999 New York men's-wear shows, to be held from July 27 through 30.
</P>
<P>
   The Barneys Woman
</P>
<P>
   What's good enough for men, women want, too. Understanding this,
Barneys New York continues to expand its women's clothing to
include not just cutting-edge fashion but also the luxury classics
on which it built its renowned men's-wear business. Next month,
Barneys plans to introduce the feminine counterparts of three
high-end men's lines: Huntsman, a top Savile Row label, which
Barneys has sold for almost 20 years; Piatelli, an Italian luxury
collection, and Battistoni, also from Italy, which supplies Barneys
with ties and shirts, many made to order.
</P>
<P>
   In one sense, these new women's lines are meant to replace the
traditional clothing that Barneys has offered under its signature
line, which is presently undergoing a face lift.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been moving more and more to fine tailoring and luxury
fabrics as customers have shown more of an interest in fine
tailoring,'' said Judy Collinson, an executive vice president of
Barneys. ``What this ultimately allows us to do is focus our own
collection on more fashion with more of a designer edge to it.''
</P>
<P>
   The women's lines will adhere to the spirit of their male
counterparts, with men's-wear fabrics and custom service _ and high
price. Jackets will range from $625 to $1,850; skirts and kilts,
$235 to $535, and trousers, $250 to $495. A corduroy coat from
Huntsman is $875, and a cashmere topper from Battistoni is $2,295.
</P>
<P>
   The lines will be on the sixth floor, near the reconstituted
store collection. The Barneys New York line is to reappear in July
as Barneys New York Collection: Taste, Luxury, Humor. Fans of the
store will be left to figure out just who among the colorful
executives at Barneys is Taste, who is Luxury and who is Humor.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
