<HEADER>
A0148 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEAH-SFCHRON-PERSONAL     06-15 0755
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH-SFCHRON-PERSONALS </SLUG>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; TIMELY SHOPPING SUGGESTIONS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; A &UR; lain Samson &LR;  is grateful to the Wherehouse for ``capturing
the spirit of Father's Day'' in an ad in Sunday's San Francisco
Chronicle that suggested, ``Movies Make Great Gifts for Dad.'' The
five video suggestions included two movies featuring guns (``The
Longest Day,'' ``Terminator 2''), two about sports (Major League
Baseball highlights and ``Greatest Moments in Sports'') and one
about breasts (Playboy's ``Babes of Baywatch'').
</P>
<P>
   P.S. Just in case that new stadium gets built for the 49ers,
sentimental fans like  &UR; Gordon Bergman  &LR;  will surely want the
Danbury Mint's ``Candlestick Park,'' a porcelain and resin version
``hand painted by skilled artisans'' of ``one of the most
recognizable football stadiums in history.'' This $49.50 tchotchke
enables fans to ``own an authentic replica of this legendary
stadium which has become synonymous with San Francisco.''
</P>
<P>
   P.P.S. Arion Press, the Rolls-Royce of limited-edition
publishers, is planning a limited edition of the New Revised
Standard Version of the Bible, the Cadillac of good books. The
volume will contain 1,200 pages, each 18 by 13 inches, and weigh 25
pounds; 400 copies will be made. The leather-bound boxed edition
costs $8,500, plus $2,500 more for illuminated initials.
</P>
<P>
   P.P.P.S. Not quite right for Father's Day, but elsewhere in the
wide world of cajoling rabbits into parting with lettuce, the
latest advertising campaign by Noxzema is a series of small signs
that will be placed on the mirrors of ladies' rooms in trendy
restaurants and clubs in Manhattan. Among the messages: ``It's not
the lighting,'' ``Look as good as the woman your date is hitting
on,'' ``He must really love you for your inner beauty'' and ``Did
someone miss her beauty sleep?'' The slogan for the product, below
these endearing words: ``Next time Noxzema.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THEY LIKE TO WATCH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Kate Coleman &LR; , who lives in Berkeley, was disappointed when
her TCI Cablevision bill for last month didn't include a promised
rebate for the end-of-``Seinfeld'' day the cable went out. Not one
to take things lying down, Coleman called and threaded her way
through a knot of bureaucrats until she found one with the
information, which was, Coleman said, only given to subscribers who
``called and made a stink.'' TCI gave her permission to deduct
$1.18 from her bill.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Paddy Morrissey &LR;  saw a bumper sticker in Berkeley that said,
``Actions speak louder than bumper stickers.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Tele-Tubbies'' fans  &UR; Leonard Joseph &LR;  and  &UR; Erich Lara &LR;  saw a
scene filmed at the University of San Francisco's basketball court,
broadcast twice on Tubby Po's tummy. The footage showed a father
teaching his son to shoot hoops.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; _ All the excitement over bringing Chez Panisse concepts to
the Louvre reminded one reader of talks 10 years ago between
restaurateur  &UR; Alice Waters  &LR; and the Oakland Museum. Waters'
proposal for a museum restaurant, including such innovations as a
wood-fired pizza oven and a vegetable garden, were met with
enthusiasm from the staff and board members. But the plan became a
chip in a political dispute between the museum's director at the
time and board members and never came to fruition.
</P>
<P>
   The museum's  &UR; Abby Wasserman  &LR; was wistful to think that Oakland
had a crack at what may be created in France. ``Alice Waters is
synonymous with California cuisine,'' she said, ``and we are the
museum of California. It was a foolish thing.''
</P>
<P>
   _ What's with Federal Express' flyer for its new Sunday delivery
service? One side of a broadsheet is an attempt to imitate a
newspaper, including an advice column whose authors use the Yiddish
word ``ferklempt,'' a fictional story about a cotton ball
manufacturer named ``Herbie Zitter,'' a fictional story quoting
``Federal Preserve Board'' chairman ``Alvin Greenspud'' and a
fictional story about deliveries from the ``Bagel Boys'' of
Saginaw, Mich.
</P>
<P>
   Is FedEx hoping for new business from Jews who work on Sunday
instead of Saturday? Did the creators of the flyer think that Jews
were likely to be Type A businessmen desperate for Sunday
deliveries?
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; ``More and more I look out and see someone with five nose
piercings and HATE tattooed across his forehead and I'm flattered.
That's awesome.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Dave Matthews in Spin magazine, which calls him rock's new
alpha male.
</P>
</TEXT>
