<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-15 18:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0156 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FASHION-ESQUIRE-STYLI     06-15 1410
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASHION-ESQUIRE-STYLIST-700&AMP;add-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMING UP FROM THE STYLIST GHETTO  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By AMY M. SPINDLER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI BEACH _ Miami is a sexy town, and Tony Melillo is the
hottest designer in residence, dressing South Beach tourists like
Leonardo DiCaprio and Barry Diller. So when he calls the Mix the
best-after hours club in the world, it's almost worth staying up
till 4:30 in the morning, when it opens. Almost.
</P>
<P>
   Just as Melillo was walking the five blocks from his apartment
to the club, the skies opened up, and everyone in the line outside
the door got soaked. Rain is a great equalizer, the perfect
accessory to wear to the Mix (Studio 54 if the velvet ropes had
been manned by Jerry Springer): rave kids with glow sticks, drag
queens, conventioneers discussing units sold, stoned surfers and
teen-age girls in side-slit miniskirts. It isn't exactly where, two
years after Melillo quit as fashion editor of elitist Esquire
magazine, anyone would expect to find him, cloaked in the privacy
of smoke, technobass and club-worthy clothes he designed.
</P>
<P>
   But Melillo, 33, has for a decade been one of fashion's most
conspicuous chameleons, adapting personas like trends: the English
aristocrat, the European playboy, the American gigolo. His latest
incarnation, hip designer, sends him into the Mix for inspiration,
wearing trousers he cut loose like jams and a muscle T-shirt with
the name of his company, Nova, emblazoned on the front.
</P>
<P>
   He's taking his new role seriously. On June 8, he left for
Korea, to work on production. On June 12, he was in Japan, to do
store appearances and television interviews. By June 22, he'll be
in New York to look at a possible boutique space on Elizabeth
Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything is fitted on me,'' he said. ``I do the whole
collection myself, take it out, wear it to a nightclub, then do my
corrections on it.''
</P>
<P>
   He's doing such a good job that when his store was broken into
soon after opening, the thieves stole clothes, not cash. Ron
Herman-Fred Segal in Los Angeles has sold more than 200 pairs of
his judo pants at $55 each.
</P>
<P>
   Nina Garduno, a vice president of that store, besides calling
Melillo the ``most charismatic person I've ever met,'' said he is
the first designer since the Prada and Gucci breakthroughs to go
after the casual sportswear market dominated for so long by generic
looks from the Gap.
</P>
<P>
   ``The response from the customer has been incredible, whether a
rock star or a regular person,'' Ms. Garduno said. ``They want
their own clothes, to look like themselves, and to create something
on their body. It's casual sportswear for the chicest people.''
</P>
<P>
   After years of doing what stylists and fashion editors do,
promoting and glorifying other people's creations, Melillo is
creating something himself. ``It's torture being a stylist,'' he
said. ``Especially when you're doing advertising. For a two-year
period, I went poor. I struggled. Clients didn't like me. They
said, `Tony came late, and left early, and sat in a room and didn't
talk to anybody.' And it was all true.''
</P>
<P>
   Top stylists and editors in fashion, years after making names
for themselves, have developed imprints even stronger than those of
many designers. Which is why a few have taken to charging $30,000
consultation fees for shows on top of their day rate, which
averages $3,000 to $5,000. That consultation can even include
choosing fabrics months before the runway shows, but the stylists
and editors never see the recognition designers get. Or the big
money.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't understand why more stylists don't become designers,''
said Kelly Klein, Melillo's close friend. ``You'd think it would be
a natural extension of their career to do that. You can really see
their mark when the clothes walk down the runway.''
</P>
<P>
   Melillo has a theory about that. ``I grew up a simple person,''
he said. ``If I'm sitting there looking at the wall, and someone
says, `What are you thinking?' I'm thinking about the wall. People
think too much. They think of all the bad things that are going to
happen when they start the company. Maybe it means I'm a little
slow, but I feel fortunate. I'm a street person, with a street
mentality, hustle and jump. I'll jump before weighing it out.''
</P>
<P>
   Melillo carved out a life style familiar in an industry defined
by low pay but big expense accounts, geared to put stylish editors
at the right place at the right time, but not to let them make
enough to escape. Dressing celebrities for Esquire photo shoots, he
befriended a lot of people with opulent life styles, and quickly
learned to live the same way, on his expense account. ``The topper
was the bill for the dog's food at the Ritz in Paris,'' he said.
``It used to come on silver plates.''
</P>
<P>
   He gave up his apartment entirely, living between four-star
hotels. ``I stayed at the Four Seasons in Hollywood for a month to
photograph three people,'' he said. The photographer at the time
was Marc Hom, who said they were lying by the pool for a week
trying to find two more people to photograph. Suddenly, Melillo
grabbed the phone, saying, ``There's this great guy Chad McQueen.''
He got McQueen on the phone.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, ``It would be great to do this picture with you,'''
Hom recalled. ``And can you bring your father?''
</P>
<P>
   Esquire would have had to pay quite a bill if they had waited
for Steve McQueen to show up. ``That's Tony,'' Hom said. ``He's
completely into the idea, forgetting this person has been dead 25
years.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Melillo's playboy days always had a lot of self-parody about
them. When one wealthy woman friend lent him a 10-room apartment on
the Upper East Side rent-free, he pondered hiring a manservent with
the money he was saving. When rumors were flying through the
fashion industry that he was having an affair with a very rich and
very famous rock star, he said, ``I can't believe she's telling
people that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He was having a dalliance with Farah Fawcett, and it was great
because at the time I wanted to interview her,'' recalled Christa
D'Souza, his wife and a writer for British Vogue, who ended up
interviewing Ms. Fawcett with Melillo and Ryan O'Neal in the room.
``I thought, how modern!'' she said. They're still married; Melillo
is the godfather of Flynn, the child Ms. D'Souza just had with
another man. Flynn's photos decorate Nova's walls.
</P>
<P>
   He once showed up wearing gold chains after spending the summer
on someone's yacht in St.-Tropez, France. ``He was so dark he
looked like a cowpat, or he'd put his head up a chimney,'' Ms.
D'Souza said. He's still tan, but now his style, as described by
Ms. Klein, is ``not into wearing too many clothes.'' When he does
wear something, he pulls his trousers so low that he had to design
Speedo-cut underwear for beneath.
</P>
<P>
   Determined to get out of Westchester, Pa., Melillo got his first
job at 19 at Williwear, with his main task being to get the staff
into clubs at night. ``He had an incredible aptitude for it,'' Ms.
D'Souza said. He met her there.
</P>
<P>
   They ended up married, and he decided to go to Milan, where he
sat for two months in the Conde Nast offices trying to get a job as
a fashion editor. His characteristic determination and optimism
paid off; they finally caved in and gave him one at the Italian
magazine Vanity. Terry McDonald later hired him for Smart magazine,
now defunct, where in 1989 he would dress so-called real people in
fashion, like intellectuals from Eastern-bloc countries, or
Milanese architects. McDonald then became editor of Esquire and
hired him there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always had this idea he would design clothing, because he
was always messing with the ideas,'' said McDonald, who is now
editor of Men's Journal. He stressed that an interest in ideas, as
opposed to simply clothing, ``is dimly perceived in some circles.''
But not by Melillo's business partner, who is not a rich, famous
woman but a surfer from Miami, Gregory Frehling, 26, who started
Nova as a small women's label in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Melillo's idea was to use the Nova name and invent a men's line,
where the store was a scene. So when the guest house of Oribe's
former salon in Miami, a coral structure that's the oldest in the
city, was for rent, Melillo took it. He planted the garden himself,
made much of the furniture, and filled it with great clothes. And
now the local surfer kids come hang out all day long.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-15-98 1806EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
