<HEADER>
A0165 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COURT-TRUSTACCOUNT-CO     06-15 0762
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COURT-TRUSTACCOUNT-CO </SLUG>
     LEGAL AID FUNDS FOR POOR IN DOUBT
AFTER HIGH COURT RULING
 &HT;     By CHRISTI HARLAN 
 &HT;     c.1998 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A program that helps pay for legal services for
poor people in 48 states will continue to have legal problems of
its own after the Supreme Court ruled 5-4 Monday that the money
being collected and disbursed does not belong to the states.
</P>
<P>
   The case involves a 17-year-old program that gathers the
interest earned on lawyers' trust accounts, which pool small
amounts of money that lawyers hold for their clients for short
periods. The amounts are too small to earn interest by themselves,
but the pooled accounts generate enough interest that states
distributed almost $100 million last year to groups that provide
legal aid to the poor.
</P>
<P>
   ``A significant setback to poor people's access to legal justice
was created'' with Monday's ruling, said Anne Harvey, litigation
administrator for the American Association of Retired Persons
Foundation. The foundation cited the need for legal assistance to
people having problems collecting Social Security benefits.
</P>
<P>
   The court ruled Monday that the interest that supports the
legal-aid groups belongs to lawyers' clients _ not the state _
despite the state's arguments that the interest wouldn't exist if
it weren't for the program that pools the clients' money, known as
Interest on Lawyers Trust Accounts, or IOLTA. If the money were
placed in individual accounts, the state argued, bank fees would
eat up any interest that was earned.
</P>
<P>
   Chief Justice William Rehnquist, who wrote the majority opinion,
agreed that individual accounts for lawyers' clients would not
generate any interest income, but he said the clients nevertheless
have a stake in the interest that is generated when their money is
pooled.
</P>
<P>
   ``While the interest income at issue here may have no
economically realizable value to its owner,'' Rehnquist wrote,
``possession, control and disposition are nonetheless valuable
rights that inhere in the property.''
</P>
<P>
   Justice David Souter, who wrote one of two dissenting opinions,
said the court created ``an essentially abstract proposition'' by
finding that clients ``own'' interest that wouldn't exist without
the state program.
</P>
<P>
   The majority ruled ``that the interest income generated by funds
held in IOLTA accounts is the `private property' of the owner of
the principal,'' Rehnquist said in his opinion. ``We express no
view as to whether these funds have been `taken' by the State; nor
do we express an opinion as to the amount of `just compensation,'
if any,'' that is due to the clients.
</P>
<P>
   Rehnquist was quoting from part of the 5th Amendment to the
Constitution, which says, ``nor shall private property be taken for
public use without just compensation.''
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court said lower courts will have to decide whether
the interest gathered from clients' money violates the 5th
Amendment. That will spark a new round of litigation in the federal
appeals court in New Orleans and, possibly, before U.S. District
Judge James Nowlin of Austin, Texas, in whose court the case began.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Samp, chief counsel for the Washington Legal Foundation,
which challenged Texas's program, said the group will continue its
efforts to stop the programs in all states that have them. The
foundation objects to some of the uses of the money generated from
the lawyers' accounts, such as litigation to enforce the Voting
Rights Act.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are 90 percent of the way home ... now that it's determined
that there's a property right,'' Samp said.
</P>
<P>
   Until the next round of court battles is over, lawyers for
Texas' legal aid program said it will continue.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's business as usual for us at the foundation,'' said
Richard Royds, a Houston lawyer who chairs the Texas Equal Access
to Justice Foundation, which distributes the money collected from
Texas lawyers' trust accounts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't lose necessarily by their having found a
property-right interest,'' Dallas lawyer Darrell Jordan said of the
five justices who formed the Supreme Court majority. ``We regard
this as a very narrow ruling that leaves IOLTA intact.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan presented the case for Texas' legal aid program in
arguments before the Supreme Court in January. Jordan represents
the Texas Supreme Court, which made the interest-collection program
mandatory for Texas lawyers in 1989. The program, which got its
start in Florida in 1981, was voluntary for Texas lawyers beginning
in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
