<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories that New York Times editors are planning
for the Page 1 of Tuesday, June 16. The N.Y. Times News Service
supervisor is Henry Louis Warnken. The final FRONTPAGE will move
later in the evening.
</P>
<P>
   For copy info: (212) 556-1927.
</P>
<P>
   For graphics, map, photo info: (212) 556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   BOSNIA-NATO (Skopje, Macedonia) _ With conflict in separatist
Kosovo Province intensifying, and diplomats fear, likely to spread
to other Balkan countries, the West has threatened the Yugoslav
president, Slobodan Milosevic, with air strikes unless he stops the
stop using military force against civilians and enters serious
negotiations. To make that message clear more than 80 NATO
warplanes lifted off from 15 European bases Monday morning,
coursing across the skies over the Adriatic Sea and Albania and
Macedonia. By Mike O'Connor.
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-CLIENT (Washington) _ The Supreme Court, by the narrowest
of margins, endangered multistate programs that for two decades
have provided the nation's poor with up to $100 million worth of
free legal help each year. Voting 5-4 in a Texas case, the justices
ruled Monday that the interest earned from short-term trust
accounts lawyers hold for their clients are the private property of
those clients.
</P>
<P>
   TEEN-GAMBLING (Atlantic City, N.J.) _ Gambling and its
ubiquitous presence throughout the country has created a new rite
of passage for young people on their way to adulthood. By Brett
Pulley.
</P>
<P>
   SUNBEAM-DUNLAP (Undated) _ America's leading corporate downsizer
has just been downsized. Albert Dunlap, the publicity-seeking chief
executive who took almost perverse pride in throwing thousands of
people out of work in the name of raising his company's stock price
was thrown out of his own job as chief executive of the Sunbeam
Corp. over the weekend. The self-proclaimed turnaround artist, who
had been running the company for almost two years, was dismissed by
a board in a revolt led by some of his hand-picked directors.
</P>
<P>
   NY-WORKFARE (New York) _ Small-scale programs represent a sharp
counterpoint to New York City's mammoth workfare program, in which
more than 32,000 welfare recipients sweep streets and answer phones
in city agencies in return for public assistance. Proponents say
the private approaches offer more promise because they teach people
specific skills and provide a variety of routes out of welfare _
instead of just handing recipients a broom or ordering them to file
papers, as New York's program typically does. By Alan Finder.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-BULLS-FEVER (Beijing) _ Clinton's state visit this month
has brought out citizens' interest in all things American, from
books to clothes to movie stars. But these all seem like passing
fancies compared to the intense passion that Chinese, especially
young Chinese, have developed for Michael Jordan and U.S.
basketball. By Elisabeth Rosenthal. (650 wors.)
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-HMO (Undated) _ After two and a half frustrating years,
the California Medical Association's HMO has filed for bankruptcy.
By Peter T. Kilborn.
</P>
<P>
   SOC-WORLDCUP-U.S. (Paris) _ U.S. opens World Cup play with match
vs. Germany. By Jere Longman.
</P>
</TEXT>
