<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Marlins-Braves rematch set for The Ted
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ An hour after the Florida Marlins eliminated the
Atlanta Braves from the NLCS last Oct. 14, a group of men, some
still in jackets and tie, sneaked onto the playing surface at
Turner Field and took a jog around the bases before posing for a
photo around home plate.
</P>
<P>
   No mere trespassers, the group included Marlins owner H. Wayne
Huizenga, team president Don Smiley and some of the suits who
operated the team that later would become World Champions. Their
cigars glowed in the midnight darkness and, their victory lap
completed, the group laughed while the photographer's flashes
illuminated the infield.
</P>
<P>
   The same team returns to The Ted for the first time tonight, and
it will hardly be a photo op. The reigning champion Marlins, with
the worst record in the major leagues at 21-47, come back to
Atlanta, not much better off than old man Santiago, who beached his
great fish carcass at the end of ``The Old Man and the Sea.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've heard the jokes,'' Marlins manager Jim Leyland said over
the weekend, when Florida accomplished a four-game split with the
New York Mets. `` 'The Mets are down at Semi-Pro Players Stadium.'
Everybody wants to be a comedian.''
</P>
<P>
   It might be funny, if it wasn't pitiful. Since Huizenga ordered
the club's downsizing last November to make it more affordable to
sell, the Marlins are indistinguishable from 1997. Only eight
players from the postseason roster _ nine, counting the recovering
Alex Fernandez _ remain on the team. Since Opening Day, some $20.6
million has been pared from the roster, with the dealing away of
Gary Sheffield and Bobby Bonilla, among others.
</P>
<P>
   In their place is a peach-fuzzed roster that could lose 110
games, a 29-year high in the National League and 12 more defeats
than the franchise withstood in its inaugural season. In all, 23
rookies have appeared in Florida uniform already this year, and the
current 25-man roster includes 14 of them, including eight of 12
pitchers. Of the three starters the Braves will face in this
series, Joe Fontenot spent all of last year at Class AA Shreveport,
Jesus Sanchez was at Class AA Binghampton, and Ryan Dempster,
Thursday's pitcher, was at Class A Brevard County.
</P>
<P>
   Until a group put together by Smiley can settle its finances _
Smiley is said to have secured $140 million to 145 million of
Huizenga's $169 million price _ the on-field exploitation of the
Marlins continues. And nobody is enjoying it.
</P>
<P>
   In what was to have been a meeting between the 1996 and 1997
champions, the New York Yankees recently swept three from Florida,
prompting the Yankees' Joe Torre to say: ``You've won the World
Series. Great. Hurray. But if you only did it for yourself, then
it's not right. That's not the right thing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
