<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BULLS-WHATNEXT-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Jordan in cat-bird seat where Bulls decisions are concerned
</P>
<P>
   By Curtis Bunn
</P>
<P>
   C. 1998 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   SALT LAKE CITY, Utah _ Even in the euphoric aftermath of a sixth
NBA championship in eight years, Michael Jordan held on to the
uneasy tension that has engulfed the Chicago Bulls all season.
After embracing teammates and playing to a Delta Center crowd that,
even in its disappointment, had to admire the game's best player,
Jordan came upon owner Jerry Reinsdorf. In Chicago, that's viewed
as good vs. evil.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan gave Reinsdorf a sideways smile. Reinsdorf offered Jordan
a celebratory cigar by holding it up. Jordan accepted the stogie
and climbed atop the makeshift platform that rested on the court,
placing him above everyone else, where he belonged. But he did not
pause, did not hug his employer, and neither said a word.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Jordan wants to make one more championship run, a true
Last Dance, with the key personnel _ coach Phil Jackson, Scottie
Pippen and, to a lesser degree, Dennis Rodman _ in place. Reinsdorf
and general manager Jerry Krause are the key impediments to those
desires. So the jubilant Jordan did not make nice with the owner,
even in what had to be one of the most glorious moments of his
sparkling career.
</P>
<P>
   Until Jordan gets what he wants _ and he almost always does,
doesn't he? _ his relationship with Bulls management will be
strained at best.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can only hope and pray that Michael and Scottie will come
back and defend the championship one more time,'' Reinsdorf said
Sunday night after Jordan spun a 45-point performance that included
the game- and series-winning jump shot with 5.2 seconds remaining
in the game.
</P>
<P>
   That was Reinsdorf at his spin-doctoring best. Public opinion of
him and Krause, who was called a ``mad gerbil'' by a Chicago Sun
Times columnist, dipped below sea level with the news that they
intended to dismantle the club after this season.
</P>
<P>
   Since then it's been one power play after another: Krause
telling Jackson he would not be back after this season; Pippen
saying he'd never wear a Bulls uniform again; Jordan saying he
would not play for another coach or without Pippen.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, however, Jordan pulled the power play of all power
plays, lifting Chicago to a 4-2 Finals victory over Utah with a
pulsating 87-86 Game 6 victory Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Had the Jazz prevented the Bulls' repeat of the three-peat,
then, perhaps, Reinsdorf had grounds to make changes. But Jordan
carried the Bulls to the summit, and who is to say that next year,
at 36, he could not do it again with Jackson on the bench and
Pippen by his side?
</P>
<P>
   ``You're seeing Michael at the top of his game,'' Pippen said
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   So why would he quit now? His close friends say he wants a
nostalgic farewell tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are still a lot of unanswered questions,'' Jordan said.
``There are a lot of sympathetic feelings about this team and where
we want it to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan wants to go on, but not without Pippen, who softened on
his ``I'm outta here'' position of last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a player right now, I don't feel like it's over,'' Pippen
said about the Bulls' run. ``You never know. Anything's possible.
You hate to see it come to an end. We feel like we're dominant,
even though we weren't 100 percent healthy. It's been a lot of
fun.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Fun?'' That's not a word Pippen had used in relation to this
season's Bulls. So his use of that word might indicate that
Jordan's will already is working. If Pippen is going to walk from
Chicago into the unknown free-agent world, he'll do so resisting
almost certain prodding from Jordan to stay.
</P>
<P>
   As for Jackson, he has admitted to already cleaning out his
office at the United Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless something absolutely unusual comes out of left field,''
he said, ``I don't expect to see us back here again.''
</P>
<P>
   He should have spoken for himself. Jordan has backed away from
his early-season statement about playing only for Jackson. He
sounds now like the loss of his coach could be offset if Pippen
stays. In fact, Jordan even addressed the notion of playing next
season without either of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``A pretty big challenge,'' he said about that possibility,
``but the question is: Do I want to do that or not? That's the
thing that has to be debated.
</P>
<P>
   ``As time gets involved, some of the feelings may change. You
never know. But that's the purpose of waiting until the end of the
summer and making final decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   Pippen has been insulted by the team's refusal to grant him a
new deal, leaving him as the 122nd-highest-paid player in the
league. A three-year, $45-million contract would be a nice start
toward easing Pippen's uneasy feelings about Reinsdorf and Krause.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan is not so much concerned about his salary as he is about
his teammates. He joins eight Chicago players who will become free
agents on July 1. Only Toni Kukoc, Ron Harper and Randy Brown are
under contract for next season.
</P>
<P>
   Luc Longley may have cost himself a spot on the 1999 roster
after going scoreless in a poor title game. Steve Kerr, Bill
Wennington and Scott Burrell also might be gone.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Rodman's case is different from the rest. His return is
contingent on Jordan and Pippen returning, and on them saying they
could put up with his silly antics. ``I definitely want to come
back,'' Rodman said. ``If they want me back.''
</P>
<P>
   If they don't think that ``Rodzilla'' is worth the aggravation,
a free agent like Charles Barkley could come calling. For $1
million, Barkley would leap at the opportunity to play with Jordan
and Pippen. But they would decide.
</P>
<P>
   Decisions aren't expected soon. Jordan sets a timeline at the
end of the summer. He knows the longer Pippen waits, the more he'll
hear from Chicago fans to make one more run. It will bring
tremendous pressure.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Jordan knows Reinsdorf will get more mail and
more heat to make Pippen feel welcome.
</P>
<P>
   And if all Jordan's maneuvering fails, he'll walk away. For
good, and with no regrets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have another life,'' he said. ``I know I have to get to it
at some point in time. Hopefully, the fans and people will
understand that.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
