<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NBA players, front offices have long off-season ahead
 &HT;    By Jeffrey Denberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   On the wings of a contentious Finals, a bravura performance by
the game's greatest player and perhaps the largest TV audience in
the history of the playoffs, the NBA should be at its zenith today
in popularity and prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   But dwarfed by the question of the Chicago Bulls' future is the
matter of the NBA's existence as we know it.
</P>
<P>
   In two weeks, the league almost certainly will lock its doors
and cease to do business while it haggles with the players union
over a division of profits.
</P>
<P>
   Before Michael Jordan can decide whether to play again or
Scottie Pippen can choose his uniform for 1998-99 or the Utah Jazz
can fine tune their veteran squad for another run, disagreement
over dispersal of dollars will strangle the NBA this summer and,
perhaps, into the new season.
</P>
<P>
   During a recent press conference, NBA Commissioner David Stern
appeared to invite a work stoppage as an alternative to escalating
salaries. The only major sports league in the U.S. that has never
lost a regular season game to labor trouble now says that is no
longer the governing issue.
</P>
<P>
   In return, the players have taken the curious step of
threatening to boycott the world championships this summer,
although most owners couldn't care less.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides are returning to the summer of 1995, when rookie and
free-agent signings were halted, and both sides tried not to come
off as spoiled brats.
</P>
<P>
   That might be tougher this time around, as the players demand a
bigger slice of the pie and question Stern's contention that 57
percent of the gross goes to the players and that as many as eight
teams actually need subsidies to remain healthy. It's all
bookkeeping, the players say.
</P>
<P>
   They want to make certain their wealthiest members do not have
restrictions placed on their ability to earn even more money.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the owners have their way, Michael and Scottie will only
make $5 million next year,'' said Hawks center Dikembe Mutombo,
vice president of the players union.
</P>
<P>
   That issue might not sit well with the public. The rank and file
of the players association might crumple as questions about their
own self-interests are raised. After all, what good does it do a
Tyrone Corbin that teammates Steve Smith and Mutombo have $50
million-plus deals, when that wealth forces Corbin and others to
take minimum money.
</P>
<P>
   And while all of that is ironed out, no rookie and no free agent
will be signed, no player traded. Teams will schedule camps for
second-round picks and undrafted players at month's end, but no
player can be signed before July 1, and a lockout appears certain
on that date.
</P>
<P>
   What does it mean to the fan? All the blustering about Jordan,
the Jazz and next week's annual draft means nothing until the end
of September, when training camps are scheduled to open. If they
don't, there is cause for some concern.
</P>
<P>
   If all of October's preseason is lost, opening night on the
first weekend of November is seriously jeopardized.
</P>
<P>
   But there are two real dates to remember: Nov. 15, when players
normally receive their first pay checks since the previous spring,
and Dec. 25, the date of the first telecast on NBC, the league's
major cash cow.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
