<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    On Deck for Atlanta: Florida Marlins
 &HT;    By Tom Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   _ When: Tonight and Wednesday at 7:40 p.m., Thursday at 1:10
p.m.
</P>
<P>
   _ Where: Turner Field._ TV/ radio: TBS will telecast tonight.
Fox Sports South will telecast Wednesday and Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   _ Probable starting pitchers: Tonight _ LHP Denny Neagle (7-4,
3.47; 3-4, 3.25 lifetime vs Marlins) vs. RHP Joe Fontenot (0-3,
7.08; first appearance vs. Braves). Wednesday _ RHP Greg Maddux
(9-2, 1.75; 6-1, 2.32 lifetime vs. Marlins) vs. LHP Jesus Sanchez
(3-3, 3.97; first appearance vs. Braves). Thursday _ LHP Tom
Glavine (9-2, 2.68; 5-6, 3.56 lifetime vs. Marlins) vs. RHP Ryan
Dempster (0-2, 10.20; first appearance vs. Braves).
</P>
<P>
   _ Series history: This is the first meeting between the two
clubs this season. The Braves lead the all-time series 35-27.
</P>
<P>
   _ Past meetings: The Marlins won last year's series 8-4 and have
beaten the Braves in 15 of their last 25 regular-season meetings.
Florida was 4-2 at The Ted last season.
</P>
<P>
   _ Marlins leaders: Avg.: Dave Berg (.305); HR: Cliff Floyd (12);
RBIs: Floyd (40); SB: Edgar Renteria (20); W: Livan Hernandez,
Brian Meadows and Jay Powell (4); ERA: Matt Mantei (0.64);
Strikeouts: Hernandez (77); Saves: Powell (2).
</P>
<P>
   _ Quickly: The Marlins just split a four-game weekend series
with the second-place New York Mets and have gone 4-3 since coming
out of a 11-game losing streak on June 8. They are in the midst of
a difficult stretch of the schedule, with 13 games against the
Braves, Mets and New York Yankees in a 17-day period. . . . At
5-24, Florida is the worst road team in the majors. Even expansion
Arizona has won 10 road games. The Marlins hit .233 away from Pro
Player Stadium. . . . The Marlins can start fast and finish strong.
The team has outscored opponents 72-43 in the first inning, and
during the last 25 2/3 innings (0.70 ERA), the bullpen has allowed
16 hits and two solo homers. . . . Edgar Renteria's 20 steals are
4th in the NL. Overall, Florida ranks in the bottom quarter of the
league in nine offensive categories. The team ERA of 5.31 is
highest in the NL. . . . Fotenot, tonight's starter, originally was
San Francisco's first-round pick of the 1995 draft; he went to
Florida in the Robb Nen deal. He is making his fifth major-league
start and is allowing a .405 average against left-handers. . . . On
the DL: INF Kevin Millar (broken right hand), RHP Alex Fernandez
(rotator cuff surgery), RHP Eric Ludwick (broken right forearm),
RHP Rafael Medina (sore right shoulder).
</P>
<P>
   _ Who's hot: Renteria is on a seven-game hit streak, batting
.464 during the Marlins' seven-game homestand. 3B Todd Zeile hit
.387 during the same period with three doubles and seven RBI in 26
at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   _ Who's not: C Greg Zaun is hitting 3-for-34 (.088) this month
with nine strikeouts. Rookie 1B Derek Lee is batting .204,
including .157 in 51 at-bats against left-handers.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
