<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-CLIENT-725&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT RULING COULD JEOPARDIZE FUNDING OF LEGAL SERVICES 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By LINDA GREENHOUSE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A sharply divided Supreme Court decision on Monday
cast constitutional doubt on state programs generating $100 million
a year for legal services for poor people by pooling the interest
on some of the money clients deposit for brief periods with their
lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   That interest is actually the property of the clients, the court
ruled in a 5-4 decision that raised, but did not answer, the
further and more salient question of whether channeling the money
for legal services amounts to an unconstitutional ``taking'' of
private property for a public purpose.
</P>
<P>
   That question will now be answered by the lower federal courts,
and eventually by the Supreme Court as the case works it way back
up through the legal system. Reaction Monday was sharply split over
whether the court's handling of the initial property question
foreshadowed an eventual ruling that the program is
unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   The case, a challenge brought to the program in Texas by
property rights advocates, represented the leading edge of a debate
that has taken place largely out of the public eye but that has
galvanized the organized bar. In many respects, it is the latest
chapter in the long-running, ideologically charged battle over the
fate of publicly funded legal services programs.
</P>
<P>
   The Justices themselves split along ideological lines. Chief
Justice William H. Rehnquist wrote the majority opinion, which was
joined by his four most conservative colleagues: Justices Antonin
Scalia, Clarence Thomas, Sandra Day O'Connor and Anthony M.
Kennedy. Justices David H. Souter, John Paul Stevens, Ruth Bader
Ginsburg and Stephen G. Breyer dissented.
</P>
<P>
   In declaring the interest to be clients' property, the court
rejected arguments put forward by the chief justices of all 50
states, the American Bar Association, 35 state attorneys general,
and numerous government groups. These groups argued that properly
understood, the interest should not be seen as the clients'
property because it would be nonexistent, eaten up by transaction
costs, except for the pooling arrangement that courts and
legislatures in all 50 states have adopted under a program known as
Interest on Lawyers Trust Accounts.
</P>
<P>
   According to a brief filed by the American Bar Association,
money generated by the programs is second only to the federal
government as a source of funding for legal services, accounting
for as much as a quarter of the legal services budgets. In
addition, Congress has been cutting the budget of the Legal
Services Corp. and placing restrictions on the types of cases that
lawyers who work for the federally funded programs can bring.
</P>
<P>
   The idea for the program, usually referred to by its initials as
IOLTA, began in Australia in the 1960s. Its adoption in the United
States came only in 1980, when Congress authorized banks to pay
interest on checking accounts for certain types of depositors.
Before then, lawyers typically deposited short-term client funds,
such as escrow or settlement deposits, in non-interest bearing
accounts, so the question of what to do with the interest did not
arise.
</P>
<P>
   Once interest-bearing checking accounts became available, the
American Bar Association and other lawyers' groups were quick to
promote adoption of the Australian idea of directing the pooled
interest to legal services. They reasoned that for clients, the
interest was largely theoretical in any event, because the costs of
opening an account and dealing with tax forms would quickly cancel
out the earnings from all but sizeable deposits. When actual net
interest to a client was a possibility, that client's deposit would
not be pooled, but would go into a separate, individual account for
the client's benefit.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Supreme Court adopted an IOLTA program for the state
in 1984. All states now have such a program.
</P>
<P>
   The case against the Texas program that the Supreme Court ruled
on was brought by a conservative public interest law firm, the
Washington Legal Foundation. It challenged the program both as an
unconstitutional taking of private property and as a form of
compelled support for causes not of a client's choosing, in
violation of the First Amendment. That aspect of the case was not
before the Supreme Court but can be renewed in the lower court
proceedings that will follow Monday's ruling.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In his majority opinion Monday, Phillips vs. Washington Legal
Foundation, No. 96-1578, Rehnquist applied a rule of English common
law that ``interest follows principal.'' Since there was no dispute
that the principal on deposit was the property of the client, the
chief justice said, it followed that ``any interest that does
accrue attaches as a property right incident to the ownership of
the underlying principal.''
</P>
<P>
   This was the case, the chief justice continued, even if at the
end of the day, there was no net interest for the client to
receive. ``We have never held that a physical item is not
`property' simply because it lacks a positive economic or market
value,'' he said, adding, ``The government may not seize rents
received by the owner of a building simply because it can prove
that the costs incurred in collecting the rents exceed the amount
collected.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether the use of the property was a ``taking'' within the
meaning of the Fifth Amendment or, if so, whether any ``just
compensation'' would be due to the clients were questions for
another day, the chief justice said.
</P>
<P>
   In a dissenting opinion, Souter objected that the court had
announced ``an essentially abstract proposition'' that ``may
ultimately turn out to have no significance'' in resolving the
ultimate constitutional question. If the amount of ``just
compensation'' turned out to be zero, he said, ``there would be no
practical consequence'' to having recognized a property right in
the first place.
</P>
<P>
   The 5th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals, in New Orleans, which
found the interest to be property in its 1996 ruling but stopped
short of deciding the other questions, will now consider the case
again. ``We're 90 percent of the way home,'' Richard Samp, the
Washington Legal Foundation's chief counsel, said Monday,
predicting that his group would win the next crucial phase.
</P>
<P>
   The program's supporters were more tempered in their
predictions. Jerome J. Shestack, president of the American Bar
Association, said in an interview that IOLTA programs were ``more
vulnerable, but still alive'' under the ruling Monday. He
speculated that if there had been a solid five votes on the court
to decide the ultimate issue against the programs, the majority
would probably have done so now rather than preserve the issue for
another day.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
