<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-EXCLUSIVE-CAESAR-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAMOUS ROMAN BATH BELIEVED DISCOVERED IN ITALY
</HEADLINE>
  (The Science Times)  
(ART ADV: Graphic of is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(ja) 
 By JOHN NOBLE WILFORD    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Great as he loomed in the heyday of Rome, the Emperor Augustus
was frail of body and suffered a lifetime of infirmities. In 23
B.C., according to a contemporary account, he almost died of ``an
abscessed liver'' and presumably would have if not for the
restorative power of cold baths in mineral springs. Word of the
emperor's cure touched off one of antiquity's more enduring health
fads.
</P>
<P>
   Cold mineral baths became popular among Romans for at least two
centuries. People abandoned the hot springs of Baiae, a spa near
Pompeii, and flocked to the cold-water resorts of Gabii, near Rome,
or Chiusi, in the Siena district of Tuscany. From personal
experience, the poet Horace sang the praises of a bracing dip in
cold mineral water for curing illnesses of the head and stomach:
</P>
<P>
   ... For Antonius Musa makes Baiae
</P>
<P>
   Useless to me and even makes me unpopular there,
</P>
<P>
   Now that at mid-winter I soak in icy water.
</P>
<P>
   The vogue of cold bathing made Antonius Musa, the emperor's
personal physician, a rich and famous man. The Roman elite sought
him out for prescriptions. Augustus and the Senate rewarded him
with money, the right as a freed slave to wear gold rings and an
exemption from taxes then and in the future for himself and all
physicians.
</P>
<P>
   For the last 100 years, archeologists and classics scholars have
been trying to find the springs of Chiusi, where Horace and perhaps
Augustus took the waters. A team of archeologists, led by David
Soren of the University of Arizona in Tucson, may have succeeded.
</P>
<P>
   Digging in Tuscany, the archeologists have tapped into a
bubbling spring of cold mineral water and excavated the ruins of
bathhouse columns and an enormous tile-paved swimming pool. All
this is in the right place and seems to fit Horace's description of
the ancient Roman spa. But confirmation may prove impossible, other
archeologists said, short of uncovering an inscription saying that
Augustus or Horace bathed here.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are either looking at the famous spring of Chiusi, or at
the very least at one of a series of springs that made this area
famous in antiquity,'' Soren said in a recent interview before
returning to Italy for further excavations.
</P>
<P>
   The style of the wall construction, Soren said, is consistent
with other Roman monuments of the second and first centuries BC.
Pottery scattered in the ruins is also of the same period. The
structures may thus be old enough to have been in use during the
reign of Augustus. The rectangular building at the center of the
site, moreover, resembles the icons used to represent spas on early
Roman road maps.
</P>
<P>
   In any event, the large size of the site shows that it was a
major spa complex unlike anything else ever found in the Siena
region and one of the largest anywhere in Italy. Frank Romer, a
classics professor at Arizona, said the excavations ``should reveal
something about Roman medicine and Roman fads at the time everybody
started taking cold baths.''
</P>
<P>
   Tana Allen, an archeologist at the University of Alberta in
Edmonton, who specializes in the healing spas of antiquity,
described the discovery as ``incredibly exciting.''
</P>
<P>
   The discovery was made near the modern Tuscan resort of
Chianciano Terme, which already boasts of three cold-water springs
that account for the town's promotional motto, ``It's Chianciano
for a healthy liver.'' But no ruins that could be associated with
an ancient spa had been uncovered until 1993. It was then that
Giulio Paolucci, an Italian archeologist, excavated the first
evidence of late Etruscan and early Roman Imperial structures.
</P>
<P>
   Soren joined the project three years ago, working with local
museums and Tuscany's Department of Antiquities. Excavations
revealed the stonewall outlines of a swimming pool estimated to
have been as large as 60 by 130 feet. Its bottom, paved with roof
tiles, was never more than 3 feet deep, enough for bathers to
immerse their bodies but inadequate for most swimming. Such
dimensions conform to Horace's descriptions.
</P>
<P>
   The pool tiles have caused some confusion among archeologists.
Some bear stamps attributed to the second century A.D. Was the pool
built then, well after the other buildings, or was that when it was
remodeled? No one is sure.
</P>
<P>
   From the ruins, archeologists have determined that imposing
brick columns bordered walkways surrounding the pool. At the middle
of the west side, a podium jutted out over the pool, probably
serving as a base for a statue devoted to the gods of bathing.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Traces of a marble horse leg were uncovered nearby. Perhaps this
was a piece of the podium statuary. While excavating other
buildings, workers removed mud near a small temple and out flowed a
spring of cold water from the hillside.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was the amazing thing for us,'' Soren said. ``The spring
was still there, and the water just started shooting out.''
</P>
<P>
   The Romans were among the first to take seriously the supposed
healing properties of mineral springs, cold or hot. The Greeks
before them had known about mineral waters, but considered them
unhealthy and unwholesome. Even if the Romans found the waters
beneficial, they were no more able to explain any salubrious
qualities than are devotees of mineral baths today.
</P>
<P>
   ``I suppose it felt wonderfully relaxing and comfortable to the
Romans,'' said Allen of the University of Alberta. ``And once you
feel relaxed, your sicknesses start to feel that they are going
away.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the biographer Suetonius tells that Musa cured Augustus
with cold baths, other contemporaries spoke of ``cold drinks'' of
the mineral water as part of the treatment. If so, patients might
have had reason to think the treatment worse than the illness.
</P>
<P>
   Analyzing the water, Janek Artiola, an environmental scientist
at Arizona, found it full of calcium and sulfates _ not recommended
for drinking. Too much of the calcium could lead to kidney stones.
Even a little of the sulfate would have a strong purgative or
laxative effect.
</P>
<P>
   Horace was apparently wise enough not to drink the spa water. He
suffered from inflammation of the eyes and may have daubed them
with the water. Classicists, Soren said, are fond of an outrageous
pun: ``You can lead a Horace to water but you can't make him
drink.''
</P>
<P>
   The water at the spring today is not that cold _ 64 degrees
Fahrenheit _ but that was apparently what most Romans considered
cold for a bath. The younger Seneca described the spa waters as
``all but hot.'' But he also reported that some old Romans had what
today would be called polar-bear clubs. They would ring in the new
year with a plunge in icy waters.
</P>
<P>
   Within walking distance of the newly discovered spa, excavations
directed by Anna Rastrelli, head of the Chiusi Museum, have turned
up remains of an Etruscan temple in use during the third and second
centuries B.C. Some of the newly assembled pieces of terra-cotta
sculpture, she said, are among ``the most stunning finds of
Etruscan sculpture in recent memory.''
</P>
<P>
   At some time after the temple was destroyed by landslide,
Rastrelli said, its terra-cotta sculptures were gathered and buried
in a deliberate manner. Fragments of the temple's stone columns and
traces of its wooden roof beams were also uncovered, as well as
coins, iron knives and small votive bronzes. Some of the coins were
dated to 200 B.C.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most impressive finds, she said, was the sculpture of
a winged woman, who appears to be about to fly off while looking
back and holding a drinking vessel in her left hand. Art historians
see in the winged figure a strong similarity to some feminine
divinities on the frieze of the great altar of Pergamum in what is
now Turkey. Other pieces indicated that the temple was dedicated to
Hercules, the Etruscan patron of healthful waters, and the nymphs
of the adjacent spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this Tuscan land of springs, a temple dedicated to the
water gods of the area would be appropriate,'' Rastrellia said.
``For then, as now, the curative properties of water held a special
meaning.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
