<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CREDIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LONG-TERM RATES HIT LOWEST LEVEL IN 30 YEARS 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By JONATHAN FUERBRINGER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Long-term government interest rates fell to their
lowest level in 30 years Monday while other government yields,
including those that effect home mortgage rates, dropped sharply.
</P>
<P>
   The drop in interest rates, which has seen the 30-year yield
fall half a percentage point since the end of April, is the kind
that could help support economic growth by boosting the housing
industry and making loans for capital investment cheaper.
</P>
<P>
   That would make it harder for the Federal Reserve to achieve a
sustained slowdown that would make policy makers less worried about
inflation and less likely to raise interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   But Monday's sharp fall in the stock market, which capped a
week-long decline that left the Nasdaq composite index down 10.5
percent from its recent high and the Dow Jones industrial average
off 6.3 percent, has some analysts wondering about the near-term
economic outlook.
</P>
<P>
   A prolonged fall in the stock market, or even just a long period
of inconclusive ups and downs, could have a chilling effect on
consumer spending, as investors decide they may not be as wealthy
as they had thought.
</P>
<P>
   ``The equity market is key,'' said Robert DiClemente, chief U.S.
economist at Salomon Smith Barney. ``If equities don't hold up it
would neutralize the effects from interest rates.''
</P>
<P>
   Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan said last week that such
a cooling in the stock market was one way that Fed could get the
slowing in growth policy that makers say they need.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts pointed to the economic turmoil in Asia, problems in
Russia and, possibly, some new doubts about the American stock
market, for reasons why investors seemed to be rushing to the safe
harbor of the American bond market.
</P>
<P>
   The 70-point drop in the Dow Jones industrial average after 3:30
p.m. Monday that pushed the day's decline over 200 points came as
the yield on the 30-year bond dropped from 5.61 percent to 5.58
percent, down from 5.66 percent Friday. The price of the bond,
which moves in the opposite direction, rose 1 6/32 to 107 26/32.
</P>
<P>
   According to Salomon Brothers, the yield is the lowest for
long-term government rates since the fall of 1968, a time when
interest rates were rising sharply because of the Vietnam War and
inflation.
</P>
<P>
   The yield on the 10-year note, which is used in setting mortgage
interest rates, also fell, dropping to 5.35 percent from 5.42
percent Friday. That is the lowest 10-year yields have been since
the fall of 1993. In January of this year, when the 10-year yield
fell to 5.36 percent, mortgage interest rates were at four-year
lows.
</P>
<P>
   Shorter-term interest rates have also fallen sharply recently,
which in part is in response to the foreign money that is coming
into the American market, analysts said. The yield on the two-year
Treasury note fell to 5.38 percent Monday from 5.43 percent Friday
and 5.57 percent in the last week.
</P>
<P>
   Where interest rates go from here is unclear. Analysts said they
could go lower if the turmoil in Asia continues and foreigners send
more money here. But some think that there is not enough data yet
proving that the economy is slowing from its recent, rapid 4
percent-plus pace to warrant a big further decline in long-term
rates.
</P>
<P>
   ``In order to go below 5.5 percent on a sustained basis, there
will need to be more evidence that the economy is slowing on a
sustainable basis, not just a flight to quality,'' said Donald
Fine, the chief market analyst at Chase Asset Management.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-15-98 1901EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
