<SLUG> BC-SMARTALK-WORLDWIDE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMARTALK ACQUIRES BAY STATE MARKETING FIRM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHANA R. SCHOENBERGER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Seeking to acquire a consumer direct-marketing division,
SmarTalk TeleServices Inc. has acquired Worldwide Direct, a
Framingham, Mass. company that markets cellular telephones through
TV advertisements, for $44.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   Worldwide, started 10 months ago by Victor Grillo Jr., 32, and
Lloyd Lapidus, 29, will have more than $50 million in sales this
year, Grillo said.
</P>
<P>
   The company will keep its Framingham operations and its 175
employees when it becomes SmarTalk's consumer marketing division,
said Lapidus, who will become the new division's executive vice
president. Grillo will run the SmarTalk division.
</P>
<P>
   Lapidus and Grillo owned about 60 percent of the firm; Global
Retail Partners, a venture capital fund run by the New York
investment bank Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette, owned the remainder
of Worldwide's shares.
</P>
<P>
   SmarTalk, a Columbus, Ohio, seller of prepaid telephone cards
with $300 million in sales this year, wanted to add direct
marketing to its retail and wholesale operations, said Joseph A.
Boroez, SmarTalk's senior vice president for marketing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had one channel missing in our portfolio, which was direct
sales,'' Boroez said. ``We identified the expert, which was
Worldwide Direct.''
</P>
<P>
   Currently, Worldwide operates a 24-hour, seven-day call center
in Framingham, which fills orders from the company's TV
commercials, which air nationwide. Famed TV personality Dick Clark
is the company's celebrity spokesperson. Phones arrive at
customers' doors within 24 hours, Grillo said.
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition also allows SmarTalk to better refine a prepaid
cellular product it had planned to launch in the third quarter by
combining the new product with Worldwide's existing line, Boroez
said.
</P>
<P>
   Grillo said the sale combines the two companies' strengths.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could sell telephones and long-distance cards on TV, and
they currently sell the long-distance cards at retail and could
also sell our cell phones at retail,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
