<SLUG> BC-DISABLED-PRISONERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT RULES THAT PRISON INMATES ARE PROTECTED BY DISABILITIES ACT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Supreme Court ruled Monday that state prison
inmates are protected by a federal law that bans discrimination
against the disabled.
</P>
<P>
   In a unanimous decision, the court said the Pennsylvania
Department of Corrections was wrong when it refused to allow a
former prisoner to take part in a motivational boot camp program
because he suffered from high blood pressure.
</P>
<P>
   The court ruled that the state's refusal violated the 1990
Americans with Disabilities Act (ADA), which bans discrimination of
a ``qualified individual with a disability'' by a ``public entity''
on account of that person's disability.
</P>
<P>
   ``State prisons fall squarely within the statutory definition of
public entity,'' Justice Antonin Scalia wrote for the court.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-three other states had joined Pennsylvania's appeal,
arguing that the ADA has led to inmate demands ``of all sorts, many
of them exceedingly unreasonable.''
</P>
<P>
   But Marjorie Rifkin of the American Civil Liberties Union's
National Prison Project said that ``there has not in fact been a
flood of lawsuits'' by inmates.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, Ronald Yeskey was sentenced to prison for 18 to 36
months for drunken driving, escape and resisting arrest. In
imposing the sentence, the court recommended that Yeskey be
assigned to a boot camp designed to offer training and instill
discipline that the state's correction's department operated. If he
successfully completed the program, Yeskey would have been released
after six months.
</P>
<P>
   But the department refused to put him in the program because of
his hypertension. It also denied him entry into any alternative
program for disabled people.
</P>
<P>
   Yeskey, who has since completed his sentence, sued for damages,
claiming the department's refusal violated the ADA.
</P>
<P>
   A federal judge threw out Yeskey's lawsuit, agreeing with
Pennsylvania authorities that the ADA did not apply to state
prisons.
</P>
<P>
   But in 1997 the 3d U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals reversed the
lower court and reinstated the suit, saying the law's broad
language covered the prisons even though they were not specifically
mentioned.
</P>
<P>
   Scalia upheld the appeals court's decision, writing that the law
``includes anyone with a disability ... and that includes
prisoners.'' He also said prison programs do fall under the ADA.
</P>
<P>
   ``Modern prisons provide inmates with many recreational
activities, medical services and educational and vocational
programs,'' he wrote. ``The text of the ADA provides no basis for
distinguishing these programs, services and activities from those
provided by public entities that are not prisons.''
</P>
<P>
   In another decision Monday, the court put in jeopardy a
multistate program that provides some $100 million a year for legal
help for the poor.
</P>
<P>
   By a 5-4 vote, the justices ruled in a Texas case that the
interest earned from short-term trust accounts that lawyers hold
for their clients are the private property of those clients.
</P>
<P>
   The case revolved around a little-known program called Interest
on Lawyers' Trust Accounts, or IOLTA, which exists in some form in
every state.
</P>
<P>
   Attorneys handling small amounts of clients' funds routinely
pool them into one trust account. The clients' sums by themselves
are too small or are deposited for too short a period to generate
interest.
</P>
<P>
   However, the combined monies do produce interest. Depending on
the state, lawyers are either required or urged to forward that
interest to a designated agency, which then doles it out to legal
aid programs.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, William Summers, a retired contractor from Missouri
City, near Houston, who had money deposited in mandatory IOLTA
accounts, challenged the Texas IOLTA program, known as the Texas
Equal Access to Justice Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Summers, joined by the conservative Washington Legal Foundation
here, argued that the Texas program, which takes in up to $10
million annually, violated the Fifth Amendment by taking private
property without just compensation.
</P>
<P>
   ``When interest is earned on money, the interest belongs to the
person whose principle generated the interest,'' Richard Samp, an
attorney for Summers, told the high court.
</P>
<P>
   The sharply divided court stopped short of killing all such
programs. Instead, it sent the Texas case back to a lower court for
a determination of whether the state has ``taken'' private property
and must pay ``just compensation'' for it.
</P>
<P>
   Today's decision upheld a 1996 ruling in which the 5th U.S.
Circuit Court of Appeals found that the interest generated was the
property of the lawyers' clients _ raising the possibility that any
diversion and pooling of that money might be an unlawful taking of
private property. Other appeals courts had reached the opposite
conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   Writing for the court majority, Chief Justice William H.
Rehnquist said, ``We hold that the interest income generated by
funds held in IOLTA accounts is the `private property' of the owner
of the principal.''
</P>
<P>
   But Rehnquist added: ``We express no view as to whether these
funds have been `taken' by the state; nor do we express an opinion
as to the amount of `just compensation,' if any, is due'' to those
who sued.
</P>
<P>
   Joining Rehnquist were Justices Sandra Day O'Connor, Antonin
Scalia, Anthony M. Kennedy and Clarence Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   Justices John Paul Stevens, David H. Souter, Ruth Bader Ginsburg
and Stephen G. Breyer dissented.
</P>
</TEXT>
