<SLUG> BC-MA-DOMESTIC-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOMESTIC PARTNERS BILL GETS BOOST IN COURT RULING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANTHONY FLINT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ An advisory ruling issued Monday by Massachusetts' top
court has cleared the way for the Legislature to allow Boston to
extend employment benefits to the partners and dependents of gay
city workers _ vaulting Boston into the company of only a handful
of major cities to take the controversial step.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Judicial Court, at the request of House Speaker
Thomas J. Finneran, said it was appropriate for Beacon Hill to
authorize cities and towns to extend benefits such as health
insurance to domestic partners of gay employees, and that
municipalities crafting such measures were would not run afoul of
the state constitution.
</P>
<P>
   The city's proposal is at the State House in the form of a home
rule petition a local ordinance that needs state approval. Finneran
was mum on his plans Monday, but backers say he has promised to
move the bill if his technical questions were answered by the SJC.
</P>
<P>
   ``The games are over. It's time to move on this bill,'' said
City Councilor Thomas M. Keane Jr., the measure's author.
</P>
<P>
   ``We anticipate the speaker will move this bill regardless of
his personal feelings about the subject,'' said state
Representative Byron Rushing (D-Boston), who shepherded the cause
along with fellow Representative Paul DeMakis (D-Boston). ``He
thought there were constitutional problems with the whole shebang.
The only way to get agreement to move the bill was to have these
questions answered. And now they have been.''
</P>
<P>
   Finneran had asked the court two questions: Whether it was
necessary for the state Legislature to act on the matter or could
Boston could just enact an ordinance on its own; and two, whether
the bill was unconstitutional because it allowed Boston and not the
state to define the term ``domestic partner'' and ``dependents.''
</P>
<P>
   Finneran was concerned about letting cities and towns define
those terms because it could lead to a legal thicket if benefits
were extended to unmarried heterosexual couples, for example, or to
elderly sisters siblings that lived together.
</P>
<P>
   The SJC judges declined to answer the first question, although
they suggested there was no reason the state Legislature couldn't
pass such a measure. On the second question, the judges said there
wasn't anything unconstitutional about letting cities and towns
define the terms in their legislation.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a clear green light,'' said Mary Bonauto, attorney for
Gay and Lesbian Advocates and Defenders, a legal advocacy group.
``The court doesn't see anything novel about this. Cities and towns
would be implementing the basic function of protecting their
employees.''
</P>
<P>
   Bonauto and others said the ruling was significant in a broader
context because it recognizes that health plans for domestic
partners serve the same purposes as employer-provided benefits
generally.
</P>
<P>
   ``Benefits are part of the overall compensation, and if some
people are not allowed this benefit because of their sexual
orientation, they are not getting fair compensation. It's a
question of fairness -- equal pay for equal work,'' said Rushing.
</P>
<P>
   In Massachusetts, Springfield, Cambridge and Northampton extend
benefits to the partners of gay employees. Those cities did not ask
the Legislature for approval to enact those acts. Nationally, San
Francisco was the first major city to pass a domestic partners
ordinance, joined by Seattle, New York, Los Angeles and Atlanta.
Vermont has a statewide measure.
</P>
<P>
   Boston does not know exactly how many employees would be
affected by the measure, though rough estimates don't exceed a few
hundred at most.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always difficult to measure because this requires you to
come out to get it,'' said Rushing. Also, he added, the partners of
many gay employees are employed and are part of a group health
insurance plans already.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
