</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GERMANY-BANK-475&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GERMAN BANK RAIDED IN TAX-DODGE INVESTIGATION 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By EDMUND L. ANDREWS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany _ Three hundred criminal investigators
descended Monday on Deutsche Bank, Germany's biggest bank, looking
for evidence that bank executives helped wealthy customers
illegally avoid taxes.
</P>
<P>
   It was the biggest single raid on a German bank in connection
with tax avoidance, a national obsession among wealthy Germans that
is estimated to cost the government more than $10 billion a year in
lost revenues.
</P>
<P>
   There is little mystery as to why wealthy Germans work so hard
at tax avoidance. On average, Germans give up about 50 percent of
their income to the government in the form of regular taxes, social
security and retirement payments, a special tax surcharge to
rebuild the former East Germany, and a 16 percent value-added tax
on most sales.
</P>
<P>
   Although Deutsche Bank has so far stayed out of trouble,
Germany's other big banks have all endured raids in recent years,
and a few top executives have been forced to resign because they
themselves were evading taxes.
</P>
<P>
   As in previous investigations of Dresdner Bank and Commerzbank,
among other financial institutions, prosecutors suspect that that
bank executives knowingly helped customers shift money to tax
havens like Switzerland and Luxembourg, where customers use
anonymous accounts to earn interest and capital gains that they do
not report to German tax authorities.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors in Frankfurt said Monday that their raid came partly
as a result of information from people who had confessed to tax
evasion. Jan Tilmann, Frankfurt's chief prosecutor, said the
investigation was still at the early stages, but that he had reason
to suspect that Deutsche Bank executives may have collaborated with
their customers in illegal tax evasion.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is evidence that unknown Deutsche Bank officials made it
possible for customers to anonymously move money out of the
country,'' Tilmann said. ``The measures taken to veil the
identities of bank customers also raise the suspicion that the
responsible bank workers at the least took into account the
possibility they were helping customers evade taxes.''
</P>
<P>
   Beginning at 10 a.m., the army of investigators showed up at
Deutsche Bank's headquarters here in Frankfurt as well as at key
branches in neighboring cities. The investigators seized thousands
of documents relating to the transfer of money and securities to
Luxembourg and Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
   German prosecutors and tax officials have become extremely
aggressive about going after tax dodgers in the last two years. By
one estimate, Germans have moved more than $300 billion out of the
country at a potential cost in lost tax revenue of more than $10
billion a year.
</P>
<P>
   The use of legal tax loopholes, as well as illegal maneuvers,
was a major drain on the Treasury last year. To stop the
hemorrhage, tax authorities have raided banks and stepped up tax
audits of businesses and wealthy individuals.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The new pressure has prompted a growing number of wealthy people
to give themselves up voluntarily, acknowledging that they failed
to pay their proper taxes in exchange for avoiding criminal
indictments. One of the most well-known cases last year involved
Hans-Georg Hofmann, then the head of Dresdner Bank's investment
banking operations.
</P>
<P>
   Hofmann voluntarily admitted that he owed taxes of several
million dollars on money he had earned in Switzerland. When word
reached the public, Hoffman was forced to resign from his post.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
