<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FATHERS-DAY-AT-THE-MOVIES-LIFEBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MONSTERS OF FATHER'S DAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's LifeBeat
lifestyle package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to LifeBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing articles with color art.) 
 By TIM HERRERA  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Father's Day reminds me of dinosaurs.
 &HT;    No, I don't mean that it makes me feel like one. It makes me
think of those big extinct reptiles with the sharp teeth, nasty
claws and ...
 &HT;    But I'm getting ahead of myself.
 &HT;    I know about Father's Day, and as the father of four I've done
pretty well by it. I can go a month without washing underwear. My
necktie collection rivals that of many department stores. I own
countless mugs, T-shirts and finger-paint artwork proclaiming
``WORLD'S GREATEST DAD!''
 &HT;    I treasure every handcrafted present my three boys and one
daughter have ever made, because they made them for me. But I was
looking for something a little different this time around.
 &HT;    ``What do you want for Father's Day this year?'' my boys asked.
 &HT;    ``What if you guys quit fighting for Father's Day?'' I replied.
 &HT;    This was no small request. A day rarely goes by in our house
without ``He hit me!'' followed by ``He hit me first!'' Then comes
the witty ``Did-not-did-too!'' exchange.
 &HT;    I was asking for a one-day truce, one that even NATO diplomats
would have trouble arranging. The treaty didn't have to be in
writing _ I'd accept a verbal agreement, with or without
handshakes.
 &HT;    I'd do a lot for an entire day without hearing ``Dork!'', ``Dog
breath!'' or something worse echoing through our house as the kids
battle for the Nintendo, the VCR or the remote control _ my remote
control.
 &HT;    But my request didn't go over very well. Either they didn't
understand or they knew the mission was impossible. Besides, they
clearly had ideas of their own.
 &HT;    ``Yeah, no fighting's good, Dad,'' they said. ``But how 'bout if
we go to the movies like we did last year? Maybe we can go see
`Godzilla?'''
 &HT;    ``What the heck,'' I said. ``Who needs peace and tranquility,
anyway?''
 &HT;    It seems we are forming a Father's Day tradition. Last year, we
also commemorated the day by watching loud, frightening, scaly
creatures on the rampage. No, we weren't watching ``The Jerry
Springer Show'' or anything on C-Span _ we went to see ``The Lost
World.''
 &HT;    It was a memorable day, but not because of the film. It was
memorable because the outing was their idea.
 &HT;    I ended up taking our two older boys _ ages 8 and 10 _ to the
``Jurassic Park'' sequel. I felt the younger kids were too little
to watch dinosaurs devour screaming humans, even at matinee prices.
 &HT;    While driving to the theater with the boys, I started thinking
about my father and the only time I could ever remember just the
two of us going to the movies.
 &HT;    It was a cool, spring Pennsylvania day. Dad and I carried light
jackets as we walked to the old Memorial Theater to see a
``Batman'' movie, strolling along the steep hills, past the
Veterans Memorial and my school, St. Joseph's Elementary.
 &HT;    Dad was barely 5-foot-4, but I was still much smaller and
struggled to keep up with his quick stride.
 &HT;    Sometimes I get angry because I can't recall everything about
that day. However, I am grateful for one image still floating in my
mind: I remember looking over, seeing the light from the movie
screen flickering on Dad's face and thinking how cool it was that
he was just spending time with me.
 &HT;    All the way home from the theater, I replayed the film for my
father. Since Dad laughed, I was positive he had liked the movie as
much as I had. But I never really found out _ I never thought to
ask.
 &HT;    Dad died about five years ago. A very compassionate physician
bit his lip and searched for the medically precise but nonetheless
sensitive words to explain to my mother and me that they could do
no more for my father. But the look of defeat on Dad's face told me
more than any doctor could.
 &HT;    Questions flooded my mind during his last moments. Could he tell
me one more World War II story? Did he know I put the scratch in
his Ford Grand Torino? Did he really want to see the Batman movie,
or did he go because I begged?
 &HT;    Dad didn't die on Father's Day, but every third Sunday in June I
think of our day at the movies.
 &HT;    As my sons and I walked out of the theater after ``The Lost
World,'' our eyes adjusting to the sunlight glaring off the parking
lot, my middle son turned and asked: ``Dad, did you like the
movie?''
 &HT;    ``I sure did, pal.''
 &HT;    He'll never know how glad I am that he asked.
 c.1998 Tim Herrera  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Tim Herrera is a Sacramento, Calif.-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
