<HEADER>
A0258 &Cx1f; tab-z
w l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KIDS-AND-LIMITS-LIFEB     06-15 1403
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KIDS-AND-LIMITS-LIFEBEAT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SETTING LIMITS FOR YOUR TODDLER 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's LifeBeat
lifestyle package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to LifeBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing articles with color art.) 
 By MARGERY D. ROSEN  
 c.1998 Child magazine  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The trouble started at lunchtime.
</P>
<P>
   My 2-year-old daughter Sarah had asked for grilled cheese, but I
had unwittingly committed an unpardonable sin: I'd cut her sandwich
into fours instead of twos.
</P>
<P>
   It was fortunate that the plate was plastic, because Sarah
expressed her annoyance by flinging it to the floor.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to stay calm, I brought out the yogurt _ cherry vanilla,
her favorite. But, silly me, I'd mixed the raisins into the yogurt
instead of letting her put them on top herself.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, though, I managed to catch the container before it
went the way of the grilled cheese.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, Mommy lost it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first thing I tell parents of toddlers is to expect the
unexpected,'' says Patricia Henderson Shimm, associate director of
the Center for Toddler Development at Barnard College in New York.
``The second thing I tell them is not to take their child's
behavior personally. Your toddler is not maliciously defying you to
make your life miserable, to get back at you, or because you're a
terrible mom or dad.''
</P>
<P>
   The primary task of being a toddler, Shimm explains, is to test
you _ that's how she learns and grows emotionally, physically and
socially.
</P>
<P>
   As you tell your toddler, again and again, which rules and
limits she needs to observe in order to be social as well as safe,
she begins to absorb the information and learn how to get along
with others. Not surprisingly, she has countless questions about
this process and her role in it, and she needs to test you until
she arrives at answers that make sense to her.
</P>
<P>
   Toddlers repeat annoying or even destructive behavior to make
sure they understand the rules: ``I drew on the walls and Mommy
yelled. But will she always yell? Is it ever OK to draw on the
walls? Let me try again and show Mommy what I did. Then I'll see
how she reacts, and I'll know for sure what the rule really is.''
</P>
<P>
   ``By continually bumping up against parental rules and pushing
against the boundaries of acceptable behavior, children develop
self-confidence and a sense of their abilities,'' says Linda
Dunlap, chair of the department of psychology at Marist College in
Poughkeepsie, N.Y. ``I would worry if a toddler weren't defiant and
didn't say no.''
 &UR; A WHOLE NEW WORLD &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The downside of a toddler's exhilarating discovery that he is
his own person is a sometimes-overwhelming panic at having to make
the very choices he yearns to make.
</P>
<P>
   ``The toddler's world can be a scary place,'' Shimm says.
``Everything seems new, big and unpredictable, so to gain control
over his environment, a child this age may be tyrannical, stubborn
and rigid.''
</P>
<P>
   He may insist on arranging his stuffed animals in precise order
on the bed every night or, as my daughter did, fly into a rage when
you don't allow him to place raisins on top of his yogurt.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best way to defuse manipulative behavior and instill
cooperation is to hone your negotiating and mediating skills,''
says Mark Roberts, director of clinical training in the psychology
department at Idaho State University in Pocatello. ``The wise
parent stays a step ahead of a toddler, and fights only those
battles that are absolutely necessary.''
</P>
<P>
   Knowing how and when to set reasonable limits, enforcing them
when you must and compromising when you can is tricky. But you can
do it _ and here's how:
 &UR; -0- &QL; 
 &UR; ALLOW SOME TESTING _ BUT NOT TOO MUCH &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Establish limits you can consistently and confidently enforce.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without question, the single most important thing a parent can
do is to set expectations and rules that are responsive and
appropriate to a child's needs,'' Roberts says.
</P>
<P>
   For example, if a child wants to work on a mural and is headed
for the dining room with her paints and paper, you might say, ``I
know you really want to paint right now, but we paint on the
kitchen floor in our house.''
</P>
<P>
   Some parents, however, set too many limits. This not only can
stifle a child's natural curiosity and spirit, but also can set up
a power struggle that the parents will probably lose.
</P>
<P>
   ``Parents who constantly complain about their child's
rule-breaking are probably making too many rules in the first
place,'' Shimm says.
 &UR; SAY NO LESS OFTEN &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``One reason a toddler's favorite word is `no' is because he
hears it so frequently,'' Shimm says.
</P>
<P>
   While you can't avoid the word entirely, you can start by making
a toddler's world safe enough that you don't have to use it so
often.
</P>
<P>
   Another way to avoid saying no is to rephrase your commands: ``I
wish I could let you splash all that tub water onto the floor _ but
we'd have such a mess. How about using this bucket?''
</P>
<P>
   Instead of saying, ``Do you want to get dressed now?'' make a
positive statement such as, ``Let's both get dressed right now.''
Or offer a choice: ``Do you want to put on the Barney shirt or the
Mickey Mouse one?''
 &UR; GIVE TODDLERS WORDS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A young child can't say, ``Gee, Mom, I had a tough day and I'm
really stressed.'' Instead, she'll show you by throwing rolls in a
restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   However, once you label her feelings for her _ ``You're tired,
and as soon as we leave you can sleep in the car'' _ she'll begin
to understand what's going on inside and will be less likely to
test you.
</P>
<P>
   ``Helping a child to interpret her feelings boosts her
self-esteem because it tells her that you're aware of, and care
about, what she's thinking and feeling,'' Roberts says.
 &UR; DON'T EXPECT TOO MUCH &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Toddlers aren't born knowing how to behave,'' Roberts says.
``They have to be socialized.''
</P>
<P>
   While you should encourage their burgeoning independence and
curiosity, you must, at the same time, temper a toddler's behavior
and teach him that it's not acceptable, for example, to bite
another person, to scream on an airplane or to run into the street.
</P>
<P>
   Remember, your lessons will most likely need to be repeated over
and over again until your child knows that you mean business.
 &UR; BE READY FOR THE UNEXPECTED &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Keep in mind the realities of toddlerhood, and prepare for them.
</P>
<P>
   For example, transitions of any kind _ leaving a playdate or
turning off the television to eat dinner _ may trigger testing
behaviors, often because a child is tired and her newly emerging
ability to cope is at a low point.
</P>
<P>
   Times of family stress _ illness, financial trouble, marital
problems _ are also hard on children. Kids are aware of these
difficult periods, even though they don't understand what's behind
them.
</P>
<P>
   Then, too, a toddler's life is filled with stresses of its own.
</P>
<P>
   ``Toilet training, learning to share, joining a playgroup or
adjusting to a new sibling are all milestones in a toddler's life
that can upset her internal equilibrium and trigger a power
struggle,'' Shimm says. ``Preparing for them is your best weapon.''
 &UR; DON'T BE TOO HARD ON YOURSELF &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Raising a toddler is difficult, and rare is the parent who
doesn't lose it at some point.
</P>
<P>
   If you do lose control, Shimm says, ``the best remedy is an
apology and a hug. Children are immensely forgiving.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, sharpen your sense of humor.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the age of 3,'' Shimm says, ``your toddler will _ almost
miraculously _ adopt the social mores of the human race.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Margery D. Rosen is a New York-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
