<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-15 19:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0259 &Cx1f; tab-z
w l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FITNESS-AND-FRUIT-LIF     06-15 1494
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FITNESS-AND-FRUIT-LIFEBEAT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE JOY OF FRUIT 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's LifeBeat
lifestyle package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to LifeBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing articles with color art.) 
 By KEN McALPINE  
 c.1998 Spirit magazine  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   We all know the real problem with eating a healthy diet: Bad
things taste good and good things taste bad, and it's no secret
where our inclinations lie.
</P>
<P>
   We all know that broccoli and spinach are nutritional manna, but
knowing that doesn't make them go down much more easily.
</P>
<P>
   That's what's so remarkable about fruit: It's good for you and
it tastes good. For some people, in fact, it's the source of all
culinary ecstasies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fruit in the microwave oven is phenomenal,'' says Nancy Clark.
``Core an apple, put in a dab of cinnamon, zap it in the microwave,
and you have this yummy-good baked apple. Bananas, peaches, really
any kind of fruit is good warmed. It's sort of like the inside of a
pie.''
</P>
<P>
   Clark, director of nutrition services at Massachusetts
SportsMedicine Brookline and author of ``Nancy Clark's Sports
Nutrition Guidebook'' (Human Kinetics, 1997), has plenty of
innovative fruit favorites _ ``Frozen banana mixed with low-fat
milk in a blender tastes like the thickest, creamiest milkshake
around,'' she swears.
</P>
<P>
   Clark isn't the only nutritionist to volunteer fruit recipes.
One I talked to espoused smoothies _ throw ice, nonfat yogurt,
low-fat milk and your choice of fruit into a blender. Another
lauded fruit pizza _ instead of tomato sauce and fatty cheese, top
the pizza with yogurt and fruit. A third went for frozen banana
chunks _ ``Tastes just like candy!''
</P>
<P>
   This is a far cry from vegetables. All nutritionists want you to
eat them, but I've never had a nutritionist tell me, ``Have I got a
great recipe for Brussels sprouts!''
</P>
<P>
   Best of all, they can eat fruit with a clear conscience. Laced
with fiber, vitamins, minerals and fluid, virtually bereft of fat
and loaded with energy-rich carbohydrates, fruit is the next best
thing to the perfect food.
</P>
<P>
   ``No food will give you a magical edge,'' says Barry Swanson,
professor of food science and human nutrition at Washington State
University in Pullman. ``But fruit comes close.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dietary Guidelines for Americans, developed by the U.S.
Department of Agriculture and the U.S. Department of Health and
Human Services, recommend two to four servings of fruit a day for
adults _ which is roughly two to four servings more than many of us
eat.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, it's easy to add fruit to your diet, and you don't
need much. A banana at breakfast takes care of two fruit servings
right there.
</P>
<P>
   And the choices are legion: Bananas, oranges, strawberries,
cantaloupe and kiwi all supply potassium and vitamin C. Potassium
is a key nutrient in blood-pressure control, and vitamin C is
essential for connective-tissue repair and iron absorption.
</P>
<P>
   Apples, passion fruit and kumquats are loaded with fiber, shown
to lower the risk of intestinal cancer. Mangoes and papayas are
good sources of beta carotene, a vitamin-A cousin that can lower
the risk for certain cancers.
</P>
<P>
   The unjustly maligned avocado _ yep, it's a fruit _ has 60
percent more potassium than bananas, and its fat is mostly
monounsaturated, the type that's been shown to lower blood
cholesterol.
</P>
<P>
   ``Variety ensures you get all these great nutrients,'' Swanson
says. ``Plus people get bored if they eat the same fruits all the
time. Variety sees to it that you keep eating fruit, which is what
you need to do.''
</P>
<P>
   How you eat the fruit is up to you, but Swanson recommends small
fruit snacks several times a day to keep your energy level up. It
will also help fill you up, making it easier to resist high-fat
midafternoon snacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Using fruit as a substitute for fatty foods can really help
improve your health,'' Swanson says. ``And for most Americans the
big thing is getting away from fats.''
</P>
<P>
   A word of caution, however: Most fruit may be fat-free, but it
still has calories.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you need to do is substitute fruit for some of the other
things you're eating,'' Clark says. ``Instead of having two bowls
of cereal for breakfast, have one bowl and add a banana. If you add
fruit without adjusting the rest of your diet, you'll be adding
more calories.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't drop-kick breakfast for a glass of orange juice, either.
Most fruits are low in protein, essential vitamins and minerals
such as calcium, zinc and iron.
</P>
<P>
   So if you skip milk, you'll lose calcium. Skip the cereal, and
lose zinc and iron _ a shame, since the vitamin C in the orange
juice would help you absorb that iron better.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fruit alone is not the magic cure for good health,'' Clark
says. ``It's still about balance.''
</P>
<P>
   For athletes, however, fruit can be close to magic, whether
they're push-it-to-the-limit pros or keeping-in-shape amateur
joggers, sports buffs or workout warriors.
</P>
<P>
   ``What athletes need most is energy, and fruits provide energy
quickly,'' Swanson says. ``The second-biggest problem for athletes
is dehydration, and fruit is filled with water. By eating fruit,
you're consuming the two things you really need.''
</P>
<P>
   Using fruit to your advantage _ before, during and after
exercise _ is easy.
</P>
<P>
   Along with water, Swanson recommends an apple or an orange 30
minutes before exercise. The thought of gobbling something solid
that close to a workout may make you squeamish, but the fiber in
the fruit can actually be an ally, holding in moisture your body
will need.
</P>
<P>
   If you can't bear the thought of solid food, Swanson says, drink
a glass of orange juice in addition to the water.
</P>
<P>
   Eating fruit during exercise is dicier. Fruit and the
carbohydrate they contain are broken down into glycogen, the body's
critical energy fuel _ but most workouts are too short to require
food of any kind during the workout.
</P>
<P>
   As a general rule your body has enough glycogen energy on hand
to keep you going for roughly 90 minutes. In fact, in exercise up
to an hour long, most sports nutritionists will tell you that water
is all you really need.
</P>
<P>
   But if you're going longer, or just feel the need for a little
carbohydrate-energy insurance, try fruit juice. There are plenty of
commercial sports drinks to pump carbohydrates into your system,
but Swanson considers fruit juice just as good. A 100-percent juice
is comparable to many commercial sports drinks, with its high sugar
content dumping energy right into your system.
</P>
<P>
   Because fruit juice is usually about 10 percent carbohydrates _
which is enough to compromise your absorption of water and possibly
upset your stomach _ you'll need to water down the juice, with
water outbalancing the juice.
</P>
<P>
   Because exercise drains your body of sugars and fluids, fruit
also is an ideal postworkout replenisher, a highly efficient
injection of carbohydrate and water at a time when your depleted
body readily absorbs them.
</P>
<P>
   And if solid food sounds unappetizing, the same answer prevails
_ go liquid.
</P>
<P>
   ``Drink what you need,'' says Susan Luke, a Charlotte,
N.C.-based sports nutritionist. ``Fruit juice is a perfect way to
get the fluids back into you and also replace the carbohydrate
you've burned up during training.''
</P>
<P>
   Luke advises athletes to meet their postworkout needs and, to a
large extent, their daily fruit requirement by downing 16 to 32
ounces of orange juice after a hard workout.
</P>
<P>
   This might sound like a lot, Luke says, but because of their
greater energy needs, athletes need more fruit: The average female
athlete needs about 10 fruit servings a day, the average male
athlete 12 to 15. Drink 32 ounces of orange juice, and right there
you're getting about six servings of fruit.
</P>
<P>
   Athlete or not, getting fruit into your diet is mostly a matter
of eating it the way you like it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fruit is terrific,'' Luke says, ``but it won't do you any good
unless you eat it. Did I tell you about my recipe for sunshine
salad? It's got pineapple juice, crushed pineapple, carrots ... ''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Ken McAlpine is a Ventura, Calif.-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to LifeBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing articles with color art.) &QL; 
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
