<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-15 19:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0266 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-bc-campaigns0615-cox     06-15 0759
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-bc-campaigns0615-cox </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ALLIANCE BEGINS UPHILL BATTLE TO 'SAVE POLITICS FROM ITSELF'
 &HT;    By KEN FOSKETT
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A new public interest campaign to end political
mudslinging opened here Monday with this cheery tidbit: Fewer than
one in 10 Americans follow news about candidates and elections very
closely.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, things don't look good for voter participation in
November,'' said Andrew Kohut, pollster for the Pew Research Center
for The People &AMP; The Press.
</P>
<P>
   Against this backdrop of declining voter interest, the Alliance
for Better Campaigns officially launched a 10-state pilot program
to ``save politics from itself.''
</P>
<P>
   The group is urging television news directors to run regular,
five-minute candidate ``mini-debates'' on the issues and air pieces
that explain the truthfulness of political advertisements.
</P>
<P>
   It wants politicians to commit to a code of conduct in which
they pledge to abide by standards of honesty and accountability,
and to appear in their own television advertisements, which might
make some less willing to launch unsubstantiated attacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to teach candidates to curtsey and bow,'' said
Rebecca Rimel, president of the Pew Charitable Trusts, which is
funding the Alliance's work. ``We want to see the candidates run
hard, fight hard ... and give the public an honest, fact-driven
campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   The 10 pilot states selected by the Alliance are Arizona,
California, Colorado, Florida, Illinois, Iowa, Maryland, Minnesota,
Oregon and Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Previous efforts to improve campaign conduct have been mixed. In
Minnesota in 1996, the two Senate candidates were urged to avoid
false and misleading attacks, but voters nonetheless reported
perceiving a high level of negative attacks in the race.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Faucheux, editor of Campaigns &AMP; Elections magazine, said the
Alliance's effort was a positive step because campaigns won't hold
themselves to higher standards. ``It has to be done by (outside)
moral assuagement,'' he said. ``It's not going to come from within
the political community. The incentive there is to win.''
</P>
<P>
   But a panel discussion among television news directors and two
political consultants staged for Monday's kickoff demonstrated the
gulf between the Alliance's lofty goals and the day-to-day business
of managing both television news and political campaigns. The
television news directors expressed frustration over making
political coverage relevant to viewers and getting candidates to
agree to debate one another.
</P>
<P>
   The two political consultants, one a Democrat and one a
Republican, said they were also frustrated.
</P>
<P>
   Kam Kuwata, campaign manager for Rep. Jane Harman's failed bid
for the Democratic gubernatorial nomination in California,
complained that the Harman campaign received virtually no
television coverage on the issues. He said consultants such as
himself increasingly had to rely on ``stunts'' such as staging a
pancake breakfast for reporters to charge that an opponent
flip-flops on the issues.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Douglass, a former California political reporter now with
ABC News, said it was a ``constant battle'' convincing news
directors to run issue stories. ``The assumption was that people
would change the channel,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Lucy Himstedt Riley, news director of WSFA-TV in Montgomery,
Ala., said her station had solved the problem of making politics
interesting by allowing voters to pose the questions to candidates
in this year's hotly contested gubernatorial race.
</P>
<P>
   The news directors said they frequently encountered problems
getting candidates to commit to debates, particularly if a
candidate is ahead in the polls. Both Kuwata and Dan Schnur, a GOP
consultant, acknowledged they would urge a candidate not to
participate in a debate if ahead in the polls.
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Cochran, president of the Radio-Television News
Directors Association, was also cool the idea of free air time for
candidates, saying it simply allowed candidates to ``rehash
restated positions.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul Taylor, executive director of the Alliance and a former
Washington Post reporter, left journalism two years ago to campaign
for more free television time for candidates. But he said he
learned a hard lesson.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you ask a broadcaster for free air time, you earn his
wrath,'' he said. ``Air time is what he sells, not what he gives
away.''
</P>
<P>
   (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
