<HEADER>
A0271 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-SUNVALLEY-3TAK     06-15 0859
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-SUNVALLEY-3TAKES-$ADV21-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SUMMER OF DOUBLE AXELS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 21) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By LINDA GREENHOUSE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Sun Valley in the summer?'' several skiing friends asked
skeptically when I mentioned our vacation plans. ``What is there to
do in Sun Valley in the summer?'' More than enough, it turned out,
to fill two August weeks at the famous Idaho ski resort and leave
us wanting to come back.
</P>
<P>
   Hiking, white-water rafting, outdoor figure skating, relaxing in
natural springs hot enough to poach a salmon, sampling an array of
interesting restaurants and just taking in the colorful passing
scene somehow left us no time to make the Hemingway pilgrimage _
the author, a frequent visitor to the resort, lived in the adjacent
city of Ketchum, where he was buried after committing suicide in
1961.
</P>
<P>
   We could also have gone on a trail ride or on a ``take a llama
to lunch'' trek that uses llamas as pack animals, browsed the two
dozen art galleries, or attended the Sun Valley Summer Symphony's
free open-air concerts. Just more excuses for planning a return
visit.
</P>
<P>
   For our family, and specifically for our 12-year-old daughter,
Hannah, Sun Valley's lure was figure skating. The resort has
offered a summer skating program since it opened in 1936, and the
Sun Valley Skating School is now a mecca for skaters from all over
the country. They come for the chance to skate in a stunningly
beautiful setting and to learn from professionals with world-class
credentials.
</P>
<P>
   The two rinks, one indoors and one out under the blue mountain
sky, are open from early morning into the evening _ and without a
hockey player in sight.
</P>
<P>
   The skating attracts young and old. A few dozen New Yorkers, who
call themselves the Geriatric Figure Skating Club, have been
meeting at Sun Valley for years under the motto, ``Old figure
skaters never die, they just go to the big rink in the sky.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever they do, it works: They look great on the ice, and the
club's oldest active member is 89. The president, Leo Roberts,
offered me my favorite souvenir of the trip, a provisional
membership card and invitation to apply for full membership when I
get old enough.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike some skating centers, where the casual public is barely
tolerated, Sun Valley offers public sessions throughout the day on
the outdoor rink, by far the more desirable of the two.
</P>
<P>
   A session lasting an hour and a half costs a reasonable $7.75.
As a lifelong but minimally competent skater, I almost didn't bring
my skates, afraid that the general skating level would be far
beyond me. But everyone is welcome, and there were plenty of
first-timers stumbling around, as well as veterans showing off
their footwork. The fresh air and friendly atmosphere were
addictive, and my husband, Gene Fidell, and I were inspired to take
a few lessons from Sherry Winder, a pro with the requisite patience
and sense of humor to take us on.
</P>
<P>
   The skating school itself, by contrast, is not for dilettantes.
We planned our time in Sun Valley to coordinate with a half-dozen
other families from our local rink in Rockville, Md., and with
Hannah's coach, Alice Shelley. So Hannah and her friends skated
four to five hours a day, taking classes like ``The Art of the
Edge'' and individual lessons from professionals, including Linda
Fratianne, the Olympic silver medalist, and Judy Blumberg, a
five-time national ice dance champion.
</P>
<P>
   These practice sessions are scheduled throughout the day for
various types and levels of skating. The 50-minute sessions must be
reserved in weeklong blocks and prepaid. Arrangements with the
various pros are usually made well in advance from a list the
school provides.
</P>
<P>
   It appeared, however, that anyone who was eligible to skate
during a given hour could almost always find a pro to give a
lesson.
</P>
<P>
   The teachers were challenging but supportive, and the girls
ended their long days tired but eager for more. The charges for ice
time and lesson fees _ up to $40 for a private 25-minute lesson _
are comparable to those at many more ordinary rinks, but it is easy
to spend $100 or more a day when you start counting by the hour.
</P>
<P>
   While skating was the main event for us, it is only a colorful
curiosity to most of Sun Valley's visitors, who come for the
hiking, fly-fishing, golf or other outdoor activities. For the
casual passer-by, there are several enjoyable ways to take in the
skating scene without actually getting on the ice.
</P>
<P>
   The obvious one is the weekly Saturday night figure-skating
show, which not only showcases the resident talent but brings in a
different world-famous skater for a starring role every week. Nancy
Kerrigan, the 1994 Olympic silver medalist, was the headline
performer we saw.
</P>
<P>
   The show is on the outdoor rink. Buy reserved seats from the
resort's sports center and bring a blanket _ at 6,000 feet,
temperatures plunge once the sun goes down, and the metal bleachers
are excellent conductors of the nighttime chill. No one warned us
about this, and by the end of the show, I felt as if I had wandered
into a late-season football game.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
