<HEADER>
A0272 &Cx1f; tab-z
w e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REMEMBERING-PHIL-HART     06-15 1258
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REMEMBERING-PHIL-HARTMAN-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN MEMORIAM: PHIL HARTMAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of Phil Hartman in a scene from
``Newsradio.'' 
 By ANDREW RYAN  
 c.1998 Canadian TV Guide  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Phil Hartman was one of the funniest guys around, but that's
only part of the reason why his sudden departure is so tragic.
</P>
<P>
   What makes it even worse is the fact that Hartman's death _ at
his own wife's hand, in a bizarre murder/suicide on May 28 _ came
at the worst possible time in his career.
</P>
<P>
   At 49, Hartman was enjoying professional peaks in many areas: He
was a lead character on a hit sitcom, ``Newsradio.'' He was also
part of the recurring voice ensemble on ``The Simpsons,'' he had
already wrapped a key role in the ambitious film ``Small Soldiers''
and he regularly lent his comic presence as a commercial pitchman
for products ranging from fast-food chains to phone companies.
</P>
<P>
   For a comic actor who had labored hard for more than a decade,
working his way from thankless bit parts on ``Saturday Night Live''
to small supporting roles in movies, everything was suddenly coming
together for Hartman.
</P>
<P>
   Then it all came to an abrupt end.
</P>
<P>
   I had the good fortune to interview Hartman on four occasions
over the years, and I can honestly say that he was every bit as
funny in person as he was on television.
</P>
<P>
   One of the first times we talked was on the telephone, in
connection with his role in the 1992 comedy ``Coneheads,'' in which
he played the pointy-headed alien leader. The comedian was calling
from a hotel near the location of his next film, the comedy ``House
Guest,'' co-starring Sinbad.
</P>
<P>
   Early in our telephone chat, Hartman broke away to politely ask
a room-service waiter to leave his lunch on the table. Hearing him
do so in that trademark Hartman unctuous voice, I immediately broke
into laughter.
</P>
<P>
   When the comedian came back on the line, he asked me what was so
funny, and I told him that it was hilarious to hear him say
something normal in his distinctive voice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get that a lot,'' he cracked.
</P>
<P>
   In that same conversation, Hartman waxed eloquent about his
memories of a Canadian boyhood in Brantford, Ont., a town best
known as the birthplace of hockey legend Wayne Gretzky.
</P>
<P>
   Although Hartman's family departed Brantford while he was quite
young, and he was subsequently reared in Connecticut and Los
Angeles, he still recalled the small town fondly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just remember Brantford as being this peaceful place, with
acres of trees and farmland and beautiful scenery,'' Hartman said.
``It was actually very inspiring for me _ it's probably why I later
went into art.''
</P>
<P>
   Hartman's artistic bent took him to California State University
in Los Angeles, where he studied graphic design and later, in the
early 1970s, achieved renown as the designer of record-album
jackets, including ones for The Eagles, America and Poco.
</P>
<P>
   Hartman had always enjoyed entertaining people, but didn't begin
to think of it as a possible career until 1975, when he joined the
Los Angeles-based improv group The Groundlings, working with
up-and-coming comics including Paul Reubens, later better known as
Pee-Wee Herman.
</P>
<P>
   Hartman was hooked immediately.
</P>
<P>
   ``I discovered I could make people laugh, really laugh,'' he
recalled, ``and I wanted more.''
</P>
<P>
   That ``more'' took shape in 1986, when he joined ``Saturday
Night Live'' as a full-time cast member.
</P>
<P>
   In the years that followed, he became known as the man of a
thousand comic faces _ his ability to mimic voice and facial
patterns was astounding. Hartman's repertoire of impressions ran
the gamut: Ed McMahon, Frank Sinatra, Jimmy Swaggart, Phil Donahue,
Ted Kennedy and Bill Clinton, to name but a few.
</P>
<P>
   He also created his own inimitable characters, including the
Anal-Retentive Chef, who spent most of his time wrapping leftover
food neatly and precisely in cling-wrap, and the Unfrozen Caveman
Lawyer, a Cro-Magnon attorney who was frightened by all things
modern.
</P>
<P>
   I talked with Hartman on another occasion, this time in person,
during his ``SNL'' years. The most ingratiating thing about his
personality, I found, was that he truly had no desire to be the
show's big star.
</P>
<P>
   During his ``SNL'' period _ from 1986 to 1994 _ Hartman shared
the stage with big talent: Dana Carvey, Mike Myers, Dennis Miller,
Chris Farley and others. Among this lineup of comic all-stars,
however, he preferred to think of himself as a supporting player.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm like the glue that kind of holds the show together,'' he
said. ``That's why I usually play characters that are within the
range of believability.''
</P>
<P>
   Hartman maintained that believability when he left ``SNL'' to
star in the NBC sitcom ``Newsradio.'' His character, smarmy news
anchor Bill MacNeil, was tailor-made for Hartman, who loved the
idea of working with a large ensemble cast.
</P>
<P>
   My fondest, most lasting memory of Phil Hartman came only a few
months ago, during media day on the ``Newsradio'' set.
</P>
<P>
   The entire cast of eight regulars was assigned to field
questions and promote the show. It was clear, however, that Hartman
was the show's esteemed elder statesman. Not only were most of the
questions directed to him, but also most of his fellow performers
looked to him for guidance in their answers.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, co-star Maura Tierney was struggling to find words
to explain the show's success, and Hartman helped her out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, well, we're an ensemble show in the truest sense of the
word,'' he purred in that radio-intoned voice. ``I guess we're
somewhat in the tradition of `Cheers' and `Taxi,' where there
really is no dominant star. But on this show, the star is me ...
But seriously, everybody on this show is capable of going out and
knocking one out of the park.''
</P>
<P>
   Hartman kept that same approach throughout the hour-long
interview session, gently reminding reporters of movie projects his
co-stars were currently working on.
</P>
<P>
   But the most telling moment came when someone asked Hartman to
compare his ``NewsRadio'' experience with his old days on
``Saturday Night Live.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What's better about doing this show is that there's more of a
team spirit and we're all very close,'' Hartman said thoughtfully.
``On `SNL' there was a competitive atmosphere conducive to cliques
and rivalries and backstabbing. It was a more difficult situation
to endure emotionally.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a very close-knit team, and I'm very, very happy.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Andrew Ryan is the features editor of Canadian TV Guide, based
in North York, Ontario.) &LR; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) &QL; 
