<HEADLINE>
DONNY OSMOND BOUNCES BACK 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of Donny Osmond during the making of
``Mulan.'' 
 By CINDY PEARLMAN  
 World rights except Chicago 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    ``Donny'' just doesn't seem to make it.
 &HT;    He's 40 now, and the father of five sons. How about ``Don?''
``Donald?'' ``Mr. Osmond?'' At least ``The Donny?''
 &HT;    ``Just call me Donny,'' the one-time teen idol and the lead half
of ``Donny and Marie'' says. ``I'll be Donny until I'm 90.''
 &HT;    It's 10 a.m. in a Honolulu hotel. It's early, but not too early
for Osmond to have had breakfast with his family, gotten in some
scuba diving and now started thinking aloud about the new talk show
he and his sister have coming up in the fall _ predictably, it's
called ``The Donny and Marie Show.''
 &HT;    Osmond has a vision, and it's of rapper Sean ``Puffy'' Combs.
No, really, he's serious.
 &HT;    ``I'd love to have Puff Daddy come on,'' Osmond says. ``I want
to sing one of Puffy's songs with him.''
 &HT;    Obviously, this isn't your father's ``Donny and Marie.'' They
won't be wearing bell bottoms, and don't expect Perry Como to show
up. Osmond is thinking of Sean Connery and Harrison Ford. His
sister wants to interview Pee Wee Herman.
 &HT;    ``It's not going to be nice and sweet,'' he promises. ``It won't
be Marie going, `Oh, you're such a great brother.' We want to
surprise people.''
 &HT;    There are limits, of course. Don't expect a tag-team version of
``The Jerry Springer Show.''
 &HT;    ``We don't want to bash and expose _ least of all each other,''
Osmond says, laughing. ``We want to do what we call entertainment
talk.''
 &HT;    The show will begin taping in July for a September debut. Until
then, though, Osmond will be heard _ though not seen _ in Disney's
lush new animated film ``Mulan,'' opening June 19.
 &HT;    His role as the singing voice of the warrior Shang _ the
speaking scenes are voiced by B.D. Wong _ realizes a standing
ambition of Osmond's. He'd actually auditioned for the speaking
voice of Hercules last year, but lost out. Only after the ``Mulan''
casting director saw him onstage in the Webber-Rice musical
``Joseph and the Amazing Technicolor Dreamcoat'' did Osmond get his
shot at animated stardom.
 &HT;    This is real stardom, too _ at least if you ask the singer's
sons, ages newborn to 19.
 &HT;    ``One of my little boys said to me, `Now that you've done a
Disney film, you're a real star, Dad,'' Osmond says.
 &HT;    An older generation already knew that, of course. The old
version of ``The Donny and Marie Show'' debuted in 1976 and ran
until 1979.
 &HT;    ``We're the people you grew up with and who visited your living
room in the '70s,'' Osmond says. ``Marie and I think, for our
audience, it will be like old friends getting back together.''
 &HT;    Those days are long gone, but Osmond has a sense of humor about
them.
 &HT;    ``I think the highlight of my young career was when a girl told
me her parents used `The Donny and Marie Show' as a potty-training
tool,'' he says with a laugh. ``If she wet her pants, she couldn't
watch the show.''
 &HT;    At the time, the Osmonds enjoyed a squeaky-clean image, whether
on television or on the concert stage. Today, though, Osmond is
willing to concede that the reality was a bit less pristine.
 &HT;    ``I had this little system down,'' he recalls. ``Marie would
help pick out the cute girls in the audience, and our road manager
would give them backstage passes.''
 &HT;    But times have changed, he hastens to add: ``At 20, I met my
wife, and those shenanigans were over.''
 &HT;    In the old days, he admits, fame sometimes went to his head.
 &HT;    ``Once Lucille Ball was guesting on our show,'' he recalls,
``and I told her she was singing flat. I was like, `Could you do
that one more time, babe?' Now I look back on that incident and
cringe.''
 &HT;    When the show ended, Osmond went his separate way. He recorded
several solo albums, including the Top-20 hit ``Soldier of Love.''
 &HT;    ``It was funny,'' he recalls. ``DJs would play the single and
then, weeks later, they would announce it was me in amazement. They
didn't think it could possibly be me, because they liked the song
so much. They couldn't believe that it was cool to be listening to
Donny Osmond again.''
 &HT;    He enjoyed being apart from the ``Donny and Marie'' vibe, he
says.
 &HT;    ``It was nice for us to be able to separate,'' he says. ``We
wanted to do our own things. You don't want to feel like you're
half of an act. Sometimes you just want to prove that you can do it
on your own.''
 &HT;    Now they're ready to reteam, but they're 20 years older. Things
won't be the way they were, Osmond says, but that's not necessarily
bad.
 &HT;    ``Over the years since our first show, our relationship wasn't
as close,'' he says. ``We got married, we had children. We had our
own lives. We would only see each other at holidays.''
 &HT;    The spur to reunite was a joint appearance on ``The Rosie
O'Donnell Show.'' It arose from an earlier visit in which Osmond,
appearing without his sister, had made fun of O'Donnell's weight
during a conversation about air travel.
 &HT;    ``I didn't think a helicopter could handle that much weight,''
he said _ incurring the audience's wrath and making himself a
running target of derision on the show for weeks to come.
 &HT;    Months later, Marie Osmond called her brother and told him she
was going on ``Rosie.'' Maybe he'd like to come along and
apologize, she suggested.
 &HT;    ``Believe me, before that I made calls and wrote letters. I
apologized profusely to Rosie,'' Osmond insists.
 &HT;    The joint appearance was nightmarish, the singer says.
 &HT;    ``During Marie's first segment,'' he recalls, ``I was in the
green room, and my sister tells Rosie how I'd rib her about being
fat when she was little. I was like, `Marie, shut up!'''
 &HT;    Then Osmond took the stage, bearing a big bouquet of flowers.
 &HT;    ``People started to throw things at me,'' he says. ``Every time
I would try to speak, Rosie would hit a button and my line about
her weight was broadcast.''
 &HT;    When Osmond agreed to sing one of his old hits with her,
O'Donnell had another surprise _ a puppy-dog costume.
 &HT;    ``I had no choice but put it on,'' Osmond recalls, wincing.
``Marie gave me no support. Marie even said, `Down on one knee.'''
 &HT;    Cowering, Osmond crooned ``Puppy Love'' and earned O'Donnell's
pardon.
 &HT;    ``It was the most humiliating moment in my entire life,'' he
says.
 &HT;    But the audience loved it. The ratings were the series'
third-highest ever, trailing only visits from Tom Cruise and Barbra
Streisand. Producer/host Dick Clark caught it, and pitched the
Osmonds on a return to television.
 &HT;    Part of his reason for agreeing, Osmond jokes, was that
O'Donnell agreed to repay their visit.
 &HT;    ``I asked Rosie to come on and she said yes,'' he says with a
mock-sinister chuckle. ``I do want some vindication for the puppy
suit. Believe me, all my friends are thinking.''
 &HT;    He may have been onstage for 35 of his 40 years, but Osmond
admits to a combination of nervousness and nostalgia as he and his
sister try to rekindle the old magic.
 &HT;    ``When we did the pilot, Marie was in her dressing room,'' he
recalls. ``I walked by, and she was sitting there chewing on her
fingernails. It was just like the old days.
 &HT;    ``I looked at Marie and said, `Are you nervous?''' he adds.
``She said, `I'm half scared to death.'
 &HT;    ``I said, `Me, too.'''
 c.1998 Cindy Pearlman  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Cindy Pearlman is a Chicago-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
