<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BETTY-THOMAS-DIRECTS-DR-DOLITTLE-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BETTY THOMAS: PUTTING WORDS IN ANIMALS' MOUTHS WITH `DR.
DOLITTLE' 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of Betty Thomas directing Eddie Murphy in a
scene from ``Dr. Dolittle.'' 
 By IAN SPELLING  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Betty Thomas thought she'd direct art films.
 &HT;    ``That seemed like such a perfect combination for me,'' she
says. ``In the 1970s, I was always networking with other women I
knew. The idea was to help each other, introduce each other to
other people.
 &HT;    ``Anyway, I found an old networking notebook I had, from 1976,
that said I wanted to direct movies,'' Thomas recalls. ``I had a
five-year plan, and the movies I'd direct would have to do with
dolphins. I guess I thought it would be the ultimate thing for
me.''
 &HT;    Thomas chuckles.
 &HT;    ``By then I'd acted and painted,'' she says. ``I'd written
little things and directed improv groups. I felt I should be the
person who said, `Here's what should happen.'''
 &HT;    That she is, but the art houses are still waiting. Thomas, the
boisterous, quick-to-laugh former star of television's ``Hill
Street Blues,'' made her name as a director with HBO's series
``Dream On,'' the acclaimed cable movie ``The Late Shift'' (1996)
and two dolphin-free features, ``The Brady Bunch Movie'' (1995) and
``Private Parts'' (1997), the latter starring Howard Stern.
 &HT;    She gets a little closer to ``Flipper'' with her latest film,
``Dr. Dolittle,'' opening June 26, with a cast that includes Eddie
Murphy and a whole lot of animals.
 &HT;    A remake of the lame 1967 Rex Harrison fantasy/musical might not
seem initially promising, but for the director Murphy made all the
difference.
 &HT;    ``I wouldn't have been interested in `Dolittle' if it weren't
for Eddie,'' she admits. ``I knew the film would be nothing like
the original if we had Eddie. I knew the film would have an edge if
we had Eddie.
 &HT;    ``And, hey, any director who wants to do comedy wants to work
with Eddie Murphy.''
 &HT;    Her biggest challenge, she says, was to get Murphy, who despises
every creature in the animal kingdom, into the same frame as the
assorted dogs, llamas, rats and tigers that share the life of Dr.
John Dolittle.
 &HT;    ``Eddie doesn't have a hell of a lot of experience with animals
in his life,'' Thomas says.
 &HT;    ``Our first week he brought in a tape of `When Animals
Attack,''' she recalls. ``Eddie insisted I see the tape, and on it
there was a kitty cat, up for adoption, that attacked this guy.
 &HT;    ``Eddie's screaming, `See! See! Anything can attack!'
 &HT;    ``After that I had to talk him into everything he did,'' she
says, laughing. ``But he did everything I asked.
 &HT;    ``Eddie brings lots of intuitive comedy to any film he does,''
the director adds more seriously. ``So you give him the basic scene
and he goes from there, coming up with ideas and jokes that just
weren't there on paper. That's what I hoped he'd do.''
 &HT;    Murphy wasn't the only improvisation-happy comic on the set.
Norm Macdonald and Chris Rock provided the voices of a dog and
guinea pig, respectively. Their freewheeling creativity only
further complicated Thomas' dealings with moody animals and the 300
intricate, computer-generated images that were employed to convince
moviegoers that the various creatures were chatting away.
 &HT;    ``I didn't record the dialogue beforehand and stick with every
line,'' she says. ``I kept changing things over and over and over
until it got funnier. I couldn't let the improv instincts of these
great comedians be blocked, so I think I made it a nightmare for
the special-effects people. But that's the way it had to be.''
 &HT;    The resulting film is a strange movie that defies easy
description, its director says.
 &HT;    ``I don't know what it is,'' she says, laughing. ``Is it a
family film? Is it a kids' movie?
 &HT;    ``I made `Brady Bunch' for 30-year-olds, and 14-year-olds went
five and six times,'' she recalls. ```Dolittle' is not the same,
but it's that kind of a movie.
 &HT;    ``It's a great, teen-ager-hip movie,'' Thomas says. ``You get an
idea of the movie's tone from having Eddie in there, and from
having Chris and Norm as our largest animals. Then you throw Albert
Brooks in there, too.
 &HT;    ``It's not a kids' movie,'' she says, ``but younger kids are
thrilled to like a movie their older brother or sister likes.''
 &HT;    Thomas sighs.
 &HT;    ``It's better than I thought it could be,'' she says. ``I don't
know that I've said that about one of my movies. It's an Eddie
Murphy movie, and there's enough of the way I do movies to make it
sort of my kind of movie, too. I'm pleased.''
 &HT;    It's no wonder that Thomas is pleased. She's one of only three
women to direct a picture that's earned more than $60 million. Her
production company, Tall Trees, green-lighted the hit teen film,
``Can't Hardly Wait,'' and Thomas is a self-described ``in-demand''
director considering three projects for her next effort.
 &HT;    Don't call her a woman director, though. Thomas resolutely
refuses to carry any sort of a banner for other female filmmakers,
or to make movies that speak for women as such.
 &HT;    ``I don't, I can't,'' says Thomas, who lives in Hollywood and is
``old enough to know better than to give my age.''
 &HT;    ``I do feel pressure to make movies that make some statement,''
she admits. ``I feel personal pressure to make films that are
revealing of me as a human being.''
 &HT;    Those revelations aren't necessary direct, she adds. Thomas
compares the process of making a film to that of painting.
 &HT;    ``You take 114 pages of white paper with some typing on them,
typing which is sometimes good and sometimes not so good,'' she
says, ``and you try to whip it together with the help of hundreds
of people doing hundreds of things.
 &HT;    ``I was an art student at college,'' she says. ``I'd have this
white canvas and had to end up with a painting. Film is similar,
but different: You're starting with some other person's vision,
which is the script, and you have to take it and make it your
vision while realizing it's a collaborative process.
 &HT;    ``Also,'' she adds, ``you can do a painting pretty quickly,
whereas a film can take a year, a year-and-a-half of your life. You
really have to love making films to do this job, and you have to
love the film you're doing to do it well.''
 &HT;    After a very busy last couple of years, Thomas admits that she'd
love to be able to take a break. But momentum in a directing career
is a fragile thing, and she's afraid to slow down while she's still
on a roll.
 &HT;    Which means that pining ``Hill Street'' fans who'd like to see
her acting again will have to wait.
 &HT;    ``You know what I'm thinking?'' she says. ``I want to retire
from directing in about 10 years, and for the last five years of my
working life I want to be the next-door neighbor on some very easy
sitcom.
 &HT;    ``Maybe I'll be like that neighbor whose face you never see on
`Home Improvement,''' she jokes. ``That would be perfect.
 &HT;    ``Then I'll retire and, hopefully, people will remember me as
both a director and an actor. That's what I'm thinking.''
 c.1998 Ian Spelling  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ian Spelling is a New York-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
