<HEADER>
A0275 &Cx1f; tab-z
w e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MING-NA-WEN-IN-MULAN-     06-15 1426
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MING-NA-WEN-IN-MULAN-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MING-NA WEN GIVES `MULAN' A SPECIAL VOICE 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of the character Mulan on horseback in a
scene from ``Mulan.'' 
 By JEANNE WOLF  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Since she first reduced audiences to sobs in ``The Joy Luck
Club'' (1993), Ming-Na Wen has built a blossoming Hollywood career
on unexpected choices.
</P>
<P>
   She went from that wrenching drama to the chop-and-sock action
flicks ``Hong Kong 97'' (1993) and ``The Streetfighter'' (1994),
starred as the acerbic Trudy in the television sitcom ``The Single
Girl'' and then shocked her fans _ and her parents _ by revealing
much more than her acting talent in a steamy love scene with Wesley
Snipes in ``One Night Stand'' (1997).
</P>
<P>
   Now she's tackling a cartoon epic in Disney's animated feature
``Mulan,'' opening June 19. Wen voices the title character, a girl
in ancient China who masquerades as a man to join the war against
invading Huns. Eddie Murphy and B.D. Wong provide other voices.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mulan'' is a dream come true for the 30-year-old, Hong
Kong-born actress, who was raised in Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was a little girl my mother first told me the story,
which is an enduring Chinese legend,'' Wen says. ``It made a big
impression on me. I think a lot of Asian girls identify with Mulan
because she's so courageous and conquers every obstacle placed in
her way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was also a Disney maniac,'' she adds. ``I loved all their
animated movies. I wanted all my vacations to be at Disney World.
I've been there about seven times, and I know every ride. So I
guess you can imagine how I felt when I found out they wanted me to
star in `Mulan.'''
</P>
<P>
   Wen also appreciates the fact that ``Mulan'' is the first Disney
animated feature to star a largely Asian cast, and that its story
will shatter some stereotypes.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's this weird misconception about Chinese women _ that
we're submissive,'' the actress says with a sigh. ``Actually, it's
a very matriarchal society. You should meet my mom. We call her
`the boss lady.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Also, Mulan breaks out of the Cinderella complex,'' she adds.
``She saves the guy, she saves China and she does it all by
believing in herself and following her heart.''
</P>
<P>
   Wen's work on ``Mulan,'' which spanned several years, took on
added resonance after the sudden death of her father midway through
production. Mulan undertakes her masquerade to save her own ailing
father from being drafted into the war against the Huns.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's willing to sacrifice her own life to protect him,'' the
actress says. ``I identified with that.''
</P>
<P>
   The man she calls her father was actually her stepfather, Wen
adds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no memory of my real father, who abandoned us in Hong
Kong when I was a baby,'' she says. ``Without my stepfather, I
don't think I'd be living my version of the American dream.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that he passed away during production just
intensified the connection I felt with Mulan,'' Wen says. ``When my
mom and I watched the film we were both thinking of my dad. We
ended up bawling through most of the film.''
</P>
<P>
   Wen had to struggle with her own Asian identity as a child in
Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's taken me a long while to embrace my own culture and love
who I am,'' she admits. ``I remember I was thinking of taking an
American name. In addition to Disney films, I liked to watch reruns
of old classic movies starring Doris Day and Ann-Margret.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to be called Maggie or Doris. Can you imagine? Maggie
Wen.''
</P>
<P>
   Wen's teen-age years were defined by her father's Chinese
restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was cleaning tables when I was 13,'' she recalls, ``and I
was seriously waitressing by the time I was 16. It wasn't easy, but
I think it gave me a good business sense.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of my friends when I was growing up were cooks and
busboys,'' she explains. ``They all worked hard, and some of that
work ethic rubbed off on me. It helped me keep my self-esteem and
my focus when I had to face the biz side of show biz.''
</P>
<P>
   Even then, Wen says, she had a rebellious streak.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember once I was waiting on this huge party,'' she says.
``I think there were 12 of them. They were being very obnoxious. At
the end of the meal, I came to the table, and they had each left a
penny next to their plates. That was their little joke.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was so offended,'' she recalls. ``I felt it was just a
reflection of the fact that they didn't think the Chinese were
really people. So I picked up every one of the pennies and went
charging off to the cash register where they were paying the check.
</P>
<P>
   ``I practically threw the pennies down and said, `You know what?
I don't need this insult. As far as I'm concerned, you can choke on
your pennies!'''
</P>
<P>
   Wen moved on to study dramatic arts at Carnegie Mellon
University in Pittsburgh. After graduation, she headed for New
York, where she soon landed a role as a 16-year-old Vietnamese
refugee on the CBS soap opera ``As The World Turns.''
</P>
<P>
   The young actress went on to a variety of theater roles before
``The Joy Luck Club,'' which brought her back to China for filming.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the first time I'd been there since we left when I was
a toddler,'' she says. ``I took my mother along. It was an
incredible experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Wen's first marriage, to actor/writer Kirk Aanes, ended in
divorce.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was young and in love,'' she says. ``I discovered too late
that we were both in show business and there was constant
competition. Every time I got a job I had to console him. That took
its toll.''
</P>
<P>
   Their breakup made Wen admittedly ``gun-shy,'' but nevertheless
when she married again, three years ago, it was to another
actor/writer _ Eric Zee, who played Dr. Peter Chow on ``Dr. Quinn,
Medicine Woman.''
</P>
<P>
   Before they were married, Wen produced Zee's play, ``Exit the
Dragon,'' which dealt with the downside of being an Asian actor in
a white show-business world.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Eric had to write the play to come to terms with the
prejudice he faced as an actor,'' she says. ``It's about three
Chinese men who are struggling to make it in show business and the
stereotypical roles they're forced to play.''
</P>
<P>
   Wen hastens to add that the problems of her first marriage have
not resurfaced in her second.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not competitive,'' she says. ``Eric wants to celebrate
my success. He's the most loving person.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a good thing, because Wen is experiencing a lot of success
lately, including her Broadway debut in David Hwang's recently
closed ``Golden Child.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Being on the Broadway stage was like living out one more
dream,'' she says. ``I feel like I'm the luckiest girl alive.''
</P>
<P>
   That success may have been foreshadowed shortly after she was
born, she adds.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Chinese people read faces,'' she explains. ``They look at
the shape of your eyebrows, your nose, your lips. The amazing thing
is that it seems to be quite accurate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyway, my mother looked at my face when I was a baby,'' she
says. ``My nose, the bridge of my nose, shoots toward the sky. It's
very high for a Chinese person. It meant that I was destined to be
in the arts.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mother didn't think that would be a good profession for
me,'' she adds with a laugh. ``So for years she did everything she
could to dissuade me from being an actress.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now that I'm successful, she takes all the credit,'' Wen adds.
``Not only that, she gives me acting tips all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Jeanne Wolf, who is based in Hollywood, reports on the
entertainment industry for television, radio and print outlets.) &LR; 
