<P>
   ASIA-MARKETPLACE _ As the Japanese yen continued its slide into
the abyss Monday, stock markets around the world trembled. So much
for the idea that Asian problems could be contained.
</P>
<P>
   (We plan to move the story by 8:30 p.m. ET.)
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or 1927.)
</P>
<P>
   (Top display)
</P>
<P>
   YEN-DOLLAR (Washington) _ For the past 10 months the Clinton
administration has warned that a full-blown recession in Japan
could prove the time bomb of the Asian crisis, triggering an sharp
fall of the Japanese yen and, in turn, a second wave of the
economic contagion rattling investors around the globe. Now that
scenario appears to be unfolding. By David E. Sanger.
</P>
<P>
   (We plan to move the story by 8:45 p.m. ET.)
</P>
<P>
   GOLDMAN-SACHS (Undated) _ Developments in the decision by
Goldman, Sachs to go public. By Joseph Kahn.
</P>
<P>
   (We plan to move the story by 9 p.m. ET.)
</P>
<P>
   (Bottom display)
</P>
<P>
   NORTEL-BAYNETWORKS _ Grasping for leadership in the market for
Internet communications equipment, Northern Telecom Ltd. of Canada,
North America's No. 2 maker of telephone gear, announced Monday
that it had agreed to acquire Bay Networks Inc., a leading data
networking company, for $9.1 billion in stock. By Seth Schiesel.
</P>
<P>
   (We plan to move the story by 9 p.m. ET.)
</P>
<P>
   BIZGLANCE (Undated) _ Digest of the day's financial stories.
(Will move by 9:30 p.m. Eastern Time.)
</P>
<P>
   Here are tonight's other regular features:
</P>
<P>
   CREDIT (New York) _ Long-term government interest rates fell to
their lowest level in 30 years Monday while other government
yields, including those that effect home mortgage rates, dropped
sharply. By Jonathan Fuerbringer.
</P>
<P>
   (Story has moved.)
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ Turmoil in Asian markets infected Wall
Street on Monday, sending the stock market to the lowest level in
three months on widening fears that Asia's recession would clamp
American corporate profit growth more seriously and deeply than
previously thought. By Sharon R. King.
</P>
<P>
   (We plan to move the story by 8:15 p.m. ET.)
</P>
<P>
   ZIFF-DAVIS-AD-COLUMN _ Ziff-Davis, the high-technology media and
marketing company, has introduced a 24-hour cable television
network focused on computing and the Internet and is counting on a
multimillion-dollar advertising campaign to put it on the map.
</P>
<P>
   (We plan to move the story by 8:15 p.m. ET.) &QL;
