<DOCNO> NYT19980615.0322 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-15 19:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0280 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-SUNVALLEY-2NDT     06-15 0987
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-SUNVALLEY-2NDTAKE-$ADV21-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: football game.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Another way to watch the skating is to eat lunch at the patio
restaurant of the Sun Valley Lodge, the resort's 500-room
centerpiece. The patio overlooks the outdoor rink, where a special
lunch-hour practice session is set aside for the pros. It was
thrilling, as well as instructive, to watch these top-level skaters
working the kinks out of their programs, coaxing breathtaking
triple jumps out of sometimes uncooperative bodies.
</P>
<P>
   And anyone can simply take a seat in the bleachers and watch a
class. Several times a week, Gia Guddat, the artistic director of
the ice show, and Gary Beacom, a top professional whose offbeat
routines have made him a television favorite, led a morning clinic
on the outdoor rink consisting of exercises of increasingly
daunting intricacy against a musical background.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Guddat was usually draped in the gloriously retro tie-dyed
outfits she designs and sells in the Skyntytes Factory in downtown
Ketchum. Beacom, by contrast, was a kind of skating Everyman,
dressed in khaki shorts, a white sport shirt and sunglasses.
Together, they made a visually arresting pair of Pied Pipers for
the two dozen skaters who tried gamely to imitate their moves.
</P>
<P>
   (As it happens, Beacom is unavailable to perform this summer; he
is serving a federal prison sentence for income tax fraud.)
</P>
<P>
   In winter, Sun Valley is only for skiing (the outdoor rink stays
open, but staff members told me that there are rarely more than 10
skaters on it). In the summer, Sun Valley serves two purposes: as a
full-service resort destination, and as a jumping-off point for
various wilderness activities in the surrounding mountains.
</P>
<P>
   Sun Valley is in the Wood River Valley in south-central Idaho,
and sits at the entrance to the Sawtooth National Recreation Area,
a 756,000-acre preserve managed by the United States Forest
Service. The recreation area marked its 25th anniversary during our
stay. There are many hiking trails of varying difficulty, all
offering heart-stopping views of the surrounding high peaks.
</P>
<P>
   We spent a late afternoon on an ``easy'' three-mile hike from a
trail head close to the Galena Mountain pass on state Route 75, 28
miles north of Sun Valley. The trail climbed 480 feet to a
9,120-foot peak and led us past alpine meadows to the tiny
emerald-green Titus Lake.
</P>
<P>
   Of the mountain ranges in the area, my favorite by far was the
Sawtooth Mountains, surely one of the most aptly named. With their
sharp side-by-side peaks, they look just like a saw laid on its
side, almost cartoonlike in their one-dimensional perfection. Ask a
kindergartner to draw mountains and you will get the Sawtooth
(Sawteeth?).
</P>
<P>
   The real gateway to the wilderness area is Stanley, a frontier
town about 65 miles north of Sun Valley on Route 75. Raft trips on
the main branch of the Salmon River begin there, with several
outfitters competing for the business.
</P>
<P>
   A few miles outside Stanley is the Redfish Lake Lodge, a
pleasantly rustic hotel, open only in summer, that makes a nice
contrast to the more refined charms of Sun Valley. Redfish Lake
itself offers boating, swimming, hiking and horseback riding.
</P>
<P>
   On the way to Stanley, about 24 miles from Ketchum on Route 75,
is Galena Lodge, a community center and restaurant. It has no
overnight accommodations, but offers a variety of activities,
including a nature adventure day camp for children and a weekly
guided wildflower walk.
</P>
<P>
   The flowers were past their peak by mid-August, but the walk was
still delightful. The lodge's homemade breads and soups are also
worth the drive.
</P>
<P>
   Our half-day of white-water rafting turned into an interesting
natural history lesson as well as a bracing adventure. The
endangered chinook salmon had just started to spawn in the Salmon
River, which under federal regulations required a half-mile portage
around the spawning site.
</P>
<P>
   The effort was made more than worthwhile by the sight of a
female salmon sitting on her nest in the middle of the shallow
river, waiting to complete an amazing life cycle that had brought
her on a 1,600-mile round trip through the dams on the Columbia
River and out to the Pacific Ocean and back. Only 0.1 of 1 percent
of the salmon spawned in the Salmon River make it back, with most
dying on the outward journey.
</P>
<P>
   We felt privileged to have glimpsed one of the precious few. The
chance to go down the Salmon at all may become increasingly rare:
the Forest Service has recently proposed sharp restrictions on the
number of rafters who will be allowed on the river, beginning next
year.
</P>
<P>
   In the midst of all this nature, the Sun Valley resort itself is
completely man made. Averell Harriman, then the chairman of the
Union Pacific Railroad, built it in 1936 on empty ranch land
outside the old mining town of Ketchum. His twin goals were to
emulate the ski resorts he enjoyed in the Alps and to give people a
reason to ride a little-used rail route.
</P>
<P>
   For a hint of Sun Valley in the winter, take the chairlift up to
the restaurant at 9,010 feet on Bald Mountain, the resort's main
ski mountain. The views are spectacular and the winds brisk.
</P>
<P>
   The resort has two hotels, the Lodge and the slightly
lower-priced Sun Valley Inn, as well as several condominium
communities, where apartments can be rented either directly through
the resort or through local real estate companies. Our
well-furnished two-bedroom, two-bath apartment in the Snowcreek
development cost $1,100 a week and had the advantage of being an
easy walk to the rink.
</P>
<P>
   Although Sun Valley and Ketchum are separately incorporated
municipalities, they essentially function as one place; a free
shuttle bus connects the two. Ketchum offers interest and amenities
on a scale well beyond its year-round population of 3,280,
including an impressive community library with more than 65,000
books.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-15-98 1926EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
