<SLUG> BC-SOC-GERMANY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR GERMANS, NOT ENOUGH OF A WIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ELIZABETH NEUFFER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN _ The Germans won. The Americans were soundly defeated.
But there was little cheering in the streets of Berlin last night.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, soccer fans here were crushed that the much-lauded
German team barely squeaked by with a 2-0 victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I counted on a 3-0 victory,'' complained Beate Eichenberg, 39,
a public relations manager who watched the game at home Monday
night with her 9-year-old daughter, Juliane. ``The Germans should
have used their chances better.''
</P>
<P>
   In Cologne, soccer fan and writer Maternus Thoene, 39, agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Really, we had hoped for a better team,'' said Thoene, who
gathered with a group of 10 Germans to watch the match. ``The game
was really, really bad in our view.''
</P>
<P>
   What troubled the Germans was that they thought it should have
been an easier win. Soccer here is a traditional, much-beloved
sport, one at which the Germans excel; by contrast, soccer is
fairly new in the US.
</P>
<P>
   The millions of Germans who tuned in Monday night expected their
team to play something other than the slow, stumbling match that
they did. Now there are fears that the German team won't pass
muster when it faces much tougher opponents.
</P>
<P>
   ``The next game is against Yugoslavia, and they are a much
better team than the Americans,'' said Thoene.
</P>
<P>
   Even German national coach Berti Vogts had a dejected air.
Speaking on television, he lamented his team's poor showing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We weren't able to keep our ordnung,'' said Vogts. The word
translates as ``order,'' but in this case it refers to efficient
and methodical play, hallmarks of the German team.
</P>
<P>
   What cheering there was Monday night was for the American team.
Many members of the US team are well-known in Germany, having
played in local leagues. And the consensus was that the Americans
played much better than they did four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Four years ago, the Americans would have lost, 6-0,'' said
Nikolas Jaspert, a 38-year-old medieval history professor.
</P>
<P>
   Americans expatriates who tuned into the game were pleased that
the US team wasn't trounced. But some of them admitted to a certain
wistfulness: This was definitely not the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Germans played an elegant game of soccer,'' sighed Julia
Jensen, a 33-year-old attorney, ``but it just doesn't hold a candle
to an American football game.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
