<DOCNO> NYT19980615.0326 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-15 19:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0288 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      06-15 0890
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEYOND MOSES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Charlton Heston's initial performance as the Moses
of the National Rifle Association, chosen to lead that extremist
pro-gun organization out of the marginal wilderness of intemperate
special interest politics, has not been promising.
</P>
<P>
   Ronald Reagan proved that you could take aging movie stardom and
translate it into political power, but Heston is no Reagan. He is
not even Heston any more. It has been more than four decades since
the release of his 1956 classic, ``The Ten Commandments,'' although
he has continued to act in less successful films.
</P>
<P>
   The first line of the 73-year-old Heston's World Wide Web
biography describes him as ``an American man's man, an epic unto
himself.'' But as the recently elected NRA head, Heston nowadays
sounds as if he thinks manly is gun-crazy. He parrots the rigid NRA
cliches against gun regulations and dismisses opponents as radicals
who include gays, feminists and racial minorities.
</P>
<P>
   Heston proceeded to tell ``Meet the Press'' Sunday that he
wanted to ``return the NRA to the mainstream of American life.''
But if he has a clue as to how to do this, he didn't reveal it.
Unfortunately for him, political mainstreams generally include some
of the unmanly.
</P>
<P>
   He did not demonstrate that much has changed in the pro-gun
lobby except the name of its president. He has, in fact, long been
an advertising pitchman for the group. The difference now is that
he has a title.
</P>
<P>
   In recent decades, the NRA has seemed callous and cold-blooded
as it moved from its original goal of promoting sport shooting to
fighting off all restraints on all guns in all hands for all
purposes. Its uncompromising position has been so outrageous in the
face of mounting crime and violence that it has been losing
political clout despite massive campaign contributions to friendly
members of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   In his Sunday TV remarks that were sometimes incoherent, Heston
appeared to make a small gesture toward sanity by saying he'd go
for legislation that would require child safety locks on all new
handguns. Sarah Brady, chairman of Handgun Control Inc, a gun
control lobby, immediately professed to be delighted at his
``unexpected support.''
</P>
<P>
   But it was not clear if he had blundered or if his view
reflected that of his organization, which has previously opposed
the locks as interfering with the use of handguns for self-defense.
Heston simultaneously gave the locks the back of his hand by
dismissing them as ``really not of much use.''
</P>
<P>
   Much more significant was his stubborn defense of AK-47s,
automatic assault weapons capable of mowing down many victims at
once. Heston said he didn't like them but thought everyone had the
right to own them.
</P>
<P>
   He resorted to familiar NRA hooey that the Second Amendment
supporting ``a well-regulated militia'' is a right equivalent to
the First Amendment protection of freedom of speech, assembly and
religion.
</P>
<P>
   The notion that freedom of thought and expression in a democracy
is no more important than universal possession of a gun is an
insult to common sense in a contemporary society burdened with a
flood of uncontrolled weapons. The Supreme Court, in fact, ruled in
1939 that the Second Amendment has nothing to do with an
individual's right to ``keep and bear arms'' but merely means that
the states have the right to raise an armed militia.
</P>
<P>
   Heston also repeated NRA opposition to extending the Brady law,
named after Sarah's husband James, who was wounded in the 1981
assassination attempt on President Reagan. That law requires a
five-day waiting period between the purchase of a gun and actually
taking possession of it. It is due to expire Nov. 30, supposedly to
be supplanted by a centralized instant-check system that will allow
licensed gun dealers to quickly determine whether a customer has a
disqualifying criminal record.
</P>
<P>
   The actor objected to the projected $15 fee for the service,
which he called a tax on gun owners. But if the fee is not
assessed, that would in effect push the cost of the instant-check
program onto taxpayers and make the measure harder to pass
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Heston may represent an organization in increasingly bad odor
with a public that is fed up with unprovoked violence on the
streets and the playgrounds, but he still has friends in high
places. One of them is Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, who knows
how to parrot the NRA line with the best of them.
</P>
<P>
   Lott acted like a cheerleader before the NRA convention last
weekend, contending that the organization was already ``the
mainstream of America.'' He thinks reading the Second Amendment
literally to allow unfettered distribution of arms is so important
that any contrary reading is ``an assault on the entire fabric of
American freedom.'' (Someone give this man the Supreme Court
ruling.)
</P>
<P>
   Lott went further, calling for ``a well-armed public.'' He
suggests a pilot project to turn local police stations into
``citizen self-defense centers,'' where the cops would train
anybody who came in off the street in the purchase and use of
firearms.
</P>
<P>
   This is really innovative thinking. More guns in the hands of
more people will mean less triggers pulled! It boggles the mind.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-15-98 1933EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
