<DOCNO> NYT19980615.0327 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-15 19:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0298 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YOUNG-POETS-900(2TAKE     06-15 0939
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-POETS-900(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POETS LET COMPETITIVE JUICES FLOW
</HEADLINE>
   (ja) 
 By BRUCE WEBER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAOS, N.M. _ To start with the winner _ after all, it was a
contest _ the new heavyweight poetry champion of the world is
Sherman Alexie, the 31-year-old American Indian writer from
Spokane, Wash. Alexie wrested the crown from the two-time defending
champ and the home-state favorite, Jimmy Santiago Baca, on Saturday
night here, before a crowd of 700 whooping literati.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love you, Jimmy,'' a woman shrieked from the audience, a
tragedy-tinged lament, as the results of the 10-round bout were
announced. Another woman retorted in triumph: ``I love you,
Sherman.''
</P>
<P>
   Poetry has long called forth gushes of emotion; that's one of
its functions, after all. But rarely does it elicit the kind of
passion that was prevalent here, not only on Saturday, but also all
week long during the 17th annual Taos Poetry Circus, which had
poetry fans loudly in love with the likes of Ntozake Shange, Jim
Carroll, Baca and Alexie, and on occasion, screaming for blood.
</P>
<P>
   The circus brought 1,500 people to this small town an hour and a
half north of Santa Fe at the foot of the Sangre de Cristo
Mountains, an artsy haven for outdoor vacationers, Indian
spiritualists and refugees from the hippie culture of the 1960s.
The attraction was the menu of round-table readings, open-mike
slams and the first-ever tag-team poetry bout, as well as
conventional readings and a workshop for students from as far away
as the Aleutian Islands and the Virgin Islands.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea is to showcase the three-ring aspect of poetry
today,'' said Anne MacNaughton, the executive director of the
circus, adding that the staid, bookish tradition of poetry ought to
be able to coexist with the angry, incantatory, oral tradition.
``We'd like to get street poets out of the street and into the
library and library poets out of the library and into the street.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the focus of the circus _ the main event? _ was the
championship bout, in which the poets alternated reading poems of
up to five minutes in length, with a panel of judges voting, in the
manner of a boxing match, after each round, awarding 10 points to
the winner of the round, and from 1 to 9 to the loser. The judges
(this year, an elementary school teacher, a master carpenter and a
cocktail waitress) are not given any guidelines. Is the poem more
important than the performance? Who knows?
</P>
<P>
   ``You like it? Score it high,'' said Amalio Madueno, a poet who
serves on the advisory board for the circus. ``You don't like it?
Score it low.''
</P>
<P>
   It's an odd spectacle, particularly with a ring announcer
introducing the contenders (``From Spokane, weighing in at 185
pounds, the challenger, Sherman Alexie''), a ring girl in a clingy
red dress and a crowd full of partisan fans howling at the
participants as though they were Mike Tyson and Evander Holyfield.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is fun,'' Alexie said to the crowd at the start of the
sixth round, sounding surprised.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the whole thing feels a little subversive, bringing, as
it does, the elements of competition, brash egotism and immediate
gratification to a milieu that traditionally finds those things
anathema.
</P>
<P>
   The organizers of the Taos championship bout are at great pains
to distinguish their event from slam poetry, a phenomenon that took
root in Chicago in the mid-1980s and now has its own annual
national championship event; the eighth is to take place in Austin,
Texas, in August. Nonetheless, slams and bouts are obviously cut
from similar cloth.
</P>
<P>
   Both involve competitive readings with judges providing
numerical scores and crowds going berserk. Rules vary from slam to
slam. But the primary difference is that a slam usually involves
several entrants, teams or individuals, who may or may not be
accomplished poets, while a bout is two poets, usually of some
reputation, going head to head.
</P>
<P>
   A further confusion is that the championship bout was also born
in Chicago, at a bar on Lincoln Avenue called the Oxford Pub in
1981. There, a blues singer named Jim Desmond became angered when a
poet named Jerome Sala read a poem that parodied John Lennon, who
had just died. They got into a fight, eventually agreeing to settle
the dispute with a competitive reading. They asked the bartender,
Al Simmons, to arrange it, which he did, with the cooperation of a
friend, Terry Jacobus. Sala won the first bout, as well as a
rematch.
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, Jacobus, a shipping clerk, happened to be a
correspondent for Rolling Stock, a magazine published in Boulder,
Colo., by the Beat poet Ed Dorn, and it was in Rolling Stock that
Anne MacNaughton and her husband, Peter Rabbit, read about the
Chicago bouts. Both writers and counter-culture devotees, they had
recently arrived in Taos and were trying to drum up a poetry scene
that would complement the gallery scene.
</P>
<P>
   ``So I called Al,'' said Rabbit, who still helps run the circus,
``and I said, `If you've got someone who wants to fight, we'll put
him up against Gregory Corso.'''
</P>
<P>
   Simmons, who is known at the circus as the Commissioner,
designed the whole event: the rules, the ring girl, everything. He
sent Jacobus, who won, mainly because the cantankerous Corso
alienated the tiny crowd and stalked off after the fifth round.
</P>
<P>
   ``So I was the first world champion,'' said Jacobus, 49, now a
mail room supervisor in Chicago, who was on hand for the bout on
Saturday. ``And then two days later I was back unloading toilet
paper.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
