<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOB-HEARING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX-FBI AGENT DENIES TIPPING OFF MOB FIGURE BEFORE ARRESTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATRICIA NEALON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The day before Angelo ``Sonny'' Mercurio and several
reputed Mafia associates were to be arrested in November 1989, an
FBI supervisor was on the phone with Mercurio, who had already
become an informant.
</P>
<P>
   Mercurio ticked off for the FBI agent the places authorities
could find several of the Mob figures wanted for arrest.
</P>
<P>
   But they never discussed Mercurio's whereabouts.
</P>
<P>
   James A. Ring, the former head of the organized crime squad in
the FBI's Boston office, testified Monday that he wouldn't
``insult'' Mercurio by asking him his whereabouts -- even though
Mercurio was on the list of those to be arrested.
</P>
<P>
   So, when the FBI rounded up key Mafia figures the next day --
including reputed capos Joseph Russo, Vincent Ferrara and Robert
Carrozza -- &UR;  &LR; Mercurio was nowhere to be found. And he remained
among the missing for nearly five years, finally arrested in
Georgia in June 1994 with 150 pounds of marijuana.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want to know if I tipped him off, the answer is no,''
an angry Ring replied to a question by defense attorney Anthony M.
Cardinale, who represents reputed New England Mafia boss Francis P.
``Cadillac Frank'' Salemme.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted him in custody,'' Ring said. ``I believed if he was
in custody he might change his mind and testify.''
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks before Mercurio fled he had provided the FBI with one
of its most prized tips ever: the exact time and place of a Mafia
induction ceremony. Agents were able to hide microphones inside the
Medford home where the secret service took place and record it --
the first tape ever of a Mafia initiation.
</P>
<P>
   While Mercurio was willing to provide information to the FBI as
a confidential informant he had refused to testify against his
fellow mobsters in court.
</P>
<P>
   Asked by Cardinale why he had not asked Mercurio where he was
calling from on Nov. 13, 1989, the day before he and several
associates were to be arrested, Ring said, ``I'm not going to
insult the man. I'm going to catch him, but I'm not going to insult
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Ring, in his seventh day of testimony in federal court, said it
would have insulted Mercurio's intelligence to act ``so cute and
ask him where he is in a direct manner. And he's not going to
figure it out?''
</P>
<P>
   US District Judge Mark L. Wolf, who is holding hearings into the
legality of extortion and racketeering charges brought against the
leaders of the local Irish and Italian mobs in 1995, asked Ring if
he had ever asked Mercurio's handler, agent John Conn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-15-98 1936EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980615.0329 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-15 19:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0301 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YOUNG-POETS-2NDTAKE-N     06-15 0840
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-POETS-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 TAOS, N.M.: toilet paper.''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Simmons, also 49, and now living in the San Francisco Bay Area,
was also on hand. He had recently retired, he said, from being the
world's greatest salesman. ``Cocaine to Cadillacs, it didn't matter
what,'' he said, adding that the spectacle of the poetry bout might
have been his finest achievement. He flies in every year. ``It's
like flying to Vegas for the fights,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sort of, yes.
</P>
<P>
   It seems indisputable that the head-to-head contests and the
hoot-and-holler atmosphere bring in spectators who would not
otherwise have an interest in poetry, which the circus promoters
say is their primary purpose. And it does seem to elicit a certain
style of poetry: narrative, dramatic and more often than not
self-referential if not first person. It's relatively accessible
stuff. But whether any of that translates into any new poetry
readers is unclear.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone agrees that for many in the audience _ and even some of
the poets _ the competition is the primary appeal; the night before
the bout, an ordinary, noncompetitive reading by two accomplished
poets, Carroll and Victor Hernandez Cruz, drew a much smaller
crowd. And though many of the headlining poets at the circus
publish their work in mainstream journals and teach at
universities, they all acknowledged the general disdain with which
the starchy academic world holds crowd-pleasing oral events like
this. Indeed, it's hard even for the participants to agree on the
value of the competitions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just an entertainment,'' said Patricia Smith, a columnist
for The Boston Globe who, as a poet, lost the championship a year
ago to Baca, and who has won the national slam championship four
times. ``It's a great thing for audience building. But if you're
looking for a competition to legitimize you as a poet, you
shouldn't be here.''
</P>
<P>
   Cruz, a Puerto Rican who grew up in New York City, and Ms.
Shange, both former world champions, noted that storytelling
competitions are traditional in Latin and African cultures.
</P>
<P>
   ``African-American culture, too, if you look at the dozens,''
said Ms. Shange, who with Baca won the tag-team competition last
week. ``So it's only fitting there should be a title for it. For me
to be the champion made sense to me as a black person. So many
things we do go unnamed.''
</P>
<P>
   She loved winning when she won; so did Cruz, whose recollection
of losing, in 1990, to Anne Waldman, came with a wry grin. ''There
was a full moon,'' he said. ``Don't ever fight a woman on the night
of a full moon.''
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's bout pitted Baca, 46, who taught himself to write in
prison after a drug conviction and whose engaging grin and fiery
reading style have made him something of a local cult hero, against
Alexie, the precocious author of 10 books of fiction and poetry
about the plight of contemporary American Indians and whose film,
``Smoke Signals,'' opens on June 26.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like competing; it gives you a headache,'' Baca, the
author of three volumes of poetry and a book of essays, said the
day before the bout. ``You lose the sense that poetry transports
you to another place.'' He had just finished recounting, with
relish, the story of his victory two years ago over Quincy Troupe,
a man to whom he had taken a dislike.
</P>
<P>
   The bout itself was a tight contest, revealing different reading
styles and different rhetorical methods.
</P>
<P>
   Alexie's poems about life on the modern reservation and the
public perceptions of Indians, were delivered with a tiny lisp, the
poems often ending on notes of piquant, suggestive unresolve, the
poet's voice leaving the sound of the last line lingering, like a
suspended musical chord.
</P>
<P>
   Baca countered with poems about the inner strength of the common
man, particularly Mexican-Americans, whom he characterized as
ordinary people surviving through force of integrity and spirit. He
almost chanted his poems, like an evangelical preacher, ending each
on a high emotional pitch, with an emphatic rap on the lectern or a
shout.
</P>
<P>
   One judge called the bout even; the two others tilted to Alexie
by the same slim margin, 96-94, probably on the strength of the
final round, in which each poet was asked for an extemporaneous
rumination on a subject drawn from a hat. Alexie drew ``chaos.''
</P>
<P>
   After 30 seconds of cogitating time, he presented an
autobiographical poem of several stanzas that traced his growing
up, ended with the birth of his son and began with language
arresting for its metaphor:
</P>
<P>
   I was born with a river in my brain
</P>
<P>
   And when the doctors cut open my forehead
</P>
<P>
   They found 1,000 salmon skeletons.
</P>
<P>
   Baca drew ``snap beans,'' and though his rambling composition
was inventive, it couldn't match Alexie's for language or
structure.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Alexie raised his hands over his head in the manner
of a champion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd have been heartbroken if I lost, judging by how emotional
I feel now,'' he said. ``Don't let anybody tell you poets aren't
competitive.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
