u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FREE-TIBET-525&AMP;ADD-NY     06-15 0829
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FREE-TIBET-525&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MUSICIANS PUT TIBET ON THEIR AGENDAS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ja) 
 By JON PARELES    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Tibetan Freedom Concerts came to the capital
determined to get the attention of politicians before President
Clinton's visit to China later this month. The Milarepa Foundation,
which expects to realize about $1 million from the concerts at
Robert F. Kennedy Stadium here, followed the concerts with a rally
the next day at the Capitol urging Clinton to press China to
negotiate with the Dalai Lama, Tibet's exiled leader.
</P>
<P>
   Organized by Adam Yauch of the Beastie Boys, the two shows sold
out at a total of 128,000 tickets with a bill of rock, hip-hop,
funk and their hybrids. It pulled in performers who were touring
the Eastern Seaboard (like the Beastie Boys, the Dave Matthews
Band, Sonic Youth, KRS-1, A Tribe Called Quest, Pulp, Sean Lennon
and Herbie Hancock) and others who bent their itineraries to
appear.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, lightning injured at least 11 people in the
audience, and weather forced curtailment of the Saturday show
halfway through.
</P>
<P>
   The lightning was the most startling occurrence at an event
that, in three years and three cities, has grown into its own
routine. Many of the performers appeared at previous Tibetan
Freedom Concerts; most emerged in the 1980s and early '90s. The
concerts are a '90s mixture of high-mindedness and rowdy energy,
praising nonviolence between bouts of moshing.
</P>
<P>
   The Tibetan Freedom Concerts remain the only rock event with its
own monastery, a tent where Buddhist monks and nuns chanted prayers
and danced. On the stadium stage, Tibetans spoke about their
country, where owning a Tibetan flag can mean a prison sentence.
Between rock bands were appearances by Tibetan groups like
Chaksam-Pa, performing a 500-year-old consecration dance.
</P>
<P>
   In May, a spokesman for the Chinese Embassy in London had
responded to the plans for this year's concert by saying, ``Western
artists have no right to intervene in the internal affairs of our
country. Any of those performers who do will not be permitted entry
to China, including Tibet, and their works will never be welcome in
our country.''
</P>
<P>
   The music had to battle the echoes of this stadium, which ought
to be declared an acoustical disaster area. None of the Western
performers had songs specifically about Tibet. Bands that hark back
to 1960s rock trotted out idealistic older songs: `` `Heroes'' and
the more cynical ``Won't Get Fooled Again'' from the Wallflowers,
``Imagine'' from Blues Traveler. Others had songs about yearnings
for justice, like the Dave Matthews Band's ``Don't Drink the
Water.'' Live sang about reincarnation with ``Lightning Crashes,''
which it performed on Saturday before the storm.
</P>
<P>
   The hip-hop groups turned ``Free Tibet'' into one more
call-and-response shout, although KRS-1 also cautioned against
``China-bashing.'' But the rappers' main agenda was praising
old-school hip-hop. KRS-1 performed with break-dancers; Wyclef
Jean's disk jockey spun a medley of old hip-hop and funk sources.
The Red Hot Chili Peppers, playing a quick closing segment with
Pearl Jam's equipment left the audience chanting, ``Free Tibet if
you want to be peaceful.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The bill mirrored the eclecticism of the Beastie Boys, whose set
touched on hip-hop, hardcore and instrumental funk. Most of the
bands did what they normally do: they brooded and bashed, trotted
out hits and worked the crowd. The brooders included Pulp, singing
about self-doubt; Radiohead, singing about alienation and
technology, and R.E.M., singing four new, elegiac songs about
bygone dreams. R.E.M. had its new drummer, Joey Waronker, along
with Barrett Martin on vibraphone. In what may have been an oblique
nod to the Tibetans, R.E.M. played ``Losing My Religion.'' Michael
Stipe of R.E.M. and Thom Yorke of Radiohead each sang with the
other's band.
</P>
<P>
   For powerful noise, no one topped Sonic Youth, whose retuned
guitars filled the stadium with resonating overtones, akin to the
rich chanting of the Tibetan monks. Herbie Hancock's funk band the
Headhunters, reunited after 20 years, had changed so little since
the 1970s that it was poised to enjoy retro affection; Guru of Gang
Starr joined them to rap about jazz. The younger bands earned their
place on the bill. Buffalo Daughter, from Japan, used old
synthesizers and a steady, pulsating bass riff in a dance-music
crescendo that was both geeky and galvanizing, and Sean Lennon
fortified Beatles-style ballads with guitar muscle.
</P>
<P>
   And Pearl Jam's abbreviated set was a gem: punky and raucous in
uptempo songs and dynamic in slower ones, with wrangling,
exploratory guitars. Eddie Vedder, the band's leader, mocked people
who said that the audience didn't care about Tibet and was only
there to hear the music. ``That sounds fine to me,'' he growled.
``We have all your money.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
