<HEADER>
A0317 &Cx1f; tic-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  'SPLAININGTHELAWOFTHELAN     06-15 0705
</HEADER>
<BODY>
 'SPLAINING THE LAW OF THE LAND  
 (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL GOODYKOONTZ  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED _ Mayhaps you found it difficult to conceal your mirth
upon learning of Vice President Al Gore's announcement nearly a
fortnight ago that the federal government would henceforth utilize
so-called ``plain language'' in its communications with the
citizenry of these Unites States of America.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, dude, you rock.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who has ever tried to mow through a tax form _ even the
1040EZ _ has found himself longing for a good, simple read, like
James Joyce's ``Ulysses'' or the instructions for a cheap Japanese
electronics product.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it is exceedingly difficult to write about how poorly
anyone else writes, since you open yourself up to similar
criticisms.
</P>
<P>
   Not that this has ever stopped me before. I see no reason to let
it now.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the government can't just heal itself. That's where
the Plain English Network comes in. The group has compiled a
handbook to help spice up government writing, including such hints
as ``write clearly,'' ``use active voice,'' ``use short
sentences,'' ``limit each paragraph to one topic'' and the like.
You know, the things most people learn in about the fourth grade.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be great if we stopped there for plain English,''
John Strylowski said. ``The problem is we go on to college.'' And
even worse: law school. &QL; 
CAPE COD CRUSADER
</P>
<P>
   Strylowski is a regulatory analyst for the Department of
Interior and a member of the Plain English Network; he was the
final editor for the handbook. He speaks pretty well himself _ the
kind of guy who will say, in all seriousness, things like, ``There
are some wonderful insurance policies out there that are just a joy
to read,'' but he has the good sense to laugh after he says it.
</P>
<P>
   He's also honest enough to acknowledge that if we're talking
about improving the way government documents are written, there
must be something lacking in the way they are written now.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, gosh,'' Strylowski said, ``I can't think of anyone who
would contend that that is not true, as things stand now. The first
step in curing your problem is admitting that you have one.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't worry, there aren't 11 more steps after that one. It's not
that easy. We're talking about years of government documents being
written in what amounts to a foreign language, after all.
</P>
<P>
   Strylowski passed along this example of how a plain English
rewrite improved one sentence in the National Park Service's Cape
Cod rules:
</P>
<P>
   _Old version (36 words) _ ``When the process of freeing a
vehicle that has been stuck results in ruts or holes, the operator
will fill the ruts or holes created by such activity before
removing the vehicle from the immediate area.''
</P>
<P>
   _New version (28 words) _ ``If you make a rut or hole while
freeing a stuck vehicle, you must fill the rut or hole before you
move the vehicle from the immediate area.'' &QL; 
FURTHER RUT SMOOTHING
</P>
<P>
   Personally, I think you could take this further. Something along
the lines of: (eight words) ``If your truck makes a hole, fill
it.'' The only word I would consider adding is KNUCKLEHEAD.
</P>
<P>
   But I don't work for the federal government. A fact for which
I'm thankful.
</P>
<P>
   The government has tried this kind of thing before. You may
recall that Jimmy Carter tried to make tax forms understandable.
Alas, like so much of what ol' Jimmy tried, people forgot about it.
</P>
<P>
   Although everyone remembers him fighting off that rabbit with a
paddle.
</P>
<P>
   Strylowski holds out higher hopes for this go-round.
</P>
<P>
   ``The beauty of this approach that we are using is that there
are specific criteria we can use,'' he said in a sentence just
dying for clarification. ``We have the presidential memo, and that
helps. It's a cudgel we can use to hit people over the head.
</P>
<P>
   ``Also, there's a buzz about this. There are people interested
in this and committed to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Funny what excites D.C. types. Better this than a fling with an
intern, I suppose.
</P>
<P>
   Hmm. Probably best to avoid plain English when it comes to that
story. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bill Goodykoontz can be reached at 444-8828, or at
bill.goodykoontz(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
