A0322 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GM-STRIKE-NYT     06-15 0639
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GM-STRIKE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRIKERS EDGE GM TOWARD SHUTDOWN
</HEADLINE>
  (ja) 
 By NICHOLE M. CHRISTIAN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ General Motors' North American operations moved closer
to being shut down completely Monday, as strikes at two Michigan
parts factories forced the company to idle 13,000 more workers and
partly close a host of other parts and assembly plants.
</P>
<P>
   The combined work stoppages, one at a sheet-metal stamping plant
that began 11 days ago and the other at a spark plug and
speedometer plant that began on Thursday, have now sent 63,100
workers home and closed more than 40 assembly and parts factories
in the United States, Mexico and Canada. Nearly all GM cars and
trucks require parts built at one of the two plants in Flint,
Mich., where 9,000 workers are walking picket lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the strikes are not settled by Wednesday,'' said James
Hall, an industry analyst with Auto Pacific Inc., ``all of GM will
likely be shut down.'' Assembly plants represent the key part of
the company's production, and 16 of its 29 assembly plants are now
closed.
</P>
<P>
   Talks at the metal stamping plant broke off Monday afternoon
after a union official accused GM negotiators of making light of
striking workers' making only $150 a week while they could be
receiving their full salaries, union negotiators said. GM denied
that such comments were made. No timetable has been set for talks
to resume. Talks at the spark plug and speedometer plant,
meanwhile, were continuing.
</P>
<P>
   The United Automobile Workers union views both strikes as a
battle to stem the tide of union jobs being moved out of North
America. General Motors maintains that the disputes concern its
efforts to catch up with its competitors by streamlining production
and gaining greater control of work practices inside the two Flint
factories.
</P>
<P>
   A few signs of progress have emerged. General Motors agreed to
return stamping dies that it acknowledged removing while the metal
stamping plant was closed during the Memorial Day weekend. Since
that concession, the top negotiators for each side have stopped
exchanging sharply worded news releases and are now negotiating in
secrecy, refusing to say anything about the tone of the talks or
the level of progress.
</P>
<P>
   But those are small rays of optimism, compared with the strikes'
financial toll on the automaker. Some analysts estimate the strikes
cost to General Motors at $40 million a day. Worst of all, the
company has lost production of more than 30,000 cars and trucks,
which translates to about $600 million in revenue.
</P>
<P>
   General Motors draws most of its profits from light trucks and
sport utility vehicles, production of which is now largely
paralyzed by strikes. Even if the strike ended on Tuesday, some
analysts argue, the loss volume would be difficult to recoup
because General Motors is scheduled to head into its two-week
summer shutdown. If there is a settlement soon, however, the
company has the option of doing away with the shutdown, a GM
spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   There was a time when GM's cars were not selling as briskly as
now and a strike would allow the company to slow production of
low-selling vehicles. ``But now that their operations are
profitable,'' Hall, the Auto Pacific analyst, said, ``they can't
afford not to be building cars and trucks.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Ward, an auto analyst with Paine Webber, said, ``Every
day that the strikes go on, GM is sacrificing its market share
while Ford and Chrysler continue to gain.''
</P>
<P>
   Since 1985, Ward said, GM's market share has slipped nine
points, to about 31 percent. He contends that every 1.5 points of
market share is equivalent to 150,00 vehicles. ``GM says it needs
to cut costs,'' he said, ``but it's much easier to do that in an
environment where you're gaining share rather than risking it. ''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
