<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves Notebook: Smoltz anxious to 'make quality pitches'
 &HT;    By Tom Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Though John Smoltz got in the work he was seeking
while on injury-rehab _ his six-inning, 82-pitch outing with Class
A Macon Monday was his longest performance since he threw 88
pitches against Houston May 17 _ he hardly sounded satisfied with
his results.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have to gain some confidence in the short time so that I can
go up (to Atlanta) and make some quality pitches,'' Smoltz told The
Macon (Ga.) Telegraph after coming off the mound Sunday. ''In two
or three days, I can answer that question. Right now, that's what
I'm struggling with every inning I come off the mound, not feeling
like I was ready.''
</P>
<P>
   Smoltz threw 61 strikes Sunday but bunched 17 of his 23-ball
count in two innings. He indicated before he resumed pitching that
his results were not as important to him as less tender elbow.
</P>
<P>
   ''The feeling of a good healthy elbow is not going to be there
but it's good enough to make pitches I need to make,'' he said.
''I'm going to stuggle with it from time to time. There are going
to be days like (Sunday), when it's 100 degrees and you think you
can get loose when you need to. And it didn't happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Smoltz, on the DL since May 24, has been slotted to make his
return start Friday night in Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   Etc....
</P>
<P>
   Manager Bobby Cox, with a win tonight, will become the all-time
winningest manager in Braves franchise history. Cox is currently
tied with Frank Selee, who won 1,004 games for the Boston Braves
(1890-1901). . . . Forget the rumors that Florida manager Jim
Leyland will resign as the Marlins sink further in the NL East. The
club owes him $1.25 million for the second half of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
