<HEADER>
A0326 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GM-DORAVILLE-COX     06-15 0511
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GM-DORAVILLE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia assembly plant gets reprieve _ for now
 &HT;    By Kristi E. Swartz
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Workers at General Motor Corp.'s Doraville (Ga.)
assembly plant got a reprieve as they were told to report to work
today, but how much longer they'll be on the job isn't known.
</P>
<P>
   Lack of progress in negotiations in Michigan leaves them
frustrated, and workers are angry they would get less than $250 a
week in unemployment benefits when the seemingly inevitable
shutdown does come.
</P>
<P>
   The strike by the United Auto Workers at two GM plants in Flint
has led to a shortage of parts in plants around the country. The
strikes by 9,200 workers at plants in Flint, Mich., have idled more
than 63,000 other GM workers at 16 assembly plants and 66
additional parts plants throughout North America.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, GM added two car plants in Lansing, Mich., and the
Cadillac plant in Detroit to the list of those affected by the
walkouts, and said it laid off several thousand more workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody knows anything,'' said Doraville plant worker Pat Mack.
``We take it day by day.''
</P>
<P>
   UAW members can receive up to $224 a week in unemployment
benefits, but GM will not provide layoff supplemental pay, at 70
percent of their income, according to GM Spokesman Gerry Holmes. If
workers are denied unemployment benefits, they can receive strike
pay, at $150 a week.
</P>
<P>
   Although the workers at the nonstriking plants are being shut
out of their jobs because of a lack of parts _ not because they are
on strike _ the UAW-GM contract prevents them from receiving
supplemental pay, Holmes said. It says that if a parent operation
is on strike, it applies to all operations, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going out because of a lack of work; nobody's prepared
for this,'' said plant worker Brad Davis.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Labor Department Spokesman Sam Hall said UAW members who
have been with GM _ or with any employer covered by unemployment
insurance _ for four of the last five quarters should receive the
maximum unemployment benefit. ``But each claim is handled on its
own merit,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   UAW employees could begin receiving payments in one or two
weeks, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Non-union workers are not affected by the strike and will
continue to report to work, Holmes said.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, most union workers still say they support those on
strike and are ready in case they are told not to come in to work.
</P>
<P>
   ``You always have to be prepared when you work at an auto
plant,'' said Barry Maxwell, an inspector who has been working for
GM for 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   With a national convention coming up, the union may feel more
pressure to settle the dispute this week.
</P>
<P>
   The convention, which begins next Monday in Las Vegas, will be
followed on June 29 with the start of GM's annual two-week plant
shutdown. U.S. workers idled by the walkouts will not get their
union-won holiday pay for the first week of the shutdown unless
they're back at work by June 26.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
