<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-15 19:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0327 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GM-JOBS-COX     06-15 0983
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GM-JOBS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Labor says GM strikes 'a protest against global sourcing'
 &HT;    By Mike Wagner
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Strikes by workers at two General Motors Corp.
plants in Flint, Mich., have ravaged the giant automaker's North
American operations, now idling about 4,500 auto workers in the
Miami (Ohio) Valley and 60,000 nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   But what looks like a labor dispute over local working
conditions is turning into a high-stakes battle over global
competition and keeping blue-collar jobs in GM's U.S. factories.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts believe the strikes by 9,200 workers in Flint are only
the beginning in the fight for survival between GM and the United
Auto Workers. Several local unions at GM's troubled plants here may
follow the Flint workers and form their own picket lines, including
3,400 workers at two GM brake plants in Dayton.
</P>
<P>
   The issues splitting the UAW and GM in Flint and Dayton differ
slightly, but the heart of both disputes remains the same. GM wants
to cut costs to compete with the world's other major automakers and
stop its market share from slipping below 30 percent. The UAW wants
to protect jobs and stop its GM membership from dropping below
200,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Flint strikes are a protest against global sourcing.
Whether it's Flint or Dayton, these local disputes represent a
larger issue of where work is to be performed inside the company or
outside the company,'' said Sean McAlinden, a labor expert with the
University of Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't get strikes like this unless both sides have a good
point to make. GM has to get itself competitive. The union thinks
there are different ways of getting competitive and you're choosing
the way that hurts us the most.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say the Flint strikes are costing the company at least
$40 million a day.
</P>
<P>
   GM officials on Monday met separately with representatives of
two United Auto Workers union locals at the Flint Metal Center and
the Delphi Flint East plant, but no progress was reported from
either side.
</P>
<P>
   Parts shortages from the strike have closed or partially closed
13 of GM's 28 wholly owned major assembly plants, and 59 parts
plants in the United States, Mexico and Canada. So far, about 4,500
Dayton-area GM workers have been laid off at five plants. The
layoffs include about 3,900 workers at the Moraine, Ohio truck
assembly plant; 375 at the Dayton brake plants; 158 workers at GM's
air bag plant; 44 hourly employees at a suspension parts plant; and
24 workers at GM's Delphi Chassis plant in Dayton.
</P>
<P>
   More plant closures and layoffs are expected today.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts expect most of GM's assembly plants to be down by
week's end, but parts still in the delivery pipeline could keep a
few open longer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big money-makers _ pickup and sport utility vehicle plants
_ are down now,'' said Stephen Girsky of Morgan Stanley Dean
Witter. ``GM can't hold out much longer beyond this week.''
</P>
<P>
   The UAW has portrayed the strikes as a fight to keep U.S. jobs
from being exported to Mexico, Thailand and South America. Its
leaders accuse GM of breaking its ``social contract'' with
Americans to provide secure jobs that pay well.
</P>
<P>
   GM said it needs to make plants more efficient to compete with
nonunion plants operated by Japanese and European companies and
foreign suppliers. GM and the union also disagree over quota and
improvement issues.
</P>
<P>
   While the strikes continue in Flint, UAW leaders in Dayton are
continuing their own fight with GM over jobs at the Ohio city's
brake plants.
</P>
<P>
   The brake plants have lost $40 million in the past two years and
have been targeted for sale or shutdown unless they become
profitable. GM and UAW Local 696, which represents workers at the
brake plants, have failed to reach an agreement after dozens of
meetings in the past two years.
</P>
<P>
   GM wants to slash more than 1,800 jobs at the brake plants and
consolidate its anti-lock brake production into one factory,
according to an internal company document.
</P>
<P>
   ``Time has run out, (GM) needs a response from local union
leadership on suggested path,'' the document said.
</P>
<P>
   GM officials delivered the document to union leaders last week
in a meeting that lasted only 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want to take out more than half our jobs and GM accuses
us of being unreasonable? We told them we couldn't accept anything
like that,'' said Gary Hill, president of UAW Local 696.
</P>
<P>
   Hill said GM is reneging on last year's contract agreement to
maintain at least 2,881 jobs from the brake plants by 2001.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty much just wait and see from here, but we are not
going to accept concessions like that,'' Hill said.
</P>
<P>
   GM has been cutting costs at Delphi plants for the past several
years in anticipation of an initial public offering late this year
or early next. GM's North American plants represent about
two-thirds of Delphi's business, though the company is aiming to
reduce that to 50 percent within five years. Delphi, the world's
largest maker of auto parts, must do that to have appeal as a
stand-alone company, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   Selling off the parts businesses is also one way GM is reducing
its payroll. It has cut its U.S. hourly workforce by about 17
percent, or 44,000 employees, in the last four years. It still has
223,000 hourly workers in the U.S.
</P>
<P>
   McAlinden believes the UAW will try to punish GM with other
strikes, possibly in Dayton, if they don't get the settlement it
wants in Flint.
</P>
<P>
   ``The International UAW has other plants lined up and ready to
go. This isn't about Flint being an old, dirty union town, it's an
international UAW strike,'' McAlinden said. ``The strike in Dayton
two years ago cost GM about $1 billion but maybe the union is
thinking that wasn't enough. Maybe it will take $6 or $7 billion
for GM to change its ways.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
