<HEADLINE>
U.S. STOCKS PLUNGE AS ASIAN TURMOIL WORSENS
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(ja) 
 By SHARON R. KING   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The turmoil in Asia sent U.S. stocks plunging Monday,
wiping out the gains of the last three months for the Dow Jones
industrial average.
</P>
<P>
   The widely followed index of blue-chip stocks fell 207 points
Monday to 8628, down 2.3 percent for the day and off 6.3 percent
from its all-time high. Some other market gauges have fallen even
more, suggesting a stock market correction is in the works.
</P>
<P>
   Investors are increasingly concerned that Asia has yet to reach
the bottom of its economic cycle. Signs of distress there are not
only persistent, but deepening.
</P>
<P>
   Japan, which many hoped would be the region's savior, announced
last week that its economy shrank sharply in the quarter ended in
March, amounting to its steepest decline since World War II. The
yen also fell to an eight-year low against the dollar. On Monday,
Japanese and other stock markets across the region fell sharply,
setting the stage for a decline when trading began on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you're really seeing is a truly global market,'' said
Anthony Conroy, a managing director at Bankers Trust. ``If you
catch a cold in Asia, it really becomes a flu almost everywhere
else.''
</P>
<P>
   For American companies that do business in Japan and throughout
Asia, the prospects are growing dimmer for a recovery anytime soon.
Monday, Minnesota Mining and Manufacturing became the latest of a
string of companies to warn investors that earnings would be
disappointing this quarter because of Asian problems.
</P>
<P>
   A midday spurt of buying by bargain hunters buoyed stock prices,
but sellers swamped the buyers at the end of the day. The 207-point
fall was the fifth-biggest ever for the Dow, but in percentage
terms, the 2.3 percent decline was not among the 20 worst days for
the average. The Dow average is still up 9.10 percent for 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's loss was the largest point decline for the Dow Jones
industrial average since it fell 222.20 points, or 2.85 percent on
Jan. 9. Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was down 21.83 points, a 1.99
percent drop and the Nasdaq composite index was down 29.30 points,
a 1.69 percent decline.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
