<SLUG> BC-BOSNIA-NATO-ART-560(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO WARPLANES GIVE WARNING TO MILOSEVIC 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Russia, Great Britain, Germany)  (ART ADV: A locator map is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204.) 
(mk) 
 By MIKE O'CONNOR   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SKOPJE, Macedonia _ More than 80 NATO warplanes lifted off from
European bases Monday morning, coursing across the skies over the
Adriatic Sea and Albania and Macedonia in an exercise to reinforce
NATO's demand that Serbia stop using military force against
civilians in Kosovo province.
</P>
<P>
   With conflict in the separatist province intensifying and,
diplomats fear, likely to spread to other Balkan countries, the
west has threatened the Yugoslav president, Slobodan Milosevic,
with measures that could eventually include air strikes unless he
stops the attacks and enters serious negotiations with leaders in
Kosovo, which has an ethnic Albanian majority.
</P>
<P>
   The primary target of Monday's exercise was Milosevic. It was
timed, said NATO officials, to take place on the day before he is
to meet the Russian president, Boris Yeltsin. Milosevic arrived in
Russia Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton called Yeltsin Monday, and in a conversation
that lasted 40 minutes was assured by the Russian president that he
would express ``very strong sentiments'' in favor of a diplomatic
solution rather than a military response to the problems in Kosovo,
where more than 250 people have been killed and tens of thousands
displaced in the violence.
</P>
<P>
   The NATO F-16s, harriers, radar-jamming planes and tankers
assembled over the Adriatic Sea at about 8 a.m. Then, leaving the
support aircraft behind, 68 fighters flew into Albania to begin
several hours of military exercises. They went up the coast,
skirted the border with Serbia by 15 miles, flew into Macedonian
airspace, then south near Skopje. When they completed their loop
they were back over Tirana, the capital of Albania.
</P>
<P>
   ``It showed that NATO has the ability to project forces rapidly
into the area,'' said Lt. Gen. Mike Short, who is an American Air
Force officer and commander of Allied Air Forces, Southern Europe.
</P>
<P>
   NATO defense ministers decided last Thursday to conduct Monday's
aerial show of force. At the same time they commissioned military
contingency plans for measures against Serbia in the event that
diplomacy failed. Those options include air strikes and the
presence of ground troops.
</P>
<P>
   The Serbian government had no direct comment on Monday's
exercises, but it released a statement saying the Yugoslav army had
assured Milosevic that it would take a strong stand in the defense
of the country.
</P>
<P>
   A new surge of refugees from Kosovo entered Albania Monday after
being flushed out of their hiding places in the mountains by
Serbian forces on Sunday night and making the trek to the border.
While about 400 refugees reached Albania, the refugees said
hundreds of others remained in the mountains after the Serbs sealed
off the mountain paths out of the country.
</P>
<P>
   Another surge of thousands of refugees could come pouring into
Albania if fighting reaches larger towns in Kosovo, a western
diplomat in Macedonia said Monday. ``That is a trip wire for
possible NATO intervention,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Albanian officials asked that the planes converge over Tirana
and be obvious to the citizens there, so some planes went as low as
2,000 feet, shocking some civilians but pleasing government
officials. They were eager to demonstrate that the western allies
supported Albanian government policies and wanted to assure ethnic
Albanians in the region that they could put their faith in NATO.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   But Macedonian authorities made no similar request and the
planes here were kept above 14,000 feet, too high to be seen or
heard, although they caused plenty of consternation.
</P>
<P>
   American officials in Washington said they were counting on the
Russian president to make it clear to Milosevic that he had to stop
the killing and start talks with the ethnic Albanian majority in
Kosovo _ or suffer the consequences. But they conceded that there
is no clear consensus within NATO of what those consequences should
be _ and disagreement about whether a U.N. Security Council
resolution is essential to authorize military actions.
</P>
<P>
   If there is no Security Council resolution or if Russia vetoes
it, Washington believes that military action can be justified on
other grounds, through the NATO charter, the U.N. charter or even
as humanitarian intervention. American officials say that
international lawyers are currently looking into the problem.
</P>
<P>
   If Milosevic ignores or rebuffs Yeltsin, making a diplomatic
solution less likely, the Americans hope Moscow will be more
willing to vote for the Security Council resolution authorizing
force that the British are already circulating at the United
Nations.
</P>
<P>
   But Mike McCurry, the president's press secretary, said Monday,
``I think it's very clear, and certainly the Russian government
knows, that we intend to proceed with that type of resolution if
necessary.'' Other American officials repeated Defense Secretary
William Cohen's warning, made last weekend, that the United States
and NATO would use force, if necessary, to deter Milosevic even if
Russia and the United Nations objected.
</P>
<P>
   But the British feel a Security Council resolution is required,
as do some senior German officials and the European Union as a
whole.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic, more than most Balkan leaders, has reason to fear
NATO air strikes. It was a bombing campaign in 1995 that brought
his proxies, the Bosnian Serbs, to negotiations that ended the war
in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   Still, political and governmental leaders, at least here,
expressed profound doubts Monday that Milosevic could be easily
bombed into negotiating with the Albanians in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   While the man in charge of Monday's flights, Gen. Short, spoke
at a NATO base in Aviano, Italy, calling them a ``superb
demonstration of NATO air power,'' Macedonia's foreign minister was
in his office looking worried.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign Minister Blagoj Handziski said western confusion and
bickering allowed the war in Bosnia to go on for three years, and
the trouble in Kosovo has gone from disagreement to uprising
because of the same problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``The divisions within the international community worry us,''
he said. ``France, England, Germany, the United States, they all
have different opinions about what to do in Kosovo. This is a
situation that is very advantageous to Milosevic. His tactic is to
use all of these differences.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   A European diplomat in the Balkans said, ``We are gambling that
by being belligerent we can control the fighting in Serbia. If we
are wrong, we will try something else. But we are asking the
Macedonians to gamble with us, and if we are wrong the Macedonians
may find themselves suddenly confronting the Serbian army.''
</P>
<P>
   But the dilemma for Macedonia is even deeper than that. While it
shares a border with Serbia of more than 150 miles, the roughly 75
per cent of Macedonia that is Slavic also shares religion, culture
and a very similar language with Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   And, the Slavs in Macedonia worry that the effort for
independence mounted by ethnic Albanians in Serbia will serve as an
example to ethnic Albanians here, who amount to some 25 per cent of
the population.
</P>
<P>
   ``NATO is asking the Macedonian government to put aside its
natural relationship with Serbia and trust that NATO can calm the
whole region enough so that there will be peace through
negotiations,'' said a senior western diplomat in Macedonia. ``The
government is under pressure from us to help us now, look to the
west now, and one day join NATO. That's want they want to do. But
are they worried? Of course they are.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
