<SLUG> BC-GM-UAWUAW-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GM protesters keep informed via Internet
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Internet users can keep up-to-date on details of the
United Auto Workers strike at two General Motors plants in
Michigan, but there are few specifics on its nationwide effects.
</P>
<P>
   Striking workers from the United Auto Workers Local 659 in the
Flint Metal Center and Delphi E West units and others interested in
how the strike is affecting workers on a day-to-day basis can visit
the union local's Web site at http://www.tir.com
</P>
<P>
   /(tilde)local659.
</P>
<P>
   The local's site is bare-bones, providing striking workers with
important, and in some cases vital, information. Recent posts have
given workers information on applying for unemployment benefits.
</P>
<P>
   The local also uses its Web site to provide a morale boost to
the strikers. Rallies and potluck suppers designed to keep spirits
up during the strike are also listed. Also posted are pro-union
letters addressed to the Flint Journal (http://www.fl.milive.com).
The newspaper is providing continuous coverage of the local and
national effects.
</P>
<P>
   The United Auto Workers' national Web site (http://www.uaw.org)
is bigger and busier with official statements from UAW leadership
but not much else.
</P>
<P>
   However, users looking for the management perspective won't find
an official response on the General Motors Web site
(http://www.gm.com). At GM's site, it's just another day at the
dealership with the focus on product information. There is not one
word about the strike or its implications.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
