<HEADER>
A0356 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHEEHY-COX     06-15 0975
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHEEHY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sheehy explores aging challenges that Viagra can't solve
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Author Gail Sheehy has some news for middle-aged men
who think Viagra is going to solve all their problems:
</P>
<P>
   It won't.
</P>
<P>
   ``Men face a larger challenge to their virility and vitality
than can be cured by any magic bullet,'' says Sheehy. ``There's
downsizing and divorce. Kids leaving home. A friend dropping dead
of a heart attack. Any of those can make a man feel out of control
and that he's suddenly disappearing over the hill.''
</P>
<P>
   To provide a road map for males heading into what she calls a
``second adulthood,'' the 60-year-old author of ``Passages''
interviewed hundreds of middle-aged men _ including a group in
Atlanta _ for her new book, ``Understanding Men's Passages''
(Random House, $24).
</P>
<P>
   Sheehy says most men breeze through adolescence, which now
extends into the 20s, and the ``first adulthood'' of the 30s. In
their 40s, however, men begin facing physical and psychological
changes.
</P>
<P>
   ``They start losing their hair, gaining weight and encountering
health problems. They may be dissatisfied with their jobs. It is a
time when many men want to stop the clock or at least turn back
time.''
</P>
<P>
   This is a period, she says, when men must shed their ``first
adulthood'' and move into their ``second adulthood.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta professor David Meltz is one of the men Sheehy found who
successfully made the transition. When he was in his late 40s a few
years ago, Meltz marched into a law school that was about to be
shut down and told the Board of Bar Examiners, ``Give me this
school. I'm the only person who can revive this place.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the next four years, he took John Marshall Law School from
the edge of extinction to the verge of accreditation by the
American Bar Association.
</P>
<P>
   But just as he was overcoming one challenge, he was confronted
with another, more personal, crisis. Under the strain of his job
and the death of his father, Meltz ended up in the hospital with a
perforated colon. His doctor gave him a choice: undergo immediate
surgery, or go home and face the possibility he would be dead by
morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made some deals in that hospital,'' Meltz says. ``I said,
`Get me out of here and I'm going to live like I haven't lived
before.'''
</P>
<P>
   Now, Meltz says, he is a different man. ``I don't fear death. I
feel I have more control than I ever did as a younger man, and that
gives me a sense of mastery.''
</P>
<P>
   Although midlife crises usually hit men in their 40s and 50s,
they can come earlier, Sheehy says. Ray Brown, a former pro
football player for the Atlanta Falcons and New Orleans Saints, was
barely in his 30s when the cheering stopped. Forced into premature
retirement, Brown says, the two years it took him to find out what
he wanted to do ``probably was the hardest time in my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown praises his wife for getting a job and giving him the time
to find himself. Now owner of a remodeling company, Brown says he
has been able to move beyond his image as a football star. ``The
right mate is the key to life,'' he told Sheehy.
</P>
<P>
   Like Brown and Meltz, most men go through some kind of ``meaning
crisis,'' Sheehy says. ``They can be as insignificant as balding or
as serious as downsizing, divorce, health problems or the death of
a parent.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheehy, who describes herself as a ``cultural interpreter,'' has
been criticized for plucking information from serious researchers
and marketing it in a feel-good package. Life's ``crises'' _
divorce, loss of a job, birthdays _ became ``passages,'' a
less-threatening description. But her approach worked.
``Passages,'' published in 1972, sold 8 million copies.
</P>
<P>
   Her new book comes as men are beginning to talk openly about
everything from impotence to their fear of aging and obsolescence.
And, with more instances of early retirement, Sheehy says members
of the boomer generation face the dilemma of what to do for the
rest of their lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can't just coast. Men live too long today to spend 30
years on the golf course.''
</P>
<P>
   That was the dilemma facing Sheehy's husband, Clay Felker. A few
years ago, the founder of New York magazine found himself out of a
job and at loose ends.
</P>
<P>
   ``I walked through the dark woods with my husband,'' Sheehy
says. ``We took a few years to find a solution.''
</P>
<P>
   Eventually they decided that since Felker's greatest pleasure
had come from nurturing new talent, he would go into teaching.
Friends raised money to endow a chair in magazine journalism at the
University of California at Berkeley, Sheehy kept a place in New
York, and the couple built a new life with bicoastal careers.
</P>
<P>
   Like her husband, Sheehy says, the men who made the best
transition into ``second adulthood'' were those who didn't retire.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although they left their first career, they redirected their
efforts, became self-employed and became their own bosses. They had
a sense of mastery and had something to get up for in the
morning.''
</P>
<P>
   Others are choosing to drop out altogether and switch roles with
their wives. As men retire in their 50s, women who have stayed home
to raise the kids are just getting started in midlife careers,
Sheehy says.
</P>
<P>
   ``This could work out very well for men who feel secure. A man
who has a partner who is excited about her career maturing may take
some of the financial responsibilities off his shoulder so he has
time to explore.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheehy sees this situation as an opportunity for men to redefine
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of being warrior and provider, they can become the
kinds of fathers their own fathers were not. They can become closer
to their wives and connect with their feelings. And that's better
than any magic pill.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
