<SLUG> BC-NORTEL-BAYNET-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORTEL-BAYNET DEAL UNITES COMPUTER NETWORKING, TELEPHONE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RONALD ROSENBERG  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   After months of rumors, Northern Telecom Ltd. Monday said it
would acquire Bay Networks Inc. in a $7.19 billion stock deal that
showed how quickly the worlds of computer networking and telephone
communications are converging.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement, Canadian-based Nortel will exchange 0.6
share of its stock for each Bay Networks share. Based on Monday's
closing price of $54 a share for Nortel, the transaction values Bay
at $32.40 a share.
</P>
<P>
   Nortel shares plunged Monday by 9 11/16, slashing the deal's
value from $9.1 billion, the amount announced based on Friday's
closing price. Bay Networks stock closed Monday at 30, up 2 7/16.
</P>
<P>
   Bay Networks of Santa Clara, Calif. is the nation's third-
largest computer networking company and was created through the
merger of California-based Synoptics Inc. and Wellfleet
Communications Inc. of Billerica, Mass. Bay Networks still has
2,000 employees in Massachusetts. Nortel is North America's No. 2
telephone equipment maker.
</P>
<P>
   The Nortel-Bay Networks combination is the largest merger yet
between a telecommunications company and a computer networking
concern. Companies that deal with voice communication are looking
to catapult &UR;  &LR; into the fast-growing field of data communications,
while computer networking companies are looking to reach new
customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The greatest challenge to the new Nortel will be to execute
cleanly on the vision,'' said Michael Duran, an analyst at Lazard
Freres &AMP; Co. LLC. ``They will have the most comprehensive product
portfolio in the industry for data and voice networking for homes,
business and telephone service providers.''
</P>
<P>
   Fueled by the pell-mell growth of the Internet and businesses
relying on computer networking, both companies see the convergence
of voice and data as their future &UR; . &LR;  Along with rivals Lucent
Technologies Inc. and Cisco Systems Inc. they see the technology
barriers distinguishing computer networking from &UR;  &LR;  voice telephone
technology disappearing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nortel wants to provide a supermarket of products and services
to telephone carriers and large corporations and with this deal for
Bay, we'll start to see greater consolidation of both data
networking and telephone equipment companies,'' predicted Roger
Wery,  &UR;  &LR; vice president at Renaissance Worldwide, a large consulting
company in Newton, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street and industry analysts have questioned whether Nortel
and Bay Networks can overcome cultural differences to successfully
compete against the biggest computer networking companies and
telephone equipment suppliers.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have a cultural nightmare where the two companies' senior
managers, one on the voice side and the other on the data side,
have to go up against Cisco, the most formidable competitor in
computer networking,'' said Maribel Lopez, a network strategies
analyst at Forrester Research in Cambridge, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Both Nortel and Bay Networks executives maintain those
differences are minor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand the cultural concerns, but we are not merging Bay
Networks into Nortel. Instead we'll have &UR;  &LR; Bay operate as an
independent business unit, one that we know is compatible with
Nortel's operations, which we think are technologically and
culturally compatible,'' said David House, Bay Networks chief
executive.
</P>
<P>
   House, a former Intel Corp. senior executive, will become
president of Nortel and join its board. He will report to John
Roth, who will continue as Nortel's chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   Both men said no layoffs are expected after the deal and that
they expect to add employees in Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   Bay Networks itself has coped with the aftermath of a merger.
After the 1994 merger of Wellfleet and Synoptics, the bicoastal
company _ renamed Bay Networks _ struggled to combine two disparate
organizations and only recently has Bay Networks begun to live up
to analysts expectations.
</P>
<P>
   For Nortel, the deal with Bay Networks caps a recent string of
investments and acquisitions in Massachusetts. In April, Nortel
acquired Aptis Communications Inc. of Chelmsford in a $305 million
stock deal and it recently invested close to $25 million in Avici
Systems Inc., also based in Westford.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
