<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-15 20:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0363 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-BULLS-CELTICS-NYT     06-15 1602
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-BULLS-CELTICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSELL'S CELTICS VS. JORDAN'S BULLS: WHO'S ON TOP? 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By IRA BERKOW    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Never in the 51 years of the National Basketball Association has
there been a dynasty to compare with Bill Russell's Celtics. Unless
it is Michael Jordan's Bulls.
</P>
<P>
   Russell's teams won 11 championships in 13 years. Jordan's have
won six in his last six full seasons, considering that he took a
year-and-a-half sabbatical to try his hand at minor league
baseball.
</P>
<P>
   The dynasties started 35 years apart, with Russell's running
from the 1956-57 season through 1968-69 and Jordan's from 1991-92
through 1997-98. Two different eras. Two different ensembles. Two
different kinds of stars. Jordan scores famously by soaring and
swooping to the hoop. Russell defended famously by soaring and
swatting balls away from the hoop.
</P>
<P>
   So, how do pro basketball's biggest dynasties compare? And what
does it say about the way the game has changed? Are Jordan's Bulls
the equal of Russell's Celtics? Are they better?
</P>
<P>
   ``How do you compare the two?'' asked Red Auerbach, the coach of
nine of those Celtics championship teams and now a vice chairman of
the Celtics' board at age 80. ``How do you compare Ali to Louis, or
Dempsey? You can't do it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I may be slanted a little bit, but there's no question in my
mind that we could do well against them,'' he said. ``If anybody
says that the players of this era are better than those of the past
era _ well, I don't buy that for a minute.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were excellent defensively and, with Russell, dominating on
the boards, where games are often won or lost. Are the Bulls
faster? No. We could run with them all day long. Are they smarter?
No. Could they shoot better? No. The guys of our era _ Havlicek,
Heinsohn, Sam Jones, Sharman, Bailey Howell _ were all outstanding
shooters and scorers.''
</P>
<P>
   Jerry West, a Hall of Fame player for the Lakers in those
Celtics years and the Lakers' general manager in the Bulls' era,
agrees to some extent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't necessarily believe that a modern team is better than
one of that past era, but the comparisons are interesting,'' he
said. ``Each team, for example, had one dominating player _ Russell
for the Celtics, Jordan for the Bulls _ plus superb role players
around them. But there is an ``X'' factor. That is Michael Jordan.
He's an incredible player, the greatest player I've ever seen. He's
the best offensive player I've ever seen, and his defense is second
to none. He's the modern-day Babe Ruth.''
</P>
<P>
   Rod Thorn, who played for Chicago during the Celtics dynasty and
is now in charge of basketball operations for the NBA, believes the
Bulls have another advantage: Scottie Pippen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Russell was in a class by himself defensively and
competitively, like Jordan,'' Thorn said. ``But no team has had two
phenomenal, all-around athletes like Jordan and Pippen on the same
team. The Bulls are more athletic than the Celtics were, and in a
game or a series, the Celtics would have no antidote for Pippen.''
</P>
<P>
   Wayne Embry, who played with and against those Celtics teams and
has been general manager of the Cavaliers, had trouble deciding
which team was superior. ``Jordan refuses to lose,'' he said.
``Like Russell. Both always found a way to beat you.''
</P>
<P>
   Comparisons are difficult because the two eras are so vastly
different, from life on the road to the skills of the players to
the makeup of the league itself.
</P>
<P>
   For example, travel was more difficult in the Celtics' era,
Auerbach pointed out. ``After a game, we'd have to catch a tiny
DC-3, and then try to grab a bite of food on the way,'' he said.
``Or we'd have to go by train. You'd board at 1 in the morning and
be in the next town at 5 a.m., and stagger to your hotel. Today,
teams have chartered planes, and stewardesses bring them their
meals.''
</P>
<P>
   But it was easier to keep a good team together during the
Russell years than in today's era of free agency, making a dynasty
harder to come by now.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's easier for players to defect,'' said Atlanta Coach Lenny
Wilkens, who was a star guard with the St. Louis Hawks and the
Seattle SuperSonics during the Celtics' era. ``In the days before
free agency, you had a lock on a player unless you trade or sell
him or he retires.''
</P>
<P>
   And players today have many more choices if they want to move.
When Russell's teams began their dynasty, in 1956, there were just
eight teams and a maximum of 96 players in the league (the number
of teams increased to 14 by their last championship in 1969). Now,
there are 29 teams and 348 players.
</P>
<P>
   Wilkens believes that growth makes the competition stronger.
``Both the Celtic and Bulls teams were great, but the number of
teams today might make it harder to win,'' he said. ``So many more
teams can knock you off.''
</P>
<P>
   Don Nelson, a player for the Celtics in their dynasty years and
a coach and general manager of other teams in the Bulls' years,
sees it differently. ``Imagine the talent level in the NBA when you
only had nine or 11 or 14 teams,'' he said. ``It was tougher then.
The talent level was exceptionally high all over the league. It
wasn't watered down a little bit the way it is now.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnny ``Red'' Kerr, the Bulls' broadcaster who was a star
center with Syracuse in the early years of the Celtics' dynasty and
then the Bulls' first coach (1966-68), agreed. ``The Bulls might go
against some of the best teams, like Olajuwon and Houston, or Shaq
and the Lakers, just twice in a season,'' Kerr said. ``Russell had
to go against Chamberlain and Nate Thurmond and Pettit 11 times in
a season.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides Russell, 11 other Celtics of that era made the Hall of
Fame as players, from Andy Phillip in the first year to John
Havlicek in the last. Only Pippen seems a certainty to make it
among Jordan's teammates.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson thinks it curious that most outstanding teams are strong
either at center or point guard, or both, as were the Celtics.
``But the Bulls are different, in that their strengths are at
shooting guard, Jordan, small forward, Pippen, and power forward,
Rodman,'' he said. ``The rest of the players are role players. But
because of the presence of Jordan, they have elevated their game.''
</P>
<P>
   West agreed, saying that some of those role players who have
been very helpful might not even make other teams.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson added: ``Russell also helped elevate the Celtics with his
winning attitude, which, like Jordan's, permeates the locker room.
But I thought that the great Celtic teams had more depth than the
Bulls. They'd bring in Frank Ramsey or Clyde Lovellette or Willie
Naulls or Larry Siegfried or Embry _ all outstanding players.'' He
might also have added the name of Nelson.
</P>
<P>
   ``And they averaged about 115 points a game, which the Bulls
don't match, while keeping the opposition scoring way down,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   While Russell won a title in his first season as a pro, it took
Jordan seven years to win his first. ``It took time for management
to assemble the right players around him,'' Wilkens said. ``But
once he got it going, there was no stopping him.''
</P>
<P>
   Only one player was part of the Celtics' dynasty from the first
season to the last, and that was Russell. As for the Bulls, only
two players remain from the teams that won three titles before
Jordan left for baseball: Jordan and Pippen. So, despite a virtual
total turnover in both eras, the extraordinary stars kept the
dynasties intact.
</P>
<P>
   ``But this also says a lot about management of both teams,''
Wilkens said. ``Auerbach was able to surround Russell with some
great players, while Jerry Krause was able to get exceptional role
players for Jordan.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilkens mentioned, in particular, the trade for Pippen, and then
Horace Grant, and then the signing of Toni Kukoc from Europe. He
also noted that the Bulls have been able to get such helpful
centers as Bill Cartwright, Brian Williams and Luc Longley, as well
as 3-point shooters such as Craig Hodges, John Paxson, Bobby
Hansen, Trent Tucker and, now, Steve Kerr.
</P>
<P>
   ``And Ron Harper _ don't forget him,'' Wilkens said. ``He's one
of the smartest players in the game, and does a superb job on
defense. And before coming to the Bulls said he was finished as a
player.''
</P>
<P>
   Red Holzman, the coach of the Knicks' two championship teams and
currently a consultant for New York, added another reminder.
``Don''t forget the coaches,'' he said. ``Auerbach's in the Hall of
Fame, and I think Phil Jackson should be too. He's handled some
difficult situations with fantastic balance. Like getting the best
out of Dennis Rodman. A lot of coaches wouldn't have been able to
deal with that.''
</P>
<P>
   Coaching has improved in this era, making it harder to win,
Embry said. ``Just the use of videotape in order to put in defenses
has made a huge difference,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And the players have changed too. ``Weight training has raised
them a level,'' Embry said.
</P>
<P>
   But players are generally younger and less experienced today,
with the best leaving college early and a handful coming into the
league directly out of high school.
</P>
<P>
   ``So many kids today are wonderfully skilled, but they haven't
learned proper fundamentals,'' West said. ``So when they run into
trouble, they have nothing to fall back on. But not Jordan. That's
one of the many places where he creates distance from many of his
opponents.''
</P>
<P>
   Red Kerr pondered the question of who would win a championship
series matching a team from the Celtics' dynasty against a Bulls
team.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a tough one,'' he said. ``I see the series going into
overtime in the seventh game.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-15-98 2027EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
