u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SWEDISH-BALLET-REVIEW     06-15 1044
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWEDISH-BALLET-REVIEW-554&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROYAL SWEDISH BALLET: GOING STRONG AT 225 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: The different spellings of Gustaf and Gustav are CQ.) 
(mk) 
 By ANNA KISSELGOFF   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   STOCKHOLM, Sweden _ The Royal Swedish Ballet ended its
225th-anniversary festival on Saturday night here with a lively
four-hour gala. During an eight-day marathon that included a
delightful ``Nutcracker'' with a Swedish flavor, the company
presented past and present repertory. The gala program did the
same, with guest artists from France, Italy and Denmark, all
countries whose dancers and ballet masters played a role in Swedish
ballet's history.
</P>
<P>
   King Carl XVI Gustaf and Queen Silvia attended the performance
at the Royal Opera House and led the standing ovation at the end
from the royal box. The King took some good-natured ribbing from
Rolf Skoglund, an actor who gave a first-class impersonation of the
18th-century Swedish king Gustav III.
</P>
<P>
   Addressing his French ballet master, Louis Gallodier (Istvan
Kisch), this Gustav recalled onstage that when he created his
ballet company in 1773 he did not want it to be ``a mere branch of
the Paris Opera Ballet.'' It was to be Swedish in spirit and
content. Catapulted into the present by the end of the program and
looking around for someone of ``equal rank,'' he told the current
king that priority must be given to support of the arts.
</P>
<P>
   The point might have more effect if addressed to politicians,
but it was well taken. The days are past when any 18th- or
19th-century monarch in Europe, and that includes Russia, could
start a ballet company by inviting the pertinent business
consultants of the day: French and Italian ballet masters.
</P>
<P>
   Filippo Taglioni, an Italian ballet master who worked in Paris
and Stockholm, was recalled on Saturday by an excerpt from his 1832
version of ``La Sylphide.'' Nicolas Le Riche, Elisabeth Platel and
Karin Averty, the high-powered stars from the Paris Opera Ballet,
danced the Act 1 pas de trois from Pierre Lacotte's familiar
reconstruction, very different from the Danish version
choreographed by August Bournonville in 1832. It was, of course,
Taglioni's daughter, the Swedish-born Marie Taglioni, who danced
the original ``Sylphide.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bournonville was remembered as well. His French father,
Antoine Bournonville, was a principal dancer in the Royal Swedish
Ballet and he himself headed the Swedish Royal Opera House from
1861 to 1864.
</P>
<P>
   Anne Marie Vessel, from the Royal Danish Ballet, choreographed a
version of a scene from ``Bellman,'' an 1844 ballet that August
Bournonville choreographed about Carl Michael Bellman (1740-95), a
Swedish poet and composer still beloved for his songs about nature,
love and drink. Johan Kobborg and Henriette Muus from the Royal
Danish Ballet were charming if muted in the mimed and danced love
spat between Bellman and his wife.
</P>
<P>
   Carla Fracci, a superstar from Italy, was given chiefly
impressionistic images from Isadora Duncan's life and dances in
``Homage to Isadora Duncan.'' Slowly but potently she worked her
magic as a Duncan mourning her drowned children.
</P>
<P>
   The choreography by Millicent Hodson and Kenneth Archer is not
the best on the Isadora theme but it works as a vehicle for Ms.
Fracci, one of American Ballet Theater's greatest ballerinas in the
1960s and 1970s. As Lena Nordin sang Schubert's ``Ave Maria,'' Ms.
Fracci's dramatic power channeled the gestures of a mother cradling
a child into an image of Duncan strangled by her scarf.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Dramatic power is also the strong suit of the Royal Swedish
Ballet. As Le Riche showed by comparison, sheer dance power as
expressed through brilliant classical technique takes second place
here. If things go as planned next year, Americans in Washington;
Costa Mesa, Calif., and later at the Brooklyn Academy of Music will
see a troupe with an admirable ensemble spirit and expressive
presence.
</P>
<P>
   The surprise of the second half of the festival was the
``Nutcracker'' choreographed by Par Isberg, a principal dancer who
is now the company's resident choreographer. He and Erik Naslund,
the director of the Swedish Dance Museum, have fashioned a fresh
and engaging scenario that stays true to the spirit of the original
1892 ``Nutcracker,'' but draws upon the Swedish children's books of
Elsa Beskow (1874-1953).
</P>
<P>
   It helps to be a Swede to recognize the characters and the
Christmas folk customs. But even if you don't know that Petter and
Lotta are orphans living with three aunts and have a little black
dog, there is no mistaking the warmth of the tree-cutting ritual,
Christmas preparations and party of Act 1.
</P>
<P>
   The live black poodle who frolics or runs across the stage on
cue is the scene-stealer. But at Friday's performance, there was
genuine emotional impact from Hans Nilsson as the charcoal burner
transformed into a prince, and the exceptionally talented Marie
Lindqvist as the housemaid who becomes his princess in the fine
classical pas de deux Isberg has choreographed in Act 2. For Lotta
and Petter, exuberantly portrayed by Ann Brattselius and Jens
Rosen, this ideal vision of the parents they do not have is
psychologically right.
</P>
<P>
   It would be easy to focus on the success of Bo-Ruben Hedwall's
adaptation of Beskow's illustrations: a village street toward which
a sleigh rides at the end of the ballet, as well as an interior
with a tile stove that grows in size along with the tree whose
paper snowmen and other ornaments come to life. Above all, Isberg
has avoided provincial charm.
</P>
<P>
   Some of Tchaikovsky's music has been cut and this ``Nutcracker''
is not a grand classical spectacle. But Isberg is impressively
fluent in two big classical ensembles, the ``Snowflakes'' and the
``Waltz of the Flowers.'' There is a wonderful use of folk forms.
The live nutcracker doll is here a traditional gift-bearer in a
straw goat's mask.
</P>
<P>
   The company showed a more serious side earlier in the week in
John Neumeier's ``Mahler's Third Symphony'' and Kenneth MacMillan's
``Mayerling.'' The second was not as well danced as the first. But
in this Swedish ``Nutcracker'' for all seasons (a must on a U.S.
tour), the company showed its heart.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
