<SLUG> BC-ADVERTISING-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING NOTES 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Burnett Bows Out of Glad Account
</P>
<P>
   Another long relationship between an advertiser and an agency is
ending as the Leo Burnett USA unit of Leo Burnett Co. in Chicago
has resigned the Glad brand account of First Brands Corp. in
Danbury, Conn., after working on campaigns for Glad plastic
products since 1961.
</P>
<P>
   Wally Petersen, a spokesman for Burnett, said the resignation
stemmed from the agency's being unable to participate in a review
that First Brands began in April for a single agency to handle
consolidated advertising duties for Glad, the STP line of
automotive products and three brands of cat litter. Burnett could
not take part, Petersen said, because STP posed a conflict with the
agency's account with Amoco Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Burnett helped the Glad brand's previous owner, Union Carbide
Corp., develop and introduce plastic wrap and bags to consumers.
Memorable campaigns included ``the Man from Glad'' in the 1960s and
``Don't get mad, get Glad'' in the 1970s. Glad ad spending last
year totaled $6.5 million, according to the Competitive Media
Reporting unit of VNU NV. Among the agencies taking part in the
First Brands review are Young &AMP; Rubicam Advertising in New York,
which handles STP, and McCann-Erickson New York, part of the
McCann-Erickson Worldwide Advertising unit of Interpublic Group of
Cos., which handles the Jonny Cat, Scoop Away and Fresh Step cat
litter brands.
</P>
<P>
   Jenny Craig Narrows Its Review
</P>
<P>
   Jenny Craig Inc. in La Jolla, Calif., which operates weight-loss
programs, has narrowed a review for the creative and media parts of
its domestic account to six agencies and two media services.
Billings are estimated at $40 million.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Pearlman, managing partner at Bob Wolf Partners &AMP; Co. in Los
Angeles, a consulting company helping to manage the review,
identified the agencies in the creative review as Suissa Miller
Advertising in Los Angeles, the incumbent; BBDO West, part of
Omnicom Group in Los Angeles; D'Arcy Masius Benton &AMP; Bowles
Communications, a unit of MacManus Group in Los Angeles; Richards
Group in Dallas; Team One Advertising, a unit of Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi
PLC in El Segundo, Calif., and Wong Doody in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   The agencies in the media review, Pearlman said, are the Western
International Media unit of Interpublic Group of Cos. in Los
Angeles, the media incumbent, and Carat/ICG in Los Angeles, part of
Aegis Group PLC.
</P>
<P>
   Accounts
</P>
<P>
   -- Jerzees Activewear, Alexander City, Ala., a division of the
Russell Corp., to McCann-Erickson New York, part of the
McCann-Erickson Worldwide Advertising unit of Interpublic Group of
Cos., to handle the apparel maker's national television buying.
Those duties had been handled by Ogilvy &AMP; Mather New York, part of
WPP Group PLC. The creative and media planning duties on the
account, with billings estimated at $10 million to $11 million,
remain at Fitzgerald &AMP; Co., Atlanta. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -- Nationsbank Corp., Charlotte, N.C., to Lopez Negrete
Communications Inc., Houston, to continue as its agency of record
for Hispanic campaigns. Billings were estimated at $3 million to $4
million. The agency, which has handled the assignment since 1993,
was retained after a review that came after Nationsbank's
acquisition of Barnett Banks Inc.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -- Andre-Boudin Bakeries, San Francisco, to Kirshenbaum Bond &AMP;
Partners West, San Francisco, to handle the bakery's integrated
marketing account, which had been handled in-house. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   People
</P>
<P>
   -- Steve Baer was named to the new position of executive vice
president and deputy creative director at Foote, Cone &AMP; Belding,
New York, part of True North Communications. He had been executive
vice president and managing director at Wells BDDP, New York, which
closed. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
