<HEADER>
A0368 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SUNBEAM-DUNLAP-560(2T     06-15 0600
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUNBEAM-DUNLAP-560(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUNLAP DISMISSED AS CHAIRMAN OF SUNBEAM 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By DANA CANEDY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For years, Albert J. Dunlap has been one of the nation's most
feared corporate executives. He downsized with a vengeance,
frequently boasting of the thousands he had thrown out of work to
lift his companies' stock prices, earning himself the nickname
``Chainsaw Al.''
</P>
<P>
   Now it is Dunlap who has been thrown out of a job. Over the
weekend, the self-proclaimed turnaround artist, who had run Sunbeam
Corp. for almost two years, was dismissed as chairman in a revolt
by a board led by some of his hand-picked directors.
</P>
<P>
   Saying it no longer believed Dunlap had the skills to revive the
ailing consumer appliance maker, the board announced Monday that
Sunbeam's financial results for the rest of the year would be far
worse than expected and that it needed a new leader.
</P>
<P>
   Dunlap, who wrote in his best-selling autobiography, ``Mean
Business,'' that the best bargain is an expensive chief executive,
became known for his wholesale sacking of factory workers and
managers alike, both at Sunbeam and elsewhere. He was tirelessly
self-promotional, popping up repeatedly on television for the last
two years plugging his book and, calling himself ``Rambo in
pinstripes,'' preaching his slash-and-burn philosophy.
</P>
<P>
   Dunlap was known to pass out autographed copies of the book
freely to Sunbeam employees, bankers, waiters, even doormen _
anyone who would take them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The outside directors have unanimously taken this decisive
action because we have lost confidence in Dunlap's leadership,''
said one board member, Peter A. Langerman, chief operating officer
of Franklin Mutual Advisors Inc., Sunbeam's largest shareholder,
who will replace him as chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry W. Levin will become the chief executive officer and try
to put things back on track. He is an executive vice president of
MacAndrews &AMP; Forbes Holdings, Sunbeam's second largest shareholder,
and a former chief executive of Revlon Inc. and Coleman Co., which
Sunbeam recently purchased.
</P>
<P>
   But his dismissal is not likely to end to Dunlap's dealings with
Sunbeam. On paper, Dunlap is owed a severance package worth as much
as $40 million. But the board has other ideas.
</P>
<P>
   Two people close to the board said the ousted chief executive
did not deserve the money. ``The board's view is they feel badly
used by Dunlap,'' said one of the people, adding that board members
felt blind-sided by unexpectedly poor financial results during the
past and current quarters. ``They are furious, and they don't want
to pay him severance and don't believe he was straight with them on
the erosion of the numbers,'' this person said.
</P>
<P>
   If the board is successful in denying him the money, Dunlap
would be one of the few chief executives to fail at the job and not
walk away with millions anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``When companies kill the king, they at least give him a decent
burial,'' said Graef S. Crystal, a watchdog of executive pay. ``I
think they're going to have to pay him the whole thing. They don't
have any choice.''
</P>
<P>
   Dunlap, who has dismissed thousands of workers at Sunbeam, Scott
Paper and Lily-Tulip, has said that 80 percent of U.S. businesses
need to be ``Dunlapped,'' i.e. subjected to massive overhauls that
``eliminate what is not the best.'' But at Sunbeam, he got into
trouble by promising more than he could deliver.
</P>
<P>
   Dunlap could not be reached for comment, and his lawyer did not
return calls.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Just months ago, board members and major shareholders were still
voicing support for the 60-year-old West Point-trained former
paratrooper, who arrived at Sunbeam in July 1996 to the delight of
investors. The stock rose nearly 50 percent that day and climbed to
a high of $53 this March after Dunlap proclaimed Sunbeam fixed and
said Sunbeam was ready to grow with the purchases of the makers of
Mr. Coffee machines, First Alert smoke alarms and Coleman outdoor
equipment.
</P>
<P>
   While Wall Street cheered, Dunlap repeatedly promised 20 percent
annual sales gains in an industry that was growing by only about 3
percent a year. For a time, he seemed to be pulling it off. Then,
in March, came regulatory filings that detailed how Sunbeam sold
$58 million worth of barbecue grills in December and gave retailers
until this month to pay for them. This helped Sunbeam post an
unrealistic 18 percent surge in sales last year.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the indications that perhaps Dunlap had promised too
much, and the information about the one-time shot in the arm from
the barbecue grill deal.
</P>
<P>
   Next, Sunbeam warned three times this year that sales were
slowing because of an unexpected slowdown in grill sales. In
essence, the special grill deal allowed the company to borrow sales
in last year's fourth quarter for products that normally sell well
in the first and second quarters.
</P>
<P>
   On May 11, the company reported a sales drop and $44.6 million
loss, blaming the poor results in part on the special grill deal
and even El Nino. A month after the disclosure of the special grill
deal, shareholders filed lawsuits against the company and Dunlap,
contending that the early-buy program was devised to prop up the
company's numbers last year at the expense of the first quarter, so
it could secure financing for its recent acquisitions. The company
and Dunlap have denied the charge.
</P>
<P>
   Still, earlier this month Sunbeam said the problems related to
the grill debacle would linger into the current quarter. Then
Monday, the board said that sales have been so bad this quarter
that the company would report an operating loss for the period and
would not meet its goal of earning $1 per share for the full year
even though that amount had been revised downward several times to
account for Sunbeam's troubles.
</P>
<P>
   ``The numbers weren't happening, and the explanation of why it
happened didn't really wash,'' said Charles M. Elson, a
Dunlap-appointed board member who made the motion to dismiss him.
</P>
<P>
   At a meeting at the Waldorf-Astoria last Tuesday, the board
asked Dunlap to explain the company's recent poor performance. ``He
said it was a transition year and don't expect a lot,'' Elson said.
That surprising statement, Elson said, sealed Dunlap's fate.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said at a press conference two weeks earlier that we would
earn 5 cents to 10 cents a share'' for the second quarter, Elson
said. ``If you are going to assure people of results, you've got to
meet the result, and when it became clear to us he wasn't going to
be making the results, that called into question his ability to
execute the long-term strategy.''
</P>
<P>
   Since shortly after he arrived, Dunlap's critics have complained
that he stuffed the pipeline with a high volume of goods to boost
sales, a claim that he had angrily denied. But in a conference call
with financial analysts on Monday, the board confirmed that part of
Sunbeam's problem stems from ``pushing to make aggressive sales
objectives over the past several months.'' As a result, retailers
had too many Sunbeam grills, electric blankets and blenders.
</P>
<P>
   One of Dunlap's earliest missteps may have been purchasing
Coleman. He apparently miscalculated what buying Coleman from Ron
Perleman in exchange for stock would do to his control. Because
now, just three months later, the company is in the hands of Levin,
a close associate of Perleman's, and Dunlap is out.
</P>
<P>
   Four board members _ Elson, Howard G. Kristol, William T. Rutter
and Faith Whittlesey _ are Dunlap appointees. They will remain on
the board, but Russell A. Kersh, a longtime Dunlap aide who is
Sunbeam's vice chairman and chief financial officer, is expected to
be fired, according to one person close to the board.
</P>
<P>
   Sunbeam also said the company would appoint three additional
board members, including a representative of Frankin Mutual and two
representing MacAndrews &AMP; Forbes. They will be Levin and Howard
Gittis, vice chairman of MacAndres &AMP; Forbes.
</P>
<P>
   The company said its three operating officers would continue to
run the company and report to Levin.
</P>
<P>
   Dunlap's own words might also have come back to haunt him if the
board took them to heart. In his book, which he promoted as
aggressively as Sunbeam promotes its toasters, Dunlap wrote: ``My
pay should be compared to superstars in other fields, not to the
average CEO. Only a handful of chief executives are worth the big
bucks they are paid. Many are grossly overpaid and should be fired
and then replaced by CEOs whose pay is strictly
performance-based.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sunbeam board apparently agreed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-15-98 2030EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
