<DOCNO> NYT19980615.0359 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-15 20:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0371 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-ARATON-NYT &LR;      06-15 0785
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ARATON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JORDAN PROVES IT TAKES MORE THAN LEGS
</HEADLINE>
   (ja) 
 By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALT LAKE CITY, Utah _ The pull-up jump shot, once a fundamental
basketball staple, reminded us Sunday night that while Michael
Jordan has dominated the Generation X 1990s, his career began in an
era that looked very different from this one. When Jordan used his
left shoulder and hand to force the defender Bryon Russell to move
left, then backward, he was dating himself as a player who did not
grow up with 24-hour cable networks, with continuous reels of
3-point shots and frantic assaults on a pliable rim.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan was once more breathtaking than any of today's young
fliers, but never averse to learning a few subtle tricks in the
gym. The Jordan of a decade ago would have elevated and levitated
over Russell for the shot that closed out the Utah Jazz, that
raised the Chicago Bulls' sixth championship flag in the last eight
years. The 35-year-old and more earthbound Jordan needed to clear
enough space, cross over on the dribble, square up and shoot.
</P>
<P>
   Forget the 40 percent series shooting, the 20 shots he missed in
44 exhausting minutes of his 103rd game of the season. Today's
typical player can't even get a decent shot under these
circumstances, and this one was for the ring.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I got the ball, I looked up and saw 18.5 seconds left,''
he said, setting up the game winner with 5.2 seconds left that gave
him 45 points and the Bulls an 87-86 victory at the Delta Center.
``I felt we couldn't call a timeout. It was do or die. John
Stockton was on the right side with Steve Kerr, and he couldn't
gamble, and as Russell reached, he gave me a clear lane. I made my
initial drive, he bit, and I stopped, pulled up, great look.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan managed to edit out his use of the left shoulder and
hand, though there were the usual news media cries that in a more
democratic basketball society, it would have been an offensive
foul. Conversely, the contact was precipitated by Russell's
reaching, which Jordan exploited, as he did against the same player
in a similar Game 1 situation during last year's finals. Russell
committed the cardinal defensive sin, not staying balanced, feet
uncrossed. By the time Jordan was in the air, Russell may as well
have been in the stands.
</P>
<P>
   ``You see these young guys come in the league with the great
legs and they think that's all it takes,'' said the Bulls reserve
Scott Burrell, Jordan's practice opposite. ``But it doesn't really
help you until you learn how to play the game. Physical talent will
help you to a certain extent, but not at crunch time.''
</P>
<P>
   This might have been the synopsis for another playoff season
when the popular coaching maxim was, ``Never trust anyone under
30.'' Three of the four semifinalists were filled with
bone-creakin', geritol-takin', retirement-contemplatin' geezers.
The fourth, Shaquille O'Neal's young Lakers, were sent to their
rooms in a four-game sweep by the Jazz.
</P>
<P>
   Principal players in the finals were Jordan, Scottie Pippen
(32), Dennis Rodman (37), John Stockton (36), Karl Malone (34),
Jeff Hornacek (35), Antoine Carr (37). Toni Kukoc, who turns 30 in
September, learned the game in the more grounded European system.
And yet, the dramatic Game 6 and conclusion aside, this
championship series was no artistic masterpiece.
</P>
<P>
   The Bulls averaged 88 points a game, the Jazz 80. The Jazz tied
the record for fewest points scored in any National Basketball
Association game with a shot clock, with 54 in Game 3. The teams'
combined 66 first-half points in Game 5 was another record low. No
team scored 100 points in any game.
</P>
<P>
   When the Knicks and the Houston Rockets played such a series in
1994, the quality of play was ridiculed. When Jordan is gone, by
next season or whenever, people will no doubt harp once again on
the inability of offenses to react smartly to double teams. The
lack of creative intermediate play. The few players who can use
their bodies to create an effective jump shot off the dribble, the
way Jordan did against Russell.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if we've played as esthetically pleasing a game
as we have in the past,'' Bulls Coach Phil Jackson admitted. ``But
the Bulls have become a different kind of entertainment, like a
sitcom, a story.''
</P>
<P>
   For all his wealth, all his fame, Jordan's story ultimately is
about a man with a ball in a gym. ``When I got here this season, I
was holding back at practice, thinking, `I don't want to be the one
who ends his season,''' Burrell said. ``Then they tell you, `Go at
him. The man doesn't get hurt.' But, yeah, you wonder why he has to
go so hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Late Sunday night, Burrell understood.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
