<SLUG> BC-SOC-COMMENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LOSS, BUT A WIN FOR THE US 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ They could have done the conservative thing, probably
the prudent thing, when they came out for the second half down a
goal to Germany. They could have replaced attackers with defenders,
thrown up a wall and kicked Jurgen Klinsmann in the ankle a few
dozen times. The US soccer team could have done what they did four
years ago when faced with a superior team _ played not to lose.
</P>
<P>
   But the Americans don't play that way anymore. ``We will play to
win,'' coach Steve Sampson has said a hundred times since he got
the job three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   And so the US did in its World Cup opener Monday night, even
after its worst nightmare _ giving up a goal in the eighth minute _
came true. The Americans settled their nerves and swallowed hard
and kept coming. They nearly tied the match in the 53d minute on
Frankie Hejduk's diving header.
</P>
<P>
   When Sampson went to his bench in the second half, for Hejduk
and Roy Wegerle and Tab Ramos, he went for offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were trying to equalize, and then to go ahead,'' Sampson
said. ``Not to conserve a 1-0 result.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead it ended up 2-0 when the Germans counterattacked and
Klinsmann, the man with the golden foot, shook himself loose from
Thomas Dooley and put the ball by Kasey Keller.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe 10 days from now, if the US fails to advance because of
goal differential, playing to win Monday night will come back to
haunt it. But if they hadn't, the Yanks would never have known,
truly, where they stand on the world stage.
</P>
<P>
   They can, and have, beaten heavyweights like Brazil and
Argentina and England in Copa Americas and Gold Cups and US Cups.
But what they need to know _ and their fans need to know _ is
whether, after a decade of taking the sport seriously, the US can
play straight up against the best teams in the world when
everyone's playing for the world's biggest prize.
</P>
<P>
   They had that chance four years ago when they met eventual
champion Brazil in the second round before a full house in the Rose
Bowl and Bora Milutinovic, Sampson's predecessor, played it safe.
The Americans lost only 1-0 _ a perfectly good result _ but didn't
take a shot on goal. Could they have won if they'd risked more? Or
would they have been humiliated? Nobody knows, then or now.
</P>
<P>
   Monday night in the Parc des Princes, we got some answers.
Sampson's squad took on the European champions, a team loaded with
renowned (if aging) players like Klinsmann and Thomas Haessler and
Andreas Moeller and Juergen Kohler that has much to prove here
after their quarterfinal exit last time.
</P>
<P>
   With a bit of luck _ if Moeller's seeing-eye header hadn't
squeezed between Mike Burns's hip and the post and if Hejduk's ball
had gone in _ the US might have had a draw. Truth is, the Germans
are two goals better than the Americans on most nights and the
Americans won't argue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their 22 are better than our 22,'' Ramos said before he and
his mates even crossed the Atlantic. ``If they play their best and
we play our best, they win.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither team was at its best Monday night. The Americans were
jittery and tentative until the second half; the Germans developed
attention deficit after going up so easily so early. But even
though the US has narrowed the technical gap on the Germans, the
essential difference remains: The Germans can almost always get the
result they want; the Americans have to hope for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``You saw how simple it is for the Germans to win games,'' said
US captain Thomas Dooley, who was a German citizen until six years
ago and played a dozen years in the pro leagues there. ``They keep
possession all over the field. They don't make any mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   The Germans knew exactly what they needed Monday night _ not
merely a victory but a couple of goals difference in the plus
column, just in case they end up tying the Yugoslavs Sunday. And
they knew exactly how to get it. Knock US playmaker Claudio Reyna
off the ball every time he touched it. Stretch the defense by
knocking the ball around and probing, probing, probing for soft
spots. And make the Americans pay immediately _ and dearly _ for
every lapse.
</P>
<P>
   Moeller's goal might have seemed fluky, but it came because
David Regis and Ernie Stewart let Klinsmann escape from their
sandwich and get his head on a corner kick and because Moeller
slipped his mark. Klinsmann's goal came because the Americans lost
the ball going forward, because Oliver Bierhoff beat Eddie Pope
down the side and got off a cross, and because Dooley lost
Klinsmann in close.
</P>
<P>
   The Germans might be the oldest team here (L'Equipe, the French
sporting daily, said they were dinosaurs who played at Jurassic
Park des Princes), but most of them have played hundreds of matches
at cutthroat levels. They may have played ragged, uninspired soccer
in qualifying to get here, but they got here, as they have 14
times.
</P>
<P>
   The Germans have won three Cups, reached five of the last eight
finals and never failed to make the second round.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're a good team,'' said Pope. ``They don't go out and win
tournaments for no reason.''
</P>
<P>
   In their hearts, the Americans knew they had little chance to
win Monday night. They admitted openly that they would be thrilled
with a draw. Even a 1-0 loss, Sampson had said, would be an
acceptable result.
</P>
<P>
   The difference between last time and this time is that the Yanks
were not playing for a 1-0 loss. They were playing to see where
they stand. The US federation has already announced a bold plan
(the Europeans think it's a pipedream) to win the Cup by 2010. They
can't get there by playing not to lose to teams like Brazil and
Germany.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans in soccer are like the Croats and Lithuanians were
in 1992, playing the Dream Team and craving to determine how big
the gap really is. Twenty points? Forty? Eighty? Five years ago,
the US played two games against the Germans. They lost the first,
4-3, the second, 3-0, and hadn't played them since.
</P>
<P>
   How close are they now? Decidedly closer, German coach Berti
Vogts reckoned.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is clear the Americans have learned a tremendous amount,''
he said. ``They have made great strides. There are simply no poor
cousins around anymore, no easy matches. That is certainly the case
with the Americans.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
