<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-US-GERMANY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GERMANY DEFEATS US, 2-0 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Soap opera viewers in the US might not have noticed the
scheduling changes caused by the World Cup Monday, at least for the
first half of Germany's 2-0 victory over the US.
</P>
<P>
   All My Children was among the shows preempted by ABC-TV to
screen the match. But the US national team might have been part of
an episode for the show, its players picked apart in a men vs. boys
contest. The US has a chance to recover when it meets Iran in Lyon
Saturday, but there was little evidence the players are ready for
prime time -- or even for midday ratings.
</P>
<P>
   They were taught a severe lesson by the Germans, who used
defensive midfielder Jens Jeremies to take Claudio Reyna out of the
game, and took control early when Andreas Moeller slipped a header
past Revolution defender Mike Burns off the post in the 10th
minute, then coasted.
</P>
<P>
   Inhibition, stage fright, plus Germany's precision, were a
recipe for disaster similar to the US' even more devastating 5-1
loss to Czechoslovakia in the debut during the 1990 World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   But the US nearly capitalized on the Germans' lethargy, and came
within inches of tying the score on Frankie Hejduk's second-half
header, before succumbing to Jurgen Klinsmann's finish midway
through the half.
</P>
<P>
   Had Hejduk not been thwarted by goalkeeper Andreas Kopke, the US
and its numerous supporters at the Parc des Princes would have been
rejuvenated. But the US needed more to rally than Hejduk's
enthusiasm and speed, and a late injection of offense from Tab
Ramos.
</P>
<P>
   ``We defended with too many people,'' Ramos said. ``We didn't go
forward at all and it is very hard to win a game if you don't go
forward. If you go forward you can still lose to Germany, 2-0. I am
very disappointed. We looked like we did in 1990 in the first
half.''
</P>
<P>
   US coach Steve Sampson left much of the team's experience out.
Marcelo Balboa and Ramos were on the bench, and their teammate
during the Italy '90 debacle, John Harkes, had been cut. Alexi
Lalas and Preki remained on the bench and Roy Wegerle only entered
in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   Sampson used three defenders, plus three defensive midfielders,
in an attempt to stifle German strikers Klinsmann and Olivier
Bierhoff. The strategy seemed reasonable, especially with Kasey
Keller in goal. But the tactic not only failed, it negatively
affected the mentality of the players. For the US players, it was
almost impossible to adjust their defensive mindset.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played very well at the start, but after it was 1-0, the
Americans began to play more offensive, more aggressively,'' German
defender Stefan Reuter said. ``But we never felt we were going to
lose this game.''
</P>
<P>
   The Germans choreographed the pace from the start, and they did
so from the back line. Jurgen Kohler, Olaf Thon, and Christian
Worns had little to do defensively, as the US used only one
striker. This allowed Germany time on the ball, and the Mannschaft
methodically carved up the US defense. Germany's attacking
midfielders measured their angles, and the attackers picked their
spots.
</P>
<P>
   After Moeller's goal, Germany starting preparing for Sunday's
game against Yugoslavia in Lens. They had solved the US scheme and
seemed capable of scoring again, if necessary. There was no call
for the Germans to extend themselves or to reveal any more than
necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the US went all out in the second half. Hejduk, who
replaced Burns, added spark on the right side and narrowly missed
tying the game with a header past Kohler in the 10th minute.
Striker Eric Wynalda helped set up the play by laying off to
defender David Regis, who crossed to Hejduk.
</P>
<P>
   But the US began leaving spaces in an attempt to score. And
Germany capitalized. Jeremies set up the second goal by dribbling
past two US players, then powering through David Regis; Bierhoff
crossed to Klinsmann, who chested down as Dooley overran the play,
then lofted a shot into the far corner of the net for a two-goal
edge.
</P>
<P>
   There were other US bright spots. Eddie Pope stifled Bierhoff,
leading scorer in Italy's Serie A with Udinese last season. Keller,
who emerged on the international scene in a 1-0 win over Brazil in
February, was poised.
</P>
<P>
   But there were also other miscalculations, especially in
preparation. The US had taken a 3-0 victory over Austria in Vienna
in April, but then was unimpressive against Kuwait and failed to
win two other home matches.
</P>
<P>
   ``We beat Brazil because Kasey had the game of his life, but
they killed us,'' Ramos said. ``We played well against Austria and
we thought they would compare to Germany. But we just showed them
too much respect.''
</P>
</TEXT>
