u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOUTH-FUTURE-COX     06-15 0617
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOUTH-FUTURE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    South's leaders see high-tech future
 &HT;    By Chris Burritt
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ In a conference plotting the future of the
South, leaders urged communities across the region _ from backwoods
to big city, from poor to prosperous _ to embrace technology with
one arm and hug their children with the other.
</P>
<P>
   The wide-ranging recommendations emerging from a 76-page draft
report by the 1998 Commission on the Future of the South,
concluding its meeting today, illustrate the breadth of the
region's problems _ and the challenges of fixing them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would suggest that no other generation of Southerners has
been in such a promising position,'' former Kentucky Gov. Martha
Layne Collins, the commission's chairman, told Monday's conference.
But she added, ``If you have low skills, you face a bleak future,
and it is getting bleaker.''
</P>
<P>
   Kentucky's current governor, Paul Patton, warned that if the
South fails to nurture children as tomorrow's work force and to
embrace technology, the region risks losing its economic momentum.
``If we do it right, we can make a quantum leap in our effort to
catch up'' with the rest of America, he said.
</P>
<P>
   When adopted in final form at an Aug. 30-Sept. 1 meeting in San
Juan, Puerto Rico, the report will serve as a blueprint that the
commission hopes state legislatures, local governments and other
groups will use in economic development.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you take one lesson in economic development away from this
report, it should be this: In the years ahead, effective education
for everyone will drive our economy, and effective education begins
with a family and their children before birth,'' the commission
said in the draft report.
</P>
<P>
   Acknowledging the gaps to be overcome, the commission expressed
hope that ``virtually all students will be able to read by grade
four.'' To help rescue at-risk children from a lifetime of trouble,
the report recommends that the region replace its patchwork of day
care with ``preschool universally available by 2003'' and mandatory
full-day kindergarten by 2000. The gap between the haves and
have-nots is growing, despite the region's broad economic and
social gains of the past quarter century, the commission said.
</P>
<P>
   Global manufacturers with the prestige of Mercedes-Benz and BMW
have created thousands of jobs, but more than one in five of the
South's children live in poverty, the commission said. The region
has nine of America's 10 most depressed counties, where, in the
worst cases, more than six in 10 children live in poverty.
</P>
<P>
   Convened once every six years by the Southern Growth Policies
Board of Research Triangle Park, N.C., the commission is a
blue-ribbon panel of governors and other leaders from 14 states and
Puerto Rico.
</P>
<P>
   Since the 1970s, the meetings have served as a national
springboard for politicians, including two governors, Jimmy Carter
of Georgia and Bill Clinton of Arkansas, who became president.
</P>
<P>
   This week's meeting focused on the future, but also touched on
the legacy of slavery.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not only have we suffered because of the innate inhumanity of
that act, we (also have) suffered because of the war that it took
to eliminate it,'' Patton said. ``We have continued to suffer
because of the injustices that continue to permeate our society.''
</P>
<P>
   The remark surprised but encouraged Veronica Biggins, an Atlanta
executive recruiter and former Clinton staffer who serves on the
Future of the South Commission.
</P>
<P>
   She's pushing, she said, for the draft report to be amended to
reflect more strongly the region's growing diversity.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
