<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-15 20:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0381 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ASIA-MARKETPLACE-ART-     06-15 0897
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ASIA-MARKETPLACE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR SELLERS TO JAPANESE, WORSE AHEAD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Ga., N.Y.)   (ART ADV: Graphic will be sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204.)  
 (af)  
 By GRETCHEN MORGENSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As the Japanese yen continued its slide toward the abyss on
Monday, stock markets around the world trembled. So much for the
idea that Asian problems could be contained.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of many big multinational companies that do business in
Asia fell Monday on fears that declining sales there would hurt
profits. Minnesota Mining and Manufacturing, for example, lost 6.7
percent of its value. IBM was down 3.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But share prices of some companies with large exposures to
Japan's incredible shrinking economy do not yet reflect the dark
reality of what is happening there. Yes, these companies' shares
have fallen, but they are likely to fall further in coming weeks as
the bleak news sinks in.
</P>
<P>
   Businesses with big Japanese exposure range from Tiffany &AMP; Co.,
the elite New York-based jeweler that produces 27 percent of its
sales in Japan, to the discount retailer Toys ``R'' Us, which has
111 stores _ one-tenth of its worldwide total _ in the Pacific Rim.
The company has 64 stores in Japan alone.
</P>
<P>
   Other players in Japan include Aflac Inc., a life insurance
concern based in Columbus, Ga., which generates 60 percent of its
earnings in Japan. Particularly hard hit is Nu Skin, a marketer of
personal-care and nutrition products that gets 70 percent of its
revenue from Japanese operations.
</P>
<P>
   Cosmetics makers are also vulnerable: Estee Lauder generated 13
percent of its operating income from the region; 16 percent of Avon
Products' sales and 10 percent of its pretax income come from the
Pacific Rim.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Japan is the largest market for Gucci, the
luxury-goods retailer. And LVMH, the Parisian purveyor of
high-class perfume, luggage, Champagne and Cognac, reported that
sales fell 30 percent through May at its duty-free goods unit as
Japanese customers cut back on travel.
</P>
<P>
   The setback in Japan is a paradox for the American companies
that battled for years to penetrate the country's relatively closed
consumer society. Because Japan was willing to open its borders
only to some, not all foreign companies, it may not be immediately
obvious to investors which companies will be hurt most by problems
there now. The companies that never broke through Japan's barriers
can now count their blessings.
</P>
<P>
   The damage is not limited to companies that do business in
Japan. The entire Pacific Rim looks like poison. The yen is
dragging down currencies elsewhere in Asia, in places like South
Korea, Indonesia and Hong Kong, as it falls in value.
</P>
<P>
   Companies with significant operations in Japan and elsewhere in
the Pacific Rim are reeling from a double punch. First, sales of
goods made overseas generally decline when a nation's local
currency is in a free fall; that's because the currency's lower
value makes foreign goods more expensive there than they once were.
</P>
<P>
   The second punch comes when these companies repatriate earnings
made in a country whose currency is weak to one with a strong
currency _ in this case, the dollar. Although these companies try
to hedge their currency risks, almost no one had predicted that the
yen _ down 8.5 percent against the dollar since May 15 _ would drop
so steeply.
</P>
<P>
   Many company managers with exposure overseas say they will make
up any shortfall there by stepping up operations elsewhere. For
example, Bernard Arnault, chairman of LVMH, told the French
business weekly Le Journal des Finances, that the company would
expand in the United States to offset slowing sales in Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe so. But it takes a long time to build businesses. Any
increases that LVMH and other companies hope to generate from new
or expanded markets will not be evident for several quarters. Sales
declines, on the other hand, can happen overnight, especially in a
country whose currency _ the yen in this case _ has fallen almost 4
percent in the last week alone.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street analysts remain mostly sanguine about these
companies' prospects. That's no surprise, given how hard it is for
executives to dispense bad news. And many analysts, perhaps waiting
for the yen to stabilize, have not updated their estimates to take
into account the its recent tailspin.
</P>
<P>
   Arnault of LVMH, for example, at last week's shareholder
meeting, said it remained his objective for the company to report a
profit rise in 1998. But his hopes are pinned on a yen value of 130
to the dollar, not the current 146.
</P>
<P>
   Another reason these shares have not crumbled further: Investors
may think Japan's problems are temporary _ a dangerous view. Craig
Chudler, Japanese market strategist at Salomon Smith Barney,
expects the gross domestic product in Japan to contract 1.5 percent
this year, more than double last year's decline of 0.7 of 1
percent. Continued weakness in Japan's stock market, down 1.3
percent Monday, will make consumers there even more likely to cut
back on discretionary spending.
</P>
<P>
   With some of these stocks down, they may look cheap. But with
few willing to predict how low the yen can sink, and with the
Japanese government doing little to address its problems, this is
no time for bottom-fishing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
