<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRODERBUND-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>


</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service)   Broderbund To Put Itself Up for Sale  
   
 By Julia Angwin  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
Broderbund, the struggling Novato software-maker, tacitly
acknowledged yesterday that it is for sale.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rumors about an acquisition of Broderbund have been swirling for
months and were confirmed yesterday when Broderbund said it had
hired investment banking firm Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette to
``explore strategic alternatives.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's usually a euphemism for being up for sale,'' said
Stephen Dube, an analyst at Wasserstein Perella Securities in New
York. ``The company has been for sale for a while _ this is just a
public admission of that fact.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Broderbund announced it would not meet Wall
Street's expectations for third-quarter sales. The news drove the
price of Broderbund shares down $2.81 to $17.38.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts were expecting Broderbund to earn 1 cent per share, or
about $200,000 in the third quarter. Instead, the company said it
will likely lose 12 to 15 cents per share, or $2.5 million to $3.3
million.
</P>
<P>
   Broderbund blames its third-quarter woes on a large number of
returns and the need to match competitors rebates _ some rivals
were offering customers rebates on the entire price of a software
package.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; This is the latest setback for Broderbund, which is the last
well-known independent maker of entertainment software. The company
is known for high-quality titles such as Myst and Where in the
World is Carmen Sandiego? but has been suffering from price wars
and consolidation in the entertainment software market.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Broderbund lost $13 million on sales of $190 million in 1997,
after two years of earning $36 million on similar sales of between
$170 to $180 million. The company laid off 7 percent of its
workforce in March.
</P>
<P>
   Some analyst say the company's problems may stem from bad
management _ particularly Broderbund chief executive Joe Durrett,
who continues to live in Connecticut while running the California
company.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a company that five years ago was far and away the top
dog in this industry and it's been allowed to deteriorate,'' said
David Farina, analyst at William Blair &AMP; Co. in Chicago
</P>
<P>
   Broderbund officials did not return calls seeking comment.
</P>
<P>
   The rumors about Broderbund being for sale began two weeks ago
when Computer Retail Week reported that the interactive division of
toymaker Hasbro, based in Pawtucket, R.I., was considering buying
Broderbund.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, possible buyers cited have included Electronic Arts,
a San Mateo game-maker; The Learning Company, a Boston-based
educational software rival; and GT Interactive Software, a New York
software conglomerate.
</P>
<P>
   By aligning with one of these giants, analysts say Broderbund
would have more leverage to convince retailers to stock its
software and could better withstand price competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Broderbund has really good brands _ they just aren't being
managed well enough,'' said Aaron Ricadela, associate editor at
Computer Retail Week in Jericho, NY.
</P>
<P>
   ``Analysts think that other companies, such as Hasbro
Interactive, would be a lot better at managing the assets that
Broderbund has been fumbling recently,'' Ricadela said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
