u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-STARR-730&AMP;ADD     06-15 0860
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-STARR-730&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARR RENEWS HIS CRITICISM OF MAGAZINE ARTICLE ABOUT LEAKS 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By STEVEN A. HOLMES   
 c. 1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Kenneth Starr renewed his attacks Monday on a
magazine article that said he and at least one subordinate had
improperly disclosed to reporters sensitive information about his
investigation of President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   In his second statement about the matter in three days, Starr
challenged the accuracy of the article, by the veteran journalist
Steven Brill, saying it ``created a serious misimpression of the
operation and policy'' of the independent counsel's office.
</P>
<P>
   Brill wrote in his new magazine, Brill's Content, that Starr and
one of his deputies, Jackie Bennett, had given reporters
information _ including accounts by witnesses who were to appear
before a grand jury _ regarding the investigation into whether
Clinton had engaged in a sexual relationship with Monica Lewinsky,
a former White House intern, and then encouraged her to lie about
it under oath.
</P>
<P>
   In his first statement, on Saturday evening, Starr challenged
Brill's conclusions but did not take issue with any of the
article's facts. He insisted that disclosures from his office were
neither illegal, since they did not involve testimony before a
grand jury, nor a violation of ethics rules barring leaks of
``substantive'' information about a prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   The statement Starr issued on Monday said his office ``does not
release grand jury material either directly or indirectly, on the
record or off the record.'' The statement went on to say that his
office ``does not release (and has never released) information
provided by witnesses during witness interviews, except as
authorized by law.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Brill's statements to the contrary,'' Starr continued,
``are false.''
</P>
<P>
   Starr did acknowledge that his office had released information
concerning its initial interview with Ms. Lewinsky. But he said
this information concerned merely the ``circumstances'' and not the
substance of that encounter and had been meant to rebut inaccurate
information about prosecutors' conduct at the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our limited disclosure,'' he said, ``was entirely appropriate
and dictated by Department of Justice policy to counter a serious,
yet unfounded, allegation of misconduct _ namely that Ms. Lewinsky
was illegally detained and coerced during the interview.''
</P>
<P>
   In January, William Ginsburg, who was then Ms. Lewinsky's
lawyer, charged that Starr had lured her to a hotel in Virginia
and, ``with the help of four or five FBI agents and three or four
U.S. attorneys, managed to detain her _ although she was
technically free to go _ for eight or nine hours without an
attorney.''
</P>
<P>
   In response, Starr's office gave at least one reporter, Susan
Schmidt of The Washington Post, a detailed account of the
circumstances that day. That account, in Ms. Schmidt's words,
depicted Starr's conduct ``as far less hostile.''
</P>
<P>
   Starr's statement on Monday appeared to be an effort to quiet a
chorus of criticism, most of it from Clinton's supporters, that has
been spawned by the article in Brill's Content. Still, while his
statement said his disclosures were ``authorized by law'' or
``dictated by Department of Justice Policy,'' it did not specify
what he regarded as the relevant statute or policy guideline.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Rules of Criminal Procedure make it a crime for
anyone, including ``an attorney for the government,'' to disclose
events occurring before a grand jury. In May, the U.S. Circuit
Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia said that rule also
includes the release of ``matters which will occur'' before the
grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   In his article, Brill quoted Starr as saying that providing
information to reporters would not violate federal law if the
material was merely statements that witnesses made to federal
agents before testifying before the grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   Starr's office did not respond to several messages on Monday
seeking further elaboration on his written statement.
</P>
<P>
   Other than referring to Ms. Schmidt's article, Starr's statement
does not specifically address other allegations made by Brill that
Starr had leaked sensitive information to reporters. Among the
reporters that Brill said Starr and his lieutenant had briefed _ an
allegation Starr had confirmed in the Brill article _ were Michael
Isikoff of Newsweek and Jackie Judd of ABC News.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In other developments on Monday, the White House filed a brief
asking a federal appeals court to sharply limit the the questioning
of a deputy counsel, Bruce Lindsey, by investigators. A federal
district court ruled last month that Clinton's claim of
attorney-client privilege could not shield Lindsey, one of the
president's closest aides, from grand jury questioning.
</P>
<P>
   The White House is seeking to reverse that decision. Lindsey's
discussions with several important witnesses, including Vernon
Jordan, is of particular interest to the investigators, according
to a sealed opinion by the Federal District judge in the case,
Norma Holloway Johnson.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
