<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOSNIA-NATO-RUSSIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIA SCOLDS U.S. GENERAL OVER NATO AIR EXERCISES 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By MICHAEL R. GORDON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ In a blunt dressing down, Russia's defense minister
told the top United States military commander Monday that Moscow
had been misled over the timing of NATO's air exercises in the
Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   The criticism underscored the differences between Russia and the
Western alliance on the eve of a critical meeting here between
President Boris Yeltsin and Slobodan Milosevic, the Yugoslav
president.
</P>
<P>
   Defense Minister Igor Sergeyev made the complaint at his meeting
with Gen. Henry Shelton, the chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff.
</P>
<P>
   Shelton sought to play down the dispute, saying both sides
shared the goal of bringing peace to Kosovo. Still, the
disagreement pointed to the underlying tensions over the province.
</P>
<P>
   As a traditional ally of the Serbs, Russia has been more
sympathetic to Belgrade's position. And as a nation with its own
share of ethnic conflicts, Russia does not want to legitimize the
principle that outside powers can intervene on humanitarian and
security grounds.
</P>
<P>
   Shelton outlined the differences to reporters on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel that Milosevic needs to move out first,'' the general
said, ``because he is the one that we have seen use excessive force
in Kosovo. We have concerns about the techniques that are being
used to put down, to squelch the uprising.''
</P>
<P>
   The Russian position, he said, is that ``Milosevic has the right
to use whatever force he needs to put them down.''
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone call Monday, President Clinton urged Yeltsin to
take a firm stand with Milosevic. Specifically, Washington wants
the Russian president to stick to the points hammered out last
Friday by Western foreign ministers and the Russian foreign
minister, Yevgeny Primakov.
</P>
<P>
   They include stopping the Serbian crackdown against ethnic
Albanian civilians, allowing the return of refugees and
establishing a dialogue between the Serbian authorities and the
ethnic Albanians in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The American hope is that if Yeltsin fails to win concessions
from Milosevic, he will support a U.N. Security Council resolution
authorizing military action against Serbia. But with Russians
publicly criticizing NATO's show of force, it is unclear whether
Yeltsin's meeting will resolve or deepen rifts within international
ranks.
</P>
<P>
   Sergeyev's comments Monday did little to fortify the impression
that Moscow was prepared to take a tough stand. In the post-Cold
War era, Russian military relations with the United States are
businesslike.
</P>
<P>
   But Sergeyev has shown a penchant for using his American
visitors as props in his protests against American foreign policy.
Earlier this year, Sergeyev began a meeting with Defense Secretary
William Cohen with a denunciation of American policy toward Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's meeting between Sergeyev and Shelton began much the
same way. The American military chief arrived in Moscow for
previously scheduled talks with Sergeyev and Gen. Anatoly Kvashnin,
chief of the Russian general staff. At the start of the meeting,
Sergeyev expressed surprise that the aerial exercises had begun so
soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am a soldier, and I value honesty in people most of all,''
Sergeyev said. ``I do not understand why they did this to me.''
</P>
<P>
   American officials insisted that there had been no intention to
mislead him. They say Cohen informed Sergeyev on Friday that there
would be aerial exercises and that NATO had contingency plans for
military strikes.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the NATO meeting in Brussels last week, there was
discussion of an exercise,'' Shelton said. ``I believe Marshal
Sergeyev left earlier on Friday, and it was only after that time
that the exercise firmed up so that it would take place as rapidly
as it did.''
</P>
<P>
   Sergeyev's outburst may have been intended to dispel the
impression that the timing of the exercises was coordinated with
the Kremlin to put pressure on Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   Shelton indicated that the United States would not take part in
any immediate air strikes against Serbia, adding that Congress
would have to be consulted.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are still some way from military action being taken,'' he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
