<HEADER>
A0398 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YEN-DOLLAR-NYT &LR;      06-15 1171
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YEN-DOLLAR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: AS JAPAN GOES, SO GOES THE NEIGHBORHOOD 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By DAVID E. SANGER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ For the last 10 months the Clinton administration
has warned that a full-blown recession in Japan could prove the
time bomb of the Asian crisis, setting off a sharp fall of the yen
and, in turn, a second wave of the economic contagion that is
spreading to investors around the globe.
</P>
<P>
   Now that appears to be what is happening. But President
Clinton's economic advisers, weary of jawboning their Japanese
counterparts, say the United States has very little leverage
remaining over Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, in internal White House arguments in recent days, some
of Clinton's advisers have argued that Japan's hidden strategy is
to let the country's currency fall _ making Japanese goods less
expensive in the United States _ even if the fall undermines other
countries in Asia that are struggling to emerge from a yearlong
nightmare, or worsens troubles in Russia and Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the yen's tumble is acting as something of a double
brake on other economies around the world. Japan's recession is
making it nearly impossible for other Asian nations (to say nothing
of American carmakers and other manufacturers) to export more goods
into Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, as the yen falls Japanese goods push out products
that other ailing Asian nations are trying to export to the United
States and Europe, particularly Korean cars, steel and
semiconductors.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is happening in Japan is hitting all of its neighbors _
Korea, Thailand _ and it is triggering a huge amount of instability
around the world,'' Charlene Barshefsky, the U.S. trade
representative, said in an interview Monday.
</P>
<P>
   But when asked what the United States could do, Barshefsky, a
veteran of five years of trade wars with Japan that have yielded
modest changes but not the sweeping economic deregulation that
Clinton once championed so publicly, offered little new.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to keep putting pressure on them, both bilaterally and
through our allies,'' she said. At the same time she conceded that
the threat the United States has occasionally wielded in trade
disputes _ closing the American market to cars or computer chips,
for example _ would probably only accentuate Japan's troubles if
used to compel Tokyo to speed up economic reforms.
</P>
<P>
   In private, administration officials have long referred to Japan
as ``the last firewall'' of the Asian crisis, and contended that if
that wall were breached, it was only a matter of time before Asia's
troubles lept the Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   It is an unproven thesis _ many said Korea was the firewall
during the depths of the first wave of Asian economic trouble in
December _ but clearly investors harbor the same worry. The
evidence came Monday on Wall Street, when last week's sell-off
accelerated into a 207.01-point drop in the Dow industrials,
prompted largely by news that the dollar had touched an eight-year
high against the yen.
</P>
<P>
   All of this is bound to complicate Clinton's first trip to
China, which begins next week.
</P>
<P>
   At the insistence of the Chinese, he is making no stopover in
Japan, America's strongest military ally in Asia. That deprives him
of a natural chance to drive home to a Japanese public _ one highly
critical of its own leadership _ America's prescription: rapid
deregulation and a bailout of Japan's banks modeled on the handling
of the U.S. savings and loan crisis in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Clinton is facing accusations from the Chinese
that the United States and Japan are engaged in an economic
conspiracy to let the yen fall, creating further troubles in the
rest of Asia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why are Japan and the United States letting the yen slide?''
China's state-run daily, The Financial News, which is controlled by
China's central bank, asked Monday morning. ``Mainly because a
falling yen suits the two countries' economic interests now, and is
beneficial in passing on their domestic economic problems to other
countries,'' the paper concluded.
</P>
<P>
   That commentary underscores an oft-expressed view in Asia these
days: That the United States is not unhappy with Asia in crisis,
especially as the American economy keeps charging along.
</P>
<P>
   China has long worried about American efforts to ``contain'' its
power, both military and economic. The falling yen and rising
dollar, in the view of some nationalists, are means to this end.
The currencies' shifts benefit the Japanese by making their exports
far more competitive against their rivals.
</P>
<P>
   And a strong dollar benefits American companies by making it
possible for them to snap up assets across Asia _ companies,
factories, banks _ at firesale prices. One of Asia's most voluble
nationalists, Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad of Malaysia, warned
recently that foreign investors who bought up Asian assets were
risking a huge political backlash.
</P>
<P>
   The opposite view _ that the Asian crisis poses a rising threat
to the United States _ is voiced almost daily nowadays by Treasury
Secretary Robert Rubin, even though he may have, intentionally or
not, accelerated the recent run on the yen.
</P>
<P>
   Time and again Rubin, who once supervised currency trading at
Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co., has repeated that the only way to strengthen
the yen is for Japan to enact the economic and market reforms the
United States has long advocated.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over time, currencies follow fundamentals,'' he told Congress
last week. He has repeatedly infuriated Japanese officials by
refusing to threaten imminent intervention in the currency markets,
and he has not backed away from his mantra that ``a strong dollar
is in the interest of the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Investors have interpreted those comments as a license to sell
the yen, without fear that the United States would join Japan in an
effort to bolster the yen. They are probably reading him correctly.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Japanese wasted $20 billion last month trying to intervene
to keep the yen in the 130s,'' one senior administration official
noted recently. ``Bob knows that running against the markets only
delays the fall of a currency, it can't stop it. So he wants to
pick his moment.''
</P>
<P>
   That is a fine strategy as long as the Japanese really fear the
effects of a devalued yen.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin still believes they do. He argues that although Japanese
businesses want a weak currency so that they can increase exports,
Japanese authorities are fearful that a weak yen could topple
Japanese banks that are struggling to remain solvent.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the administration, though, some officials have begun to
question whether Rubin has read the Japanese correctly.
</P>
<P>
   In meetings last week and phone conversations over the weekend,
they have begun to argue that Japanese authorities now realize they
can no longer prop up the yen _ so they might as well just let it
fall, and hope that exports will surge.
</P>
<P>
   The fate of many of Asia's economies may hinge on who is
correctly divining Japan's intentions. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
