<SLUG> BC-DOWDOW16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Asian economic troubles will hurt U.S., strategist warns
 &HT;    By Tom Walker
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The stock market tumble that opened the week is expected to
continue today on fear that Asia's economic problems will hurt U.S.
corporate profits.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not going to be pleasant (this morning),'' Al Goldman,
chief market strategist at A.G. Edwards &AMP; Sons, told Dow Jones News
Service. He added, however, that the Dow is now ``deeply
oversold,'' and may be poised for an eventual move higher.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's fall in fact gave the Dow Jones industrial average its
fifth worst one-day point loss ever. The benchmark index of 30 blue
chip stocks dropped 207.01 points, or 2.3 percent, falling below
the psychologically important 8,700 level to close at 8,627.93.
</P>
<P>
   It was the Dow's worst day since Jan. 9, and the market's
broadest decline since April 27. Broader and secondary market
averages fell just shy of 2 percent each.
</P>
<P>
   The fall Monday was compounded by the fact that investors who
might normally be seeking bargains stayed out of the market with an
eye toward Asia, Dow Jones suggested.
</P>
<P>
   The underlying problem is the year-old Asian economic malaise.
Already, corporate profits in the United States have declined in
the fourth quarter of 1997 and first quarter of 1998. And while
many analysts have anticipated a rise in second-half profits of
more than 10 percent for Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 companies, the
concern now is that Asia's continuing crisis may reduce that
increase.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
