<SLUG> BC-MCI-INTERNET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCI OFFERS TO SELL MORE INTERNET UNITS
</HEADLINE>
   (ja) 
 By SETH SCHIESEL    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Continuing to try to win regulatory approval of its $37 billion
acquisition by Worldcom Inc., MCI Communications Corp. has offered
to sell additional components of its Internet business, people
close to the negotiations between MCI and regulators said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear how precise MCI had been in its offer, but the
people close to the discussions said MCI had offered to sell parts
of its Internet business that were not included in the $625 million
deal that MCI struck with Cable and Wireless PLC last month.
</P>
<P>
   Both the Justice Department and antitrust regulators from the
European Union are weighing Worldcom's planned takeover of MCI,
which was announced last fall. The regulators are concerned that
the combined MCI-Worldcom could wield dominant power in the
Internet industry.
</P>
<P>
   MCI, the nation's No. 2 long-distance telephone company, is also
one of the country's largest Internet carriers. Worldcom's Uunet
operation is the world's biggest Internet service provider.
</P>
<P>
   MCI made a big gamble last month when it announced a deal to
sell to Cable and Wireless the wholesale part of MCI's Internet
business, but not the units that provide data services directly to
consumers and big business customers. Before the deal was made
public, MCI tried to win assurances from regulators that the Cable
and Wireless arrangement would be sufficient to allay antitrust
concerns about MCI-Worldcom, but the regulators refused to sign off
on either deal.
</P>
<P>
   In the apparent hope that it could present the regulators with a
fait accompli, MCI went ahead and announced the Cable and Wireless
deal anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``By divesting MCI's Internet backbone, we have eliminated any
overlap with Worldcom's Internet business,'' the chairman of MCI,
Bert Roberts Jr., said at the time. ``We have formed an agreement
that addresses antitrust concerns with the MCI-Worldcom merger.''
</P>
<P>
   The regulators did not agree. Karel van Miert, the European
Union's competition commissioner, has made no secret of his
intention to oppose MCI's deal with Worldcom unless the companies
sell additional Internet assets.
</P>
<P>
   The European Union has said it may not make a formal decision on
the MCI-Worldcom merger until July 15. But an influential advisory
committee is scheduled to meet on Friday and Van Miert will make a
recommendation to the committee before then.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department has not set a formal time table for its
deliberation, but the department is working closely with the
European officials.
</P>
<P>
   The regulators hold significant bargaining power in their
negotiations with MCI and Worldcom, especially with Worldcom. If
the MCI-Worldcom deal does not win all of the necessary regulatory
approvals by the end of the year, MCI can demand $1.6 billion in
cash from Worldcom along with the right to walk away from the deal.
</P>
<P>
   It is clear that the MCI-Worldcom merger would sail through the
regulatory reviews were Worldcom to agree to sell Uunet. But
Worldcom is not willing to do that. John Sidgmore, who runs Uunet,
is Worldcom's vice chairman and it is likely that Worldcom would
rather see the MCI deal die than sell Uunet.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves MCI and Cable and Wireless in an odd position. Cable
and Wireless recently sued MCI for the right of first refusal to
any additional Internet assets that MCI might sell. That suit was
rejected in court last week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-15-98 2101EDT &QL; 
