A0409 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUSCHWITZ-SYNAGOGUE-3     06-15 0675
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUSCHWITZ-SYNAGOGUE-375&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER SYNAGOGUE NEAR AUSCHWITZ TO BECOME RELIGIOUS, CULTURAL
CENTER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Calif., Israel, Germany, Poland)  (th) 
 By NADINE BROZAN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Until the Nazis marched in, the Polish town of Oswiecim, which
was named Auschwitz by the Germans, had 12 synagogues. All but one
were destroyed by the Nazis as they built the concentration camps
of Auschwitz and Birkenau. Somehow, one small house of worship
remained standing, and after the war it was converted into a carpet
warehouse.
</P>
<P>
   In March, the building, the former Lomdei Mishnayot Synagogue,
became the first property to be returned to the Polish Jewish
community under a government restitution program. But there was
only one Jew out of the prewar population of 7,000 still living in
Oswiecim, so the synagogue was passed on to Jews in nearby
Bielsko-Biala.
</P>
<P>
   In New York on Monday, flanked by congressmen and Holocaust
survivors, Fred Schwartz, a philanthropist once known as ``Fred the
Furrier,'' announced that the Auschwitz Jewish Center Foundation,
which he established in 1995, had taken title to the building and
an adjoining house.
</P>
<P>
   He plans to transform them into a Jewish religious and cultural
center where visitors to the camps will have a place to reflect and
say Kaddish, the prayer of mourning. It will also serve as a center
to teach about the Holocaust and the vibrant Jewish community that
flourished in Oswiecim from 1250 until the Nazis came. The
renovation is expected to cost $5 million to $10 million.
</P>
<P>
   Schwartz had no direct links to the camps, but when he visited
Auschwitz in 1993, ``it was as if I had had an epiphany,'' he said
at a news conference. ``The camps were a vacant environment of
namelessness, facelessness,'' he said. ``I felt that until we can
attach human characteristics to the people who perished there, we
won't understand the horror.''
</P>
<P>
   With his wife, Allyne, he began exploring ways to do that, and
learned of the synagogue.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is critical to underscore that, however correct Elie Wiesel
may be in reminding us to bear witness, Auschwitz is more than past
history and memory,'' said Rep. Tom Lantos, D-Calif., the only
Holocaust survivor in Congress. ``It is also a place of the present
and the future. Its importance is not only to pay tribute to
martyrs but to make a connection between the internments of the
past, the dangers of the present and the hopes of the future.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   For Hirsch Kornreich, a Bobover Hasidic Jew and retired real
estate broker from Brooklyn, who spoke along with Ascher Scharf,
another survivor, the memories are overwhelming.
</P>
<P>
   Kornreich, 69, was born in the house that is to be renovated,
which was home to his family for 150 years. His voice breaking, he
pointed to a photo of the building and showed the windows of the
room where his parents and grandparents were married, where he was
circumcised.
</P>
<P>
   ``The synagogue was where my parents prayed, where my bar
mitzvah took place,'' he said, pointing to it. ``The bar mitzvah
marked the last of my freedom. One day shortly after that I was
kidnapped by the SS and taken to a labor camp. There, on May 12,
1942, I was told that my entire family, 144 people, was deported to
a death camp, one of the first families to be burned there. I
didn't even have the privilege of saying Kaddish for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Describing the experience before an audience was unbearably
painful, he said, explaining: ``I had pictures of my mother, my
father, of my cousins playing there, flashing in my mind. The whole
picture of the past came in front of me.''
</P>
<P>
   Now Kornreich, who returned to the house only once, in 1993, is
looking forward to its rededication, probably in two or three
years. He will take his wife, five children and 40 grandchildren
and great-grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will stand in front of my house and my synagogue and I will
know that the people of Israel will live forever,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
