<SLUG> BC-GLF-U.S.-OPEN-525(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. OPEN REMAINS LEHMAN'S FAVORITE TOURNAMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ja) 
 By CLIFTON BROWN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A few days after last year's U.S. Open, Tom Lehman recalls, he
went to a driving range and angrily hit golf balls as hard as he
could for several hours. Who could blame him? For the third
consecutive year, Lehman had held or shared the lead after three
rounds of the Open, yet he failed to win it. In 1995, he finished
third. In 1996, he finished tied for second. And last year, Lehman
was third again.
</P>
<P>
   Change a shot here, or a bad bounce there, and Lehman could very
well have at least one Open title, maybe more. Instead, he is still
trying to win his first; it is the tournament he wants the most,
and the tournament that has dealt him the most heartache.
</P>
<P>
   Will Lehman carry an extra burden this week, haunted by too many
bad memories and two many missed opportunities? Lehman doesn't
think so. He still loves the Open, even if it doesn't always love
him back. In fact, he smiled when asked to describe how he feels
about this year's Open, which begins Thursday at The Olympic Club
in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has always been my favorite tournament, ever since I saw
Tom Watson chip in at Pebble Beach to win back in 1982,'' Lehman
said. ``I was just out of college back then, and it was very
exciting. I was at the point in my life where my dream of being a
professional golfer was actually on the verge of becoming reality.
I said to myself, `That's the one I want.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I still want it. At my age, 39, you're still at a time of your
career when you have a lot of prime years left. I can't say I'm
due, because golf doesn't owe you anything. But if I keep knocking
on the door, I think I'll get one.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, Lehman has the accurate tee-to-green game suited for
the tournament this week. And he will not lose because of a lack of
preparation. During last Friday's heavy afternoon rain at the
Westchester Country Club, a solitary figure stood on the putting
green, hitting putt after putt, ignoring the rain. It was Lehman.
</P>
<P>
   Dedication like that lifted Lehman from mini-tours 10 years ago
to the top of his profession today. Ask Lehman about the lean
years, 1986 through 1991, when he lost his PGA Tour card, and he
will tell you about taking showers in the rain because he couldn't
afford a motel, or emptying his bank account to play in a
tournament in South Africa. Lehman knows hard times, and though he
is financially secure now, he has not forgotten hard work.
</P>
<P>
   His ability to persevere makes Lehman confident that if he
contends again this weekend, he will not fold under the pressure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I've asked myself if I'm lacking something to win the
U.S. Open,'' said Lehman, a strange admission for someone who has
already won a major, the 1996 British Open. ``This is the answer I
came away with: I'm not lacking anything. I'm good enough. I'm
mentally tough enough. I just have to do it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've played well at the Open, but I've made some mistakes the
last nine holes when victory was in sight. I got too aggressive. If
I was so nervous I couldn't breathe, couldn't get the club back,
then I'd be worried. But it's a lot easier to be more patient than
it is to correct choking your guts out.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Lehman was encouraged by his third-place finish at the 1995 U.S.
Open at Shinnecock Hills. But the last two years have been more
difficult for him to take. In 1996 at Oakland Hills, Lehman made
the turn for the back nine Sunday with a three-stroke lead. But he
bogeyed Nos. 10 and 12, then made a crucial final bogey at No. 18,
which opened the door for Steve Jones to win by one stroke. Lehman
got a bad break on his tee shot on that final hole when it landed
in the fairway, but kicked hard left into a bunker. He was forced
to pitch out instead of going for the green on his next shot. After
his third shot landed 15 feet from the pin, he missed the putt.
Jones made a steady pressure-packed par, and Lehman was denied
again.
</P>
<P>
   Last year at Congressional Country Club was even more
frustrating. Tied for the lead as he reached No. 16 on Sunday,
Lehman was too aggressive. He aimed for the pin instead of the fat
part of the green and made bogey. Then, on his second shot at the
17th, Lehman hit a 7-iron into the water next to the green, and his
hope for winning sank with his ball. Ernie Els collected his second
U.S. Open title. Lehman collected more condolences.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was painful,'' said Lehman, who stared in disbelief for
several agonizing moments after he saw his ball disappear into the
water. ``I was in perfect position to win that tournament, tied for
the lead with three holes to play, and sitting in the middle of the
fairway at 16. Making bogey at 16, that's where I'm talking about
getting too aggressive. The pin was way back right and if I had
just taken it 20 feet left of the hole, maybe I still could have
won. But by going right at the flag, and missing it just a hair to
the right, then I was dead.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was tough. It felt like I should have won that one.''
</P>
<P>
   After that, Lehman's disappointment showed in his game. Though
he won the European PGA Tour Loch Lomond tournament last July, he
has not won on the PGA Tour since the 1996 Tour Championship.
Lehman was the 1996 PGA Tour Player of the Year, winning his first
major, more than $1.7 million in earnings, and firmly establishing
himself as one of the world's best. But Lehman's earning fell to a
bit more than $960,000 last year, and he has been fighting a flaw
in his swing for a month that has sent many of his iron shots
hooking left.
</P>
<P>
   Part of Lehman's difficulty swinging was also caused by losing
about 30 pounds since last year, which slightly threw off his
timing and balance. Life can be cruel sometimes. While Lehman
looked and felt better, he was playing worse. Yet, he has been more
consistent the past month, and what better time would there be for
Lehman to end a victory drought than this week?
</P>
<P>
   Whoever wins the Open this year will have to handle one of
golf's most difficult challenges. Under normal circumstances,
Olympic is a severe test. But set to U.S. Golf Association
standards, with thick, 5-inch deep rough, the course will be
particularly brutal.
</P>
<P>
   On a scorecard, the Lake Course at Olympic does not look
particularly challenging, measuring 6,797 yards, with only one
fairway bunker and no water hazards. What makes the layout so
tough? The greens are among the smallest in tournament golf.
Precision is more important than power at Olympic, forcing long
hitters to put their drivers away on most holes. It will be
essential for players to drive the ball accurately, yet keeping the
ball in the fairways will be even more difficult because the
fairways are sloping, sometimes pushing tee shots toward the rough.
</P>
<P>
   But Lehman has proved at previous opens that he is methodical
and poised enough not to be fazed when birdies are hard to come by.
So while much of the focus this week will be on other golfers like
Els, Tiger Woods, Justin Leonard, David Duval, Colin Montgomerie,
Casey Martin and Fred Couples, Lehman is looking forward to another
chance. Let others grab the headlines during the week. Lehman
simply wants the trophy on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the pressure is off a little bit because the focus of
golf has gotten so much on the younger players,'' Lehman said.
``The expectation level is on me isn't as high, but my expectations
are still the same. If I'm playing well, there's no reason I can't
be in position to win.''
</P>
</TEXT>
