<HEADLINE>
COMPANY NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DOW JONES TO INVEST $232 MILLION IN WALL STREET JOURNAL
</P>
<P>
   Dow Jones &AMP; Co. said Monday that it would invest $232 million in
The Wall Street Journal to expand pages and color capacity. In a
speech Monday to securities analysts, the chief executive of Dow
Jones, Peter Kann, said the program would allow The Wall Street
Journal to expand its daily pages to 96 pages, from 80 pages, and
that it would be capable of increasing the number of color pages of
advertising to 24 pages, from eight pages. He said the new capacity
would be fully in place by 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Wandel &AMP; Goltermann Management Holding GmbH, Germany, has
reached an agreement with Wavetek Corp., San Diego, Calif., to
merge, combining the two makers of electronic communications
equipment. The purchase price was not disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   Seagram Co., Montreal, said it would invest $90 million to take
a majority stake in its South Korean whisky joint venture with
Doosan Group, raising its share to 78 percent from 50 percent. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
