<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-BULLS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SIX-TIME CHAMPIONS FACE UNCERTAIN FUTURE 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By MIKE WISE    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALT LAKE CITY _ It will take lots of money and a huge dose of
humility. But mostly, the greatest basketball player ever will have
to decide whether to pack it in after another game for the ages or
come back because he is the only person who can top Michael Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   Keeping America's sports dynasty intact will not be easy, but
Jordan and the Chicago Bulls made perhaps the best argument of all
not to go their own ways Sunday night by securing their third
consecutive National Basketball Association title and sixth in the
last eight years.
</P>
<P>
   They returned to Chicago as champions again but in much the same
way they left the devastated Delta Center _ in suspended animation,
no one sure about his immediate future.
</P>
<P>
   Several factors weigh heavily into whether the owner, Jerry
Reinsdorf, and the general manager, Jerry Krause, decide to rebuild
rather than reload. Among the issues they face are these:
</P>
<P>
   _ Scottie Pippen's professed desire to play elsewhere as opposed
to securing a lucrative deal from Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   _ Coach Phil Jackson's professed desire to sit out a year and
weigh his options away from the game.
</P>
<P>
   _ Whether Jordan believes the franchise can genuinely compete
for a championship if he decides to play one more season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he definitely wants to play,'' Jordan's agent, David
Falk, said recently. ``He wants to play for a championship-caliber
team in Chicago. So I hope that they can create an atmosphere where
they're not going through transition.''
</P>
<P>
   Coaching vacancies notwithstanding, Jackson is said to be
leaning toward a sabbatical from the game. While Pippen's decision
may have the domino effect, the league's unsettled labor situation
could also play a pivotal part in whether the Bulls stay together.
</P>
<P>
   If, as expected, the owners lock out the players on July 1, it
will postpone all free-agent signings and trades until a new
collective bargaining agreement is signed by both sides. It will
give Jordan, Pippen, Dennis Rodman and their supporting cast more
time to consider their options.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless something absolutely unusual happens, I don't expect to
see us back here,'' Jackson said after Jordan shot down the Jazz in
the final seconds of an 87-86 victory on Sunday. ``And what a great
run it's been.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether he would consider retiring, Jordan declined to
give a definitive answer. ``You know, it's a gut feeling,'' he
said. ``It's just a feeling I have. When I walked away the first
time, it was a feeling. It wasn't something someone told me. When I
came back, it was a feeling. If and when that time comes, where
I've got to walk away, I hope that because I walked away no one
will look at me any less.''
</P>
<P>
   The impact of losing Jordan will be felt far and wide around the
league, from NBC's ratings to sellouts in visiting arenas. The
desire for him to play one more season grows with each game-winning
shot. Not that Jordan is letting that influence his decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, the economy may take a different turn,'' he said. ``But
I would advise you to invest wisely. And my life has to continue.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be a pretty big challenge,'' he said of returning.
``But the question is, do I want to do that or not, and that's the
thing that has to be debated over the summer. My answer is, there's
still a lot of unanswered questions.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Jordan has said that he will not play for a coach other
than Jackson, he seems to have softened his stance in the past few
weeks and has hitched his wagon more to Pippen's decision.
</P>
<P>
   Even without his All-Star teammate, however, Jordan could have a
team with championship potential. Toni Kukoc has developed into
enough of an offensive force to shoulder some of the scoring burden
in his move to small forward. If Krause could secure a capable
veteran in the free-agent market, Jordan might not see a severe
drop-off in talent.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, a major overhaul of the roster would probably
mean this current Chicago crop of players has indeed played
together for the last time.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson has reportedly cleared out his office. Steve Kerr,
another free agent, seemed to be of the opinion that the Bulls had
made their last run.
</P>
<P>
   With Jordan able to command in the neighborhood of $40 million a
season in salary, and with only so many dollars to go around, the
thinking is that Reinsdorf will spend only so much to pursue a
fourth straight championship _ a feat last accomplished by the
Boston Celtics, who won eight consecutive titles from 1959 to 1966.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reality is that we planned this as our last year,''
Jackson said. ``Right now, we're just celebrating it as our last
year. Unless something absolutely unusual comes out of left field,
I don't expect to see us back again.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
