<HEADER>
A0418 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COWBOYS-YOUNGER-COX     06-15 0594
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COWBOYS-YOUNGER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gailey working to make Cowboys younger
 &HT;    By Rick Cantu
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ When Chan Gailey inherited the Dallas Cowboys
four months ago, he found a team of graybeards whose best years
were behind them.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys were the NFL's third-oldest team last season. The
first-year coach is shedding some of the team's old geezers.
</P>
<P>
   Gailey's hit list includes a who's who of Cowboys legends.
</P>
<P>
   Safety Bill Bates, 37, and running back Herschel Walker, 36, are
unrestricted free agents who are not expected to be invited to
summer camp. Guard Nate Newton, 36, knowing his job was on the
line, dropped nearly 100 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback Wade Wilson, 39, and wideout Anthony Miller, 33,
already have been released. Tackle Mark Tuinei, 39, wants to make a
comeback but his chances are weaker than his surgically repaired
knees.
</P>
<P>
   The old and wise Cowboys still have enough talented players to
make a serious run at the playoffs, 31-year-old quarterback Troy
Aikman said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a tendency in the NFL, especially when you get past
30, for people to say you've lost a step,'' Aikman said. ``I still
feel that the guys who have can still be awfully productive.''
</P>
<P>
   Aikman's optimism coincides with the arrival of Gailey, a
no-nonsense coach who replaced Barry Switzer. The veteran
quarterback was so enthusiastic during last week's minicamp at
Valley Ranch, he said he wants to play though the 2003 season.
</P>
<P>
   Aikman won't make public digs against Switzer, but their
relationship was strained for several years. The energetic Gailey
is one reason Aikman believes the current core of veterans will win
again.
</P>
<P>
   ``The nucleus has been here a number of years, but you can look
at that in many ways,'' Aikman said. ``We're not to the point where
we can't be productive.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When guys get older, it doesn't mean they can't play,'' wide
receiver Michael Irvin said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't mean you can't play at the same level you used to
play at. Actually, sometimes when you get a little older, you get
better, you get wiser.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year the only teams older than the Cowboys were San
Francisco and Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas is making plans to upgrade its youth movement. For
starters, third- year pro Randall Godfrey is making a run at a new
position, middle linebacker. That spot has been filled by veteran
Fred Strickland for two years but Godfrey rotated at the position
in minicamp.
</P>
<P>
   Defensive coordinator Dave Campo said the Cowboys will use their
best three linebackers. That could turn out to be Godfrey, Dexter
Coakley and veteran Broderick Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   Rookie Greg Ellis is projected to start at defensive end.
Third-year pro Kavika Pittman, a disappointment in his first two
years in Dallas, is the likely starter on the other side.
</P>
<P>
   The future of 30-year-old defensive end Tony Tolbert remains in
question. He rested two bad knees during minicamp, an indication
his days as a major contributor might be over. Tolbert is scheduled
to count $3.4 million against the Cowboys' salary cap this season
but Gailey isn't ready to pull the trigger.
</P>
<P>
   When asked if Tolbert remains with the team, Gailey said,
``Today, you better believe it.''
</P>
<P>
   Other young players who are expected to compete on defense are
rookie lineman Michael Myers, rookie linebacker Darren Hambrick and
fifth-year defensive end Hurvin McCormack.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Cantu writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
