<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NORTEL-BAYNETWORKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORTEL TO BUY INTERNET EQUIPMENT MAKER FOR $9 BILLION  
 (ATTN.: CALIF., MASS.)
</HEADLINE>
   (ja) 
 By SETH SCHIESEL     
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Grasping for leadership in the market for Internet
communications equipment, Northern Telecom Ltd. of Canada, North
America's No. 2 maker of telephone gear, announced Monday that it
had agreed to acquire Bay Networks Inc., a leading data networking
company, for $9.1 billion in stock.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's deal was the largest in a recent series of mergers in
the telecommunications equipment and data networking sectors.
Companies that have thrived making equipment for traditional
telephone systems have been trying to jump into the fast-growing
market for gear that links computers at high speeds.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, small communications equipment makers and foreign
companies that have struggled to win business from big U.S.
communications carriers have looked to mergers as a way to enhance
their distribution networks.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, Alcatel Alsthom of France, one of the world's
biggest communications equipment makers, tried to bolster its
presence in the United States when it agreed to acquire DSC
Communications Corp. for $4.4 billion in stock. Earlier that week
Ciena Corp. agreed to be acquired by Tellabs Inc. for $7.1 billion
in stock.
</P>
<P>
   With Monday's announcement Northern Telecom made a bold, and
expensive, bid for a company with a culture that appears quite
different from its own and that has had difficulty in recent years
meeting the high expectations of Wall Street and industry experts.
</P>
<P>
   As a maker of equipment that routes information between
computers, Bay has had some difficulty contending with competition
from Cisco Systems Inc., which is three times Bay's size.
</P>
<P>
   Many analysts agreed that integrating Bay and Northern Telecom
successfully could pose a challenge but said the deal made sense in
light of the fundamental direction of the companies' industries.
</P>
<P>
   Networks based on Internet technology, known as IP, for Internet
protocol, are gaining in popularity over more traditional
circuit-switched networks. While traditional networks in essence
force different streams of information to stay within their own
digital lanes, networks based on Internet technology can perform
more efficiently by allowing packets of information to switch lanes
in search of faster paths to their destinations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time to design networks that are designed for IP and put
the voice over top of that, which is a huge change from the circuit
world of the past,'' John Roth, Northern Telecom's chief executive,
said in an interview. Referring to Bay's chairman, Roth added, ``In
talking to Dave House, we were looking to put some of their
technology in our products. Then we realized the fit was just
great.''
</P>
<P>
   But investors were not so sure of that Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Northern Telecom's shares fell by 15.2 percent after the deal
was announced, falling $9.6875, to $54 on the New York Stock
Exchange. Some institutional investors had told Northern Telecom's
management that they would not support an acquisition of Bay, which
had been rumored for weeks, and they followed through on that
promise.
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of the agreement, shareholders of Bay will
receive 0.6 share of Northern Telecom for each share of Bay owned.
Northern Telecom's shares closed at $63.6875 on Friday, making the
deal worth $38.21 for each share of Bay. Investors had speculated
that Northern Telecom could acquire Bay for a price in the
mid-$30s.
</P>
<P>
   Bay's shares closed on Friday at $28.3125, meaning the original
premium for Bay's stockowners was about 35 percent. Shares of Bay
rose 8.6 percent, or $2.4375 Monday, to $30.75.
</P>
<P>
   Northern Telecom said the deal, which it intends to complete in
the third quarter, would dilute the company's earnings this year
and add to earnings after that, discounting charges the company
will take to pay for the merger. Some analysts, however, said that
was an aggressive timetable.
</P>
<P>
   Another financial issue that emerged Monday was that as a
Canadian company, and as one that is mostly owned by another
company, BCE of Canada, Northern Telecom must use the purchase
method of merger accounting, which forces an acquirer to take
charges against future earnings to cover the difference between the
assessed value of the target and the purchase price.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of last quarter Bay had a book value of $1.5 billion.
If Northern Telecom pays $9.1 billion for the company, it could
have to take charges of as much as $7.6 billion. Analysts estimated
that Northern Telecom would try to write off as much as 80 percent
of that as a one-time charge to cover the value of Bay's in-process
research and development.
</P>
<P>
   House would become president of Northern Telecom, taking that
title from Roth, but would remain based at Bay's present
headquarters in Santa Clara, Calif. That also raised concerns among
analysts, because many of Bay's recent problems emerged because of
an internal rift between the company's two predecessors, Synoptics
Communications, based in Santa Clara, and Wellfleet Communications,
based in Billerica, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Synoptics and Wellfleet merged in 1994 to form Bay.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we take a three- to five-year horizon, we may well say this
was a good deal for Nortel,'' said Gregory Geiling, an analyst for
J.P. Morgan Securities. ``Near term, though, this is going to be a
very difficult acquisition to integrate, from a culture
perspective, from a product perspective and from a location
perspective, and that's why investors are really beating up Nortel
today.''
</P>
<P>
   Bay was advised in the transaction by Morgan Stanley Dean Witter
and by the law firm of Simpson Thacher &AMP; Bartlett. Northern Telecom
was advised by Deutsche Bank Securities and by the law firm of
Cleary, Gottlieb, Steen &AMP; Hamilton. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
