<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAFRICA-BOTHA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOTHA AVOIDS CROSS-EXAMINATION IN CONTEMPT TRIAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (ja) 
 By SUZANNE DALEY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JOHANNESBURG, South Africa _ Disappointing many South Africans
who wanted to see one of apartheid's harshest leaders submit to
cross-examination, lawyers for former President P.W. Botha began
closing arguments in his contempt trial Monday without calling him
or anyone else to the witness stand.
</P>
<P>
   Botha, 82, is on trial for repeatedly refusing to appear before
the country's Truth and Reconciliation Commission, which wants to
question him about his role in atrocities committed under his
leadership.
</P>
<P>
   But the frail Botha, who sits in court on a specially padded
chair beside the dock, has called the commission investigating
South Africa's brutal past a ``circus'' that he will not submit to.
</P>
<P>
   In arguing his case, his lawyers intend to lean heavily on
potential technical faults in the subpoena. Privately, they say
that if the subpoena is thrown out, it is unlikely that the
commission or the prosecutor will be interested in trying the case
again.
</P>
<P>
   But they were unable to finish in the one day allotted to them,
so the case was adjourned until Aug. 17. A ruling is expected the
next day.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecution of Botha has been contentious, with many whites
complaining that it is simply a vengeful act against an old man. At
the start of the trial, there were widespread expectations of
demonstrations and even violence from his supporters. But few have
turned up, and Botha usually has had only a handful of friends and
his daughter in the courtroom.
</P>
<P>
   Efforts to raise money for his defense have also fallen flat.
His legal fees are perhaps as much as $5,000 a day, and his former
agriculture minister, Greyling Wentzel, said recently that he had
only about $2,000 in pledges.
</P>
<P>
   During the eight-day trial, the prosecution called more than a
half dozen witnesses trying to make clear that the commission had
good reason to want to question Botha. Some of the testimony
consisted of dry accounts of the documents the commission has
uncovered, some of them calling for anti-apartheid activists to be
``eliminated,'' ``neutralized'' or permanently removed from
society.
</P>
<P>
   But other witnesses brought home the pain and the horror of the
attacks on the supposed enemies of the state. One witness was
present when a church building was blown up, and he was sucked
through the floor. Botha, who was in office from 1978 to 1989, is
accused of having ordered the explosion.
</P>
<P>
   In summing up his case, the prosecutor, Bruce Morrison, lashed
out at Botha, saying he had chosen to treat the commission's
subpoenas as if the commission did not exist.
</P>
<P>
   ``His refusal to attend is the result of a willful and
deliberate defiance,'' Morrison said.
</P>
<P>
   He added that the former president, who was ousted in an
internal party struggle after he suffered a stroke, had harmed his
claim that the commission was biased. Morrison said Botha, in
last-minute negotiations to avert the trial, had agreed to appear
before the panel for an ``investigation'' but not a full hearing.
</P>
<P>
   His efforts, therefore, stand ``revealed as an unsuccessful
exercise in devious defiance _ seeking to find some technical
failing somewhere while in reality the accused would have
testified, if he could have cloaked this in a face-saving
formula,'' Morrison said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to arguing that the subpoena is invalid on technical
grounds, Botha's lawyers are trying to argue that the commission
was biased against Botha in issuing the subpoena in the first
place. They intend to highlight statements that various members of
the commission have made, which they believe show a prejudice
toward their client.
</P>
<P>
   And they are arguing that Botha did not have to appear before
the panel because he had made a deal with the chairman of the
commission, Archbishop Desmond Tutu, to answer questions only in
writing.
</P>
<P>
   Tutu denied this on the stand, but Botha's version of events
will apparently not be heard.
</P>
<P>
   During his testimony, the archbishop had also pleaded with Botha
to apologize for the pain that had occurred under his leadership, a
plea that clearly agitated the former president.
</P>
<P>
   Monday one of his lawyers, Ernst Penzhorn, spoke out on the
matter, saying Botha had been astonished by the request. ``He will
not reply to it at this stage,'' Penzhorn said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
