A0427 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-STARR-NYT &LR;      06-15 0468
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-STARR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: STARR KEEPS TALKING 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Tuesday, June 16:
</P>
<P>
   If the art of public relations were a handgun, Kenneth Starr
would have been footless long ago. The independent counsel has a
perverse gift for talking when he should remain silent and for
saying all the wrong things when he opens his mouth. An interview
in which he confessed to giving information to reporters is the
latest of Starr's golden bloopers. The interviewer, Steven Brill of
Brill's Content magazine, argues that Starr broke the law against
disclosure of grand jury information, and the White House weighed
in with its usual pitch for investigating Starr rather than
President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   In tracing coverage of the Monica Lewinsky story, Brill makes
telling points about journalistic excess and Starr's clumsiness.
But he also loads his legal argument against Starr and seems naive
about White House spin. There are, for example, federal court
decisions that support Starr's contention that he can discuss
matters that do not come directly from grand jury testimony. In our
interpretation, Justice Department rules do allow prosecutors
latitude in talking about investigations and in defending against
calculated attacks like those orchestrated by the White House.
Brill documents Paul Begala's decision to hit Starr with a ``food
fight'' over leaks and Lanny Davis' determination to divert
attention from what the president's secretary said about Ms.
Lewinsky's contacts with the White House by starting ``a fight
about the process and the prosecutor.''
</P>
<P>
   Such tactics, of course, inhibit rather than promote the public
interest. In that regard, Starr needs to produce his report to the
House of Representatives and bring any appropriate indictments, and
Clinton needs to countermand his lawyers' strategy of delay. Since
one of those lawyers, David Kendall, has asked a federal court to
look into Starr's contacts with the press, the question of Starr's
conduct is already before the proper forum. Judge Norma Holloway
Johnson has jurisdiction to discipline Starr if he has broken the
rules, or Clinton and Attorney General Janet Reno can dismiss him.
</P>
<P>
   But the political situation remains fixed where it has been for
some time. Clinton's leadership stature has declined steadily for
definable reasons: deceptive or missing answers about his personal
and campaign finances, his response and that of his associates to
legal inquiries, his own abandonment of the plan to explain his
mystifying dealings with Ms. Lewinsky. The Independent Counsel Act
is often described as too far-reaching. But Starr has demonstrated
that even being armed with it is no guarantee of getting the truth
from this administration. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-15-98 2128EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
