<SLUG> BC-ASIA-ECON-ART-375&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HONG KONG STOCKS DIVE, AS DO OTHER ASIAN MARKETS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(th) 
 By MARK LANDLER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG _ Now that Hong Kong has confirmed its economy is in
reverse, the bad news is coming thick and fast. Unemployment here
reached 4.2 percent from March through May, the highest rate in 15
years. And the stock market plunged 5.7 percent Monday to its
lowest closing level since Jan. 30, 1995.
</P>
<P>
   As they have been for three weeks, Hong Kong stocks were
battered by the falling Japanese yen. Analysts also said the
unemployment figures, announced Monday by the government, eroded
the confidence of investors, since Hong Kong offers little
protection to people who lose their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're used to 1 percent or 2 percent unemployment,'' said Ian
Perkin, chief economist of the Hong Kong General Chamber of
Commerce. ``People are starting to get very angry and uncertain
about the future.''
</P>
<P>
   The plunge here in the benchmark Hang Seng stock index led a
steep Asian share decline. In Thailand, stocks tumbled 6 percent;
in South Korea, 4.8 percent; in the Philippines, 4.5 percent; in
Malaysia, 4.3 percent; in Singapore, 3.5 percent; in Japan, 1.3
percent, and in Indonesia, half of 1 percent. Only Taiwan, which
rose 2.3 percent, was spared.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Hong Kong's market is entering its third consecutive
week of heavy losses, analysts said the worst might be yet to come.
Japan and the United States have shown no signs of intervening to
arrest the fall of the yen. And Hong Kong's property market, which
drives the broader Hang Seng index, is undergoing a huge drop in
prices.
</P>
<P>
   The Hang Seng dropped 452.94 points Monday, to 7,462.50. Some
analysts said it could slide to 6,900, its lowest point in 1995. In
a report on the Hong Kong economy, Salomon Smith Barney said the
index could fall as low as 5,500.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can shift the deck chairs, but we're not going to improve
the overall weight of the ship,'' said Jan Lee, chief economist
here at Hongkong and Shanghai Bank. ``We've got to go through this
pain before we can begin to recover.''
</P>
<P>
   Lee predicted unemployment would rise to 5.5 percent by the end
of 1998. And he said that the overall economy, which shrank at a 2
percent annual rate in the first quarter, would probably finish
1998 with a 1 percent decline _ the first full year of recession
since Hong Kong began tracking its growth in 1961.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Milestones like these are fanning political tensions in this
normally apolitical territory. Several recently elected legislators
recently formed a coalition to press the government to ease the
economic pain. Coalition members, who include pro-democracy and
pro-Beijing representatives, have harshly criticized what they call
the government's aloofness and insensitivity to the plight of
ordinary people.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal is to put some money back into people's pockets,''
said Emily Lau, an outspoken pro-democracy leader who was recently
elected to the Legislative Council here. ``Hong Kong is sitting on
this huge mountain of reserves, yet the government just tells
people they have to suffer.''
</P>
<P>
   Allen Lee, the head of the Liberal Party, who is leading the
coalition, said the government should inject some cash into the
economy by cutting taxes and accelerating several large public
works projects. ``We all feel that Hong Kong is facing a crisis,
but it seems that the government is unmoved,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said they had already moved up five such projects,
worth $168 million for jobs. The government also announced a
package of more modest measures, such as expanding the civil
service and improving job-training programs.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Joseph W.P. Wong, Hong Kong's education and manpower
secretary, acknowledged that unemployment would probably rise
further before the economic crisis abated. He said retail,
restaurant and transportation industries had been hardest hit by
the recent surge in unemployment.
</P>
<P>
   Several analysts noted that because Hong Kong's currency is
linked to the U.S. dollar at a fixed exchange rate, the territory
had little room to maneuver in responding to external economic
pressures like the declining yen. The government has defended the
currency, the Hong Kong dollar, by raising interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   The slumping stock market, rising unemployment and soaring
interest rates are bad enough. But for this city of inveterate
gamblers, there was no more telling sign of economic distress than
the Hong Kong Jockey Club's announcement on Sunday that the amount
of money bet on horse racing fell for the first time since it
started keeping records in 1970.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you compare us to the stock market or the property
market, we're not doing that badly,'' said Wilson Cheng, a
spokesman for the Jockey Club, noting that $11.9 billion had been
bet at the races in the 1998 season, a decline of eight-tenths of a
percent from the previous season. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
