<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
(HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
  c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   STOCKS FALL TO 3-MONTH LOW ON GROWING ASIAN CONCERNS
</P>
<P>
   The turmoil in Asia has sent U.S. stock markets tumbling, wiping
out the gains of the last three months for the Dow Jones industrial
average. On Monday, the Dow fell 207 points, or 2.3 percent. Some
other market gauges have fallen even more, suggesting what Wall
Street calls a market correction _ a drop of 10 percent or more _
is under way.
</P>
<P>
   Investors are increasingly concerned that the economic crisis in
Asia has yet to reach bottom. Japan, which many hoped would be the
region's savior, announced last week that its economy shrank
sharply in the first quarter, amounting to its steepest decline
since World War II.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Long-term Treasury rates &LR;  fell to their lowest level in 30
years. The yield dropped to 5.58 percent, from 5.66 percent on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   SUNBEAM DISMISSES CHIEF EXECUTIVE
</P>
<P>
   Albert Dunlap, who has gained a reputation as a turnaround
artist by downsizing many companies, was dismissed as chief
executive of Sunbeam. The board of Sunbeam, the consumer appliance
maker, said that 1998 earnings would be much worse than anticipated
and that outside directors had lost confidence in Dunlap's
leadership.
</P>
<P>
   ASIAN NATIONS WANT JAPAN TO ACT
</P>
<P>
   The governments of China, Hong Kong, Thailand, and other Asian
countries have called on Japan to stem the fall of the yen, which
has been plummeting lately and has reached an eight year low.
</P>
<P>
   HONG KONG SUFFERS FROM TURMOIL
</P>
<P>
   The falling yen has caused economic concern in Hong Kong, where
stocks fell 5.7 percent _ the lowest level in more than three
years. Other markets in Asia also tumbled.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT AND COMPAQ BUY STAKES
</P>
<P>
   Both Microsoft and Compaq Computer are investing $212.5 million
for 10 percent stakes in Road Runner, a high-speed cable modem
Internet venture.
</P>
<P>
   MCI OFFERS TO SELL INTERNET UNITS
</P>
<P>
   Worldcom and MCI Communications have offered to sell more of
MCI's Internet business to win approval for their merger from
regulators. MCI agreed last month to sell parts of its Internet
business to Cable and Wireless for $625 million.
</P>
<P>
   GM FORCED TO CLOSE MORE PLANTS
</P>
<P>
   The North American operations of GM moved closer to being shut
down completely, as strikes at two Michigan parts factories forced
the auto maker to idle 13,000 more workers and partly close a host
of other parts and assembly plants. The strikes have now sent
63,100 workers home and closed more than 40 assembly and parts
factories in the United States, Mexico, and Canada.
</P>
<P>
   3M WARNS ABOUT LOWER EARNINGS
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Minnesota Mining and Manufacturing fell 6.7 percent,
to $81, after the company said second-quarter earnings would be
below estimates. The shortfall was attributed to weak Asian
economies, modest domestic growth and the strengthening dollar. 3M
said it would consider layoffs as well as other cost-cutting
measures.
</P>
<P>
   TAX RAID AT DEUTSCHE BANK OFFICES
</P>
<P>
   German investigators raided Deutsche Bank offices for evidence
that executives of Germany's biggest bank helped wealthy clients
avoid taxes. Germany loses more than $10 billion a year to illegal
tax dodging.
</P>
<P>
   TELEGLOBE IN $3-BILLION DEAL
</P>
<P>
   Teleglobe, a global wholesaler of telecommunications services,
will acquire Excel Communications in a $3.1 billion stock swap.
</P>
<P>
   PACT CALLS FOR MORE AIR CONTROLLERS
</P>
<P>
   The government and the nation's air traffic controllers
announced a tentative agreement on a contract that would increase
hiring and pay at the busiest towers in an effort to improve safety
at a time when air traffic errors are rising.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
