<SLUG> BC-KERRY-SPEECH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KERRY, IN SPEECH, TO PROPOSE WIDE CHANGES IN PUBLIC EDUCATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN MCGRORY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Senator John F. Kerry, in a dramatic break from
Democratic dogma, plans to propose Tuesday gutting the seniority
systems that protect burned-out and unqualified teachers in many of
the nation's public schools, and instead providing principals and
superintendents greater powers to hire and fire at will.
</P>
<P>
   In a lengthy speech intended to serve as a partial foundation to
build a presidential campaign, Kerry will also propose dismantling
a teacher certification process that he said would prevent
historian Doris Kearns Goodwin from teaching high school history
because she does not have a master's degree in education.
</P>
<P>
   In an advance copy of the speech provided to the Boston Globe
Monday, Kerry crosses traditional party lines with abandon _
embracing many traditional Republican themes while distancing
himself in tone and substance from teachers unions, a powerful
bastion of Democratic support. Aides said Monday that he has spent
months pondering the elements of the speech as he tries to
strengthen his standing on education issues in anticipation of a
national campaign. He plans to deliver the address at 10 a.m. at
Northeastern University.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one can convince me that a country that puts a man on the
moon or balances its budget or pushes its stock market over 9,000
cannot put a good teacher in every classroom, a discipline code for
every school community and a curriculum in every district that
challenges our children to reach higher and higher,'' says the
draft of Kerry's speech. ``Shame on us all for giving up on the
vast majority of our children before we've even joined the real
fight.''
</P>
<P>
   Kerry will advocate treating every public school as if it were a
charter school _ gutting the bureau-cracy that has become a popular
punching bag for politicians, stripping away many of the rules, and
allowing the principals to actively recruit the teachers they want
in their classrooms, even from other schools.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, he said, all parents should be given a choice of
sending their children to any public school, though he stopped
short of endorsing school vouchers, a plan advocated by many
Republican leaders that allows parents to send children to private
and parochial schools with the government's financial help. Kerry
will argue that vouchers do not aid enough children and divert
attention from what he sees as the real problem: to fix public
schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is time we end a system that condemns each child to an
administrator's choice and not a parent's choice, where possible,''
the speech says. ``Public school choice _ not private vouchers _ is
also quite simply and quite realistically a practical necessity,
even inevitability, because no one pretends there will ever be
enough commitment or money to build an alternative system for
everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   The speech harks back to Kerry's controversial address at Yale
University in 1992, when he questioned the usefulness of the
nation's affirmative action programs, effectively crossing swords
with the traditions of his own party. Tuesday's speech, aides
privately said, will probably foreshadow a series of policy
pronouncements by Kerry seeking to find moderate ground on key
issues, much as President Clinton has done.
</P>
<P>
   By proposing to effectively gut the seniority, or tenure,
system, Kerry is joining calls from Republican Senator Alfonse M.
D'Amato of New York, among others. Clinton has not addressed the
topic of teacher tenure in his myriad speeches on education reform.
</P>
<P>
   Before giving his address, Kerry met Monday with key
teachers-union leaders to brief them on his proposals.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the speech, Kerry returns repeatedly to the theme of
a thick and ancient bureaucracy standing in the way of progress in
public schools. He said school systems are top-heavy with managers
who direct classroom activities and set regulations from a
headquarters building distant from any school, and they are often
inhibited by powerful teachers unions trying to protect their own.
</P>
<P>
   Kerry plans to say that under the current system, accomplished
scholars such as Goodwin might be able to teach in public schools
but first must cut through a tangle of red tape. In another example
of such an obstacle, he said  &UR;  &LR; Massachusetts school officials have
greater freedom to dismiss unqualified teachers but still are
required to muddle through a series of cumbersome steps.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact is, the resistance to accountability and creativity
is too evident all across the nation,'' Kerry says in the speech.
</P>
<P>
   In Kerry's vision, public school principals would be given
immense powers to recruit and hire new teachers and fire those
deemed to be lacking. He proposed higher salaries, but provided no
clear mechanism for how to raise the money.
</P>
<P>
   The teacher certification process would be whittled down to
attract more and better graduates from liberal arts colleges and
not be limited to those who majored in education, according to the
Kerry plan. He will note that education majors as a group fared
below average on college entrance exams.
</P>
<P>
   Kerry said in most school districts only college graduates with
a degree in education are eligible to be hired _ unlike most
private schools, where liberal arts majors are often considered to
be the best job candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe every principal in this country ought to have the
same right as headmasters at private schools, to hire a liberal
arts graduate as a teacher and to measure competency,'' the speech
reads.
</P>
<P>
   Kerry plans to say that the federal government must step in with
an unspecified amount of emergency matching grants to help bring
poorer school districts up to par with wealthier ones. He noted
that states that fund school districts through local property taxes
are being increasingly challenged in the courts. Thirteen states
have been ordered to develop new funding plans, Kerry plans to say.
``It is in the interest of all Americans to do so,'' the speech
says. ``Otherwise, we'll keep the status quo alive.''
</P>
<P>
   On other fronts, Kerry proposes recruiting business executives
to serve on school committees and offer help with financial issues
and having companies loan workers to schools to teach. He plans
``second chance'' schools for violent offenders to separate them
from other students but still give them a venue for learning.
</P>
<P>
   Though his most significant proposals involve limiting the
protections given to teachers, Kerry says in his speech, ``Let's be
clear, we don't need teacher-bashing. Many of the limitations on
teachers are ones that we put there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
