<HEADLINE>
POOR COMMUNICATION IN MILITARY BEFORE SKI LIFT INCIDENT DESCRIBED 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMP LEJEUNE, N.C. _ Four months before a Marine jet hit a ski
lift cable in the Italian alps, communications of safety
information between the Marines and the Air Force was so poor that
a Marine plane once came nose to nose with two Air Force fighters
flying the same route, according to an internal Marine memorandum
introduced in legal proceedings here Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The memo was introduced on the opening day of a hearing to
determine what charges should be brought against the pilot and
navigator of the Marine jet that on Feb. 3 accidentally severed the
cable, causing 20 people to fall to their deaths near Cavalese,
Italy.
</P>
<P>
   The pilot, Capt. Richard J. Ashby, 32, and the navigator, Capt.
Joseph Schweitzer, 30, were in the front of the EA-6B Prowler jet.
A similar hearing was held last month for the two officers in the
rear cockpit, Capt. William L. Raney 2d, 26, and Capt. Chandler P.
Seagraves, 28. No ruling has yet been issued on the rear cockpit
officers.
</P>
<P>
   This hearing is different in character, though, because Ashby
and Schweitzer had direct responsibility for flying and navigating.
Also, the captains in Monday's hearing both have high-powered
civilian lawyers: Ashby is represented by Frank Spinner, who
recently defended Air Force 1st Lt. Kelly Flinn, the B-52 pilot
accused of adultery. Schweitzer has chosen David L. Beck, a retired
Marine Corps judge and aviator who represented Clayton Lonetree,
the Marine sergeant who was convicted of espionage at the Moscow
embassy where he was a guard.
</P>
<P>
   The private lawyers used the memo to touch on the sensitive
question of whether officers more senior than the crew of the plane
itself should also face court-martial.
</P>
<P>
   The memo complained that no one in the Marines took the
near-collision, for which no date or other details were provided,
as a warning to improve communications and weed out the
contradictory and incomplete information that Marine pilots had for
their low-level missions. The Prowler squadrons, brought in to
conduct electronic warfare over Bosnia, rotated through every six
months and counted on the Air Force for local flight information,
according to testimony here. But the Marines lacked a systematic
way to get new information, purge old information and assure that
everyone in the squadron had read the appropriate documents.
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Col. B.E. Bronars wrote the memo to his superior, Maj. Gen.
Michael D. Ryan, who is in charge of the Second Marine Air Wing,
including all four Prowler squadrons. ``I was somewhat surprised
that, as a result of that incident, no one apparently sought out
what other policies may exist that could result in similar or more
dire events,'' Bronars wrote in the memo, dated Sept. 12, 1997. But
his memo itself seems to have been ignored; Monday the commander of
the Prowler squadron involved in the accident, Lt. Col. Richard
Muegge, testified that he had never seen it.
</P>
<P>
   Bad communication was a key factor in the ski lift accident in
Italy. The Air Force had warned its own pilots of a local rule of
not flying below 2,000 feet, but the paperwork on file in the
Marine office gave minimum altitudes ranging down to 500 feet.
Muegge testified again Monday that he thought the minimum was 1,000
feet. Several officers of the squadron have testified that they did
not realize that they were routinely violating the rules until they
searched their files just after the accident. Muegge, who is facing
``Non-judicial punishment,'' is among those who testified that they
never received an e-mail that specified speed restrictions on the
route.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Bronars' memo said that the Marine squadron's operations
department ``failed to ensure that there was sufficient
documentation and reference sources available for air crew to
adequately plan and execute low-level training missions.'' But, he
wrote, most of the crews were satisfied with the information on
hand, and this showed complacency about safety, even after the
head-to-head encounter with the two Air Force F-16s. Such
approaches are feared by pilots because closure rates are so high;
Prowlers routinely fly at 7 or 8 miles a minute and F-16s even
faster, meaning that such planes could go from one mile apart to a
collision in four seconds or less. At low altitude, there is little
room to maneuver.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Air Force apparently had established that the routes be
flown in opposite directions on odd numbered days,'' Bronars said
in the memo, ``The Prowler squadron was unaware of that policy and,
up to that point, flew those routes the same direction, regardless
of the day.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides introducing the memo, the lawyers for two crewmen also
aggressively questioned witnesses Monday on whether officers who
now face charges in the case, including Muegge, had access to
crucial evidence, like the accordion file with flight information,
before it was taken into custody.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
