<HEADLINE>
NAVAJO MEDICINE TOOK KNOWLEDGE OF CEREMONIES TO GRAVE WITH HIM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL DONOVAN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WINDOW ROCK, Ariz. _ Nevy Jensen is gone, and with him has
passed a precious store of traditional Navajo knowledge that will
be difficult or impossible to replace, according to his friends and
to officials of the Navajo Nation.
</P>
<P>
   Jensen, 80, one of the most respected medicine men on the Navajo
Indian Reservation, died in a car accident this month on Arizona
89. He had lived most of his life in the Gray Mountain and Cameron
areas of the reservation north of Flagstaff.
</P>
<P>
   At a time when the average medicine man knows one or two
ceremonies, officials said, Jensen knew several, including the
Blessingway, (CORRECT, one wore) the Enemy Way, the Shooting Arrow
Way, the Navajo Window Way and the Outreaching Evil Way.
</P>
<P>
   All are used to bring Navajos back into harmony with nature and
to cure various illnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Jensen was one of only a few who knew how to perform the
Shooting Arrow Way, a ceremony devoted to healing tribal members
who have been affected adversely by lightning or storms, said
Johnson Dennison, dean of instruction at Dine College.
</P>
<P>
   Among non-Navajos, Jensen may have been better known in Germany
and Japan than in the United States because he was one of a handful
of medicine men willing to appear on camera and speak about Navajo
ceremonies and traditional healing. He also allowed outsiders to
record some of the chants he used in ceremonies.
</P>
<P>
   But in the past 20 years, he also became a popular speaker at
conventions and seminars throughout the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was active throughout his life,'' said his daughter,
Darlene Jensen, ``but it seems that he became more active in his
last years because of all of his speaking engagements as well as
his continuing to practice as a medicine man.''
</P>
<P>
   Jensen and Dine College, formerly known as Navajo Community
College, go back a long way.
</P>
<P>
   Back in the 1960s, when the college was in the planning stages,
officials sought someone willing to share knowledge of ceremonies
and traditional healing. Most medicine men declined, but Jensen
agreed, saying he also would advise students and teachers on the
best way to set up a curriculum for traditional healing.
</P>
<P>
   He did so, his daughter said, because he foresaw a day when
traditional practices would be in danger of being lost forever.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was ahead of his time on that philosophy,'' said Darlene
Jensen.
</P>
<P>
   And he apparently was right. Today, the average age of a
medicine man is approaching 60, and only one or two new ones are
being certified annually, tribal officials say.
</P>
<P>
   The situation has become so bad that the Navajo Nation recently
has established a training program for medicine men apprentices,
with plans to start the instruction this fall.
</P>
<P>
   It takes from five to 10 years to learn a ceremony, so the tribe
is giving preference to Navajos willing to learn the Shooting Arrow
Way and five other ceremonies now in danger of being lost.
</P>
<P>
   Navajo Nation President Thomas Atcitty said Jensen's death is
even more tragic as tribal officials had hoped he would have played
an important role in the training of young Navajos.
</P>
<P>
   Dennison said many families in the western portion of the
reservation will miss Jensen because of his reputation as someone
who really cared for his patients and wanted to make sure the
ceremony worked.
</P>
<P>
   Many Navajos complain that medicine men today seem to hurry
through ceremonies; Jensen was well known for his slow, careful
style, making sure that the patients understood the stories he was
telling as well as what was needed from them to make the ceremony a
success.
</P>
<P>
   Jensen's reputation was such that tribal officials asked him
many times over the past 40 years to conduct ceremonies for the
tribe or for the Navajo people as a whole, including recent ones at
tribal lands near the San Francisco Peaks.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his wife, Alice, 13 children, at least 49
grandchildren and four great-grandchildren. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-15-98 2137EDT &QL; 
