<SLUG> BC-NJ-POLICE-CAMERAS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW JERSEY TO PUT CAMERAS IN ALL STATE POLICE CARS ON TOLL ROADS 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By DAVID M. HERSZENHORN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. _ Responding to an outcry over the shooting of
three young men by state troopers on the New Jersey Turnpike in
April, Gov. Christie Whitman said on Monday that all 245 state
police cruisers that patrol New Jersey's toll roads would be
equipped with video cameras.
</P>
<P>
   The governor and other officials said the decision to install
the cameras was intended to meet demands from both the public and
the state police that a more watchful eye be used to record exactly
what happens when troopers pull over drivers. After the incident in
April, in which two state troopers shot and wounded three men in a
van, the troopers said the van's driver had been speeding. The men
and their lawyers said the van had been singled out because its
occupants were black and Hispanic.
</P>
<P>
   Allegations that the troopers were engaged in racial
``profiling'' _ the practice of stopping a motor vehicle based on
the race of its occupants in hopes of seizing narcotics or other
contraband _ prompted civil rights advocates to demand the on-board
cameras, which are used by many state police agencies nationwide
and by more than 80 municipal police departments in New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly with the most recent incident, it was clear that it
was something we should move forward with,'' Whitman said on Monday
afternoon at a Manhattan news conference after speaking at a
biotechnology industry convention there. She called the cameras
``very important for law enforcement and public confidence'' and
said they would provide ``noncontrovertible evidence of what
happens when a police stop is made.''
</P>
<P>
   Whitman said the authorities that govern the state's three toll
roads _ the New Jersey Turnpike, the Garden State Parkway and the
Atlantic City Expressway _would pay a total of $1 million to
install the cameras, using money from their operating budgets. U.S.
Sen. Robert Torricelli said he would press the Justice Department
for additional funds to install cameras in all 785 state police
vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   ``This offers protection both to the police who want to prove
that they are operating within existing rules and people who want
to prove that they are occasionally victimized,'' Torricelli said.
</P>
<P>
   The governor's announcement was applauded by the Rev. Reginald
Jackson, executive director of the statewide Black Ministers
Council, which has urged state officials to prevent profile stops,
and by Col. Carl Williams, superintendent of the state police.
</P>
<P>
   ``I commend the governor and the attorney general,'' Jackson
said. ``This is a positive first step.'' He also said black clergy
members wanted assurances that the video cameras would turn on
automatically and not be operated manually by the troopers.
</P>
<P>
   State officials said the specifications of the recording
equipment have yet to be determined.
</P>
<P>
   The incident on April 23, in which Troopers James Kenna and John
Hogan shot three men on their way to a basketball clinic at a North
Carolina college, is under investigation by a special state
prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, Williams said video cameras ``serve to provide
an even greater margin of safety to state troopers, police officers
and the public served.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-15-98 2143EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
