<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-METS-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OUTGOING YOSHII SAYS NOMO HAS CHATTY SIDE 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By JASON DIAMOS    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ They seem to be the Japanese Odd Couple. Hideo Nomo and
Masato Yoshii may be best friends, but their outward appearances
could not be any more disparate.
</P>
<P>
   Nomo does his news conferences stone-faced. Answers of more than
a few words are considered garrulous. Yoshii, on the other hand, is
just as likely to hit his interviewer with a one-liner as he is to
respond with in-depth analysis. He smiles frequently and displays a
warm sense of humor.
</P>
<P>
   But Yoshii swears that there is another side to Nomo, one that
is not easily seen in a public setting.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a talkative person,'' Yoshii said through his
interpreter, Bob Norton, after Nomo had just tossed six shutout
innings Sunday afternoon in the Mets' loss to the Marlins, his
second start with New York. ``He's funny, just like anybody else in
the clubhouse.''
</P>
<P>
   But it looks as if Nomo has watched the scene in the movie
``Bull Durham'' where Kevin Costner teaches Tim Robbins the
importance of using cliches when dealing with reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Not that a colorful public persona is a prerequisite of being a
successful major leaguer. As Mets Manager Bobby Valentine said
after Nomo's performance Sunday, ``If Nomo pitches like that, we'll
be fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Here are some samples of Nomo's post-game news conference on
Sunday after the Mets' bullpen had blown a 4-0 lead in a 5-4 loss
to the lowly Florida Marlins.
</P>
<P>
   _ Was that your best performance of the season? ``No, it was
not.''
</P>
<P>
   _ What was your best performance this season? ``I can't
remember,'' he said with a rare laugh.
</P>
<P>
   _ How much has it helped having Yoshii on the team? ``Having him
on my team is definitely a plus.''
</P>
<P>
   Nomo can use more than a few words when he wants to. When asked
how it affected him to pitch in the overbearing heat and humidity
of a South Florida summer afternoon, Nomo said: ``That's hard to
explain. The heat, the humidity and also the sun, it was like being
in an oven. Then you have the pressure of the game. So it is pretty
hard to explain.''
</P>
<P>
   But that is a far cry from Yoshii saying this spring that Mark
McGwire is big, ``like Godzilla.'' Or, earlier this season, when he
said that he half expected McGwire to start breathing fire at him.
</P>
<P>
   One reason Yoshii might be more comfortable answering questions
is that Nomo came under criticism by the Japanese news media when
he jumped to the major leagues.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't really talked with him, but maybe there is an effect
from the way he was treated in Japan,'' Yoshii said. ``The Japanese
media seem to exaggerate a lot of stuff, expect certain answers,
come up with their own conclusions.
</P>
<P>
   ``In that way, maybe he is a little more guarded.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Yoshii?
</P>
<P>
   ``Me, I don't really care what they write,'' he said, with a
laugh, of course.
</P>
<P>
   __
</P>
<P>
   HEAR THIS: WE WANT HUNDLEY
</P>
<P>
   Todd Hundley believes deep down that he will be traded in the
off season. But Fred Wilpon on Monday once again emphasized that he
and the co-owner, Nelson Doubleday, would like to have Hundley and
Mike Piazza on the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question that is the way we feel,'' Wilpon said.
``And not only the ownership, but the baseball people. Todd playing
on the same team with Mike would give us the best possible
offensive team on the field.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilpon added: ``Todd has this in his mind. But hopefully that
will all be dissipated. People know I have a special regard for
Todd and the way he plays the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Referring to General Manager Steve Phillips, Wilpon said: ``It
is up to Steve and his people to figure out how and where both
Hundley and Piazza would be able to play in the same lineup
together. Yes, I think something can work.''
</P>
<P>
   __
</P>
<P>
   FEELING THE VOID?
</P>
<P>
   One of the interesting twists in the collapse of the Mets'
bullpen in a 5-4 defeat to the Marlins on Sunday and a 4-3 loss to
them on Friday night, was that Greg McMichael, whom the Mets dealt
to the Dodgers in the Nomo trade, would probably have been called
upon to hold the leads for Nomo and Yoshii.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets allowed the tying runs in the eighth innings of both
games, and the winning runs in the ninth inning both times.
</P>
<P>
   Outside of Dennis Cook and the closer John Franco, the bullpen
has struggled, having had tough times in the extremely important
setup innings. John Hudek lost both games.
</P>
<P>
   Turk Wendell allowed a costly hit Friday. Mel Rojas has been
unable to nail down third outs and Brian Bohanon has been
victimized by hard luck.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to settle it out and fill that void,'' Manager
Bobby Valentine said of the shuffling of roles he is trying to
accomplish in the bullpen in the absence of McMichael. ``We'll get
it done. But we need a little time to get settled.''
</P>
<P>
   __
</P>
<P>
   GOOD REPORT FOR GILKEY
</P>
<P>
   Bernard Gilkey, who was hit above the left eye with a pitch
Friday night, saw another eye doctor Monday as a precautionary
measure. No new damage was found. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
