<HEADER>
A0456 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCOTUS-2TAKES-NYT &LR;      06-15 0654
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISABLED STATE INMATES PROTECTED BY ANTI-DISCRIMINATION LAW
</HEADLINE>
   (ja) 
 By LINDA GREENHOUSE    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Disabled state prisoners are covered by the federal
law that prohibits discrimination against people with disabilities,
the Supreme Court ruled unanimously Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The justices rejected an argument put forward by Pennsylvania,
and backed by most other states, that Congress could not have meant
to interfere with the ``historic sovereign function of state prison
management'' when it enacted the Americans with Disabilities Act of
1990. Title II of that law applies to government programs,
prohibiting any ``public entity'' from discriminating against a
``qualified individual with a disability.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The statute's language unmistakably includes state prisons and
prisoners within its coverage,'' Justice Antonin Scalia said in his
opinion for the court. Noting that Congress referred in general
terms to barring discrimination in the ``services, programs, or
activities'' run by public agencies, Scalia said the law's text
``provides no basis for distinguishing these programs, services,
and activities from those provided by public entities that are not
prisons.''
</P>
<P>
   The decision upheld a ruling last year by the federal appeals
court in Philadelphia on behalf of an inmate whose hypertension
cost him a place in a boot camp program that would have led to a
speedy parole. The inmate, Ronald Yeskey, sued state prison
officials on the grounds that his exclusion on the basis of his
medical condition violated the Americans with Disabilities Act.
</P>
<P>
   Yeskey, a first-time offender who was convicted of drunken
driving, resisting arrest and other offenses, eventually served 32
months in prison. Had he successfully completed the boot camp
program, he would have been paroled after six months. His lawyer,
Donald Specter, said Monday that Yeskey would now seek damages from
the state from the extra confinement.
</P>
<P>
   While the decision Monday, an unusually brief six pages, left no
doubt about the proper interpretation of the disability act, it may
not end the debate over the statute's application to the states.
California has been litigating a separate, constitutionally based
challenge to the law's application to state prisons, arguing that
Congress lacked the authority to extend the law to the states and
to breach state immunity from suit in federal court.
</P>
<P>
   While the state lost its case in the lower federal courts in
California, Gov. Pete Wilson has appealed to the Supreme Court, and
the justices are likely to announce shortly whether they will hear
that case, Wilson vs. Armstrong, No. 97-686.
</P>
<P>
   In his opinion Monday, Pennsylvania vs. Yeskey, No. 97-634,
Scalia made a brief reference to the constitutional questions while
noting that because the lower courts had decided the case purely on
the grounds of statutory interpretation, the Supreme Court would
not address the further issues. But it is possible that some
justices _ including Scalia, who wrote the 5-to-4 decision last
year that struck down the Brady gun control law on state
sovereignty grounds _ might be interested in using the prison case
as a vehicle for the court's ongoing federalism debate.
</P>
<P>
   The lower federal courts had been in dispute over whether, as a
matter of statutory interpretation, the law applied to state
prisons. Suits have been brought around the country on behalf of
prisoners with a wide range of conditions, including deafness,
paralysis, mental retardation and chronic disease.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration entered this case on behalf of the
inmate, asking the court to uphold the ruling of the U.S. Court of
Appeals for the Third Circuit.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Department regulations have long viewed the disability
act as well as an earlier law, the Rehabilitation Act of 1973, as
applicable to state prisons.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   There were also these other developments at the court Monday:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Silence at Sentencing  &QL; 
 &LR;  Accepting an appeal from a Pennsylvania inmate, the court agreed
to decide whether the Fifth Amendment right against compelled
self-incrimination applies at a sentencing proceeding as well as at
trial.
</P>
<P>
   The question is a surprisingly unsettled one, and it is of
growing importance, given the increasing use of mandatory minimum
sentences that often depend on fairly precise factual
determinations, such as the quantities of illegal drugs a defendant
bought or sold.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, Mitchell vs. United States, No. 97-7541, a woman
who pleaded guilty to conspiracy to distribute cocaine did not
speak at her sentencing hearing to rebut the government's evidence
of the quantities involved. The trial judge told the woman, Amanda
Mitchell, that her failure to testify was a factor in his decision
to give her the maximum 10-year sentence.
</P>
<P>
   In upholding the sentence, the third circuit held that the Fifth
Amendment right to remain silent did not apply at sentencing
because ``if a defendant's testimony cannot incriminate her, she
cannot claim a Fifth Amendment privilege.''
</P>
<P>
   In her Supreme Court appeal, Ms. Mitchell's lawyer is arguing
that because 90 percent of criminal defendants plead guilty,
``sentencing is frequently of greater importance than the question
of guilt or innocence'' and defendants must be able to protect
themselves against admitting additional crimes at the sentencing
hearing.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Court Jurisdiction  &QL; 
 &LR;  The court issued an important ruling on the 1996 federal law that
limited prisoners' rights to habeas corpus review. By a vote of
5-4, the court upheld its own jurisdiction to review the denial, by
a federal court of appeals, of an inmate's right to appeal an
adverse ruling by a federal district court.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1996 law, the Antiterrorism and Effective Death Penalty
Act, Congress provided that inmates could appeal their habeas
corpus cases only by special permission of the court of appeals. So
the question for the justices Monday was whether the denial of what
is known as a certificate of appealability can itself be appealed
to the Supreme Court. Habeas corpus is the means by which federal
courts review the constitutionality of convictions or sentences.
</P>
<P>
   As a matter of federal law, the Supreme Court has jurisdiction
to review only those cases that are ``in'' the appeals courts. The
technical issue in this case, Hohn vs. United States, No. 96-8986,
was whether an application for the certificate met that definition.
</P>
<P>
   In holding that it did, the majority overturned a 1945 precedent
that had suggested otherwise. Justice Anthony Kennedy wrote the
majority opinion, joined by Justices John Paul Stevens, David
Souter, Ruth Bader Ginsburg, and Stephen Breyer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our rule permits us to carry out our normal function of
reviewing possible misapplications of law by the courts of appeals
without having to resort to extraordinary measures,'' Kennedy said.
</P>
<P>
   In a dissenting opinion, Scalia objected that the majority
``ignores the obvious intent'' of the 1996 law, which he said ``was
to eliminate the interminable delays in the execution of state and
Federal criminal sentences, and the shameful overloading of our
federal criminal justice system, produced by various aspects of
this Court's habeas corpus jurisprudence.''
</P>
<P>
   Chief Justice William Rehnquist, along with Clarence Thomas and
Sandra Day O'Connor, joined Scalia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
