<SLUG> BC-ZIFF-DAVIS-AD-COLUMN-555&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: ZIFF-DAVIS PUSHES ZDTV  
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JANE L. LEVERE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ziff-davis, the high-technology media and marketing company, has
introduced a 24-hour cable television network focused on computing
and the Internet and is counting on a multimillion-dollar
advertising campaign to put it on the map.
</P>
<P>
   Ziff-Davis Inc., which is 70 percent owned by Softbank Corp.,
the Japanese computer company, introduced the network, ZDTV, last
month. Ziff-Davis is investing $100 million in the network over a
two-year period, ending early next year, including an estimated $10
million for the advertising campaign. Ziff-Davis is based in New
York, ZDTV in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign, which was developed by Blazing Paradigm in San
Francisco, is directed at three audiences: cable affiliates, which
Ziff-Davis is wooing to carry the network's programming; potential
viewers, whom Ziff-Davis hopes will watch the programming and also
ask their cable operators to carry it, and potential advertisers.
</P>
<P>
   To date, Ziff-Davis has signed agreements with 17 cable
operators in 15 states, most recently with DirectTV Inc., a unit of
Hughes Electronic Corp., which has more than 3.6 million
subscribers. By the end of this month, ZDTV expects to be available
in 6 million homes.
</P>
<P>
   The creative work for the ad campaign is largely the same for
all three audiences. Written in a somewhat humorous tone with an
edge, the advertising ``tries to capture the personality and
attitude of the channel,'' said Sam Pond, creative director of
Blazing Paradigm. ``The ads have to show that it's not a geek
pointing to a motherboard, that the channel has the spirit and
energy technology has today.''
</P>
<P>
   A 30-second television spot announces that ``as we launch the
future of computer entertainment, we'd like to take a moment to
reflect on the past,'' then cuts first to footage of a ``Pong''
video game, popular 20 years ago, and next to a montage of photos
of the new ZDTV shows. All print ads depict television sets
floating in empty rooms, with various ZDTV programs on their
screens. One ad asks, ``If food gets its own channel, why shouldn't
computers?'' while another says: ``Introducing a TV network all
about computing and the Internet. (And to think television used to
be called the idiot box.)''
</P>
<P>
   Advertisements geared toward cable affiliates and advertisers
are running in industry publications. The cable ads will continue,
but the advertisers' campaign will run only at the time of the
network's introduction. Print advertising for viewers is running
through this month on the television listings page of The Wall
Street Journal, and in the June and July issues of Wired, Red
Herring, Upside and Fast Company. It is also running indefinitely
in the 17 Ziff-Davis computer magazines for the U.S. market, which
include PC magazine, Internet Computing and Yahoo! Internet Life.
The television ad, also geared toward viewers, is appearing
indefinitely on MSNBC.
</P>
<P>
   An unusual component of the advertising is a direct response
campaign on the company's web site (ZDNet.com) and on the network's
web site (ZDTV.com). It asks prospective viewers to have their
local cable operator ``ZDTV me'' by filling out a form and
expressing their interest in the network. Ziff-Davis will forward
the form to the operator. Greg Jarboe, a company spokesman, said
that 17,000 people had completed the form as of early June.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Larry Gerbrandt, a senior analyst at Paul Kagan Associates, a
Carmel, Calif., consulting firm, who follows the cable industry,
said that although ``Ziff-Davis has staked out some territory here
that's been underserved, right now it's all about carriage.'' He
added, ``They've got to get shelf space.''
</P>
<P>
   He called the company's $10 million budget ``a useful amount of
money, enough to get them on radar screens.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Nail, a senior analyst at Forrester Research Inc. in
Cambridge, Mass., called the Ziff-Davis online petition initiative
superb, saying, ``People on the site are exactly the audience for
the TV programming.'' Still, he added, ``The big question in my
mind is whether instead of watching `Baywatch,' consumers will
watch programs about computers.''
</P>
<P>
   Other analysts, recalling less than spectacular earlier forays
into cable by Ziff-Davis and its rivals, questioned the network's
prospects. Ziff-Davis produced a show called ``The Site'' for MSNBC
that the latter canceled last fall after 16 months, when it
switched to an all-news format. Jones Education Co. of Denver
killed its computer network in 1996, after two years. Andy
Holdgate, a spokesman, said that it could not persuade enough cable
operators to carry it.
</P>
<P>
   Halsey Minor, chairman and chief executive officer of Cnet, a
San Francisco-based high-technology media company, said: ``The
question is whether ZDTV will be able to do the programming that
delivers on their marketing. They're taking a huge gamble.''
</P>
<P>
   Cnet, which once considered creating a 24-hour high-technology
cable network but ultimately opted not to do so, produces four
computer-related television shows shown on the Sci-Fi Channel and
USA Network.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Kurnit, chief executive officer of Mining Co., a network
of special interest Internet Web sites, and the former president of
Viewer's Choice, a pay-per-view cable network, was more sanguine.
</P>
<P>
   ``The stars line up for me; I think this network is around for
the long haul,'' he said. ``They ought to win with their
distribution plan because they're giving cable operators a way to
position themselves as more technologically savvy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
