<SLUG> BC-NY-VETO-LAWSUIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASSEMBLY DEMOCRATS FILE SUIT CHALLENGING VETOES BY PATAKI 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By RAYMOND HERNANDEZ    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Setting the stage for a constitutional showdown,
the Democrats who control the State Assembly filed a lawsuit on
Monday challenging Gov. George Pataki's decision to veto dozens of
items from the budget that the legislature enacted two months ago.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit, filed in State Supreme Court in Manhattan, centers
on the legal question of whether the governor overstepped his
authority in April when he went beyond vetoing individual
appropriations. He also struck passages from provisions known as
language bills, which set state policy and specify how money is to
be spent.
</P>
<P>
   In their suit, the Democratic leaders of the Assembly contend
that the governor's veto authority is limited to appropriations and
does not extend to altering language bills. They said his decision
to alter more than 50 language bills was unconstitutional and
undermined the law-making authority of the legislature.
</P>
<P>
   ``These vetoes are beyond his budget authority and are unique in
state history,'' Sheldon Silver of Manhattan, the Democratic
speaker of the Assembly, said in a news conference in the Capitol
on Monday afternoon. ``No other governor has ever attempted to
challenge this constitutional prohibition.''
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit is just the latest sign of how relations have become
severely strained between Pataki, a Republican, and Silver, the
governor's main rival in the legislature. The two men have rarely
met in recent weeks even though the legislative session is
scheduled to end on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The suit drew an angry response from the Pataki administration.
``This is a blatantly partisan and political act,'' Michael McKeon,
a spokesman for the governor, said. ``But unfortunately, that is
what we have come to expect from the speaker.''
</P>
<P>
   The majority leader of the Republican-led Senate, Joseph Bruno,
an ally of the governor, expressed disappointment with the suit,
saying it was unproductive. He called on all sides to negotiate to
restore some of the programs that Pataki vetoed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is unfortunate the legislature and the executive can't work
together to resolve the differences over budget language, the
budget process and related issues without resorting to legal
action,'' said Bruno, of Rensselaer County, in a statement released
by his office.
</P>
<P>
   In April, Pataki struck more than 1,000 items from the budget
that the legislature sent him, cutting $760 million in new spending
for this year and $800 million in borrowing for future years. The
vetoes were the governor's way of seizing control of the budget
process after both the Assembly and the Senate took the
unprecedented step of adopting the budget without his involvement.
</P>
<P>
   The suit filed on Monday does not seek to restore any of the
money the governor cut from the budget. Democrats acknowledge that
the governor has the line-item veto authority over appropriations
in the budget.
</P>
<P>
   But the suit does challenge the governor's decision to strike
language from bills that do not appropriate money, but outline how,
when and where money is to be spent for a variety of programs and
state agencies. Democrats contend that such use of veto power by a
governor is unprecedented and gives Pataki more control over the
budget than the state constitution permits.
</P>
<P>
   In one instance, they said, Pataki struck a provision that
detailed how a community college child care program would be
carried out. In another, he vetoed a bill that set up a program
intended to help welfare recipients find jobs. In another instance,
he struck a passage that set eligibility requirements for disabled
workers applying for Medicaid.
</P>
<P>
   ``These vetoes are a constitutional expression of the governor's
absolute contempt for the legislature,'' said Richard Brodsky, a
Democratic Assemblyman from Westchester County. ``They essentially
mean that the governor can run government on his own. No other
governor has ever hinted at trying to assert that kind of power.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
