<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINESE-PRESIDENT-MOVIE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEFORE CLINTON VISIT, PROPAGANDA MOVIE STARS CHINESE PRESIDENT
</HEADLINE>
  (ja) 
 By ERIK ECKHOLM    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ ``Across the Pacific,'' an hourlong documentary on
President Jiang Zemin's state visit to the United States last year,
opened in major theaters around the country Monday, not by
coincidence just 10 days before President Clinton arrives for a
much-heralded reciprocal visit.
</P>
<P>
   This government product, which is playing a few times a day in
several Beijing theaters in between more commonplace Chinese dramas
or Hong Kong B-movies, stars Jiang as a jovial Renaissance man: He
plays the guitar and swims the Pacific surf; he stands beside
Clinton fielding questions from the press; he dazzles a White House
banquet; he wows Harvard by speaking in English; he charms the New
York Stock Exchange, all the while building a new partnership with
America.
</P>
<P>
   The movie is an unusually blatant effort to portray Jiang the
way he wants to be seen, as a relaxed, witty statesman of the top
rank. Even more, in its air-brushed version of Jiang's visit it
portrays the course of Chinese-American relations the way China
wishes it to be _ as on a smooth track to partnership.
</P>
<P>
   It is impossible to know what China's top leaders really think,
but few people here seem aware of how deeply the recent outbreak in
Washington of China-related charges and scandals, the roiling
accusations of national security braches and illegal campaign
donations, may cut into Clinton's ability to forge stronger ties
just now.
</P>
<P>
   Typical is the attitude of Xu Jianzhong, 66, a retired postal
worker who was one of the few to make the first showing this
morning of ``Across the Pacific'' at a theater near Tiananmen
Square.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important for the world's richest country and the world's
most populous country to have a good relationship,'' he said. ``Of
course President Clinton feels pressures, but he's a statesman and
he won't let them interfere.''
</P>
<P>
   One problem is that few people here have had a chance to learn
much about the various China-related charges flying about in
Washington, because, for the most part, only short, defensive
rebuttals appear in the media. But even relatively sophisticated
officials, scholars and journalists with access to better
information tend to view the scandals as a plot by anti-Chinese
forces to derail friendly ties.
</P>
<P>
   A typical article last Sunday in People's Daily, the mouthpiece
of the Communist Party, said, ``As President Clinton's visit to
China approaches, some people in the Congress and media have
suddenly fabricated absurd arguments in an attempt to undermine the
healthy development of bilateral relations.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people with ulterior motives have alleged that American
security interests have been threatened,'' it added. These people
``must give up the Cold War mentality.''
</P>
<P>
   Such arguments are often sincerely felt, say Chinese scholars
who know both countries well. The Chinese have become so pragmatic
in their own thinking, some say, that they have a hard time
imagining that a great power would allow little details like an
improper campaign donation to disrupt ties.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Chinese are now so cynical about ideology,'' said Suisheng
Zhao, an expert on Chinese politics at Colby College in Maine. ``So
they don't believe Americans have their own moral standards
either.''
</P>
<P>
   Interviews with a range of Chinese citizens suggest a widely
shared yearning for good relations with the United States, and an
assumption that this will both encourage further political
liberalization in China and give a good boost to the economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, Clinton's visit will help encourage the opening up
here,'' said Ji Xiangyu, a 21-year-old college student. ``Will it
be easier for us to get a visa to the United States?'' she added
hopefully.
</P>
<P>
   Apart from some open political dissidents and relatives of the
hundreds of civilians killed in 1989 when the military suppressed
the Tiananmen demonstrations, the suggestion that Clinton should
avoid the square when he visits Beijing seems to find little
resonance here.
</P>
<P>
   The violence in and around that giant plaza at the heart of
Beijing remains an unhealed wound for some, but others say that the
square is too commonly used for ceremonies and recreation for one
more president's visit to matter.
</P>
<P>
   Su Pei, a university student out shopping this sunny afternoon,
said of the unresolved issues of 1989: ``This is a Chinese affair,
while Clinton coming to China is an international affair. Whether
he goes to the square just doesn't matter.''
</P>
<P>
   But on Saturday, the parents of one student who was killed at
Tiananmen criticized Clinton for agreeing to be welcomed there. In
a letter to journalists and American officials, Ding Zilin, a
professor who has been an outspoken government critic since 1989
and her husband, Jiang Peikun, said that to hold a ceremony there
``greatly hurts the feelings of freedom-seeking Chinese people and
especially the feelings of relatives of the June 4 dead.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with European journalists made public Monday,
the American ambassador to China, James Sasser, said he had no
indication that China would release more dissidents. But he said
that in view of ``glacial'' but real improvements in human rights,
he hoped that American economic sanctions imposed after the 1989
crackdown might soon be lifted.
</P>
<P>
   In Beijing Monday, checks of movie theaters found that few
people had yet paid the $1.80 needed to see the new documentary.
However, theater workers said they expected that school and worker
groups would come soon, possibly with free tickets.
</P>
<P>
   The film's prospects may be undermined by the television
premiere, this Friday, of a similar homage titled, ``A Handshake
Goes Beyond the Century _ President Jiang Zemin's Visit to the
United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week in the official press, along with announcements about
the movie, came praise for Jiang that was unusually fulsome by the
recent standards of ``collective leadership with Jiang Zemin at the
core,'' as the party leaders refer to themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Jiang ``possesses a wide knowledge of things ancient and modern,
speaks fluent English, plays the guitar, sings Beijing opera and is
good at swimming and dancing,'' the China Youth Daily said. ``And
he is amiable and worthy of respect.''
</P>
<P>
   Another paper, calling Jiang ``extraordinarily quick-witted and
charismatic,'' said he had ``conquered the hearts of Americans.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
