<HEADER>
A0470 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-TEACHERS-300&AMP;ADD-N     06-15 0910
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-TEACHERS-300&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROPOSAL SEEKS TO RAISE REQUIREMENTS FOR TEACHERS TO RETAIN STATE
LICENSES 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By SOMINI SENGUPTA   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ After deliberating for more than two years on how to
raise the bar for public-school teachers in New York, state
education officials have settled on a proposal that cracks down on
college teaching programs and requires all new teachers to enroll
in college courses or professional development seminars every five
years in order to retain their state teaching licenses.
</P>
<P>
   If approved by the board of regents, which sets state education
policy, the proposal would effectively abolish the lifetime
licenses that the state's 202,000 teachers now hold. Few states
still maintain permanent teaching certificates.
</P>
<P>
   Unveiled Monday by the regents task force on teaching, the
proposal calls for teachers to take, though not necessarily pass,
175 hours of continuing education every five years. The requirement
would apply to teachers who earn a state license beginning in
September 2000, but it would not affect those who are licensed now.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal also ups the ante for teacher education programs at
colleges and universities around the state. Under this measure,
which would go into effect in 1999, the state would decertify
programs at which fewer than 80 percent of students pass the three
tests required for licensing.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, 25 of the states' 113 teacher education programs fell
below that mark on the liberal arts test, 8 of them colleges of the
City University of New York. For instance, at Medgar Evers College,
41 percent passed that test in 1996-1997, and 52 percent passed at
York College; but 88 percent passed at Queens College, 83 percent
at Staten Island and 78 percent at Hunter.
</P>
<P>
   Louise Mirrer, the vice chancellor for academic affairs at CUNY,
said Monday that scores have been improving at all of the programs,
and expressed confidence that each campus would meet the 80 percent
threshold by next year.
</P>
<P>
   The 16-member board of regents is scheduled to vote in mid-July
on the proposal, which needs a majority for approval. The plan
already has the support of the eight board members on the task
force. &QL;
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Richard P. Mills, the state education commissioner, must then
draft regulations on each of the task force's points, including how
much time a school would be allowed to bring up student scores
before losing its certification. The task force had earlier
proposed a slightly higher bar for the colleges: an 85 percent
threshold.
</P>
<P>
   The teacher review proposal, though, is stiffer than one the
task force had been considering. In November, in a draft report,
the committee recommended that teachers undergo a performance
review every five years or face dismissal; but the process for
dismissal is long and complicated.
</P>
<P>
   Under the latest proposal, the state could simply revoke a
teacher's license if he or she did not undergo the required 175
hours of continuing education.
</P>
<P>
   ``In every way, I think this is a tougher set of requirements,''
Mills said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Teachers' union officials in New York City described the latest
recommendation as stricter ``in some ways'' but also ``a more
balanced approach.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It recognizes that it is professional development that is the
key, instead of a punitive approach and a testing approach,'' said
Susan Amlung, a spokeswoman for the United Federation of Teachers.
``Professional development is a much more constructive way of
achieving and maintaining teacher quality.''
</P>
<P>
   Union officials in New York City said they hoped the state would
require districts to provide the seminars, rather than place the
burden on teachers. ``It's a very stiff requirement _ 175 hours is
a lot,'' Ms. Amlung said.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, J.D. LaRock, a spokesman for the schools chancellor, Dr.
Rudy Crew, praised the state proposal but expressed concern for the
potential costs of the professional development requirement.
``Insofar as these recommendations will mean extra cost for us, we
will look to the state for help,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Although the professional development requirement would apply
only to new teachers, state education officials say that, if
approved, it would have far-reaching effects in a few years. About
half the state's teaching force is expected to retire in the next
decade, according to a state education department spokesman, Alan
Ray. New York City alone anticipates hiring 30,000 teachers over
the next four years, LaRock said.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal also recommends setting up some criteria by which
teachers are reviewed every year by officials in their district.
Teachers who are found to be deficient would have to abide by ``an
improvement plan'' to be developed by locals officials, according
to the proposal. Now, all teachers are to be evaluated yearly, but
there are no state-mandated guidelines.
</P>
<P>
   The task force also wants teachers to have a master's degree or
to get one within two years of entering the classroom; they now
have five years to get a master's.
</P>
<P>
   To attract teachers, the Regents will ask Gov. George E. Pataki
and the legislature to enact legislation offering scholarships to
undergraduate and graduate students in exchange for a promise to
teach in needy schools, as well as a $10,000 bonus for certified
teachers who agree to teach for three years in such schools.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
