<DOCNO> NYT19980615.0412 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-15 22:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0471 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OHIO-TORNADO-COX     06-15 0552
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OHIO-TORNADO-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By Steve Bennish
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ A tornado caused minor damage near Greenville,
Ohio and another funnel cloud touched down briefly near Miamisburg,
Ohio during Monday's rush hour as heavy thunderstorms pounded the
area.
</P>
<P>
   The brief but intense storms hit hardest in Darke County, Ohio.
Winds picked up a 300-pound pickup truck camper and smashed it in
two against Dave Ranly's house three miles north of Greenville. The
winds, estimated at 75 mph, carried away another camper top. It
couldn't be located, Ranly said.
</P>
<P>
   Ranly said he briefly saw a funnel cloud as it passed overhead
before he retreated into his basement with his children.
</P>
<P>
   ``I looked up and said, `Oh, s---,' '' he recalled.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Hemmerich of Darke County's Emergency Management Agency,
said the damage was caused by straight-line winds from a tornado
that didn't touch down. ``The wind underneath it can do a lot of
damage as well,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The National Weather Service also confirmed a tornado touchdown
a quarter-mile north of Ohio 725 in Miamisburg. No damage was
reported.
</P>
<P>
   The storm downed power lines in Montgomery, Preble, Greene and
Darke counties in Ohio. Dayton Power and Light Co. said 700
customers in Dayton, Miamisburg, Centerville, Ohio, Beavercreek,
Ohio and Xenia, Ohio lost power for several hours, with most
restored by 9 p.m., said spokesman Mike Novosad.
</P>
<P>
   The National Weather Service said Monday evening that 0.74
inches of rain fell at Dayton International Airport from midnight
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The Miami Valley got an especially large dose of rain for a June
weekend. With June only half over, rainfall is already 2.1 inches
above average for the month, according to the National Weather
Service. Through 7 P.M. Monday, it recorded 4.67 inches of rain.
</P>
<P>
   Commuters to Dayton's southern suburbs had to navigate suddenly
flooded streets in Moraine, Kettering and West Carrollton, all in
Ohio. Kettering police fielded reports of flooding throughout the
city. Rushing waters lifted sewer lids.
</P>
<P>
   The heavy weather followed a weekend of unusually heavy rainfall
and damaging winds.
</P>
<P>
   The Miami Valley Conservancy District recorded the heaviest
rainfall from Thursday morning to Friday morning. In that period
Sidney recorded 4.09 inches, Lockington Dam recorded 3.74 inches
and Versailles recorded 2.85 inches.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Beeman, a hydrologist with the district, said Monday the
Great Miami River in downtown Dayton is 3 feet above normal for
this time of year but well below flood stage.
</P>
<P>
   Residents of Clayton, Ohio spent the weekend cleaning up after
high winds swept through the area Friday, toppling trees throughout
the area, including many more than 50 feet tall.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks like bulldozers went through _ or a bomb,'' said
Delaine Niesley.
</P>
<P>
   Niesley spent Monday telephoning lumber companies hoping to
recoup the thousands of dollars in estimated clean-up costs for
eight large trees ripped out of the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Niesley suspects a tornado touched down, but that couldn't be
confirmed Monday evening.
</P>
<P>
   Today, expect showers and thunderstorms throughout the day.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Bennish writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
