</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-RESTAURANT-LAWSUIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESTAURATEUR SUES PARTNER OVER PROFITS 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By MARIAN BURROS    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The breakup of one of the most unlikely partnerships
in the culinary world has led to a lawsuit in which one well-known
partner has accused the other of misappropriating money.
</P>
<P>
   The plaintiff, Warner LeRoy, the owner of Tavern on the Green,
has accused David Bouley, one of the city's most respected chefs
and restaurateurs, of cheating him out of his share of income and
profits at Bouley Bakery, the restaurant on Duane Street, which the
two men own in a partnership that is to eventually include other
restaurants, a culinary school and a shop in TriBeCa.
</P>
<P>
   The suit, filed last Thursday, came six months after Bouley had
started negotiations to buy out LeRoy's share of the partnership.
Bouley said he had offered LeRoy $4.15 million to buy out his $2.05
million share of the partnership.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we were close to a number, just a few hundred
thousand off,'' Bouley said, ``but then I was served with the
suit.''
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit seeks to have Bouley Bakery placed in a receivership
that would manage the business until LeRoy receives an accounting
of the bakery's income. It also seeks punitive damages and legal
fees.
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Goldstein, a lawyer for Bouley, called the accusations
of misappropriation ridiculous.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. LeRoy has his own bookkeeper at the bakery,'' Goldstein
said. ``The only thing I can think of is that he is doing this to
strengthen his position in the buyout.''
</P>
<P>
   Through a spokeswoman, LeRoy said he would have no comment. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-15-98 2206EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
