<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-15 22:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0483 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-GOLDMAN-SACHS-NY     06-15 0748
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-GOLDMAN-SACHS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A UNIQUE WALL STREET FIRM JOINS THE CROWD 
</HEADLINE>
   (Editorial Observer)  
 (af)  
 By FLOYD NORRIS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The following editorial will appear in The New York Times, on
Tuesday, June 16:
</P>
<P>
   Hire the best, and pay them less.
</P>
<P>
   That has been part of the secret of Goldman, Sachs, the premier
firm on Wall Street and the only one not owned by public
shareholders, either directly or as part of a larger company. There
are other strong firms and there are areas of the business where
Goldman is not the best. But over all, it has an image others can
only envy, as was shown in the most recent banking mega-merger.
</P>
<P>
   Normally, each side in merger negotiations is represented by an
investment banker whose job is to help its client get the best deal
possible and avoid a merger that will not work out. But Norwest and
Wells Fargo each insisted on being represented by Goldman, whatever
the potential conflicts. So Goldman assigned separate teams, and
will collect big fees from each side.
</P>
<P>
   Although Goldman has a reputation of paying less than some
lesser firms, every new investment banker has dreamt of grabbing
Wall Street's most coveted brass ring: a Goldman partnership. Win
that, and a person is set for life, both in money and prestige.
Even the losers did not suffer too badly; people who left Goldman,
often after concluding they would not make partner, have been
sought after by many firms.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the fact that the partners could get away with paying
a bit less than the competition for talent in a business where
talent is of supreme importance also helped to raise Goldman's
profits. That made the lure of a partnership even greater, for it
is the partners who share in those profits. And because the
partners must leave most of the money at work in the partnership,
they have the greatest part of their wealth tied up in the future
performance of the firm _ a clear incentive to avoid the
bet-the-store risks that have severely damaged some other firms.
</P>
<P>
   But now Goldman is walking away from that structure. At a
meeting over the weekend in Palisades, N.Y., the partners agreed to
convert their partnership to a corporation and sell stock to the
public, probably sometime this fall. Then you too can own a part of
Goldman, even if you never came close to Harvard Business School
and have no idea whether or not the term ``net present value''
refers to the cost of Christmas gifts.
</P>
<P>
   Why is Goldman doing this? For the money, of course. The capital
it could raise from the public will come in handy to expand
Goldman's investments, and its stock can be used for acquisitions,
which some see as a necessity when many Wall Street firms are part
of bigger operations.
</P>
<P>
   So the partners, already rich, will become a lot richer.
Currently, when they gradually cash out after retirement, they get
paid based on Goldman's book value _ the value of its assets less
its liabilities. But that figure gives no weight to Goldman's
reputation, or to the current bull market. When Goldman goes
public, its stock is expected to sell for at least three times its
book value. The average partner is expected to have stock worth
more than $100 million.
</P>
<P>
   It is hard to resist such a windfall, particularly since it may
not be available forever. Goldman partners know that within two
years of Morgan Stanley's going public in 1986, at about 2.7 times
book value, its shares fell to below book value. That was a result
of the 1987 crash, which made investors fear _ wrongly, as it
turned out _ that Wall Street's good times were over.
</P>
<P>
   Goldman traditionally names new partners every other year, with
the next, and probably final, class expected to be anointed this
fall. One of them may be Abby Joseph Cohen, Goldman's highly
respected market guru and one of the few strategists who has been
consistently bullish, and therefore right, since 1991. Then the
partners, including the new ones, will be able to cash in if they
wish to do so by selling shares and taking profits that might
vanish if this bull market ever does.
</P>
<P>
   Goldman will no doubt remain a fearsome competitor with a great
attraction to prospective employees. But it will no longer be
unique. And management may find that it is harder to attract and
retain top talent without paying more for it, either in cash or in
stock options. By going public, Goldman may have diminished the
very pre-eminence that makes it so attractive.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
