<SLUG> BC-PHOTO-FULL-UPDATE-NYT </SLUG>
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving 6/15/98. Photo clients will
automatically receive these photos via AP's PhotoExpress or may
download them from either the Wieck Photo Database in Dallas at
972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at 305-448-8411.
Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) NEW YORK -- June 15, 1998 -- SOTHEBY-HAWKES-PROFILE,
6-15 -- Dana Hawkes, a Sotheby's vice president, with rock 'n' roll
collectibles. Raised in Boston, Ms. Hawkes majored in art history
at Swarthmore. She went to work for Sotheby's in 1984, when
collectibles brought in $800,000 annually to the New York house.
Now, Ms. Hawkes says, the field brings in $6 million to $8 million
a year. She credits the increase to nostalgic baby boomers who have
reached the age of disposable income. (Librado Romero/New York
Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) TUSCALOOSA, Ala. -- June 15, 1998 --
BEAR-BRYANT-MUSEUM-2, 6-15 -- Jula Norris, from left, Mary Cleland
and Bonnie Williams drove from Montgomery, Ala., to visit Bear
Bryant museum in Tuscaloosa. This exhibit includes the famous
houndstooth hat worn by coach Bryant. Bryant won three national
championships in the 1960s - and six in all - and made the name
``Alabama'' stand for something good. Alabama was synonymous with
George Wallace - and racism - then. (Neil Brake/The Tuscaloosa News
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) TUSCALOOSA, Ala. -- June 15, 1998 --
BEAR-BRYANT-MUSEUM-1, 6-15 -- The bronze bust of Paul William
``Bear'' Bryant that glares from the museum's entrance is about
five times life-size, and still might not be quite big enough. The
faithful - old women, teen-agers and grown men who see him as
something more than mortal - file past the Bear Bryant museum's
long-flat footballs, frayed jerseys and ancient cleats, just
remembering. (Neil Brake/The Tuscaloosa News Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) WILDWOOD, N.J. -- June 15, 1998 -- TEEN-GAMBLING-2, 6-15
-- At the Gateway 26 Casino Arcade in Wildwood, Marci Polite,
Jennifer Eaton and Sherry Flemingloss, left to right, Girl Scouts
from Cherry Hill, N.J., try their hand. Although children have been
gambling for years, the fundamental principal of gambling - buying
a chance to win more money - is indeed more prevalent in the lives
of young people than it has ever been, some experts say. (Laura
Pedrick/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) WASHINGTON -- June 15, 1998 -- TIBET-RALLY, 6-15 --
Thousands of people, mostly young adults, crowd the steps of the
U.S. Capitol on Monday to protest China's rule over Tibet. The
event follows a celebrity-studded benefit rock concert for the
Tibetan cause over the weekend and just days before Clinton begins
a June 25-July 3 state visit to China. (Paul Hosefros/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) SHORT HILLS, N.J. -- June 15, 1998 -- SUNBEAM-DUNLAP-2,
6-15 -- Peter Langerman, the chief operating officer of Franklin
Mutual Advisers Inc. during a recent meeting the company's
headquarters. Langerman was named Sunbeam's new chairman after the
company's directors fired Al Dunlap. Dunlap, known as ``Chain Saw''
failed to produce a profit for the appliance maker during the last
six months. (Jonathan Levine/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) DELRAY BEACH, Fla. -- June 15, 1998 -- SUNBEAM-DUNLAP-1,
6-15 -- Former Sunbeam Corp. chairman Al Dunlap, nicknamed ``Chain
Saw'' in his office at the Sunbeam's corporate headquarters.
Sunbeam Corp.'s directors fired Dunlap after he failed to produce a
profit for the appliance maker during the last six months. The
firing Saturday marks the end of a two-year stint at Sunbeam for
the renowned turnaround specialist who cut 12,000 employees without
growing the business. (Susan Greenwood/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. -- June 15, 1998 -- TEEN-GAMBLING-1,
6-15 -- Seniors at Atlantic City High School participate in
``Project Prom'', a non-alcoholic after prom event intended to
encourage students to stay at the school rather than drink and
drive throughout the night. With so many other things to worry
about, many parents and educators say they have not yet focused on
gambling as one of their major concerns. (Darlene Lathan/New York
Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) BEIJING -- June 15, 1998 -- CHINA-BULLS-FEVER, 6-15 -- In
a dormroom, students at Beijing University cheer wildly as Michael
Jordan scores the winning basket with just seconds to go in game 6
of the NBA's finals. Jordan, who is known as ``kongzhong feiren''
or space flier to the Chinesse, is better known than President
Clinton. (Elisabeth Rosenthal/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) BOSTON -- June 15, 198 -- HIGHTECH-OLDER-BOS, 6-15 --
Erick Andrews, a 52-year-old computer engineer and software
developer who took a buyout from Digital Equipment Corp. in 1990,
says he can't give his skills away. ``I can't even find a McJob,''
he says. U.S. Census Bureau statistics show an unemployment rate of
17 percent for information technology workers over age 50, compared
with a scant 2 percent for all professionals 50 and older. (Barry
Chin/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) BOSTON -- June 15, 1998 -- SCI-HEARTS-EXPERIMENTAL-BOS,
6-15 -- Cardiac surgeon James Symes injects a gene solution into
the beating heart of his patient. The syringe contains several
million pieces of ``naked DNA'' carrying the genetic code for a
protein called vascular endothelial growth factor, VEGF for short.
The goal of this procedure is to grow a new blood supply for
oxygen-starved sections of a patient's heart. (Tom Landers/Boston
Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
