<HEADER>
A0491 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-WORKFARE-MODEL-NYT     06-15 0585
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-WORKFARE-MODEL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLEXIBILITY AND PLANNING ARE STRESSED IN CHICAGO 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: Sidebar with NY-WORKFARE.) 
(th) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ In a small, windowless room in a welfare center on the
South Side here, Elizabeth Matos is deciding what to do in the next
month to progress from welfare to work.
</P>
<P>
   Miss Matos, 35, who has two children, wants to work with young
children, and so she has been volunteering 25 hours a week as an
aide at a preschool. Under an experimental program called Pathways,
the volunteer work satisfies state rules on work participation,
allowing her to keep her welfare benefits.
</P>
<P>
   It is also the starting point for an extremely flexible program
intended to get her a job.
</P>
<P>
   Seated around a table with three other welfare recipients, Miss
Matos says she would like to build on her volunteer work by
enrolling at a community college. If she earned an associate's
degree, she says, she could become a preschool teacher.
</P>
<P>
   Toby Herr, the director of Pathways, explains patiently that
Miss Matos cannot go to college full time for two years and remain
on welfare, under the rules in Illinois. But Ms. Herr says Miss
Matos may qualify as a preschool aide if she takes two short
courses on child development.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Herr makes a few quick calls and learns that Miss Matos can
register for the first course in two weeks. She can take the second
course in the fall, after which she should be able to be hired as
an aide. Then, while she works, Miss Matos could pursue a community
college degree.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is that OK?'' Ms. Herr says.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's great,'' Miss Matos responds, with a wide smile.
</P>
<P>
   In 15 minutes, the women developed a personalized plan for Miss
Matos. Each participant attends a monthly meeting, reporting to job
counselors on what he or she did the previous month and working up
a plan for the next month. The plans are written into formal,
color-coded paper diaries, which must be signed by the appropriate
authorities and handed in each month.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Herr created Pathways three years ago as an adaptation of a
nonprofit welfare-to-work program called Project Match, which she
founded in 1985 in the Cabrini-Green housing complex. The programs
view the route from welfare to work as a broad continuum, one that
does not stop when someone gets a job. Ms. Herr said research shows
that most people leaving welfare work at two to five jobs before
their lives stabilize, if they do at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not an event, but a process,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Pathways was designed to be used in traditional government
welfare centers, while still employing the core ideas of Project
Match: individual planning and maximum flexibility.
</P>
<P>
   For a welfare recipient with a history of working, the monthly
plan might involve daily attendance at a job-search center in
downtown Chicago. For someone with limited or no work experience, a
plan might start with volunteering at her child's school. The goal
is to understand who people are and how to move them along in
positive experiences, all the way to a job.
</P>
<P>
   Only a few dozen people are enrolled in the Pathways program at
any time. Of the 33 who began the program in 1995, 14 were employed
at the end of the first year. More than 800 people have
participated in Ms. Herr's original program, Project Match, since
1985; research of a sample group showed that 54 percent were
working year-round in the fifth year after they had entered the
program, according to a paper published by Ms. Herr. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-15-98 2220EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
