A0492 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-JORDAN-BULLS-NYT     06-15 0408
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-JORDAN-BULLS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: MICHAEL'S LAST HURRAH? 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The following editorial will appear in The New York Times on
Tuesday, June 16:
</P>
<P>
   The Chicago Bulls won their sixth basketball championship in
eight years Sunday night, and once again the hard part was finding
a story line that did not begin and end with Michael Jordan. There
was Scottie Pippen, who basically quit during a couple of important
games in years past but who this time played heroically despite
injury. There was Karl Malone, a stubborn old warrior who almost
carried the Utah Jazz to a seventh game by himself. There were the
referees, whose odd calls near the end seemed to tilt in Jordan's
favor. There was, finally, the dynastic question _ whether this was
truly the end of the Bulls' great run of championships, or whether
Jerry Reinsdorf, the team's owner, will cough up the $80 million
necessary to keep Michael, Scottie and Phil Jackson, the coach,
together.
</P>
<P>
   Yet these were mere subplots in the larger drama of Michael
Jordan, a drama that has as much to do with his singular
determination as his supernal talent, and never loses its appeal
even though we have seen it before. The Bulls are losing, the Bulls
are running out of time, so here comes Jordan, ready for yet
another display of virtuosity and iron will. With 37.1 seconds to
go, he drives through traffic for a layup, cutting the Jazz's lead
to one point. With 18.9 seconds to go, he regains possession by
stripping the ball from an unsuspecting Malone, then calmly brings
the ball over midcourt, fakes his defender and, with 5.2 ticks
left, sinks an 18-foot jump shot to win the game.
</P>
<P>
   The issue now is whether we will ever see Jordan on center stage
again, with this cast or any other. Reinsdorf wants Jordan back.
But Jordan has said that he will not play for the Bulls unless
Coach Jackson and Pippen return, and both want big money. Then
again, Jordan cannot move elsewhere unless he is willing to absorb
a huge pay cut. Even under present salary cap rules, which the
owners are determined to tighten in negotiations this summer, no
other team can come close to matching his salary.
</P>
<P>
   It is hard to predict the outcome of this chess game, but of one
thing we are (fairly) sure: Jordan will be playing somewhere. He
simply does not look like a man ready to retire, and hardly anyone,
including the league, wants him to.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
