<HEADLINE>
JAZZ WINNERS FOR ALL TASTES 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By BEN RATLIFF   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The first annual Jazz Awards, produced by Knit Media
and benefiting two organizations supporting destitute musicians,
Musicares and the Jazz Foundation of America, were presented Monday
night at Alice Tully Hall Monday night. Eric Bogosian was the
master of ceremonies, and Joe Henderson, Alice and Ravi Coltrane,
Geri Allen and others were scheduled to perform.
</P>
<P>
   For each of the 24 categories listed, separate awards were given
by two nominating bodies: one a consortium of record producers,
members of the news media, club owners, managers and agents; the
other the Jazz Journalists Association, a worldwide group of
critics. Predictably, the critics and industry voters had different
opinions on all but four categories.
</P>
<P>
   For best artist in performance, the winners were Danilo Perez
(from the industry) and the Mingus Big Band (from the journalists).
The lifetime achievement award was similarly split between Benny
Carter and Max Roach; the BMI best composer award, Wynton Marsalis
and Maria Schneider; recording of the year, Pat Metheny and Charlie
Haden's ``Beyond the Missouri Sky'' (Verve) and T.S. Monk's ``Monk
on Monk'' (N2K); best debut artist, Brad Mehldau and Olu Dara, and
musician of the year, Wynton Marsalis and Ornette Coleman.
</P>
<P>
   Winners in both camps were Sonny Rollins, improviser of the
year; Mingus Big Band, for big band; Kenny Barron, keyboardist, and
Rollins, tenor saxophonist.
</P>
</TEXT>
