<HEADER>
A0500 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOLDMAN-SACHS-ART-NYT     06-15 1510
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOLDMAN-SACHS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOLDMAN GOES FOR A BIT OF GUSTO 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(th) 
 By JOSEPH KAHN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ On the day that Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co. announced its
plans to go public, Jon Corzine and Henry Paulson Jr. might have
been expected to relax, even exult a little.
</P>
<P>
   After all, they have succeeded where at least two generations of
Goldman leaders repeatedly failed, persuading a famously feisty but
publicity-shy partnership to dissolve itself and embrace what it
had long shunned _ a brave new world of expansion, acquisitions,
stock options and shareholder meetings.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, in a whirlwind of conference calls, video links, press
interviews and hand-holding sessions, Corzine and Paulson,
co-chairmen and co-chief executives of the big investment bank,
spent much of the day Monday emphasizing what Goldman will not do,
how it will not change its ways.
</P>
<P>
   Partners will not hoard the proceeds of a public offering, they
said. Defying conventional wisdom, Goldman, Wall Street's premier
blue-chip firm, has no interest in buying a Main Street brokerage
firm, they stressed. Goldman will not entertain merger proposals,
with commercial banks or anyone else, they insisted, and will never
permit the firm's culture to be diluted by outsiders.
</P>
<P>
   ``Contrary to what you might read, we are not doing this because
of the money,'' Corzine said. ``This is not about money or cashing
out.''
</P>
<P>
   Paulson, spelling out how Goldman plans to distinguish itself in
the future from its metamorphosing rivals, added, ``We don't think
that being a financial conglomerate is the way to go.''
</P>
<P>
   The co-leaders have reasons for their naysaying. A frenzy of
speculation has accompanied Goldman's decision to go public, both
inside its workaday headquarters at 85 Broad St. and up and down
Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   Employees want to know how they will share the wealth. Market
analysts wonder whether Goldman's decision to go public perhaps
signifies the top of the long bull market in stocks. Rival
financial institutions want to know if they are suitable marriage
partners for the Street's most eligible bachelor.
</P>
<P>
   Goldman may have handled hundreds, even thousands, of initial
public offerings in recent years, but selling itself to investors
is shaping up to be the trickiest of all.
</P>
<P>
   The firm looks set to put a princely price tag on itself,
perhaps $30 billion, listing enough of itself on the stock market
to qualify as the largest single initial sale of shares in U.S.
history. But the co-chairmen say their company consists above all
of ``elevator assets,'' people who walk out the door each night.
That leaves no room for upheaval, little margin for error.
</P>
<P>
   The co-leaders are also under pressure to present a strategy for
growth that will justify the high price they plan to place on their
own stock. Measured as a multiple of book value, or assets minus
liabilities, Goldman is contemplating selling stock at prices
roughly double what shares in securities firms traded for just two
years ago. What is more, Goldman will be entering at a time when
some analysts say the market is peaking.
</P>
<P>
   ``These guys are very smart, the best on Wall Street, and they
are saying it is time to sell shares,'' said Kathleen Smith,
manager of a $10 million fund at Renaissance Capital Corp. that
invests in initial public offerings. ``Is this the top? If anybody
knows, they would.''
</P>
<P>
   In their first formal interview as co-chairmen _ Paulson was
elevated to share the top executive spots with Corzine earlier this
month _ they sought to assuage some of those concerns.
</P>
<P>
   They also put forward an agenda for growth, which _ if shy of
the aggressive wanderlust of rivals like Sanford Weill, the
chairman of Travelers Group, who recently agreed to merge his
company with Citicorp, the largest financial deal in history _ is
plenty daring by the standards of Goldman's own cautious history.
</P>
<P>
   ``We intend to be the pre-eminent, independent global investment
bank,'' Corzine said, stressing the word ``independent.'' ``We are
going to be damn tough, and we will have the capital to compete.''
</P>
<P>
   What is at the top of their agenda? Increasing Goldman's asset
management business, which involves handling the investments in
stocks and bonds of institutions and wealthy individuals. The firm
has some $160 billion under management but is eager to increase
that figure as rapidly as possible.
</P>
<P>
   They said the firm had already studied buying the kinds of big
fund management companies that a private Goldman might have found
it hard to swallow, given that it had only cash, not stock, with
which to make purchases.
</P>
<P>
   Goldman sees the asset management business as particularly
desirable because it generates relatively steady and reliable
returns compared with trading and underwriting, two of Goldman's
main revenue sources today.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will have some new strategic opportunities, and we will go
into acquisition mode,'' Corzine said. ``I am not talking about
mergers, but acquisitions.'' He declined to specify any companies
on Goldman target list, joking that ``we want to buy them when they
are cheap.''
</P>
<P>
   The two executives also said they had expansion plans in Japan
and Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Europe, Paulson said, looks enticing because monetary union
there will create new opportunities for cross-border fund
management. Japan, Corzine said, is in the ``throes of a
revolution,'' as Tokyo deregulates long-sheltered markets and the
Japanese look to foreign firms to manage their money. ``There is
access to clients there today that we never had before,'' Corzine
added.
</P>
<P>
   Domestically, Goldman plans to broaden its private client
services business, which is intended for rich people. It has
rejected the idea of buying or merging with a retail broker, of the
type that deals with middle-class American investors. ``We simply
do not see ourselves getting into retail,'' Paulson said, declaring
that territory ``off strategy.''
</P>
<P>
   Also declared ``off strategy'' was any alliance with a
commercial bank, including the suitor mentioned most often, Chase
Manhattan Bank. The two Goldman leaders said that they saw few
reasons to join Goldman's core operations and those of a commercial
bank, and that Goldman had no designs on traditional banking.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps foremost on the agenda of the two top partners
Monday was their commitment to keeping Goldman's culture of
self-effacing, behind-the-scenes teamwork relatively unchanged and
to preserving as many elements of its partnership as possible.
</P>
<P>
   To insure that Goldman does not lose key members of its staff,
the two executives said they had decided to share the wealth in a
way that they said was ``unprecedented'' compared with other Wall
Street firms that had gone public and with other recent offerings.
</P>
<P>
   Every full-time Goldman employee will get at least some stock
bonus, they said. But none will receive cash, and the stock will be
``restricted,'' so that those who receive it will not be able to
sell immediately. Paulson said the moratorium on stock sales could
be seven years or longer, but he declined to specify an exact
figure, saying it was still under consideration.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be spread broadly, deeply and generously,'' Corzine
said. ``I do not know of any other company that has done anything
like this.''
</P>
<P>
   They declined to specify how they would divide the wealth and
said most previous reports were wrong. But some people within the
firm say that if Goldman is valued at $30 billion, then they expect
about $8 billion of that stock to be reserved for people below the
level of partner, including managing directors, vice presidents and
associates who make up Goldman's front-line force.
</P>
<P>
   That would leave the 190 partners with about $22 billion in
equity. Senior partners are expected to have stakes worth $125
million to $150 million, while junior partners would get ownership
shares that range from $50 million to $80 million, people at the
firm say.
</P>
<P>
   The two leaders acknowledged that Goldman had recently
experienced some extraordinary times. Monday, the firm announced
results for its second quarter in which it posted pretax profits of
just over $1 billion, up 70 percent from the corresponding period a
year earlier. That continues a strong trend in which Goldman
appears likely to trump last year's record profits of $3 billion
comfortably.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine and Paulson were not allowed to boast about the latest
figures. They now have lawyers advising them as to what they can
and cannot say as a potential public company considering a share
offering, and they have taken the advice seriously. But Paulson
gave a synopsis of his thinking that does not suggest a firm about
to remake itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to sound arrogant, because I don't feel
arrogant,'' he said. ``But when we look around at all the big
mergers and what our competitors are doing, we are very happy with
who we are.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
