<HEADLINE>
CART PROBLEMS BEDEVIL MARTIN 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ When the U.S. Open begins on Thursday, Casey
Martin may be more worried about his cart than his golf game.
</P>
<P>
   Martin's one-seat cart broke down after his opening tee shot
during Monday's practice round at the Olympic Club. A backup cart
was brought to him on the second hole, but a wheel came off the
ground when he pulled away after his tee shot. Unhappy with the way
that cart handled, Martin walked for two holes before a regular
cart was brought to him on the fourth hole. He used it for the rest
of his round.
</P>
<P>
   Martin, who suffers from a rare circulatory disorder in his
right leg, will become the first player to use a cart at the U.S.
Open. Monday was the second time in two weeks that Martin has
encountered problems with the one-seat cart.
</P>
<P>
   In his sectional qualifier in Cincinnati last week, his cart
would not start after his tee shot on No. 3, forcing him to walk
for two holes. After Monday's round, Martin said he would ride
whatever cart the U.S. Golf Association told him to ride on
Thursday, but he would prefer to have a regular cart. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
