A0514 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MICROSOFT-COMPAQ-INVE     06-15 0810
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-COMPAQ-INVEST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICROSOFT AND COMPAQ TO BUY 10 PERCENT STAKES IN ROAD RUNNER 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By LAWRENCE M. FISHER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Microsoft Corp. and Compaq Computer Corp. said Monday that they
would each invest $212.5 million for 10 percent stakes in Road
Runner, the high-speed cable-modem joint venture of Time Warner
Inc., Time Warner Entertainment/Advance-Newhouse and the Mediaone
Group.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the deal reflected the interest of Microsoft and
Compaq in fostering the growth of high-speed Internet connections
for home users. For most users, the Internet experience is limited
by the amount of information that can be squeezed through a
telephone line.
</P>
<P>
   Until the current bottleneck in this information plumbing, or
bandwidth, can be opened, consumers will find little performance
gained in buying more powerful computers or new software.
</P>
<P>
   Cable modems and a competing telephone line technology known as
ADSL, for Asymmetrical Digital Subscriber Link, promise to break
through this traffic jam. Under optimal circumstances cable modems
and some configurations of ADSL can pump about 4 million bits a
second from the Internet into a PC, compared with a maximum speed
of fewer than 56,000 bits a second from the fastest dial-up modems.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft, Compaq and other leaders in the personal computer
industry are investing in both cable modems and ADSL technology in
the hope that high-speed Internet connections will increase sales
of higher-speed computers and associated software.
</P>
<P>
   To that end, they are spreading their bets. Last year, Microsoft
bought a $1 billion stake in Comcast Corp., a major cable company
that owns a small interest in the At Home Network, a provider of
cable Internet services. But Microsoft, Compaq and Intel Corp. are
also founding members of the ADSL Forum, a group promoting
high-speed data connections over telephone lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line for both of these companies is it is in their
best interests to accelerate the arrival of high-bandwidth services
to consumers,'' said Michael Harris, an analyst with Kinetic
Strategies in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given the glacial pace at which the telcos move, they're
probably better off pushing the cable companies,'' Harris added.
``But they are really agnostic; they just want more bandwidth to
the home no matter how it gets there.''
</P>
<P>
   The Road Runner venture, which was announced late last year but
officially closed Monday, says it has more than 90,000 subscribers,
compared with At Home's 110,000 users. As part of their effort to
accelerate the delivery of broadband services over cable modems to
consumers and small businesses, Microsoft will provide the new
venture its expertise in Internet, client, server and application
software, while Compaq said it would deliver PCs with pre-installed
cable modems to the market by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real objective here is to make high-speed cable access the
dominant technology,'' said Doug Holmes, executive vice president
for strategy and business development of Mediaone, the broadband
and cable unit of the US West, which split last week. ``To that
extent, we and At Home are complementary. We expect to collaborate
with At Home.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Jermoluk, At Home's president and chief executive, cast
the deal with Compaq and Microsoft in a similar light. ``It's good
to have them investing in cable,'' Jermoluk said. ``We don't
compete with Road Runner; there's no overlap. Any technology they
develop in their partnership with Road Runner will only help us.''
</P>
<P>
   At Home has not worked with Compaq, but has joined with
Microsoft to improve server software for its Internet service.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft's chairman and chief executive, Bill Gates, said in a
statement, ``This venture brings the right combination of
technology and Internet access to make high-speed Internet
connectivity a reality for consumers.''
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft's Internet Explorer is currently the standard Web
browser offered with Road Runner's service, but users can change to
Netscape Navigator or other programs as they wish. At Home users
now get a highly customized version of Navigator but will soon be
able to choose between Navigator and Explorer at the time their
service is installed.
</P>
<P>
   Ownership of Road Runner on a fully diluted basis will break
down as follows: Microsoft and Compaq each will have 10 percent;
Time Warner Inc. will have about 9 percent; Time Warner
Entertainment (through its Time Warner Cable division), in which
Time Warner Inc. and Mediaone Group are partners, will have about
20 percent; Mediaone Group will have about 25 percent, and Time
Warner Entertainment/Advance-Newhouse will have about 26 percent.
Advance/Newhouse is a partnership of Advance Communications Corp.,
a subsidiary of Advance Publications Inc. and Newhouse Broadcasting
Corp. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
