<HEADLINE>
MALL DEVELOPER AIMS TO ATTRACT SHOPPERS FROM MANHATTAN 
 
</HEADLINE>
  (ja) 
 By JAYSON BLAIR    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   An Ohio developer announced Monday that his company had secured
$163 million in bank loans to build one of the larger malls in the
New York City metropolitan area: a shopping and entertainment
complex that will rise on a 110-acre site near Newark International
Airport, with a view of the Manhattan skyline.
</P>
<P>
   At 1.3 million square feet, the planned Jersey Gardens mall in
Elizabeth, just across from Staten Island, would be the
eighth-largest mall in New Jersey. But it is its proximity to New
York City, the appeal of its 3 percent sales tax and developers'
plans to make it a tourist attraction that has caught the attention
of city officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a real long shot to think that tourists would choose
Elizabeth, New Jersey, over Manhattan,'' New York Deputy Mayor
Randy Levine said. ``I mean, who gets on a plane and says, `Honey,
let's go fly to Elizabeth.'''
</P>
<P>
   Herbert Glimcher, the chairman and chief executive of Glimcher
Realty Trust, a developer of shopping malls based in Columbus,
Ohio, said the mall would feature more than 200 stores, anchored by
12 national retailers.
</P>
<P>
   Glimcher said he would not release the names of the anchor
stores until negotiations were completed. The mall will include a
multiplex theater and a food court. But the centerpiece will be an
entertainment complex designed by Michael Ovitz, the former
president of Walt Disney Co.
</P>
<P>
   Glimcher said the entire mall would have a sports and
entertainment theme. He declined to give details of Ovitz's
complex, but said it would include interactive sports games.
</P>
<P>
   He said that Ovitz would also help on other aspects of the mall
design. The two are working on similar mall projects in Columbus
and in Carson, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Glimcher said that David Rockwell, a New York architect, is
helping with the design. Rockwell has been involved in designing
many entertainment attractions, including the Academy Awards
Theater in Hollywood and improvements to Radio City Music Hall.
</P>
<P>
   Workers broke ground on the project in April, but Glimcher said
Monday that the last obstacle to his plan was removed when
Huntington National Bank and Bankers Trust agreed to loan his
company $163 million of the $360 million needed for the project.
Glimcher's company is putting up $56 million for the project and
about $140 million is coming from state economic development bonds
and government grants.
</P>
<P>
   Glimcher said he expected that the mall would open in late 1999
and would draw more than 30 million visitors a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be an exciting place to come to, hopefully a
destination place for many,'' he said. ``We won't have a roller
coaster, but we are going to have a lot of exciting entertainment
features.''
</P>
<P>
   Malachy Kavanagh, a spokesman for the International Council of
Shopping Centers, said that the industry was eagerly awaiting the
results of the Ovitz-Glimcher partnership.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are really coming out with a new mall concept that
everyone is waiting to see, primarily because Herb Glimcher has a
great reputation in the mall business and Michael Ovitz has a great
reputation in entertainment,'' Kavanagh said.
</P>
<P>
   The mall site, near Exit 13A of the New Jersey Turnpike, is in
one of the most congested areas in the state. In order to
accommodate the expected volume of visitors, Glimcher said he had
agreed to pay for millions of dollars in road improvements and to
expand a toll plaza on the turnpike.
</P>
<P>
   Shoppers at the Elizabeth site will benefit from no state taxes
on clothing or food. And because the mall is located in an urban
enterprise zone, the sales tax would be only 3 percent, half of the
normal rate for New Jersey. That compares with 8.25 percent in
Manhattan, accounting for local and state taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth officials said the project would create 1,600
construction jobs and 5,200 permanent jobs, and would generate
between $4.6 million and $6.4 million in annual tax revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Christian Bollwage of Elizabeth said, ``The benefit to the
City of Elizabeth is that we are taking a former landfill that was
generating no tax revenue and turning it into something that will
benefit the city by creating jobs and revenue.''
</P>
</TEXT>
