<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK MAYOR VISITS CAMDEN YARDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ja) 
 By MIKE ALLEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ New York Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, who has said his
heart wants to keep the New York Yankees in the Bronx although a
move to Manhattan might be more lucrative, visited Oriole Park at
Camden Yards here to see how a baseball stadium can fit into a
downtown.
</P>
<P>
   Oriole Park, the home of the Baltimore Orioles, is perched just
west of the city's Inner Harbor amid a forest of the hotels, shops
and cybercafes that Giuliani contends would spring up around a new
Yankees stadium on the West Side of Manhattan. Giuliani checked out
the locker rooms, third base line and the 75 skyboxes, and
pronounced them worthy of emulation.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an enormously _ an enormously _ successful project,''
Giuliani said. ``When you look at the development that it's helped
in part to energize, it really is quite impressive.''
</P>
<P>
   The stadium, which opened in 1992, was designed to evoke
turn-of-the-century parks, with steel trusses and a brick facade. A
team of Giuliani administration officials visited earlier and was
heartened to find that only one-fourth of the fans park at the
stadium. The rest arrive by train or walk from outlying garages,
which would be necessities for a Manhattan park.
</P>
<P>
   The Bronx borough president, Fernando Ferrer, made light of the
mayor's field trip. ``Oriole Park was modeled on Yankee Stadium,''
he said. ``The mayor should come up to the Bronx and take a look.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani also went to Baltimore to attend a ``Salute to Rudy
Giuliani'' reception that raised more than $20,000 for the
Baltimore City Republican Central Committee. Guests paid $100 to
have their pictures taken with Giuliani. For $25, they enjoyed the
buffet of corned beef and mile-long hot dogs.
</P>
<P>
   The local party chairman, David Blumberg, said Giuliani drew a
larger audience than several famous Republicans who had spoken to
the committee, including House Speaker Newt Gingrich.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody can touch this guy,'' Blumberg said.
</P>
<P>
   Parrying a question about his ambitions, Giuliani joked that he
might become a radio talk show host or baseball announcer.
</P>
<P>
   After speaking, Giuliani gave a copy of his new children's book,
``What Will You Be?,'' to Blumberg, who is also librarian of the
Baltimore City Jail. Giuliani said that he considered this
inscription for Blumberg's patrons: ``Glad you're there.''
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the evening, Giuliani watched the Yankees play the
Orioles at a second Republican fund-raiser, where 40 people paid
$1,000 each to watch the game with the mayor.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
