<SLUG> BC-NY-SQUEEGEE-SHOOTING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OFFICER IN SQUEEGEE-MAN SHOOTING HAS A CIVILIAN COMPLAINT RECORD 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By MICHAEL COOPER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The New York City police officer who was charged
Monday with the off-duty shooting of a squeegee man in the Bronx on
Sunday evening was removed from patrol duty earlier this year
because he had accumulated an unusually high number of complaints
of using excessive force against civilians, police said.
</P>
<P>
   The accused officer, Michael Meyer, 28, had previously been
transferred from his patrol post in the 75th Precinct in the East
New York section of Brooklyn and assigned to the Police
Department's buildings maintenance section, where he had little
contact with the public, police officials said.
</P>
<P>
   But the officer's 9-millimeter service pistol was not taken away
when he was reassigned, police said. He is now accused of using
that pistol to critically injure Antoine Reid, a squeegee man who
had tried to wash the windshield of Meyer's car on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The shooting occurred shortly after 5 p.m. as Meyer drove his
girlfriend and her 6-year-old son home from a game at Yankee
Stadium, police said.
</P>
<P>
   As Meyer waited in traffic at an exit of the Major Deegan
Expressway near East 138th Street, police said, Reid began
spreading soap on the driver's side of the windshield of the
officer's white 1988 Pontiac.
</P>
<P>
   Meyer objected, and witnesses told detectives that he yelled at
Reid and got out of his car. They argued physically and verbally,
said a police investigator who spoke on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in front of his girlfriend and her child, Meyer drew his
service pistol and fired a shot that passed through Reid's chest
and struck a blue car behind him that was carrying six people home
from the Puerto Rican Day parade, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Meyer was arraigned Monday on charges of second-degree attempted
murder, assault, criminal possession of a weapon _ for using his
service pistol for an illegal act _ and reckless endangerment,
according to a complaint filed Monday in Bronx Criminal Court. He
was held on bail that was set at $50,000 in cash or a $100,000
bond. His lawyer, Bruce Smirti, did not return calls seeking
comment.
</P>
<P>
   Reid, who turned 38 Monday, was taken to Lincoln Hospital, where
his spleen was removed and he underwent surgery on his liver,
according to the criminal complaint. Monday night he remained in
critical but stable condition, unable to speak with detectives or
his family because he has a tube going down his throat, said Sister
Mary Caulfield, a hospital spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   As a police officer, Meyer had a history of disciplinary
problems. Earlier this year, he became one of 16 officers removed
from law enforcement duties under a new program designed to monitor
potentially troubled officers. The program calls for police
officials to monitor officers with six or more complaints of using
excessive force placed against them at the Civilian Complaint
Review Board within five years.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said that when they moved Meyer off patrol they could
not take away his service weapon without placing him on modified
duty, which involves formal charges and a hearing. The officials
noted that none of the civilian complaints against Meyer involved
the use of his firearm.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is still allowed to carry his weapon because we had no
previous reason that he should not,'' Police Commissioner Howard
Safir said Monday in a news conference at City Hall. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
