u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-KICKBACK-PLEAS-NYT     06-15 0793
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-KICKBACK-PLEAS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GUILTY PLEAS ARE EXPECTED IN OFFICE CONSTRUCTION BID-RIGGING 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By CHARLES V. BAGLI    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Five top executives and four companies in the
construction industry have agreed to plead guilty to collecting
kickbacks and rigging the bidding on billions of dollars in
renovation work for many of the city's most powerful corporations
during the 1990s, according to investigators and lawyers in the
case.
</P>
<P>
   Three of the executives will go to prison in the plea
arrangements with the Manhattan district attorney's office while
the individuals and companies will pay a total of $20 million in
fines, according to those involved.
</P>
<P>
   The deal, which is expected to be announced Wednesday, is the
latest step in a long-running investigation that has already rocked
the multibillion-dollar interior construction industry and changed
the way business is done in the city.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the companies and executives have also agreed to provide
information and testify in the ongoing investigation of corruption
throughout the industry, from major property owners, designers and
real estate brokers to the furniture and lighting suppliers for the
city's blue chip corporations and firms.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators say that the companies unknowingly bore the
inflated expense of the bid-rigging scheme, although some of the
contractors maintain that they did not pass on the cost of the
bribes.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike cases in the past that targeted corrupt construction
union officials or mobsters, the investigation by District Attorney
Robert Morgenthau has ensnared politically connected figures at the
top of one of the city's most important industries, which involves
the design and construction of office space.
</P>
<P>
   ``We decided to look into criminal conduct which affects the
economic viability of the city,'' Morgenthau said Monday. ``The
interior construction industry is only the latest chapter in a book
that includes the carpenters union, the carting industry and co-op
managers. New York cannot be competitive if corrupt practitioners
are skimming 10 to 15 percent off the top.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Cherkasky, the president of Kroll Associates, a
corporate investigations firm, said the investigation is having a
huge impact on the industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's big players, not two-bit hustlers,'' he said, ``and it
indicates that at the top layers of the industry, bribes and
payoffs were a way of doing business.''
</P>
<P>
   Cherkasky, a former prosecutor, said that as a result of the
investigation, ``business is booming'' for his firm and others as
corporations hire them to monitor construction work.
</P>
<P>
   At the center of the scheme, according to investigators,
contractors and defense lawyers, was Robert Bennis, a consultant
for Conde Nast Publications, Christie's auction house, the New York
Mercantile Exchange and many investment banks and law firms.
</P>
<P>
   Bennis, who is expected to plead guilty, was in a critical
position to steer work to favored contractors because his job was
to coordinate the leasing, design and construction of office space
for his corporate clients, according to investigators, some defense
attorneys and real estate executives.
</P>
<P>
   But the tiny club that defense lawyers and investigators say was
able to control much of the office construction work in Manhattan
also involved some of the biggest contractors in the country,
including AJ Contracting Co. and Structure Tone Inc. Structure
Tone's estimated 1997 revenues exceeded $1.1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   In return for $14 million in kickbacks between 1992 and 1997,
the executives at the center of the scheme steered contracts to
participating contractors that in some cases were worth more than
$100 million each, according to investigators and contractors.
</P>
<P>
   Rumors about the pending plea agreements have been swirling
about the real estate industry for months. The district attorney's
office and lawyers for the executives declined to comment on the
case before the agreement is announced Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers on both sides of the plea negotiations, however,
confirmed the following:
</P>
<P>
   Bennis and his partner, Maurice Reissman, are expected to plead
guilty to bribery, pay about $3.3 million in fines and restitution
and serve up to three years in prison. Lawyers for the two men did
not return phone calls seeking comment.
</P>
<P>
   Bennis' lifelong friend and a contractor, Howard Lazar, has
struck a similar deal. Lazar, who pleaded guilty to attempted
bribery in the 1970s, drummed up business for the bid-rigging club
and used a company called JDL Holdings to funnel kickbacks to
Bennis. His brother, Gerald Lazar, is also expected to plead guilty
to charges related to the scheme, although he will not receive a
prison term. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
