<SLUG> BC-NY-CAPITAL-TRIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRST CAPITAL CASE SINCE DEATH PENALTY REINSTATED BEGINS 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By JOHN T. McQUISTON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   RIVERHEAD, N.Y. _ Long Island's first capital punishment case
since New York's reinstatement of the death penalty in 1995 began
Monday with the judge telling prospective jurors that the trial
could last seven months.
</P>
<P>
   The defendant, Robert Shulman, 44, a former postal worker, is
charged with murdering three prostitutes in his small apartment in
Hicksville, dismembering their bodies and disposing of them in
garbage bins.
</P>
<P>
   He has pleaded not guilty, and insists that a lengthy detailed
confession that he signed during nearly 35 hours of questioning
following his arrest on April 6, 1996, was coerced by police.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 71 prospective jurors, 26 indicated an interest in
serving on the jury. They were asked to fill out a detailed
questionnaire that contained nearly 200 questions, some of them
concerning their views on the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Arthur Pitts noted that serving on the jury could create a
hardship, but said that those chosen would meet only once or twice
during the summer. He said that opening statements in the trial
were not scheduled until Sept. 8, the day after Labor Day.
</P>
<P>
   Shulman, who is also charged in Westchester County with two
counts of murder for people found dumped in trash bins in Yonkers,
could be sentenced to death by the Suffolk jury if found guilty of
first-degree murder. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
