<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-GOTTI-LAWYER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE BACKS LAWYER'S BID TO REPRESENT GOTTI'S SON 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By ROBERT D. McFADDEN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Bruce Cutler, the combative lawyer disqualified from
defending John J. Gotti seven years ago for being too close to the
mob, won a round for himself Monday when a judge upheld his right
to defend the son of the Dapper Don in a federal racketeering case
in Westchester County.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Barrington Parker Jr., who is to preside at the trial of
John A. Gotti and 15 other defendants in White Plains next fall,
rebuffed the government's move to exclude Cutler and a second
lawyer from the defense, but agreed to remove two other lawyers in
the case.
</P>
<P>
   The federal judge said Cutler might have been ``house counsel''
to the Gambino crime family in 1990, when wiretaps caught him
discussing mob secrets, making him a potential witness and thus
ineligible to defend the elder Gotti in a trial that sent him to
prison for life on murder and racketeering charges.
</P>
<P>
   But Parker held that the 1990 tapes, and even some made later by
the government, were not enough to show Cutler should be
disqualified now. ``The allegations concerning Cutler are years
old'' the judge said, and are ``largely unrelated to the current
indictment.''
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors had no comment, but Cutler said of the ruling: ``It
feels good to be back in the ring. That's where I belong.'' He said
he was looking forward to ``rolling up the sleeves and getting
justice.''
</P>
<P>
   John A. Gotti, who has been held without bail since January and
is said by prosecutors to be a captain in the organization once
controlled by his father, is accused with other defendants of
involvement in a telephone calling-card fraud, of extorting money
from construction companies and labor unions and of a conspiracy
that virtually took control of Scores, a Manhattan nightclub.
</P>
<P>
   While 23 defendants were indicted, seven have pleaded guilty,
and some will testify, leaving 16 defendants. The case, largely
based on 7,000 surveillance tapes, is seen as a major attack on the
remnants of a Mafia decimated by trials that sent many old-line
leaders to prison, and as a signal to mob successors that they face
relentless prosecution and imprisonment.
</P>
<P>
   The successes came after years in which mobsters like John J.
Gotti, defended by lawyers like Cutler, seemed immune. Gotti, who
was found not guilty in assault, racketeering and shooting cases,
became known as ``the Teflon Don,'' and Cutler rode to national
prominence.
</P>
<P>
   But the streak ran out in the 1990s. Using tapes secretly
recorded by the government in a social club in Little Italy,
prosecutors moved in 1991 to disqualify Cutler, saying he had been
``house counsel'' for the Gambino family and, privy to mob secrets,
was a potential witness against his client. An appeals court later
called his disqualification drastic, but said it was warranted
because he had ``entangled himself to an extraordinary degree in
the activities of the Gambino crime family.''
</P>
<P>
   Citing the same argument, and basing it on five of the same
tapes used to disqualify Cutler in 1991 and on others made in 1995
and 1997, prosecutors in White Plains asked Parker to remove him
from the current case.
</P>
<P>
   But Parker disagreed. ``The government's bare-bones assertion
that the evidence that Cutler served as house counsel in 1990 is
equally potent today has not been adequately supported,'' he wrote.
``In the light of the passage of time, the changed identity of the
defendants, and the disparate substantive crimes charged,'' he
said, prosecutors had not proved their argument.
</P>
<P>
   Besides allowing Cutler to continue representing Gotti, along
with Gerald Shargel, Parker rejected a government move to
disqualify Joseph Corozzo Jr. from representing Anthony Plomitallo,
saying the lawyer's videotaped presence at a casino with John A.
Gotti meant little.
</P>
<P>
   But the judge disqualified two other lawyers _ Robert Ellis
because his prior representation of another defendant might
conflict with his defense of Gregory DePalma, and Richard Rehbock
because former clients of his might be called as witnesses,
presenting him with ``a nearly impossible ethical dilemma.''
</P>
<P>
   Ellis said he was ``awfully disappointed.'' Rehbock insisted
that former clients would pose no conflict of interest for him
because most would not be called as witnesses, and those who might
were willing to sign waivers releasing him from obligations arising
from possibly conflicting loyalties. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
