<SLUG> BC-OBIT-YOUNG-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEWIS H. YOUNG, FORMER EDITOR OF BUSINESS WEEK, DEAD AT 73 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By MILT FREUDENHEIM    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lewis H. Young, a former editor in chief of Business Week who
expanded the horizons of business reporting, died Friday in
Manhattan. He was 73 and lived in Ossining, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Young died of a heart attack as he was leaving his office at
Cahners Publishing Co., where he was editorial director of
Electronic News, said his wife, Joanne Root Young.
</P>
<P>
   Trained in engineering and physics, Young was among the first
business magazine editors to emphasize coverage of technology,
electronics and computers. At Business Week, he was in charge
during a period when economic news was frequently prominent,
including an Arab oil embargo, recession in the mid-1970s and the
New York City financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
   He was also editor in chief of Electronics Magazine, which, like
Business Week, was a McGraw-Hill publication. He also started
several other business and electronics magazines.
</P>
<P>
   He was active with Catalyst, a national advocacy group for the
advancement of women in business and the professions, for a number
of years and became chairman of its board in 1982.
</P>
<P>
   After 15 years as chief editor, he left Business Week in 1984.
Young moved to Hong Kong and started the magazine Far East
Business. In 1989, he joined the Cahners Publishing, a unit of Reed
Elsevier PLC, the British-Dutch information company.
</P>
<P>
   He directed Asian operations of Cahners and was editorial
director of Cahners' Electronic Business Asia, based in Hong Kong.
In 1992, he became editorial director of Electronic Business, a
Cahners monthly based in Boston. He moved to Electronic News as
editorial director last year.
</P>
<P>
   Young was born in Philadelphia. He received undergraduate
degrees in mechanical engineering and physics at Purdue University.
After college, he was a physicist with the Bettis Atomic Power
division of Westinghouse Electric Corp. He earned a master's degree
in business administration from New York University. He was a first
lieutenant in the Army Corps of Engineers from 1943 to 1946.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his wife, he is survived by a daughter, Mrs. Anne
Albanese of Norwalk, Conn., and a sister, Pauline Schamberg of
Buffalo Grove, Ill. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-15-98 2318EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980615.0450 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-15 23:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0664 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-AUTO-INSURE-POLITI     06-15 0729
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-AUTO-INSURE-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROPOSAL TIES CAR INSURANCE TO MILEAGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By RICHARD PEREZ-PENA    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Seizing on an issue that dominated last year's
gubernatorial race in New Jersey, Lt. Gov. Betsy McCaughey Ross
released a plan Monday to lower auto insurance rates in New York,
including a proposal for pay-by-the-mile premiums.
</P>
<P>
   It was one of two proposals to lower the rates offered Monday by
candidates for the Democratic gubernatorial nomination. Peter
Vallone, speaker of the New York City Council, offered a more
limited proposal, but Ms. McCaughey Ross's plan would give
consumers who do little driving a choice of paying a flat rate, as
drivers do now, or paying a rate based on mileage.
</P>
<P>
   Insurance companies already include miles driven as one of many
factors in calculating premiums, but her plan would make the
correlation much more direct.
</P>
<P>
   ``The risk isn't in owning a car, it's in driving one,'' Ms.
McCaughey Ross said. ``People who drive less should not be made to
line insurance companies' pockets.''
</P>
<P>
   The mileage-based approach would be a boon to people who drive
infrequently, a group that includes elderly drivers, residents of
New York City and women. All three constituencies could be crucial
to McCaughey Ross's political fortunes; older people are more
likely to vote, she is appealing explicitly for women's votes, and
she is trying to raise her relatively low standing among New York
City voters.
</P>
<P>
   She said her proposals would lower rates 25 percent, but much of
that is based on speculative projections of savings from other
elements of her plan, like appointing a consumer advocate and
cutting administrative costs.
</P>
<P>
   In New Jersey last year, Gov. Christie Whitman, a Republican,
was nearly beaten by a little-known Democrat, state Sen. Jim
McGreevey, who accused her of doing nothing about the state's auto
insurance premiums, the highest in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. McCaughey Ross and the other Democrats who are vying for
their party's gubernatorial nomination _ Charles Hynes, the
Brooklyn district attorney; James Larocca, a former state
commissioner of both transportation and energy, and Vallone _ have
said they hope to use the issue to greater effect in New York.
</P>
<P>
   In outlining his own insurance plan, Vallone charged that one of
the reasons for New York's high rates is a law signed by Gov.
George Pataki in 1995, when Ms. McCaughey Ross was a loyal member
of the Republican governor's team. She switched party affiliation
in September and immediately started making plans for her
gubernatorial race.
</P>
<P>
   A Vallone campaign aide said that 1995 law increased drivers'
minimum coverage, which resulted in higher rates. ``Ross said
nothing when the state passed this legislation,'' said Kim Rubey, a
spokeswoman for the Vallone campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Vallone released a less detailed proposal that called for
creating a toll-free telephone number and an Internet site to help
people comparison-shop, as well as limiting insurers' profits, and
strengthening penalties for fraud. He did not say how much his
proposal might lower rates.
</P>
<P>
   The Pataki camp dismissed the proposals by Vallone and McCaughey
Ross as pandering. ``Neither one makes any sense,'' said Zenia
Mucha, the governor's communications director. ``This is nothing
more than election-year politics.''
</P>
<P>
   In a poll conducted this week by the John Zogby International
polling firm, more than half the New Yorkers surveyed said they
considered auto insurance rates a ``very important'' issue in the
race for governor, but a similar number said they did not think it
would change their decision on whether to vote for Pataki.
</P>
<P>
   Even though McCaughey Ross's plan could have appeal among
important voting blocs, it has political risks, as well.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Griffin, vice president of the American Insurance
Association, said lowering rates for one group would lead to higher
rates for others; in this case, upstate residents, who drive the
longest distances and have been McCaughey Ross's greatest source of
support.
</P>
<P>
   The lieutenant governor argued that since insurers were making
healthy profits now, it would be possible to lower everyone's
rates. But she conceded that when profits are slim or nonexistent,
lower rates for those who drive less will force up the rates for
those who drive more. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
