<HEADER>
A0687 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-YANKS-ORIOLES-NYT     06-15 0837
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-ORIOLES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ORIOLES BEAT YANKEES, 7-4 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ The Yankees insisted that the bad blood with the
Baltimore Orioles no longer existed, that they had no intention of
retaliating for the incident last month in which the Orioles'
Armando Benitez hit Tino Martinez with a pitch, triggering a brawl
and suspensions.
</P>
<P>
   Monday night's home plate umpire, John Hirschbeck, did not
believe any of it. After Mike Stanton allowed a seventh-inning home
run to Baltimore's Rafael Palmeiro, Stanton threw a fastball into
the back of Eric Davis, the Orioles' next batter. Hirschbeck
immediately ejected Stanton.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees went on to lose, 7-4, in a game marked by Ricky
Ledee's first major league home run and interrupted for 27 minutes
by rain. But the outcome has little chance of affecting the
American League East race, for the Orioles are 22 games behind the
first-place Yankees in the loss column. It could be, though, that
the Yankees have evened a month-old score.
</P>
<P>
   After being ejected, Stanton reacted as if he had no intention
of hitting Davis, shrugging as if to way, ``Who, me?'' Intentional
or not, the coincidences were plentiful. Like Benitez on May 19,
Stanton had allowed an important home run. Like Benitez, Stanton
hit the next batter with his next pitch. Like Martinez, Davis wears
No. 24. Like Benitez, Stanton threw a fastball. Like Benitez,
Stanton planted his fastball between the 2 and the 4.
</P>
<P>
   Suspicions will linger and the bad blood will simmer when the
Yankees play the second game of this three-game series on Tuesday
night.
</P>
<P>
   The Orioles and the Yankees were tied in the bottom of the sixth
inning, 4-4, when B.J. Surhoff singled and took second on a
groundout. Lenny Webster, Baltimore's light-hitting catcher, took a
hard swing and lofted a high fly toward left.
</P>
<P>
   The dimensions in Camden Yards are notoriously short, 364 feet
to left-center, and Ledee, playing deep in left field, stepped
back. A second or two passed before Ledee realized he had badly
misjudged the ball and it was falling in front of him. By the time
he recovered, it was too late. Surhoff took third, Webster stopped
at first and David Wells, the Yankee starter, jerked his shoulders
in some frustration.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Bordick then lifted another fly to left. Surhoff moved back
to third to tag up, and Ledee measured the fly, backing up and
moving forward as he caught the ball. Ledee's throw beat Surhoff to
the plate, but in fielding the hop, the Yankees' catcher, Jorge
Posada, had drawn his right foot back, leaving half of the plate
uncovered.
</P>
<P>
   Through this open door to home did Surhoff slide _ safely,
according to Hirschbeck. The Yankees argued, but they trailed
nevertheless, by 5-4, and caught the Orioles nevermore.
</P>
<P>
   Thick, dark clouds that haunted Camden Yards all day burst about
two hours before the game and did little to stem the 83-degree
heat; rather, the humidity hung in the air, and on the pitchers,
riding their shoulders like weighted backpacks.
</P>
<P>
   Wells has pitched his best games this year in cool temperatures
_ his perfect game in 59 degrees _ and his worst game occurred on a
steamy night in Texas. Two innings into Monday night's game, creeks
of sweat flowed down his face, and Wells seemed to be laboring.
</P>
<P>
   Facing a former Toronto teammate, Joe Carter, in the first
inning, Wells went inside with a fastball _ and Carter turned on
it, whacking a line drive off the foul pole down the left-field
line. It was the 18th home run allowed by Wells, who has walked
only 17 batters.
</P>
<P>
   Webster opened the third with a single and moved to second on a
sacrifice bunt. Webster failed to tag up and take third, however,
after Roberto Alomar flied out to deep right-center. But with two
out, Carter squibbed a roller down the third-base line for a cheap
single that scored Webster. Harold Baines followed with a single
and Palmeiro laced a run-scoring double to make it 3-0.
</P>
<P>
   Darryl Strawberry singled with one out in the Yankee fourth, and
Posada followed with a single to left. Ledee came to the plate,
having been wiped out by Baltimore's Scott Erickson in his first
at-bat _ two fastballs and a wicked slider, a three-pitch
strikeout. In this at-bat, Ledee fell behind 0-2 again, on
fastballs. Erickson tried a fastball, and Ledee fouled it off.
</P>
<P>
   Then Erickson missed with his next three pitches. Ledee, playing
his second game in the big leagues, then fouled off a fastball.
Erickson came back with another fastball, on the outside part of
the plate, and Ledee reached out and lifted it over the wall in
left field, the opposite way. Three batters, three runs, tie game.
</P>
<P>
   Wells retired the first two hitters in the fifth, but Carter
pulled a double down the left-field line. Baines singled again and
Carter scored, giving Baltimore a 4-3 lead. With one out in the
Yankees' sixth, however, Posada launched a homer into the stands in
right-center field, tying the score one more time.
</P>
</TEXT>
